<html>
<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 52 No. 2</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="v52n2.htm">Volume 52 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>
<h1>Fundamental Justice, Stigma and Fault<a href="#note">*</a>
<p> 
NANCY K. THOMSON</h1>
<p><br>
<i>The Supreme Court of Canada has held that, absent special stigma, the minimum degree of fault required by the</i> Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms<i> for</i> Criminal Code<i> offences is one based on an objective standard. This article considers the Court's reliance on the notion of stigma as the primary factor to be considered in determining the constitutionally required degree of fault. The author concludes that stigma has limited utility as an analytical tool outside the context of murder and that the preferred analysis is contextual in nature. Within the framework of the fault analysis under s. 7 of the</i> Charter<i>, a contextual approach recognizes that different factors may assume more or less prominence depending on the offence under scrutiny. Such an approach is necessary to define the principles of fundamental justice which are at stake in any given case. The persistence of constructive liability in the offence of unlawful act manslaughter is discussed as one example of how the stigma analysis has undermined a principled resolution of fault issues by the Court.
<p>
La Cour supr&ecirc;me a d&eacute;clar&eacute; que la</i> Charte canadienne des droits et libert&eacute;s<i> exige que les infractions se trouvant au</i> Code criminel<i>, sauf celles auxquelles se rattachent des stigmates particuli&egrave;rement s&eacute;v&egrave;res, se fondent, au minimum, sur une norme de faute objective. Dans cet article, l'auteure analyse l'importance accord&eacute;e par la Cour &agrave; cette notion de stigmates dans la d&eacute;termination de l'exigence constitutionnelle en mati&egrave;re de faute. L'auteure constate que, sur le plan analytique, la notion de stigmates est peu utile, sauf en ce qui a trait au crime de meurtre. Elle estime  pr&eacute;f&eacute;rable, dans le cadre de l'analyse de la faute en vertu de l'article 7 de la</i> Charte<i>, d'adopter une approche contextuelle, selon laquelle l'importance relative des diff&eacute;rents facteurs peut varier d'une
infraction &agrave; l'autre. Selon l'auteure, une telle approche est n&eacute;cessaire &agrave; l'identification des principes de justice fondamentale qui sont mis en jeu dans un cas donn&eacute;. L'auteure donne l'exemple de l'homicide involontaire par suite d'un acte ill&eacute;gal, une infraction &agrave; responsabilit&eacute; imput&eacute;e, pour d&eacute;montrer que l'analyse des stigmates a emp&ecirc;ch&eacute; la Cour de
r&eacute;gler ad&eacute;quatement, au niveau des principes, les questions relatives &agrave; la faute.</i>
<blockquote>
Although it is true that <i>mens rea</i> in the sense of one state of mind required for all forms of criminal responsibility does not exist, and that instead there are only a number of <i>mentes reae</i> varying from crime to crime and from material element to material element, the maxim <i>actus non facit reum nisi mens sit rea</i> is still of paramount importance. It serves as a reminder of the moral nature of the criminal law and also offers an ideal
against which particular rules of that law can be measured.
<blockquote>
G.H. Gordon<br>
<cite>The Criminal Law of Scotland</cite><sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup>
</blockquote></blockquote>
<p><br>
<h3>Introduction</h3>

The Supreme Court of Canada released its most recent package of decisions concerning the constitutional requirement of fault in September 1993.<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> In those decisions, the Court confirms
earlier <i>dicta</i> that, in all but a very few crimes, the minimum fault level required by the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite><sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> will be based on an objective
standard. The Court continues to derive its analysis from a doctrine first articulated in <cite>R. v. Vaillancourt</cite><sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> and later developed in <cite>R. v. Martineau</cite>.<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> This doctrine relies on the notion of stigma as determinative of the constitutionally required level of fault under s. 7 of the Charter.
<p>
These decisions mark the latest pronouncements in the Court's review of the constitutional requirement for a mental element in criminal offences, a process which began in 1985 with <cite>Reference re Section 94(2) of the Motor Vehicle Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> In the <cite>Motor Vehicle Reference</cite>, the Court rejected absolute liability as a fault standard for any offence where there is a potential for a penalty of imprisonment. In doing so, the Court elevated <i>mens rea</i> to a constitutionally required element in all <cite>Criminal Code</cite><sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> offences. 
<p>
Since the <cite>Motor Vehicle Reference</cite>, the Court has ruled that constructive murder is unconstitutional<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> and that the principles of fundamental justice require subjective foresight in the offences of murder,<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> attempted  murder,<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> and accessory liability to an offence requiring subjective foresight,<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> due to the stigma that attaches upon conviction. On the other hand, the Court has decided that such stigma does not accompany a conviction of unlawfully causing bodily harm,<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup> dangerous driving,<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> unlawful act
manslaughter,<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> failing to provide the necessaries of life,<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> and careless use of a firearm.<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup> Objective foresight is the basis of liability for these offences.
<p>
The Court has continued to rely on stigma to determine the constitutionally required level of fault. Having initially
identified two factors---stigma and punishment ---as determinative of the level of fault required, the Court later states that punishment is merely a secondary consideration.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> The primary consideration is the stigma which attaches to an accused person upon conviction. While the analysis appeared to hold up in early and straightforward cases dealing with murder, its weaknesses have been thrown into sharp relief in later cases dealing with criminal negligence and manslaughter. In these cases, it appears that the Court, sensing that a principled application of the stigma doctrine could result in incoherence in the criminal law, has manipulated the level of stigma associated with the offences under investigation in order to reach the desired outcome. The stigma doctrine, rather than proving to be an insightful aid in carrying out the analysis, has become a hurdle which is easily overcome. Once over the hurdle, the Court is able to avoid some of the more difficult issues relating to fault in the context of a particular <cite>Criminal Code</cite> provision.
<p>
In this article, I will review the validity of the notion of stigma, assess its usefulness in determining the required degree of fault for an offence, and propose alternative grounds upon which the analysis should be based. The importance of carrying out the fault analysis in the specific context of the offence under consideration will be
emphasized. The persistence of constructive liability in the offence of unlawful act manslaughter is discussed as one example of how the stigma analysis has undermined a principled resolution of fault issues by the Court.
<p>
At a more fundamental level, I will consider whether there is a danger in attempting to constitutionalize fault using the analytical techniques the Court has employed in recent cases. In considering fault, it should be emphasized that the Court is not assessing the degree of fault which will result in the &quot;best&quot; or most desirable law from the perspective of public policy and the goals of criminal legislation. The discussion is, by the very nature of the inquiry, narrowed to focus on that degree of fault which is required as an absolute minimum to ensure that the principles of fundamental justice are not violated upon conviction. In framing the exercise in this manner, the Court recognizes some dimensions of the complexities of fault, but fails to recognize others. The resulting decontextualization of the law relating to fault may undermine some of the very principles of fundamental justice that the Court is seeking to protect.
<p>
<h3>Fundamental Justice</h3>

A. SCOPE AND CONTENT: THE <cite>MOTOR VEHICLE REFERENCE</cite>
<p>
The analysis of the constitutionally required level of fault is carried out under s. 7 of the <cite>Charter</cite>. This &quot;most eloquent but mysterious provision&quot;<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> states that no one is to be deprived of life, liberty, or security of the person &quot;except in accordance with the principles of fundamental justice.&quot; In the <cite>Motor Vehicle Reference</cite>, Lamer J. (as he then was), writing for the majority, attempted to give content and scope to the principles of fundamental justice.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> He undertook a purposive analysis of the term in accordance with the method established by the Court in <cite>R. v. Big M Drug Mart</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> While rejecting any argument that such a purposive analysis could be based only on the procedural correctness of a law, Lamer J. likewise rejected a full substantive review. Steering between these two extremes, he embraced a review
which would &quot;secure for persons `the full benefit of the <cite>Charter</cite>'s  protection.'&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup> He specifically rejected equating the much broader concept of fundamental justice with the narrow, procedural protection provided by the traditional conception of natural justice.
 <p>
Lamer J. finds that the principles of fundamental justice have as their source &quot;the basic tenets and principles, not only of our judicial process, but also of the other components of our legal system.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> They represent principles which have been recognized by the common law and are considered to be &quot;essential elements of a system for the administration of justice which is founded upon the belief in the dignity and worth of the human person and the rule of law.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> Unfortunately, these are vague concepts which are of limited usefulness as guides for identifying in any meaningful way the principles of fundamental justice related to a specific provision of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>. However, his words allow us to discern his method in giving content to the term &quot;principles of fundamental justice&quot; as it relates to absolute liability in penal law.
<p>
In this case, Lamer J. finds that it is a principle of fundamental justice that the innocent must not be punished. To support his proposition, he relies on the common law and the work of the respected British legal scholar, Glanville Williams. He quotes from Dickson J. in <cite>R. v. Sault Ste. Marie</cite> that &quot;there is a generally held revulsion against punishing the morally innocent&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> and goes on to hold that absolute liability is contrary to the principles of fundamental justice when the potential punishment for the offence is imprisonment.
<p>
Lamer J.'s analysis of absolute liability and fundamental justice is carried out at an abstract level, rather than in the context of the particular regulatory offence defined by s. 94 of the British Columbia <cite>Motor Vehicle Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> As Wilson J. points out in concurring reasons, Lamer J.
&quot;has relied heavily upon the common law which precluded punishment in the absence of a guilty mind.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> However, as Wilson J. notes, this case does not deal with an offence which was part of the common law. Rather, the Court is analyzing &quot;a statutory offence as to which the legislature has stated in no uncertain terms that guilt is established by proof of the act itself.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> Lamer J., having carried out his analysis at an abstract level, finds that any offence which combines absolute liability with the <i>potential</i> for imprisonment is unconstitutional.
<p>
Wilson J. characterizes the principles of fundamental justice as the fundamental tenets of our justice system. In determining the principle of fundamental justice at stake in the <cite>Motor Vehicle Reference</cite>, she focuses her analysis on the provision itself which combines mandatory imprisonment with absolute liability in the regulatory context. She concludes that absolute liability does not in and of itself violate the principles of fundamental justice, and then considers whether it does so when combined with mandatory imprisonment as under s. 94. She considers various theories of punishment, relying on the work of respected scholars and reform bodies, such as the Law Reform Commission of Canada, to conclude that absolute liability is only unconstitutional when it results in
mandatory imprisonment, as it does in this case.<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup>
<p>
B. A CONTEXTUALIZED APPROACH TO FUNDAMENTAL JUSTICE AND FAULT
<p>
What are we to gain from this seminal case which sets out guidelines for giving content to the principles of fundamental justice in the context of fault? I believe we can properly conclude that in defining a framework for the principles of fundamental justice, a court should look to the common law, to works of legal writers, and to law reform bodies to obtain evidence of the basic tenets of the legal system. 
<p>
Having stated that the framework for the principles of fundamental justice can be derived from these sources, it must nonetheless be acknowledged that such principles will be difficult to delineate and state in a conclusive manner. The difficulty in reducing an intricate and interactive web of principles to a number of relatively simple propositions is obvious. Indeed, it is likely that attempts by the courts to articulate such propositions will fail to
incorporate the richness and diversity of the underlying tenets of our justice system. This is a hazard inherent in the
constitutionalization of fault.
<p>
Wilson J.'s approach in the <cite>Motor Vehicle Reference</cite> is enlightening because it highlights the importance of scrutinizing the basic tenets of the justice system as they relate to fault from a perspective which focuses specifically on the issue under review. Her approach is contextual in nature and is carried out within the
close confines of the particular issue, namely the constitutionality of absolute liability combined with mandatory imprisonment in the context of a regulatory offence.
<p>
Within the framework of the fault analysis under s. 7 of the <cite>Charter</cite>, a contextual approach recognizes that different factors may assume more or less prominence depending on the offence under scrutiny. The sources alluded to earlier---the common law, academic writers, and law reform commissions---assist in identifying those
factors which are significant for each offence in order to identify the relevant principles of fundamental justice which should be considered. For example, the need for proportionality between punishment and moral blameworthiness is a recurring theme throughout the criminal law, and it is the focus of studies by academic lawyers
and law reform commissions. Since a penalty upon conviction is a common element in all offences, an assessment of proportionality should play a role in the fault analysis of all offences. 
<p>
In contrast, stigma, which is a striking feature in the offence of murder, has little relevance in other offences. Furthermore, outside the context of murder, the notion of stigma becomes conceptually uncertain. As will be discussed below, although the Court has formulated a doctrine of stigma which it has applied to the fault
analysis in all cases but one,<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> it has not defined what stigma is, nor how it is to be assessed. Therefore, while stigma may assume a dominant role in the fault analysis for murder, it should play a minor role in relation to other offences.
<p>
A contextual approach to the fault analysis would preclude the application of factors which have little relevance to the specific offence in question. Furthermore, a contextual analysis makes it difficult for the Court to ignore features of an offence which have been recognized as anomalous in our justice system. For example, as will be seen below, the Court's treatment of constructive liability outside the offence of murder is deficient in part because the Court does not use a contextual approach in its analysis. 
<p>
A contextual approach avoids resolving the issues in the abstract, thereby restricting the ambit of the propositions put forward by the Court in a particular case to the specific offence under scrutiny. In the <cite>Motor Vehicle Reference</cite>, Lamer J. decontextualizes his analysis by situating the discussion at an abstract level.  He carries out his analysis of whether absolute liability is contrary to the principles of fundamental justice within the framework of the criminal common law at large, not within the narrow regulatory context of s. 94. He concludes that absolute liability when combined with the potential for imprisonment violates s. 7 of the <cite>Charter</cite>.  The proposition thus stated is broader than it needed to have been in order to deal with the provision under review in the <cite>Motor Vehicle Reference</cite>. 
<p>
The utility of a contextual approach has been approved by the Court in other situations. In <cite>R. v. Morgentaler</cite>, the majority opinion, written by Dickson C.J.C.,  stressed the importance of exploring the rights protected by s. 7 of the <cite>Charter</cite> within the context of the case before the Court. Dickson C.J.C. stated:
<blockquote>
I prefer to rest my conclusions on a narrower analysis than that put forward on behalf of the appellants. I do not think it would be appropriate to attempt an all-encompassing explication of so important a provision as s. 7 so early in the history of <cite>Charter</cite> interpretation. The Court should be presented with a wide variety of claims and factual situations before articulating the full range of s. 7 rights.<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Wilson J. advocated use of a contextual approach in the s. 1 <cite>Charter</cite> analysis in <cite>Edmonton Journal v. Alta. (A.G.)</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> The issue in <cite>Edmonton Journal</cite> was whether a provincial law prohibiting media reporting of matrimonial disputes violated s. 2(b) of the <cite>Charter</cite>. Wilson J., writing for herself, agreed with the majority that the law violated freedom of
expression, but noted that she had reached her conclusion based on a different approach from the majority. Cory J., for the majority, analyzed the s. 2(b) right at an abstract level. In Wilson's opinion, the more desirable approach was one which considered the values being protected in the context of the particular case. Thus while an abstract approach would characterize the right sought to be protected as the right to &quot;the free exchange of ideas and opinions in a democratic form of society,&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> Wilson J. described the rights at stake as &quot;the right of litigants to the protection of their privacy in matrimonial disputes and the right of the public to an open court process.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup> She noted:
<blockquote>
The contextual approach attempts to bring into sharp relief the aspect of the right or freedom which is truly at stake in the case as well as the relevant aspects of any values in competition with it. It seems to be more sensitive to the reality of the dilemma posed by the particular facts and therefore more conducive to finding a fair and just compromise between the two competing values under s. 1.<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The contextual approach to the s. 1 analysis advocated by Wilson J. was expressly approved by Dickson C.J.C. in <cite>R. v. Keegstra</cite><sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> and by McLachlin J. in <cite>Rocket v. Royal College of Dental Surgeons of Ontario</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> In <cite>R. v. Wholesale Travel Group Inc.</cite>, Cory J. cited Wilson J.'s remarks in <cite>Edmonton Journal</cite> with approval and noted, &quot;[i]t is now clear that the <cite>Charter</cite> is to be interpreted in light of the context in which the claim arises. <i>Context is relevant both with respect to the delineation of the meaning and scope of</i> Charter <i>rights</i>, as well as to the determination of the balance to be struck [under the s. 1 analysis].&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup>
<p>
Although in <cite>Edmonton Journal</cite> Wilson J. was referring to the balancing of rights under s. 1 of the <cite>Charter</cite>, it is apparent from her approach in the <cite>Motor Vehicle Reference</cite> that she
implicitly, if not explicitly, advocates a similar approach to the s. 7 analysis. Arguably, the contextual approach would be equally useful in &quot;bring[ing] into sharp relief&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> the basic tenets of the justice system relating to fault for a particular offence. 
<p>
I believe that the importance of carrying out the fault analysis in the context of the provision under scrutiny cannot be overemphasized. When the analysis is carried out in the abstract, there is a temptation to overstate principles in an effort to settle the issue. By predetermining issues before they actually arise in a case where a particular <cite>Criminal Code</cite> provision is under scrutiny, the Court runs the risk of foreclosing a principled, multi-faceted debate when the issue does arise at some later time. Where the issue is as convoluted and complex as fault, the risk is magnified. Indeed, an abstract approach to the fault analysis may render future consideration of fault in a particular case one-dimensional and unworkable.
<p>
A contextualized approach is crucial for determining the fault required for each offence in a meaningful and coherent manner. Only through this narrow, issue-based approach can complexities and nuances relating to fault be fully recognized and accounted for. It is counterproductive to cast the net too widely and state the principles of fundamental justice in the abstract. It is similarly counterproductive to develop a narrow principle in one situation and seek to apply it in the fault analysis for all cases. I suggest that this is what the Court has done by extending the doctrine of stigma, which was formulated in the context of murder, to other offences. While the notion of stigma is particularly apt in the context of murder, it has little value in a comparative fault analysis for other offences.
<p>
<h3>Stigma</h3>

A. EARLY APPLICATION OF THE CONCEPT OF STIGMA: THE MURDER CASES
<p>
The doctrine of stigma is first articulated in cases dealing with constructive murder. In <cite>R. v. Vaillancourt</cite>,<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> the Supreme Court of Canada struck down s. 213(d) of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite> because it was contrary to ss. 7 and 11(d) of the <cite>Charter</cite>. Seven judges, over the sole dissent of McIntyre J., held that s. 7 requires at least objective foresight of death for a conviction of murder. Section 213(d) did not meet this test, since it declared that, if death resulted from the use of a weapon during the commission of certain offences, including robbery, the accused was automatically guilty of murder. The majority held that s. 213(d) could not be saved under s. 1 of the <cite>Charter</cite>.
<p>
Section 213(d) provided:
<blockquote>
213. Culpable homicide is murder where a person causes the death of a human being while committing or attempting to commit [listed offences], whether or not the person means to cause death to any human being and whether or not he knows that death is likely to be caused to any human being, if
<p>
. . .
<p>
(d) he uses a weapon or has it upon his person
<blockquote>
(i) during or at the time he commits or attempts to commit the offence, or 
<p>
(ii) during or at the time of his flight after committing or attempting to commit the offence, 
</blockquote>
and the death ensues as a consequence.<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The only <i>mens rea</i> required for a conviction was the intent to commit (or attempt to commit) the underlying offence and the intent to use a weapon, or have it upon one's person. It was irrelevant whether the accused intended to cause bodily harm or death.
<p>
In <cite>Vaillancourt</cite>, Lamer J. first reviews the history of the constructive murder provisions and concludes that its origins are questionable.<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> He then canvasses academic criticisms and case law which support the conclusion that the law should be abolished. He also notes that the Law Reform Commission of Canada criticized s. 213 in <cite>Homicide</cite> (1984), Working Paper 33<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup> and excluded constructive murder from its Draft Criminal Code.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> Lamer J. describes constructive murder as a &quot;peculiarly common law concept which appears to be unknown outside a circle of common law jurisdictions, and it has not fared well within those jurisdictions.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> The rule was abolished in the United Kingdom in 1957, but is still quite widely accepted in the United States. Even in the United States, however, Lamer J. notes that the rule is in decline. Where it is still in force, its scope has been severely narrowed by limiting the underlying felonies on which it is predicated. Lamer J.'s survey of other jurisdictions provides convincing authority that constructive murder as a basis for criminal liability is suspect. 
<p>
At this point, Lamer J. focuses the discussion on s. 7. He states that, &quot;[u]nder section 7, if a conviction, given either the stigma attached to the offence or the available penalties, will result in the deprivation of life, liberty or security of the person, then Parliament must respect the principles of fundamental justice.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup>
<p>
Lamer J. finds that, due to the high degree of stigma associated with a conviction for murder and its penalties, the principles of fundamental justice require a level of <i>mens rea</i> which reflects the particular nature of the crime. Writing for four justices, he stops just short of holding that subjective foresight of death is required for a murder conviction. For now, he is content to find that s. 7 principles of fundamental justice require at least objective foresight of death.<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup>
<p>
Few can argue with Lamer J.'s characterization of murder as the most serious offence in our society. His observation regarding the stigma attached to a conviction for murder is similarly incontrovertible.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> Indeed, the (U.K.) Criminal Law Revision Committee in its report on offences against the person<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> recognized that the stigma associated with the offence of murder serves a deterrent purpose and is one of the principal justifications for retaining the separate offences of murder and manslaughter.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> However, we must ask whether the concept of stigma should even be the dominant factor which determines the constitutionally required level of fault for murder, or indeed any crime.
<p>
Lamer J.'s use of stigma becomes increasingly problematic when he extends the stigma analysis to theft. He states in <cite>Vaillancourt</cite>:
<blockquote>
. . . there are, though very few in number, certain crimes where, because of the special nature of the stigma attached to the conviction therefor or the available penalties, the principles of fundamental justice require a <i>mens rea</i> reflecting the particular nature of that crime. Such is theft, where, in my view, a conviction requires some proof of dishonesty. Murder is another such offence.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Lamer J. has taken the analysis out of the context of murder and into the realm of an offence which is not before the
Court. He overreaches the particular issue which is being appealed by finding that stigma is relevant to other offences, including theft. Outside the context of murder, the concept of stigma is conceptually uncertain. It is not self-evident that significant stigma attaches to a conviction for theft. This example confuses the issue. Nor does Lamer J. say specifically how stigma is to be assessed. Is it to be assessed intuitively by the courts (seemingly
the method used in <cite>Vaillancourt</cite>) or against community standards? Either way, the stigma test appears to suffer from vagueness and unpredictability of results.
<p> 
In <cite>Martineau</cite>,<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> Lamer, now as Chief Justice, employs the same analytical techniques. Writing for five members of the Court,<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup> he holds that murder requires subjective foresight of death. Although only one of the constructive murder provisions (s. 213(a)) was at issue in <cite>Martineau</cite>, the majority strikes down the remaining three constructive murder provisions (ss 213(a)-(c)) and strikes the words &quot;ought to know&quot; from s. 212(c) [now s. 229(c)] because they are indicative of an objective standard. Lamer C.J.C. holds that subjective foresight of death is required for any conviction of murder, even though it is not necessary to resolve the case:
<blockquote>
[In <cite>Vaillancourt</cite>] I concluded that objective foreseeability of death was the minimum threshold test before a conviction for murder could be sustained. I went on to state, however, that it was my view that the principles of fundamental justice require more; they demand that a conviction for murder requires proof beyond a reasonable doubt of subjective foresight of death. . . . I am still of that view today, and indeed, while I agree with the Alberta Court of Appeal and <i>could dispose of the appeal on the basis of objective foreseeability, it is on the basis
of the principle of subjective foresight of death that I choose to dispose of this appeal</i>.<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Lamer C.J.C.'s reasons in <cite>Martineau</cite> are brief. He states that &quot;the principles of fundamental justice require, because of the special nature of the stigma attached to a conviction for murder, and the available penalties&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> subjective foresight of death. In the next sentence he says: &quot;The effect of s. 213 is to violate the principle that punishment must be proportionate to the moral blameworthiness of the offender. . . .&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup> This principle of
proportionality is conceptually distinct from stigma and is arguably a more reliable indicator of the fault level required. Of the two concepts---stigma or proportionality with the penalty that will be imposed---surely the latter is more reliably grounded in the principles of fundamental justice and more suitable as a basis for the fault analysis.
<p>
The punishment for murder is the most severe punishment meted out under our <cite>Criminal Code</cite>. It involves a substantial deprivation of liberty. The moral blameworthiness required for a conviction of murder must also be substantial, in proportion to the punishment. Negligence and objective foresight, in light of the severe penalties, will not suffice. Subjective foresight is required. Stigma relates to society's view of the accused;
proportionality focuses on whether the severity of the punishment matches the moral culpability of the accused. If we ask whether stigma is pivotal, or determinative, of the constitutionally required degree of fault the answer is no. 
<p>
In <cite>Martineau</cite>, there is a sense that the Court is rushing the process of constitutionalization of fault. Sopinka J., writing for himself but concurring in the result, sounds a note of caution:
<blockquote>
. . . the issue of subjective foresight of death should be addressed only if it is necessary to do so in order to decide this case or if there is an overriding reason to make it desirable to do so. Overbroad statements of principle are inimical to the tradition of incremental development of the common law. Likewise, the development of law under the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite> is best served by deciding cases before the courts, not by
anticipating the results of future cases.<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Sopinka J. concludes that there was no overriding reason to decide the issue of subjective foresight in <cite>Martineau</cite>. Furthermore, he recognizes the danger in making a decision regarding the validity of provisions on which neither the parties nor the interveners have made submissions. Lamer C.J.C. justifies making a
determination of issues which are not before the Court on the basis of the participation of a large number of Attorneys General in the case as interveners. Sopinka J. states, however: &quot;. . . it is not strictly accurate to state that the Attorneys General intervened on the issue [of the constitutionality of s. 212(c) or ss 213(b)-(c)]. . . . I am not convinced that the submissions of the Attorneys General, not to mention the parties, would have been the same had s. 212(c) or other sections been challenged.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> Sopinka J. holds that only s. 213(a) is unconstitutional because it does not require proof of objective foresight. He concludes, &quot;[o]ther constitutional issues with respect to the murder provisions of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite> I would leave for another day.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup>
 <p>
The Supreme Court released its decision in <cite>Logan</cite><sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> on the same day as <cite>Martineau</cite>. <cite>Logan</cite> dealt with the required level of fault for a conviction of attempted murder by parties to an offence under s. 21(2). Section 21(2) made an accessory criminally responsible on an objective standard for any offence which he or she knew, or ought to have known, the principal was likely to commit. Under s. 21(2), it was therefore possible to judge a principal on a subjective standard while judging the
accessory on an objective standard for the same offence. In dealing with the fault requirement under this section, Lamer C.J.C. states: &quot;[w]ith respect, I cannot construe <cite>Vaillancourt</cite> as saying that, as a general proposition, Parliament cannot ever enact provisions requiring different levels of guilt for principal offenders and parties.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> However, if the offence is &quot;one of the few for which s. 7 requires a minimum degree of <i>mens rea</i>, <cite>Vaillancourt</cite> does preclude Parliament from providing for the conviction of a party to that offence on the basis of a degree of <i>mens rea</i> below the constitutionally required minimum.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> The majority therefore holds that the words &quot;ought to have known&quot; in s. 21(2) are inoperative in cases where the principal offence requires subjective foresight for conviction. 
<p>
Lamer C.J.C. finds that subjective foresight of death is required for the offence of attempted murder because the completed crime requires that degree of fault. The majority in <cite>Logan</cite> appears to settle the constitutional question of fault for attempted murder on the logic that the <i>mens rea</i> for the attempt should be the same as the <i>mens rea</i> for the completed crime.
<p>
In referring to the fault required for attempted murder, Lamer C.J.C. says that stigma, not the available penalties, is the primary factor in determining the constitutionally required level of fault. He states: &quot;[i]t should be noted that, as a basis for a constitutionally required minimum degree of <i>mens rea</i>, the social stigma associated with a conviction is the most important consideration, not the sentence.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> This statement seems to be at odds with the dual emphasis in <cite>Martineau</cite> on stigma and proportionality between the punishment and the moral blameworthiness of the offender. Lamer C.J.C.'s reasons for moving away from reliance on proportionality may be that the punishment for attempted murder is not always as severe as the
punishment for murder. He uses the example of theft to illustrate his rationale for giving primacy to stigma. He notes that the penalties for theft range from a maximum of six months, if the Crown elects to proceed summarily, to a maximum of ten years on the indictable charge. &quot;Whether the actual or available punishment is severe or not, the social stigma associated with being labelled dishonest will be automatically and unavoidably imposed upon
conviction.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> Lamer C.J.C. apparently decides that he must distance the &quot;penalty&quot; side of the test in <cite>Vaillancourt</cite> from the analysis in <cite>Logan</cite>. He therefore states that stigma is the primary consideration in matching the <i>mens rea</i> of the attempt to the <i>mens rea</i> of the completed crime.
<p>
This was unnecessary. As L'Heureux-Dub&eacute; J. reasons in her judgment, when mere attempts are at issue, <i>mens rea</i> assumes a dominant role.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> While there must be both <i>mens rea</i> and an <i>actus reus</i> to constitute an attempt, the criminality of the misconduct lies mainly
in the intention of the accused. The rationale for requiring subjective foresight for attempt crimes &quot;radiates from the primacy of the <i>mens rea</i> component, not from any potential penalties or social stigma that might attend conviction for the completed offence.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup>
<p>
In both the <cite>Martineau</cite> and <cite>Logan</cite> majority reasons, there is no attempt to canvass the common law, writings of academic and other lawyers, or findings and recommendations of law reform bodies in order to build a framework of the principles of fundamental justice as they specifically relate to the provision under
scrutiny.<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> Lamer C.J.C. starts the analysis in both decisions from where he
left off in <cite>Vaillancourt</cite>, using the concept of stigma to resolve the required level of fault for the offence. As noted, while the concept of stigma has some value as a factor for determining the required degree of fault in the context of murder as the offence which attracts the harshest punishments, outside this context its value as a tool is limited because of its conceptual uncertainty. Furthermore, in the context of other offences, as the  examination of <cite>Logan</cite> above begins to illustrate, reliance on the doctrine of stigma circumvents a principled and fully contextual analysis.
<p>
B. THE ELASTICITY OF STIGMA AND ITS LIMITATIONS AS AN ANALYTICAL TOOL
<p>
The Court first extends the doctrine of stigma beyond the offence of murder in <cite>DeSousa</cite><sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup> where it considers the constitutionally required degree of fault for the offence of unlawfully causing bodily harm (s. 269 of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>). In <cite>DeSousa</cite>, the weakness of the Supreme Court's analysis in the murder cases becomes immediately apparent. A unanimous bench of five justices<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> declares that, absent very special stigma, objective fault is
constitutionally sufficient for any type of offence. 
<p>
In <cite>DeSousa</cite>, the Court holds that the offence of unlawfully causing bodily harm does not violate s. 7. The Court interprets s. 269 to require two separate mental elements. First, the mental element of the underlying offence must be satisfied: the bodily harm must be caused as a result of an &quot;unlawful act.&quot;  The Court holds that to be unlawful, either federal or provincial offences can qualify, but not offences based on absolute liability or those which have a constitutionally insufficient mental element of their own. Second, Sopinka J. interprets the offence to require that the unlawful act be at least objectively dangerous. The test, borrowed from British case law on unlawful act manslaughter, is whether a reasonable person would realize that the underlying unlawful act would subject another person to the risk of bodily harm.
<p>
The s. 7 analysis is brief. Sopinka J. states: 
<blockquote>
As this Court has not indicated that fundamental justice requires fault based on a subjective standard for all offences, the mental element required by s. 269 passes constitutional muster unless s. 269 is one of those few offences which due to its stigma and penalty require fault based on a subjective standard. I agree with the respondent [Crown] and interveners that s. 269 has neither the stigma nor criminal sanction to require a more demanding mental element than it already has.<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Sopinka J. does not set out a framework for the principles of fundamental justice at issue in the context of unlawfully causing bodily harm. The Court gives no substantive consideration to whether the offence of unlawfully causing bodily harm should be interpreted as one which does require subjective foresight of the risk of harm. In addition, Sopinka J. further abstracts the analysis from the context of the offence under consideration by basing his analysis on the law relating to unlawful act manslaughter. His conclusions arise from the concept of stigma and he thereby circumvents a contextual analysis of fault.
<p>
We can now see the danger inherent in developing a test which has narrow applicability to the context of murder and applying it in all cases. Its elastic nature makes stigma difficult to assess in any principled manner. How is the severe stigma associated with theft to be compared with the stigma associated with unlawfully causing bodily harm?  Theft in a particular set of circumstances may have a great deal of stigma attached to it. Theft in another context may have very little. Similarly, unlawfully causing bodily harm in some circumstances may attract very low stigma; in others, a significantly higher level may be involved, depending on how the offence was carried out.
<p>
<cite>DeSousa</cite>, Sopinka J. tacitly approves constructive liability in <cite>Criminal Code</cite> offences, without acknowledging that this contradicts the Court's rejection of constructive liability in <cite>Vaillancourt</cite> and <cite>Martineau</cite>.<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> He states in <i>obiter</i> that there is no common law or constitutional principle that requires fault to be related to each of the elements of the <i>actus reus</i> of the offence. He goes further and notes that there are a number of <cite>Criminal Code</cite> offences which &quot;call for a more serious charge if certain consequences follow. To require intention in relation to each and every consequence would bring a large number of offences into question. . . .&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup> Sopinka J. lists 13 other <cite>Criminal Code</cite> offences, including manslaughter, where this would be the case. His comments are <i>obiter</i> and they are clearly unnecessary to determine the fault required for the offence under consideration. Nor are his comments reflective of the position taken by modern law reform commissions or academic writers that fault must relate to the penalized consequence or circumstances which form part of the <i>actus reus</i>.<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> As Stuart puts it, &quot;[a] test of foresight, whether subjective or objective, has little meaning if it exists in the air and does not fully relate to the consequences.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> Arguably, in taking his analysis outside the context of the offence in question, Sopinka J. has significantly foreclosed the fault discussion in future cases where any of the listed offences he addresses in <i>obiter</i> may be under scrutiny. 
<p>
In fact, in <cite>Creighton</cite><sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup> a majority of the Court does rely on <cite>DeSousa</cite> to hold that objective foresight of harm meets the constitutional fault requirements for unlawful act manslaughter under s. 222(5) of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> McLachlin J. (L'Heureux-Dub&eacute;, Gonthier and Cory JJ. concurring)
notes that <cite>DeSousa</cite> has determined that the fact that an offence depends upon a predicate offence does not render it unconstitutional, provided that the predicate offence involves a dangerous act, is not an offence of absolute liability, and is not unconstitutional. 
<p>
McLachlin J. finds that the test for unlawful act manslaughter is objective foreseeability of a risk of bodily harm which is neither trivial nor transitory. She relies on Sopinka J.'s <i>obiter</i> comments in <cite>DeSousa</cite> for the proposition that subjective foreseeability of the risk of the <i>actus reus</i> is not required. She also holds, although it was not necessary to address the issue in this case, that the <i>mens rea</i> for manslaughter by criminal negligence should also be assessed according to an objective standard. Her discussion relating to criminal negligence is in the nature of an aside:
<blockquote>
The cases establish that in addition to the <i>actus reus</i> and <i>mens rea</i> associated with the underlying act, all that is required to support a manslaughter conviction is reasonable foreseeability of the risk of bodily harm. While s. 222(5)(a) does not expressly require foreseeable bodily harm, it has been so interpreted: see <cite>R. v. DeSousa</cite>, <i>supra</i>. The unlawful act must be objectively dangerous, that is likely to injure
another person. The law of unlawful act manslaughter has not, however, gone so far as to require foreseeability of death. The same is true for manslaughter predicated on criminal negligence; while criminal negligence, <i>infra</i>, requires a marked departure from the standards of a reasonable person in all the circumstances, it
does not require foreseeability of death.<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Having found the mental element at common law for unlawful act manslaughter and criminal negligence to be objective foreseeability of harm which is neither trivial nor transitory, McLachlin J. proceeds to determine whether this mental element accords with the principles of fundamental justice.
<p>
She reasons that the objective test based on foreseeability of harm does not violate the principles of fundamental justice because it is entirely appropriate to the stigma associated with the offence of manslaughter. She disagrees with Lamer C.J.C., who characterizes the stigma associated with manslaughter as high enough to justify objective foreseeability of death.
<blockquote>
To the extent that stigma is relied on as requiring foreseeability of the risk of death in the offence of manslaughter, I
find it unconvincing. The most important feature of the stigma of manslaughter is the stigma which is <i>not</i> attached to it. The <cite>Criminal Code</cite> confines manslaughter to non-intentional homicide. A person convicted of manslaughter is <i>not</i> a murderer.<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup>
</blockquote>
McLachlin J.'s reasoning has a perplexing circularity: &quot;. . . the stigma attached to manslaughter is an appropriate stigma.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup>
<p>
McLachlin J. then finds that the relationship between the required <i>mens rea</i> and the penalty for manslaughter is appropriate because of the flexibility available with respect to sentencing. &quot;Murder entails a mandatory life sentence; manslaughter carries with it no minimum sentence. This is appropriate. Because manslaughter can occur in a wide variety of circumstances, the penalties must be flexible.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup>
<p>
The notion of stigma, on which her reasoning hinges, has allowed McLachlin J. to overcome the subjective hurdle. However, this points to the problem with using stigma: its elasticity makes it capable of being manipulated at will. In <cite>Creighton</cite>, for example, one senses that McLachlin J. has tailored her assessment of the stigma associated with a conviction of manslaughter to suit the desired outcome. The fact that the actual circumstances of the killing in <cite>Creighton</cite> themselves could give rise to a high degree of stigma is not factored into her analysis.<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup>
<p>
In <cite>Creighton</cite>, Lamer C.J.C. (Sopinka, Iacobucci, and Major JJ. concurring) also agrees that an objective standard is appropriate for unlawful act manslaughter. 
<blockquote>
The only basis upon which subjective foresight of death or the risk of death could be found to be constitutionally required in the case of unlawful act manslaughter, therefore, would be to find that the offence is one of those crimes for which `because of the special nature of the stigma attached to a conviction therefor or the available penalties the principles of fundamental justice require a <i>mens rea</i> reflecting the particular nature of that
crime.'<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Lamer C.J.C. concludes that the stigma which attaches to unlawful act manslaughter, while significant, does not approach the opprobrium reserved for those special offences. He finds, however, that the stigma attaching to manslaughter is sufficiently high to require, at a minimum, objective foresight of the risk of death. As we have seen, McLachlin J. used the stigma analysis to reach the conclusion that objective foresight need only relate to the risk of
harm, not death. These divergent findings highlight the weakness of the doctrine of stigma as a basis for determining the constitutionally required degree of fault. 
<p>
In the companion cases to <cite>Creighton</cite> (<cite>Naglik, Gosset</cite>, and <cite>Finlay</cite>), application of the stigma analysis is formulaic: first, assess the fault required by the <cite>Criminal Code</cite> provision at issue (based on precedent, statutory interpretation, and legislative intent), second, determine that the
stigma associated with the offence is not particularly high, and finally, conclude that an objective standard will meet the constitutionally required level of fault as defined by the chosen degree of stigma. In none of these cases does the Court carry out a contextual analysis of the fault associated with the provision under review. The analysis turns on the manipulatable criterion of stigma.
<p>
C. <cite>HUNDAL</cite>:  APPLYING A CONTEXTUALIZED ANALYSIS
<p>
<cite>DeSousa</cite> and <cite>Creighton</cite> stand in direct opposition to <cite>Hundal</cite>,<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup> in which the Court carries out a contextual fault analysis without reference to stigma. At issue in <cite>Hundal</cite> was the constitutionality of the dangerous driving provision of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>, s. 233 (now s. 249). Section 233 does not specify the degree of fault required for conviction. Cory J. finds that &quot;the law with regard to driving offences is a mess.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup> A survey of earlier cases dealing with the section reveals that the requisite <i>mens rea</i> has ranged from something &quot;more than inadvertent negligence&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> to a &quot;standard of care that a prudent driver would have exercised. . .  .&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup> Cory J. (L'Heureux-Dub&eacute;, Sopinka, Gonthier, and Iacobucci JJ. concurring) favours an objective standard but notes that the constitutionality of an objective standard will depend on the elements of the particular provision and its context. The Court's analysis is grounded in the
context of the specific offence under review and in the facts of this particular case.
<p>
Cory J. does not find the constitutionality of s. 233 to be self-evident. He undertakes a principled analysis to justify his conclusion that a modified objective standard for dangerous driving is, in fact, constitutional. He states that the test for negligence is objective, requiring a &quot;marked departure from the standard of care of a reasonable person,&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup> and advocates a &quot;clear distinction in the law between one who has been aware (pure subjective intent) and one who should have taken care irrespective of awareness (pure objective intent).&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup>
<p>
He notes that driving is a licensed activity which is often automatic and reflexive: &quot;[i]t would be a denial of common sense for a driver, whose conduct was objectively dangerous, to be acquitted on the ground that he was not thinking of his manner of driving at the time of the accident.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup> He describes negligent driving as &quot;a continuum that progresses, or regresses, from momentary lack of attention giving rise to civil responsibility through careless driving under a provincial Highway Traffic Act to dangerous driving under the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> Cory J. considers the wording of the section and the public policy underlying the offence, and concludes that a modified objective test which takes into account the circumstances surrounding the offence is appropriate.<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup>
<p>
In <cite>Hundal</cite>, the Court asserts that mere unreasonable behaviour will not suffice for a conviction. A conviction will require a gross departure from the standard of care of a reasonable person. In separate reasons, McLachlin J. (Lamer C.J.C. concurring) sets out justifications for taking the objective approach in criminal
negligence which have been put forward by various academic writers:
<blockquote>
It follows that a dangerous or repugnant act, coupled with want of care representing a marked departure from the standard of a reasonable person in all the circumstances, may constitute a criminal offence. To accept the appellant's submission that in all criminal cases the Crown must establish subjective <i>mens rea</i> would be to put the range of culpable conduct described by Stuart, Rosenberg and Stalker---conduct which has long formed part of our criminal law---beyond the law's reach. That, to me, does not make sense.<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup>
</blockquote>
McLachlin J. expressly agrees with Cory J. that &quot;there should be a clear distinction in the law between one who was aware (pure subjective intent) and one who should have taken care irrespective of awareness (pure objective intent).&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup>
<p>
I believe that the analysis in <cite>Hundal</cite> leads to a supportable outcome. The judgments go only as far as necessary to resolve the issues before the Court. The decision accords with the view of most judges, writers, and law commissions that there is a philosophical and just basis for punishing someone who was not aware of the risk but who ought to have been.<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup> In the context of criminal negligence, the attractiveness of the objective test is that it takes into account two important factors: whether the wrongdoer was &quot;on notice&quot; that his conduct was potentially harmful (and yet he did not take heed), and whether the mistake that the wrongdoer made was unreasonable. If both are present, then we may describe his conduct as that which a reasonable person would not have pursued in the circumstances. In such cases, we are willing to say that inadvertence to risk, as well as choosing to take a particular risk, may warrant the just censure of others. In other words, when the circumstances give the actor reason to think that his conduct risks harm to another, his failure to take notice of the risks associated with his conduct is culpable. In such cases, it can be argued that negligence may support sanctions as convincingly as does intentional conduct. Hence, in applying the objective standard of fault to the accused's conduct in the circumstances of <cite>Hundal</cite>, Cory J. found that the &quot;appellant's manner of driving represented a gross departure from the standard of a reasonably prudent driver&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup> in the circumstances of the accident.
<p>
D. THE ANOMALY OF CONSTRUCTIVE LIABILITY AND ITS PERSISTENCE IN SUPREME COURT JURISPRUDENCE
<p>
One of the disturbing aspects in the Supreme Court's treatment of the constitutional aspects of fault is the persistence
of constructive liability without appropriate consideration of its implications within the general framework of criminal liability. Although the Court rejected the constructive murder rule in <cite>Vaillancourt</cite> and <cite>Martineau</cite>, it has given tacit approval to constructive liability in <cite>DeSousa</cite> and upheld the constructive crime of unlawful act manslaughter in <cite>Creighton</cite>, without substantiating its position through analysis.<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup> In neither of these cases does the Court directly address the fact that constructive liability is at issue. The Court avoids the issue by divorcing its analysis from the context of the offence and the circumstances of each case and focusing instead on stigma. 
<p>
The most powerful manifestation of constructive liability is the felony-murder rule which provides that if a person is killed during the commission of a felony, the felon is criminally liable not only for the felony but also for the death, which is treated as murder. According to the traditional doctrine, the death constitutes murder even though the felon did not intend to kill. The felony-murder rule was held to be unconstitutional in <cite>Vaillancourt</cite> and <cite>Martineau</cite>.
<p>
Another constructive liability offence at common law, the misdemeanour-manslaughter rule, is codified in s. 222(5) of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite> as unlawful act manslaughter. Unlawful act manslaughter takes the criminal intent or recklessness with respect to a (relatively minor)<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup> underlying offence, couples it with the harm caused (death), and constructs liability for the serious offence (manslaughter). Similarly, unlawfully causing bodily harm imports the logic of constructive liability in that an accused person can be found guilty without intending to bring about the consequence of bodily harm. 
<p>
Critics of constructive liability contend that it produces an unjust disproportionality between punishment and intent.<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> They argue that constructive liability is clearly unjust even where the unlawful act requires some element of subjective intent to be proved, because the accused is still being punished for an act which he neither desired nor intended. 
<p>
Other objections to constructive liability are often based on the argument that there must be a match between the <i>mens rea</i> and the <i>actus reus</i> which is prohibited. Where part of the <i>actus reus</i> consists of causing death (as in unlawful act manslaughter), then <i>mens rea</i> should relate to that consequence as well as to the unlawful act. Similarly, if part of the <i>actus reus</i> consists of causing injury (as in unlawfully causing
bodily harm), then the intention or recklessness must go to causing the injury as well as to the predicate offence. However, constructive liability requires no such connection between the <i>mens rea</i> and the <i>actus reus</i>.
<p>
Constructive liability has been justified on the basis of retribution and deterrence.<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup> It is argued that the felony-murder rule in particular is a retributive rule which is premised on society's belief that a killing committed in the course of a serious crime deserves the stigma of murder. Holding the accused liable for murder, it is argued, reaffirms society's belief in the sanctity of life, expresses solidarity with the victim, and serves to give the accused his just desserts.<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup>
Constructive liability, in general, is supposedly based on the relationship between dessert and consequences (instead of the relationship between dessert and intent). If a particular level of intent is present for certain consequences, this form of proportionality demands that the causation of more serious consequences is deserving of the more serious punishment.<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup>
<p>
Arguments put forward to justify felony murder, if persuasive at all, are less persuasive in the context of manslaughter.<sup><a href="#one01">101</a></sup> Since the underlying wrongful conduct in unlawful act
manslaughter may be less inherently dangerous than the conduct underlying a felony murder, it is arguably less worthy of condemnation and of punishment proportional to the actual consequences.<sup><a href="#one02">102</a></sup>
<p>
The offence of unlawfully causing bodily harm has an aspect of constructive liability if there is no requirement that there be reasonable foresight of the consequence of bodily harm. If an accused is engaged in some sort of unlawful behavior, and bodily harm which is unforeseeable results, under s. 269 the accused can be held liable for unlawfully causing bodily harm, which is possibly a more serious offence than the offence on which the bodily harm is predicated. In <cite>DeSousa</cite>, Sopinka J. explicitly states that there is no common law or constitutional principle that the fault requirement must relate to the consequences, as well as the unlawful act, which together form the elements of the <i>actus reus</i>. In so stating, he endorses constructive liability and the anomalies which accompany it. Sopinka J., however, does not address the issue. He does not canvass the common law, academic writers, and law reform commissions to build a framework in which to carry out his s. 7 analysis, and he thus avoids addressing the problems of constructive liability which arise within this framework. Although Sopinka J. holds that in this particular offence there must be objective foresight of bodily harm, he has at a theoretical level approved the
use of constructive liability in other <cite>Criminal Code</cite> offences, including manslaughter, without confronting and analyzing the issue.
<p>
In <cite>Creighton</cite>, the Court never acknowledges the link between unlawful act manslaughter and the common law offence of misdemeanour-manslaughter. Indeed, the issue of constructive liability is not addressed in any of the judgments in <cite>Creighton</cite>, although the main point in contention between McLachlin J. and Lamer C.J.C. is whether <i>mens rea</i> should relate to death or mere harm. The majority favours the latter view, thereby implicitly confirming the offence as one of constructive liability. McLachlin J. refers to Sopinka J.'s statement in <cite>DeSousa</cite> to justify her reasoning that the mental element of unlawful act manslaughter is reasonable foreseeability of the risk of bodily harm, in keeping with constructive liability principles:
<blockquote>
It is now settled that the fact that an offence depends upon a predicate offence does not render it unconstitutional, provided that the predicate offence involves a dangerous act, is not an offence of absolute liability, and is not unconstitutional: <cite>R. v. DeSousa</cite>, [1992] 2 S.C.R. 944. But a further objection is raised in this case. It is said that the offence of manslaughter is unconstitutional because it requires only foreseeability of the risk of bodily harm and not foreseeability of death, and that the trial judge erred in requiring only foreseeability of bodily  harm.
<p>
The cases establish that in addition to the <i>actus reus</i> and the <i>mens rea</i> associated with the underlying act, all that is required to support a manslaughter conviction is reasonable foreseeability of the risk of bodily harm.<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup>
</blockquote>
On McLachlin J.'s reasoning, an accused may be found guilty of the more serious offence of manslaughter where he committed a less serious offence as long as there was reasonable foresight of bodily harm. It is not necessary that the bodily harm be serious; it need only be &quot;neither trivial nor transitory.&quot;<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup> McLachlin J. has clearly defined the offence as one of constructive liability. 
<p>
Neither McLachlin J. nor Lamer C.J.C. situates the arguments in <cite>Creighton</cite> within the framework of constructive liability. Neither of them discusses the common law offence of misdemeanour-manslaughter. This is surprising, since the offence of unlawful act manslaughter so clearly resonates with constructive liability overtones. Neither of them addresses the perplexing anomaly of the Court's emphatic rejection of constructive liability in the context of murder and its acceptance of constructive liability in other contexts. Under a contextualized analysis, it would have been harder to ignore the widespread recognition of the doctrinal anomalies associated with constructive liability. It may be that constructive liability in these offences <i>is</i> compatible with the principles of fundamental justice. However, since the Court failed to address the issue, there is now a significant gap in its
reasoning.
<p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>

Within the framework of the fault analysis under s. 7 of the <cite>Charter</cite>, a contextual approach recognizes that different factors will assume prominence in determining which principles of fundamental justice are relevant to the offence under scrutiny. The Court should look to the common law, academic writers, and law reform commissions to assist in identifying such factors. A contextual analysis avoids resolving the issues in the abstract and thereby restricts the ambit of the propositions put forward by the Court in a particular case to the offence under scrutiny.
<p>
In <cite>Vaillancourt</cite>, Lamer C.J.C. utilized the doctrine of stigma as an analytical tool which was helpful in the context of the offence of murder. However, in extending the notion of stigma beyond the context of murder, the Court established a questionable framework of analysis for determining the constitutionally required degree of fault. 
<p>
Furthermore, outside the context of murder, the notion of stigma becomes conceptually uncertain. Stigma, with its inherent elasticity and malleability, cannot form the basis of a principled review. By characterizing the stigma of the offence as sufficiently low, a court can find negligence or objective <i>mens rea</i> to be sufficient to meet the constitutional standard set out in s. 7. The Court's reliance on the elastic notion of stigma has allowed it to short-circuit the analysis of the principles of fundamental justice surrounding each issue. In <cite>DeSousa</cite>, for example, Sopinka J. gives cursory attention to the analysis of the principles of fundamental justice which might require a court to find that a subjective standard of <i>mens rea</i> is constitutionally necessary. In so doing, he artificially divorces fault from its context. In <cite>Creighton</cite>, McLachlin J. proceeds on the assumption that the stigma associated with manslaughter is sufficiently low that she need not even consider whether subjective fault is required.
<p>
The Court's approval of constructive liability in <cite>DeSousa</cite> and <cite>Creighton</cite> is disturbing in light of its sound rejection of the constructive murder rule in <cite>Vaillancourt</cite>. The majority in <cite>Creighton</cite> did not address the element of constructive liability in unlawful act manslaughter and therefore did not adequately justify its position. This inconsistent treatment of constructive liability has resulted in a significant degree of incoherence in Canadian criminal law.
<p>
La Forest J.'s reasons in <cite>Creighton</cite> strike a rather ironic note. He states:
<blockquote>
I start with the fact that, both at the constitutional level and in the interpretation of offences, I favour where practicable the adoption of subjective rather than objective <i>mens rea</i>.; see, for example my concurrence with Wilson J. in <cite>R. v. Tutton</cite>, [1989] 1 S.C.R. 1392, a case dealing with manslaughter by criminal negligence. . . .
<p>
I was concerned about the application of the doctrine [of objective <i>mens rea</i>] to offences of a truly criminal character that apply to a wide variety of circumstances. However, any possibility of limiting objective <i>mens rea</i> to regulatory offences or offences having a regulatory base has now been overtaken by the unanimous decision of the panel (comprising a majority of the Court) in <cite>R. v. DeSousa</cite>.<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup>
</blockquote>
La Forest J.'s comments pinpoint a basic problem that has been created by the Supreme Court's review of the constitutional requirement for fault. By deciding once and for all what level of fault is required as a constitutional minimum, the Court has effectively ended the debate in Canada surrounding one of the fundamental perplexities of the criminal law. This might be acceptable were it not for the doubtful analytical techniques which the Court has used to reach its conclusions. By resorting to analytical techniques such as the doctrine of stigma which have allowed it to jump over the most significant hurdle in the fault analysis, namely, whether there is a requirement for subjective intent, the Court has avoided some of the most difficult questions surrounding the issue of criminal fault. The result of the Court's deliberations may be to strip from the law many of the nuances relating to fault that have shaped the very principles of fundamental justice that the Court is seeking to protect.
<p>
Parliament may enact, and the courts may interpret, any given provision to import a higher level of <i>mens rea</i> than is constitutionally required. However, in light of the outcome of the Supreme Court's deliberations, why should they do so?  Parliament can argue that it need only meet its constitutional obligations. The courts may reason that there is no need to go further.
<p>
The irony of the stigma analysis is that it was fashioned to bring the law into line with forward-looking criminal law principles. It later became the vehicle for circumventing a principled, contextualized consideration of fault. In the end, we are left with a statement about the constitutionally required level of fault which is too general, and which is predicated on an unworkable analysis. &quot;What the court is saying here is if Parliament wants to define a crime with an objective basis of liability---as long as it's not a `stigma' offence---then it will be constitutionally permissible for them to do so.&quot;<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup>
<p><br>
<hr>
