<li><a name="ninety2"><i>Ibid.</i> at 874.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="ninety3">See H.L.A. Hart,</a> &quot;Negligence, <i>mens rea</i>, and Criminal Responsibility&quot; <cite>Punishment and Responsibility: Essays in the Philosophy of Law</cite> (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1968) at 149--52; and G.P. Fletcher, &quot;The Theory of Criminal Negligence: A Comparative Analysis&quot; (1971) 119 U. Pa. L. Rev. 401. The Law Reform Commission of Canada in <cite>Recodifying Criminal Law</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 43 at 25, recommended the following definition of criminal negligence: &quot;[a] person is negligent as to conduct, circumstances or consequences if it is a marked departure from the ordinary standard of reasonable care to engage in such conduct, to take the risk (conscious or otherwise) that such consequences will result, or to take the risk (conscious or otherwise) that such circumstances obtain.&quot;  The Law Commission (U.K.)  recommended the following definition of &quot;negligently&quot; in
its Draft Criminal Code Bill: &quot;s. 22(b): a person acts `negligently' when his act is a very serious deviation from the standard of care to be expected of a reasonable person.&quot;  U.K., The Law Commission, <cite>Codification of the Criminal Law</cite> (London: H.M.S.O., 1985) at 184.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety4"><i>Supra</i> note 13 at 889.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="ninety5">Unlawful act manslaughter is considered in <cite>Creighton</cite></a>, <i>supra</i> note 2.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety6">With the collapse of the constructive</a> murder rule in Canada, serious unlawful acts such as robbery and aggravated sexual assault could theoretically come in under the unlawful act manslaughter rule. There is, however, little incentive for the Crown to proceed under unlawful act manslaughter for these serious offences since the penalties associated with the underlying act are frequently just as severe as the penalty imposed for manslaughter.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety7">See for example, D. Stuart,</a> <cite>Canadian Criminal Law: A Treatise</cite>, 2nd ed. (Toronto: Carswell, 1987) at 207--39. &quot;To one not versed in the intricacies of our homicide law, it will come as a shock that our most serious offences, murder and manslaughter, are exceptions to the pure <i>mens rea</i> principle which requires that the accused be actually aware of the relevant consequences and/or circumstances,&quot; <i>ibid.</i> at 207. Constructive liability has been described as &quot;a noxious doctrine in the criminal law&quot;: P. Healy, &quot;<cite>Creighton</cite> Quartet: Enigma Variations in a Lower Key&quot; (1993) 23 C.R. (4th) 265 at 269. See also A.J. Ashworth, &quot;The Elasticity of Mens Rea&quot; in <cite>Crime Proof and Punishment</cite> (London: Butterworths, 1981) 45 at 52; G.P. Fletcher, &quot;Reflections on Felony-Murder&quot; (1981) 12 Sw. U.L. Rev. 413; and J.J. Hippard, &quot;The Unconstitutionality of Criminal Liability Without Fault: An Argument for a Constitutional Doctrine of Mens Rea&quot; (1973) 10 Hous. L. Rev. 1039. The Law Reform Commission of Canada recommended the abolition of constructive murder in its working paper, <cite>Homicide</cite> (Working Paper No. 33), <i>supra</i> note 42 at 51: &quot;[t]o treat an unintentional killer as though he intended to kill involves the criminal law in artificiality and fictions and in the injustice of not treating significantly different cases differently.&quot;
<p>
<li><a name="ninety8">D. Crump &amp; S.W. Crump,</a> &quot;In Defense of the Felony Murder Doctrine&quot; (1985) 8 Harv. J. L. &amp; Pub. Pol'y 359 [hereinafter Crump]; G.P. Fletcher, &quot;Reflections on Felony-Murder&quot; <i>supra</i> note 97.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety9">Crump,</a> <i>ibid.</i> at 362--9. See also L.L. Weinrib, &quot;Desserts, Punishment, and Criminal Responsibility&quot; (1986) 49 Law and Contemp. Prob. 47 at 76.
<p>
<li><a name="onehundred">We see this reasoning in attempts:</a> whereas the same level of intent (and
hence the same level of blameworthiness) is present for the attempted crime and the completed crime, the criminal law punishes the completed crime more severely because the consequences of the attempt have materialized. In <cite>Recodifying Criminal Law</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 43 at 45, the Law Reform Commission of Canada recommended that the penalty for attempts should be set at half the penalty for the completed crime. The Commission's justification was that &quot;an attempter creates less actual harm than a successful committer.&quot;
<p>
<li><a name="one01">The Law Reform Commission of Canada</a> recommended that the doctrine of constructive liability should not define substantive offences. It therefore removed the offences of constructive murder, unlawful act manslaughter, and unlawfully causing bodily harm from its Draft Criminal Code. <cite>Recodifying Criminal Law</cite>, <i>ibid.</i> at 56--8 and 62.
<p>
<li><a name="one02">The (U.K.) Criminal Law Revision Committee</a> recommended abolition of unlawful act manslaughter declaring that &quot;[these cases] should not be treated as manslaughter because the offender's fault falls too far short of the unlucky result. So serious an offence as manslaughter should not be a lottery.&quot;  CLRC, <i>supra</i> note 48 at 56.
<p>
<li><a name="one03"><cite>Creighton</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 2 at 42--3 (McLachlin J.).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one04"><i>Ibid.</i> at 45.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one05"><i>Ibid.</i> at 37--8.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one06">Comment attributed to David Butt,</a> Ministry of the Attorney General and Crown Prosecutor who argued <cite>DeSousa</cite> and <cite>Naglik</cite> at the Supreme Court, as reported by C. Schmitz, &quot;SCC settles <i>mens rea</i> requirements for manslaughter, negligence offences&quot; <cite>The Lawyers Weekly</cite> (24 September 1993) 1 at 27.
</ol><p><br>
