<html>
<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 52 No. 1</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="v52n1.htm">Volume 52 Number 1</a>]</center><p><br>
<h1>The Unit of Taxation:
Current Canadian Issues<a href="#note">*</a>
<p> 
JOYCE M. CRAGO</h1>
<p><br>
<i>There has been a trend in Canada, particularly since the late 1960s, toward recognizing the marital unit rather than the individual as the appropriate unit for purposes of income taxation. In this article, the author examines the profound social policy choices underlying the choice of a tax unit. She illuminates the Canadian system by  comparing it and its development with the American system. She analyses the individual and family units of taxation using broad goals of a tax system and concludes that an individual system of taxation better meets the objectives of equity, neutrality and simplicity. From this ideal she goes on to show how the current Canadian tax system can be reformed by adopting the principled solution of an individual-based tax unit together with a family-based system of income maintenance.
<p>
La tendance au Canada, surtout depuis la fin des ann&eacute;es 60, a fait du couple mari&eacute; plut&ocirc;t que de l'individu l'unit&eacute; de base dans le calcul de l'imp&ocirc;t sur le revenu. Dans cet article, l'auteur examine la politique sociale profonde derri&egrave;re le choix d'une unit&eacute; de calcul d'imp&ocirc;ts. Elle fait la lumi&egrave;re sur le syst&egrave;me canadien en le comparant au syst&egrave;me am&eacute;ricain et en mettant en contraste le d&eacute;veloppement des deux syst&egrave;mes. Elle analyse les syst&egrave;mes de taxation sur une base individuelle et sur une base familiale en s'appuyant sur l'int&eacute;r&ecirc;t pr&eacute;sent&eacute; par chacun d'eux et conclut qu'un syst&egrave;me bas&eacute; sur l'individu r&eacute;pond mieux aux principes
d'&eacute;quit&eacute;, de neutralit&eacute; et de simplicit&eacute;. Prenant cet id&eacute;al comme point de d&eacute;part, elle d&eacute;montre comment on pourrait r&eacute;former le syst&egrave;me d'imposition sur le revenu actuel au Canada en adoptant la solution d'un calcul d'imp&ocirc;ts bas&eacute; sur l'individu, conjointement &agrave; un syst&egrave;me de revenus bas&eacute; sur la famille.</i>
<p><br>

<h3>I. Introduction</h3>

One of the fundamental choices that must be made in any system of taxation is to determine what the unit to be taxed will be. The choice of unit not only affects how the tax system is structured, it also has profound effects on society at large: it can promote certain types of family structures by providing them with economic incentives; it can affect a married woman's decision to work outside the home. This article demonstrates that the individual is the most justifiable unit of taxation. While this statement might seem uncontroversial---the individual has been used as the unit of taxation in Canada since 1917---there are many who advocate a change to a family unit of taxation because they view it as more in accord with reality. In fact, since the recommendation in 1966 by the Carter Commission<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> that the family be substituted as the basis of taxation in Canada, there has been recurring debate about such a change. Moreover, since 1966, while theoretically maintaining an individual unit of taxation, the Canadian tax system has gradually moved to recognize the family as the unit of taxation. At this time the debate has been intensified by the pressure that exists on Canada to harmonize its tax system with its biggest trading partner, the United States, which presently has a family taxation system. As well, there is a possibility that the outcome of several cases on income-splitting presently percolating through the Canadian court system could create renewed enthusiasm for the family unit. Calls for change are subtle, but may
spark serious debate at any time. This article attempts to inform such a debate.
<p>
In part II, this article will deal with the history of both the Canadian and the American systems of taxation, focusing on the change in the United States from an individual taxation system to a family taxation system and highlighting the problems which followed from that change. This article will then deal with the differences among the family unit proponents and emphasize how those differences point to a fundamental flaw within their arguments. In part III, this article will introduce the three objectives of a taxation system---equity, neutrality, and simplicity---and show how these objectives will always conflict and create policy difficulties, as well as how they can be used to evaluate the two units of taxation. This article will then analyse both units of taxation in depth using each of these three objectives in turn. Finally, in part IV, this article will outline factors other than the ideas written about in part III
which might influence a change to a family taxation system. The article then gives suggestions for changes to the present Canadian system which will make it more equitable and allow a principled solution to the perennial debate. It concludes that the best unit of taxation is individual-based, together with a family-based system of income maintenance.
<p>

<h3>II. The Present Canadian and American Taxation Systems and Their Evolution</h3>

As Canada and the United States both originally adopted the individual as the basic tax unit, it is instructive to see why the American system has developed so differently. Specifically, it is useful in any debate about the comparative merits of individual and family units of taxation to understand why the United States moved to the family as the basic tax unit and to explain its experience since making the change.
<p>
1. CANADIAN TAXATION SYSTEM
<p>
<i>a. History of the System</i><br>
As already mentioned, the initial choice of taxation unit in Canada and in the United States was the individual. This
determination was made in Canada in 1917 when the federal government introduced the <cite>Income War Tax Act</cite>. In the United States, a federal income tax statute was introduced four years earlier, in 1913. Several commentators have said that the initial choice in Canada was made more by default than as a result of any analysis of the issues at stake,<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> but a contrast between the original choice of tax unit in the New World (Canada, United States, and Australia) and Europe does not bear out this statement. The initial choice of taxation unit in most European countries (Britain, France, and Sweden) was the family, based on the assumption that the tax unit should correspond to property rights under the civil law or marital property law.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> Most European countries introduced income tax systems much
earlier than the New World; Britain in 1799 and Sweden at the end of the sixteenth century.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> These systems started at a time when marital property rules treated the couple or family as a unit under the control of the male head of the household. In countries where married women had gained control of their property when income tax provisions were introduced (Canada, United States, and Australia) it was taken for granted that the taxpayer would be the individual. While there may not have been a discussion in Canada of the policy implications inherent in the choice of tax unit---and there was certainly no discussion of the ability to pay---the underlying reason for the choice, in my opinion, seems clear: consistency with the marital property regime.
<p>
Compared to the United States, the history of Canada's tax treatment of the family is remarkably sedate and uneventful. Canada adopted the individual as the unit of taxation in 1917 and has never swerved from its original path; the United States has taken a very different course. Under the current Canadian tax system, the unit of
taxation is the individual and the person who has the property or legal interest in income is taxed on it. The most important aspect of this system of taxation is that the taxpayer's marital status does not, on the whole,<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> affect his or her tax status. In 1966, the Carter Commission<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup>
recommended that Canada should adopt the family as the unit of taxation; children were to be included in the tax unit.<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> These recommendations were never acted upon.
<p>
The last official examination of Canada's tax unit was done in 1975--76 by a federal Interdepartmental Committee on the Taxation of Women.<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> On the issue of the tax unit, the committee was split down the middle; half of its members, led by the Revenue Department, supported joint spousal taxation, the
other members, separate taxation.
<p>
<i>b. Current Canadian System</i><br>
While the individual is the basic unit of taxation in Canada, marital and family status are relevant in some provisions of the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> In the years since the Carter Commission, there has been a gradual change in the income tax system to recognize the family as the unit of taxation. The latest amendment in the long line of changes is the legislation introduced by the Department of Finance in the February 1992 budget to treat common-law couples in the same way as married couples for all purposes of the <cite>Act</cite>.
<p>
The provisions that make marital and family status relevant in the <cite>Act</cite> can be categorized into three groups: those that are favourable or unfavourable to the marital unit and those that are designed to maintain neutrality toward the marriage unit.
<p>
First let me deal with the provisions that are designed to preserve the principle of using the individual as the tax unit, those that maintain neutrality in the treatment of spouses. The <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> provides rules to ensure that marriage does not affect the separate tax liability of individual spouses. The most important of these provisions are the &quot;attribution rules,&quot;<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> which are intended to prevent spouses from transferring property from one to the other in order to split income and reduce the total amount of tax payable. The reason for the rules is obvious; under an individual system of taxation the higher income spouse (usually the husband) can make tax savings by hiving off income which would ordinarily be assessed to him onto his spouse, who has a lower marginal tax rate because of earning little or no income. The attribution rules nullify the desired effect of transfers of income or income-producing assets to spouses by &quot;attributing&quot; or &quot;deeming&quot; the income from the transferred income or asset to continue to belong to the transferor.
<p>
The attribution rules were tightened considerably in 1985 and in particular, loans were no longer permitted as an exclusion from the attribution rules. However, the attribution rules apply only to income from property and capital gains and losses realized on the subsequent disposition of property. It is a matter of debate among practitioners as to how effective these rules are in practice.
<p>
The other provisions that are designed to maintain the integrity of the tax base and the progressivity of the rates are aimed at preventing the reallocation of certain kinds of income (other than income from property) to persons other than the legal owners of that income<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> and frustrating &quot;non-arm's length&quot; transfers for inadequate consideration.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup> The latter are designed to limit the potential effects of attempts to split income between non-arm's length persons; spouses deal with each other at non-arm's length.<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup>
<p>
The second category of provisions that make marital and family status relevant in the <cite>Act</cite> are those which are designed to reduce tax liabilities of couple families---those which are favourable to the marital unit. These provisions allow tax credits to the high-earner spouse and permit the transfer of unused tax credits to the high-earner spouse. Specifically these provisions are: the married credit;<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> the ability to
transfer unused age, pension, tuition, education, and disability credits;<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> the
ability to transfer dividend income from Canadian corporations;<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup> spousal rollovers of capital property during lifetime or on death;<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> and the provisions with respect to spousal RRSPs and the treatment of RRSPs on death.
<p>
In addition there are provisions with respect to RRSPs that are favourable to the marital unit. The <cite>Act</cite> allows one spouse a deduction for contributing to the other's RRSP.<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> There are also rules which allow a rollover of pension payments to a spousal RRSP<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> and tax free transfer of one spouse's RRSP to the other spouse's RRSP on
death.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup>
<p>
Last are the provisions which work to the detriment of the marital or family unit. These are designed to limit or reduce the tax-delivered or directly delivered benefits or increase the tax liability of individuals. These rules generally require that family income be aggregated to determine eligibility for payments. Specifically the provisions are: the refundable goods and services tax credit for lower-income Canadians;<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup> provincial property and sales tax credits;<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> and the recently introduced child tax benefit which targets low-income families with children.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> This will be payable monthly to eligible individuals, generally to mothers. There
is also the rule that each family can have only one principal residence exemption from capital gains taxation.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> The current Canadian system, while theoretically an
individual-based system of taxation, is in reality a modified-individual tax unit. 
<p>
2. UNITED STATES SYSTEM
<p>
<i>a.  Evolution of the American System</i><sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup><br>
It is virtually impossible to analyse the current American system of taxation without looking at its evolution. In the United States, the early income tax statute, adopted in 1913, required each person to report his or her own income. The main challenge that destroyed the American separate tax system was the taxation of spouses living in states which had inherited community of property systems through their exposure to Spanish or French civil
law.<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> Their laws reflected the concept that marriage was a partnership with each spouse entitled to a present interest in half of the marital property and income, although in practice the husband had complete control. Because of the enormous tax savings that could be generated by income-splitting, there were
many court challenges to the concept of separate taxation. In 1930, the United States Supreme Court held in <cite>Poe v. Seaborn</cite><sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> that a husband's earnings in a community property state were subject, by law, to his wife's one-half interest. Each spouse, therefore, was taxed on one-half the
community income. In the same year, the same court in <cite>Lucas v. Earl</cite><sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> decided that a husband in a common law or separate property state was taxed on the full amount of his income, even though under a contract with his wife she held a one-half interest in that income. The inequity between these two decisions led to 
<blockquote>
widespread feelings of unfairness and almost twenty years of legislative chaos. Husbands from common law states felt disadvantaged compared to their counterparts from community property states who paid much lower taxes on the same income.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Finally in 1948, in an attempt to alleviate the criticisms and in a desire to reduce taxes substantially after
World War II, Congress decided to extend the benefit of full income-splitting to all married couples.
<p>
Although it was hoped that this new regime would solve the tax unit issue forever, problems soon reappeared. Widowed, divorced, and single persons with dependents resented having to pay much higher taxes than married people;<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> the &quot;marriage bonus&quot; or &quot;single's penalty&quot; resulted in single persons sometimes paying as much as 42 percent higher taxes than married persons with the same income.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> Pressure mounted on Congress to mitigate the harshness of the system and Congress responded in 1969 with four different tax rate schedules: one for married couples filing jointly,
another (higher one) for married couples filing separately, one for singles, and one for heads of households. Although the lowest rate schedule was still for married couples filing jointly, the gap was closed between singles and married couples so that spouses no longer received the equivalent of full splitting. On the contrary, many
couples with both spouses in the labour force now found that their tax burden increased when they married and there was an outcry by two-income couples against this new &quot;marriage penalty&quot; in the tax system. The penalty was incurred by the marriage of two income-producing individuals. It arose when each spouse contributed
at least 20 percent of the couple's total income and was greatest when the incomes of the two spouses were equal.<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> Congress responded in 1981 with an earned income deduction for lower-income spouses.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup>
<p>
<i>b.  Current American System</i><br>
The debate over the tax unit continues; American tax theorists are generally critical of the American regime. The
current American system has four rate schedules and the complications that arise due to the difficulties involved in
determining which of the four tax schedules to use are legion. The authors of a 1989 article spend 86 pages detailing the complexities.<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> The complexity in the American system is due not only to the four rate schedules, but also to the tendency of legislators over the years to add amendments that have the effect of appeasing the current annoyingly squeaky wheel. The development of tax policy in this area in the United
States has been dominated by the phenomenon of assuaging an alienated segment. Professor Bittker characterizes the debate over the tax unit in the United States as a constant procession of different groups of people moving &quot;to the centre of the stage in the ever changing but never ending drama entitled `Victims of Tax Injustice.'&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> Even though he recommends a return to the individual as
the unit of taxation, he nonetheless recognizes the political impossibility of achieving a reform that would raise the tax burden of most married people. Reforms are hampered by the large number of under-taxed one-earner couples with enormous political clout.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> Consider the comments of James Baker when he was Secretary of the Treasury in 1985: &quot;We are living in a pro-family society and any social or economic policy that does not recognize the importance of the American family is doomed to failure.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> One of the lessons for Canada is that the choice
of the family as the unit of taxation creates a host of problems including the dilemma of allocating tax burdens between single and married persons.
<p>
3. DIFFERENT CONCEPTIONS OF THE FAMILY UNIT: <cite>CARTER V. OLDMAN</cite>
<p>
While the family unit has often been presented as if it were a single, well-defined policy option, there has nonetheless been controversy and confusion over what effect its implementation will have and how this effect can be justified. In 1960, Oliver Oldman and Ralph Temple, two American law professors, recommended that the
most suitable unit of taxation was the married couple.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> Following from this basic premise, they developed a hierarchial structure on which a taxation system should be based:
<p>
1) An unmarried person should pay the same or greater tax than a one-income married couple with equal income;
<p>
2) A one-income married couple should pay higher tax than a dual-income married couple with equal income; and
<p>
3) A two-income married couple should pay more than two single persons with the same total income. 
<p>
The rationale for assigning the relative burdens of taxation between single and married persons was that a married couple having the same total income as two single people should have a heavier tax burden based on the economic advantages of joint living. One single person with the same income as a married couple should pay a greater tax since the advantages of joint living are never so great that two can live more cheaply than one. Essentially the basis for the recommendation was an ability-to-pay argument based on the economies of scale of joint living arrangements which increase the aggregate level of discretionary income when compared with those levels before
marriage. The rationale did not adequately establish that the family's income is a proper measure of the individual family member's ability to pay. The underlying assumption that family income is pooled and shared within the family was not stated and therefore not properly supported by reasoning and empirical evidence.
<p>
In 1966, the Carter Commission published a report which followed Oldman and Temple's recommendations with one modification: a one-income married couple and a dual-income married couple should be treated similarly---there should not be a difference in the tax burden between one and two-income married couples with the same
income. They rejected the suggestion of imputing income in kind for the value of the housework done by the stay-at-home spouse.<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> This change simply made the family unit politically feasible: a tax system which taxed housewives would undoubtedly be too controversial to implement. 
<p>
The Carter model achieves horizontal equity (that equal-income couples should pay the same amount of tax without regard to the source of the income or division between the spouses),<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> but compromises on no &quot;tax on marriage.&quot;  The &quot;tax on marriage&quot; is a result of the Commission recommendation of two rate structures: one schedule with a higher tax rate for family units and a second schedule with a lower tax rate for individuals.<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup>
<p>
It is instructive that the &quot;tax on marriage&quot; (at the higher-income levels) was the main reason given by the government of Canada for not supporting the taxation of the family as a unit. The other reason was that the effect of taxation of the family as a unit would generally be to subject the woman's income to a higher rate of
tax than it would have borne if she were single. In the <cite>White Paper</cite> on tax reform in 1969,<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup> and in the legislation that followed in 1971,<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> the government rejected aggregation of all income of married persons and joint filing at the time, but left open the
question of a future shift to the family as the unit of taxation.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup>
<p>
The Carter Commission presented an economic justification to defend its proposals. The Commission's position was that a fair taxation system must be based on the ability-to-pay principle and that the object of a progressive tax system and graduated rates is to redistribute income appropriately from those who have more to those who have less. The Commission recommended the adoption of the family as the unit of taxation, primarily on the ground that the family is &quot;the basic economic unit in society&quot;<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup> and thus determines the ability to pay. Like Oldman and Temple, the Commission failed to support this conclusion by showing that the &quot;pooling and sharing&quot; of family income which they implicitly assumed occurs within the family actually does occur. 
<p>
A decade later, in a 1977 article, &quot;Taxation of the Family in Comprehensive and Simplified Income Tax,&quot;<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> Professors McIntyre and Oldman strongly advocated not
only allowing income-splitting for married persons, but returning to a conceptually pure system of taxation in which all the concessions for single, widowed, and divorced persons should be eliminated. The McIntyre and Oldman system would remove any &quot;tax on marriage&quot; but impose a &quot;tax on remaining single.&quot;  The &quot;tax on remaining single&quot; is a result of a 50/50 attribution of income between the spouses, each of whom will be taxed as a single individual. This permits a single taxpayer to save tax by marrying someone with no
income or less income.
<p>
The economic justification presented by Professors McIntyre and Oldman is an interesting counterpoint to the Carter Commission justification. McIntyre and Oldman also base their model on an ability-to-pay principle; however, they come to very different conclusions than Carter. In their view, the family is the economic cornerstone of society and each family member should be taxed on the items s/he actually consumes or accumulates, regardless of source. They recommend that each family member, including children, should be taxed on the benefit they enjoy from the family income. In their view the correct way to distribute the benefit of the income is to attribute 50 percent to each of the marital spouses because this approximates the reality of the family as an economic unit. They
reject Carter's economy of scale argument as inadequate and based on insufficient data. They propose the benefit rule as a normative model for taxation of the family. However, as is shown below in the `Pooling and Sharing' section, the empirical evidence for Oldman and McIntyre's explicit assumption that 50-percent attribution approximates the reality of the modern family is lacking; in light of the evidence that does exist, the conclusion is highly suspect. Until this assumption can be established with more than assertions, justifications for using the family unit will be fundamentally flawed.
<p>
<h3>III.  Choice of a Taxation Unit---What Is the Best Unit?</h3>

1. UNDERSTANDING GENERAL CONCEPTS OF TAXATION
<p>
Policy choices in an area as complex and difficult as taxation can be obscured in jargon and mired in the details of an increasingly complex statute. My purpose is to examine the options involved in choosing a taxation unit and to evaluate these options. Because this policy choice will affect all areas of the taxation system, the options available must be assessed according to the system's overall objectives. The simplest way to do this is to judge both of the possible taxation units under what are generally considered to be the broad goals of a taxation system: fairness,
neutrality, and simplicity.
<p>
In the following pages, I will first briefly discuss the ideas of fairness, neutrality, and simplicity and then show how these differing goals produce difficult policy choices. I will go on to analyse in detail both units of taxation using each of these three objectives.
<p>
<i>a.  Equity</i><br>
Equity in a taxation system has two dimensions: vertical and horizontal. &quot;Vertical equity&quot; is achieved when people at different income levels pay suitably different taxes. Many difficult fundamental choices abound in this area, chiefly the appropriate progressive rate structure, ranging from a mildly progressive rate structure to a steep curve.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> Fundamentally, the objective of vertical equality is to ensure an equitable distribution of the burdens of taxation in a manner that reflects in a general way the broad ability to pay.
<p>
 &quot;Horizontal equity&quot; is the premise that people in equal positions should be treated alike. It means essentially that people (either individuals or families) with the same income and/or ability to pay should pay the same tax. At a simplistic level, the concept of horizontal equity means that A and B, a married couple each with
an income of $20,000, should pay the same tax as C and D, a married couple with an income of $40,000, earned entirely by C while D is a stay-at-home spouse. The concept of horizontal equity raises the issue of the distribution of the income between the spouses.
<p>
However, the concept of horizontal equity also raises the issue of how to deal with &quot;imputed income.&quot;  Imputed income arises whenever a person &quot;who owns productive assets, or who supplies productive services, uses them directly to produce goods and services that he consumes himself.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> One example of imputed income is the rental value of a house which an owner occupies. The owner's economic power, or ability to pay tax, is greater because of the rent which she does not have to pay. Imputed income arises in the context of the taxation of the family when a stay-at-home spouse provides services to her family. Imputed income raises several issues: do the two couples above, A and B and C and D, have the same ability to pay tax?  If not, how should the income tax system deal with the differences?  This problem has
confounded generations of tax policy experts and remains a current Canadian issue in the debate on the tax unit.
<p>
Fairness---the broad rubric which encompasses both vertical and horizontal equity ---also applies to the choice of the unit of taxation. It demands that justice be done in the allocation of taxation burdens and benefits within a society. From this consideration comes the general principle, agreed upon by most theorists, that the way to apportion the burdens of taxation is through ability to pay.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> More specifically, taxes are considered to be equitable when they are levied according to a defined tax capacity. The project then becomes one of choosing the tax unit which best suits this purpose---the tax unit most appropriate for assessing a person's ability to pay.
<p>
<i>b.  Neutrality</i><br>
The concept of &quot;neutrality&quot; in a tax system is generally held to mean that taxation considerations should not influence behaviour: the tax system should affect life and market choices as little as possible. Specifically, the tax unit should not affect the decision to marry or to work outside the home. While the meaning of neutrality is straightforward on one level---tax considerations should not influence decisions to marry or work outside the home---on another level it is far from absolute. The concept of neutrality is closely tied to the shared values of society and to current social norms. An example of this is society's reactions, at various times, to disincentives to labour force participation by wives. Discussions of whether neutrality in its widest context should always be a goal of a sound tax system are beyond the scope of this article. In my judgment the tax system should not punish or reward people for a decision to marry or to work outside the home.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup>
<p>
With respect to the decision to marry, in order for the income tax system to achieve a marriage-neutral stance, it should not impose a &quot;tax on marriage&quot; (tax disincentive for marriage) or a &quot;tax on remaining single&quot; (tax incentive for marriage). No &quot;tax on marriage&quot; means that two single taxpayers should pay no more tax if they marry. Thus, A and B, two single taxpayers each with an income of $20,000 should not pay more income tax when they marry and have an aggregate income of $40,000 than when they were single. No &quot;tax on remaining single&quot; means that a single person should not be able to save tax by marrying someone who has no income or less income. In order to have no &quot;tax on remaining single,&quot; C with an income of $40,000 should not pay less tax when she marries D who has no income or income of less than $40,000.
<p>
<i>c.  Simplicity</i><br>
Tax systems are becomingly increasingly complex. In my view, the goal of simplicity in a tax regime is an important one. A sound tax system is one that is reasonably easy for the taxpayer to comply with and for the tax authorities to administer. It is unlikely that a tax system will be accepted as fair if the average person cannot comply easily. Ease of compliance is critical in a self-reporting system.
<p>
Administrative simplicity is an important practical matter. If the cost of administering the system exceeds the revenue generated, the overall aim of revenue generation to meet government needs is defeated. Simplicity considerations encompass the costs of administering either an individual or a family system of taxation. The attribution rules are generally thought to be necessary to maintain the integrity of an individual system of taxation. They are, however, a source of complexity. On the other hand, defining the family unit would be necessary to a family system of taxation. This means that both units of taxation would demand similarly complex tax regimes. 
<p>
The three goals of fairness, neutrality, and simplicity are not discrete and separate considerations. They intersect and impact upon each other in complex and multiple ways. For example, the attribution rules, which I have chosen to discuss under the heading of administrative feasibility, raise fairness issues.
<p>
<i>d.  Social Policy Choices Implicit in the Choice of a Tax Unit</i><br>
One of the reasons that the problem of who is to be taxed has proven to be so intractable over the years is that there is an essential conundrum in the choice between the individual and the family. The dilemma is that, given a progressive rate structure, neutrality with respect to the decision to marry is incompatible with a regime of equal taxes for equal-income couples. Either horizontal equity or neutrality must be sacrificed. The phenomenon can be
illustrated by the following widely used criteria for a tax system:<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup>
<p>
1) a progressive rate structure;
<p>
2) payment of the same amount of tax by equal-income couples (without regard to the source of the income or division between the spouses);
<p>
3) no &quot;tax on marriage&quot;---two single persons pay no more tax if they marry; and
<p>
4) no &quot;tax on remaining single&quot;---a single person saves no tax by marrying someone who has no income or less income.
<p>
The criteria are chosen to reflect the concepts of vertical equity (1), horizontal equity (2), and neutrality (3 and 4).
<p>
There is no pattern of taxation that can be devised without eliminating one of the four criteria. The incompatibility of these criteria can be illustrated by the following example.<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup>
<blockquote>
Assume that A, B, C, and D are single individuals; A and B have equal incomes of $10,000 each; C earns $20,000; and D has no income. Let T(A), T(B) and T(C) represent the tax liability of A, B and C respectively. If the tax system is progressive . . . then (1) T(C) $ &gt; $ T(A) + T(B). Now assume that A and B marry and that C and D marry. If, under the second criterion, equal-income married couples pay the same tax, then (2) T(AB) = T(CD). Finally, the third criterion, marriage neutrality, requires that (3) T(A) + T(B) = T(AB) and that (4)  T(C) = T(CD). Substituting equations (3) and (4) into equation (2) yields T(A) +  T(B) = T(C). This, however, contradicts equation (1). Thus, equations (2), (3), and (4) cannot exist simultaneously in a tax system with a progressive rate schedule. [Horizontal equity (equation 2) and neutrality (equations 3 and 4) cannot be achieved without violating a progressive rate structure (equation 1).]
</blockquote>
The implications of the choice of taxation unit are thus very stark. All aggregation systems achieve horizontal equity (equal income couples pay equal tax) but compromise on neutrality (there is either a &quot;tax on marriage&quot; or a &quot;tax on remaining single&quot;); all individual systems necessarily compromise on horizontal
equity<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup> but achieve neutrality. The only way in which a tax system can be simultaneously progressive and neutral on the marriage decision is if married and unmarried people are taxed on exactly the same basis, and this of course will lead to horizontal inequity. Both units will create similar levels of complexity to administer, so simplicity considerations do not solve the problem. An understanding of the inevitably difficult choices in the selection of a tax unit is fundamental to an understanding of the evolution of tax systems.
<p>
2. ANALYSIS OF THE TAXATION UNITS UNDER THREE TAXATION OBJECTIVES
<p>
<i>A.  Fairness</i><br>
Fairness considerations require that the tax unit chosen be the most appropriate one to assess a person's ability to pay. The question that this part of the article will attempt to answer is, &quot;What is the unit of Canadian society which best reflects the ability to pay, the individual or the family?&quot;
<p>
<i>a.  Pooling and sharing</i><br>
If the family is chosen, the fundamental reason must be that the family's income best reflects the ability to pay rather than the individual family member's income. This then assumes a pooling and sharing of assets as the norm. It also assumes equal control of the assets by the marital couple. As Jack London, at one time a strong proponent of the family as the unit of taxation,<sup><a href="fifty4">54</a></sup> stated in a 1979 article, &quot;[t]he entire debate [over the unit of taxation] hinges on the accuracy of&quot; the statement that
<blockquote>
the reality of the family . . . is one of economic mutuality which, though it varies in degree from unit to unit, is one sufficiently meshed economically, ordinarily, to consider it a unit for purposes of determining taxpaying capacity.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Many writers in this area tend to assume that there is economic mutuality within the family, based on their intuitive sense of the practice of sharing.<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> Most commentators, if they view the issue
critically, admit that this assumption has not been verified in the literature. However, many commentators gloss over this fundamental tenet. Typical of this latter approach is the statement by McIntyre and Oldman that married couples should be assumed to share their income equally because &quot;common experience suggests that at least
partial pooling of sources to finance community consumption is almost universal.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> Louise Dulude points out that McIntyre and Oldman's support for this statement was &quot;a 1965 article based on unsupported statements of various sociologists in the 1950s and early 60s (the most up-to-date reference being a book entitled <cite>Building a Successful Marriage</cite>).&quot;<sup><a href="fifty8">58</a></sup>
<p>
Some commentators do not assume complete sharing but take an intermediate position that married couples share consumption, if not income. Accordingly, &quot;the wealth and well-being---and thus the amount of discretionary income of a married person---relates to the couples' income, not to individual circumstances.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> From this the conclusion is drawn that the marital unit is the most appropriate economic unit for a taxation system based on an ability-to-pay principle. While I would agree that the position that married couples share consumption to some degree is more defensible than complete sharing, I do not agree that this leads inexorably to the conclusion that the married couple is the most appropriate tax unit based on ability to pay. While members of a spousal unit may share current income, there is no evidence that they share savings. And even the assumption that spouses share a current income may be optimistic. While it is clear, for example, that spouses live in the same accommodation, there is no evidence that the remaining elements of a standard of living are equally shared. Different amounts may be spent on recreation and food outside the spousal dwelling. With respect to the issue of pooling and sharing, more intellectually rigorous commentators admit that unequal sharing with respect to intra-family distribution may be as plausible as equal sharing.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup>
<p>
There is minimal literature on how income and assets are shared by spouses. The only serious survey that I have found in the literature is by Jan Pahl---in Great Britain---as cited by Dulude in her article.<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> Pahl concluded that &quot;there is a considerable amount of evidence to suggest that such sharing of income cannot be taken for granted.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> She found four
standard patterns of money management which were characteristic of different types of families: 
<ol>
<li><i>the whole wage system</i>, characteristic of families living on social assistance or social security. Under that system, the husband hands over his salary or benefit cheque to his wife who manages all their financial affairs.
<p>
<li><i>the allowance system</i>, typical of families where the wife stays home and the husband gives her an &quot;allowance&quot; or &quot;wage,&quot; not so much related to the husband's actual income as to some community norm of an appropriate sum. Sometimes, the husband keeps back as much as half of his income.
<p>
<li><i>the pooling system</i>, mainly characteristic of newly married couples where both husband and wife are earning.  &quot;The pooling system also seems to be more common among those who have received a longer than average education.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> However, even where both spouses are employed, the spending patterns do not always give the wife equal financial power. Her earnings are often used for household expenditures, while the man keeps more of his money for personal use and for savings.
<p>
<li><i>the individual control system</i>, which is still quite rare, gives both spouses who are very well off full control over their individual sources of earned or unearned income.
</ol>
What are the conclusions to be drawn from this?  &quot;[C]ouples with very low incomes do share everything because they have no choice. . . . [S]pouses who each have substantial incomes and assets do not tend to share much at all. Among middle-income people, sharing seems most common when the spouses are young and have similar
incomes and least frequent when the wife has no income and stays home.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> It appears that sometimes spouses pool and share all or most of their incomes and
assets; more often they do not. In fact, with the exception of families who live at subsistence levels, the earnings and assets of couples who have choices are generally controlled and managed by the spouse who has legal title to them.
<p>
Margrit Eichler, a Canadian sociologist, is critical of the universality of the concept of economic mutuality within families. In a 1988 book, <cite>Families in Canada Today: Recent Changes and Their Policy Consequences</cite>, she commented on the validity of the idea of family income as follows:
<blockquote>
the concept of family income in most instances misrepresents actual circumstances. The majority of income in Canada is <i>not</i> family income, but is, instead, income of individuals who tend to be members of families. . . . It is important to realize that . . . individual income is under the control of the income earner. Economists <i>assume</i> that income that is paid to one family member benefits all family members, but this remains an assumption. While in many cases it is probably a correct assumption, in others it is likely inappropriate. It tells us nothing about who disposes of income for what purposes, since information on how money within families is spent is exceedingly sparse. . . . [A]s an indicator of access to income of individual family members, family income as a variable is not particularly useful.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The phenomenon of non-economic mutuality within families was also pointed out in the recent report of the Women and Taxation Working Group of the Fair Tax Commission.<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> They report that
<blockquote>
[t]he study of . . . intra-family distributions has been very limited. The available evidence suggests there is a complex process of resource allocation within families resulting in a variety of arrangements. It confirms that not all women in couple relationships have complete access to, or equal control over, the income of the other spouse. As a result, the assumption that all income is pooled is misleading.<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup>
</blockquote>
There is one statistical piece of information which is helpful in this debate, however. The trend in Canada is that an increasing portion of the after-tax income of the average Canadian family is available for individual spending choices. Statistics Canada figures show that the average Canadian family in 1990 spent only 35 percent of after-tax income on food, shelter, and clothing.<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> The figure in 1978 was 45 percent spent on these three items.<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup> Therefore in 1990 the average Canadian family had 65 percent, or two-thirds, of income available for individual expenditures. While this percentage has probably decreased since the recession in the early 1990s, the overall trend is still clearly towards greater non-essential expenditure. Furthermore, considerable evidence exists to show that couples do not generally share important capital and savings holdings such as business assets, savings, retirement funds, and pension rights.<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup>
<p>
There is no solid evidence that pooling and sharing are the norm in the Canadian marital unit; the data that is available seems to point to the conclusion that married couples do not share their income equally. All aggregate systems are based on the assumption of economic mutuality. The foundation of economic mutuality is questionable; the only evidence supporting pooling and sharing is anecdotal evidence, personal opinion, and intuition.<sup><a hef="#seventy1">71</a></sup> The concrete evidence points to the fact that most married couples tend to act as independent individuals with respect to a significant portion of their income. It does not seem wise to base a system of taxation on anecdotal evidence and intuition.
<p>
<i>b.  Economies of scale</i><br>
The concept of economies of scale played a large part in the Carter Commission recommendation that the family unit should pay more taxes than comparable individual units. Economies of scale refer to savings that families enjoy as a result of joint living arrangements. The married couple will enjoy economies of scale in consumption; a single home is cheaper to maintain than two establishments, and the duplication of many other expenses, from toasters to newspapers, can often be avoided. Reductions in the cost of food are also typical. Therefore the Carter Commission suggested that the ability to pay of a married couple who enjoy these economies of scale is greater than two unattached individuals. The Commission recommended a separate rate structure for married couples which would
have allocated an additional tax burden on families of approximately 20 percent based on savings due to economies of scale.
<p>
A simple example illustrates how this occurs. A and B are married and each has an income of $20,000. C and D are two single individuals who each have an income of $20,000. A and B have the same total income as C and D, but A and B live together and C and D live separately. The Carter model of economies of scale dictates that A and B should pay more tax than C and D. However, E, a single individual with an income of $40,000, should pay more tax than A and B.
<p>
There are two problems with economies of scale as a concept for allocating taxation burdens. First, the theory of confining economies of scale to the marital unit is both over-inclusive and under-inclusive. The advantages of economies of scale are not limited to the spousal unit. Roommates can achieve these savings. In 1978, Gerzog reported that 62.5 percent of single persons in the United States share their homes with someone else.<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> Therefore, taxing the marital unit at a higher rate based on economies of scale savings available to them does not accurately reflect the prevalent living conditions or the actual ability to pay tax for a significant portion of society. In this way the assumption is under-inclusive.
<p>
The assumption is also over-inclusive since not all spousal units can enjoy economies of scale. Commuting couples, for example, are forced to maintain separate residences and have the additional expense of commuting to be together on weekends because they are married. There are no figures available on the frequency of this arrangement; however, it is clear that the multiplicity of living arrangements make economies of scale a questionable basis for incorporation into rate schedules to allocate tax burdens. As McIntyre and Oldman said in 1977, &quot;[t]he great variety of living arrangements which now characterize our society undermines the economies of scale argument for persons above the subsistence level. Generalities about economies of scale are no longer useful . . . .&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> It is interesting to note that Oldman had been the co-author of the original economies of scale theory.
<p>
Second, it becomes more and more difficult to determine the extent of economies-of-scale savings as income levels rise above subsistence. To determine the amount of cost-of-living advantage that married couples enjoy as a result of joint living arrangements, tax theorists usually look to government cost-of-living indices for households of various sizes. Statistics Canada has developed indices of low-income cut-offs for cities of different sizes and rural areas. The cut-offs are used to classify families as poor or non-poor. They focus only on the minimum cost of living for various households. For example, the 1989 figures suggest that a childless married couple living in a city with 500,000 or more inhabitants needs an income of $16,027 to be as well off as an unattached individual with an income of $12,148; that is 32 percent more income.<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup>
<p>
A tax theorist would then assume that a single person with $12,000 of income should pay the same tax as a married couple with $16,000 of income and proceed to extrapolate this saving to higher-income levels.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> Does it hold that a single taxpayer with income of $45,000 should pay the same tax as a married couple with income of $60,000?  Or that a single taxpayer with income of $75,000 can live as well,
and hence has about the same tax paying capacity as a married couple with $100,000 of income?  The absurdity of simply using a 32-percent addition to determine economies of scale advantages for higher income levels seems obvious.
<p>
However, it is not clear that more complex calculations will result in more meaningful comparisons. Changing the percentage of additional increase so it is not constant at middle and higher income levels is one suggestion. For example, using a 20-percent differential at middle-income levels and a 10-percent differential at high-income levels would yield the following results. A single taxpayer with income of $40,000 would be assumed to have the same
ability to pay tax as a married taxpayer with income of $48,000. At high income levels a single income of $100,000 would be judged equal to a married income of $110,000. This approach seems equally arbitrary.<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup> The basis of economies of scale may be persuasive for taxpayers at low income levels, but it is much less valid when comparing middle- and high-income households of various sizes. The usefulness of any such measure in drawing conclusions about the relative tax paying abilities of middle and high-income single and married persons is doubtful.
<p>
<i>c.  Horizontal equity and imputed income</i><br>
Horizontal equity is one of the fundamental problems in the area of taxation of the family. If the individual is chosen as the basic tax unit, the concept of horizontal equity, as it is commonly conceived, will be sacrificed. Horizontal equity is the concept that people in equal positions should be treated alike. More specifically, the criterion is stated as &quot;equal taxation for equal-income married couples.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup> Under an individual taxation system distribution of income between the spouses will matter. The issue is most obvious in the case of a single income couple. The classic example to illustrate such inequity is: A and B, a dual-income couple, have an income of $30,000 each, while C and D, a one-income couple, have an income of $60,000 earned entirely by C while D is a stay-at-home spouse. Due to the progressivity of the tax rates, C and D will pay more tax than A and B. Horizontal equity will be sacrificed. Equal-income couples will be treated differently. Or put another way, two couples with equal ability to pay will be taxed at different levels. Is this true?  On a basic level, it is. However, a closer assessment of the situation reveals a much more complex reality. Do the two couples have equal ability to pay?  In Family C/D (made up of C and D), Mr C goes out to work and earns $60,000, and Mrs D stays home. In Family A/B (A and B), Mr A and Mrs B both work outside the home and each earns $30,000. While in monetary terms their incomes may be seen as equal, in reality the ability to pay is not the same. In Family A/B income is earned at the expense of essential household production. Essential household production will either not be performed in Family A/B, and therefore impose additional practical and psychic costs; or will be purchased in the market place, imposing further non-discretionary expenditures. In Family C/D, these extra costs do not arise because Mrs C remains at home performing these essential tasks. In effect, she produces
non-taxable income for the family. This income is referred to as imputed income or income in kind.
<p>
Since most tax theorists admit that the two families do not have equal ability to pay tax, the next question is how to deal with the inequities which arise. The most common solution offered to mitigate the unfairness is to include in the income base the value of the goods and services produced in the home. In fact, this was the recommendation offered by Douglas Hartle in a 1969 study prepared for the Royal Commission on the Status of Women in Canada.<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup> He suggested that an arbitrary amount for each individual's unpaid household work should be included in the tax base. His recommendation was that $2,000 of imputed income be included in the income tax base for every able-bodied man or woman with a tax credit of up to $2,000 for work outside the home.<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup> This was subsequently rejected by the Bird Report<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup> on the basis that implementation would be too difficult. Perhaps more importantly, the Commission found it &quot;undesirable that a married woman who stays at home keeping house for her family and has no income of her own should be liable to a tax which her husband would have to pay.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup>
<p>
The problem of imputed income has proven to be intractable over the years. Generally, the reasoning is that the administrative problems in measuring the amounts and values of these goods and services, namely imputed income, make inclusion in the income tax base an impossibility. Proxies which have been put forward to resolve the issue of imputed income include a credit for all full-time workers;<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup> a lower rate of tax for the earned income of women;<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup> and discontinuance of the marital tax credit. Another suggestion made was that husbands should pay tax on the imputed income from women's household services. This was based on the assumption that, in many cases, husbands are the primary beneficiaries of this work.<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> The outcome of these recommendations in the past has been that they were seen as either not administratively feasible,<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup> or politically unattractive.
<p>
The omission of imputed income from the tax base is partly reconciled in the view of some tax writers by the fact that the tax system does, albeit indirectly, take imputed income into account.<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup> The progressive rate structure has the effect of taxing the one-income couple more
heavily than the two-income couple. However, this is an arbitrary solution and certainly not specifically directed toward the issue.
<p>
To my mind, horizontal equity, as a fundamental tenet of a tax system, creates a plethora of unsolvable problems. Should one of the goals of our tax system be &quot;equal taxation of families with the same monetary income&quot;?  In my view, it should not. Unless the value of imputed income is included in the tax base, horizontal equity is not a rational, meaningful objective. Aggregation of monetary income applied to married couples is a poor measure of the ability to pay under equity criteria whenever the division of time between
production in the home and marketplace differs among married couples. A spouse, like other taxpayers, should be taxed on the income he or she owns and controls, since this best indicates his or her ability to pay.<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup>
<p>
<i>d.  Support of Children</i><br>
If the individual is chosen as the unit of taxation, the allocation of relative tax burdens might also result in inequities in the case of a family with children. Intuitively it does seem that this is a situation where the family would be a more feasible economic unit. Although the tax treatment of children is beyond the scope of this article, it is my view that the appropriate tax treatment of children is not to adopt the family as the unit of taxation. In my judgment, equity considerations are best met with a scheme of tax allowances to recognize the costs incurred by the family in raising children. The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) reports that, since 1974, there has been a tendency among its members to move away from tax deductions for children in favour of tax credits and, to an even greater extent, toward systems of cash transfers.<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup> Canada has been part of this trend, first in 1987 with its move from tax deductions to tax credits, and now in 1993 with the child tax benefit which targets low-income families with children. This will be payable monthly to eligible individuals, generally to mothers. Some groups are already decrying the plan as insufficient,<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> and, predictably, others are viewing it as too rich.<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> Leaving the quantum of the benefit aside, the concept of the child tax benefit does seem to embody all the equity considerations and in my view is a better way to proceed than adopting the family as the unit of taxation.
<p>
<i>e.  Conclusions</i><br>
Fairness considerations dictate that whichever unit is chosen, the individual unit, the spousal or marital unit, or the
family unit, it should best reflect the ability to pay across Canadian society. Is the argument that the family is the economic unit of Canadian society persuasive?  Does an individual's marital status best define his or her ability to pay or does the income that each person owns and controls better reflect his or her ability to pay?
<p>
To be an accurate reflection of ability to pay, any aggregate system must display an economic mutuality; pooling and sharing must be the norm. The evidence that exists suggests that pooling and sharing may not be the norm except at the low end of the income scale where there are no choices about how income is spent.
<p>
Furthermore, if the decision is made that the unit of taxation will be the marital unit, the thorny problem of the allocation of tax burdens between single and married persons must be faced. Some acceptable basis must be found to allocate the different taxation burdens. If the Oldman II model is chosen (if there is to be only one rate structure this will be inevitable) inequities result. Let me illustrate: A and B each have an income of $40,000. However, A
is married to a stay-at-home spouse and as a result will pay taxes on only $20,000. With a progressive rate structure B will pay much higher taxes than A.<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> This two-to-one ratio seems unduly harsh to the unattached individual and, on the other hand, unduly permissive to a one-income couple.<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup>
<p>
To achieve a more equitable arrangement there could be two rate structures: one for married couples and one for single persons. This is the other option, the Carter model. However, it is important to understand that the unstated premise for this model is also an equal attribution of income to family members on the basis of benefits received. The benefit argument, unstated and implicit in the Carter model, seems unpersuasive to legitimize income splitting for <i>all</i> married couples with respect to <i>all</i> income received by the spouses. Moreover, there must be a basis for the difference between the rate structures. The concept of savings due to economies of scale seems to be the primary candidate. However, the problems with the fit of this concept to the spousal unit appear to render it
largely unworkable. Like pooling and sharing, the concept of economies of scale only works at a subsistence level. Additionally, economies of scale are not confined to a spousal unit but may be realized in a multitude of joint living arrangements.
<p>
I conclude that the choice of the individual as the unit of taxation better reflects fairness considerations. Although the economic mutuality of the family may be intuitively appealing, on closer inspection the family is not the unit in Canadian society that best reflects the ability to pay. Also, if the marital unit is chosen there appears to be no equitable way to allocate the tax burdens between married and single persons.<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup> Each spouse should pay tax on the income he or she owns and controls, since this best indicates his or her ability to pay.
<p>
<i>B.  Neutrality</i><br>
The tax unit should affect life choices as little as possible, particularly in regard to decisions about marriage or
taking a job outside the home. At the most fundamental level, the choice of a tax unit has implications for the type of family structure that will be promoted and provided with economic incentives.
<p>
<i>a.  The decision of the secondary earner to work</i><sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup><br>
Any aggregate system, regardless of the tax burden allocation, has a disincentive to the secondary earner (usually the wife) to work for pay outside the home. The aggregate system penalizes the two-income couple in two ways.<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup> First, when the secondary worker returns to work, &quot;the second salary is added to the first in computing the couple's combined taxable income, with the result that the first dollar of the second salary is taxed at the marginal rate applicable to the last dollar of the first salary.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup> A and B are married and A's income is taxed at the highest marginal rate of 50 percent. When B returns to paid employment her income will be taxed at A's marginal rate, not the lower rate which her income would normally attract. This is a source of inefficiency in an aggregate system; distorting secondary labour supply substantially reduces economic efficiency.
<p>
Second, &quot;on leaving home to take a job, the second spouse usually incurs expenses---for transportation, more formal clothing, lunches, etc.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> ---that usually cannot be deducted.<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup>
<blockquote>
This results in a disparity between the couple's statutory income and their economic gain, which is then widened by the working spouse's inability to give as much time as formerly to maintaining the home, preparing meals, and shopping for bargains, so that the couple may have to hire [household help], eat more frequently in restaurants, and pay more for goods and services.<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This effect is exacerbated by the fact that prior to returning to paid employment, the single income couple was not taxed on the wife's work in the home since the value of goods and services produced in the home was not taxed. One critic of the American system offered an example---a married woman whose $10,000 salary yields a net of only $1,600.<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup> Because the income tax base ignores income from the products and services produced by the taxpayer in her home, this causes overproduction of goods and services in the home and is therefore inefficient.<sup><a href="#one01">101</a></sup>
<p>
The hybrid Canadian system with its array of marital credits and transfer of unused credits has the same effect. The non-refundable married credit is available to individuals in recognition of the support given to a low-income spouse. The maximum federal credit for 1993 is $915; the credit is reduced if the spouse's income exceeds $538. This means that the higher-income spouse's tax burden will be increased once the secondary spouse's income exceeds $538.
<p>
These burdens on the double income married couple are a deterrent to the employment of married women outside the home in an aggregate system. In theory, of course, the burden arises whether the &quot;secondary&quot; wage-earner is the husband or the wife, and hence falls on the couple jointly. However, in a society that takes the husband's job for granted and views the wife as the secondary wage-earner, it is reasonable to describe the existing state of affairs as biased against women.<sup><a href="#one02">102</a></sup> A non-neutral system encourages
economic dependency for women. 
<blockquote>
Most nonworking spouses are women who are economically dependent on their husbands. Thus, what is in form a gender-neutral favoritism of home production may in fact be a form of sex discrimination that tends to keep women economically dependent on men.<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup>
</blockquote>
With the change in most Canadian family law acts to shorter term support on dissolution of marriage and the
increasing rate of divorce in Canada, economic dependency of women is an issue which must concern us. Any system which encourages economic dependency is problematic.
<p>
However, some commentators allege that non-neutrality is not an issue with respect to the decision of women to work outside the home. They point to the labour force participation of married women which has increased phenomenally in the last 40 years. In 1941 the rate was four percent, at the time of the Carter Commission in 1961 the rate was 22 percent, and in 1985 the rate of participation was 55 percent.<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup> However, the increasing labour force participation rate for married women does not
refute the suggestion that the tax system affects those participation rates.<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup> We have no way of determining what the rates would be under a tax system that was neutral to the decision of the secondary worker to return to waged work.
<p>
<i>b.  The decision to marry</i><br>
An individual tax unit by its very nature is neutral to the decision to marry; an aggregate system is not. An aggregate tax system, if it is to be progressive, must either impose more tax on two single taxpayers if they marry (a &quot;tax on marriage&quot;), or allow a single person to save tax by marrying someone who has no income or less income (a &quot;tax on remaining single&quot;).
<p>
Some tax experts believe that the taxation system does not actually influence the decision to marry or to remain single. The research group for the Carter Commission was of this view. They accepted the statement of the British Royal Commission on Taxation, &quot;We are sceptical of the suggestion that men and women are dissuaded
from marriage by any such nice calculation of the financial odds.&quot;<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup> Even as late as 1990 some commentators were saying that, &quot;It is doubtful whether the tax consequences of marriage greatly influence the decision to marry.&quot;<sup><a href="#one07">107</a></sup>
<p>
However, this view seems out of touch with reality. The Swedish experience at the end of World War II provides one example. In Sweden at that time, there was a much higher tax burden on two-earner married couples compared to unmarried taxpayers due to the steep progressivity of the rate schedule. In 1960, the tax unit was extended to include common-law relationships to stop the increasingly widespread practice among upper-income couples of cohabiting without marriage.<sup><a href="#one08">108</a></sup>
<p>
The experience in the United States during the 1970s, after the 1969 change to alleviate the burden on single taxpayers which in turn created a tax on marriage for some taxpayers, is also instructive. A number of articles<sup><a href="#one09">109</a></sup> pondered the issue of coming to grips with the
non-neutrality of an aggregate system, including, &quot;The Marriage Penalty: The Working Couple's Dilemma&quot;<sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup> and &quot;Marry in Haste, Repent at Tax Time: Marital Status as a Tax Determinant.&quot;<sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup> The demands were for a return to an individual system of taxation because the taxation system was penalizing individuals for a decision to marry.
<p>
The above evidence would seem to suggest that tax considerations can influence decisions to marry. The current Canadian system, although an individual system, is also not neutral to the decision to marry. The most obvious evidence of this is the non-refundable married credit which is available to an individual who marries a low-income person. There are also a host of tax reducing provisions for couples that were mentioned earlier.<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup>
<p>
Beginning in 1993 the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> will treat common-law couples as married for purposes of the 
<cite>Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup> This introduction will do much to make the Canadian system neutral to the decision to marry.<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup>
<p>
<i>c.  Incentives for type of family structure</i><br>
The choice of a basic unit of taxpayer has implications for the type of family structure that will be promoted and provided with economic incentives. An aggregate system provides significant tax savings for a very particular type of family structure, not for all families. Families where one spouse earns enough income to support the family, and where the other spouse stays at home, are the main beneficiaries of an aggregate system. This is true no matter which burden allocation method is chosen because the value of the services of the stay-at-home spouse are not included in the tax base. Under the Oldman II model of burden allocation, not only is the value of the imputed income ignored, the income of the highly paid worker will be split in two and each spouse will then be taxed as an individual on only one-half of the income. The Carter model has the same effect of ignoring the value of the non-waged household and child care service and splitting the income between the spouses. There is a higher tax burden than under the Oldman II method (Carter recommended 20 percent), but there is still a significant economic benefit for the one-income family.
<p>
Since the stay-at-home spouse is commonly the wife and the highly paid spouse is more likely to be the husband, an aggregate system is providing tax incentives for a traditional family model comprised of a male income-earner who earns enough income to support the family (normally an affluent taxpayer) and a female stay-at-home spouse. The savings under any system of taxation that uses the family as the basic tax unit are enormous for this  quot;traditional
model&quot; family.
<p>
<i>C.  Simplicity</i><br>
The last goal I will consider is simplicity. A sound tax system is one which is reasonably easy for the taxpayer to comply with and for the authorities to administer.
<p>
<i>a.  Ease of compliance</i><br>
In a self-reporting system of taxation ease of compliance is crucial. In order for the average taxpayer to comply, she must grasp the underlying broad, general principles. For example, a tax system where taxpayers understand that they must file either jointly or individually is easier to comply with than one where there is a complex combination of individual and joint filing. Also, the public has difficulty grasping tax systems whose basic components are more
or less arbitrary. For example, if different rate structures are to be used, the basis for the rate structure should ideally be clear to the average taxpayer. Put most simply, it is easier to comply when you can grasp the rationale for the rule. It is unlikely that a tax system will be accepted as fair if the average person does not understand, albeit at an elementary level, the general underlying principles.
<p>
What do simplicity considerations dictate with respect to the choice of a unit of taxation?  The basis for the Canadian model of individual taxation is easily understood; so too is the Oldman II family model of taxation. The Carter model, with more than one rate schedule and the somewhat arbitrary basis for the allocation of tax burdens between the rate schedules, is less satisfactory in this regard. However, the Oldman II family model of taxation gives rise to inequitable tax burden allocations between single and married taxpayers which in turn can precipitate all the complexities of the American system. These considerations militate for the individual as the tax unit. While it can be argued that an individual system also can be subject to demands for reallocation of tax burdens,<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup> the pressure will be less severe because the system is much more equitable. While the number of rate schedules and the basis for those schedules are certainly not the only factors, nor even the major cause of complexity in income tax statutes,<sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup> they are a consideration.
<p>
<i>b.  Ease of administration</i><br>
Administrative simplicity is a practical concern and an important one. If the cost of administering the system exceeds the revenue generated, the overall aim of revenue generation to meet government needs is defeated. Therefore the cost of administering either an individual or a family system of taxation must be considered. The attribution rules are generally thought to be a necessary component in maintaining the integrity of an individual
system of taxation. If the individual is chosen as the tax unit, taxation officials become involved in characterizing transactions and transfers between members of a family unit. The attribution rules attempt to prevent spouses from transferring property from one to the other in the hope of ensuring that the tax liability of the income accrues to the lower-income spouse. Most tax commentators believe that joint spousal taxation would simplify the administration of the tax system.<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup>
<p>
However, if the family is chosen as the unit of taxation, tax officials will become involved in a definition of who constitutes a family unit for the purposes of the <cite>Act</cite>, at a time when there may no longer be a tenable definition of the &quot;family unit.&quot;  In September 1992, an Ontario human rights tribunal held that same sex
couples will now be included in the definition of spousal unit.<sup><a href="#one18">118</a></sup> This ruling is, in my view, a harbinger of things to come and, if the family is chosen as the unit of taxation, eventually the determination of who constitutes a same sex couple must be made. Can adults living together as  &quot;roommates&quot; qualify as a family for purposes of income tax legislation?<sup><a href="#one19">119</a></sup> The definition of a family unit is becoming an increasingly contentious issue. This, in my view, is a trend that will continue; I do not see any abatement in the near future.
<p>
My conclusions regarding administrative feasibility of an aggregate system and an individual system are that both present very difficult administrative issues. The issues in this area, as they are presently defined, present no clear advantage for one unit of taxation over the other.
<p>
<i>D.  The Best Unit of Taxation:  Conclusions</i><br>
My conclusion, based on the three goals of fairness, neutrality, and simplicity, is that the best choice for the unit of
taxation is the individual. Neutrality considerations clearly dictate that the choice should be the individual; it is impossible for an aggregate system to avoid either tax incentives or disincentives for marriage. Simplicity considerations show no clear difference between the individual and the family as the unit of taxation. Perhaps with the attribution rules as they are currently structured, there is a slight bias toward the family as the more administratively feasible system. However, in my view, it is the fairness and equity considerations that are decisive. The available information shows that pooling and sharing, implicit assumptions in the choice of any aggregate system, are not the norm in many families. Furthermore, if the family is chosen as the unit of taxation, there must be an allocation of the tax burdens between single and married taxpayers. This is virtually impossible to do in an equitable manner.
<p>
The family was advocated as the unit of taxation by the Carter Commission. The Commission argued that the appropriate measure of ability to pay for family members is total family income. They argued that differences in the distribution of spousal income in a marriage should not result in variations in the tax payments of married couples with the same total income.  For the reasons I have outlined, chiefly the lack of fairness in any aggregate system, I believe these arguments are flawed.
<p>
There are two other arguments against adopting the spousal unit as the unit of taxation. First, the concept of a couple as a life-long economic unit with joint income, wealth, and expenses may no longer be appropriate in light of changing family structures, increasing divorce rates, and falling marriage rates.<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup>
<p>
 Second, using the couple as the tax unit is in conflict with the goal of women's autonomy as it does not recognize women as distinct from their relationships with others. Historically, the filing of joint tax returns for husbands and wives was necessary because women were legally incapable of acting for themselves.
<p>
<h3>IV.  Implications of the Best Tax Unit for the Canadian Tax System</h3>

1. PRESSURES FOR CHANGE
<p>
There are factors other than simple taxation policy involved in the choice of a unit of tax. For example, any discussion will inevitably be framed by the recommendation of the Carter Commission, which favoured an aggregation of marital income. The fascination in Canada with the family as the unit of taxation seems to be a result of this influential report. From my perspective, the Carter recommendations on the tax unit fell far short of a standard of excellence, and of their own stated criteria of fairness, neutrality, and simplicity.<sup><a href="#one21">121</a></sup> The Carter Commission, in my view, gave the concept of the family as the unit of tax an undeserved patina of respectability.<sup><a href="one22">122</a></sup> However, the weight of the view of the Carter Commission is undeniable.
<p>
Another factor which might influence the choice of tax unit is the growing importance of economic internationalism.<sup><a href="one23">123</a></sup> It is inevitable that there will be pressure for countries associated economically to integrate their taxation systems. We are living in a time when the economic ties between
Canada and the United States are becoming stronger. The American family system of taxation is intuitively appealing to many economists. Economic thought, and thus tax policy criteria, envision the operative units of economic activity as households or firms, not individuals. They believe that a family system of taxation is more
in accord with reality. The segment of the population that seeks to promote traditional family values will also be adherents to this view.
<p>
Finally, experience in the United States has taught us that the importance of judicial decisions should not be underestimated in this area of policy-making. Taxpayers can now use the equality provisions of the <cite>Charter</cite> to challenge separate taxation. Two recent cases, <cite>Schachtschneider</cite><sup><a href="#one24">124</a></sup> and <cite>Ross</cite>,<sup><a href="#one25">125</a></sup> both challenges to the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> under s. 15 of the <cite>Charter</cite>, are examples of the increased litigation in this area. <cite>Schachtschneider</cite> challenged the equivalent-to-married tax credit. <cite>Ross</cite> challenged the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> disallowance of a child-care payments deduction to an individual closely related to the child (the stay-at-home mother in this case) and the disallowance of the stay-at-home wife's claim to one-half the husband's income as her own. The potential for tax savings is an irresistible lure for high-income one-earner couples to use the judicial system to challenge an individual system of taxation.
<p>
The cumulative effect of these factors---the Carter Commission recommendation, growing economic internationalism, future judicial decisions, and the amendment-by-amendment move to the family unit of taxation---may reopen the debate on the aggregation of income.
<p>
2. RECOMMENDATIONS FOR REFORM
<p>
In my judgment, it is important to undertake reform in this area, primarily to render the existing system more equitable, but also to mute calls for a change to an aggregate system. In Canada today the unit of taxation is the individual. However, the taxation system is increasingly recognizing the marital unit. Most commentators in this area bemoan the schizophrenic nature of the Canadian tax system. For example, Jack London in a 1988 paper said
that 
<blockquote>
[T]he federal income tax system . . . lacks an intellectually or rationally defensible perspective on whether married persons are, or ought to be, considered tax units requiring aggregation of their joint incomes from all sources.<sup><a href="#one26">126</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Maureen Maloney in 1989 stated that
<blockquote>
the Income Tax Act appears to have adopted the worst of both regimes:  its use of the individual as the basic tax unit reflects a desire to ensure equality, yet its manner of giving spousal deductions, unused reliefs, etc., undermines this aim.<sup><a href="#one27">127</a></sup>
</blockquote>
and further that
<blockquote>
[t]he unit of taxation should remain the individual and any movement toward recognition of the marital or family unit should be carefully watched and eliminated.<sup><a href="#one28">128</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Is this dual recognition of the individual and the married couple necessarily negative?  In my opinion, it is not. While I disagree that the duality in the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> is necessarily wrong, I agree that there should be a principled basis for the decision to tax the spousal unit jointly or separately. In my judgment an individual-based system of taxation together with a family-based system of income maintenance is the most coherent, rational approach.<sup><a href="#one29">129</a></sup> Such a system is the best choice because it not only achieves the fairness of an individual system but it also recognizes family responsibilities at the lowest income levels. The rationale for adopting the spousal unit at subsistence levels is that there is economic mutuality in families at low income levels. I submit that such a system achieves the best of both regimes. Aggregation of income should be maintained for provisions that are designed to limit or reduce the tax-delivered or directly delivered benefits that families can claim. These include the child and sales tax credit. These are components of income maintenance that the government finds it convenient to administer, along with the personal income tax.
<p>
I would, however, recommend the repeal of all of the provisions that are designed to reduce tax liabilities of couple families, on the basis that they are not targeted at low-income families. These are the provisions which allow the high-earner spouse various credits (such as the married credit) and allow for the transfer of unused tax credits to the higher income spouse.
<p>
I am more ambivalent about my recommendation regarding the attribution rules, the provisions that are designed to maintain the individual as the tax unit.  On balance, I will recommend that these provisions should be left in place, but should be reconsidered.
<p>
<i>a.  Repeal of the marital credit</i><sup><a href="#one30">130</a></sup><br>
One of the current issues in the reform of the Canadian tax system is to repeal the marital credit. The history of the marital credit is important for two reasons. First, it reveals an underlying philosophy of encouraging dependency. Second, it provides evidence of the effects of non-neutral taxation provisions on the decision of the secondary earner to work outside the home. The married exemption was part of the <cite>Income War Tax Act</cite> that introduced income tax to Canada in 1917. Over the years the married exemption amount has generally been the same as the personal exemption amount. In 1925 an amendment to the married exemption was introduced that required one of the spouses to be &quot;dependent.&quot;  This was enforced by providing that the marriage exemption could be claimed only if the other spouse's income was less than $1500. This provision constituted a clear inducement to actual dependency.<sup><a href="#one31">131</a></sup> By 1942, the cap on married women's income had been lowered to $660. In 1942, the government amended the married exemption to induce married women to enter waged work by removing the $660 limit and the requirement for dependency. The goal was total mobilization of the labour force in World War II. In 1947, the limit was put back into the provision and the dependency requirements were re-enacted.<sup><a href="#one32">132</a></sup> In 1987, the married exemption deduction was converted into a tax credit.
<p>
Today, the marital credit is structured as a non-refundable credit available to a high-income spouse in recognition of the support given to a low-income spouse. I would recommend that the marital credit be repealed. It encourages the dependency of women and provides a disincentive to part-time or initial-level employment, since the first dollars earned are taxed at the husband's higher marginal rate. In 1989, the cost of this credit was approximately $1.5 billion dollars federally.<sup><a href="#one33">133</a></sup> The figure rises to approximately $2.4 billion when the value of the marital credit in the nine provinces and two territories is added.<sup><a href="#one34">134</a></sup>
<p>
The repeal of the marital dependency credit has often been suggested in the past. In 1970, the Canadian Royal Commission on the Status of Women concluded that
<blockquote>
[i]n all justice the married status exemption should not be given when there is no dependent in the family. We believe that a woman does not become economically dependent by virtue of her marriage. If she is in fact dependent, it is the result of the couple's personal choice. A childless couple has the right to decide that the wife will devote all her time to homemaking but there is no reason why the State should attach an advantage to this choice by giving the husband a married status exemption.<sup><a href="#one35">135</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In 1983, Judy Erola, who was then Minister Reponsible for the Status of Women, made the same recommendation. Her suggestion was met with a storm of protest and the government of the day was forced to bow to political pressure and withdraw it.<sup><a href="#one36">136</a></sup> Louise Dulude states that the main obstacle is &quot;housewives who, deprived of any compensation for their work, do not see the marital exemption as a denial of their economic value, but as the only measure in the tax act that grants them some recognition.&quot;<sup><a href="#one37">137</a></sup>
<p>
As recently as November 1992, the Fair Tax Commission's Working Group on Women and Taxation was split in its recommendation: one group believed the provisions should be eliminated; the other group that the provisions should be maintained, but the benefit delivered to the lower-income spouse.<sup><a href="#one38">138</a></sup>
<p>
I do not believe that the marital credit should be maintained. It is fundamentally flawed in its structure and it should be repealed. However, I do sympathize with the underlying concern of the Working Group that the benefits should not be withdrawn from low-income families. My recommendation would be to use a portion of the money to enrich the child tax benefit scheme to target low-income families with children. In my opinion, the repeal of the marital
credit is politically feasible at this time. Most Canadians seem to have accepted the need for the non-universality of programs such as family allowances.<sup><a href="#one39">139</a></sup>
<p>
<i>b.  Repeal of the Transfer of Unused Spousal Credits</i><br>
The second reform that should be undertaken is to repeal the transfer of unused spousal credits. The <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> presently allows the lower-income spouse to transfer unused tax credits to the higher-income spouse. These include the age amount, pension income amount, disability amount, and the tuition fees and education amounts. Also the transfer of dividend income to the higher-income spouse is permitted, if, as a result of this transfer, the higher-income taxpayer can increase his claim for the married credit. It is not possible to measure the cost of these provisions separately, given the available data. These provisions are designed to lower the tax liabilities of all families, not only lower-income families. In fact, the main beneficiaries of these rules are higher-income families. I would recommend their repeal on the basis that there is no rational basis for allocating tax savings to this group. In a time of increasing deficits, tax concessions should be specifically targeted.
<p>
<i>c.  Reconsider the Attribution Rules</i><br>
Reform of the current Canadian tax system demands that the attribution rules be reconsidered. My dilemma with the attribution rules is as follows: on the one hand repeal of these rules may facilitate transfer of property between spouses; on the other hand retention of the attribution rules may preserve the individual as the unit of taxation. If, and I stress this point, transfer of effective legal title and control were a condition, the result might be more financial autonomy for women and an incentive to adopt true sharing between the spouses. However, this effect is far from assured. Several commentators have wondered whether the effect of the repeal of the attribution rules would be an increased transfer of legal control. In these times of increasing instability of marriages, perhaps husbands would be loathe to transfer their properties to wives simply to reap tax savings. Professor Bittker comments on the American situation,
<blockquote>
Taxpayers pass up many opportunities to reduce their taxes by intrafamily gifts, possibly from ignorance or inertia, but perhaps because they attach more significance to their legal rights than academicians assert. The contemporary women's rights movement is a reminder of the long struggle for married women's property laws, whose underlying premise was that the division of legal rights between the husband and wife is a significant matter, not a trivial one.<sup><a href="#one40">140</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Other commentators assert that the presence of the attribution rules in the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> is acknowledgement by the government that the family is the economic unit of society.<sup><a href="#one41">141</a></sup>
<p>
Some commentators believe that the attribution rules do not work. For example, Maureen Maloney states that
<blockquote>
[s]tringent though the attribution rules may first appear, they have in practice been easily and widely avoided. . . . As a consequence, the attribution rules have often only served to catch the unwary or uneducated, while allowing those who are able to afford good tax advice to escape them.<sup><a href="#one42">142</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Jack London in a paper in 1979, and a subsequent panel discussion on the &quot;Taxation of the Family,&quot; admits that his fundamental problem with the system of taxation in Canada as it existed at that point in time---with the individual as the unit of taxation and the pre-1985 attribution rules---was the inequities in the application of the attribution rules that he had seen as a tax practitioner. Persons with income from business or property were able to arrange their affairs so as to split their income with family members, but wage earners (usually less affluent) did not have the same possibility of income-splitting open to them.<sup><a href="#one43">143</a></sup>
<p>
The 1985 amendments to the attribution rules were much more restrictive, and much more complex.<sup><a href="#one44">144</a></sup> The three key differences between the new attribution rules and the old attribution rules were: first, the new provisions apply to loans of property as well as to transfers; second, the rules apply
not only to a transfer or loan to a person, but also to a transfer or loan that is &quot;for the benefit of&quot; a person; and third, the definition of substituted property was expanded and included shares received as stock dividends.<sup><a href="#one45">145</a></sup>
<p>
In the final analysis I am persuaded, in the face of many unknowns, that the attribution rules should be retained. I would, however, recommend that they be revisited to determine if the 1985 attempt to tighten the rules has succeeded. Also, the concept of repealing the attribution rules, subject to a transfer of effective legal title and control, should be studied to determine if it will facilitate a more equal sharing within families.
<p>
<h3>V.  Conclusions</h3>

The primary purpose of this article was to determine the best unit of taxation. In my judgment, individual taxation is the best system of taxation; it better meets the objectives of fairness, neutrality, and simplicity than taxation of the marital or spousal unit. Individual taxation is more in accord with the reality within families, particularly with respect to current behaviour in pooling and sharing of economic resources. The trend among the western industrialized countries has been toward the choice of the individual as the unit of taxation, and away from compulsory joint or family taxation.<sup><a href="#one46">146</a></sup> In my view, the economic unit in Canadian society that best reflects the ability to pay taxes is the individual.
<p>
A secondary, albeit unstated, objective of this article was to encourage the reader to make up his or her own mind on the best unit of taxation by presenting clearly the ideas and policy choices involved. The taxation system and the choices involved therein, especially with respect to the choice of the unit of taxation, imply very profound social policy choices. An understanding of these issues will leave the reader better prepared to participate knowledgeably in any upcoming debates on the tax unit in Canada.
<p><br>
