<p>
<li><a name="sixty6">The Commission</a> on Fair Taxation was set up by the Ontario government to study and make recommendations on various issues; one of the topics to be considered was &quot;Women and Taxation.&quot;  The Ontario Treasurer released the report of the &quot;Working Group on Women and Taxation&quot; in 1992. Their mandate was to determine if there is systemic discrimination in the tax system toward women and to make recommendations to alleviate the problem. It should be noted that this report covers only one of the eight subject areas to be considered by the Fair Tax Commission. Fair Tax Commission, <cite>Report of the Women and Taxation Working Group</cite> (Toronto: Ontario Ministry of Treasury and Economics, November 1992) at 8 [hereinafter &quot;the Fair Tax Commission's Working Group&quot;].
<p>
<li><a name="sixty7"><i>Ibid.</i> at 7.</a> The report says that this is particularly true in families where wife assault occurs and states that one in five Canadian men admits to using violence against his partner. In such families, the forms of economic abuse that occur include: forcing the wife to ask for money, giving the wife an allowance, taking the wife's money away, and not letting the wife know about, or have access to, family income.
<p>
<li><a name="sixty8">The breakdown is as follows:</a> 17.3 percent on shelter; 12.6 percent food and 5.5 percent clothing for a total of 35.4 percent on the three items. Statistics Canada Catalogue 62555, &quot;Family Expenditure in Canada.&quot;
