<p>
<li><a name="seventy1">Perhaps</a> the strength of the concept of pooling and sharing within the marital unit is due to unspoken emotional and unconscious wishes that sharing were the norm, and we cannot bring ourselves somehow to admit that it is not. The more I am faced with the predominance in the male literature of the view that sharing is the norm in families, the more I marvel at the difference between the two views. On the one hand there is a rosy &quot;Father Knows Best&quot; picture of the family and on the other hand a much harsher, grittier reality of the lack of mutuality in families.
<p>
<li><a name="seventy2">Gerzog, <i>supra</i> note 25 at 35.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventy3">McIntyre &amp; Oldman, <i>supra</i> note 46 at 1595.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventy4">Davies, <i>supra</i> note 60 at 171.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventy5">The complexities</a> introduced by considering where the taxpayer lived in Canada are ignored.
<p>
<li><a name="seventy6">In fact,</a> this was one of the problems of the Carter Commission concept of non-discretionary expenses. The Commission said that non-discretionary expenses increase, although not proportionately as income rises. <i>supra</i> note 1 at 8-12. The amounts assigned at higher income levels were not convincing.
<p>
<li><a name="seventy7">This was the primary</a> criterion for distribution of taxation burdens adopted by the American Congress in 1948. Gann, <i>supra</i> note 25 at 24.
<p>
<li><a name="seventy8">Royal Commission on the Status of Women,</a> <cite>The Taxation of Women in Canada: A Research Report</cite> (Study No.5) by D.G. Hartle (Ottawa: Information Canada, 1969).
<p>
<li><a name="seventy9">Kathleen Lahey</a> is critical of the traditional analysis of imputed income and offers an alternative. &quot;Policy analysts have long believed that the tax exemption of women's nonwaged work from the tax base causes distortions, non-neutralities, and inequities among differently situated groups of taxpayers because it confers tax benefits on families that have such workers. Most policy analysts had always acted as if the nonwaged worker (women) `owned' that `imputed' income, and therefore was the taxpayer to whom it should be imputed. Indeed, this was one of the assumptions that had flawed the paper that Douglas Hartle had prepared for the Royal Commission on the Status of Women on the taxation of women. In contrast to this mainstream position, Jack London has made the suggestion that women should receive a money salary for this work, which would then make it possible to tax them on the value created without offending anyone's sense of fairness.&quot; K.A. Lahey, <cite>The Taxation of Women in Canada: A Research Report</cite> (Kingston: Queen's University, Faculty of Law, September 1988) at 67.
<p>
<li><a name="eighty"><cite>Report of the Royal Commission on the Status of Women in Canada</cite></a> (Ottawa: Information Canada, 1970). This report is sometimes referred to as &quot;the Bird Report,&quot; after the name of its Chair, Francis Bird.
