<p>
<li><a name="ninety1">The burden</a> of supporting another person is sometimes given as the justification for this differential. However it does not appear persuasive when the legal regimes governing support are examined.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety2">Gann,</a> <i>supra</i> note 25 at 26, n. 100. &quot;Let us grant that married couples share their incomes equally. But suppose that the world consisted only of couples with only one income recipient and single persons who live alone. Would the two-to-one relationship be equitable in such a world?  I believe
the answer would be clearly `No.'&quot;
<p>
<li><a name="ninety3">This is the main</a> basis for the conclusion of several commentators that abandoning
marital status as a basis for allocating tax burdens is the best route for the American tax system. Bittker,  <i>supra</i> note 25; and Gann, <i>supra</i> note 25 at 1--2. However, they then conclude that this is not politically feasible.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety4">This terminology,</a> which is used in all the literature, can be problematic. It implies that a stay-at-home wife does not work and that work can only be used to describe a situation outside the home where there is monetary compensation involved. The terminology serves to obscure the double-work day of many women who have waged employment. I use the terminology because I do not have an alternative.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety5">Bittker, <i>supra</i> note 25 at 1431.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="ninety6"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
