<p>
<li><a name="ninety8">This effect</a> is not limited to a two-income couple; anyone who works will have these expenses. However, I include the issue here as it is a factor whenever someone has a choice whether to work outside the home. It should be noted that this phenomenon is not limited to an aggregate system of taxation but would be present under an individual system where there was no earned income deduction or credit.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety9">Bittker, <i>supra</i> note 25 at 1431--1432.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="onehundred">Hearings on the Economic</a> Problems of Women Before the Joint Economic Committee, 93d Congress, 1st Session, pt. II, 254 (1973) as cited in Bittker, <i>supra</i> note 25 at 1432. Mrs X is married to a man with an income of $15,000 per year. She is offered two jobs: an industrial job that promises long hours and pays $15,000 and a college teaching job with flexible hours and a salary of $10,000. Since Mrs X feels that she must bear primary responsibility for the home duties, she considers only the teaching job. Mrs X finds that family expenses will increase by $5,000 if she returns to work. Her income will be taxed at her husband's marginal rate. His taxable income is $8,000 so her first dollar will be taxed at 22 percent. Her employment will therefore
increase the family's federal income tax bill from $1,380 to $3,820 (1972 rates); her share of the bill is $2,440. If State and local taxes average five percent, her cost is $500. Social security taxes amount to another $486 (1972 rates). Mrs X's gross income will yield a net of $1,592.
<p>
<li><a name="one01">The overproduction</a> and inefficiency is illustrated by the following example from Gann, <i>supra</i> note 25 at 40. Assume that Y works 40 hours each week outside the home and is paid $10 per hour. Y pays a housekeeper $7 per hour for 10 hours of work each week. The Government then imposes a 40-percent tax on Y's earned income, and the wages paid to the housekeeper are non-deductible personal expenditures. After the imposition of the tax, Y should choose to work only 30 hours in the marketplace and work 10 hours at home in place of hiring the housekeeper. This replacement saves Y $1 for each hour replaced---the difference between Y's after-tax wage per hour, and the housekeeper's wage per hour. The welfare cost to society is $3 per hour, the difference in the before-tax wage of Y and the housekeeper.
<p>
<li><a name="one02">C. O'Kelley, Jr.,</a> &quot;Tax Policy for Post-Liberal Society: A Flat-Tax-Inspired Redefinition of the Purpose and Ideal Structure of a Progressive Income Tax&quot; (1985) 58 S. Cal. L. Rev. 727 at 760.
<p>
<li><a name="one03"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a name="one04">Dominion Bureau of Statistics</a> as cited in M. Boyd, &quot;Changing Canadian Family Forms: Issues for Women&quot; in N. Mandell &amp; A. Duffy, eds., <cite>Reconstructing the Canadian Family: Feminist Perspectives</cite> (Toronto: Butterworths, 1988) 85 at 92.
<p>
<li><a name="one05">Gann, <i>supra</i> note 25 at 43.</a>
