<p>
<li><a name="one14">It is interesting</a> to note that the number of common-law unions has increased to the point that one in twelve couples now report living common-law. Since 1981 there has been a 38-percent increase in the number of reported common-law unions. In 1986, eight percent of all couples, about 487,000 families, reported that their union was common-law. In 1981, six percent of all couples, or about 352,000 families reported living in such unions. Target Groups Project of Statistics Canada, from Transition, June 1989.
<p>
<li><a name="one15">One example</a> is <cite>Ross v. M.N.R.</cite> [1992] Tax C.C.J., No. 92--1914(IT). This case on income-splitting is an example of demands for reallocation of tax burdens in an individual system of taxation.
<p>
<li><a name="one16">I do not want</a> to mislead by suggesting that these are the main factors of complexity in a taxation system. The <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> is becoming increasingly complicated; calculations for RRSP
contributions and the new child tax benefit provision are only two recent examples.
<p>
<li><a name="one17">This was the reason</a> given by half of the members when the last official examination of Canada's tax unit was done in 1975--76 by a federal Interdepartmental Committee on the Taxation of Women. On the issue of the tax unit, the committee was split down the middle. Half of its members, led by the Revenue Department, supported joint spousal taxation because they found it fairer and thought it would simplify the administration of the tax system. The other members were equally adamant that only separate taxation was fair because joint taxation would discriminate against employed women and create an undesirable tax on marriage. See <i>supra</i> note 8.
<p>
<li><a name="one18"><cite>Leshner v. Ministry of the Attorney General, Ont.</cite></a>, [1992] Ont. H.R.C. No. 443. This ruling potentially has profound implications for federal income tax law, initially with respect to pensions; but of course it is not binding on federal legislation.
<p>
<li><a name="one19">Administrative</a> feasibility issues may prove to be problematic in the proposed new
federal recognition of common-law opposite sex couples for tax purposes. The definition in the <cite>Act</cite> follows one year of cohabitation; in contrast, responsibilities for support under Ontario family law require three years of cohabitation in a conjugal relationship. See <cite>Family Law Act</cite>, R.S.O. 1990, c. F.3, ss 29(a), 30.
<p>
<li><a name="one20">The Fair Tax Commission's Working Group,</a> <i>supra</i> note 66 at 9, citing M.
