<p>
<li><a name="one21">The Commission</a> assertion that aggregation was the norm in nearly all &quot;the important countries,&quot; including the United States, Britain, and nearly all the European countries, is interesting. They stated, &quot;Canada is a conspicuous exception in its adherence to the individual basis of taxation.&quot;
<i>supra</i> note 1 at 124. Based on the OECD report, <i>supra</i> note 88, and the hard data that the trend in Western industrialized countries since 1955 has been toward the individual as the unit of taxation and away from compulsory joint taxation, <i>ibid.</i> at 17, this assertion seems perplexing.
<p>
<li><a name="one22">It is interesting</a> to speculate on why the Carter Commission adopted its recommendation, but the truth is no doubt lost in the annals of history. Kathleen Lahey suggests that the Commission's recommendations on the taxation of the family represent a clear statement about the relative importance of families and women, and a blatantly sexist approach. She suggests that as long as women are subsumed within the conceptual units like the household and the family, tax policy criteria like equity, neutrality, and fairness do not apply to them. The family as the tax unit appears to have intuitive appeal to economists, who have been trained to think of the household as the smallest economic unit for most purposes. They tend not to notice that such thinking submerges women's roles and that by subsuming a weaker individual into a group, there is the inevitable economic domination by the stronger individual. Lahey, <i>supra</i> note 79 at 54--55.
<p>
<li><a name="one23">The spectre of American</a> influence is a continuing factor in Canadian discussions of policy issues. For example, the current debates on health care systems show the very real pressures that exist on Canada to harmonize its programs with that of the United States, its largest trading partner.
<p>
<li><a name="one24">The Tax Court of Canada</a> rejected the challenge and was upheld by the Federal Court of Appeal. The case is currently seeking leave to appeal to the Supreme Court of Canada. Tax C.C.J., No. 91--1006(IT); F.C.C.A. [1993], No. A--1190--91.
