<html>
<head>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 52 No. 1</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="v52n1.htm">Volume 52 Number 1</a>]</center><p><br>
<h1> Standing to Challenge Searches and Seizures Under the <cite>Charter</cite>: The Lessons of the American Experience and Their Application to Canadian Law
<p> 
 JONATHAN DAWE</h1>
<p><br>
<i>Taken together, s. 8 and s. 24(2) of the </i>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms<I> allow persons whose right to be secure against unreasonable searches and seizures has been infringed to prevent any evidence seized from being used against them. The following question then arises: what is the extent of the right protected by s. 8?  While the Supreme Court has not conclusively answered this question, several provincial Courts of Appeal have followed the American case law in this area and adopted restrictive definitions of privacy accompanied by narrow rules of standing. In this paper the author argues that the American approach is theoretically flawed and badly suited for incorporation into </i>Charter<i> jurisprudence. Instead, the author suggests, adopting a broader conception of the interests protected by s. 8 would help Canadian courts avoid the confusion and inconsistency of the American
doctrine. In addition, it is argued that a fully realized understanding of these interests would allow for a more coherent articulation of the principles of the s. 24(2) exclusionary remedy than is available under the existing doctrine.
<p>
La consid&eacute;ration conjointe des articles 8 et 24(2) de la </i>Charte canadienne des droits et libert&eacute;s<i>  permet &agrave; ceux et celles qui ont subi une violation du droit &agrave; la protection
contre les fouilles ou les saisies abusives d'emp&ecirc;cher l'utilisation &agrave; leur encontre des &eacute;l&eacute;ments de preuve saisis. Il faut donc poser la question suivante: quelle est l'&eacute;tendue du
droit prot&eacute;g&eacute; par l'article 8?  La Cour supr&ecirc;me n'est pas encore parvenue &agrave; une r&eacute;ponse concr&egrave;te &agrave; cette question. Pourtant plusieurs cours d'appel provinciales ont suivi la
jurisprudence am&eacute;ricaine et ont adopt&eacute; des d&eacute;finitions restrictives sur le droit &agrave; la vie priv&eacute;e ainsi que des r&egrave;gles &eacute;troites sur le droit de se pr&eacute;senter devant une cour de justice. Dans cet article, l'auteur sugg&egrave;re que les principes derri&egrave;re la m&eacute;thode am&eacute;ricaine sont imparfaits et ne devraient pas &ecirc;tre incorpor&eacute;s dans la jurisprudence de la Charte. Il sugg&egrave;re par contre qu'une conception plus large des int&eacute;r&ecirc;ts prot&eacute;g&eacute;s par l'article 8 aiderait les tribunaux canadiens &agrave; &eacute;viter la confusion et l'inconsistance de la doctrine am&eacute;ricaine. L'auteur propose &eacute;galement qu'une bonne compr&eacute;hension de ces int&eacute;r&ecirc;ts permettrait une articulation plus coh&eacute;rente que celle qui existe sous la doctrine courante des principes du rem&egrave;de d'exclusion de l'article 24(2).</i>
<p><br>
<h3>Introduction</h3>

Section 8 of the <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite><sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> guarantees the right of Canadians to &quot;be secure against unreasonable search and seizure.&quot;<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> When called on to define the extent of this right and, as a consequence,
the availability of the remedies provided by s. 24,<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> Canadian courts have often been presented with difficult interpretive choices. Although the jurisprudence developed since 1982 has established many key components of the framework of Canadian search and seizure doctrine, a number of important interpretive choices have yet to be made, and several significant issues remain unresolved. One problem that remains outstanding is often referred to as the question of &quot;standing:&quot;<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> given that an unreasonable search and seizure has taken place, who is entitled to object to its constitutionality, and who can claim a remedy under s. 24?  Since s. 24 grants a remedy only to persons &quot;whose rights or freedoms . . . have been infringed,&quot; resolving the question of standing will often require an explicit or implicit determination of the scope of the right guaranteed by s. 8.
<p>
Although the Supreme Court of Canada has not conclusively addressed the issue of standing in search and seizure cases, many Canadian courts that have considered the matter have looked to the American jurisprudence for guidance, and have incorporated into their judgments varying aspects of the American doctrine on standing. Although the U.S. experience is often a valuable tool that can be used in analysing <cite>Charter</cite> issues, careful consideration must be given to the applicability of U.S. precedent to Canada. Even more importantly, courts must consider whether the path taken by American courts is one that <i>should</i> be followed in Canada, or whether public policy, constitutional theory, or both would be better served by a different approach. In the case of the problem of standing in search and seizure cases, it can be argued that the current U.S. doctrine is seriously flawed, and that Canadian courts should consider a different alternative. So far, however, Canadian courts have not done so; rather, the tendency in both the trial courts and the provincial courts of appeal has been to adopt the American doctrine on standing in search and seizure cases without critically analysing either the doctrine itself or its applicability to the situation under the Canadian Constitution. 
<p>
The numerous flaws in American Fourth Amendment<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> jurisprudence have often been pointed out by commentators in the United States. In 1973, one observer noted that the situation was &quot;a mess&quot;<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup>; by 1983 another commentator was moved to remark that &quot;the
situation has not improved&quot;<sup><a href="seven">7</a></sup> in the intervening years. Although another decade has now passed, the U.S. Supreme Court has done little to respond to these criticisms. Since the early 1970s the Court has adopted increasingly restrictive standing rules, based on an ever-shrinking conception of what constitutes a legitimate expectation of privacy. The effect has been a considerable limitation on the situations where the Fourth Amendment can be appealed to and the exclusionary rule invoked. At the same time, the Court has characterized the exclusionary rule as being intended solely as a means of police control. The incoherence of this state of affairs is evident---if the purpose of the exclusionary rule is to deter police misconduct, it hardly makes
sense not to exclude evidence in cases of flagrant police misbehaviour solely because the applicant cannot tie the misconduct sufficiently closely to a violation of his or her individual privacy interests. This has been pointed out by Professor Doernberg, who comments:
<blockquote>
When the Court speaks of fourth amendment rights, it speaks only of individuals; when it speaks of remedies, it speaks only of society as a collective unit. Clearly the Court is operating under different and inconsistent theories of fourth amendment rights and remedies.<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Doernberg has suggested that the reason for this incoherence is a failure on the part of the Court to appreciate that
the Fourth Amendment has a dual nature---it is intended &quot;both to protect the rights of individuals and to prevent the government from functioning as in a police state.&quot;<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> This
latter &quot;collective right,&quot; he proposes, implicitly underlies the &quot;police regulation&quot; aspect of the exclusionary rule, and deserves recognition in the form of a broader conception of the right enshrined in the Fourth Amendment and, consequently, a more liberal approach to standing rules.
<p>
This article sets out to argue that the criticism that has been directed at American standing rules in search and seizure cases has important consequences for the development of the law in Canada. First, it will be argued that the course chosen by the U.S. Supreme Court in dealing with standing in search and seizure cases is inconsistent with Fourth Amendment principles---principles that also underlie the <cite>Charter's</cite> protections against unreasonable search and seizure. It will be suggested that the resulting confusion and incoherence of the American jurisprudence make it a poor model for Canadian courts to follow. Secondly, it will be argued that the structure of the right and remedy under the <cite>Charter</cite> differs in significant respects from the Fourth Amendment, so that even if a narrow standing regime were suitable in the United States it would nonetheless be inappropriate in the
Canadian context. Finally, the article will suggest that rejecting the American approach to standing in search and seizure cases and applying ideas similar to Doernberg's conception of Fourth Amendment rights to the <cite>Charter</cite> would have an additional benefit for Canadian law: as well as avoiding the confusion of the American  doctrine, such an approach to the right guaranteed by s. 8 would, it is suggested, make s. 8 more consistent with certain aspects of the exclusionary remedy provided by s. 24(2). Before proceeding with these arguments, however, it is necessary to review briefly the American doctrine on standing in search and seizure cases and to examine how it has been applied by Canadian courts in the context of the <cite>Charter</cite>.
<p>
<h3>U.S. Fourth Amendment &quot;Standing&quot; Doctrine<sup><href="#ten">10</a></sup></h3>

For a considerable period of time following the birth of the exclusionary rule<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> in the United States, the U.S. Supreme Court did not consider in detail the
question of who was entitled to invoke it. Lower federal courts did address the issue, however, holding that in order to establish a Fourth Amendment violation a claimant must have had some proprietary or related interest in the goods seized or the place searched.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup>
<p>
In <cite>Jones v. United States</cite><sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> the U.S. Supreme Court rejected the narrow property-based standing doctrine developed in the courts below in favour of a broader rule. In this case, Jones had been charged with possession of narcotics following a search of a friend's apartment to which he had free access. He wished to challenge the constitutionality of the search warrant, claiming that it had been issued without probable cause having been shown. Since Jones was not the tenant of the apartment, the trial court and court of appeal had denied him standing to make this claim, based on the fact that he had no proprietary interest in the place searched. The alternative route to standing under the existing doctrine---establishing a proprietary interest in the goods seized---was also effectively closed to Jones, since if he admitted to owning the drugs, this admission could be used against him at trial even if the drugs themselves were excluded as evidence.
<p>
The Supreme Court disagreed with the courts below, and found two alternative grounds for granting standing to Jones. Stating that:
<blockquote>
It is unnecessary and ill-advised to import into the law surrounding the constitutional right to be free from
unreasonable searches and seizures subtle distinctions, developed and refined by the common law in evolving the body of private property law which, more than perhaps any other branch of law, has been shaped by distinctions whose validity is largely historical. . . <sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup>
</blockquote>
the Court rejected the idea that a proprietary interest in the place searched was required to bestow standing on an applicant. The majority instead declared that:
<blockquote>
[A]nyone legitimately on premises where a search occurs may challenge its legality by way of a motion to suppress,
when its fruits are proposed to be used against him.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Turning to the second ground Jones had raised, the Court pointed out that:
<blockquote>
[T]o hold that petitioner's failure to acknowledge interest in the narcotics . . . prevented his attack upon the search, would be to permit the Government to have the advantage of contradictory positions as a basis for conviction. Petitioner's conviction flows from his possession of the narcotics at the time of the search. Yet the fruits of that search, upon which the conviction depends, were admitted into evidence on the ground that petitioner did not have possession of the narcotics at that time. It is not consonant with the amenities, to put it mildly, of the administration
of criminal justice to sanction such squarely contradictory assertions of power by the Government.<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup>
</blockquote>
To counter this problem, the Court held that people charged with possessory offences would be entitled to challenge the constitutionality of the search that led to the seizure of the objects they stood accused of possessing without having to prove that they were in fact in possession of the items,<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> a rule which became known as the &quot;automatic standing rule.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup>
<p>
The Court moved Fourth Amendment doctrine even further away from a property-based approach in a subsequent case, <cite>Katz v. United States</cite>.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> The petitioner in <cite>Katz</cite> had made a number of telephone calls from a public telephone that, unbeknownst to him, was being monitored electronically by the police (who were acting without a warrant). The Court began by holding that electronic eavesdropping constituted a search under the Fourth Amendment. Declaring that &quot;the Fourth Amendment protects people, not places,&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> the Court went on to reject the government's characterization of the issue as being whether a telephone booth was a &quot;constitutionally protected area.&quot;  Rather, the Court stated that the purpose of the Fourth Amendment was the protection of citizens from government intrusion of their privacy rights, and that the relevant consideration was whether the victim of the search had an identifiable privacy interest. Harlan J., concurring, articulated a test that found favour in the cases that followed:
<blockquote>
[T]here is a twofold requirement, first that a person have exhibited an actual (subjective) expectation of privacy
and, second, that the expectation be one that society is prepared to recognize as &quot;reasonable.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In <cite>Mancusi v. DeForte</cite><sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> the court applied its new privacy-based understanding of the Fourth Amendment to the issue of standing. DeForte, a Teamsters Union official, sought standing to challenge the search of the union headquarters and the seizure of certain papers. DeForte did not have a private office at the headquarters (he shared an office with other union officials) and did not have a proprietary interest in the materials seized, which belonged to the union. The Court granted him standing nevertheless, citing <cite>Jones</cite> and <cite>Katz</cite> and declaring that, while DeForte may not have had the legal power to exclude all others from the shared office, he nonetheless had &quot;a reasonable expectation of freedom from governmental intrusion.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> 
<p>
In the 1969 decision in <cite>Alderman v. United States</cite>,<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> the Court addressed the issue of whether someone could apply under the exclusionary rule for suppression of evidence obtained through a violation of a third party's privacy interests, a question that had been mentioned in passing but not firmly resolved in several of the earlier cases discussed above. The case involved a number of conspiracy charges, which had been brought after evidence against the alleged conspirators had been obtained by police wiretaps of one accused's house. The various accused were affected by the wiretaps in different ways: some of the alleged conspirators' own conversations had been recorded; another had not had his own conversations taped, but owned the house where the wiretaps were placed; and a third group was implicated in the taped conversations of the others although their own conversations had not been recorded. The Court held that the latter group did not have standing to challenge the admission of the evidence, stating that:
<blockquote>
[S]uppression of the product of a Fourth Amendment violation can be successfully urged only by those whose rights were violated by the search itself, not by those who are aggrieved solely by the introduction of damaging evidence.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Court went on to declare that &quot;Fourth Amendment rights are personal rights which, like some other constitutional rights, may not be vicariously asserted.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> However,
the court continued by granting standing to the petitioner whose property had been implicated in the eavesdropping, holding that either privacy interests (under <cite>Katz</cite>) or proprietary interests (under the pre-<cite>Katz</cite> rule) were sufficient to confer standing on a claimant.<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup>
<p>
Fortas J. dissented on the first point, declaring that:
<blockquote>
The Fourth Amendment is not merely a privilege accorded to him whose domain has been lawlessly invaded. It grants the individual a personal right, not to privacy, but to insist that the state utilize only lawful means of proceeding against him.<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup>
</blockquote>
He went on to add that while <cite>Jones</cite> held that &quot;something more than the generalized interest of any citizen in governmental obedience to law&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> was required to give a claimant standing, anyone &quot;against whom the search was directed&quot; was &quot;the victim of an invasion of privacy&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> within the meaning of the <cite>Jones</cite> test, even if it was not his or her possessions or surroundings that were searched. Being the target of the unconstitutional search, in his view, was
<blockquote>
enough to give [the target of the search] &quot;standing&quot; to object that the government agents conducted their
unlawful search and seizure to obtain evidence to use against him. The Government violates his rights when it seeks to deprive him of his liberty by unlawfully seizing evidence in the course of an investigation and using it against him at trial.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The approach taken by Fortas J. (which became known as &quot;target standing&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup>) was explicitly rejected by the Court in the 1979 decision in <cite>Rakas v. Illinois</cite>,<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup> a case that initiated the Court's movement toward both a narrowed standing doctrine and a narrowed conception of privacy. In <cite>Rakas</cite>, a car carrying three men (one of whom was the car's owner) was unlawfully stopped and searched, and evidence was found that implicated the car's occupants in a robbery which had recently taken place. The two non-owners sought to have this evidence excluded, arguing first that they were targets of the search, and alternatively that they were &quot;legitimately on the premises&quot; of their friend's car, and thus entitled to standing by virtue of  <cite>Jones</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> Rehnquist J., writing for the Court, categorically rejected the &quot;target standing&quot; approach, declaring that:
<blockquote>
A person who is aggrieved by an illegal search and seizure only through the introduction of damaging evidence secured by a search of a third person's premises or property has not had any of his Fourth Amendment rights infringed.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Turning to the second argument, Rehnquist J. overruled the &quot;legitimately on the premises&quot; test derived from <cite>Jones</cite>, while maintaining that <cite>Jones</cite> was correctly decided on its facts:
<blockquote>
We think that <cite>Jones</cite> on its facts merely stands for the unremarkable proposition that a person can have a legally sufficient interest in a place other than his own home so that the Fourth Amendment protects him from unreasonable government intrusion into that place.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The sole correct approach, according to the Court, was whether the petitioner had a &quot;legitimate expectation of
privacy&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> in the place searched. Whether or not the claimant was legitimately on the premises might be relevant to the question of whether or not he or she had a legitimate expectation of privacy, but it could not &quot;be deemed controlling.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup>
<p>
In rejecting the defendants' assertion that they had a legitimate expectation of privacy while in the car, the majority did not exhaustively state what considerations it believed would be relevant in applying the &quot;legitimate expectation of privacy&quot; test. Considerable attention was paid, however, to the fact that the defendants &quot;asserted neither a property nor a possessory interest in the automobile, nor an interest in the property seized.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> To the four dissenters, led by White J., the true meaning of the majority's opinion was that: 
<blockquote>
The Court today holds that the Fourth Amendment protects property, not people, and specifically that a legitimate
occupant of an automobile may not invoke the exclusionary rule and challenge a search of that vehicle unless he happens to own or have a possessory interest in it.<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In the dissenters' view, this approach had &quot;no support in the Court's controlling decisions, or in common sense.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup>
<p>
Although the <cite>Rakas</cite> majority disputed the dissenters' contention that property rights had played a paramount role in its decision, the dissenters' claim that the majority was equating privacy with property gained some credibility in 1980 with the release of the Court's decision in <cite>Rawlings v. Kentucky</cite>.<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup> The accused in this case had placed a quantity of drugs in his friend Cox's purse (with her consent) as they visited a friend's house. While they were there, the police arrived, intending to arrest one of the house's occupants who, as it turned out, was not home at the time. Once inside the house the police unlawfully detained all those present while a search warrant was sent for, telling them that they could only leave if they consented to be searched. Rawlings and Cox were thus detained illegally until the warrant arrived, at which point Cox's purse was searched and the drugs were found. Rawlings claimed them as his own, and at trial sought to have the evidence excluded. Rehnquist J., again writing for the Court, held that Rawlings did not have a reasonable expectation of privacy in Cox's purse. He based his opinion on a number of factors, which included the fact that Rawlings had known Cox for only a week and the ground that he did not &quot;have any right to exclude other persons from access to Cox's purse.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> As one commentator on
the decision has pointed out, this appears to reject the concept of  relative privacy from government intrusion contained in <cite>DeForte</cite> (as contrasted with the property-based concept of freedom from intrusion by the whole world):
<blockquote>
Though Rawlings may not have anticipated total privacy vis-&agrave;-vis Cox and her invitees, he may nonetheless have expected that the government would be excluded. But as <cite>Rakas</cite> . . . and <cite>Rawlings</cite> now make clear, expectation of freedom from governmental intrusion is not sufficient to bring the fourth amendment into play; the new doctrine of standing requires freedom from any intrusion.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In a further development, the majority also rejected Rawlings' contention that he had standing on the basis of his
admitted ownership of the drugs, a doctrine that, as noted earlier, pre-dated <cite>Jones</cite> and had been upheld in <cite>Alderman</cite>.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup> Finally, in <cite>United States v. Salvucci</cite>,<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> released the same day as <cite>Rawlings</cite>, the Court overturned the &quot;automatic standing&quot; rule of <cite>Jones</cite>, preventing Rawlings from claiming standing in that way.
<p>
 The state of affairs arrived at after <cite>Rawlings</cite> and <cite>Salvucci</cite> (which has not changed appreciably in the past thirteen years) can be summarized as follows: the U.S. Court has clearly rejected any concept of &quot;vicarious&quot; standing,<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> and has, moreover, rejected the idea that the Fourth Amendment contains a right to be secure against illegal government activity <i>per se</i>.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> Instead, the Court's conception of the Fourth Amendment has collapsed into the question of whether there existed a &quot;legitimate expectation of privacy&quot;<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> ---an expectation of privacy both subjectively held and objectively reasonable. In determining whether a legitimate expectation of privacy exists, the Court now applies a very narrow understanding of privacy---one based heavily (although perhaps not exclusively) on concepts of private property, and one that recognizes no distinction between expectations of privacy <i>vis-&agrave;-vis</i> the state and expectations <i>vis-&agrave;-vis</i> the rest of the world.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> At the same time, a property interest in the item seized is no longer sufficient by itself to grant standing to a petitioner---a separate expectation of privacy must be established.<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup>
<p>
While the above discussion includes only a fraction of the many twists, turns, and exceptions that have arisen during the &quot;tortured history&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup> of this area of Fourth Amendment law, it does serve to describe the American doctrine's chief salient features, the relevance and wisdom of which must be considered by Canadian courts as they attempt to draw from the American experience. The following section will
briefly outline the way in which Canadian courts have considered and adopted the American &quot;standing&quot; doctrine in their s. 8 jurisprudence. 
<p>
<h3>Section 8 of the <cite>Charter</cite></h3>

In its first major pronouncement on s. 8 interpretation, <cite>Hunter v. Southam</cite>,<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup> the Supreme Court of Canada stated clearly that privacy interests, not property interests, were the basis of the s. 8 right. Dickson J. (as he then was) referred approvingly to the U.S. Supreme Court's formulation of the Fourth Amendment right in <cite>Katz</cite>,<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> noting that:
<blockquote>
[In <cite>Katz</cite>] Justice Stewart rejected any necessary connection between that Amendment and the notion of trespass. With respect, I believe this approach is equally appropriate in construing the protections in s. 8 of the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup>
</blockquote>
He was careful, however, to leave open the possibility that s. 8 rights might extend beyond an interest in privacy:
<blockquote>
I would be wary of foreclosing the possibility that the right to be secure against unreasonable search and seizure might protect interests beyond the right of privacy, but for purposes of the present appeal I am satisfied that its protections go at least that far.<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In subsequent decisions, the Supreme Court has made it clear that s. 8 protection extends to such violations of privacy as electronic eavesdropping.<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> The Court has not yet specified in detail, however, the full nature and extent of the right to privacy, and has not elaborated on the idea that s. 8 may protect interests beyond privacy.
<p>
A number of early decisions by lower courts in Canada did not follow the narrow American interpretation of the &quot;reasonable expectation of privacy test,&quot; and instead construed the privacy rights referred to by the Supreme Court in <cite>Hunter v. Southam</cite> broadly.<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup> For example, in <cite>Re Church of Scientology and the Queen</cite><sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> the Ontario High Court held that individuals had a privacy interest in church records of &quot;counselling sessions&quot; which had been seized. The reason for this was that the individuals had expected the church would keep the information confidential, although the documents were church property rather than the property of the individuals. Borins J. of the Ontario District Court went somewhat further in <cite>R. v. Guiller</cite>,<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> a case involving an unlawful search of a third party's premises that led to the seizure of letters written by the accused. In granting the accused standing to challenge the search, the judge stated:
<blockquote>
It seems to me that a reasonable expectation of privacy contains the expectation that when a search of third party
premises is conducted, as a result of which evidence prejudicial to an accused is located and seized, the search will be conducted pursuant to constitutionally valid standards.<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This result was followed in <cite>R. v. Leonard</cite>,<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> which involved
a situation similar to that encountered in <cite>Rawlings</cite> (a body search of the accused's travelling companion leading to the seizure of narcotics).
<p>
However, the validity of these decisions as precedents has been placed in doubt by several more recent decisions of the Alberta, Ontario, and British Columbia Courts of Appeal. In the 1987 decision in <cite>R. v. Leaney and  Rawlinson</cite><sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> the Alberta Court of Appeal denied Leaney standing to challenge searches of his co-accused Rawlinson's apartment, on the grounds that he did not have a reasonable expectation of privacy in the place searched.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> The Court, however, merely stated its conclusion on this issue without giving detailed supporting reasons. A more exhaustive treatment was
provided by the Ontario Court of Appeal in <cite>R. v. Pugliese</cite>.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup> In that case the Ontario Court referred extensively and approvingly to the U.S. Supreme Court's <cite>Rakas, Rawlings</cite>, and <cite>Salvucci</cite> decisions and rejected the appellant's claim that he had standing to challenge the seizure of cocaine from the apartment of one McInnis, who allegedly worked as a &quot;runner&quot; for the appellant's narcotics trafficking operation. Pugliese had argued both that he had an expectation of privacy in McInnis's apartment, and alternatively that he acquired standing from the fact that he was
the target of the search. The Court rejected both of these contentions. In discussing the privacy claim, Finlayson J.A. began by noting that &quot;the appellant . . . was in no position to refuse entry to McInnis's apartment to any person who had McInnis's permission to enter.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> However, he then changed direction, declaring that &quot;this discussion about the appellant's legal or proprietary rights in the premises or
in the articles seized is beside the point,&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup> and that the real issue was whether there was a reasonable expectation of privacy. He continued by saying that there was no evidence on the record suggesting that the accused ever had such an expectation. To what extent the judgment should be read as an
acceptance of the narrow and largely property-based American approach to privacy is thus somewhat uncertain, although the number of apparently approving references to the above-mentioned U.S. cases is suggestive.
<p>
On the issue of &quot;target standing&quot; the Court was considerably less equivocal, rejecting it in no uncertain terms. &quot;The appellant's target theory,&quot; declared the Court, &quot;has never been accepted in this jurisdiction and has been specifically rejected in the United States.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> Finlayson J.A. went on to declare that:
<blockquote>
A constitutional right to privacy is not created merely by reason of a person becoming the target of a search. An
accused person's right to challenge the legality of a search and seizure depends upon whether he has first discharged the burden of satisfying the court that <i>his</i> personal constitutional rights have been violated.<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The approach taken by the Ontario Court in <cite>Pugliese</cite> has been approved on several occasions by the British Columbia Court of Appeal.<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> In <cite>R. v. Arason and
Desrosier</cite><sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup> the B.C. Court held that the appellants had no standing to challenge a warrantless perimeter search of a building leased by a third party which the appellants used to grow marijuana, on the grounds that the lessee was the building's sole &quot;occupant.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> Similarly, in <cite>R. v. Sandhu</cite><sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> the Court denied the accused standing to challenge the constitutionality of a warrantless search of a co-accused's bag. After discussing the Ontario Court's holding in <cite>Pugliese</cite>, Prowse J.A. declared:
<blockquote>
In this case, I conclude that Mr Sandhu does not have standing to challenge the admissibility of the evidence obtained in the search and seizure on December 27, 1990 at the airport. The onus was on him to prove, on a balance of probabilities, that he had a reasonable expectation of privacy with respect to the bag and its contents. The evidence does not support that conclusion. Although the evidence does suggest that Mr Ahmed [the co-accused] had a reasonable expectation of privacy with respect to the bag and its contents, the authorities do not support the proposition that Mr Sandhu can rely on that fact to give him standing in these circumstances.<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup>
</blockquote>
These decisions raise a number of important issues which will be discussed below. To begin, the &quot;expectation of privacy&quot; standard will be examined, and problems associated with its implementation in the United States will be discussed. This, in turn, will lead into a discussion of the differences between the American exclusionary rule and s. 24(2) of the <cite>Charter</cite>---differences which, it will be argued, make the American standing doctrine unsuitable for adoption in Canada. Finally, the nature of the right and remedy in the <cite>Charter</cite> will be discussed, with reference to several American commentators who have criticized and offered alternatives to the current U.S. doctrine. It will be argued that a broad conception of the right enshrined in s. 8 (and, consequently, a liberal standing rule) is supported by the language and purpose of the <cite>Charter</cite>. Moreover, it will be suggested that such a broad understanding of s. 8 would further benefit the <cite>Charter</cite> by helping to relate s. 8 to the exclusionary rule, creating a theoretical basis for the full development of section 24(2).
<p>
<h3>Problems with the &quot;Expectation of Privacy&quot; Test</h3>

While the initial change from a &quot;property-based&quot; to a &quot;privacy-based&quot; rationale for Fourth Amendment rights in the United States was widely seen as having\break expanded those rights considerably,<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> the &quot;privacy&quot; standard has proven vulnerable to subsequent re-narrowing by the courts. In the words of one commentator:
<blockquote>
The progression from <cite>Jones</cite> to <cite>Rawlings</cite> provides a painful lesson for those who support a broad view of the fourth amendment. The vague, all-encompassing test of <cite>Katz</cite>, with its dependence on questions of fact for deciding fourth amendment issues, has proved just as useful for restricting constitutional protections late in the 1970's as it was for expanding those protections a decade [earlier].<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The source of the problem is the fact that the term &quot;privacy,&quot; which is intended in both Fourth Amendment and <cite>Charter</cite> jurisprudence to delineate the extent of the constitutionally protected &quot;security&quot; interest, is only marginally less vague than the word &quot;security&quot; it stands in place of. As a consequence, the privacy standard carries with it the inherent danger that it will be applied in a conclusory way, and that analysis will in actuality be driven by the court's view of the advisability of the exclusionary remedy rather than by considerations of what truly constitutes a &quot;legitimate&quot; or &quot;reasonable&quot; expectation of privacy. There is ample evidence supporting the argument that distaste for the exclusionary rule was in fact the prime motivating force behind the Burger Court's narrowing of Fourth Amendment &quot;standing&quot; doctrine.<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup> In <cite>Rakas</cite>, Rehnquist J. commented disparagingly that:
<blockqutoe>
Each time the exclusionary rule is applied it exacts a substantial social cost for the vindication of Fourth
Amendment rights. Relevant and reliable evidence is kept from the trier of fact and the search for truth at trial is
deflected.<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Burger C.J., for his part, also attacked the exclusionary rule on a number of occasions.<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup> In view of this hostility toward the remedy, one can interpret the Court's reluctance to grant standing as being motivated by a desire to avoid applying the exclusionary rule rather
than by considerations flowing out of a well thought out theory of privacy.
<p>
The consequence of the Court's reliance on standing as a covert tool for attacking the exclusionary rule has been a body of jurisprudence that often turns on distinctions that appear irrelevant or even irrational when seen in terms of an ordinary, everyday understanding of privacy. For example, following the holding in <cite>Rakas</cite> that ordinary passengers in a car do not have standing to object to its search, lower courts on one occasion held that a
passenger in a taxi had an expectation of privacy (since he could &quot;determine its destination . . . [and] exclude others from it during his ride&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup>), but on another occasion determined that a driver in sole possession of a rental car did not have such an expectation of privacy, on the grounds that he was in violation of the terms of the rental contract (which named his wife the sole driver) and thus had relinquished any legally enforceable possessory right in the car.<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup> It is difficult to relate
this type of casuistic distinction to any conventional understanding of privacy, and it is even more difficult to justify on policy grounds why this type of distinction <i>should</i> determine the constitutionality of a search. There is at least some value in having legal doctrine that is sensible and clear, and it is difficult to argue that the American standing doctrine has either of these qualities.
<p>
In addition to the above criticism of the inconsistent and peculiar outcomes of cases under the American doctrine, the Burger Court's jurisprudence on standing can be attacked by arguing that several of the central propositions introduced and relied on by the Court in reaching its conclusions are incorrect. One of the most troubling of these propositions is the contention (expressed initially in <cite>Rakas</cite> and reiterated in <cite>Rawlings</cite>) that an expectation of privacy from intrusion by the whole world is a necessary antecedent to an expectation of privacy from intrusion by government agents. Such a position runs completely counter to most people's experience---in countless situations in day-to-day life people reveal secrets or entrust items to others in implicit reliance that the items or information will not be turned over to the government, albeit with no legal recourse that would prevent the
recipient of the trust from violating it. It is rather perverse to declare that any such expectation of privacy is &quot;unreasonable&quot; simply because it is somewhat weaker than an expectation backed up by an enforceable private-law interest. The unsuccessful petitioners in <cite>Rakas</cite>, for instance, were accused of having committed an armed robbery in concert with the car's owner (and driver), and no doubt fully expected that the owner would not voluntarily provide evidence to the police that would incriminate them all---an expectation that
in hindsight appears to have been fully justified, since the owner in fact did not consent to the police search (and successfully argued that it violated his own constitutional rights). The petitioners' trust in the owner certainly appears &quot;reasonable&quot; in the usual sense of the word---the chances of it being broken were remote.
Nonetheless, the Court in essence held that the remote possibility that the owner <i>might</i> voluntarily reveal their joint secret (a chance that did <i>not</i> materialize) was sufficient to destroy the occupants' expectation of privacy entirely.
<p>
Such a limited understanding of &quot;privacy&quot; has very little connection with the ordinary person's conception of the term. As LaFave points out:
<blockquote>
[W]hile a &quot;right to exclude&quot; may be an easy way to establish the requisite legitimate expectation of privacy, it hardly follows that it is the <i>only way</i>; as the <cite>Rawlings</cite> dissenters note, &quot;such a harsh threshold requirement was not imposed even in the heyday of a property rights oriented Fourth Amendment.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Although the person who controls admission to premises or who is the bailee of goods may have the power to allow a police search against the will of the accused, the Court's approach leads to &quot;the incredible result that whenever police could conduct a lawful search with the bailee's [or owner of the premises's] consent, they may then proceed to make that search without the bailee's [or owner's] consent because the bailor will not have standing to
object.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup>
<p>
 A further difficulty with the U.S. Supreme Court's approach to standing arises from the fact that it fails to distinguish between two very different reasons that might underlie an absence of subjective expectation of freedom from government intrusion. A person might lack such a subjective expectation, for example, because he or she is carrying out some activity in a public place. Alternatively, the subjective expectation could be destroyed simply because the government has made it clear that the person's privacy interests are not going to be respected by the state (an &quot;Orwellian type of advance notice,&quot; in the words of one author).<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> For instance, in <cite>Rawlings</cite> much was made by the Court of the fact that Rawlings admitted at trial that he expected Cox's purse would be searched by the police---the Court considered this indicative of his lack of subjective expectation that the purse would be free from governmental intrusion. However, as several commentators have pointed out,<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup> Rawlings may well have meant by his admission only that his subjective expectation that the purse would remain protected from government intrusion vanished once the police arrived at the house, illegally detained the occupants and their guests, and made it absolutely clear that everyone was going to be searched whether they consented or not. As LaFave points out:
<blockquote>
[I]f one can be deprived of Fourth Amendment standing by being informed in advance by the police of the intrusion
they intend to make, then it is certainly correct, as the <cite>Rawlings</cite> dissenters complained, that the majority &quot;has turned the development of the law of search and seizure on its head.&quot;  This would mean, for example, that Rawlings likewise had no standing with respect to his own person, which he also expected would be intruded on by the police, and that equally ridiculous results would obtain in an infinite variety of search cases.<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup>
</blockquote>
As noted earlier, several provincial Courts of Appeal have adopted the constricted view of privacy articulated by the U.S. Supreme Court. In a few decisions, moreover, these courts have relied on property-based considerations reminiscent of those found in <cite>Rakas</cite>.<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup> In light of the above
criticisms of the American standing doctrine, it can be argued that this wholesale incorporation of flawed U.S. jurisprudence into Canadian law should be rejected by the Supreme Court of Canada. There are additional arguments that can be made in support of an alternative approach to the question of standing in search and seizure cases. Before discussing these arguments, however, it is necessary to outline the Canadian and American rules governing the exclusion of illegally obtained evidence.
<p>
<h3>The Canadian and American Exclusionary Rules</h3>

Although the rights guaranteed in s. 8 of the <cite>Charter</cite> are similar in many respects to those protected by the Fourth Amendment, the two constitutional provisions are not identical. As Dickson J. warned in <cite>Hunter</cite>, because of the differences &quot;American decisions can be transplanted into the Canadian context only with the greatest of caution.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup>
<p>
 An even greater barrier to the importation of American doctrine into Canadian law is presented, however, by the very different remedial structures of the two constitutions. Unlike the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>, the Constitution of the United States contains no express remedial provision analogous to
either s. 52 or s. 24. In particular, the American exclusionary rule emerged as a &quot;judge-made&quot; remedy to Fourth Amendment violations and, as such, does not contain internal qualifiers to its application such as those found in s. 24(2) of the <cite>Charter</cite>.
<p>
EVOLUTION OF THE AMERICAN EXCLUSIONARY RULE<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup>
<p>
At its inception<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> and for many years thereafter, the exclusionary rule in the United States was held to be available to any petitioner who had standing and who had demonstrated a Fourth Amendment violation.<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> Courts applying the rule did not engage in any further balancing, or consider alternative remedies. Initially, the rule was seen as having several purposes,<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup> including deterring unconstitutional state interference with individual rights, remedying the wrong done to the individual<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup> and upholding the integrity of the courts by preventing them from appearing to condone police wrongdoing.<sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup> Over the subsequent years of the rule's development, however, &quot;the individual remedy and judicial integrity concerns tended to vanish from exclusionary rule jurisprudence altogether.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup> By the Burger Court's day, the rule was characterized solely as a means of deterring police misconduct.<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup> This emphasis on the deterrence rationale led the Court to adopt a &quot;good faith&quot; exception to the rule in cases where police had relied on a faulty warrant, since, it was argued, &quot;good faith&quot; errors by police officers could not be deterred, and the rule would not serve to check the actions of judges who issued faulty warrants.<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> Subject to this exception, however, the rule can still be invoked at the behest of the accused who crosses the &quot;threshold&quot; barriers---no other &quot;internal balancing&quot; is involved, and the court cannot substitute another remedy (since the Supreme Court, despite its frequent criticism of the exclusionary rule, has never developed any alternative remedies for a Fourth Amendment violation).
<p>
EXCLUSION OF EVIDENCE IN CANADA UNDER S. 24(2)
<p>
In contrast to the American Bill of Rights, the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite> contains an explicit remedial provision, which includes an express direction that &quot;all the circumstances&quot; must be considered before illegally obtained evidence is excluded. Section 24 declares:
<blockquote>
24. (1) Anyone whose rights or freedoms, as guaranteed by this Charter, have been infringed or denied may apply to a court of competent jurisdiction to obtain such remedy as the court considers appropriate and just in the circumstances.
<p>
(2) Where, in proceedings under subsection (1), a court concludes that evidence was obtained in a manner that infringed or denied any rights or freedoms guaranteed by this Charter, the evidence shall be excluded if it is established that, having regard to all the circumstances, the admission of it in the proceedings would bring the administration of justice into disrepute.
</blockquote>
While s. 24(2) on the one hand eliminates some of the remedial discretion found in s. 24(1) in cases involving
unconstitutionally obtained evidence by instructing judges that they &quot;shall&quot; exclude the evidence if the second part of the test is met, it also orders courts to undertake an analysis of whether, under all the circumstances, the administration of justice would be brought into disrepute if the evidence were admitted. The Supreme Court
considered the content of this second, rather imprecise instruction in <cite>Collins v. The Queen</cite>,<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup> and described the relevant factors that must be considered.<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup>
<p>
The presence of internal &quot;balancing&quot; in s. 24(2) has important consequences when the applicability of the American standing rules to the <cite>Charter</cite> is considered. As noted in the preceding section, the U.S. Supreme Court's reluctance to grant standing appears to have been motivated largely by that Court's opinion that the exclusionary remedy had excessive social costs. It was also suggested that in attempting to rein in the exclusionary
rule by restricting the right, the Court lessened both the self-consistency of the doctrine and its connection with common sense. Even if one takes a kinder view of the Court's actions and does not accept this last claim, it can still be maintained that American-style covert curbing of the exclusionary rule is unnecessary in Canada, where the internal limitations of s. 24(2) allow the balancing of social costs to be done openly and directly. As a rule, Canadian courts have taken the position that the existence of a balancing provision in s. 1 implies that the rights guaranteed under the rest of the <cite>Charter</cite> should be broadly interpreted. Similar considerations apply to s. 24(2)---using arcane standing requirements to limit the use of the exclusionary rule is inadvisable, considering that a better tool for reaching the same result has been included in the <cite>Charter</cite> itself.
<p>
<h3>Target Standing<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup></h3>

As noted earlier, in many third-party search cases both a broadly interpreted but strictly privacy-based approach to standing and an approach that incorporates some variant of &quot;target standing&quot; produce the same results---as the facts of the cases discussed in the previous sections reveal, more often than not the two issues overlap.<sup><a href="#one01">101</a></sup> As argued above, however, the purely privacy-based approach suffers from a number of drawbacks---the vagueness and flexibility of the &quot;privacy&quot; concept lessens its use as a guide, leaving the doctrine open to manipulation and the danger that rules will be adopted that are based on irrational distinctions, serve no justifiable policy goal, and needlessly complicate and confuse the law. Restricting
s. 8 to privacy rights can also be criticized on a more fundamental level as being under-inclusive, ignoring other interests that s. 8 should protect. Although these other interests can often be protected by a liberal interpretation of privacy, it can still be argued that in some cases channelling the analysis through the concept of privacy obscures the underlying purposes of s. 8 and complicates its interaction with s. 24.
<p>
Courts that have denied applicants standing to challenge third-party searches<sup><a href="#one02">102</a></sup> have tended to argue that the effect of granting standing would be to allow someone to claim a remedy for the violation of someone else's rights without having suffered a violation of his or her own personal rights. It is indeed the case that s. 24(1) (and, by extension, s. 24(2)<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup>) provides remedies only to applicants whose own <cite>Charter</cite> rights have been infringed<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup> ---a fact that has been used to deny petitioners standing to object to third-party searches on the grounds that they were attempting to claim a remedy for the rights violation of another. This argument presupposes, however, that the applicant's own rights have not been violated by the search in question, a conclusion usually reached on the basis that the applicant had no privacy interest or proprietary right that was infringed. While it is true that s. 24 cannot be invoked in a truly vicarious manner, characterizing the issue in these cases in this way simply assumes the conclusion---it ignores the possibility that s. 8 might extend beyond the realm of privacy and property and guarantee that an individual be secure from the effects of any governmental
action in violation of the Constitution. If s. 8 were understood in this way, people who are the targets of unreasonable searches of a third party's property or person would be able in some circumstances to claim that their own constitutional rights had been infringed, and that standing to challenge the search flows from this violation.
<p>
Arguments along these lines have been made by several American commentators<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup> in reference to the rights protected by the Fourth Amendment. Doernberg, in particular, has suggested that the Fourth Amendment has two aspects---an &quot;individualist&quot; element that protects privacy interests and a &quot;collective&quot; component that protects the right of society as a whole to be free from illegal governmental action. Drawing on the language of the Fourth Amendment, he writes:
<blockquote>
The two phrases, &quot;the right of the people,&quot; and &quot;to be secure,&quot; should guide those seeking fully to understand the fourth amendment. They imply that the amendment is a broad limitation on government; freedom from unreasonable searches is a constitutionally mandated social state.<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Moreover, he argues, the fact that the current American doctrine interprets the right in a narrowly individualized manner yet considers the exclusionary remedy's only goal to be police deterrence has resulted in &quot;lines of analysis irreconcilable with each other because they lack a consistent, articulable theoretical basis.&quot;<sup><a href="#one07">107</a></sup>
<p>
This echoes the view expressed by Fortas J. in his dissent in <cite>Alderman</cite>, where he wrote:
<blockquote>
The Fourth Amendment is not merely a privilege accorded to him whose domain has been lawlessly invaded. It grants the individual a personal right, not to privacy, but to insist that the state utilize only lawful means of proceeding against him. And it is an assurance that the government will exercise its formidable powers to arrest and to investigate only subject to the rule of law.<sup><a href="#one08">108</a></sup>
</blockquote>
To what extent can a similar argument be made about the <cite>Charter</cite>?  To be sure, the situation in the United States differs in several very important respects from that in Canada. It is often said that American legal and political thought has traditionally been characterized by a greater suspicion of government and a stronger belief in the value of unfettered individual liberty than has been found in this country.<sup><a href="#one09">109</a></sup> To the extent that the original intent of the two nations' constitutions is relevant to their interpretation, it is probably fair to say that the Framers of the Bill of Rights are likely to have placed a greater emphasis on controlling state actions than their more recent Canadian counterparts. Moreover, since Canadian jurisprudence on the exclusionary remedy has largely rejected the American view that it is solely a method of police control, Doernberg's arguments relating to the intellectual coherence of right and remedy may carry less weight
when applied north of the border.
<p>
 Despite these differences, an analysis similar to Doernberg's is supportable in the Canadian context---one which
suggests that s. 8 should be recognized as including a more generalized protection against unconstitutional state searches and seizures that goes beyond a narrow conception of individual privacy. The argument has several strands---textual, purposive, and policy-based---each of which will be discussed in turn.
<P>
THE LANGUAGE OF SECTION 8
<p>
Section 8 of the <cite>Charter</cite> reads, in English and French, as follows:
<blockquote>
8. Everyone has the right to be secure against unreasonable search and seizure.<br>
8. Chacun a droit &agrave; la protection contre les fouilles, les perquisitions ou les saisies abusives.
</blockquote>
The &quot;right to be secure&quot; is not identical to a right to privacy: although &quot;security&quot; in this context undoubtedly includes some aspect of privacy, the concept of security may well extend further. As noted earlier, this possibility was specifically pointed out and left open by the Supreme Court in <cite>Hunter v. Southam</cite>.<sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup> As Lamer J. (as he then was) noted in the <cite>B.C. Motor Vehicles Reference</cite>,<sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup> the security rights contained in s. 8 are specific examples of the right to liberty and security of the person enshrined in s. 7. It is significant, therefore, that in the s. 7 context the right to security of the person has been held to have aspects other than those strictly related to privacy.<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup> In particular, it can be argued that a criminal conviction and consequent loss of liberty pose a threat to one's security. If that conviction is brought about by means of evidence obtained through an unreasonable search, it is arguable that one's security interests are infringed in a manner captured by s. 8.
<p>
Further guidance regarding the meaning of s. 8 can be found by examining the choice of words in the French-language version of the section, and, in particular, the choice of the word <i>abusif</i> to qualify the power to search. According to the French language dictionary <cite>Micro Robert</cite>, the word <i>abusif</i> and the
related term <i>abus</i> are defined as follows: 
<blockquote>
<i>abusif:</i> qui constitue un abus.<br>
<i>abus:</i> usage excessif ou unjuste.
</blockquote>
The meaning of <i>abusif</i> is thus closer to that of the English `abusive' than to `unreasonable' (which is better
approximated in French by <i>d&eacute;raisonnable</i>). The deliberate choice of this wording therefore suggests a recognition by the drafters of s. 8 that the underlying purpose of the right was the prevention of abuses of state power. An unconstitutional police search of one person intended to side-step constitutional limitations and incriminate a third party could well be the sort of abusive action the drafters had in mind.
<p>
PURPOSIVE APPROACH
<p>
As Dickson J. (as he then was) noted in <cite>Hunter v. Southam</cite>, &quot;The <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite> is a purposive document,&quot;<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup> and must be interpreted with the underlying purposes in mind. In considering the question of standing, it is necessary to consider the purpose both of the right guaranteed in s. 8 and of the exclusionary remedy provided in s. 24. If, as suggested above, one purpose of either the right or the remedy is to protect against or control government abuses of a more general nature than immediate invasions of individual privacy, a narrow standing rule would run counter to this purpose and would not be consonant with the governing interpretive principle of the <cite>Charter</cite>. Consequently, it is necessary to examine and consider the aim of each section. 
<p>
<i>Section 8</i><br>
It was argued in the previous section that the language of s. 8 suggests that its purpose includes a generalized protection of individuals from abusive governmental searches that extends beyond the concept of privacy (although, as pointed out previously, the two concepts often overlap in a given case). This interpretation, however, flows not only from the words of the section, but can be inferred from the underlying principles of the <cite>Charter</cite> as a whole.
<p>
Why do we as a society prohibit unreasonable searches and seizures?  We do so not because the detrimental impact of such a search on the affected individuals in every instance outweighs the immediate societal benefits the search would bring---this is clearly not the case. Rather, we do so because as a society we reject such a narrow utilitarian calculus---our socio-political system is founded on the belief that individuals should not be sacrificed at will in the name of the common good. While our faith in this position is very largely due to conceptions of natural rights and justice, it also has what could be described as a broad utilitarian basis---a conviction that in the long run a commitment to individual autonomy will provide a better life for us all, and a belief that any short-term gains that
violations of this principle might seem to produce would prove in the end to be illusory. 
<p>
At the same time, we are forced to recognize that letting individual liberty run absolutely unchecked would lead to chaos, and to admit that some social controls are necessary. We fear the consequences of uncontrolled state power, however, and consequently insist that strict and clearly marked limits must be imposed on what the state can do. These limits are exemplified by the <cite>Charter</cite>---a document that delineates boundaries that (at least in principle) the state is only entitled to cross when to do so is absolutely necessary (&quot;demonstrably justified,&quot; in the language of s. 1). Yet the <cite>Charter</cite> also serves a more subtle function that goes beyond simple regulation. As a collection and articulation of our basic principles, it acts as a means by which we as a society remind ourselves of our values---tolerance, liberty, and respect for others---and provides us with a vision of who we like to think we are, reproaching us when we fail to live up to our own ideals.
<p>
This suggests that third-party searches cause harm in two ways. There is harm not only to the individual who is directly affected; in addition, our vision of ourselves as a society is damaged by the fact that the state, the agent of our collective will, has treated an individual as a mere object without rights. While this harms society as a whole, it injures in particular that individual who was the target of the state's abuse of its powers, who bears the brunt of the consequences of the state's wrongful act. While in some cases we may be willing to accept that such acts are necessary or justified, the <cite>Charter</cite> tells us that such justification is to be accomplished under s. 1 or s. 24(2) before the court---the agent of our collective conscience---in order both to control such abuses of individual rights by bringing them into the open, and to ensure that we recognize that even if in the end society considers the infringements justified, a line has been crossed, and our principles have been disturbed.
<p>
Adopting a narrow standing rule fails to recognize the full extent of the harm that a third-party search causes. By limiting the conception of the s. 8 right to encompass only the first individual in the chain of those affected by an unreasonable search, both the social harm and the harm to other individuals are ignored. Such an approach disregards a crucial element of the reason we think unreasonable searches are wrong and merit constitutional protection in the first place.
<p>
In addition, since the courts, as guardians of our rights, rely on interested parties to bring wrongful acts of the state to their notice, there is the pragmatic problem that a narrow standing rule prevents the courts from considering incidents of government malfeasance or carelessness that harms individuals and should properly be placed before them. Relying on the most immediately aggrieved party to always bring suit is unrealistic---in some situations he or she will not necessarily be the person with the greatest interest in pursuing the claim and will not press it to its  fullest. In the context of constitutional challenges to legislation, the Supreme Court of Canada has recognized the pitfalls of excessively narrow standing rules and has allowed persons who were not necessarily the most directly affected by the impugned legislation to bring suits attacking its validity if there appeared to be no other way the issue would be brought before the court.<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup> Similar considerations should arguably apply when what is attacked is state action rather than state legislation, such as cases where the actual target of an unreasonable search and seizure is a third party.
<p>
While the Supreme Court has remained carefully noncommittal on the question of third-party standing in search and seizure cases in most of its judgments to date, there are a few signs indicating that it accepts the principles underlying a broad standing rule. In <cite>R. v. Thompson</cite>,<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup> the Court gave what may prove to be an important signal of its intentions in this regard. The case involved a wiretap authorization which allowed the police to tap telephones both at the appellants' residence and at any other place they might &quot;resort to.&quot;  The police used this authorization to eavesdrop on several public pay telephones that were often used by the appellants but were also used by other members of the public. The police had reasonable grounds to suspect the appellants of wrongdoing, and were thus legitimately authorized to intrude on the appellants' privacy interests. Nonetheless, the appellants argued that the failure of the authorizing judge to limit the intrusion on
third-party users of the pay phones rendered the search unreasonable, an argument which was rejected by the B.C. Court of Appeal on the grounds that the appellants lacked standing to raise allegations of violations of third-party privacy rights.
<p>
The Supreme Court, however, accepted the argument and held not only that the appellants had standing, but determined in addition that s. 8 had been violated. Sopinka J., writing for the Court, stated:
<blockquote>
In my view, the extent of invasion into the privacy of these third parties is constitutionally relevant to the issue of
whether there has been an &quot;unreasonable&quot; search and seizure. To hold otherwise would be to ignore the purpose of s. 8 of the Charter which is to restrain invasion of privacy to within reasonable limits. A potentially massive invasion of privacy cannot be ignored simply because it is not brought to the attention of the court by one of these persons. Since these persons are unlikely to know of the invasion of their privacy, such invasions would escape scrutiny, and s. 8 would not fulfill its purpose.<sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup>
</blockquote>
By recognizing that the purpose of s. 8 is the restraint of invasion of privacy in general, rather than simply the invasion of privacy of the individual bringing the claim, the Court appears to have acknowledged the existence of a broader generalized intent of s. 8 to regulate government action. In addition, the Court seems to accept the position that third parties who bear the brunt of unreasonable government actions are best suited to bring these actions to the Court's attention, even though their privacy interests may not be directly affected.
<p>
The issue confronted by the Court in <cite>Thompson</cite> is somewhat different from the typical third-party standing cases considered earlier, in that the appellants' own privacy interests had clearly been infringed.<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup> However, the infringement of <i>their</i> privacy interests was reasonable, and consequently did not violate the <cite>Charter</cite>---rather, the s. 8 infringement arose from the violation of the privacy of the third parties. If the violation of third-party privacy interests is the key to the constitutionality of the search, it is illogical to base the determination of standing on whether or not the appellants' own privacy interests have been infringed, since once standing is granted this factor becomes irrelevant to the determination of the issue. It thus can be argued that the logic of <cite>Thompson</cite> dictates that the targets of unreasonable searches be entitled to raise the issue of unreasonableness without proving that a violation of their personal privacy interest took place.
<p>
Further support for this position can be drawn from the Supreme Court's decision in <cite>R. v. Big M Drug Mart
Ltd.</cite><sup><a href="#one18">118</a></sup> In that case, the Court held that anyone charged with a criminal offence had standing to challenge the constitutionality of the law under which they were charged even if their own rights had not been violated.<sup><a href="#one19">119</a></sup> In this way, the Court recognized that s. 52 of the <cite>Charter</cite> gives the judiciary a broad mandate to regulate the actions of the legislature. Although s. 52 deals only with the constitutionality of legislation and not with the constitutionality of non-legislative state action, the same regulatory function would seem equally appropriate in circumstances involving unconstitutional state actions carried out in the absence of or contrary to legislation. State action not authorized by law is even more likely to be abusive and in violation of constitutional norms than action that has at least passed the scrutiny of Parliament---a fact recognized by s. 1, which states that an infringement of a protected right or liberty can only be
justified if it is &quot;prescribed by law.&quot;  According to <cite>Big M</cite>, the courts have a mandate to regulate unconstitutional legislation without having their hands tied by narrow standing rules. It would be inconsistent with this approach and with the principle of the supremacy of the <cite>Charter</cite> to turn around and impose narrow and restrictive standing rules when what is impugned is the state's acts rather than its laws.
<p>
A comparison of the <cite>Big M</cite> standing rule to the equivalent American doctrine is revealing. In contrast to the <cite>Big M</cite> approach, courts in the United States have held that as a general rule applicants must demonstrate a violation of their own constitutional rights before they can claim standing to challenge the constitutionality of legislation. The U.S. Supreme Court has stated that:
<blockquote>
Embedded in the traditional rules governing constitutional adjudication is the principle that a person to whom a
statute may constitutionally be applied will not be heard to challenge that statute on the ground that it may conceivably be applied unconstitutionally to others, in other situations not before the Court. . . . [This principle reflects] the conviction that under our constitutional system courts are not roving commissions assigned to pass judgment on the validity of the nation's laws.<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The fact that the Supreme Court of Canada has not followed the American route and has instead taken the opposite course suggests that there is a general difference between the American and Canadian systems with respect to all issues of standing relating to constitutional challenges.<sup><a href="#one21">121</a></sup> If this is the case,
there is no reason why Canadian judges should blindly follow the American standing rules on issues such as third-party searches that involve state action---on the contrary, a different approach may in fact be more in keeping with our basic constitutional principles.
<p>
In <cite>R. v. Montoute</cite><sup><a href="#one22">122</a></sup> the Alberta Court of Appeal took what may be a step toward the introduction of a broad third-party standing rule in Canadian law. During the course of the investigation of an alleged conspiracy to traffic in narcotics, a wiretap was placed without prior judicial  authorization on the telephone of one of the accused's co-conspirators. The issue the court faced was whether the accused (who was not a party to the conversations that were recorded) had standing to challenge the admissibility of these taped conversations at his trial (if there was no s. 8 violation, the evidence would be admissible under the conspiratorial exception to the hearsay rule<sup><a href="#one23">123</a></sup>). Harradence J.A., writing for the majority on this point, declared that:
<blockquote>
An interpretation of the Charter that precludes an accused . . . from moving under s. 24(2) to exclude that evidence would not be in keeping with the approach laid down by Dickson C.J.C. in <cite>Hunter v. Southam</cite>.<sup><a href="#one24">124</a></sup>
</blockquote>
He continued by commenting that:
<blockquote>
If a co-conspirator's Charter rights have been breached in obtaining his declaration furthering the conspiratorial objectives to the extent that its admission would bring the administration of justice into disrepute, it would drag the
administration of justice even further and deeper into the mire of disrepute to give &quot;judicial condonation to unacceptable conduct by investigatory agencies&quot; by the admission of that evidence on the pretext that s. 24(2) was not available to a co-conspirator as his Charter rights had not been breached. This would be a classic example of relying on a legal fiction [the conspiratorial exception to the hearsay rule] to incriminate an accused and then resorting to the &quot;austerity of tabulated legalism&quot; to deny a Charter remedy. . . . To deny a co-conspirator a Charter remedy [in this instance] would be &quot;the use of the sword without the scales&quot; and a clear example of the use of &quot;brute force&quot; to obtain a conviction.<sup><a href="#one25">125</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Many of Harradence J.A.'s comments regarding the repute of the administration of justice can be interpreted as being equally applicable in cases involving the seizure of real evidence from a third party, and it may well be that the Court intended them to be interpreted in this way. While it is also possible to read the opinion as only intending that standing be given to the targets of third-party searches in cases where the Crown attempts to take advantage of the so-called &quot;legal fiction&quot; of the conspiratorial hearsay rule exception,<sup><a href="#one26">126</a></sup> it is hard to see why this latter factor should play such an important role in deciding the issue. The former interpretation thus appears to be the more plausible one, at least from the point of view of
principle.<sup><a href="#one27">127</a></sup>
<p>
Section 24(2)<br>
Some further support for the argument that the <cite>Charter</cite> protects individuals from wrongful government actions that effect security interests beyond an immediate privacy interest can be found in the terms of the remedy provided by s. 24(2). The key provisions of s. 24(2) are the declarations that unconstitutionally obtained evidence <i>shall</i> be excluded <i>if</i> the admission of it could<sup><a href="#one28">128</a></sup> bring the
administration of justice into disrepute. As the Supreme Court has pointed out time and again, in its view the intent of s. 24(2) is not to provide automatic exclusion of all unconstitutionally obtained evidence, and its central purpose is not to deter police wrongdoing. Nonetheless, it has become clear that the behaviour of the police can be highly relevant to the question of whether admission of evidence would harm the reputation of the administration of justice. If the violation of the individual right is &quot;flagrant and serious&quot; or if the conduct of the police indicates a wilful disregard of the <cite>Charter</cite>, the Court has declared<sup><a href="#one29">129</a></sup> that the administration of justice would be brought into disrepute if the court &quot;did not exclude [the] evidence and dissociate itself from the conduct of the police.&quot;<sup><a href="#one30">130</a></sup>
<p>
This position was reiterated by Dickson C.J.C. in <cite>R. v. Genest</cite>,<sup><a href="#one31">131</a></sup> a case in which the police had searched a house with excessive force under the guise of a clearly defective warrant (described by the Chief Justice as &quot;a fishing licence, not a search warrant&quot;<sup><a href="#one32">132</a></sup>). He declared:
<blockquote>
While the purpose of s. 24(2) is not to deter police misconduct, the courts should be reluctant to admit evidence that
shows the signs of being obtained by an abuse of common law and Charter rights by the police.<sup><a href="#one33">133</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Similarly, in <cite>R. v. Duguay</cite><sup><a href="#one34">134</a></sup> a six-to-one majority of the Court approved<sup><a href="#one35">135</a></sup> of the principles enunciated in the Ontario Court of Appeal by
MacKinnon A.C.J.O., who had declared:
<blockquote>
If the court should turn a blind eye to [police misconduct], then the police may assume that they have the court's
tacit approval of it. I do not view the exclusion of evidence as a punishment of the police for their conduct, although it is to be hoped that it will act as a future deterrent. It is rather an affirmation of fundamental values in our society, and the only means [in the case at hand] of ensuring that the individual's Charter rights are not illusory.<sup><a href="#one36">136</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In short, s. 24(2) has several functions, one of which is to allow the courts to denounce and disapprove of unconscionable police behaviour by refusing to be a party to the admission of evidence obtained in blatant disregard of <cite>Charter</cite> values. This principle, however, is just as applicable to cases where the evidence is being used against someone other than the person searched as it is to cases where the immediate victim of the search and the accused are one and the same individual. In both cases, the admission of the evidence could be seen as a condonation by the courts of flagrantly unconstitutional and illegal government acts, and the administration of justice could as a consequence be brought into disrepute. A narrow standing rule, however, prevents the courts
from even beginning to examine the issue of police conduct in all third-party search cases, since such a rule ensures that the accused will never be allowed to bring the matter to the attention of the court. Thus, a narrow standing rule would effectively thwart one of the underlying purposes of s. 24(2), while a broader rule that does not eliminate claimants at such an early stage of the proceedings would allow the merits of their claims to be fully examined. The
latter approach, therefore, seems more consonant with s. 24(2) which, after all, states that courts are to examine &quot;all the circumstances&quot; relating to an unconstitutional search.
<p>
DETERRENCE AND SECTION 24(2)
<p>
Underlying the issue of standing is the more fundamental and even more difficult question of the merits and rationales of the exclusionary rule. As mentioned earlier, in the United States the narrowing of Fourth Amendment standing rules can be seen as an attempt by the Supreme Court to curb what it considers the exclusionary rule's excesses. At the same time, the rule itself is justified by the Court entirely in terms of its deterrent effect on police misconduct. As Doernberg points out, this incoherence between right and remedy has produced an inconsistent and at times nonsensical body of jurisprudence.
<p>
In Canada, a different approach has been taken to the remedial side of search and seizure law---the application of the exclusionary remedy has been limited, and its purpose has largely been characterized as the protection of the integrity of the justice system rather than the deterrence of future police wrongdoing. In light of this aspect of Canadian constitutional structure the narrow U.S. standing rules appear to be unnecessary and inconsistent with
the purposes of the <cite>Charter</cite>. In addition, the more expansive conception of the right protected by s. 8 that goes hand-in-hand with a broad approach to standing would have an additional (and arguably beneficial) effect: it will provide a theoretical basis and rationale for the incorporation of some deterrence considerations into the s. 24(2) remedy---considerations that, it is suggested, have been unduly ignored.
<p>
Canadian search and seizure law suffers from an ailment that is in some respects the converse of the one Doernberg diagnoses as afflicting Fourth Amendment doctrine in the United States. In the U.S., the inconsistency between the narrowly individualistic right and the strictly deterrent-based remedy has created incoherence as the right has been cut down further and further by the Court's attempt to avoid the consequences of the remedy. In Canada, on the other hand, courts have at least to some extent recognized the broader dimensions of the right, but have not incorporated all its implications into the remedy, by ignoring or rejecting out of hand the concept of deterrence of police misconduct as one of the rationales underlying s. 24(2).
<p>
The recognition that there is a societal interest in the government behaving lawfully that underlies a broad approach to the standing question also supports a deterrent rationale for the exclusionary rule by clarifying the harm to society caused by illegal searches and seizures. If the right is seen purely in terms of individual privacy interests, using the exclusionary rule as a deterrent is difficult to justify, since the deterrent effect is unlikely to benefit that particular accused in the future.<sup><a href="#one37">137</a></sup> If, on the other hand, the right is seen as having as a component a more general interest in government lawfulness, deterrence makes more sense---society as a whole, which has suffered as a consequence of official wrongdoing, benefits if patterns of wrongdoing are eliminated.
<p>
Moreover, by focusing attention on the effects a rights violation has on society's interest in the rule of law, this approach emphasizes the true meaning and extent of the term &quot;administration of justice&quot; in s. 24(2). The repute of the administration of justice is a function not only of societal opinion of the courts as institutions; it depends in addition on how society views the police, the prisons, and all the other constituent parts that
together make up the justice system. In considering the repute of the administration of justice in s. 24(2) analysis, Canadian courts have tended to focus their attention almost exclusively on the repute of the judiciary, ignoring the fact that there are other equally important aspects to the reputation of the justice system as a whole.<sup><a href="#one38">138</a></sup> While courts have recognized that judicial condonation of police misconduct will harm the system's repute, they have failed to acknowledge overtly the fact that widespread police misconduct <i>itself</i> lowers the public's perception of the administration of justice. 
<p>
It can be argued that deterrence considerations have in practice played a larger role in courts' s. 24(2) decisions than
they have been willing to admit. The fact that the remedy in s. 24(2) is the exclusion of evidence in itself provides some indication of this---if denunciation of police wrongdoing were all that was required, courts could in at least some cases rely solely on declarations that the police had misbehaved, a remedy that courts in other contexts have considered to be a sufficient spur to correct constitutional violations.<sup><a href="#one39">139</a></sup> The
exclusionary rule, in contrast, recognizes the underlying incentives that the police have to cut corners and infringe rights, and realizes that to eliminate or at least control these excesses a remedy with some teeth is required. Canadian courts have acknowledged that the exclusionary rule has deterrent effects, but have tended to treat these effects as simply incidental to the denunciatory function.<sup><a href="#one40">140</a></sup> This less-than-complete understanding of the nature of the remedy has arguably hampered the clarity and coherence of judicial analysis.
<p>
The deterrent effect of the exclusion of evidence on police misconduct has been attacked by some, most notably former U.S. Chief Justice Burger,<sup><a href="#one41">141</a></sup> as illusory. In his view, a key flaw in the deterrence argument is that &quot;[t]he suppression doctrine vaguely assumes that law enforcement is a monolithic government enterprise&quot;<sup><a href="#one42">142</a></sup> when in fact it is not---individual officers have very little stake in or knowledge of the final outcome of particular cases, and thus are not deterred by the sanction of excluding evidence at trial. While this argument has some merit, it misconceives in several important ways the argument in favour of the exclusionary rule. First, the term &quot;deterrence&quot; is in some ways a misnomer for what the exclusionary rule does---it conjures up a vision of control based on punishment, operating like the criminal law. As a stick for chastising errant police officers, the exclusionary rule indeed falls short, since, as Burger C.J. points out, individual officers stand to lose very little personally by its operation. However, the
exclusionary rule is actually more concerned with removing incentives than with creating this type of &quot;deterrent&quot; effect---it relies more on eliminating carrots than on creating sticks. Seen in this way, the rule is much more sensible. After all, the police conduct searches and seizures for the purpose of making arrests and, in the long run, getting convictions. If they know that the outcome of a flagrant breach of the Constitution will be that their work is for naught, they will be less likely to engage in such breaches---even if they have no fear of personal sanction, police officers are not likely to want to waste their time.
<p>
While the precise benefits of the exclusionary rule may be difficult to quantify, this does not mean that they are nonexistent. In other areas, such as the right to counsel, it is indisputable that judicial pronouncements have had a genuine impact on police behaviour.<sup><a href="#one43">143</a></sup> Had the Court's statements on these matters not been backed up by the threat of the exclusionary rule, it is unlikely that the police would have adapted
to meet the minimum constitutional standard as quickly as they did.
<p>
Considering that Canadian courts have recognized that the exclusionary rule has a deterrent effect,<sup><a href="#one44">144</a></sup> the courts' refusal to explicitly consider the effect when deciding whether to apply the exclusionary rule is in some ways peculiar---if the deterrent effect is indeed significant, it should surely be a relevant factor in determining the applicability of the s. 24(2) remedy in a given case. In many decided cases, it is likely that deterrence of state misbehaviour actually has played a role in judges' decisions, but has been hidden behind discussions of &quot;the integrity of the justice system.&quot; Although deterrence and judicial integrity are often overlapping concerns, it can be argued that the clarity and consistency of the justice system are promoted by minimizing the use of covert tools as often as possible. If this is the case, bringing deterrence out in the open as an aspect of the s. 24(2) remedy should be seen as a positive development, even if one believes that it should not be
elevated to the pre-eminent position it occupies in U.S. doctrine.
<p>As noted earlier, a deterrent rationale for the exclusionary rule fits uncomfortably with a narrowly individualistic
conception of s. 8, but is consistent with a view of s. 8 that includes a broader societal interest in preventing state
misbehaviour (which Doernberg characterizes as a &quot;collective component&quot;<sup><a href="#one45">145</a></sup> of the right). As it was argued earlier that the inclusion of this latter understanding in s. 8 would assist in the full realization of the purpose of the right, it can also be argued that it would help create a theoretical foundation for the full realization of the s. 24(2) remedy.
<p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>

Due to the relatively short time the <cite>Charter</cite> has existed, the full content of many of its protections has yet to be illuminated by the courts, and the rather arcane issue of third-party standing to challenge searches and seizures may remain a dark and unexplored corner of ss 8 and 24(2) for some time to come. Nevertheless, when the time arrives for the Supreme Court to consider the matter, it is to be hoped that the Court will learn from the U.S. experience and will refrain from blindly repeating American mistakes. While the Court has dropped some hints that it is prepared to chart its own course on the issue, what it will do when the issue is placed squarely before it remains to be seen.
<p>
As this article has suggested, the question of third-party standing is one that naturally involves deeper issues concerning the nature and purpose of the <cite>Charter</cite>'s rights and remedies. Resolving the third-party standing question by adopting a broad standing rule could thus provide the Court with an opportunity to articulate a broader and arguably better understanding of the nature of s. 8 rights and their associated remedy---one that includes a recognition of the protection they provide to society in general and to the rule of law. By doing so, the Court would place both right and remedy on a firmer basis, strengthening and clarifying the relationship between them. Seen in this way, the issue of third-party standing appears as more than just a minor technical problem in search and seizure law. As the American experience illustrates, building theoretical coherence into the law is more than merely an idle concern of legal academics---rather, the price that incoherent doctrine eventually extracts is paid in the form of inconsistent and ultimately irrational results, which harm both the justice system and society as a whole.
<p><br>
<hr>
<p>
<center><h2>Endnotes</h2></center>
<ol>
<li><a name="one"><cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite></a>, Part I of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1982</cite>, being Schedule B of the <cite>Canada Act 1982</cite> (U.K.), 1982, c. 11 [hereinafter <cite>Charter</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name="two">Section 8 states:</a> &quot;Everyone has the right to be secure against unreasonable search and seizure.&quot;
<p>
<li><a name="three">Section 24 states:</a>
<blockquote>
24.  (1) Anyone whose rights or freedoms, as guaranteed by this Charter, have been infringed or denied may apply to a court of competent jurisdiction to obtain such remedy as the court considers appropriate and just in the circumstances.
<p>
<dd>(2) Where, in proceedings under subsection (1), a court concludes that evidence was obtained in a manner that infringed or denied any rights or freedoms guaranteed by this Charter, the evidence shall be excluded if it is established that, having regard to all the circumstances, the admission of it in the proceedings would bring the administration of justice into disrepute.
</blockquote>
<li><a name="four">The use of the term</a> &quot;standing&quot; in American and some Canadian search and seizure cases can be a source of considerable confusion. As the term implies, questions of standing involve the determination of whether or not a particular person is entitled to challenge the constitutionality of a search or seizure. This problem, however, can be broken down into two subsidiary questions:
<blockquote>
1.  Did the impugned state action violate the individual claimant's constitutional rights?
<p>
2. If the petitioner's own individual rights were not violated, can he or she nonetheless claim a remedy (such as the
exclusion of evidence) on the basis that the search violated the rights of a third party?
</blockquote>
As the term is used in other areas of constitutional law, only those cases falling under the second branch raise the question of standing---as Gibson and Gibson point out, cases under the first branch &quot;are not properly questions of standing at all: they are substantive questions of scope that every accused person should have the standing to raise in his or her defence&quot; (D. Gibson &amp; S. Gibson, &quot;Enforcement of the Canadian
Charter of Rights and Freedoms (Section 24),&quot; in G.A. Beaudoin &amp; E. Ratushny, eds., <cite>The Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>, 2nd ed. (Toronto: Carswell, 1989) 781 at 789). In the United States, however, courts have tended to classify all cases where a clear violation of a third party's rights took place as
&quot;standing&quot; cases, regardless of whether the petitioner was claiming that his or her own rights were also violated or was merely asserting a vicarious claim based on what had happened to the third party. This classification practice has continued, notwithstanding the fact that American courts have invariably rejected the idea that a truly
vicarious claim could ever be successful. As a result, cases that turn on essentially the same issue---for example, whether the claimant had a reasonable expectation of privacy in the place searched---are classified differently by American courts depending on whether or not the protected interest of a third party was also violated, even though the courts' analysis otherwise disregards the infringement of the third party's rights. For example, in <cite>Katz v. United States</cite>, 389 U.S. 347 (1967) (discussed <i>infra</i>) the issue was whether the petitioner had a reasonable expectation of privacy while in a public telephone booth, while <cite>Rawlings v. Kentucky</cite>, 448 U.S. 98 (1980) (also discussed <i>infra</i>) turned on whether the accused had a reasonable expectation of privacy in relation to goods stored in a friend's purse. <cite>Rawlings</cite>, however, is discussed in terms of standing while <cite>Katz</cite> is not, apparently because the search in <cite>Rawlings</cite> also violated the rights of the purse's owner. Although the U.S. Supreme Court has questioned whether this rather confusing division of the case law &quot;serves any useful analytical purpose&quot; (<cite>Rakas v. Illinois</cite>, 439 U.S. 128 at 138 (1979)), the Court has continued to use the distinction. Influenced by their American counterparts, a number of Canadian courts have also invoked the language of standing when referring to what were in essence substantive questions about the nature of the right in s. 8. For convenience this article will use the terminology of &quot;standing&quot; in the sense that it is used by the courts, despite its technical inaccuracy.
<p>
<li><a name="five">The Fourth Amendment of the United States Constitution states:</a>
<center>Amendment IV</center>
The right of the people to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects, against unreasonable searches and seizures, shall not be violated, and no Warrants shall issue, but upon probable cause, supported by Oath or  affirmation, and particularly describing the place to be searched or things to be seized.
<p>
<li><a name="six">R. Dworkin,</a> &quot;Fact Style Adjudication and the Fourth Amendment: The Limits of Lawyering&quot; (1973) 48 Ind. L.J. 329 at 329.
<p>
<li><a name="seven">D.L. Doernberg,</a> &quot;`The Right of the People': Reconciling Collective and Individual Interests Under the Fourth Amendment&quot; (1983) 58 N.Y.U.L.Rev. 259 at 259.
<p>
<li><a name="eight"><i>Ibid.</i> at 283.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="nine"><i>Ibid.</i> at 260.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="ten">The history and development</a> of Fourth Amendment doctrine in the United States has been the subject of innumerable academic articles and texts; for a comprehensive treatment, see W.R. LaFave, <cite>Search and Seizure: A Treatise on the Fourth Amendment</cite>, vol. 4 (St. Paul, Minnesota: West, 1987). See also <i>supra</i> note 4 for a discussion of the use of the term &quot;standing&quot; in search and seizure law.
<p>
<li><a name="eleven">In <cite>Weeks v. United States</cite>,</a> 232 U.S. 383 (1914) [hereinafter cite>Weeks</cite>].
<p>
<li><a name="twelve">See <cite>Jones v. United States</cite>,</a> 362 U.S. 257 at 261 (1960) [hereinafter <cite>Jones</cite>]. See also I. Mickenberg, &quot;Fourth Amendment Standing After <cite>Rakas v. Illinois</cite>: From Property to Privacy and Back&quot; (1981) 16 New Eng. L. Rev. 197 for a discussion of the lower courts' holdings.
<p>
<li><a name="thirteen"><cite>Jones</cite>, <i>ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a name="fourteen"><i>Ibid.</i> at 266 (Frankfurter J.).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="fifteen"><i>Ibid.</i> at 267.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="sixteen"><i>Ibid.</i> at 263.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventeen"><i>Ibid.</i> at 264.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="eighteen">See LaFave, <i>supra</i> note 10 at 346--351.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="nineteen">389 U.S. 347 (1967) [hereinafter <cite>Katz</cite>].</a>
<p>
<li><a name="twenty"><i>Ibid.</i> at 351.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="twenty1"><i>Ibid.</i> at 361.</a>
<p>
