<p>
<li><a name="ninety9">In</a> <cite>Collins</cite>, <i>ibid.</i> at 18ff Lamer J. listed some of the factors he considered relevant, including:
<ul>
<li>what kind of evidence was obtained?
<li>what <cite>Charter</cite> right was violated?
<li>was the <cite>Charter</cite> violation serious or was it of a merely technical nature?
<li>was it deliberate, wilful or flagrant, or was it inadvertent and committed in good faith?
<li>did it occur in circumstances of urgency or necessity?
<li>were there other investigatory techniques available?
<li>would the evidence have been obtained in any event?
<li>is the offence serious?
<li>is the evidence essential to substantiate the charge?
<li>are other remedies available?
</ul>
As subsequent decisions have confirmed (see, for example, <cite>R. v. Wise</cite> (1992), 70 C.C.C. (3d) 193 (S.C.C.)), these factors are to be examined in light of three principles:
<blockquote>
1.  the effect of admission on the fairness of the trial process;<br>
2.  the seriousness of the violation; and<br>
3.  the effect of exclusion on the reputation of the administration of justice.
</blockquote>
<li><a name="onehundred">Note that in the United States,</a> where a range of different third-party standing rules apply under the various state constitutions, a number of subtle distinctions are drawn between various alternatives. In particular, the term &quot;target standing&quot; has often been used to refer to a rule whereby someone who was intended by the police to be the target at the time of the search has standing, but someone against whom evidence was discovered merely by accident does not. See LaFave, <i>supra</i> note 10 at 351. Such subtle differences are beyond the scope of this article, and for convenience the term &quot;target standing&quot; will be used in what follows to refer generically to <i>any</i> rule in which the person against whom seized evidence is tendered has standing to challenge the constitutionality of the search.
<p>
<li><a name="one01">That is,</a> the petitioner will be able to argue both that he or she had a privacy interest in the place searched and that the illegal police action had been directed at the petitioner.
<p>
<li><a name="one02">An example</a> is the Ontario Court of Appeal in <cite>Pugliese</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 65.
