<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 52 No. 1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#0000ff" vlink="#4040ad">
<CENTER>[<A HREF="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</A>] [<A HREF="v52n1.htm">Volume 52 Number 1</A>]</CENTER>
<P><BR>
<H1>Pornography, Harm, and Censorship: A Feminist (Re)Vision of the Right to Freedom of Expression<a href="#note">*</a>
<p>
BETTINA QUISTGAARD</H1>
<P>
<i>In </i>R. v. Butler<i>, the Supreme Court of Canada held that while the anti-obscenity provisions in the</i> Criminal Code<i> constitute a limitation of the right to freedom of expression guaranteed in s. 2(b) of the </i>Charter of Rights and Freedoms<i>, the limitation can be justified on the basis of the harm that pornography causes to women. Because the court based its judgment on the traditional liberal understanding of the purposes of
freedom of expression, however, it misconceived the nature of the harm caused by pornography, searching unsuccessfully, for example, for causal links between pornography and violence towards women. Some feminist theorists also approach pornography in this way, and argue that censorship is the &quot;solution&quot; to the harm caused by pornography. The author argues, however, that such an analysis leads to a misguided opposition between feminism and freedom of expression and implicates feminism in an understanding of freedom of expression that itself contains the same patriarchal values that inform traditional liberalism. The author then shows that feminist and poststructuralist theories of language yield a richer analysis of pornography which focuses on its constitutive role in creating the discourse within which women and their sexuality come to be understood within society. From this perspective, it is possible to move beyond the traditional emphasis on censorship as the antidote to pornography, and to develop a positive conception of the right to free expression that would enable women to create alternative understandings of their experience, which can be counterposed to the traditional patriarchal discourse that pornography exemplifies.
<p>
Dans le jugement de </i>R. c. Butler<i>, la Cour supr&ecirc;me du Canada a d&eacute;cid&eacute; que, m&ecirc;me si les articles du </i>Code criminel<i> portant sur l'obsc&eacute;nit&eacute; vont &agrave; l'encontre
du droit &agrave; la libert&eacute; d'expression garanti par l'article 2(b) de la </i>Charte canadienne des droits et libert&eacute;s<i>, cette violation peut &ecirc;tre justifi&eacute;e par le tort que la pornographie cause aux femmes. Etant donn&eacute; que la Cour a fond&eacute; son jugement sur une conception traditionellement lib&eacute;rale des objectifs du droit &agrave; la libert&eacute; d'expression, la Cour n'a pas compris la nature du tort caus&eacute; par la pornographie, en cherchant sans succ&egrave;s, par example, des liens de causalit&eacute; entre la pornographie et la violence contre les femmes. Plusieurs f&eacute;ministes s'attaquent &agrave; la pornographie de cette fa&ccedil;on; elles disent que la censure est la &quot;solution&quot; au tort caus&eacute; par la pornographie. Pour sa part, l'auteur pr&eacute;tend que ce type d'analyse m&egrave;ne &agrave; une confrontation inopportune entre le f&eacute;minisme et la libert&eacute; d'expression, et qu'elle implique le f&eacute;minisme dans une conception de la libert&eacute; d'expression qui d&eacute;double les valeurs patriarcales du lib&eacute;ralisme traditionel. Ensuite, l'auteur d&eacute;montre que les th&eacute;ories f&eacute;ministes et poststructuralistes sur le langage offre une analyse plus approfondie de la pornographie qui s'attarde au r&ocirc;le que la pornographie joue dans la cr&eacute;ation du discours &agrave; l'int&eacute;rieur duquel les femmes et leur sexualit&eacute; sont comprises dans notre soci&eacute;t&eacute;. A partir de ces th&eacute;ories, il devient possible d'aller au del&agrave; de l'id&eacute;e traditionelle qu'il faut censurer la pornographie pour la contrer, et il devient possible de d&eacute;velopper une conception positive du droit
&agrave; la libert&eacute; d'expression qui permettrait aux femmes de cr&eacute;er d'autres fa&ccedil;ons de comprendre leurs exp&eacute;riences, qui pourraient venir &agrave; l'encontre des discours patriarcaux traditionels dont la pornographie est une example.</i>
<p><br>
In <cite>R. v. Butler</cite>,<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> the Supreme Court of Canada struggled to reconcile the issue of pornography with its own doctrinal interpretation of the right to freedom of expression as guaranteed in s. 2(b) of the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>.<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> The difficulties encountered---particularly in finding a &quot;causal&quot; relationship
between pornography and &quot;harm&quot; to women as a group---can be explained in large part by the continuing influence of liberal philosophy on the contemporary judicial understanding of freedom of expression, and the resulting failure to comprehend the enigmatic and indeterminate nature of the pornographic message. Liberal philosophy has been incorporated into the Supreme Court's definition of the right to freedom of expression through the adoption of the traditional liberal &quot;purposes&quot; for protecting expression. In turn, these purposes stem from particular assumptions about human beings (or, more aptly, &quot;man&quot;), society, and language, and how these concepts are related to one another. As they are not always realized in human experience, the assumptions are also held out as social ideals---goals to be aspired to in the liberal vision of a just and
good society.
<p>
These assumptions, however, are dangerously simplistic and partial. As will be shown, they provide an inadequate and misguided basis for understanding the depth and complexity of the &quot;harm&quot; to women and society that results from pornography. Furthermore, the assumptions are fundamentally gendered, having their roots in a
philosophical tradition that has excluded women, both from the very act of constructing them, as well as from their meaning. The reliance on these assumptions and ideals in judicial doctrine implicates the history and contemporary manifestations of gender inequality; it implicates relations of power and domination. These assertions problematize the judicial doctrine of the right to freedom of expression as guaranteed in the <cite>Charter</cite>. Indeed, they
begin to suggest the dangers attending the uncritical acceptance of the stated purposes of freedom of expression and their underlying premises---namely, that the judicial doctrine itself will serve as a vehicle for the re-creation of the status quo, legitimating and reinforcing existing power relations and the exclusion of women's voices and concerns. The problem of pornography provides a telling example of how this danger is a real---and realized---one.
<p>
The central premise of this article is that freedom of expression, and its judicial-doctrinal interpretation, is <i>in
itself</i> a feminist issue. Among North American feminists, any consideration of this right has tended to reduce to the issue of pornography, where a debate has been waged about whether pornography causes &quot;harm&quot; to women and whether it should be censored. Very little attention has been given by feminists to the philosophical and
judicial construction of the right itself or its transformative potential. Yet, to continue to conduct the debate over pornography within the parameters of the prescribed meaning of freedom of expression, particularly its construction as a <i>negative</i> right, is to re-create a set of assumptions that is part of the patriarchal structure and to close the door to alternative visions of human beings, society, and what freedom of expression might mean for women and men.
<p>
This article will begin by examining the assumptions that underpin the stated purposes of the right to freedom of expression. Then, drawing on feminist theory, it will critically assess these assumptions, revealing both their gendered meanings and their inadequacy for comprehending the pornographic message and its impact on women, men, and society. As will be seen, this impact is not an external, <i>causal</i> one. Indeed, in the <cite>Butler</cite> decision, the Supreme Court's efforts to find such a causal link appear to have been futile. While there may be some instances in which pornography directly spurs a man to abuse or use violence against a
woman, and while there is the very real problem of so-called &quot;snuff&quot; films in which women are actually killed in the production, the more widespread and insidious harm resulting from pornography can be seen only from the perspective of a more complex understanding of the relationship between expression and action than that implicit in the liberal theory of free expression.
<p>
It will be suggested that such an understanding is offered by feminist poststructuralist theory, which sees pornography as a <i>constitutive discourse</i> rather than an external and causative force. As a constitutive discourse, pornography does not have a fixed or essential meaning; its meaning is contingent, indeterminate, and the
site of political struggle. It is the indeterminacy of the pornographic message that haunts those who search for a <i>causal</i> relationship between pornography and actual violence. It is also this indeterminacy that looms over feminist debates about harm and censorship. While its meaning is neither fixed nor essential, pornography does have a powerful, dominant meaning within the context of patriarchal structures and relations. This dominant meaning asserts particular gender identities, namely male sexual dominance and female enjoyment of violence and degradation. While pornography has other possible meanings, these are marginalized by the power and apparent inevitability of the patriarchal message. The concept of constitutive discourse means that the meaning of pornography is <i>internalized</i> by individual men and women so as to become part of their <i>subjectivities</i>, although not all men and women are affected in the same way. Indeed, pornography has different, even contradictory, meanings for women as well as men. Any attempt at a monolithic definition of pornography that asserts its meaning as an institution of patriarchy and a form of violence against women must be an exclusive definition (as all definitions usually are).
<p>
The article will then re-examine the issues of harm and censorship in light of the insights of feminist poststructuralist theory. Importantly, this perspective, which enables a recognition of pornography's enigmatic and contingent nature, opens up the debate about pornography by allowing for a more inclusive discussion of the meaning of pornography and its role in a patriarchal society. By characterizing pornography as a constitutive discourse, feminist poststructuralism renders the harm of pornography &quot;visible.&quot; The harm is not a physical or directly observable harm, but one that works from within by constituting our subjectivities. As part of who we are, the dominant message of pornography works to reinforce the discourses and institutions of patriarchy through the actions and expression of individual men and women. Thus, the insights of feminist poststructuralist theory suggest that women <i>do</i> need to object to and challenge pornography's sexist messages. However,
because meanings are not fixed or essential, the apparent &quot;solution&quot; some feminists see in state censorship does not necessarily follow from a recognition of harm. From a feminist poststructuralist vantage point, the question of what to do about pornography becomes more complex, more problematic, more political and strategic. Pornography is a challenge riddled with political-legal dilemmas for feminists. Yet these dilemmas have been obscured by a polemic and static debate about harm and censorship.
<p>
Finally, it will be submitted that the indeterminacy of the pornographic message, and of meanings more generally, suggests the possibility of resistance and change without censorship---the possibility of transforming not only the pornographic message but also the right to freedom of expression itself. In the final section, I will begin to outline an alternative set of purposes for protecting the right which both affirm the importance of &quot;free expression&quot; and make it more meaningful for women and other oppressed groups who are struggling to have their voices heard in an unequal society.
<p>
<h3>The Purposes of the Right to Freedom of Expression: Drawing Out the Assumptions</h3>

The Supreme Court of Canada has adopted a purposive approach to the definition of rights guaranteed in the <cite>Charter</cite>. In <cite>Hunter v. Southam Inc.</cite>,<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> it was established that, before determining whether or not a right has been infringed, the Court must first specify the purpose of a right in order to delineate the nature of the interests it is meant to protect. In defining the nature and
scope of the right to freedom of expression, the Court has articulated three &quot;core&quot; purposes: promotion of the search for truth, participation in the political process, and individual self-fulfilment.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> Each of these three purposes can be traced to liberal philosophy and liberal understandings of the role of free expression in a democratic society. Specifically, the core purposes are those advanced by Thomas Emerson in his classic article &quot;Toward a General Theory of the First Amendment.&quot;<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> This approach should not be surprising, as the <cite>Charter</cite> is essentially a liberal document, setting out rights formulated to guarantee the liberty of the individual in the face of collective or state power.<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup>
<p>
Derived from liberal theory, these purposes are guided by and grounded in particular liberal assumptions about the nature of human beings, society, language, and expression, and the relationships among these constructs. Furthermore, they stem from and support the view of freedom of expression as a &quot;negative&quot; right---a right to be free from interference by other individuals and by the collectivity---which itself has significant implications. I will begin by examining each purpose and exposing the premises on which it is grounded and from which it derives its meaning. Then, in the following section, I will suggest the inadequacies and fallacies of these assumptions.
<p>
First, however, a brief word about my use of the term &quot;liberalism&quot; is warranted here. While the purposes of freedom of expression, and the assumptions that underpin them, are rooted in the liberal tradition of thought, it should be noted that &quot;liberalism&quot; is in no way a monolithic or cumulative philosophy. Despite the variety within this tradition, there are certain core principles that characterize liberal thought, such as an unwavering faith in the individual and individual initiative, as well as the priority of liberty over other values. The focus here will be on those aspects of the liberal tradition that have shaped the right to freedom of expression, and that have been incorporated into contemporary judicial doctrine through the continued reliance on the traditional liberal purposes for guaranteeing the right.
<p>
The first purpose of freedom of expression is to promote society's search for truth and knowledge. This is an idea that can be traced to the writings of John Stuart Mill. In his treatise <cite>On Liberty</cite>,<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> Mill explained the importance of free expression for arriving at truth:
<blockquote>
First, if any opinion is compelled to silence, that opinion may for aught we can certainly know, be true. To deny this
is to assume our own infallibility. Secondly, though the silenced opinion be in error, it may, and very commonly does, contain a portion of the truth; and since the general or prevailing opinion on any subject is rarely or never the whole truth, it is only by the collision of adverse opinions that the remainder of the truth has any chance of being supplied. Thirdly, even if the received opinion be not only true, but the whole truth; unless it is suffered to be, and
actually is, vigorously and earnestly contested, it will, by most of those who receive it, be held in the manner of prejudice, with little comprehension or feeling of its rational grounds. And not only this, but, fourthly, the meaning of the doctrine itself will be in danger of being lost, or enfeebled, and deprived of its vital effect on the character and conduct: the dogma of becoming a mere formal profession, inefficacious for good, but cumbering the ground, and preventing the growth of any real and heartfelt conviction, from reason or personal experience.<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Thus, freedom of expression is necessary to ensure that the most sound and most rational decision is arrived at by considering all the facts and arguments that can be put forth on behalf of any proposition. It is because human beings are not infallible that truth can come only from this clash of ideas.<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup>
<p>
This understanding of how society can and should attain truth and knowledge rests on the assumption that there is indeed a &quot;truth,&quot; seen also as an ideal, which can be found through Reason. Mill suggests that there is a &quot;preponderance&quot; among mankind of rational opinions and rational conduct, and through the human capacity for Reason &quot;[w]rong opinions and practices gradually yield to fact and argument.&quot;<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> In other words, wrong ideas can be <i>corrected</i> by Reason and the free  expression/clash of ideas. Reason is a concept not unique to liberal thought. With its roots in Greek philosophy, Reason has formed the central pursuit of the Western tradition of philosophy and it has had a variety of meanings
ascribed to it. In the context of the purposes of freedom of expression, Reason is understood as the distinctly human capacity for abstract and objective thought, uninfluenced by emotion or other subjective factors. It represents the human capacity to transcend the particularity of circumstances and relationships. Importantly, human fallibility does not negate the essentially rational nature of human beings. Thomas Emerson laments:
<blockquote>
Human judgment is a frail thing. It may err in being subject to emotion, prejudice or personal interest. It suffers from lack of information, insight or inadequate thinking. It . . . must always remain incomplete and subject to further extension, refinement, rejection or modification.<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup>
</blockquote>
However, he maintains the assumption and ideal of rational transcendence and the ability of men of Reason to arrive at the truth.
<p>
The view that false speech can be corrected by &quot;more speech&quot; and human Reason leads to and supports the further idea that expression in itself is not typically harmful; it &quot;is normally conceived as doing less injury to other social goals than action.&quot;<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup> The consequences of action are
distinguished from those of speech. While the effects of action are generally immediate, instantaneous and irremediable, those of speech are not; the latter can be countered with &quot;truth,&quot; which the man of Reason will recognize. Thus, when Mill states that &quot;the only purpose for which power can be rightfully exercised over any member of a civilized community, against his will, is to prevent harm to others,&quot;<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> the implication is that it is <i>physical</i> acts that cause harm and that justify limitations on individual freedom. As Emerson points out,
<blockquote>
. . . [T]he essence of a system of freedom of expression lies in the distinction between expression and action. The whole theory rests upon the general proposition that expression must be free and unrestrained, that the state may not seek to achieve other social objectives through control of expression, and that the attainment of such objectives can and must be secured through regulation of action. The dynamics of the system require that this line be carefully drawn and strictly adhered to.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup>
</blockquote>
It should be noted that this radical separation of speech and action is more characteristic of American First Amendment jurisprudence. Canadian jurisprudence takes a more sophisticated view of the difference between speech and action, distinguishing between the <i>form</i> of expression and its <i>content</i>. The Supreme Court has recognized that expression has both content and form, and that the two can be inextricably connective. Activity can be expressive if it attempts to convey meaning.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> According to
this view, the concept of form contains <i>within it</i> a distinction between thought and action. While some activity does convey meaning, thereby constituting expression, other activity does not and, in turn, will not be protected under s. 2(b) of the <cite>Charter</cite>. It is unclear, however, where the line between pure action and expressive action is to be drawn, and the Supreme Court has not provided any principled way to approach this problem.
<p>
The search for truth is often characterized in terms of a &quot;free market-place of ideas,&quot; an image analogous to the concept of a free economic market and frequently used in the jurisprudence of the Supreme Court. Truth requires an &quot;open competition&quot; among competing ideas and claims to truth. This characterization reveals another assumption: human beings are seen as equal in their capacity for reason and in their opportunities for expressing themselves. Freedom of expression, understood as a <i>negative</i> right entailing a right of individuals to be free from restraints and governmental interference, assumes that in the absence of such interference all individuals have an equal freedom to express their opinions. &quot;Equality&quot; in this context means &quot;formal&quot; equality, that is, the equal application of the law to all. As freedom is the natural state of man and, in turn, defined as the absence of restraint, laws (which constitute restraints) must be applied equally to all in order to guarantee equal freedom.
<p>
The second purpose of freedom of expression is to promote participation in the political process through open discussion &quot;which is available to all members of the community.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup> This purpose is grounded in a vision of a democratic society in which all persons share in the making of social decisions. Emerson suggests that this vision also embraces the right of all to participate in the building of <i>culture</i>. Again, there is an assumption here that in the absence of governmental restraint on free expression, all members of a society do have equal voice and equal opportunity to participate.
<p>
Finally, freedom of expression is protected under the <cite>Charter</cite> because it is seen to promote individual self-fulfilment. This purpose supports freedom of expression not merely as a means to democracy and truth, but as a good <i>in itself</i>. It also reflects a faith in, and focus on, the <i>individual</i>. Emerson argues that the proper end of human beings is to see the realization of their characters and potentialities.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> Human beings have powers to reason, to imagine, and to feel, and it is through the development of these that each of us finds our meaning and place in the world. Expression, then, is integral to the &quot;affirmation of the self,&quot; with the &quot;self&quot; being understood as a unified and coherent whole. This process of self-fulfilment is seen as an individual one; it is a process of <i>self-determination.</i> As Emerson explains, each person's &quot;mind is his own and its functioning is necessarily an individual affair.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup>
<p>
This understanding of the individual is premised on the assumption and ideal of <i>autonomy</i>. Autonomy is defined reactively as self-control and self-mastery, and it implies that individuals, by their nature, are separated from one another---physically and mentally. As Mill states: &quot;Over himself, over his own body and mind, the individual is sovereign.&quot;<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> The individual is seen to have an inherent
personality that can be realized through thought and expression. Here language is understood as having an independent existence apart from the individual who hears and speaks, with the meaning of words being determined and fixed by an external reality. The rational individual thus receives a message and deliberates on it. Its meaning can be objectively known. The individual may choose to act on the message, or she may not. In this way, the autonomous, rational individual mediates expression. 
<p>
The value of freedom is tied to the ideal of autonomy. Separateness from others means freedom from others---that is, negative freedom, or liberty. As F.A. von Hayek explains, liberty &quot;assures the individual of the right within a known domain to pursue his own aims on the basis of his own knowledge.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> The assumption of equality also underpins autonomy. As each individual is by nature autonomous, we are all equal in our autonomy and, in turn, our freedom. It is the role of the government, through the making of laws and the equal application of these laws to all, to promote this autonomy by protecting the freedom of each person up to the point where the freedom of others is threatened. 
<p>
Thus, the purposes defining the right to freedom of expression contain within them the assumption that individuals have an <i>essential</i> nature. They are rational, equal in their freedom, unified, autonomous, and self-defining. Such individuals stand apart from language, which is external and whose meanings are fixed by an objective, knowable reality. Expression, in conjunction with freedom of thought, is a central means by which individuals
realize their inherent personalities as well as &quot;truth.&quot; Importantly, these assumptions also serve as ideals toward which humankind should aspire; they serve as the goals to which the protection of the right of freedom of expression must be directed.
<p>
All of these assumptions and ideals have been called into question by feminist scholars, who have argued that they are not only inadequate and misleading representations of human experience, but they are also deeply and profoundly gendered. Their philosophical construction has both excluded women and constituted women as the
<i>Other</i>---that is, as the very negation of what is valued and idealized. The next section will draw on feminist theory to assess critically the underpinnings of freedom of expression doctrine.
<p>
<h3>Feminist Critiques of the Assumptions and Purposes of the Right to Freedom of Expression</h3>

As noted, the assumptions underlying the doctrinal interpretation of the right to freedom of expression implicate a
formal view of equality, which defines equality as the equal application of the law to all. In contrast to this view, the Supreme Court has adopted a &quot;group disadvantage&quot; approach to equality as it is guaranteed under s. 15 of the <cite>Charter</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup> This approach recognizes <i>systemic</i> inequality in Canadian society and the historical disadvantage that continues to support both overt and structural discrimination against particular <i>groups</i>, including women. Furthermore, it acknowledges that <i>substantive</i> equality may in particular instances require the <i>unequal</i> application of law. These two views of equality sit uneasily beside one another in the Court's jurisprudence. From the perspective of the group disadvantage approach, it becomes difficult to maintain the assumption implicated in the freedom of expression
doctrine that, absent governmental interference, all individuals are equal in their freedom of expression and participate on an equal basis in the social and political decision-making processes. Indeed, an important feminist critique is that &quot;free speech&quot; does not in fact exist. Formulated as a negative right, freedom of expression &quot;tends to presuppose that whole segments of the population are not systematically silenced <i>socially</i>, prior to government action.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> In a society of inequality, members of disadvantaged groups have not had equal access to decision-making processes, politically,
economically, or socially. Economic inequalities are particularly serious for freedom of expression, as access to the pervasive, privately-controlled media has become a central means of asserting ideas and alternative visions of society. Disadvantaged groups, then, have not had equal power to express themselves in the supposedly &quot;free&quot; market-place of ideas. Indeed, it has been argued that such groups are <i>silenced</i> by the overwhelming dominance of the ideas of the ruling group---namely, able-bodied, heterosexual, Christian white males.
<p>
It is significant that this inequality of free expression was not recognized in the Supreme Court's decision in <cite>Butler</cite>. While the Court acknowledged women's inequality in society, it did not draw any connection between, on the one hand, this general group disadvantage and the discriminatory effects of pornography, and, on
the other, women's lack of access to the means of expression. The tension in the <cite>Charter</cite> between negative, <i>individual</i> rights (such as freedom of expression) and so-called <i>collective</i> rights (such as equality understood in substantive terms) is apparent in the <cite>Butler</cite> decision, as the Court struggled to
reconcile its doctrinal interpretation of s. 2(b) with the claim of group-based harm by searching for a &quot;causal link&quot; between pornography and &quot;changes&quot; in men's attitudes and behaviour. However, the Court did not confront this tension or attempt to go below the surface and consider the conflicting premises on which its
analysis was based. As a result, the assumption of equality contained in the purposes of the right to freedom of expression remained intact. Yet, by not recognizing this inequality---by assuming it away or masking it---the s. 2(b) right itself serves to perpetuate existing inequalities, regardless of the outcome of a particular case. It serves to avoid the fact that for disadvantaged groups, &quot;. . . the urgent issue of freedom of speech is not primarily the avoidance of state intervention as such, but finding an affirmative means to get access to speech for those to whom it has been denied.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> While this criticism does not undermine the notion of formal equality implicit in freedom of expression doctrine (which does not deny that there is an unequal
distribution of resources in society, including access to communication resources), it does raise important questions about the adequacy of the concepts of formal equality and negative freedom for promoting the freedom of expression of <i>all</i> members of society.
<p>
The assumptions of truth and Reason are also problematic. Reason, in the context of freedom of expression doctrine, is understood as the capacity for abstract and objective thought. However, the claim to objectivity has come under increasing criticism in the social sciences (as well as the natural sciences), most notably by scholars influenced by poststructuralist and postmodern social theory. That there is no neutral place from which to view the world has also been a central tenet of feminist scholarship, which has sought to expose the gendered content of apparently neutral rules and premises.
<p>
Reason has itself been the subject of feminist analysis. Genevieve Lloyd has undertaken a critical review of Western
philosophical formulations of Reason.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> Lloyd notes that Reason has not only inspired Western ideals of objective knowledge, but it has also figured in our assessments of <i>character</i>: &quot;It is incorporated not only into our criteria of truth, but also into our understanding of what it is to be a person at all.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> While the &quot;aspiration to a Reason common to all, transcending the contingent historical circumstances which differentiate minds from one another, lies at the very heart of our philosophical heritage,&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> Lloyd argues that Reason is not an inherent capacity of human beings. Rather, it is a socially constructed concept. Moreover, it is a concept that is
profoundly gendered.
<p>
The ideal of Reason has been associated with the &quot;masculine&quot; identity, while that which the Man of Reason has sought to transcend, transform, or control---namely, the particularity of life, contingency, disorder, emotion, passion, and connection---has been associated with the &quot;feminine&quot; identity and Nature. Within this framework, the masculine identity is equated with superiority, and the feminine identity is devalued. Thus, what have been deemed to be distinctly &quot;feminine&quot; traits have been excluded from the ideal of Reason. As Lloyd explains, &quot;What has happened has not been a simple exclusion of women, but a constitution of femininity through that exclusion.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> The philosophical construction of Reason, then, has been central to the conceptualization and institutionalization of <i>gender difference</i> and <i>gender hierarchy.</i>
<p>
The ideal of Reason, as well as past differences in the lives of women and men, continue to haunt male and female consciousness and lived experience. To assume in our understanding of the right to freedom of expression that there exists a human capacity for Reason, as defined by the Western philosophical tradition, is to propagate an assumption and ideal that exclude and devalue women's experiences. This is not to say that the appropriate response is to include women by asserting the distinctly &quot;feminine&quot; traits. Indeed, as Lloyd points out, &quot;The idea that women have their own distinctive kind of intellectual or moral character has itself been partly formed within
the philosophical tradition to which it may now appear to be a reaction.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> As a result, 
<blockquote>
[u]nless the structural features of our concepts of gender are understood, any emphasis on a supposedly distinctive style of thought or morality is liable to be caught up in a deeper, older structure of male norms and female complements. The affirmation of the value and importance of &quot;the feminine&quot; cannot of itself be expected to shake the underlying normative structures, for, ironically, it will occur in a space already prepared for it by the intellectual tradition it seeks to reject.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Lloyd leaves open the possibility that there is &quot;a Reason genuinely common to all.&quot; If it exists, &quot;it is something to be achieved in the future, not celebrated in the present.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup>
<p>
Because Reason---the apparent means to the attainment of truth---is a socially constructed value and a concept that has excluded the lived experiences of women, the notion of &quot;truth&quot; in the Court's freedom of expression doctrine becomes suspect. Indeed, truth appears to have a dangerous connection with social power and hierarchy. As suggested by the discussion of Reason---long held out as a truth about &quot;man&quot;---the voices of the powerful can impose their values and ideals on others and parade them as &quot;truth.&quot; The intimate relationship between truth and power is rendered even more perilous in the context of an assumption of equal freedom, including freedom of expression. This is so because the inequalities of power are masked by formal equality. In this web, domination comes to appear <i>natural</i> and <i>inevitable</i>. It is in this way that
pornography masquerades as the true expression of women's and men's sexuality. The pornographic message, created <i>by</i> men largely <i>for</i> men, is sent and received in the context of patriarchal relations and apparently equal freedom of expression. The full implications of its power, including its reinforcing effect on
discrimination against women and its &quot;silencing&quot; of women as a group, have been rendered invisible when viewed through the lens of the purposes of the right to freedom of expression. Just what these full implications are will be discussed shortly.
<p>
It must be noted that any attempt to assess critically the limitations and gender bias of the doctrinal assumptions of Reason and, in turn, truth, runs up against a serious hurdle. These assumptions linger, not only in the doctrinal interpretation of freedom of expression, but also in the law more generally. Courts, for example, continue to understand their own legitimacy in terms of a &quot;neutral&quot; justice founded on &quot;facts&quot; and objective reasoning. Thus, to question Reason and truth is to question the role of the Courts themselves.
<p>
Just as problematic as equality, Reason, and truth, is the assumption and ideal of individual autonomy. This single premise, which envisions human beings as separate, discrete, and self-determining, implicates many others---including Reason---and is far-reaching in its influence on how we think about individual selfhood, society, and expression. A variety of criticisms has been levelled against this assumption by feminists, some of which are more
persuasive and helpful than others.
<p>
For example, Robin West has argued that the conceptualization of human beings as discrete and unconnected while &quot;trivially true&quot; of men is &quot;patently untrue&quot; of women.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> She suggests that one of the central insights of recent feminist theory is that women are <i>essentially connected</i> rather than <i>essentially separate.</i> They are connected to human life both materially---through pregnancy, intercourse, and breast-feeding---and, as a result, existentially---through their moral and practical lives. The material fact of connectedness leads to a world view that is radically different from that implied by the notion of autonomy. It is a world of relationships, responsibility, caring, and intimacy, with a notion of selfhood as being constructed through relationships.<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> This world view stands in contrast to that of the autonomous male who understands the world in terms of competition with others for freedom and separate selfhood. West is careful to note that this existential state of connectedness is in no sense biologically <i>mandated</i>, but it is nevertheless biologically <i>grounded</i>. While these claims assert women's existential connectedness, rather than autonomy, and suggest that women's experience is excluded from any assumption of autonomy, they do not offer an historical explanation of women's difference or offer a sustained critique of autonomy in and of itself.
<p>
Catherine Keller has also considered the assumption and ideal of autonomy, or, as she refers to it, the &quot;separate self.&quot; She traces the construction of the notion of separate selfhood from Greek mythology and heroic tales. With a long cultural and philosophical history, separation has become an ideal that has taken hold of Western imaginations:
<blockquote>
To be a self, must I be something separate and apart? How else could I be myself? Myth and religion, philosophy and psychology center our civilization on the assumption that an individual is a discrete being: I am cleanly divided from the surrounding world of persons and places; I remain essentially the same self from moment to moment. Common sense identifies separateness with the freedom we cherish in the name of &quot;independence&quot; and &quot;autonomy.&quot; The assumption that selfhood requires separation is even rooted in language. The Latin for
&quot;self,&quot; <i>se</i> meaning &quot;on one's own,&quot; yields with <i>parare</i> (&quot;to prepare&quot;) the verb &quot;to separate.&quot; For our culture it is separation which prepares the way for
selfhood.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup>
</blockquote>
She argues that the separate self is an illusion, &quot;because willy-nilly each subject exists in interdependence with its world.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup>
<blockquote>
However much the ego feels single and apart, this feeling may represent not truth but denial. It is less precise to call this ego separate than <i>separative</i>, implying an activity or an intention rather than any fundamental state of being. . . . Its sense of itself as separate, as over and against the world, the Other, and even its own body, endows it with its identity. It is <i>this</i>, not <i>that</i>.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Keller further argues that the separative self is <i>gendered</i>, as separation and sexism have functioned together. In the fear of self-loss, connectedness, merger, and the influence of others that motivates all insistence on separate selfhood &quot;lurks a profound fear of women.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> The separative self,
which is identifiable historically (but neither essentially nor necessarily) with males and the masculine, has constructed itself on the basis of, and at the expense of, women, whom it has constructed as the Other---the connected, the dependent, the &quot;soluble self.&quot; The separative self externalizes relationship by projecting and imposing both the threats and comforts of relationship onto the Other. Yet, the fundamental opposition between self and Other is in fact dialectical, as it &quot;serves the dual purpose of establishing the self's sense of its inner independence from influence and compensating for the haunting fear that that independence is illusory. As it cannot embrace interdependence, it ironically comes to depend upon the dependent Other, in reality or fantasy.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> Interestingly enough, but in no way surprising, it is this dialectical opposition that pornography re-creates---the construction of the &quot;soluble feminine self&quot; who
dissolves into the needs and demands of the separative masculine self, the woman who exists as object to serve the identity needs of man the subject. Yet, the pornographic image reveals a dependency of the masculine on the feminine---a need for some form of connectedness (albeit a destructive form). 
<p>
Thus, the assumption and ideal of the masculine separate self, which is closely tied to the philosophical construct of Reason, has also played a central role in constructing and justifying the oppression of women. As with Reason, autonomy is defined at the expense of, and in opposition to, women and femininity. The connectedness that West tells us is part of women's experience, has been, at least in part, constructed and imposed by the separative self. In turn, it has been crucial in defining women's <i>devalued</i> roles as mothers, nurturers, and homemakers. The
maintenance of the ideal of autonomy through freedom of expression doctrine both denies women's experience, as well as men's, and holds out an illusory and gendered goal. This means that any claim by women to &quot;what men have&quot;---that is, autonomy---as well as any claim that women are more connected, runs up against the danger of (re)creating the prior conceptual framework within which gender difference and gender hierarchy have been constructed. Keller argues that the alternatives of autonomy and relation represent a false choice. Connectedness, both to individuals and to society more generally, represents the experience of both men and women.
<p>
Jennifer Nedelsky has argued that what feminism requires is a new conception of autonomy.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> &quot;The prevailing concept stands at the core of liberal theory and carries with it the individualism characteristic of liberalism. Such a conception cannot meet the aspirations of feminism.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> Nedelsky points out that liberalism takes atomistic individuals as the basic units of political and legal theory &quot;and thus fails to recognize the inherently social nature of human beings.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> Individuals are not self-made nor are they essentially separate. She suggests that:
<blockquote>
We come into being in a social context that is literally <i>constitutive of us</i>. Some of our most essential
characteristics, such as our capacity for language and the conceptual framework through which we see the world, are not made by us, but given to us (or developed in us) through our interactions with others. [emphasis added]<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> 
</blockquote>
Thus, relationships are central to constituting the self. In contrast, the ideal of autonomy denies the strength that the self derives from its context of relations. Furthermore, as an individual sphere of unfettered action and thought, autonomy requires for its realization the erection of <i>boundaries</i> around the self in order to keep out the influence and desires of others. One of the most important forms of boundary our society erects is <i>negative
rights</i>, including the right to freedom of expression. As has been noted, freedom of expression guarantees that the autonomous individual is free to express himself/herself without coercion or restraint from others or society up to the point where that freedom intrudes on the freedom of others. Nedelsky argues that the essence of autonomy in its liberal incarnation is the <i>power</i> to close out others. This power is not a form of inner strength; rather, it is a power <i>from</i> and <i>over</i> others. An important part of autonomy is seen to be the exercise of <i>control</i> and <i>choice</i>, not only over objects but over other people. Thus, the sought-after illusion of security is achieved through power, domination, and isolation.<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup> The exercise of this power, and the relationships it structures, are masked by the assumption of autonomy and by the boundaries constructed around individuals. For example, as was discussed above, the unequal access of women to free expression is hidden and maintained through the formulation of the right to freedom of expression in negative terms---that is, in terms of a boundary.
<p>
It is suggested that the basic value of autonomy is one that feminism must retain while rejecting its &quot;liberal incarnation.&quot; Feminists want to free women to shape their own lives rather than be shaped by men and patriarchy. They do not want to deny or renounce the individual, nor do they seek to privilege a patriarchal
community. In this way, feminism differs from many communitarian theories in its critique of liberal individualism. For feminism, the problem with individual autonomy is not so much that it prioritizes the individual and his/her desires over the needs of the community, but that it denies the crucial relationship between the individual and the community and thereby denies some of the important ways in which power and domination are exercised. Nedelsky proposes a reconceptualization of autonomy: &quot;relational autonomy.&quot; Rather than assuming and seeking separateness, autonomy must be understood in the context of <i>relationships,</i> because what actually enables
people to be autonomous is not isolation but constructive connection---relationships not distorted by power and domination. According to this view of autonomy, the &quot;self&quot; becomes a <i>capacity,</i> a <i>process,</i> rather than a fixed substance. Understanding autonomy in this way allows for a consideration of how our relationships with others shape our choices and options in life, and opens the possibility of increasing those options through a restructuring of social relationships.
<p>
These feminist critiques of autonomy counter the assumption of a separate, fixed, and self-defining individual in need of protection---through such rights as freedom of expression---against interference by the collective with its selfhood and its freedom. They suggest, instead, that the individual is fundamentally related to other individuals and to society/culture more generally. Moreover, they assert that individual identity is constituted in and by these relationships. The question now becomes: What is the role of language and expression in these constitutive relationships? More specifically, what is the role of pornography?
<p>
<h3>Language and Expression: Constituting the Self and Subjectivity</h3>

As discussed above, the claim that individuals are self-determining, autonomous, and rational leads to a view of
expression as a means of asserting the innate views and personality of the author, or the self. Language is thus external to the individual, and meaning is determined by an objective, knowable &quot;reality.&quot; In turn, expression is received by the unified, separate self and processed through the self's rational capacity (as potentially modified by prejudice). Importantly, the message is seen to have a clear, fixed meaning, which exists independently of the individual who hears it. The autonomous individual is then free to choose how he or she acts on the messages received. In contrast, a recognition of constitutive social relationships points to a very different role for language and expression. When we think about our relationships to others and to the society in which we live, we cannot help but notice that those relationships are conducted in large part through language and expression.
<p>
In seeking to understand better the role of expression and the significance of pornography, the work of Chris Weedon is particularly helpful.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> Drawing on the writings of Ferdinand de Saussure, Sigmund Freud, Jacques Derrida, and Michel Foucault, among others, Weedon has sought to develop a feminist poststructuralist theory of the relationship among language, subjectivity, social organization, and power within the context of patriarchy. She argues that poststructuralism is a useful approach for feminism, as its focus on
language, subjectivity, and relations of power help to explain many of the key relationships, processes, and structures that (re)create women's oppression, such as: how knowledge is produced and what type of knowledge is produced; how power is exercised through language and meaning; the existence of competing subjective realities and the social interests on behalf of which they work; resistance to change; and the relationship between material conditions and subjectivities. In addition, its view of the individual as the site of competing subjectivities acknowledges, and provides an explanation for, individual consciousness and the <i>plurality</i> of women's voices. Moreover, poststructuralism opens up the possibility of social change through language, as it comprehends language not as a passive medium for the expression of individual personality but, rather, as truly social and the site of struggle over meaning which is a prerequisite for political change. This possibility has significant implications
for a feminist analysis of freedom of expression. Indeed, it suggests the importance of freedom of expression to feminist politics and practice.
<p>
As in the case of liberal philosophy, poststructuralism is a label applied to a range of theoretical positions. Unlike other forms of poststructuralism, <i>feminist</i> poststructuralism is expressly concerned with the transformation of the hierarchical relationships of patriarchy. Weedon points out that &quot;most of the theorists who have produced poststructuralist texts are themselves unsympathetic to feminism. However it is important to distinguish between the political potential and usefulness of a theory and the particular affiliations of its author.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> Weedon does not present her theory as an all-encompassing, universalized feminist
theory; she admits that it cannot address all the issues of concern to feminists. She also acknowledges that many feminists (most notably, radical and liberal feminists) have been critical of poststructuralism, as it decentres the rational unitary, autonomous subject of liberalism and the essential female nature that lies at the centre of much radical feminism. However, Weedon argues that the feminist poststructuralist perspective enables a recognition and
understanding of the different meanings feminists give to &quot;woman&quot; and &quot;femininity,&quot; and it provides a means of assessing &quot;the <i>practical</i> implications of particular ways of theorizing women's
oppression.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup>
<p>
To understand Weedon's poststructuralist theory and the role it envisions for language, it is first necessary to explain Saussure's structural linguistic theory of the &quot;sign&quot; on which poststructuralist theory builds but which it radically transforms. Saussure posited a theory of language in which language is a pre-given, fixed structure existing prior to its realization in speech or writing. He theorized language as an abstract system consisting of chains of signs. Each sign is made up of a &quot;signifier&quot; (a sound or written image) and a &quot;signified&quot; (a
meaning). For Saussure, there is no natural connection between the signifier and the signified. Each derives its meaning from its difference from all other signs in the language chain. For example, the signifier &quot;whore&quot; derives its meaning from its difference from other signifiers such as &quot;virgin&quot; and &quot;mother.&quot;
<p>
Poststructuralism takes from Saussure the idea that meaning is produced <i>within</i> language rather than reflected <i>by</i> language; individual signs have no fixed or intrinsic meaning but acquire meaning through the language chain. Poststructuralism sees human beings as connected through language, and meaning as constructed through human relationships. Furthermore, as language itself is always existing in historically specific discourses and social contexts, different languages and different discourses within the same language divide the world in a variety of ways and give it different meaning. The concept of &quot;discourse,&quot; as developed in the work of Foucault, refers to    
<blockquote>
. . . ways of constituting knowledge, together with the social practices, forms of subjectivity and power relations which inhere in such knowledges and the relations between them. Discourses are more than ways of thinking and producing meaning. They constitute the &quot;nature&quot; of the body, unconscious and conscious mind and emotional life of the subjects which they govern.<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Meaning, then, is contingent and indeterminate. It is not fixed by an external reality that can be known objectively through Reason. As a result, meaning is not guaranteed by the subject who speaks or expresses herself but is open to plural interpretations. This conception of language and meaning clearly represents a fundamental critique of the view implicit in freedom of expression doctrine.
<p>
Although meaning is contingent and indeterminate, poststructuralism maintains that particular meanings do become
temporarily fixed or dominant. This is necessary for communication. It further asserts that power relations in society, including their manifestations in social institutions and practices, will influence <i>which</i> meanings do become temporarily fixed. Wheedon points out that:
<blockquote>
How we live our lives as conscious thinking subjects, and how we give meaning to the material social relations under which we live and which structure our everyday lives, depends on the range and social power of existing discourses, our access to them and the political strength of the interests which they represent.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Thus, the dominance of liberal assumptions in the judicial interpretation of the right to freedom of expression and the complicity of feminists in the maintenance of freedom of expression doctrine can be explained by the social power of liberalism in legal and political discourses. 
<p>
That particular meanings become dominant and temporarily fixed has implications for the notion of a &quot;truth&quot; to be found through the free clash of ideas, which is one of the articulated purposes of the right to freedom of expression. What appears as &quot;truth&quot; (as &quot;common sense,&quot; or as  &quot;natural&quot;) is merely the dominant meaning as defined by the most powerful discourses, and the &quot;clash of ideas&quot; is more akin to monopoly control than a free market-place. In Weedon's words: &quot;It is in making claims to truth that discourses demonstrate their inevitable conservatism, their investment in particular versions of meaning and their hostility to change.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> Weedon further argues that &quot;truth is a social construct used to uphold patriarchal interests. . . .&quot;<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> This critique of the notion of truth has significant implications for feminist strategies. It is possible, Weedon notes, for feminists to assert new truths about women. Liberal feminists have taken this approach, arguing that women's physiology did not make them incapable of attaining an education or becoming successful in a career. Weedon believes, however, that such efforts are unlikely to succeed in transforming patriarchy. Once again, women's lack of resources and institutional bases for putting forth alternative claims to truth stand in the way of making &quot;much impact on the discursive hierarchy of existing writing and research, backed, as it is, by capitalist and patriarchal interests.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup>
<p>
While language enables us to think, speak, and give meaning to the world, it is also the place where our sense of self, our <i>subjectivity</i>, is constructed. &quot;Subjectivity&quot; refers to &quot;the conscious and unconcious thoughts and emotions of the individual, her sense of herself and her ways of understanding her relation to the world.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> In contrast to the liberal assumption of an &quot;essence at the heart of the individual which is unique, fixed and coherent and which makes her what she
is,&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup> poststructuralism <i>decentres</i> the subject. It asserts that subjectivity is constituted through relationships---through language and a range of competing discourses. In the face of competing and often contradictory discourses, human subjectivity is neither unified nor rational. Rather, it is the site of disunity and conflict---the site of struggle over meaning. The self, then, is open to continuous redefinition. From this perspective, gender identities are not essential, and particular versions of femininity and masculinity are never inevitable. The claim that individual subjectivity is socially constructed does not deny individual agency. As Weedon explains,
<blockquote>
. . . [L]anguage, in the form of socially and historically specific discourses, cannot have any social and political effectivity except in and through the actions of the individuals who become its bearers by taking up the forms of subjectivity and the meanings and values which it proposes and acting upon them. The individual is both the site for a range of possible forms of subjectivity and, at any particular moment of thought or speech, a subject, subjected to
the regime of meaning of a particular discourse and enabled to act accordingly. The position of subject from which language is articulated, from which speech, acts, thoughts or writing appear to originate, is integral to the structure of language and, by extension, to the structure of conscious subjectivity which it constitutes.<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Discourses are seen to offer each of us a variety of &quot;subject positions&quot; through which we can consciously live our lives. For example, women are offered a range of competing subject positions: career woman, pornographic sexual object, successful wife and mother. Subject positions are constructed through the media and through all our social institutions, including law. Again, the power of subject positions depends on the power of the discourses that construct them, on the individual's access to them, and on the material circumstances of each individual's life. In a patriarchal society, discourses and subject positions that maintain gender inequality are most powerful, while feminist discourses---and the alternative subject positions they offer women---are marginalized and devalued.
<p>
A recognition of the social power of particular subject positions for women, such as sexual object and wife/mother, helps to explain women's <i>complicity</i> in their own oppression. In social debates about the issue of pornography, the question of why women &quot;willingly&quot; pose for pornographic magazines or appear in pornographic films has presented feminism with a difficult challenge. If women &quot;willingly&quot; do so, how is it that pornography oppresses women? Are these women simply &quot;wrong&quot; in their failure to comprehend their oppression? Weedon notes that liberal feminism, &quot;with its belief in the sovereignty of the individual, is unable to deal satisfactorily with the question of `complicity with oppression.'  If a woman's choice is based on her free will then it must be valid.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> Thus, &quot;the structural and institutional oppression of women disappears behind the belief that if I as rational sovereign subject freely choose my way of life on the basis of my individual rational consciousness which gives me knowledge of the world, then I am not oppressed.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup> Feminist poststructuralism implicates language, meaning, and patriarchal discourses in women's oppression; these are internalized by the individual woman in the form of subject positions through which she lives her life and reflects upon it.
<p>
Discourses, located in social institutions and processes, are constantly competing with one another for the allegiance of individual agents. The political and social interests of a discourse cannot be realized without the agency of individuals who are subjectively motivated to either reproduce or transform social practices and relationships of power. As a result, the subject positions constructed by discourses are &quot;part of the battle to determine the day to day practices of family life.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> They are &quot;central to the process of political change and to preserving the status quo.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> In this way, language and its expression are inseparable from human action. When our actions are manifestations of socially constructed subject positions, when they reinforce one discourse or another, they do have <i>meaning</i> even when they appear not to. For example, the rape of a woman by a man and other acts of violence against women
are not merely physical acts; they convey a meaning of male dominance. Thus, the separation of speech and action urged by the assumptions of autonomy and Reason becomes illusory. It was noted earlier that Canadian freedom of expression jurisprudence has not maintained such a radical dichotomy between expression and action. However, the alternative distinction between form and content is also problematic. The concept of &quot;form&quot; contains within it the separation of expression and action. Some actions are intended to convey meaning while others are not. The alternative theory of meaning outlined above suggests that meaning, expression, and action cannot be isolated from one another without ignoring the social construction of subjectivity and, moreover, the power relations that
underpin particular subjectivities.
<p>
Poststructuralism regards language as &quot;the place where actual and possible forms of social organization and their likely social and political consequences are defined and contested.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup> Meanings can never be permanently fixed. Being contingent and indeterminate, they are always open to challenge and redefinition. This opens up possibilities for change:
<blockquote>
Once language is understood in terms of competing discourses, competing ways of giving meaning to the world, which imply differences in the organization of social power, then language becomes an important site of political struggle.<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The poststructuralist conception of power is also important for effecting change. Power 
<blockquote>
. . . is a relation. It inheres in difference and is a dynamic of control and lack of control between discourses and the
subjects, constituted by discourses, who are their agents. Power is exercised within discourses in the ways in which they constitute and govern individual subjects.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Moreover, power is seen to be &quot;polymorphous&quot;; it eludes the total control of any group or body and thus never flows in only one direction. Recognizing the multiplicity of power relations is crucial to feminist analysis and practice, as it opens up a whole range of points of resistance.
<p>
Despite the ongoing battle for the subjectivity of each individual---&quot;a battle in which real interests are at stake, for example, gender-based social power&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> ---dominant, liberal assumptions about the nature of subjectivity and language obscure this power struggle. The liberal tradition suggests that each individual possesses an unchanging essence of subjectivity:
<blockquote>
Consciousness is thought to be a continuous stream rather than the fragmented and contradictory effect of a discursive battle for the subjectivity of the individual. The exclusiveness of the assumption of a particular form of subjectivity, which rules out its alternatives, together with the individual subject's misrecognition of herself as the true author of her thoughts, speech and writing, gives the articulation of subjectivity in language the temporary
appearance of fixity. This sense of fixity seems to rule out change.<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Thus, the liberal assumptions underpinning freedom of expression doctrine are implicated in patriarchal discourses that assert their own truth, mask the power of language, and deny the crucial role of language in effecting social change. In short, they serve to preserve the status quo of patriarchy.
<p>
It has been argued that the core purposes that have framed the doctrinal interpretation of the right to freedom of expression rest on a set of assumptions that are inadequate for understanding the crucial relationships among the individual, society, and expression. Furthermore, the assumptions are gendered and, as such, implicate the relations and discourses of patriarchy. One consequence of failing to examine these assumptions critically is that the power relations of patriarchy are masked and silently reproduced. Another is that issues such as pornography become distorted when seen through a lens that portrays language as a passive medium for the expression of innate and essential personality. In particular, a recognition and understanding of the complexity of the harm resulting from
pornography remains elusive when the pornographic message is viewed from a perspective that understands the world in terms of autonomy, rationality, truth, and equality of expression. Indeed, the meaning of &quot;harm&quot; in legal doctrine has been constructed by a discourse that sees language and expression as external to the individual rather than constitutive of individual subjectivity.
<p>
In her writings on the issue of pornography, Catherine MacKinnon has argued that &quot;the issue is not whether pornography is harmful, but how the harm of pornography is to become visible.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> The following section will examine the question of the harm resulting from pornography and suggest that the alternative view of expression and individual subjectivity outlined above provides a way of making this harm &quot;visible.&quot;
<p>
<h3>Conceptualizing Harm: The Feminist Struggle Over the Meaning of Pornography</h3>

Within feminism, there has been much debate about whether or not pornography &quot;causes harm&quot; to women, men, and society. The debate can be seen as part of a discursive struggle over the meaning of pornography and harm, with particular meanings having specific political/practical consequences. The issue of harm has been a
contentious one, at least in part because the question of a causal link between the viewing of pornography by men and actual violence against women has remained &quot;unresolved.&quot; Another reason for the contention is the failure of many feminists to acknowledge expressly that their various positions on the issue are premised on quite
different assumptions about expression, language, and individual subjectivity. As a result, much of the &quot;debate&quot; has been little more than a lot of people talking past one another.
<p>
The characterization of harm has been central to defining the right to freedom of expression, as only that speech that causes harm has been deemed to be subject to restraint. There are at least three distinct arguments made about the relationship between pornography and harm. While these are by no means monolithic or exhaustive, they provide a useful way to structure the debate in order to describe and analyse it. One view, often expressed by feminists who accept the world view of liberal philosophy, is that pornography---understood as &quot;mere words and images&quot;---cannot cause harm; while sticks and stones may break my bones, names will never hurt me. This view suggests that the violent and degrading images expressed in pornography are either benign or beneficial. The latter characterization is premised on the idea that pornography allows men to fantasize about their impulses without having to act them out. Another view asserts that men <i>learn</i> from the images they see and the messages they receive. They learn that violence against women is acceptable and is part of what it means to be a &quot;man.&quot; Furthermore, through watching repeated violence, men come to be <i>desensitized</i> to violence. A third view, typically expressed by so-called radical feminists, tells us that pornography, in the context of a patriarchal society, plays a central role in the construction of gender identities and sexuality in such a way as to
institutionalize inequality, domination, and violence.
<p>
As noted, each of these views is premised on different assumptions about the relationship between expression and
subjectivity. The first view reflects the understanding of language, meaning, and subjectivity that is implicated in the assumptions of autonomy, rationality, and truth. It reflects the traditional liberal conceptualization of language as a passive medium existing apart from the individual, as well as the liberal understanding of harm as being either physical or in some way external to the individual. This meaning of harm is derived from the central value of liberty or negative freedom. &quot;The individual is free to the extent that she is not restrained by external forces, primarily viewed as law, physical force, and other overt coercion.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> Restraint is understood as restraint <i>by</i> others who then threaten an individual's <i>inherent</i> freedom. The individual <i>cannot</i> be restrained by &quot;internal&quot; forces, because her &quot;mind is her own.&quot; A distinction, then, is drawn between expression and action. This distinction is premised on the belief that speech is less immediate and more remediable than action; it is generally not a threat to individual liberty. On the basis of the expression-action dichotomy, a further distinction is drawn between <i>individual</i> and <i>group</i> harms. As Emerson argues,
<blockquote>
. . . [T]he harm to the individual interest is more likely to be direct and immediate in its impact, and irremediable by resource to regulation of the subsequent conduct stimulated by the expression. For this reason communication injuring an individual interest is more readily classifiable as &quot;action&quot; than injury to the general social
interest which is capable of protection by control of subsequent overt acts.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In the case of civil libel and slander, which injure <i>individual</i> business, professional or other property <i>interests,</i> the harm does not flow from any action resulting from the communication. Rather, it flows directly from the communication itself. It is on this basis that the harm of civil libel and slander are distinguished from the harm of pornography, which is understood in terms of any <i>subsequent action</i> caused by the expression. According to this view, only that pornography which directly incites a man to physical violence or coercion would be seen to &quot;cause harm.&quot; Significantly, this requirement of a causal nexus can be satisfied only by looking at <i>individual</i> cases <i>after</i> the unlawful action has occurred. Moreover, this approach does not provide a rationale for prohibiting pornography in general.
<p>
The second view of the harm that results from pornography focuses largely on men and their responses to pornographic messages. This approach moves away from the individualistic conception of harm and considers <i>men</i> as a group who cause harm, and <i>women</i> as a group who are the victims of such harm. It suggests that men &quot;learn&quot; from pornography; they learn that violence and degradation are acceptable and that women desire to be treated in this way. In turn, men are seen to act on what they have learned to be true.
Those who take this view are also looking for an identifiable and objectively knowable causal link between pornography and harm to women, but here the causal link is between pornography and men's <i>attitudes</i> which, in turn, are acted on. Attitudinal change becomes the crucial link between the message and the action. Much of the social scientific research conducted on the impact of pornography reflects this understanding of the relationship between pornography and harm. However, the results of the various studies have been ambiguous as not <i>all</i> men have shown negative attitudinal responses to pornographic imagery.
<p>
While at first glance this second view of harm appears to break down the assumptions of autonomy and rationality, a closer look suggests that these values continue to be held out as ideals. Some proponents of this conception of harm argue that negative attitudes can be changed by the same process through which they are formed, that is, through education and learning. The suggestion appears to be that because the pornographic message is a <i>false</i> one, the truth can emerge if rational people are informed of it. Also, by continuing to assert the requirement, and hence the potential existence, of a causal relationship between pornography and actual violence as mediated by attitude, this view is not really different from that expressed by Emerson in his lament that the human mind, while having the capacity for Reason, is subject to prejudice and misinformation. The second approach sustains a view of language as external to individuals by implying (through the assumption of a cause-effect relationship) the separation of expression, attitude, and action into discrete stages of a causal chain. This separation
is underscored by the fact that <i>physical violence</i> remains the ultimate definition of harm. There is also an assumption here of an essential and unified subjectivity. That is, there is an assumption that men's minds work alike and that all men, or at least most, will respond to pornography in the same way. Similarly, it is assumed that all women are victims of the pornographic message. This also suggests that pornography is seen as having a single, fixed meaning.
<p>
In its decision in <cite>Butler</cite>, the Supreme Court of Canada adopted the second view of harm. In its consideration of the constitutionality of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite> provisions dealing with obscene material, the Court first found that pornography constituted expression. It then held that the promotion of  &quot;morality&quot; was not a valid reason to prohibit such expression in the face of the <cite>Charter</cite> guarantee of freedom of expression. However, the &quot;prevention of harm to society&quot; was deemed to be a valid reason. This conclusion reflects the traditional liberal position that expression must be restricted only for the purpose of preventing harm. However, the claim that this harm is not only to individuals but also to <i>society</i>, represents a move away from the assumptions underpinning the purposes of freedom of expression. In order to uphold the impugned legislation, then, the Court had to show what this social harm was and how it came about. In his decision for the majority, Sopinka J. struggled to find a causal connection between the pornographic message and harm to both women as a group and society in general. In his struggle, he shifted between various characterizations of the harm and the nature of the connection, resulting in a troublesome and unpersuasive judgment.
<p>
The dominant view of harm reflected in the decision is that pornography causes attitudinal changes that then lead to actual violence. Sopinka J. cited Wilson J. in <cite>R. v. Town Cinema Theatres Ltd.</cite>,<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> who noted that &quot;[t]he public has concluded that exposure to material that degrades the human dimensions of life to a subhuman or merely physical dimension and thereby contributes to a process of <i>moral desensitization</i> must be harmful in some way [emphasis added].&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup> Later, it was suggested that harm &quot;means that it <i>predisposes persons to act in an antisocial manner,</i> as for example, the physical or mental mistreatment of women by men [emphasis added].&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> In characterizing the objectives of the impugned legislation, Sopinka J. asserted that the purpose of s. 163 of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite> is &quot;the avoidance of harm resulting from the <i>antisocial attitudinal changes</i> that exposure to obscene material causes [emphasis added].&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup>
<p>
This emphasis on <i>changes</i> in men's attitudes is problematic for a number of reasons. First, it fails to recognize <i>existing</i> attitudes of sexism and discrimination against women. In turn, it isolates pornography and directs attention away from the myriad of other patriarchal discourses that (re)create women's inequality. It is interesting that Sopinka J. actually did refer to the problem of existing attitudes when he cited the <cite>MacGuigan
Report</cite> which found that &quot;[t]he clear and unquestionable danger of this type of material [pornography] is that it <i>reinforces</i> some unhealthy tendencies in Canadian society. The effect of this material is to <i>reinforce male-female stereotypes</i> to the detriment of both sexes [emphasis added].&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> However, he did not pursue the implications of this view. Thus, while the <cite>Butler</cite> decision appears to be a victory for women in its recognition that pornography results in harm to women as a group and threatens the feminist goal of ending women's oppression, the extent of that recognition may be only skin-deep. Indeed, at only one point did Sopinka J. expressly suggest that there is a &quot;threat to equality&quot; from audience exposure to certain types of violent and degrading material.<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup>
<p>
A second difficulty arising from the focus on attitudinal change is that, while some studies have found a link between exposure to pornography and a change in how some men view women, the results typically have been inconclusive. This fact led Sopinka J. to adopt an ambiguous, if not contradictory, position on the question of
causation. In his application of the rational connection test under the s. 1 analysis, he found that &quot;the rational link between s. 163 and the objective of Parliament relates to the <i>actual causal relationship</i> between obscenity and the risk of harm to society at large [emphasis added].&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> However, he went on to note that &quot;a direct link between obscenity and harm to society may be difficult, if not impossible, to establish.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> In the end Sopinka J. resorted to Reason: &quot;[I]t is reasonable to presume that exposure to images bears a causal relationship to changes in attitudes and beliefs.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup> While the causation of antisocial attitudinal changes has not been <i>proven</i>, the further link to actual violence and discriminatory behaviour---the crucial link---has been even more elusive. Again, Sopinka J. finally relied on the &quot;underlying logic&quot; of the conclusion that exposure to violent material bears a causal relationship to acts of sexual violence.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> This &quot;common sense&quot; or &quot;rational&quot; approach to the questions of <i>if</i> and <i>how</i> pornography harms women and society is hardly satisfactory. Indeed, it dodges the issue. Furthermore, if what constitutes logic, common sense, and reason is determined by the relative power of competing discourses and the temporary fixing of particular meanings given to experience, then the reliance on logic becomes an act of support for the status quo. 
<p>
There are at least two further difficulties associated with the Court's search for a causal nexus between pornography and men's attitudes and behaviours toward women. The first is that the Court's reliance on the <i>reasonableness</i> and <i>logic</i> of the causal link breaks down any distinction between pornography and other violent and degrading depictions of women and men. What about popular films that show women being raped, abused, and murdered? Do these not cause &quot;harm&quot;? Why draw the line at pornography? Is there a principled distinction here? This is an important issue, but the Court, in its confusing decision, does not even acknowledge it. The final problem is the <i>exclusion of women.</i> While the Court seemed to acknowledge that pornography is a feminist issue, it maintained the traditional focus on <i>men.</i> Thus, most of the discussion of harm in <cite>Butler</cite> was concerned with the impact of pornography on men's attitudes and behaviour. However, Sopinka J. did note in passing that &quot;materials portraying women as a class of objects for sexual exploitation and abuse have a negative impact on the individual's sense of self-worth and  acceptance.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup> Nothing more was said about this. 
<p>
While the <cite>Butler</cite> decision was hailed by many feminists as a victory for women's equality, there are enough ambiguities and problems in the decision to warrant more suspicion than glee. For feminists, it is significant that the Supreme Court did not provide an adequate explanation of the extent and complexity of the harm to women resulting from pornography; it did not make the harm &quot;visible.&quot; What the Court did not consider was the third view of the harm, according to which pornography plays a constitutive role in the social construction of men's and women's subjectivities. Importantly, the Court could not easily have adopted such a view in light of the assumptions about the nature of language and expression underpinning its definition of the right to freedom of expression. Yet, I would like to argue that it is from this vantage point that the complexity and depth of pornography's harm can be made &quot;visible.&quot; 
<p>
The third view of harm characterizes pornography as a constitutive discourse that, although its meaning is not inherent, is given power and specific meaning within the context of a larger patriarchal system of discourses and the material experience of oppression and large-scale violence against women. It is part of the political struggle over the meaning of &quot;woman,&quot; &quot;man,&quot; and &quot;sexuality,&quot; and the relationship between these social constructs. In this way, the &quot;harm&quot; is not so much that we <i>learn</i> from pornography. Rather, the harm is the role pornography plays in the construction of powerful subject positions through which both men and women consciously live their lives, as well as its role in (re)creating and reinforcing the dominance of patriarchal discourses and their manifestations in institutions and social structures. This harm affects both individual women and women as a group.
<p>
In pornography, women are constructed as subordinate objects who enjoy being degraded and brutalized; men are constructed as dominant, aggressive, and the possessors of women for their own pleasure; sexuality is constructed in terms of asymmetrical power, violence, and exploitation. The social debate surrounding pornography has added to these the further subject positions of women as &quot;victims&quot; and men as the &quot;perpetrators&quot; of violence. As powerful subject positions, these constructions are incorporated into who we are---our subjectivities---and they thereby shape what we do, what we believe, and who we become. Constitutive of our identities, they influence our attitudes and behaviours in a way that cannot be reduced to causation. A further harm is that the pornographic message---which is in no way confined to what we label as &quot;pornography&quot;---is so
powerful, so dominant in our culture, that it has been accepted as somehow &quot;natural&quot; and &quot;true.&quot; Parading as truth, it has stifled the imaginations of both women and men to develop alternative
meanings and new subject positions through which we might live and think about our lives. Moreover, the dominant liberal discourse on the nature of language and the role of expression denies that such transformations and alternatives are even possible.
<p>
It is in <i>all</i> of these ways that pornography can be seen to &quot;silence&quot; and &quot;harm&quot; women.
<p>
This third view has been confused and distorted in the claims made by some feminist scholars who appear to have adopted it. Most notably, Catherine MacKinnon has asserted both that gender identities are socially constructed and that pornography plays a central role in the constitution of these identities.<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup> However, she has not made explicit the alternative theory of language on which her arguments rest, and this failure has served to undermine the cogency and coherence of her arguments. Indeed, she has continued to use the term &quot;causation&quot; to describe the link between pornography and attitudes of behaviour and violence,<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup> although she criticizes the particular form of
linear causation underpinning legal reasoning.<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup>
<p>
MacKinnon has argued that pornography &quot;<i>is</i> a form of forced sex, a practice of sexual politics, an institution of gender inequality [emphasis added].&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup> For her,
pornography has one meaning---a fixed meaning. More generally, she writes in terms of monolithic and unified meanings and identities, making bold assertions about &quot;men,&quot; &quot;women's experience,&quot; and &quot;the feminist perspective.&quot; What MacKinnon has not acknowledged is that identities that are socially constituted are neither unified nor rational, and that pornography, understood as a discourse, has no inherent meaning but, rather, is contingent and indeterminate. Indeed, not every man and woman is affected by pornography in the same way, as individuals are influenced differently by the relative power of discourses in their lives, by their access to alternative subject positions, and by their material circumstances which give authority to particular discourses and subject positions. Some women describe their experience of pornography as &quot;liberating,&quot; although others have been forced to act out violent and degrading scenes from pornographic films; some men resist its oppressive and sexist meaning, while others accept its message of male dominance.
<p>
It has been argued here that pornography does harm women as a group and it does harm some individual women, although not every woman and man is influenced by its message in the same way. The harm is not a physical and observable harm, but one that works from within by constituting our subjectivities. Through the construction of
powerful subject positions that define men as dominant and women as the objects of male pleasure, pornography works to reinforce the discourses and institutions of patriarchy. This harm has been made invisible by the dominant understanding of language, meaning, and expression which underpins the Supreme Court's definitions of freedom
of expression and harm.
<p>
Although pornography's harm has been made visible, it does not necessarily follow that the appropriate response to such harm is <i>censorship.</i> In the next section, I will consider the implications of characterizing pornography as a constitutive discourse for the debate within feminism about whether or not pornography should be legally prohibited---that is, censored.
<p>
<h3>A Feminist Poststructuralist Re-Thinking of the Censorship Debate</h3>

There is no single feminist voice on the meaning of pornography and, in turn, no single approach to what, if anything, should be done about it. The debate about how feminism should respond to pornography has focused mainly on the issue of censorship---that is, on whether or not pornography should be prohibited by legislation. Feminist perspectives on censorship are related to the various characterizations of harm, to the assumptions made about individuals and the nature of expression that underpin them, and to the meanings of the right to freedom of expression that these assumptions implicate. Thus, feminist opinion on censorship ranges from the belief that pornography is central to women's oppression and, given the inequality of freedom of expression, it must be subject to state control; through the understanding that pornography is against women's interests and must be campaigned
against without relying on the patriarchal state for protection; to a claim that pornography is merely representation and, unlike acts, cannot cause oppression and therefore does not constitute a valid reason for restricting expression. In light of the preceding discussion of the very real harms of pornography, the latter view must be seen as highly problematic and difficult to sustain. Moreover, as it is based on a set of assumptions that are fundamentally gendered, it is itself implicated in patriarchal discourses and structures. I will examine the first and second opinions in more detail, as they encompass much of the feminist debate, considering the strengths and weaknesses of each from the perspective set out above---that pornography is a constitutive discourse, and, as it has no inherent or fixed meaning, its influence on individual men and women is contingent.
<p>
The first opinion is typically associated with Catherine MacKinnon. As has been noted, she begins from the premise that pornography, as a form of sexual violence, is <i>central</i> to the institutionalization of patriarchy, which she sees as an all-embracing structure of misogyny. Moreover, MacKinnon asserts that we live in a &quot;pornographic culture,&quot; wherein the particular messages of pornography continuously spill over into mass culture, making degradation and violence against women the cultural norm. The right to freedom of expression, framed as it is in negative terms, is also understood as a constituent part of patriarchal power relations, as its assumption of equality of voice ignores the fact that women are not equal to men in their power to express their views and ideas. MacKinnon concludes that pornography must be censored.<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup>
<p>
Rather than starting with a focus on pornography, the second approach begins 
<blockquote>
. . . from the premise that feminism is a form of dissent which threatens a power structure based on male authority, male privilege, and male status. The patriarchal state can tolerate small equity reforms and adjustments advocated by feminists but, as the pressures for social change escalate, what feminists have most to fear is the censorship of themselves.<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup>
</blockquote>
From this perspective pornography is seen as only one of the many ways in which women are harmed by patriarchy, and the ultimate goal of liberating women from male dominance requires that the right to freedom of expression be supported by tolerating pornography and renouncing censorship.
<p>
Neither of these views is complete, and both rely on problematic assumptions. Furthermore, neither offers a full exploration of the <i>political implications</i> of the arguments asserted. First of all, the first view omits the insights of the second. The advocacy of censorship both neglects to discuss the importance of freedom of expression to feminist causes and fails to distinguish convincingly between pornography and the myriad of other patriarchal discourses that constitute and structure women's inequality. Some feminist authors, such as Naomi Wolf, have suggested that the imagery and meanings of &quot;soft porn,&quot; such as those found in <cite>Playboy</cite>, as well as the subject positions offered by women's magazines, advertising, and romance novels, are even more powerful in their influence on how women consciously live their lives.<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup> Because their oppressive meanings are less obvious, they are all the more insidious. If the exercise of power is located in language and meaning, and much of the harm resulting from pornography is the constitution of identities and subjectivities that reinforce male dominance, then drawing the line at pornography becomes problematic and somewhat arbitrary. Furthermore, as explicit sex remains the distinguishing feature of pornography, the dark shadow of &quot;social morality&quot; looms too close for comfort.
<p>
MacKinnon's approach is also problematic because it is grounded on an understanding of both patriarchy and pornography as monolithic and deterministic discourses and structures. In turn, she has unified and universalized their influence; all women become merely victims, and all men are deemed oppressors. In MacKinnon's work there seems to be &quot;an implicit assumption that somewhere and somehow there exists an unchanging and predefined female sexuality which is: romantic, egalitarian, natural, gentle, free of power dynamics, monogamous, emotional, nurturing and spontaneous.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> Also implicit is a view of men &quot;who have no self-reflection and whose engagement with the cultural complex is completely passive and
unselective.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup> As discussed above, this reductionism fails to take into
account the varying and contingent influence of pornography and patriarchy. Furthermore, it perpetuates and further fixes the dominant meanings of pornography, femininity, and masculinity---meanings that MacKinnon asserts are a cause of women's oppression. It is significant that the censorship of pornography further entrenches and institutionalizes these meanings in legal discourse, both in legislation and in judicial decisions. The <cite>Butler</cite> decision provides a telling example of this process.
<p>
MacKinnon's monolithic categories, then, are exclusive. Women who do not feel oppressed by pornography, or who experience it as liberating, are deemed once again to be &quot;victims,&quot; but this time of a false consciousness. Furthermore, in addressing the campaign against pornography from a supposedly united female subjectivity, MacKinnon assumes that women are oppressed first and foremost by a universal patriarchy, unmediated by race, class, sexual orientation, or history. Her premises do not allow for an analysis of how other modes of oppression intersect with gender in the discourse of pornography. For Black women, who historically have been constructed
as more primitive and more sexual, there is an important racial dimension in pornography that stereotypes Black female sexuality in images received by white men and women.<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup> For lesbians, who have had their erotica expropriated by hostile law enforcers, censorship and any definition of pornography for legislative purposes is replete with dangers.
<p>
The important point here is that any advocacy of censorship, whether through criminal legislation or civil legislation (as in the Minneapolis Ordinances authored by MacKinnon and Andrea Dworkin), denies and represses the disunity within feminism and among women on the meaning of pornography. It also fails to consider the political alliances that are implicated by reliance on legislation. Conservative groups can agree with feminists that pornography degrades and harms women because, for them, women's sexuality outside the family is itself seen as cheapened and degraded. Thus, while legislation might be enacted that seems clear on its face, the indeterminacy of <i>its</i> meaning raises the question of who has the ultimate power to determine its meaning. Who will interpret the legislation? Who will enforce it? As Lisa Duggan has argued, &quot;[I]t is the alignment of political and cultural forces that gives meaning to issues and laws.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup> A feminist law of censorship, once enacted, is subject to these influences. Thus, restrictive laws must be approached with caution.
<p>
The second view of pornography and censorship, which emphasizes the need for freedom of expression, is rendered problematic by the failure to grapple with the power relations structured by freedom of expression as it has been interpreted by the courts. There is little if any recognition of women's unequal voice and the ways in which pornography and other patriarchal discourses &quot;silence&quot; women. There is little discussion of how a negative right to freedom of expression maintains existing power relations between, on the one hand, those who do have free expression and, on the other, those who do not because their subjectivities have been shaped in ways that
support the status quo, and because they have little socio-economic power to assert their opinions in the &quot;market-place of ideas.&quot; Indeed, by advocating freedom of expression without a critical analysis of the assumptions that are thereby reproduced, feminists who adopt this view, while ultimately seeking to liberate women, may be subverting this goal by their reliance on a set of assumptions that are gendered and that do not allow the harms of pornography and other discourses to be adequately understood. This approach, which implicitly accepts the theory of language underpinning freedom of expression doctrine, can comprehend the harm of pornography only in terms of causation; it cannot begin to see the constitutive nature of its message, the indeterminacy of its meaning, and its influence on women as an oppressed group.
<p>
I would like to suggest that the emphasis on the question of censorship has resulted in a static and often polarized debate. In part, this is the result of the failure by advocates of both positions---pro-censorship and anti-censorship---to take seriously the political-strategic implications of their views. Moreover, it is the result of a failure to assess critically the right to freedom of expression itself, particularly the view of language and of the individual that defines its doctrinal purposes and limits. What neither approach offers is the possibility of breaking out of this bounded debate---the possibility of meaningful alternatives. Neither, through the assumptions they implicitly or explicitly accept, provides for the possibility and means of effective resistance. MacKinnon's view closes off the possibility of resistance by conceptualizing both pornography and patriarchy as a unified all-encompassing discursive structure, and by defining all women as victims and all men as perpetrators. As victims of this monolithic
structure, what can women possibly do to challenge pornography, other than turn to the state for protection? For advocates of freedom of expression, resistance means &quot;more speech&quot;---countering the falsehoods of pornography with truths about women so that men of Reason will change their attitudes and behaviours toward women. This position neglects women's structural and material inequality, thereby avoiding the very real problem of women's lack of access to the institutions and the resources necessary to generate powerful alternatives. That pornography is simply false and that there exists some &quot;truth&quot; about women's sexuality is a claim that has been shown to be illusory. Furthermore, the reliance on Reason is both illusory and gendered. Indeed, by accepting the view of language implicated in the right to freedom of expression, these feminists deny that pornography might be indeterminate and contingent in its meaning. They locate the problem of political change in the nature of the separate (autonomous) individual herself, in her self-knowledge, and in her struggle to find her true nature, rather than in language and social relationships.
<p>
It is in the indeterminacy of meaning---that is, in the understanding that language is not unified, fixed, and external, but a site of political struggle over meaning---that the key to resistance lies. It is from this vantage point that feminists can begin to articulate alternative meanings of both the pornographic message and the right to freedom of expression, meanings that will promote women's liberation from patriarchal oppression.
<p>
Robin West has adopted the view that pornography is indeterminate in its meaning, and she has sought to draw out some of the possible implications of this indeterminacy.<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup> She suggests that pornography engenders contradictory meanings for women. On the one hand, it presents a threat of violence which is supported by women's material experience in our society. On the other, it offers the promise of pleasure. Both the threat and the promise are made simultaneously. The dominant meaning of pornography depends on who is looking at it. Thus, some women will experience pornography as liberating, while others will find it harmful. West further suggests that it is through this contradiction that the power of pornography, and the hierarchies it reinforces, are maintained. The promise of pornography serves to legitimate the inequality of power that it helps to structure by constructing the female self and sexuality as finding pleasure in violence; the threat serves as an instrument of patriarchal power. Both the threat and the promise work within a belief system that tells women <i>at the same time</i> that words and images cannot cause harm and that pornography does indeed lead to violence. Again, the message is contradictory.
<p>
For West, this contradiction presents women with the opportunity to transform the meaning of pornography. Women, she argues, can seize upon the liberating promise of pleasure and rewrite the meaning of those constructs that pornography attempts to fix---rewrite them in such a way as to ensure compliance with the promise. It is
acknowledged, however, that this is no easy task, as the dominance of pornography has constrained both women's and men's imagination of alternative discourses on sexuality and gender identity. She suggests that one way to struggle against the dominance is to fight the meanings pornography constructs,
<blockquote>
. . . but another way is by fighting the dominance of the pornographic imagination. We do the latter by ending our own silence. We fight the dominance of the pornographic imagination in the same way we fight the dominance of other forms of legal ideology---by understanding its content, its history, its source, and its contingency in our lives, and then by exercising our censored, suppressed and silenced imagination, by generating our own sexual imagery, by becoming our own sexual authority, and thereby repossessing our own sexual world.<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Chris Weedon has made a similar argument. She suggests that one of the important ways in which power is exercised is through language and meaning, and, in turn, through the constitution of subjectivity within discourse and the production of social agents. By recognizing language, meaning, and subjectivity as important ways of exercising power, women can begin to resist particular subject positions. However, like West, she argues that resistance must take place from an alternative subject position. What is needed is alternative subjectivities and discourses on women's---and men's---sexualities. Yet, largely preoccupied with the pornography and censorship debate, feminists have effectively reproduced the dominance of pornography while neglecting to imagine <i>who else</i> men and women might be and become. Many of those who advocate censorship seem to have assumed that once the pornographic message is locked away, women will be free to express their own meanings. This belief stems from an assumption that women have some essential feminine sexuality. If, on the other hand, one believes that individuals have no inherent nature and their experience has no pre-given meaning, change will not come about without women having access to alternative discourses and subjectivities. Merely telling women and men that pornography is false does not provide such alternatives.<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> Indeed, the discourse on pornography needs to be refocused---it needs to move away from the sterile debate about censorship versus freedom of expression to consider the actual and possible sexualities and identities of women <i>in all their variety.</i>
<p>
These arguments suggest several important implications for the debate about what to do about pornography. The first is that censorship alone is passive, negative, and unconstructive. As such, it does not allow women to exercise power. Rather, it places them in the protective hands of the patriarchal state. The second is, as Weedon points out, that the most powerful discourses have firm material and institutional bases. Change at the subjective level of consciousness is limited by material relationships and practices. This suggests that women are not silenced by pornography alone, but also by an institutional structure and a media system that exclude them. The strategy of resistance through alternative discourses is rendered problematic by women's lack of access to the means of having
these alternatives heard.
<p>
Women, then, are confronted with an apparently fundamental dilemma. On the one hand, pornography and patriarchy are open to resistance through language and expression; on the other hand, women do not have the material bases for asserting powerful discourses of resistance. I would like to suggest that the alternative
conceptualizations of language, expression, and the individual presented here provide a possible way out of this dilemma---through a transformation of the meaning of the right to freedom of expression itself. As in the case of autonomy, freedom of expression is a value that is important to feminism, as women struggle to change meanings
and develop alternative discourses. In Weedon's words: &quot;In rewriting the meaning of the feminine or of `femaleness,' feminists make language the site of a struggle over meaning which is a prerequisite for political change.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> Censorship or any other restrictions on the right to freedom of expression only serve to limit the right and stand at odds with an effort to expand the right to be more inclusive of women.
<p>
What women need as they struggle for liberation is a <i>positive right</i> to free expression, a right that will empower them to demand access to the means of expression and permit them to voice alternative meanings and subject positions. In articulating such a positive right, we must redefine the purposes of the right to freedom of expression, rejecting their current incarnations and formulating them in light of the alternative view of human expression set out above. Framed as a negative right, freedom of expression serves the interests of the already powerful. Furthermore, by re-creating a particular set of assumptions about expression and the individual, the dominant meaning of freedom of expression obscures the power relations that it helps to structure and masks the harms in which patriarchal discourses---including pornography---result. In the next section, I will suggest what a (re)visioned right to freedom of expression might begin to look like.
<p>
<h3>Towards a (Re)Vision of the Right to Freedom of Expression</h3>

It has been argued that the doctrinal purposes of freedom of expression are premised on a set of assumptions about individuals, language, and society that are overly simplistic, deceiving, and gendered. The assumptions, however, are powerful ones, and the seeming inevitability of their particular meanings is reinforced by their incorporation into social structures and institutions, including law. Even though it might be acknowledged that the assumptions do not hold true in particular cases, they are held out as ideals and goals that can be realized, in part, through the promotion of free expression. In this way, freedom of expression &quot;comprehends a vision of society, a faith and a whole way of life.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup> It offers the promise of the good life---a promise of a society characterized by equality, individual self-fulfilment and autonomy, democracy, reason, and stability---if individuals are not restrained in their freedom of expression. In the context of the assumptions of this liberal vision, the promise seems plausible. However, when the assumptions and purposes of freedom of expression are themselves exposed as illusory, the promise falls flat. As in the case of pornography, the promise of freedom of expression can be appropriated by women seeking to change meanings and relationships of power. A demand can be made that the promises be met. To support such a demand, an alternative articulation of the purposes of freedom of expression is needed---an alternative premised on an understanding of the individual as socially constituted through relationships, language, and material circumstances.
<p>
Each of the three core purposes of the freedom of expression---truth-seeking, democracy, and individual self-fulfilment---can be re-stated in light of the arguments set out in this article. First, it has been asserted that there are no social truths to be found through free expression in an equal market-place of ideas. The goal of free expression cannot be the search for truth. Instead, one purpose of the right to freedom of expression must be <i>the constant questioning of claims to truth.</i> The problem here is not that falsehoods must be challenged so that truth will emerge, but that <i>some meanings are held out to be true.</i> The contingency and indeterminacy of these proposed &quot;truths,&quot; as well as the power that supports them, are obscured by the faith in truth. As a result, other ideas and perspectives, notably those with less power and fewer material and institutional resources behind them, are marginalized. Indeed, the universalizing nature of &quot;truths&quot; works to silence competing claims. In this way, the belief in the ideal of truth serves to <i>undermine</i> free expression. Although Mill argued that even if an idea represented the &quot;whole truth&quot; it must still be contested so it can be known rationally, the suggestion here is that it is not the truth or falsity of any idea that must be revealed through the clash of ideas, but, rather, the contingency of all meanings. An alternative purpose of freedom of expression, then, is to allow for meanings to be contested in the context of both an awareness of their contingency and an understanding of language as the site of political struggle over meaning. Importantly, as this alternative purpose acknowledges the role of power in fixing meanings, it underscores the need for an affirmative right to free expression, providing those who have less power to voice their views with the means to participate fully in the struggle to shape the world and themselves through language.
<p>
The purpose of promoting democracy rests on the assumption that all individuals have equal freedom of expression in the absence of governmental constraint. Given this equality, free expression promotes democracy by enabling everyone to participate in social decision-making processes. As in the case of truth, the assumption of equality masks real disparities in the power of discourses and access to the means of voicing opinions and ideas. In light of existing inequalities, and both social and judicial recognition of these, freedom of expression must be understood to encompass a positive right of access to resources and the media. Such a positive right would focus attention on questions of media ownership and control, and on the barriers to women's access.
<p>
Finally, the purpose of enabling individual self-fulfilment is premised on the assumption of autonomy, as well as a view of language as existing separate from individuals and expression as a means of developing an inherent individual personality. Yet, it has been argued that individuals are not autonomous. We are connected through our relationships and through language and meaning, all of which play a central role in the social construction of our
subjectivity and consciousness. An alternative purpose of free expression might be to promote a wider range of discourses and subject positions through which individuals can give meaning to their experiences and consciously live their lives. Again, the seemingly natural quality of dominant subject positions must be contested and resisted. 
<p>
This idea implicates another purpose of the right to freedom of expression that is less frequently articulated: the fostering of diversity and pluralism in society. According to this purpose, freedom of expression &quot;provides a key means for individuals and groups to exercise and manifest to others their cultural and ideological diversity. It aids in the fostering of a society in which individuals and groups can feel freer to be different.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup> This is indeed an important goal of free expression, but without acknowledging that difference is socially constructed through language and meaning in ways that create and re-create hierarchies and the oppression of difference, and without exposing the exercise of power through language, freedom of expression as it is currently interpreted will not promote this goal.
<p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>

This paper has attempted to assess critically the assumptions underlying the judicial interpretation of the right to freedom of expression as guaranteed in s. 2(b) of the <cite>Charter</cite>, in light of the confounding issue of pornography. It has been argued that these assumptions are illusory and gendered, and, moreover, that they serve to re-create patriarchal power relations by masking both the exercise of power through language and the  &quot;harm&quot; in which expression can result. By reinterpreting the purposes of the right to freedom of expression, the value of this right is reaffirmed. It is because meanings are not fixed or determinate that language and meaning become important sites of political struggle. Thus, for women and other oppressed groups, the most pressing need is to articulate alternative discourses and to have access to the means to do so. It has been suggested that freedom of expression, if it is to fulfil its promises of a democratic, pluralistic society of &quot;equals,&quot; must be understood to encompass a positive right.
<p>
Of course, as a positive right, freedom of expression will not necessarily be legally enforceable. Given the current judicial retreat from an activist stance to the <cite>Charter</cite>'s guarantees and the move toward increasing deference to governmental objectives, the likelihood of judicial intervention to affirm more expression for oppressed groups is small indeed. However, even a position of deference does not preclude a judicial recognition of an alternative vision of freedom of expression. Judicial and social recognition of a positive right would give women a powerful tool for political resistance and lobbying.
<p>
The question of censorship must be reassessed from this alternative perspective. The current debate has been conducted largely within the parameters of the dominant interpretation of the right to freedom of expression. Importantly, censorship or any other restriction on expression, even if understood as a short-term remedy, seems to go against and possibly even undermine the call for a broader and more comprehensive right upon which active  resistance can be based. The strategy of resistance outlined here is a long-term and largely political one. I would suggest, however, that such a strategy can best serve the feminist goal of women's liberation. Not only does it enable the empowerment of women through expression and action, but it allows for the inclusion of <i>all</i> women's voices; sexuality is not defined by a monolithic interpretation of the meaning of pornography. Finally, it also permits the inclusion of men in the struggle for more constructive identities and relationships. Characterizing all men as oppressors, or ignoring each man's role in the construction of meanings, is not politically useful. 
<p><br><hr><p>
