<li><a name="seventy2"><i>Ibid.</i> at 482.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventy3"><i>Ibid.</i> at 483.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventy4"><i>Ibid.</i> at 483.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventy5"><i>Ibid.</i></a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventy6"><i>Ibid.</i> at 479.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventy7"><i>Supra</i> note 22.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventy8"><i>Ibid.</i> at 147.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="seventy9"><i>Ibid.</i> at 156.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="eighty"><i>Ibid.</i> at 148.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="eighty1">MacKinnon</a> has in fact argued that pornography cannot be reformed or suppressed or banned---it can only be changed. However, as evidenced by her drafting of the Minneapolis Ordinances which seek to reconceptualize pornography as an equality issue within the context of American jurisprudence which has not yet recognized it as such, in the final analysis she is promoting the prohibition of pornographic material, although she would place the impetus for prohibition in the hands of women rather than the state. As some critics have pointed out, this approach does not really place power in the hands of women, but maintains a relationship of dependence on
the patriarchal state for enforcement.
<p>
<li><a name="eighty2">T. McCormack,</a> &quot;Must We Censor Pornography? Civil Liberties and Feminist Jurisprudence&quot; in David Schneiderman, ed., <cite>Freedom of Expression and the Charter</cite> (Toronto: Thomson Professional Publishing, Canada, 1991) at 78.
<p>
<li><a name="eighty3">N. Wolf, <cite>The Beauty Myth</cite> (Toronto: Random House, 1990).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="eighty4">P. Parmar,</a> &quot;Rage and Desire: Confronting Pornography,&quot; in G. Chester &amp; J. Dickey, eds., <cite>Feminism and Censorship: The Current Debate</cite> (Bridport, Dorset: Prism Press, 1988) 124, quoting McKinnon.
<p>
<li><a name="eighty5">M. McIntosh,</a> &quot;Liberalism and the Contradictions of Sexual Politics,&quot; in L. Segal &amp; M. McIntosh, eds., <cite>Sex Exposed: Sexuality and the Pornography Debate</cite> (London: Virago Press, 1992) 160.
<p>
<li><a name="eighty6">Parmar, <i>supra</i> note 84.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="eighty7">L. Duggan,</a> &quot;Censorship in the Name of Feminism&quot; in <cite>Feminism and Censorship</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 84 at 85.
<p>
<li><a name="eighty8">R. West,</a> &quot;Pornography as a Legal Text&quot; in S. Gubar &amp; J. Hoff, eds., <cite>For Adult Users Only</cite> (Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 1989).
<p>
<li><a name="eighty9"><i>Ibid.</i> at 129.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="ninety">It should</a> be noted here that the possibility of resistance by women provides a basis for
distinguishing child pornography. Children have not yet developed a command of language, a comprehension of the nature of expression and meaning, or a material basis from which to assert alternative subjectivities. Thus, they do not have the means to resist the power of the exploitative message of child pornography. Prohibitive legislation may be the appropriate response in this case.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety1"><i>Supra</i> note 43 at 9.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="ninety2">Emerson, <i>supra</i> note 5 at 886.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="ninety3">Lepofsky, <i>supra</i> note 4 at 11.</a>
</ol><p><br>
