<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 52 No. 1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>[<A HREF="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol52#1">Volume 52 Number 1</A>]</CENTER>
<P><BR>
<H1>Same-Sex Spousal Benefits and the Evolving Conception of Family<a href="#note">*</a>
<p>
PETER RUSK</H1>
<P>
<i>This paper explores the discrimination faced by same-sex couples claiming spousal benefits and is divided into three parts: Part I, which surveys the extent and origin of this discrimination; Part II, which analyses the protection afforded by the</i> Charter<i>; and Part III, which discusses tactical considerations relevant to those seeking to redress this inequity. The author illustrates how this denial of entitlement emanates as much from discriminatory judicial reasoning as it does from discriminatory legislation. It is also shown how this discrimination is reflective of the entrenchment of male-heterosexual privilege in our society and the idealization of the conventional family form.
Although arguments which focus on &quot;dismantling&quot; the &quot;family&quot; are acknowledged as being integral in effecting long-term change, it is argued that &quot;sameness&quot; or &quot;inclusion&quot; arguments are necessary to effect an initial shift in the status quo conception of family.
<p>
Cet article examine la discrimination &agrave; laquelle les couples du m&ecirc;me sexe font face lorsqu'ils r&eacute;clament les avantages sociaux dont b&eacute;n&eacute;ficient les couples h&eacute;t&eacute;rosexuels. Ce texte est divis&eacute; en trois parties: la premi&egrave;re partie se veut &ecirc;tre un survol de l'&eacute;tendu et des origines de cette discrimination; la deuxi&egrave;me partie analyse la protection qu'offre la</i> Charte canadienne des droits et libert&eacute;s<i>; et la troisi&egrave;me partie examine les consid&eacute;rations tactiques pertinentes pour ceux qui veulent redresser ces injustices. L'auteur d&eacute;montre que les difficult&eacute;s d'acc&egrave;s aux avantages sociaux pour les couples du m&ecirc;me sexe provient autant de d&eacute;cisions juridiques discriminatoires que proviennent, selon l'auteur, de lois discriminatoires. Cette forme de discrimination refl&egrave;te la r&eacute;pandu du privil&egrave;ge dont b&eacute;n&eacute;ficient les hommes h&eacute;t&eacute;rosexuels dans notre soci&eacute;t&eacute; et l'id&eacute;alisation de la famille conventionelle. Tandis que l'auteur est d'accord avec ceux qui disent qu'il faut &quot;d&eacute;manteler&quot; la  &quot;famille&quot; pour effectuer des changements &agrave; long terme, il propose que les arguments qui s'appuient sur la &quot;similarit&eacute;&quot; et &quot;l'inclusion&quot; sont n&eacute;cessaire pour engendrer une transformation initiale dans la conception que nous avons maintenant de la famille.</i>
<p><br>

<h3>Introduction</h3>

In Canada, same-sex couples are discriminated against <i>vis-&agrave;-vis</i> opposite-sex couples. Same-sex couples are denied benefits available to opposite-sex couples and thus are discouraged from forming functional families.<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> This discrimination is perpetuated not only by legislative exclusions but also by a judiciary that often interprets legislation in a discriminatory manner. In order to effectively redress this pervasive unfairness it is necessary not only to clearly identify areas of discrimination but also to recognize their entrenched male heterosexist roots. In addition, it is necessary to address perhaps the more problematic issue of <i>how</i>, once exposed, this discrimination can be remedied.<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> The underlying theme of this &quot;how-to&quot; debate concerns whether equity can best be achieved by arguing for the inclusion of same-sex couples in the &quot;conventional family,&quot; and hence its benefits, or whether it is preferable to opt for an approach that is more active in deconstructing an institution many see as inherently oppressive and exclusionary.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup>
<p>
<h3>I.   Discrimination on the Basis of Sexual Orientation</h3>

The politics of sexual orientation have resulted in the perpetuation of dichotomies that attribute certain characteristics to same-sex couples and other, usually opposite, characteristics to opposite-sex couples. The attributes associated with opposite-sex couples are, for example, mutual dependence, stability, nurturing, childbearing, child rearing, and monogamy. The attributes associated with same-sex couples are independence, instability, autonomy, the inability to bear or properly raise children, and polygamy. Such dichotomous characterizations serve to rationalize the exclusion of same-sex couples from legislative schemes that accord benefits to opposite-sex couples.
<p>
In order for these characterizations to be &quot;effective&quot; in their perpetuation of this disadvantage, it is necessary that the two sets of attributes be viewed as opposite and mutually exclusive.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> As such, there is no room for the consideration of innovative family forms. There is only good and bad, right and wrong. The attributes associated with conventional families are valued; those associated with same-sex couples are devalued. Conventional families are cast as idealistic havens in a foreboding
world, while same-sex couples are cast as being devoid of those positive &quot;family&quot; attributes, as being part of the &quot;cold&quot; world.
<p>
It is clear that although conventional families are generally idealized, especially as compared with same-sex families, they at the same time serve as the site of much of the oppression faced by women.<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> Women are characterized as possessing attributes that make them best suited to the private or family sphere, freeing men to participate in the public or labour sphere. Since women's work in the home is not valued, they are not paid, further reinforcing their &quot;dependence.&quot;  Viewed in this manner, it becomes clear that by threatening conventional families, the pursuit of same-sex spousal equality threatens not only heterosexual privilege, but <i>male</i> heterosexual privilege.
<p>
The denial of same-sex benefits, and the related judicial reasoning discussed below, should be understood and interpreted in this light. The &quot;protection&quot; of male heterosexist power lies at the root of the legislative and judicial discrimination faced by same-sex couples. It accounts for what appear to be strained attempts at effective judicial reasoning as well as the rationalizations given by governments for the exclusion of same-sex couples from benefit plans and human rights protection. This discrimination is a product of ingrained and pervasive oppression. Since the advent of Judeo-Christianity, male-dominated heterosexuality, as a social structure, has been the unquestioned norm.<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> And because it has become the &quot;norm,&quot; those who are &quot;different&quot; are marginalized.
<p>
Paradoxically, however, the threat that same-sex families pose to the conventional family form is juxtaposed against the threat that the conventional family form poses to same-sex couples. Because it is the norm, the ideology of the conventional family threatens to subsume the reality and uniqueness of same-sex families. For example, faced with a prejudiced judiciary, same-sex couples are often forced to employ &quot;sameness&quot; arguments in order to secure benefits traditionally available to opposite-sex couples. From another perspective, the legislative and judicial favouritism accorded to opposite-sex couples, combined with greater social approval of that which is &quot;the norm,&quot; makes it more attractive for many lesbians and gays to adopt the norm and deny their sexuality. However, despite the ability of same-sex couples to adopt most of the trappings of opposite-sex coupledom, sexuality remains a difference.<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup>
<p>
Some lesbian and gay theorists argue that by seeking equal status as &quot;spouses,&quot; same-sex couples are implicitly perpetuating prevailing modes of heterosexist thinking. Although this debate is analysed in Part III, it is useful at this point to note that the perspective taken in this article is that &quot;the family&quot; is an evolving, and not static, institution. As a result of fighting stereotypes and seeking inclusion, advocates of lesbian and gay
rights will fundamentally transform the social and legislative conception of what constitutes an appropriate family unit. As it becomes more pluralistic and inclusive, &quot;the family&quot; will become a less oppressive institution.
<p>
Part I constitutes the first segment of this analysis and limits itself to a survey of the discrimination faced by same-sex couples. It is important to emphasize that the differential treatment described below amounts to discrimination, not merely distinction.<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> As McIntyre J. stated in <cite>Andrews v. Law Society of British Columbia</cite>, 
<blockquote>
[D]iscrimination may be described as a distinction, whether intentional or not but based on grounds relating to personal characteristics of the individual or group, which has the effect of imposing burdens, obligations, or disadvantages on such individual or group not imposed upon others, or which withholds or limits access to opportunities, benefits, and advantages available to other members of society.<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup>
</blockquote>
As will be seen throughout this article, judges resort to stereotypical assumptions about same-sex couples to conclude that since they are unlike opposite-sex couples, it is defensible to treat them differently. Yet without such things as spousal pension benefits, statutory mechanisms of dispute resolution, and family crisis leave, same-sex couples are denied the tools available to opposite-sex couples that aid in the formation of functional family units. 
<p>
A. WHO CAN AND CANNOT MARRY
<p>
In Canada, the federal government has the jurisdiction to enact laws regarding who can and cannot marry.<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> These requirements, known as essential validity marriage requirements, have never been
comprehensively defined by the federal government and, consequently, there is no specific prohibition of same-sex
marriages.<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> The common law nevertheless requires that individuals be of
the opposite sex.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup>
<p>
When the invalidity of an essential requirement is established, such marriages are declared <i>void ab initio</i>, never to have occurred. This <i>de facto</i> prohibition against same-sex marriages is a message to same-sex couples that these relationships are not worthy of social legitimation.
<p>
On a more practical level, the result of the inability to marry is that same-sex partners are not automatically considered to be &quot;spouses,&quot; but rather are subjected to judicial and administrative interpretations of what it means to be a &quot;spouse.&quot;  Some of the legislation mentioned in the following sections clearly stipulates that &quot;spouses&quot; must be two people of the opposite sex;<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> however most simply refers to &quot;spouses,&quot; with no defining section.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> In the former situation, there is a clear unwillingness to declare opposite-sex provisions unconstitutional. When afforded the discretion to determine what &quot;spouse&quot; means, judges tend to define the term in a discriminatory way, referring to other heterosexist legislative and dictionary definitions to support their assertions.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> Much, if not most, of the inequitable treatment described below would be immediately undercut if same-sex couples were given the option to marry or, in other words, the ability to become &quot;spouses.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup>
<p>
B. IMMIGRATION
<p>
At present, the <cite>Immigration Act</cite>'s stated purpose of &quot;facilitat[ing] the reunion in Canada of Canadian citizens and permanent residents with their close relatives from abroad&quot; is limited to the reunification of married spouses, fianc&eacute;s and fianc&eacute;es, parents, grandparents, children, adopted children, grandchildren, brothers and sisters, and nieces and nephews.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> Although individual gays and lesbians are no longer barred from entering Canada,<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> they are unable to sponsor lesbian and gay partners for the purpose of immigrating to Canada.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> However, applications for immigration can be approved on &quot;humanitarian and compassionate grounds.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup>
<p>
C. SOCIAL ASSISTANCE
<p>
In this area of provincial legislation, same-sex couples are actually at an advantage, but for unfortunate reasons. When an individual's &quot;need&quot; for social assistance<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup> is tested, a welfare caseworker will take into account whether there is a &quot;spouse&quot; on whom the claimant can rely for support. If the claimant is a woman, a male &quot;spouse&quot; is often assumed to be sharing his income with her,
irrespective of whether this is the actual situation. Whether or not the man is a &quot;spouse&quot; and hence supporting the claimant is often based on considerations as trivial as whether the two are having sexual relations.<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> The statutory scheme reflects the presumption that opposite-sex relationships are caring, supportive, and interdependent. As same-sex relationships are presupposed to have none of these characteristics, support between same-sex partners is deemed to exist less frequently.<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup>
<p>
D. FAMILY EMERGENCIES
<p>
The ability of family members to help one another in crisis situations is a crucial component in the development and maintenance of family bonds. Opposite-sex couples benefit from statutes that confer rights and benefits when such situations occur. Notable exceptions to this rule are Ontario's <cite>Substitute Decisions Act, 1992</cite><sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> and <cite>Consent to Treatment Act, 1992</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> Both Acts define &quot;partners&quot; as 
<blockquote>
[persons who] have lived together for at least one year and have a close personal relationship that is of primary importance in both persons' lives.<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Nevertheless, if one partner should die, the surviving same-sex partner could not collect benefits pursuant to the <cite>Workers' Compensation Act</cite><sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> or the <cite>Compensation for Victims of Crime Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> It is even questionable whether a same-sex partner is entitled to leave from work to attend the funeral of his or her lover. The Supreme Court of Canada recently ruled that Brian Mossop was not entitled to funeral leave to attend the funeral of his partner's father on the grounds that his partner, and hence his partner's father, were not &quot;immediate family members&quot; as provided for in the governing collective agreement.<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> The case arose out of a challenge brought by Mossop that this denial violated the provision of the <cite>Canadian Human Rights Act</cite> [<cite>CHRA</cite>] that prohibits discrimination on the basis of family status.<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> Mossop's appeal to the Supreme Court of Canada was denied on the grounds that discrimination on the basis of family status cannot be interpreted to include discrimination against same-sex couples since at the time of the inclusion of the family status ground in 1983, Parliament specifically decided not to include sexual orientation as a prohibited ground of discrimination.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup>
<p>
It is important to note that Mossop narrowed the scope of the appeal by not raising any  <cite>Charter</cite><sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> issues and in particular by not referring to the <cite>Birch</cite> decision, which read sexual orientation into the <cite>CHRA</cite>.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup> The appeal was confined to whether same-sex couples constituted a family under the
<cite>CHRA</cite> and thus whether there was discrimination on the basis of family status.<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> Given that the Court failed to read a human rights document in a broad and purposive manner, it is unlikely that the Court would be any more flexible in interpreting other types of statutes when determining whether same-sex partners are &quot;spouses&quot; or whether they constitute a &quot;family.&quot;
<p>
E. INCOME TAX ACT
<p>
The <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> [<cite>ITA</cite>] contains provisions that accord benefits based on spousal status.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> Despite early reluctance,<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> the federal government has recently amended the <cite>ITA</cite> to specifically define the term &quot;spouse&quot; to include common law, opposite-sex couples.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> Same-sex couples cannot benefit from provisions such as those relating to spousal tax credits;<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> inter-spousal transfers of unused pension, education, and disability credits;<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> and registered retirement savings plans.<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> It is interesting to note how these
&quot;transfers&quot; benefit one-income families,<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> promoting the stereotypically conventional family in which there is one (male) breadwinner.
<p>
F. PENSIONS
<p>
Statutory pension schemes in Canada account for the existence of opposite-sex marriages or partnerships only.<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup> For example, the term &quot;spouse&quot; in the <cite>Public
Service Pension Act</cite> is defined as 
<blockquote>
either of a man or a woman who,
<p>
(a) are married to each other, or
<p>
(b) are not married to each other and are living together in a conjugal relationship 
<blockquote>
(i) continuously for a period of not less than three years or
<p>
(ii) in a relationship of some permanence, if they are the natural or adoptive parents, as defined in the Family Law Act, 1986, of a child.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup>
</blockquote></blockquote>
This statute was recently successfully challenged<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> as being in violation of the
<cite>Ontario Human Rights Code</cite> provision protecting against discrimination based on sexual  orientation.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup>
<p>
A recent <cite>Charter</cite> challenge of similar pension provisions was not, however, as successful. James Egan and John Nesbit failed in their s. 15 <cite>Charter</cite> challenge of the <cite>Old Age Security Act</cite>, which also excludes same-sex couples.<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> The <cite>Old Age Security Act</cite> defines &quot;spouse&quot; as 
<blockquote>
a person of the opposite sex who is living with that person, having lived with that person for at least one year, if the two persons have publicly represented themselves as husband and wife.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The trial judge, in denying their suit, used the logic that since Egan and Nesbit did not fall into the category of &quot;spouses,&quot; they were not entitled to the same treatment as other (married and common law) spouses.<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> This ruling was affirmed at the Federal Court of Appeal for similar reasons.<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup>
<p>
G. CUSTODY
<p>
In Ontario, child custody disputes are resolved according to what would be &quot;in the best interests of the child.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> The <cite>Children's Law Reform Act</cite> instructs judges to use, among others, the following criteria in evaluating the custody ruling that would be in the best interest of the child: the permanence and stability of the family unit in which it is proposed that the child will live; the relationship between the child and the person claiming custody; current and proposed living arrangements; and any past conduct relevant to the proposed custodian's ability to act as a parent.<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup> The <cite>Divorce Act</cite>, which applies to custody disputes that arise out of divorce, states similar criteria.<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup>
<p>
These &quot;best interest&quot; criteria are problematic for same-sex parents for two principal reasons. First, judges may be unwilling to consider a same-sex partnership as a &quot;stable family unit,&quot; adhering to the dichotomous conception that same-sex relationships are fleeting and unstable whereas opposite-sex relationships are stable and nurturing. And, as Katherine Arnup notes, because same-sex couples often have to stay secretive about their relationships, it is more difficult to offer conclusive evidence as to the permanence of such relationships.<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup>
<p>
Second, judicial discretion determines the extent to which homosexual conduct is considered to affect a parent's ability to parent. Although some judges pay lip service to the fact that being gay or lesbian is not a relevant consideration in determining child custody, many decisions indicate that sexual orientation is often considered
to be a negative factor. For example, in <cite>Bezaire v. Bezaire</cite>, Arnup J. states that &quot;(i)n my view homosexuality . . . is not in itself a ground for refusing custody&quot; but then qualifies this by stating that 
<blockquote>
It would be wrong to lay down any general rule as to the weight to be given to the evidence of homosexuality on the part of one of the parents. As I have said, in each case it is an aspect which the trial judge, upon hearing the evidence, must consider but from the aspect of the effect or likely effect upon the welfare of the children.<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In this case, Arnup J. was deferring to a trial judge who had stated that
<blockquote>
[I]t will be a condition of the custody order that no other person shall reside with Mrs. Bezaire without the approval of the court . . . I have indicated that I am attempting to improve the situation and that includes negativing any open, declared and avowed lesbian or homosexual relationship.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Like the trial judge in <cite>Bezaire</cite>, most judges are relatively straightforward about the inferences they draw from the finding that a parent is gay or lesbian. In <cite>Bernhardt v. Bernhardt</cite>, Hamilton J., in awarding custody to the father, stated that &quot;[t]he child clearly wishes to stay with her mother, <i>but</i>
the mother appears committed to a lesbian relationship, is unemployed and is given to heavy drinking, violence and
profanity&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> (emphasis added). In <cite>K. v. K.</cite>, Rowe J. states that &quot;Mrs. K.'s homosexuality is, in my opinion, no more of a bar to her obtaining custody than is the fact of Mr K.'s drug use.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> The inappropriateness of these comparisons aside, being lesbian or gay was determined in <cite>K. v. K.</cite> to be a lesser impediment than drug use, although the judge was satisfied that Mrs K.'s lesbian relationship &quot;will be discreet and will not be flaunted to the children or to the community at large.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup>
<p>
Paradoxically, the amount of judicial discretion afforded to judges to determine what is in the best interest of children has been unfavourable for lesbian and gay parents and, in turn, not in the best interests of the children. This discretion permits Courts to adhere to dichotomous views of relationships: opposite-sex relationships are nurturing and provide for good role models, same-sex relationships are destructive and provide for bad role models. 
<p>
H. DIVISION OF PROPERTY
<p>
Under the <cite>Family Law Act</cite> of Ontario,<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> only two people who are married can benefit from the division of property regime found in that <cite>Act</cite>. This regime
seeks to ensure the equal sharing of the wealth that accrued to the couple during the marriage. Its stated purpose is to foster marriage as an equal partnership, with the presumption that equal contributions are made by the spouses throughout the marriage.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> But whereas opposite-sex couples have control over the extent to which the regime applies to them, by making marriage contracts or by not marrying, same-sex couples can rely only on the doctrine of constructive trust.<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> For example, in <cite>Anderson v. Luoma</cite>, the B.C. Supreme Court divided a lesbian couple's property according to this doctrine to reflect the partners' relative economic
contributions to the relationship.<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup>
<p>
I.  SPOUSAL SUPPORT
<p>
On marriage breakdown, both married and common law couples benefit from the <cite>Family Law Act</cite> provisions for spousal support.<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> Support orders are calculated by the courts in light of the objectives enumerated in the <cite>Act</cite>.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> Recent rulings have aimed to compensate spouses for the loss of income-earning potential that is causally connected to the marriage.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup> Opposite-sex couples have a choice of regime: they can accept the support scheme of the <cite>FLA</cite> or make a domestic contract to modify it in any way.<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> Same-sex couples can only make domestic contracts. Although a feasible alternative for the contractually sophisticated, domestic contracts are nevertheless inferior to support orders in that they are often drafted when the circumstances relating to the relationship breakdown are not known.
<p>
J. INTESTACY
<p>
Same-sex couples are equally disadvantaged compared with opposite couples if the partnership ends with death. If the deceased same-sex partner does not have a will, then the surviving partner will not receive any of the deceased's assets, aside from a possible constructive trust claim on the deceased's estate.<sup><a  href="#sixty7">67</a></sup> In contrast, the surviving spouse of a marriage can elect to receive his or her entitlement to property under the deceased's will, if a will exists, or as per the division of property regime in the <cite>Family Law Act.</cite><sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> Dependant's relief is also available only to dependants of marriages and common law relationships.<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup>
<p>
K. HUMAN RIGHTS CODES
<p>
Sexual orientation is not a prohibited ground of discrimination in the human rights codes of six Canadian
jurisdictions: Newfoundland, Prince Edward Island, Saskatchewan, Alberta, British Columbia, and the Northwest Territories. Unlike the <cite>Charter</cite>, which protects against discrimination on grounds enumerated in s. 15 or upon analogous grounds,<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> the protection afforded by these human rights codes is limited to those grounds of discrimination that are enumerated. In these jurisdictions, private acts of discrimination<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup> on the basis of sexual orientation are legally acceptable, and only when the discriminating body can be considered to be &quot;government&quot; will the <cite>Charter</cite> afford some protection.<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup>
<p>
The constitutionality of human rights codes that do not conform to the <cite>Charter</cite> was addressed by the Ontario Court of Appeal decision in <cite>Birch.</cite><sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> The Court ruled not only that sexual orientation was a prohibited ground of discrimination under the <cite>Charter</cite>, but also that the <cite>CHRA</cite> itself was unconstitutional for excluding sexual orientation as a prohibited ground. As a remedy, it &quot;read in&quot; sexual orientation to the <cite>CHRA</cite>.<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup> The federal government did not appeal the decision, and introduced legislation to amend the <cite>CHRA</cite> to conform to the <cite>Birch</cite> decision. <sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup>
<p>
It is interesting to note that most academic literature concentrates almost exclusively on the <cite>Charter</cite> as the means by which the inequities faced by same-sex couples can best be redressed.<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup> This emphasis can be explained by several observations. First, as has been noted, human rights code protection against discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation exists only in seven jurisdictions<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup> and is limited to enumerated activities alone. Second, in contrast to court actions, human rights complainants lose control over their complaints once they are submitted. The Ontario Human Rights Commission, for example, takes
over the investigation of the complaint and renders a decision as to whether or not the complaint can proceed to the hearing stage. The Commission's decision, subject to one &quot;reconsideration,&quot; is
final.<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup> Third, the <cite>Charter</cite> is a document of more
powerful symbolic and jurisprudential importance and is hence a more effective way of challenging the <i>status quo</i> and redressing the inequities faced by same-sex couples. Lastly, and perhaps most
significant, human rights codes are not as efficient in practice as they were designed to be. Several years may pass before a claim is resolved; some cases have stretched out over five years.<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup> The Ontario Government is currently investigating ways in which to overhaul the Ontario Human Rights Commission.<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup>
<p>
L. SUMMARY
<p>
It is interesting to note that the above examples of legislative discrimination against same-sex couples are a result of underinclusive legislation. The existence of this legislation, coupled with judicial prejudice when it is being interpreted in the courts, undermines the ability of same-sex couples to form functional families. First, same-sex couples are not afforded the financial benefits that are made available to opposite-sex couples. Second, although same-sex couples are free to make contracts which mimic the effects of legislation such as the <cite>Family Law Act</cite>, such an alternative is practically available only to those who are relatively wealthy and legally sophisticated. Last, and possibly most significant, the discretion accorded to courts by virtue of unclear or imprecise legislation is almost always used to the detriment of lesbian and gay claimants, particularly in the area of child custody. Courts continue to perpetuate dichotomies that typify same-sex couples as being unstable, unsupportive, polygamous, and unable to bear or properly raise children. Opposite-sex couples are conversely characterized as virtuous and therefore, implicitly, more deserving of state benefits and favourable court judgments.
<p>
Although gays and lesbians are, theoretically, free to form relationships that have many of the indicia of functional families,<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup> the state, by making one family form financially and socially preferable,<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup> and the judiciary, by rendering homophobic judgments, indirectly discourage their creation. This discouragement should be viewed as a reaction to the threat that same-sex couples pose to a male heterosexual-dominated society. The following sections will discuss, in greater detail, the nature of this threat and the strategies that can be employed to counter this discrimination most effectively.
<p>
<h3>II. The <cite>Charter</cite></h3>

Placed against this discrimination is a relatively progressive <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>.<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup> As Bruce Ryder describes it, there is a
compassion/no-condonation dichotomy operating within Canadian society. He characterizes the exclusion of same-sex benefits from legislation and the hesitancy of judges and legislatures to change these laws as reflecting the desire not to condone, or at least not to be seen as condoning, what is to many an abhorrent and sinful lifestyle. On the other hand, he notes a highly compassionate streak in Canadian society, as reflected by the <cite>Charter</cite>, several human rights codes, and opinion polls, which abhors any type of discrimination.<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup>
<p>
Despite this &quot;compassion,&quot; the remedial route offered by the <cite>Charter</cite> has been compromised by the courts. Although obtaining <cite>Charter</cite> protection against discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation should be relatively straightforward, as will be illustrated, courts often undercut this protection by adhering to narrow and outdated judicial reasoning that relies on stereotype in
denying same-sex couples full protection. These types of reasoning will be discussed not only in order to illustrate homophobic interpretations of the <cite>Charter</cite> but also in order to uncover the tactics that block successful same-sex spousal <cite>Charter</cite> litigation. Such tactics include the revival of the discarded similarly-situated test and the use of unconvincing s. 1 justifications which reveal the homophobic attitudes of the respective judges.
<p>
These strained attempts to deny same-sex couples equality attest to the fact that same-sex couples are seen as a threat to the established order and the privilege that flows from it. This established order involves a hierarchy of social relations in which men are the dominant sex, heterosexuality the accepted sexual
orientation, and conventional families the idealized form of familial arrangement. The ability of same-sex couples to form functional families is stymied by reasoning that is designed to protect this privilege. And because this privilege has existed for so long, it has become the &quot;norm&quot; and is accepted as the &quot;truth.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup>
<p>
A. THE SECTION 15 TEST
<p>
Section 15 of the <cite>Charter</cite> guarantees that 
<blockquote>
Every individual is equal before and under the law and has the right to equal benefit and equal protection of the law without discrimination and, <i>in particular</i>, without discrimination based on race, national or ethnic origin, colour, religion, sex, age or mental or physical disability.
</blockquote>
The test for determining whether a s. 15 violation has taken place is found in <cite>Andrews v. Law Society of British Columbia</cite>:<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup>
<blockquote>
A complainant under s. 15 must show not only that he or she is not receiving equal treatment before and under the law or that the law has a differential impact on him or her in the protection or benefit accorded by law but, <i>in addition</i>, must show that the impact of the law is discriminatory.<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup> [emphasis added]
</blockquote>
Whether or not sexual orientation can be considered an analogous ground of discrimination to those listed in s. 15 is considered as part of the second branch of the test.<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup>
<p>
The purpose of the four equality rights in s. 15, as expressed by McIntyre J. in <cite>Andrews</cite>, is to ensure that &quot;a law . . . should not because of irrelevant personal differences have a more burdensome or less beneficial impact on one than another.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> In particular, &quot;equal benefit of the law&quot; has been defined as referring to the stipulation that individuals must benefit equally from the existence of government benefit programs.<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> It would not be difficult for same-sex couples who were subject to the discrimination noted previously to argue successfully that they were not being accorded &quot;equal benefit of the law.&quot;  Same-sex couples are clearly treated differently from opposite-sex couples under these laws.
<p>
What must be shown in the second branch of the test is that these distinctions constitute &quot;discrimination.&quot;  To establish this, it must be shown that (a) the different treatment results in
disadvantage and (b) the complainant is a member of an enumerated, analogous, or &quot;protected&quot; group.<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> According to McIntyre J.,
<blockquote>
[D]iscrimination may be described as a distinction, whether intentional or not but based on grounds relating to personal characteristics of the individual or group, <i>which has the effect of imposing burdens, obligations or disadvantages on such individual or group not imposed upon others, or which withholds or
limits access to opportunities, benefits and advantages available to other members of society</i>.<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup> [emphasis added]
</blockquote>
Denying same-sex spousal benefits clearly has the result of hindering the formation of functional same-sex families, both in terms of the economic disadvantage caused by the laws mentioned above and also in terms of the stereotypical assumptions that these laws reinforce regarding such things as a lesbian or gay person's ability to be a parent, a lesbian or gay person's ability to be caring, and a lesbian or gay person's ability to have a meaningful, committed relationship. This legislative discrimination, coupled with judicial prejudice, dissuades same-sex couples from forming these types of relationships and hence hinders the ability of lesbians and gays to participate fully in Canadian society.<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup>
<p>
Determining whether or not sexual orientation is to be included as an analogous form of discrimination under s. 15 involves the consideration of various factors, factors that are best encompassed by McIntyre J.'s statement that s. 15 is designed to protect &quot;discrete and insular minorities.&quot;<sup><a   href="#ninety4">94</a></sup> In <cite>Turpin</cite>, Wilson J. noted the indicia of &quot;stereotyping,
historical disadvantage [and] vulnerability to political and social prejudice,&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup> adding that
<blockquote>
[T]his categorization is not an end in itself but merely one of the analytical tools which are of assistance in determining whether an interest advanced by a particular claimant is the kind of interest s. 15 of the <cite>Charter</cite> is designed to protect. It is a means of ensuring that equality rights are given the same broad, purposive interpretation accorded to other <cite>Charter</cite> rights.<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Historically, prejudice and social stigmatization has resulted in lesbians and gays leading lives removed from the mainstream. And, as was discussed previously, not only have legislative enactments resulted in the perpetuation of lesbian and gay insularity, but court judgments as well have served to perpetuate stereotypical assumptions about lesbians and gays. In addition, even the more homophobic  judgments contain admissions that lesbians and gays do constitute a distinct group.<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> Finally, it is important to note that sexual orientation often is conceded by counsel for the government as being an analogous ground of discrimination.<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup> These concessions are consistent with government policy statements.<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup>
<p>
B. THE &quot;SIMILARLY-SITUATED&quot; PROBLEM
<p>
A problematic aspect of same-sex <cite>Charter</cite> litigation is that courts have tended to revive the &quot;similarly-situated&quot; discrimination test that seemed to have been discredited conclusively
by McIntyre J. in <cite>Andrews</cite>.<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup> An emphasis on this analysis is therefore necessary in any s. 15 discussion regarding sexual orientation. As McIntyre J. stated in <cite>Andrews</cite>, &quot;[A] bad law will not be saved merely because it operates equally upon those to whom it has application.&quot;<sup><a href="#one01">101</a></sup> In criticizing the decision in <cite>Bliss v. A.G. Canada</cite>,<sup><a href="#one02">102</a></sup> where Bliss' claim that she was discriminated against because she was pregnant was dismissed because all pregnant people, the class formed by the legislation, were treated equally, McIntyre J. stated that &quot;[t]his case, of course, was decided before the advent of the <cite>Charter</cite>.&quot;<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup> He also adopted the following criticism of the similarly-situated test:
<blockquote>
[T]he test accepts an idea of equality which is almost mechanical, with no scope for considering the reason for the distinction. In consequence, subtleties are found to justify a finding of dissimilarity which reduce the test to a categorization game. Moreover, the test is not helpful. After all, most laws are enacted for the specific purpose of offering a benefit or imposing a burden on some persons and not others.<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Moreover, McIntyre J. noted that
<blockquote>
[T]he test cannot be accepted as a fixed rule or formula for the resolution of equality questions arising under the <cite>Charter</cite>. Consideration must be given to the content of the law, to its purpose, and its impact upon those to whom it applies, and also upon those whom it excludes from its application. The issues which will arise from case to case are such that it would be wrong to attempt to confine these considerations within such a fixed and limited formula.<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup>
</blockquote>
An effective s. 15 test must look beyond individual legislatively created categories and analyse how individuals are treated across categories. The &quot;larger context&quot; must be examined.<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup> 
<p>
In the <cite>Egan</cite> trial, although Martin J. specifically denies using a similarly situated test, this is exactly what he does:
<blockquote>
Parliament has chosen to address the needs of persons of the opposite sex who live together in a conjugal state, either statutory or common law, as husband and wife . . . [The same-sex] <i>relationship is a different one than a spousal relationship</i> and . . . the parties to such [a] relationship cannot expect to share the benefits accorded to those in spousal relationships, not because of their sexual orientation, but because their relationship is not a spousal one.<sup><a href="#one07">107</a></sup> [emphasis added]
</blockquote>
Martin J. deferred to the categorization made by Parliament and was satisfied that individuals within that category were being treated equally. In addition, Martin J.'s rationalization that the case should be dismissed because of the plaintiff's lack of spousal status is misleading. He ignored the reality that the only reason their relationship was not a spousal one was their sexual orientation. Martin J. also ignored jurisprudence that confirms that an enumerated or analogous group does not have to be specifically mentioned in a statute in order for there to be a finding of discrimination on that ground. In <cite>Brooks v. Canada Safeway Ltd.</cite>,<sup><a href="#one08">108</a></sup> although the impugned group insurance plan discriminated on the basis of pregnancy, the Supreme Court found discrimination on the basis of sex since only women could become pregnant.<sup><a href="#one09">109</a></sup> In <cite>Knodel</cite>, Rowles J. held that there was discrimination based on sexual orientation specifically because the legislative definition of &quot;spouse&quot; did not include same-sex partners.<sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup>
<p>
At the Federal Court of Appeal, Robertson J. also supported Parliament's categorization:
<blockquote>
Before us is a case in which a benefit has been conferred on a narrow class of persons who can be readily identified and who are in financial need because of a pattern of financial interdependency, characteristic of heterosexual couples, and which cannot in any reasonable way be deemed relevant to same-sex couples or, for that matter, other non-spousal relationships.<sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup>
</blockquote>
It is clear that Robertson J.'s reasoning rests on his adherence to the dichotomous view that opposite-sex relationships are characterized by interdependence while same-sex relationships are characterized by independence. Moreover, it is unclear how opposite-sex couples, aside from those who have marriage
certificates, are any more &quot;identifiable&quot; than same-sex couples.<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup> 
<p>
In <cite>Andrews 2</cite>, lesbian partners sought a declaration that the exclusion of same-sex couples from the definition of &quot;spouse&quot; in the <cite>Health Insurance Act</cite> violated their right to equality under s. 15.<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup> The trial judge, McRae J., dismissed this claim on the grounds that since the applicants were not similarly situated to married couples, they were not entitled to the benefits accorded to married couples.<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup> Further, McRae J. noted that there was no discrimination, because the applicants were treated similarly to other excluded &quot;couples&quot; who may be living together, such as common law couples.<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup> The exclusion of two groups, as opposed to just one, is not a justification for s. 15 infringement. In addition, whereas common law partners can marry, same-sex couples cannot. This judgment was specifically criticized by the British Columbia Supreme Court in <cite>Knodel</cite>, with Rowles J. noting that the similarly-situated test was rejected by the Supreme Court of Canada in <cite>Andrews</cite>.<sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup>
<p>
It is also interesting to note that despite government commitments to ensure that sexual orientation is a prohibited ground of discrimination in all areas of federal jurisdiction,<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup> lawyers from the Department of Justice continue to argue their cases using reasoning similar to that noted above. In <cite>Knodel</cite>, counsel for the Crown argued that the definition of spouse &quot;does not make a distinction based upon sexual orientation but is simply a
distinction between `spouses' and `non-spouses.'&quot;<sup><a href="#one18">118</a></sup> Similarly, the factum submitted by the Department of Justice in <cite>Veysey</cite> argued that &quot;the respondent was denied his visit, not because of his sexual orientation, but because the person he nominated for the proposed visit was not his spouse. . . .&quot;<sup><a href="#one19">119</a></sup> Such arguments clearly put into question the Department of Justice's commitment to eliminating discrimination based on sexual orientation.
<p>
These arguments and judicial reasoning indicate that judges and possibly Crown lawyers simply cannot conceive of same-sex couples as being able to form relationships that are loving, emotionally and financially supportive, and/or that include children. There is a rigid adherence to dichotomous perceptions that opposite-sex couples possess all of these characteristics and same-sex couples possess none of them. It is because of this mutual exclusivity that same-sex couples are often put in the position of arguing sameness as a justification for entitlement. The implicit message is that same-sex couples are worthy of state benefits and recognition only if they are like opposite-sex couples. But, as <cite>Andrews 2</cite> illustrates, this pursuit is most often in vain. Despite the similarity of the claimants' lesbian relationship to that of the conventional family,<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup> their sexual orientation proved determinative.
<p>
C. REMEDY REQUESTED
<p>
Another potentially problematic area of <cite>Charter</cite> jurisprudence is whether or not courts will award a remedy that imposes a financial burden on governments. Although courts have traditionally been hesitant to usurp federal spending powers, there are indications that a court may do so when a <cite>Charter</cite> right has been violated. Notable among cases in which a financial burden is placed on governments is <cite>Re Singh and the Minister of Employment and Immigration</cite>, where the Supreme Court of Canada declared the principles of the <cite>Charter</cite> to be above all but the most extreme cost considerations.<sup><a href="#one21">121</a></sup> Although the Supreme Court has since retreated from that relatively bold stance, it has recently upheld the ability of courts to make rulings, pursuant to s. 24(1) of the <cite>Charter</cite>, that impose financial burdens on governments.<sup><a href="#one22">122</a></sup> Section 24(1) states:
<blockquote>
Anyone whose rights or freedoms, as guaranteed by this Charter, have been infringed or denied may apply to a court of competent jurisdiction to obtain such remedy as the court considers appropriate and just in the circumstances.
</blockquote>
Because the denial of spousal benefits is usually the result of a wrongful exclusion, the necessary remedy would be either &quot;reading in&quot; a provision which would make the statute consistent with the
<cite>Charter</cite> or declaring the legislation invalid, with the possibility of suspending this declaration pending acceptable amendments by a legislature. In <cite>Schachter</cite>, the Supreme Court enunciated the following principles: First, it must be decided whether reading in, declaring the legislation invalid, or declaring part of the legislation invalid interferes least with the original scheme and purpose of the legislation in question.<sup><a href="#one23">123</a></sup> Second, reading in must not impose a
&quot;substantial&quot; financial burden on the legislature.<sup><a href="#one24">124</a></sup> Third, a suspended declaration of invalidity will be made whenever it is not feasible to read in a provision, according to the above criteria, and whenever an immediate declaration of invalidity would have overly harsh repercussions on the general public or would be inconsistent with the overall purpose of the <cite>Charter</cite>.<sup><a href="#one25">125</a></sup>
<p>
With regard to the requirement that the legislative objective remain intact, it is possible for a court to find that extending spousal benefits to same-sex couples is contrary to Parliament's intention of promoting conventional families. However, because a declaration of invalidity would likely have an even greater impact on those families that the legislature is seeking to promote, this seems unlikely. For example, not having old age pension benefits at all arguably harms such families more than would extending the benefit to same-sex
couples. A likely alternative, however, is a court declaring the legislation invalid, but temporarily suspending the invalidity pending a legislative resolution of the matter. A court will likely opt for this alternative if it does not want to be responsible for altering laws which perpetuate male heterosexual privilege.
<p>
The ruling in <cite>Schachter</cite> makes the third possibility, reading in the inclusion of same-sex couples, the least problematic. Courts can impose a financial burden on governments as long as the group
sought to be included is proportionately small relative to the group already included.<sup><a href="#one26">126</a></sup> In the case of <cite>Schachter</cite>, the Supreme Court refused to extend benefits that were already available to adoptive parents to natural parents, noting that this latter group &quot;likely vastly outnumbers&quot; the former group.<sup><a href="#one27">127</a></sup> Lamer C.J. contrasted this to the situation in <cite>T&eacute;trault-Gadoury v. Canada</cite>,<sup><a  href="#one28">128</a></sup> where it was decided that benefits which had previously been restricted to those under the age of 65 should be extended to those over the age of 65.<sup><a href="#one29">129</a></sup> Same-sex couples, relative to opposite-sex couples, are a similarly &quot;small, discrete group.&quot;<sup><a href="#one30">130</a></sup> In fact, the Ontario Court of Appeal in <cite>Birch</cite> stated that lesbians and gays do constitute a small enough group, relative to heterosexuals, to warrant the &quot;reading in&quot; option.<sup><a href="#one31">131</a></sup>
<p>
D. SECTION 1
<p>
Section 1 allows for much judicial discretion in deciding whether there has been a justifiable limitation on the enjoyment of <cite>Charter</cite> rights. Hence, it is likely to be the most problematic aspect of same-sex spousal litigation. According to the <cite>Oakes</cite> test, the government has the onus of proving that a
<cite>Charter</cite> right has been limited for &quot;pressing and substantial&quot; reasons that are consistent with the promotion of a &quot;free and democratic society&quot; and that the means chosen are
proportional to the ends sought.<sup><a href="#one32">132</a></sup>
<p>
It is most likely that governments will justify a s. 15 infringement in the name of promoting &quot;traditional families.&quot;  This assertion involves many related issues: Why does the state want to foster this particular family form? Is it procreation? Is it capitalism? Is it Christianity? Is it male heterosexual privilege? Crown counsel often admits that the government has chosen to benefit conventional family units.<sup><a href="#one33">133</a></sup> In <cite>Andrews 2</cite>, McRae J. stated that the promotion of traditional families is a valid governmental objective for s. 1.<sup><a href="#one34">134</a></sup> It is important to
expose the bias underlying this assertion in order to discredit it as a valid s. 1 objective.<sup><a href="#one35">135</a></sup>
<p>
One of the primary stated purposes of the promotion of conventional families is to encourage procreation, despite the fact that the capacity to procreate has never been a necessary requirement to marry. <sup><a href="#one36">136</a></sup> In fact, at common law, lack of <i>consummation</i> is no longer even a ground for voiding a marriage.<sup><a href="#one37</a></sup> Same-sex couples are actually being held to the higher standard of having to be able to <i>procreate</i>, McRae J. stating in Andrews that &quot;[h]omosexual couples are <i>not</i> similarly situated to opposite-sex couples. Heterosexual couples procreate and raise children.&quot;<sup><a href="#one38">138</a></sup> McRae J.'s adherence to dichotomous characterizations of same-sex couples ignores the reality that not only can same-sex couples &quot;raise children&quot; but that new reproductive technologies do provide for alternative ways to
procreate aside from vaginal intercourse.
<p>
Another common s. 1 justification is administrative convenience.<sup><a href="#one39">139</a></sup> With regard to extending <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> definitions of &quot;spouse&quot; to include common law spouses, then Attorney General John Crosbie stated that &quot;the impediment to extending equal treatment to common law spouses is that Revenue Canada would be unable to administer a definition of common law spouse with a high degree of accuracy.&quot; <sup><a href="#one40">140</a></sup> Despite this uncertainty, the federal government has recently passed legislation that extends spousal provisions in the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> to common law spouses. In fact, of the Acts discussed in this paper, only the <cite>Family Law Act</cite>, <cite>Succession Law Reform Act</cite>, and <cite>Immigration Act</cite> continue to contain provisions that exclude common law couples.<sup><a href="#one41">141</a></sup>
<p>
In <cite>Andrews 2</cite>, McRae J. argued that it would be administratively impracticable to extend to same-sex couples benefits that were already available to common law, opposite-sex couples:
<blockquote>
In order to make the scheme under the Act administratively and economically practicable, there needs to be an objective interpretation imposed that will necessarily exclude some persons. Simplicity and administrative convenience are legitimate concerns. ... <sup><a href="#one42">142</a></sup>
</blockquote>
McRae J. did not explain how it is easier to verify the status of a common law relationship than that of a same-sex relationship. This distinction is arbitrary.
<p>
E. SUMMARY
<p>
The <cite>Charter</cite> does afford lesbian and gay litigants protection against discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation. However, this protection is undercut markedly by legal reasoning that is informed by homophobic bias. The effect of this limited protection is that in addition to being unprotected against private acts of discrimination in most jurisdictions in Canada,<sup><a href="#one43">143</a></sup> lesbian and gay litigants often are unable to use the <cite>Charter</cite> to challenge successfully government legislation, such as that mentioned in Part I, that discriminates on the basis of sexual orientation.
<p>
The pervasiveness of homophobic judgments attests to the political powerlessness of lesbians and gays and serves as an indication that same-sex spouses represent a serious threat to the established patriarchal social order, at the pinnacle of which are heterosexual men and conventional families. Mary Eaton and Cynthia Petersen, in their critique of the <cite>Andrews 2</cite> &quot;traditional family&quot; s. 1 justification, characterized the patriarchal heterosexist agenda as follows:
<blockquote>
First, the political economy of the family is such that, as a general rule, home-centred labour is performed by women without cash payment. This bolsters the economy as a whole and frees up male labour for use in the public sphere. Second, by performing the functions of child birthing and care, women contribute substantially to the economy by reproducing human capital. Third, the power structure of the nuclear family perpetuates patriarchal domination on a microscopic scale.<sup><a href="#one44">144</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This agenda has become so much the norm that its tenets, heterosexism and sexism, are rarely even questioned by the judiciary. Same-sex couples are, by reflex, attributed characteristics that most often bear no relationship to reality, characteristics that invariably cast these relationships as being either inferior to
opposite-sex relationships or simply non-existent.
<p>
<h3>III.   Strategies for Change</h3>

In order to be accorded equitable treatment, same-sex couples face the challenge of arguing that same-sex relationships are, in fact, legitimate.<sup><a href="#one45">145</a></sup> This can be done in one of two general ways: either maintain that same-sex relationships are &quot;like&quot; opposite-sex relationships, that they possess the qualities traditionally associated with conventional families; or maintain that same-sex relationships are in fact unique, that they are not &quot;like&quot; opposite-sex relationships but nevertheless should be accorded equitable treatment. These two approaches are, on their face, mutually exclusive. One approach argues for inclusion in the sphere of &quot;family,&quot; the other seeks to deconstruct or possibly completely destroy an institution that is argued to be inherently exclusionary and discriminatory. This Part will explore this debate and will suggest that not only can these two approaches be seen as complementary, but that this dilemma can be bypassed somewhat by using &quot;functional&quot; definitions of the word &quot;spouse.&quot;
<p>
A.  TOWARD A NEW IDEOLOGY OF THE FAMILY
<p>
In order to secure the spousal benefits that are available to opposite-sex couples, many same-sex couples assert that same-sex relationships have the same characteristics as those associated with opposite-sex couples. Presumably, many litigants feel that the most effective way to gain the sympathy of a heterosexual society and heterosexual judiciary is to mimic those attributes that our society values. This may be so in the short term, when an individual litigant is before a heterosexist judge. However, such an approach may do less, in the long term, to dismantle the ideology of the conventional family which is responsible for much of the oppression faced by lesbians and gays and other individuals who are not predisposed to conforming to that mold.
<p>
Didi Herman criticizes the fact that almost all same-sex spousal litigation is following this &quot;sameness&quot; route, referring to the <cite>Andrews 2</cite> factum as a case in point: 
<blockquote>
[Karen Andrews and Mary Trenholm] regard themselves and hold themselves out to the community as each other's spouse and intend to continue to live together as each other's spouse. Andrews and Trenholm are each other's sole domestic and sexual partners, own their own home as joint tenants, have their assets in a joint bank account and have named each other as beneficiary under their wills.<sup><a href="#one46">146</a></sup>
</blockquote>
This strategy of arguing &quot;sameness&quot; can be considered to be patently assimilationist. The existence and experience of lesbian and gay and other alternative family forms is marginalized due to the
fact that the only way of obtaining &quot;family&quot; assistance is to conform to the dominant conception of what constitutes a family. Those attributes associated with conventional families, attributes
that are reflected in the <cite>Andrews 2</cite> factum, bear repeating: mutual dependence, stability, nurturing, child-bearing, child-rearing, and monogamy.<sup><a href="#one47">147</a></sup>
<p>
Despite these concerns, it is submitted that such an approach is a productive first step. By being included under the rubric of &quot;family,&quot; same-sex couples will ultimately transform its underlying tenets; although same-sex couples can argue that same-sex relationships are in many ways &quot;the same,&quot; the sexual configuration of same-sex relationships will nevertheless challenge the status quo sufficiently to shift its conception as to what constitutes a &quot;conventional family.&quot;  Only once these underlying tenets are shifted will it become more feasible for same-sex couples to argue that, despite differences that may exist, same-sex couples must nevertheless be accorded equitable treatment.<sup><a href="#one48">148</a></sup> In fact, such arguments are essential in effecting a further shift in the status quo conception of what constitutes an appropriate family unit.<sup><a href="#one49">149</a></sup>
<p>
Some lesbian and gay and feminist theorists argue for a regime that distributes benefits solely on the basis of individual need and entitlement, asserting that the state has no role supporting any sort of family unit. For example, Carol Smart argues that 
<blockquote>
A primary goal must be to jettison the privileged status of the heterosexual married couple, but not in order to create a different hierarchy of <i>unmarried</i> households. The aim is not to extend the legal and social definition of marriage to cover cohabitees or even homosexual couples, it is to abandon the status of marriage altogether and to devise a system of rights, duties, or obligations which are not dependent on any form of <i>coupledom</i> or marriage or quasi-marriage.<sup><a href="#one50">150</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The implicit assertion in this argument is that <i>any</i> family-centred regime that is sanctioned by the state will necessarily be oppressive.
<p>
Although this approach ultimately would put an end to much of the discrimination faced by same-sex partners, it is possible, if not likely, that the withdrawal of state support for family units will result in the decline of the formation of families and hence jeopardize the many positive functions currently performed by
families in our society. Families are a primary vehicle through which religions, languages, and cultures are passed on from generation to generation. This is especially so if the religion, culture, or language in question is shared by a relatively small portion of the population.<sup><a href="#one51">151</a></sup> Familial ties are necessary insofar as they provide some privatization of interpersonal relationships, some sphere within which individuals can make intimate decisions regarding such things as morality and religion.<sup><a href="#one52">152</a></sup>
<p>
Families also serve to protect individuals from more direct or imminent forms of oppression, such as racism and homophobia. In this respect, families again serve a more important function for minority groups. Harriet Michel notes that &quot;family&quot; units were crucial to the survival of black Americans, particularly during the time of
slavery:
<blockquote>
Because slavery often denied us the right to live with our biological kin, our definition of family became any group of individuals who collectively come together in order to provide economic and emotional support to the members of the group.<sup><a href="#one53">153</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Similarly, a &quot;same-sex family&quot;<sup><a href="#one54">154</a></sup> is a lesbian or gay
person's primary refuge in an ideologically heterosexist world.
<p>
Accordingly, the ideology of the family must be deconstructed only insofar as it includes stereotypes concerning such issues as sexuality, gender, dependence, procreation, and monogamy. It is not an institution that needs to be abandoned completely. This partial deconstruction of the conventional family can be achieved by statutorily defining families according to &quot;functional&quot; indicia such as economic and emotional support. Same-sex couples would no longer have to argue that same-sex relationships conform to heterosexist stereotypes in order to qualify for benefits but rather will be able to point to fixed, written criteria that can be evaluated more objectively.<sup><a href="#one55">155</a></sup> In addition, questionable functional criteria that are written can be more easily challenged as being discriminatory, particularly if they are seen to be heterosexually-biased.
<p>
This functional approach can also be used when the statute in question does not define its use of the word &quot;spouse&quot; or &quot;family.&quot;  In <cite>Braschi v. Stahl</cite>, a case dealing with eviction, the New York Court of Appeals ruled a same-sex couple to be the legal equivalent of a family.<sup><a href="#one56">156</a></sup> The Court interpreted the term &quot;family&quot; in the statute in question as
referring not only to the conventional family form but to a plurality of family forms, noting that the &quot;reality of family life&quot; necessitated a broad interpretation of the word. The Court ruled that 
<blockquote>
[T]he term family ... should not be rigidly restricted to those people who have formalized their relationship by obtaining, for instance, a marriage certificate or an adoption order. The intended protection against sudden eviction should not rest on fictitious legal distinctions or genetic history ... (but rather on) ... the exclusivity and longevity of the relationship, the level of emotional and financial commitment. ...<sup><a href="#one57">157</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Court did not, unlike courts in most cases involving lesbian and gay plaintiffs, defer to heterosexist stereotype, to dictionary definitions of &quot;family,&quot; or to heterosexist definitions of &quot;family&quot; found in other statutes.<sup><a href="#one58">158</a></sup>
<p>
This general approach is also evidenced somewhat in <cite>Knodel</cite>. Although Rowles J. did not go so far as to list new indicia of what constitutes a family, she did accept the following expert evidence that the plaintiff same-sex couple did constitute a &quot;familial unit&quot; for the purpose of the legislation in question. 
<blockquote>
[T]he term &quot;family&quot; does not have one definition for all purposes in Canada. As families evolve in our pluralistic society, the language by which families are described evolves. Dr. Eichler uses the term &quot;familial relationship&quot; to characterize the many kinds of relationships that exist outside of the traditional and legally married family.<sup><a href="#one59">159</a></sup>
</blockquote>
It is unclear whether other Canadian courts will follow Rowles J.'s relatively progressive approach as to what constitutes a family. It is nevertheless desirable that, when advocating for change, a pluralistic conception of family be employed as a means of trying to effect a shift in what our society views as a &quot;proper&quot; family unit.
<p>
B. A NEW DEFINITION OF &quot;SPOUSE&quot;
<p>
A more pluralistic definition of &quot;spouse&quot; should be the cornerstone of any legislative reform in which families are deemed to be the most appropriate unit of appraisal. As discussed above, the adoption of such a definition will be crucial in extending equitable treatment to partners who choose not to marry. The following is an
example of such a definition:
<blockquote>
&quot;Partner&quot; refers to individuals who mutually intend to be partners. Indicia of this intention MAY include, BUT ARE NOT RESTRICTED TO, the following:
<ul>
<li>a marriage certificate
<li>cohabitation and any related arrangements
<li>sharing of financial resources
<li>emotional commitment
<li>length of relationship
<li>co-parenting agreements
<li>self-identification as partners.<sup><a href="#one60">160</a></sup>
</ul></blockquote>
Such a definition has the advantage of emphasizing that partnership and family formation do not necessarily assume the format of the conventional family. It focuses on the intent of the parties to have a partnership rather than rigid and artificial requirements such as the securing of a marriage licence or cohabitation for three years.<sup><a href="#one61">161</a></sup> The word &quot;partner&quot; has been used instead of the word &quot;spouse&quot; to signify this new conception of what constitutes a family. In addition, as will be discussed below, this definition should be made context-specific to satisfy the particularities of different legislative schemes.
<p>
Although it is arguable that the above criteria reflect conventional family norms, it is necessary to provide courts with indicia as to what constitutes a partnership given that it is a relatively new legislative concept. Without any criteria, courts are more likely to equate &quot;an intention to be partners&quot; with &quot;an intention to be spouses&quot; and make use of stereotypes associated with what it means to be a &quot;spouse&quot; and &quot;family&quot; when deciding whether two individuals are partners. In addition, the inclusion of the possibility of polygamous partnerships and the clearly optional nature of these criteria would serve as a clear indication of legislative intent to depart from conventional conceptions of &quot;spouse&quot; and &quot;family.&quot;<sup><a href="#one62">162</a></sup>
<p>
An interesting example of a legislative attempt to accommodate alternative family forms can be found in Ontario's <cite>Consent to Treatment Act</cite>,<sup><a href="#one63">163</a></sup> which allows for a &quot;spouse or partner&quot; to give consent to medical treatment on behalf of an individual who is deemed to be incapable of doing so.<sup><a href="#one64">164</a></sup> The definitions of &quot;spouse&quot; and &quot;partners&quot; in s. 1 of the <cite>Act</cite> are as follows:
<blockquote>
&quot;[S]pouse&quot; means a person of the opposite sex 
<ol type="a">
<li>to whom the person is married, or 
<li>with whom the person is living in a conjugal relationship outside marriage if the two persons, 
<ol type="i">
<li>have cohabited for at least one year, 
<li>are together the parents of a child, OR
<li>have together entered into a cohabitation agreement under section 53 of the <cite>Family Law Act</cite>
</ol></ol>
Two persons are partners for the purpose of this <cite>Act</cite> if they have lived together for at least one year and have a close personal relationship that others recognize is of primary importance in both persons' lives.
</blockquote>
Although this definition is progressive in that it acknowledges other family forms, it is problematic in two general
respects.<sup><a href="#one65">165</a></sup> First, same-sex couples and opposite-sex couples are not treated equally in that same-sex couples cannot be deemed to be partners by co-parenting a child or by entering into a
cohabitation agreement. Second, same-sex couples are put to a higher standard in that same-sex relationships must be &quot;recognized by others.&quot;  This criteria is especially unreasonable for same-sex couples who, due to homophobia, are not only less likely to have their relationship &quot;recognized by others&quot; but are also less likely to cohabit.<sup><a href="#one66">166</a></sup>
<p>
The above definitions are not intended to be examples of what are proper or improper definitions of partners in all cases. Depending on the legislation, it will be necessary to alter this conception of partnership in order to secure equitable application of the particular legislative scheme. For example, in order to be subject to the division of property provisions in most family law legislation, two individuals must be married.<sup><a href="#one67">167</a></sup> It is possible that the legislature may wish to preserve this &quot;opting in&quot; system, in which case the recognition of a partnership could be subject to registration by the parties.<sup><a href="#one68">168</a></sup> In the area of social welfare legislation, a system of individual entitlement would alleviate much of the disadvantage faced by women in need of social assistance.<sup><a href="#one69">169</a></sup> In the area of taxation, it may be more equitable to apply some definition of partnership that reflects the actual economies realized by cohabitation and/or the joining of financial resources. Hence, the definition might emphasize financial interdependence and sharing more than emotional commitment, for
example.
<p>
C. MARRIAGE OR AREA-BY-AREA CHANGES?
<p>
The question regarding same-sex marriages is posed usually from the dominant heterosexist perspective: &quot;Should homosexuals be allowed to enter a legal marriage?&quot;  Although it is unjust to deny lesbians and gays the right to marry, simply answering &quot;yes&quot; to the above question implicitly accepts that the dominant heterosexist perspective about social organization is the only perspective.<sup><a href="#one70">170</a></sup> As Nitya Duclos suggests, it is more empowering, and in fact more productive,
to pose the question from the perspective of lesbians and gays. According to Duclos, the question should be 
<blockquote>
Will lesbians and gay men or some of them benefit from legal recognition and regulation of their relationships through the marriage system?
</blockquote>
Duclos continues by explaining that this phraseology
<blockquote>
puts lesbians and gay men front and center as people with whom and for whom we are concerned. It specifies that legal recognition is one form of recognition and that the issue involves the <i>regulation</i> of those relationships by law. It expressly removes from consideration any doubt that lesbians and gay men have relationships---something the earlier question left open. And it asserts that marriage is a system of legal and social rules, not
elemental but socially constructed and open to change.<sup><a href="#one71">171</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Because marriage does involve a multiplicity of rights, obligations, and legal consequences spanning such various areas of law as social welfare, taxation, and family law, it may be preferable to determine what type of reform would be most advantageous to same-sex couples in each particular area of legislation.<sup><a href="#one72">172</a></sup> Although most of the legislation mentioned in the first part of this article is disadvantageous to same-sex couples, there are areas where most same-sex couples are likely better off. For example, same-sex couples &quot;benefit&quot; from not being considered a viable socio-economic unit in that no income is deemed to be shared by them for income tax purposes or, most often, for the purposes of the &quot;spouse in the house&quot; rule in the administration of social assistance.<sup><a href="#one73">173</a></sup> An area-by-area approach would also allow for the re-evaluation of the tenets of the
specific legislation in question, possibly benefiting other disenfranchised groups who are being treated inequitably by its scheme. For example, the increasing recognition of same-sex relationships may prompt a re-evaluation of the &quot;spouse in the house&quot; rule, which is particularly disadvantageous to women.<sup><a href="#one74">174</a></sup>
<p>
Despite the beneficial aspects of area-by-area reform, the option of marriage should still be available to same-sex couples if it remains available to opposite-sex couples.<sup><a href="#one75">175</a></sup> Most opposition to this prospect centres around the conception that entry or advocating entry into a heterosexual-dominated institution will prompt conformation with its norms. Examples of this are Karen Andrews arguing &quot;sameness&quot; in
order to get a spousal benefit, and lesbian and gay advocates arguing for the right to marry on the grounds that their family units conform to criteria similar to those of opposite-sex family units. 
<p>
Although these concerns have merit, there are countervailing benefits that may result from same-sex couples obtaining the right to marry. First, it is arguable that securing a marriage licence may in fact decrease the need for same-sex couples to employ sameness arguments to secure the rights available to opposite-sex couples. A marriage
certificate will automatically entitle a same-sex couple to various benefits, possibly restricting &quot;sameness&quot; arguments to areas where judicial discretion, and hence possibly prejudice, remain, for
example in the realm of child custody disputes.<sup><a href="#one76">176</a></sup> Without the option of obtaining a marriage certificate, gays and lesbians would be more subject to judicial discretion as to what constitutes a &quot;family&quot; or what constitutes a &quot;spouse&quot; and hence more likely to employ sameness arguments. In addition, it must be realized that not marrying is in no way an inoculation against conformity. For example, both lesbian couples in <cite>Andrews 2</cite> and <cite>Anderson v. Luoma</cite>, aside from their sexual orientation, already conformed to what can be considered the &quot;norm.&quot;<sup><a href="#one77">177</a></sup>
<p>
Second, advocating the right to marry can serve as the catalyst that forces society to re-evaluate the heterosexist bias not only of marriage but of most other social institutions as well. Although marriage is often characterized as a static, heterosexist, male-dominated institution, it can also be seen as an evolving institution that adapts to changes in social norms, an institution capable of accommodating same-sex couples.<sup><a href="#one78">178</a></sup> The sanctioning of same-sex relationships by the state would imply a high degree of
social legitimation of these relationships. Although this might be thought inherently repugnant and unnecessary by many lesbian and gay theorists, such legitimation can be quite effective in dismantling judicial, legislative, and social prejudice and the characterization of same-sex relationships as being inferior to opposite-sex relationships.
<p>
D. SUMMARY
<p>
Initially, same-sex couples will most easily achieve equal treatment by employing sameness arguments. Despite the
assimilationist nature of these arguments, the concept of the traditional family nevertheless will shift simply by virtue of same-sex couples arguing for equality and being included within the concept of family. Once this begins to occur, lesbian and gay advocates will be able to argue more productively for equal treatment without ignoring, or perhaps concealing, the ways in which lesbian and gay relationships are unique.
<p>
It is acknowledged that it is impossible to embrace reforms that satisfy all cultural particularities and ideological perspectives. The above suggestions are intended to serve as a middle ground between those who advocate sameness and those, on the other extreme, who advocate the dismantling of the concept of family. Sameness
arguments are valuable in that they argue for inclusion in an institution that can be seen as evolving and capable of fundamental change. Those who argue for the dismantling of &quot;the family&quot; contribute to the debate by accelerating the critical evaluation, and hence reform, of an institution that is inherently exclusionary and discriminatory. It is hoped that this debate will help bring about legal reforms which recognize same-sex marriages and which adopt more pluralistic definitions of &quot;spouse&quot; that would apply to couples who choose not to marry.
<p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>

The scope of the discrimination faced by same-sex couples attests to the firm entrenchment of male-heterosexist privilege in our society. This privilege accounts for the existence of laws that benefit the conventional family form. The threat to this privilege accounts for many badly written, discriminatory judgments that incorporate outdated legal reasoning, as well as for the almost resolute unwillingness of governments to amend heterosexist legislation. Homophobic judgments and legislation serve to perpetuate dichotomies that ascribe certain &quot;inferior&quot;
characteristics to same-sex couples and other relatively &quot;superior&quot; characteristics to opposite-sex couples.
<p>
The conclusions that flow from same-sex couples being &quot;bad&quot; are numerous. Same-sex couples are denied financial assistance in the areas of health care, pensions, workers' compensation, and income tax. Same-sex couples cannot take advantage of state planning schemes respecting property division, intestacy, and spousal support. Same-sex families often cannot even form or function due to the inability to obtain leave from work, sponsor a partner for immigration purposes, or obtain the unrestricted custody of children. In most Canadian jurisdictions, same-sex couples are not protected against any private acts of discrimination. In those jurisdictions
where there is protection, it is usually restricted to discrimination relating to the provision of services, accommodation, and employment. Because same-sex couples are labeled &quot;bad,&quot; they are denied tools
available to opposite-sex couples that aid in the formation of viable family units. 
<p>
It is most likely that this inequity will be redressed through <cite>Charter</cite> litigation. Despite the prevalence of homophobic judgments and unsatisfactory legal reasoning, the majority of recent legal reforms in this area have emanated from court challenges. Yet, to the extent that representation on the judiciary continues to represent male heterosexual privilege, same-sex spousal claimants will continue to encounter impediments such as &quot;similarly-situated&quot; arguments and dictionary-definition justifications.
<p>
Because of this intransigence, those advocating for change must be clear regarding different strategies that have been proposed as a means of furthering lesbian and gay rights. Possibly the most prominent debate has revolved around the issue of whether same-sex couples should argue for inclusion in the conventional notion of family and hence transform it from within, or whether same-sex couples should aim to dismantle this inherently heterosexist
institution from without. As was suggested in Part III, one approach does not necessarily preclude the other. Although sameness or inclusion arguments would be more productive in effecting an initial shift in the status quo conception of family, both approaches contribute to the deconstruction of the oppressive tenets of the conventional family and to the acceptance of a more universal conception of family.
<p>
Ultimately, pluralistic definitions of family will be not only recognized statutorily, but also accepted intimately by most Canadians, including the judiciary. Although the discrimination discussed in this article is pervasive, several prominent lesbian and gay rights cases in the past decade indicate a possible shift away from this legacy of entrenched homophobia. It is to be hoped that this trend will continue and evolve to the point where lesbian and
gay families are able to participate fully in Canadian society.
<p><br><hr><p>
<CENTER><H2>Endnotes</H2></CENTER>
<OL>
<a name="note">*</a> I wish to thank Janet Mosher, who thoughtfully encouraged initial drafts of this paper, and the J.S.D. Tory Foundation, whose support prompted subsequent revisions.
<p>
<li><a name="one">The term</a> &quot;functional family&quot; is meant to be an inclusive term that refers to individuals who unite for purposes <i>such as</i> childbearing, child rearing, emotional support, financial support, and cohabitation. (The concept of a &quot;functional family&quot; is discussed further in Part III.)  In contrast, the term &quot;conventional family&quot; refers to a family unit in which there are a man and a woman who typically are married and who typically have children. According to this conventional stereotype, it is usually the man who engages in paid employment and the woman who performs unpaid house and child-rearing work.  &quot;Ideally&quot; this family is also white and middle-class. It is important to note that the term &quot;conventional family&quot; is used instead of the more common &quot;traditional family&quot; as a means of challenging the presupposition that families have always conformed to what is now the dominant family form. In fact, it is arguable that the current dominant conception of family extends only as far back as Judeo-Christianity itself. See D. Greenberg, <cite>The Construction of Homosexuality</cite> (Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1988).
<p>
<li><a name="two">The implicit</a> assumption in this article is that political/social change and legislative change happen concurrently and reinforce one another. Changing social conceptions of what constitutes an appropriate family spur legislative change and <i>vice versa</i>. In this respect, arguments that advocate political/social change are interchangeable with those that advocate legislative change.
<p>
<li><a name="three">The footnotes</a> to this article should serve as an invitation to the reader to explore further the issues discussed. This article contributes to the existing scholarship by focusing its discussion of discrimination on the following issues: (1) how resistance to lesbian and gay liberation can be seen as an attempt to safeguard a male-dominated, heterosexist social order; (2) the way in which difference theory is used to perpetuate this discrimination; (3) how judicial prejudice has undercut protection afforded by the <cite>Canadian Charter
of Rights and Freedoms</cite> (see <i>infra</i> note 83); (4) strategies lesbian and gay activists can employ when advocating for change; and (5) how this debate contributes to the evolution of the concept of &quot;family.&quot;  It should also be noted, at the outset, that all of the articles, judgments, and texts referred to in this article reflect, at least to some extent, the perspectives of the individual writers. Although my perspective as a gay man is relevant to the discussion offered in this article, it is by no means determinative. As within any other group, there is wide divergence within the lesbian and gay community as to how these issues can best be resolved. This divergence will be highlighted in Part III.
<p>
<li><a name="four">J. Mosher,</a> &quot;The Harms of Dichotomy: Access to Welfare Benefits as a Case in Point&quot; (1991) 9 C.J.F.L. 97 at 99--116.
<p>
<li><a name="five">Dichotomy</a> can also be seen as a means by which the disadvantage of women is perpetuated. According to Mosher, the dichotomies associated with this disadvantage are: public/private, labour market/family, independence/dependence. The former, &quot;male&quot; attributes are valued by society while those latter attributes which are associated with women are not. For a discussion of dichotomy and its relation to the perpetuation of the disadvantage of women, see Mosher, <i>ibid.</i>
<p>
<li><a name="six">Greenberg,</a> <i>supra</i> note 1. It should be noted that Canada's varied ethnic, racial, and cultural groups, each with their own particular social institutions and norms, are all subjected to an overarching Euro-centric/male heterosexist social structure, particularly in governing institutions such as the judiciary, and are all subjected to the marginalization that results from being labeled &quot;different.&quot;
<p>
<li><a name="seven">With respect</a> to individual court cases, this difference can be conclusive. See <i>Andrews 2, infra</i> note 12, and <cite>Egan</cite> (F.C.T.D. and F.C.A.), <i>infra</i> note 46.
<p>
<li><a name="eight">See Part II</a> for a more complete discussion of how these distinctions violate s. 15 of the <cite>Charter</cite>.
<p>
<li><a name="nine"><cite>Andrews</cite>, <i>infra</i> note 86 at 18.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="ten"><cite>Constitution Act, 1982</cite></a>, being Schedule B to the <cite>Canada Act 1982</cite> (U.K.), c. 11, s. 91(26).
<p>
<li><a name="eleven">B. Ryder,</a> &quot;Equality Rights and Sexual Orientation: Confronting Heterosexual Family Privilege&quot; (1990) 9 C.J.F.L. 39 at 52. Ryder's article offers a broad survey of the different types of
discrimination faced by same-sex couples. Part I of this paper, which also surveys this discrimination, complements Ryder's research by highlighting recent legislative and judicial developments and by focusing its analysis on issues such as those listed in note 3, <i>supra</i>.
<p>
<li><a name="twelve"><cite>Corbett v. Corbett</cite>,</a> [1970] 2 All E.R. 33 (P.D.A.); <cite>B. v. A.</cite> (1991), 29 R.F.L. (3d) 258 (Ont. S.C.); <cite>Adams and Sullivan v. Howerton</cite> (1980), 486 Fed. Supp. 1119 (U.S. Dist. Ct); <cite>Anderson v. Luoma</cite> (1986), 50 R.F.L. (2d) 127 (B.C.S.C.); <cite>Re Andrews et al. and Minister of Health for Ontario et al.</cite> (1988), 64 O.R. (2d) 258 (Ont. H.C.) [hereinafter <cite>Andrews 2</cite>]. In <cite>Layland v. Ontario (Minister of Consumer and Commercial Relations)</cite> (17 March 1993, Action No. 234/92, Ont. Div. Ct) [unreported], two men sought judicial review of the refusal of the City Clerk's Office of Ottawa to issue them a marriage certificate. Southey J. ruled that, according to the common law, two people of the same sex could not marry. In contrast, Greer J.'s dissent highlights the evolving nature of the common law:
<blockquote>
One of the questions the Court was being asked to consider was whether there was a common law prohibition against same-sex marriages. The object of the common law is to solve difficulties and adjust relations in social and commercial life. It must meet, so far as it can, sets of fact abnormal as well as usual. It must grow with the development of the nation. It must face and deal with changing or novel circumstances. Unless it can do that it fails in its function and declines in its dignity and value. An expanding society demands an expanding common law. 
<p>
That the common law expands to meet social needs is not a new concept. The above words were written by McCardie J. of the King's Bench Division in a 1924 sale of goods case, <cite>Prager v. Blatspiel, Stamp and Heacock, Ltd.</cite>, [1924] 1 K.B. 566 at 570. The common law does not remain static. Its very essence is that it is able to grow to meet the expanding needs of society.
</blockquote>
<li><a name="thirteen">For example,</a> the <cite>Family Law Act</cite>, R.S.O. 1990, c. F.3, defines &quot;spouse&quot; in ss 1(1) and 29 as &quot;either of a man and woman who are married to each other&quot; and &quot;either of a man and woman who are not married to each other and have cohabited (a) continuously for a
period of not less than three years.&quot;  It is interesting to note that an opposite-sex requirement is superimposed on the marriage requirement. Given the inability of same-sex couples to marry, it is not clear why this added requirement is necessary.
<p>
<li><a name="fourteen">For example,</a> the regulations to the <cite>Health Insurance Act</cite> (R.R.O. 1980, Reg. 452, s. 1(c)), which formed the basis of the <cite>Andrews 2</cite> case (<i>supra</i> note 12) define &quot;dependant&quot; as &quot;the spouse of an insured person,&quot; with no subsequent definition of the word &quot;spouse.&quot;
<p>
<li><a name="fifteen">For example,</a> in <cite>Andrews 2</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 12 at 261, McRae J. states that &quot;in approximately 79 statutes in Ontario where the word `spouse' is used it always refers to a person of the opposite sex. . . . I have been referred to and have resorted to a number of dictionaries among them---Black's Law Dictionary, The Oxford Dictionary, Jowitts Dictionary of English Law, the Random House Dictionary and others. All define spouse as an opposite sex partner.&quot;
<p>
<li><a name="sixteen">Whether</a> or not this is an optimal course of action with respect to the furtherance of the
interests of same-sex couples will be discussed in Part III.
<p>
<li><a name="seventeen"><cite>Immigration Act</cite>,</a> R.S.C. 1985, c. I--2, s. 3(c) and <cite>Immigration Regulations</cite>, C.R.C. 1978, c. 940, ss 41(1) and 43(1), respectively.
<p>
<li><a name="eighteen">In his article</a> &quot;From Subversion to Liberation: Homosexuals and the Immigration Act, 1952--1957&quot; (1987) 2 C.J.L. &amp; Soc. 1, Philip Girard explains that lesbians and gays were originally included in the category of persons prohibited from entering Canada for security reasons (Cold War
blackmail), largely as a result of U.S. government lobbying. Girard states that although this may have been a valid concern (although not necessarily a valid justification) in the 1950s, increasing focus on the law's discriminatory nature and stigmatizing effect (&quot;homosexuals&quot; were grouped with prostitutes, beggars, pimps, and vagrants, for example) resulted in its amendment in 1976.
<p>
<li><a name="nineteen"><cite>Immigration Regulations</cite></a>, <i>supra</i> note 17 at s. 41(1). In response to recommendation #31 of the <cite>Report of the Parliamentary Committee on Equality Rights</cite>, <i>infra</i> note 36, that &quot;section 3(f) of the <cite>Immigration Act</cite> be amended to state, that . . . the Act, the Immigration Regulations, and immigration guidelines contain standards of admission that do not discriminate in a manner prohibited by the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>,&quot; then Minister of Justice John Crosbie stated that the government proposed to &quot;amend subsection 3(f) to provide that standards of admission should not discriminate in a manner prohibited by the <cite>Charter</cite>.&quot; See <cite>Toward Equality</cite>, <i>infra</i> note 35 at 27. With regard to whether sexual orientation is a prohibited ground of discrimination under the <cite>Charter</cite>, see Part III, Section A. To date, there has been no successful <cite>Charter</cite> challenge to the government's exclusion of same-sex families from the <cite>Immigration Act</cite> and no corresponding amendment.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty">In her article,</a> &quot;Defining `Family'---A Comment on the Family Reunification Provisions in the <cite>Immigration Act</cite>&quot; (1988) 3 J.L. &amp; Social Pol'y 104 at 110, D. McIntosh notes that, although an application may be brought on &quot;humanitarian and compassionate grounds,&quot; the prospects of an immigration official admitting a lesbian or gay partner into Canada on this basis is highly unlikely
given the fact that the prohibition against lesbian and gay immigrants was removed from the <cite>Immigration Act</cite> only in 1976. Nevertheless, at least one lawyer, Mary Joseph of Toronto, has been successful in advancing the immigration claims of her clients using this ground (M. Joseph, Address (The 29th Annual Conference on Law and Contemporary Affairs: Challenging Public and Private Boundaries, 5 February 1993, Toronto) [unpublished]).
<p>
<li><a name="twenty1">Social assistance</a> in Ontario is currently administered through the <cite>Family
Benefits Act</cite>, R.S.O. 1990, c. F.2 and the <cite>General Welfare Assistance Act</cite>, R.S.O. 1990, c. G.6.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty2">M. Leighton,</a> &quot;Handmaids' Tales: Family Benefits Assistance and the Single-Mother-Led Family&quot; (1987) 45 U.T. Fac. L. Rev. 324 at 327. Prior to 1986, attribution of income occurred whenever two persons were &quot;spouses,&quot; &quot;spouse&quot; being defined as two people who &quot;lived together as if they were husband and wife&quot; (R.R.O. 1980, Reg. 318, s. 1). Amendments to this regulation, which were passed in 1986 and 1987, narrowed this definition so as to allow less administrative discretion when determining whether individuals were spouses for the purposes of attribution (R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 366, s. 1). For example, s. 1(2) now directs that &quot;sexual factors shall not be investigated or considered.&quot; Nevertheless, the new regulations still leave much room for the use of stereotype when ascertaining whether or not income should be attributed. For an analysis of how social assistance legislation contributes to the perpetuation of the disadvantage faced by women, see Mosher, <i>supra</i> note 4.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty3">Ironically</a>, a same-sex couple's assertion that they are &quot;spouses&quot; would likely have the effect of reducing the entitlement of the recipient spouse.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty4">S.O. 1992, c. 30 (formerly &quot;Bill 108&quot;).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="twenty5">S.O. 1992, c. 31 (formerly &quot;Bill 109&quot;).</a>
<p>
<li><a name="twenty6">Section 1(2) of both Acts.</a> It is interesting to note that the definition of &quot;partner&quot; is in addition to a somewhat standard definition of &quot;spouse&quot;: 
<ol type="a">... a person of the opposite sex,
<li>to whom the person is married, or
<li>with whom the person is living in a conjugal relationship outside of marriage, if the two persons,
<ol type="i">
<li>have cohabited for at least one year,
<li>are together the parents of a child, or
<li>have together entered into a cohabitation agreement under section 53 of the <cite>Family Law Act</cite>.
</ol></ol>
It is arguably easier to satisfy the definition of &quot;spouse.&quot;  See Part III, Section B.
