<li><a name="fifty6">(1979), 10 R.F.L. (2d) 32 at 41 (Man. Q.B.).</a> It is interesting to note that most of the judgment focuses on the inappropriateness of the mother's behavior. In this respect, note Hamilton J.'s comment, also at 41: &quot;On balance, I am more concerned with the harmful effect of the mother's way of life on the child than I am with respect to some of the uncertainties with respect to the care and attention the father can provide.&quot;  A similar double standard seems to exist with respect to post-divorce or post-separation relationships. As Ryder notes, <i>supra</i> note 11 at 59, the reluctance of courts to grant custody to parents in a
same-sex relationship is in sharp contrast with the courts' increased willingness to grant custody to the parent who is involved in an opposite-sex relationship, irrespective of whether they are married. Compare Ryder's assessment of this situation with that of J. Atkinson, <cite>Modern Child Custody Practice</cite>, Vol. 1 (New York: Kluwer Law Book, 1986) at 290, who contends that courts treat homosexual parents similarly to the manner in which they treat
