<li><a name="seventy1">&quot;Private acts of discrimination&quot;</a> refers to situations of discrimination in which there is little or no governmental involvement.
<p>
<li><a name="seventy2">As clarified by the Supreme Court of Canada</a> in <cite>R.W.D.S.U. v. Dolphin Delivery Ltd.</cite>, [1986] 2 S.C.R. 573, the <cite>Charter</cite> protects only against acts of government or of individuals or institutions with a sufficient nexus to government. The <cite>Charter</cite> offers no protection against private acts of discrimination.
