<li><a name="ninety1">Whether or not sexual</a> orientation is a protected ground of discrimination under the <cite>Charter</cite> has yet to be specifically pronounced by the Supreme Court of Canada, although there have been lower court rulings. For example, in <cite>Birch</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 73, the Ontario Court of Appeal ruled that it is an included ground. <cite>Charter</cite> issues were not raised in the Supreme Court of Canada in <cite>Mossop</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 29.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety2"><cite>Andrews</cite></a>, <i>supra</i> note 86 at 18. As noted previously, defenders of the status quo would assert that the differences in treatment discussed in this article amount to
mere distinction, not discrimination. The similarly-situated test, which is discussed in the following section, is also used to deny same-sex couples <cite>Charter</cite> protection.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety3">According to McIntyre J.,</a> <i>ibid.</i> at 15, the &quot;purpose of s. 15 is to ensure equality in the formulation and application of the law. The promotion of equality entails the promotion of a society in which all are secure in the knowledge that they are recognized at law as human beings equally deserving of concern, respect, and consideration.&quot;
<p>
<li><a name="ninety4"><i>Ibid.</i> at 24.</a>
