<li><a name="ninety6"><i>Ibid.</i></a> referring to <cite>Hunter v. Southam Inc.</cite>, [1984] 2 S.C.R. 145, and <cite>R. v. Big M Drug Mart Ltd.</cite>, [1985] 1 S.C.R. 295.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety7">In <cite>Andrews 2</cite></a>, <i>supra</i> note 12 at 263, McRae J. states that &quot;[h]omosexual couples living together in a domestic situation therefore can be identified as a distinct
class.&quot;  But McRae J. then goes on to use the discredited similarly situated test (see Part II, Section B) to justify his conclusion that s. 15 discrimination has not occurred in this case: &quot;Homosexual couples are <i>not</i> similarly situated to heterosexual couples. Heterosexual couples procreate and raise children . . . [T]he applicants are being treated in exactly the same manner as all of the other unmarried (whether in the legal or `common-law' sense) people in the province. Heterosexual couples of the same sex, brothers and
brothers, sisters and sisters, brothers and sisters, cousins, parents and adult children and any combination of them may be living together under similar circumstances to the applicants but would in each case pay OHIP premiums as `single persons.'&quot;  With regard to s. 1, McRae J. states at 265 that &quot;[t]he legislative objective of establishing and maintaining <i>traditional families</i> is one of substantial importance.&quot;  [emphasis added] This support of traditional families was gratuitous in light of the fact that no s. 15 violation was found.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety8">See <cite>Veysey v. Correctional Services of Canada</cite></a> (1990), 109 N.R. 300 at 304 (F.C.A.); <cite>Knodel</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 88 at 371.
<p>
<li><a name="ninety9">See <cite>Equality for All</cite></a>, <i>supra</i> note 36 at 29. In <cite>Toward Equality</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 36 at 13, then Minister of Justice John Crosbie stated that the &quot;Department of Justice is of the view that the courts will find that sexual orientation is encompassed by the guarantees in section 15 of the <cite>Charter</cite>. The government will take whatever measures are
necessary to ensure that sexual orientation is a prohibited ground of discrimination in relation to all areas of federal jurisdiction.&quot; More recently, then Minister of Justice Kim Campbell stated that &quot;the government's commitment in 1986 with respect to sexual orientation was to do whatever is required. The government has taken the position that it (sexual orientation) is covered by section 15 of the <cite>Charter</cite>.&quot;  See Ryder, <i>supra</i> note 11 at 76.
<p>
