<HEAD>
<TITLE>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 52 No. 1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>[<A HREF="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol52#1">Volume 52 Number 1</A>]</CENTER>
<P><BR>
<H1>Comments<br>
Council and Court: Prospects in <cite>Lockerbie</cite> for an International Rule of Law <a href="#note">*</a></h1>

<i>With the Cold War's demise, the Security Council now enjoys powers formerly checked by reciprocal vetos. The
first test of this new ascendancy came via a Libyan application to the International Court of Justice in 1992. At stake was the validity of two Security Council resolutions which responded to the destruction of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland. On 14 April 1992, the Court declined Libya's request for provisional relief. This article construes the Court's Order as highlighting the need for a system of judicial review within the United Nations. Such
a system would likely have led the Court to a different decision in</i> Lockerbie<i>. The legitimate activity of all United Nations organs is limited. Constraints are informed in part by what is termed an international rule of law, which in the last resort mandates oversight of these constraints by the Court. The proposal advanced by the author would grant the Court a broad power of</i> certiorari<i> tempered by deferential standards of review.
<p>
Avec la fin de la guerre froide, le Conseil de s&eacute;curit&eacute; peut employer des pouvoirs autrefois bloqu&eacute;s par des v&eacute;tos de r&eacute;ciprocit&eacute;. Cette nouvelle ascension a &eacute;t&eacute; mise &agrave; l'&eacute;preuve pour la premi&egrave;re fois par une demande libyenne &agrave; la Cour internationale de justice en 1992. Cette demande remettait en question la validit&eacute; de deux r&eacute;solutions du Conseil de s&eacute;curit&eacute; li&eacute;es &agrave; la destruction du vol Pan Am 103 au-dessus de Lockerbie en &eacute;cosse. Le 14 avril 1992, la Cour a rejet&eacute; la demande libyenne de secours provisoire. Cet article interpr&egrave;te la d&eacute;cision de la Cour comme l'expression de la necessit&eacute; d'un syst&egrave;me d'examen judiciaire &agrave; l'int&eacute;rieur m&ecirc;me des Nations unies. Un tel syst&egrave;me aurait probablement men&eacute; &agrave; une d&eacute;cision diff&eacute;rente dans l'affaire </i>Lockerbie<i>. Les activit&eacute;s l&eacute;gitimes de tous les organes des Nations unies sont limit&eacute;es. Ils se trouvent contraints par ce qu'on appelle l'autorit&eacute; international de la loi, qui, en dernier ressort, exige que la Cour passe outre &agrave; ces contraintes. La proposition de l'auteur donnerait &agrave; la Cour un large pouvoir de </i><b>certiorari</b><i>, temp&eacute;r&eacute; par un comportement de d&eacute;f&eacute;rence lors de l'examen judiciaire.</i>
<p>
<h3>I. Introduction</h3>

In 1890, William Edward Hall observed that, over the centuries, international law progressed in fifty-year intervals,
emerging in a more solid position at the end of each period than that which it occupied at the beginning.<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> While he predicted that the world would still engage in great wars, he concluded that the international system would, after each conflict, atone by embracing &quot;straighter obligations than those which it before acknowledged.&quot;<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> The twentieth century has been kind to Hall's thesis. First at Versailles, then at San Francisco, we have increasingly sought to consolidate the yields of peace by agreeing to strict measures for international governance.
<p>
Nearly fifty years after San Francisco, we witness the demise of another war. With it has come the collapse of the Soviet Union, freedom in Eastern and Baltic Europe, a reunified Germany, and the possibility of Middle Eastern peace. These events have inspired a renewed scrutiny of the mechanisms and principles that shape the international community.<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup> They have also changed the dynamic within existing structures. In this flux, the United Nations seeks to confirm its efficacy as an instrument of dispute resolution and peace making.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> As a result, the United Nations Security Council is only now invoking the full powers that were accorded it in 1945, but that the Cold War had paralysed through a pattern of reciprocal vetos. Given this Security Council ascendancy, it was only a matter of time before a member state questioned anew the limits of the Council's competence.
<p>
That state proved to be Libya. Held responsible for the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, and on the receiving end of two Security Council resolutions demanding extradition of two accused, Libya applied to the International Court of Justice for a vindication of what it claimed were violated treaty rights. Pending the Court's
disposition of the application, Libya also requested provisional relief to enjoin any coercion. The application to the Court was widely regarded as a desperate and cynical example of a state trying to evade responsibility for its terrorist acts. Whether this conclusion was justified or not, the fascinating questions raised by the case remind us that even inglorious claimants can raise worthwhile issues.<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup>
<p>
The decision by which the Court declined to indicate provisional measures<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> has variously been praised as potentially &quot;the most important and jurisprudentially rich of any handed down by this Court since the end of the Cold War&quot;<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> and criticized as
&quot;another blow&quot;<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> to respect for the Court and perhaps &quot;a tombstone to the premature end to the `New World Order'.&quot;<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> The case presented an extraordinary situation arising from the simultaneous treatment of a dispute by the Security Council and the Court. Before this case, their concomitant exercise of concurrent but not exclusive powers had not given rise to serious
problems. The Pan Am 103 dispute, however, presented new challenges through the possibility of inconsistent decisions between the two organs. <cite>Lockerbie</cite> therefore provided a rare opportunity to confront directly the relationship between the Security Council and the Court, a relationship still not fully defined, thanks largely to
Cold War tensions.
<p>
I will suggest that most of the majority and dissenting opinions disappoint in their failure to give adequate consideration to the constitutional questions of <cite>Lockerbie</cite>, and that provisional measures should likely have been indicated. By not construing the United Nations Charter as an international constitution, the judgments leave ambiguous whether or not the Security Council---as distinct from the Charter---is above or beyond the reach of the Court.<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> It is true that the application was only preliminary, and clearly some allowance must be made for a decision not on the merits. Yet we ought not to allow the possibility of a hypothetical merits stage to excuse an insufficiently nuanced verdict at the provisional stage. If indeed <cite>Lockerbie</cite> proceeds to its merits, the dispute may well have been resolved by the United Nations sanctions now in place or even by the use of force.<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> If the case does not proceed to its merits, then the decision on interim measures will be the Court's last word on the matter. For this reason, it is proper to ask whether the Court brought the appropriate level of rigour, even at the provisional stage, to its analysis.
<p>
Unfortunately, the Court's denial of provisional measures turned on the inflexibly formal observation that the Security Council had acted under Chapter VII of the United Nations Charter.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup> Article 25 of the Charter renders Council decisions under Chapter VII obligatory, and by Article 103 all Charter obligations trump those arising under any other international arrangement. By this simple reasoning, the Court threatened to preclude, &quot;in blanket fashion, the exercise of judicial jurisdiction <i>whenever</i> and <i>simply because</i> the Council is in a chapter VII decision mode.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> It also allowed the Court to postpone the formulation of a coherent theory with which to resolve future conflicts; the majority did not need such a theory, and the dissenting judges did not suggest a viable alternative.
<p>
This article, using <cite>Lockerbie</cite> as a vehicle, will explore the relationship between the United Nations Security Council and the International Court of Justice, and the prospects for what I will call an international rule of law for these two organs. What I hope to show is that a commitment to this rule of law necessitates a limited system of judicial review within the United Nations. This system affirms the Court as the ultimate safeguard against patently unreasonable violations of institutional competence and principles of general or customary international law.
<p>
<h3>II.   Background</h3>

1. PAN AM 103
<p>
On the evening of 21 December 1988, Pan American Airliner 103 departed London Heathrow bound for New York. The <cite>Maid of the Seas</cite>' flight ended thirty-eight minutes later, when the Boeing 747 exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing all 259 passengers and crew on board and a further 11 local residents on the ground.
Investigations into the cause of the explosion began immediately. Following the questioning of 14 000 individuals in 50 countries and after hours of forensic analysis, suspicion focused on Syrian and Iranian complicity: the bomb was of a type used by a Syrian-based terrorist group backed by Iran.<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> Theories abounded that the bombing retaliated for the downing of an Iranian airbus by U.S. Navy warship <cite>Vincennes</cite> on 3 July 1988.<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> By mid-1990, however, attention shifted.<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup> An inch-by-inch search of the 845-square-mile area surrounding the crash site yielded fragments of the bomb's timing device that led investigators toward Libya.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup>
<p>
On 14 November 1991, three years after the bombing, a United States federal grand jury in Washington, D.C., indicted two Libyan nationals---Abdel Baset Ali Mohamed al-Megrahi and Al Amin Khalife Fhimah<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> ---on charges of having caused the bomb to be placed on Pan Am 103. The 193-count indictment identified the two accused as officials of Libyan Arab Airlines and members of Libya's intelligence organization. Simultaneous charges were laid by the Lord Advocate of Scotland against the two men for conspiracy, murder, and contravention of the <cite>Aviation Security Act</cite> of 1982.<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> The two were alleged to have placed the bomb or caused it to have been placed on board Air Malta Flight KM180 from Luqa Airport, Malta, to Frankfurt's Main Airport. Several ounces of Semtex plastic explosives had allegedly been concealed within a Toshiba radio cassette player and placed in a bronze-coloured Samsonite suitcase filled with clothes. This suitcase
had then been transferred without further inspection to cargo container AVE 4041 PA on Pan American flight PA 103A to Heathrow.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> In London, baggage handlers stowed the container in a forward cargo bay of flight 103 bound for New York, John F. Kennedy Airport.<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup>
<p>
Both American and British statements asserted that a mosaic of physical evidence revealed Libyan state responsibility.<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> Libya immediately denied the American and
British charges, and suggested that they be submitted to the International Court of Justice or some other neutral body for adjudication. The U.S. State Department rejected the suggestion outright, saying that (a) the indictments were a matter for United States courts to settle;<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> (b) no competent international tribunal existed to try the accused; and (c) the Libyan government could not be
expected to prosecute vigorously the agents it ordered to carry out the deed.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> Less than one week after the American and British charges, Libyan Supreme Court Justice Ahmed al-Taher al-Zawi was named by Libya to conduct an inquiry into the allegations. The Libyan government confirmed its judiciary's readiness to cooperate with all legal authorities in the United States and the United Kingdom. It also announced the appointment of a new intelligence chief, perceived by some as a sign that the Colonel Muammar el-Qaddafi government was anxious to dispel charges that its security agencies engaged in terrorism.
<p>
On 27 November 1991, the United States and the United Kingdom issued joint statements, demanding the surrender of the two indicted Libyan nationals, and repeating that Libya must take &quot;responsibility
for the actions of Libyan officials.&quot;<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> They also demanded
compensation for the bombing and for the production of witnesses and evidence for the case.<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> In response, the Libyan government issued a communiqu&eacute;, stating that the application would be dealt with seriously and in accordance with principles of international law.
Judge al-Zawi announced that the two Libyan suspects had been placed under house arrest, were being questioned, and would face the death penalty if convicted. He also ruled out handing the suspects over to
Britain or any other country for trial; however, Judge al-Zawi did request the assistance of American and British authorities, offering to travel to these countries to review evidence and to cooperate with his counterparts. He also proposed a meeting of legal experts from the two countries and Libya to aid his investigation. None of his proposals received any response.<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> At the same time, Ali Treiki, Libyan delegate to the Arab League, indicated that his government would accept a judge nominated by the United Nations to decide the fate of the two suspects.<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup>
<p>
Unsatisfied with these responses, the United States, France,<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> and the United Kingdom agreed in December 1991 to begin a campaign to win international support for sanctions against Libya.<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> Just over one week later the United States rejected Libya's invitation for the West to send judges to the trial of the two accused.<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> On 2 January 1992, these three Western powers sent their ambassadors to put their case in the capitals of the twelve other member countries of the Security Council. Initial preference among the United States, the United Kingdom, and France had been to impose trade penalties immediately. After sounding out other Security Council members, though, they opted for a slower step-by-step approach.<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> The United States' representative to the United Nations, Thomas R. Pickering, was reported to have advised the Bush Administration that to achieve its objectives in the Security Council, the United States would have to mount a diplomatic campaign of intensity comparable to that of the Persian Gulf crisis. The three allies were said to have postponed their campaign after calculating that changes in the roster of the Security Council would make the body more sympathetic to their plans after January 1992. At that time, Cuba, the Ivory Coast, Romania, Yemen, and Zaire were to leave the Council and be replaced by Venezuela, Japan, Morocco, Cape Verde, and Hungary. With Japan having assumed one of the seats reserved for African and Asian states, the number of Council members belonging to the so-called non-aligned movement fell from seven to six. As a consequence, with only nine votes necessary to adopt a resolution, the non-aligned nations could no longer prevent the adoption of resolutions by the fifteen-member Council.<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup>
<p>
In letters dated 17 January 1992, Ibrahim Mohammed Elbushari, Libya's Secretary of the People's Committee for Foreign Liaison and International Cooperation, notified James A. Baker, U.S. Secretary of State, and Douglas Hurd, U.K. Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, that all three countries were parties to the 1971 <cite>Montreal Convention for the Suppression of Unlawful Acts Against the Safety of Civil Aviation</cite><sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> and that Libya had complied with all its obligations under that convention. Elbushari's letter, issued under Article 14(1) of the Montreal Convention, requested arbitration of the dispute. Neither the United States nor Britain acceded to this request.
<p>
2. SECURITY COUNCIL RESOLUTION 731 (1992)
<p>
After two months of intense diplomatic efforts, the United Nations Security Council unanimously adopted resolution 731 (1992).<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> It confirmed that the Security Council, determined to eliminate international terrorism,
<ol>
<li><i>Condemns</i> the destruction of Pan American flight 103 ... and the resultant loss of hundreds of
lives;
<li><i>Strongly deplores</i> the fact that the Libyan Government has not yet responded effectively to the above requests [by the United States and the United Kingdom] to cooperate fully in establishing responsibility for the terrorist acts ... against Pan American flight 103 ... ; [and]
<li><i>Urges</i> the Libyan Government immediately to provide a full and effective response to those requests so as to contribute to the elimination of international terrorism; ... .<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup>
</ol>
Resolution 731 (1992) was particularly noteworthy in two respects. It represented the first time that the Security Council had been asked to call for the extradition of the citizens of one country to stand trial in another. It also marked the first occasion that the Security Council had given implicit support to accusations of state-sponsored terrorism against a member government of the United Nations.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> Libya responded to the resolution with disinformation. On 11 February 1992, for example, Qaddafi was reported to be planning an announcement that the two suspects had disappeared and may have been executed.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup>
<p>
3. REFERENCE OF DISPUTE BY LIBYA TO INTERNATIONAL COURT OF JUSTICE
<p>
On 3 March 1992 Libya instituted proceedings in the International Court of Justice against the United States of America and the United Kingdom in respect of &quot;a dispute ... between Libya and the United States over the interpretation or application of the Montreal Convention.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> The Court was asked to adjudge and declare the following:
<ol type="a">
<li>that Libya has fully complied with all of its obligations under the Montreal Convention;
<li>that the United States and the United Kingdom have breached, and are continuing to breach, their legal obligations to Libya under Article 5(2), 5(3), 7, 8(2) and 11 of the Montreal Convention; and
<li>that the United States and the United Kingdom are under a legal obligation immediately to cease and desist from such breaches and from the use of any and all force or threats against Libya, including the threat of force against Libya, and from all violations of the sovereignty, territorial integrity, and the political independence of Libya.
</ol>
Libya also asked the Court to indicate provisional measures as follows:
<ol type="a">
<li>to enjoin the United States from taking any action against Libya calculated to coerce or to compel Libya to
surrender the accused individuals to any jurisdiction outside of Libya; and
<li>to ensure that no steps are taken that would prejudice in any way the rights of Libya with respect to the legal proceedings that are the subject of Libya's application.
</ol>
Parallel with its application to the Court, Libya offered to hand the two accused to a neutral country for trial.<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> The United States on the following day dismissed the offer, characterizing it as a delaying tactic. U.S. State Department spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler did regard the
gesture, however, as an admission that Libya recognized its ability to surrender Libyan nationals.<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> On 23 March 1992, Libya made a new offer to hand the two accused Libyans over to the Arab League.<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup>
<p>
4. PLEADINGS BEFORE INTERNATIONAL COURT OF JUSTICE
<p>
During oral pleadings on Libya's application to the Court, the litigants advanced two sets of arguments, one relating to the Montreal Convention and Libya's request for interim measures, and the other pertaining to the relationship between the Security Council and the Court. On the first set, the United States and the United Kingdom contended the following points, each of which was contested by Libya: (a) that Libya had failed to provide the Court <i>prima facie</i> jurisdiction due to the absence of a &quot;dispute&quot;; (b) that, if such a &quot;dispute&quot; existed, Libya had failed to show that it could not be settled through negotiation; (c) that even if the &quot;dispute&quot; could not be resolved through negotiation, Libya's request for arbitration was inadequate; (d) that even if the request for arbitration had been adequate, the matter had been brought prematurely with respect to the six-month period in Article 14(1) of the Montreal Convention; (e) that there was no nexus between the rights sought to be protected and
the provisional measures requested; (f) that there was insufficient urgency to warrant interim protection; and (g) that a failure to indicate interim measures would not result in irreparable harm to the Applicant.
<p>
On the second set of submissions, pertaining to the relationship between the Security Council and the Court, the United Kingdom argued that Libya's request for interim measures should be denied because it was intended merely to fetter the Security Council in the exercise of its powers and to preclude it from broadening its action to include
Libya as a state actor in terrorism. The United States asserted that the Court should decline provisional measures simply because the Security Council was already seized of the matter. 
<p>
5. SECURITY COUNCIL RESOLUTION 748 (1992)
<p>
Unsatisfied with the Libyan response to resolution 731 (1992), the United States, the United Kingdom, and France opted to elevate the matter into Chapter VII of the Charter and to threaten Libya with economic sanctions if it continued to refuse to extradite the two accused. China indicated its opposition to sanctions against individual countries. After voicing this position, China was advised by the United States, Britain, and France that it would risk losing trade preferences from the United States and seriously impair relations with the other two countries were Beijing to veto a resolution on the sanctions.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup> The Security Council passed resolution 748 (1992) on 31 March 1992, by a margin of 10 votes to 0.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> Five countries, including China, abstained. The resolution reaffirmed resolution 731 (1992) and continued as follows:
<blockquote>
<i>Determining</i> ... that the failure by the Libyan Government to demonstrate by concrete actions its renunciation of terrorism and in particular its continued failure to respond fully and effectively to the requests in
resolution 731 (1992) constitute a threat to international peace and security, ...
<p>
<i>Acting</i> under Chapter VII of the Charter,
<ol>
<li><i>Decides</i> that the Libyan Government must now comply without any further delay with paragraph 3 of resolution 731 (1992) ...
<li><i>Decides also</i> that the Libyan Government must commit itself definitively to cease all forms of terrorist action and all assistance to terrorist groups and that it must promptly, by concrete actions, demonstrate its renunciation of terrorism; [and]
<li><i>Decides</i> that, on 15 April 1992 all States shall adopt the measures set out below, which shall apply until the Security Council decides that the Libyan Government has complied with paragraphs 1 and 2 above; ... .<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup>
</ol></blockquote>
Although resolution 748 (1992) was passed three days after the completion of oral submissions at the International Court of Justice, the parties were nevertheless invited to return and make submissions on the resolution. Both respondents submitted that, because the resolution bound Libya, it precluded any conflicting order by the Court. Libya, conversely, submitted that because no hierarchy existed between the Security Council and Court within the United Nations, and because each exercised its own competence, the risk of conflicting decisions by the two bodies did not render the Libyan claim inadmissible. Libya regarded both resolutions as contrary to international law, and criticized the Security Council's invocation of Chapter VII as a pretext to elude application of the Montreal Convention.
<p>
On 4 April 1992, Qaddafi rejected the United Nations' renewed demands that the two accused be handed over.<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> Two weeks later, Ibrahim Lagwell, counsel for the two accused,
indicated that they would be willing to go to trial in the West if they were given guarantees that the trial would be
fair.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> The dispute took another turn when the International Court of Justice
ruled on Libya's application for interim relief on 14 April 1992.
<p>
<h3>III.   Judgments by International Court of Justice</h3>

1. ORDER OF THE COURT
<p>
By 11 votes to 5,<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> the Court held that the circumstances of the
cases did not require the exercise of its power under Article 41 of the Statute of the International Court of Justice<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> to indicate provisional measures. The operative component of the terse Order lies in paragraphs 41 through 45 inclusive. The Court first noted that under Article 41 it could not make definitive findings either of fact or of law on the issues relating to the merits; the Court's Order therefore did not
affect the parties' rights to contest such issues at the stage of the merits. The Order's key paragraph<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup> then noted
<blockquote>
[that] both Libya and the United States, as Members of the United Nations, are obliged to accept and carry out the decisions of the Security Council in accordance with Article 25 of the Charter; ... [that] <i>prima facie</i> this obligation extends to the decision contained in resolution 748 (1992); and ... [that] in accordance with Article 103 of the Charter, the obligations of the Parties in that respect prevail over their obligations under any other international agreement, including the Montreal Convention ...<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Therefore it was regarded as inappropriate to protect the rights claimed by Libya under the Montreal Convention through provisional measures. To the contrary, the Court feared that such protection would likely impair the rights that <i>prima facie</i> were enjoyed by the United States by virtue of resolution 748 (1992). In declining to indicate provisional measures, the Court reiterated that it had not been called on to determine the question of its
jurisdiction to entertain the merits of the case; the rights of the Government of Libya and the Government of the United States to submit arguments in respect of this point at the merits stage therefore emerged unaffected from the Order.<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup>
<p>
Given the brief Order by the Court, one must look to the separate and particularly to the dissenting opinions for discussion of the most juridically rich aspects of the case. Indeed, only 3 of the 11 majority judges adopted the majority opinion without comment,<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup> the other 8 indicating one level of displeasure or another with the matters before the Court. The remaining 5 judges each wrote dissenting opinions.
<p>
2. THE CONCURRING DECLARATIONS AND OPINIONS
<p>
Most of the concurring judgments aimed to broaden the basis of the Order beyond resolution 748 (1992). A failure to rely (at least implicitly) on resolution 731 (1992) risked the perception that without the later resolution the Court would have indicated provisional measures. This in turn would have implied a willingness by the Court to reach a decision incompatible with the actions of the Security Council. Acting President Oda therefore felt that provisional measures should have been declined due to a &quot;mismatch&quot; between the Application and the rights that Libya sought to protect.<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> Judge Ni would have denied provisional measures on the basis that the temporal requirement of the Montreal Convention had not been met.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup> The joint declaration by Judges Evensen, Tarassov, Guillaume, and Aguilar Mawdsley agreed fully with the Order and gave only additional comments.
<p>
By contrast, Judge Lachs emphasized that the Court and the Security Council should each perform their functions without prejudicing the exercise of the other's powers. While he felt that the two organs ought therefore to work in harmony, he added interestingly that they were not to act &quot;in concert.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> The failure to indicate measures, he concluded, was not an abdication of the Court's powers but a reflection of the system within which the Court is meant to render justice. Judge Shahabuddeen, however, gave a separate opinion that reluctantly endorsed the Order. Without resolution 748 (1992), he suggested that Libya's application would have been allowed. Because of the Security Council's action, though, the Court had no choice but to take account of resolution 748 (1992) in finding the applicable law. With the resolution presumed to be valid, Articles 25 and 103 of the Charter rendered unenforceable whatever rights Libya might formerly have held. Although he maintained that no imposition of superior authority had taken place, his opinion included a series of questions that go to the heart of the dispute:
<blockquote>
Are there any limits to the Council's powers of appreciation? In the equilibrium of forces underpinning the structure of the United Nations within the evolving international order, is there any conceivable point beyond which a legal issue may properly arise as to the competence of the Security Council to produce such overriding results? If there are any limits, what are those limits and what body, if other than the Security Council, is competent to say what
those limits are?<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup>
</blockquote>
3.  THE DISSENTING OPINIONS
<p>
Each of the five dissenting judges wrote independent opinions, and each found that the circumstances justified the
exercise of the Court's power to indicate provisional measures. All noted the organic but autonomous nature of United Nations organs. They agreed that this autonomy rendered it fully appropriate for the Security Council and the Court to be seized simultaneously with the same matter. Indeed, they noted that the jurisdictions of the two organs had already been invoked concurrently in several prominent cases.<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup> However, the unique aspect of the <cite>Lockerbie</cite> application---namely, that the Court and Security Council had been approached by opposing parties in the dispute---raised the possibility of inconsistent treatments of
the dispute by the Council and Court, a prospect to which the dissenting judges reacted differently. Judge Bedjaoui, for example, objected that the Court's role was not to exercise appellate jurisdiction over the Council, any more than the Council should impair the integrity of the Court's international judicial function.<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> Judge Weeramantry, on the other hand, concluded that owing to the exercise of independent judgment, assessments by the Council and Court would not and need not always be in complete coincidence.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup>
<p>
Several others expressed substantive concerns with the manner in which the dispute was handled. Judge Ajibola regretted that the joint statements of 27 November 1991, and the two Security Council resolutions that relied on them, all appeared to violate the presumption of innocence of the two accused.<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> Judge Shahabuddeen questioned whether an impartial trial was possible in the United States,<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> and Judge <i>ad hoc</i> El-Kosheri wrote that the two accused &quot;could not possibly receive a fair trial, neither in the United States or in the United Kingdom, and not in Libya.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> Judge Bedjaoui criticized the majority's retroactive use of resolution 748 (1992), contending that because the resolution did not yet have legal existence when proceedings before the Court concluded, it should have been beyond the case's purview.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup>
<p>
The dissents also differed on the degree of scrutiny to which they would subject Security Council resolutions at the provisional stage. Judge Bedjaoui regarded such resolutions as enjoying a presumption of validity, of lawfulness, and of binding authority in preliminary matters.<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup> Without being seized of the wider matter, the Court could not censure the Security Council's discretionary characterization of the situation as one likely to threaten international peace and security. Yet Judge Bedjaoui immediately qualified this presumption by exempting a resolution that has &quot;as its object, or effect, not to withdraw a right from an Applicant State, but to prevent the exercise, by the Court itself, of the judicial function with which it has been invested by the Charter.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> In such a situation, conflicting decisions by the Court
and the Security Council would apparently be acceptable since the conflict would arise from an exercise of independent judicial function in laying down international legality.
<p>
Similarly, Judge Weeramantry noted that among the matters entirely within the discretion of the Security Council are determinations under Article 39 of the existence of threats to the peace, breaches of peace, and acts of aggression. For this reason, he observed that the Security Council is the only judge of circumstances that would activate Chapter VII: &quot;[A]ny matter which is the subject of a valid Security Council decision under Chapter VII does not appear, <i>prima facie</i>, to be one with which the Court can properly deal.&quot;<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup> He later concluded that the Court would not confront the Security Council where it had already exercised its powers &quot;<i>in a manner</i> which places obligations upon all United Nations Members&quot;; in areas not covered by the Security Council's &quot;<i>binding</i> decisions under Chapter VII,&quot; the Court would be free to use its influence and authority.<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup> Yet Judge Bedjaoui's and Judge Weeramantry's conclusions confound their premise. If Security Council resolutions are beyond censure at the provisional stage, how is the Court to discern the resolutions that by purpose or effect prevent
its exercise of the judicial function (and are thus invalid)? Assuming that the Security Council would not voice its malign purposes, how is the Court to divine them otherwise? If only the Security Council can assess the circumstances that engage Chapter VII, what would prompt it to declare its own actions invalid? If, instead, it is the Court that should distinguish &quot;valid&quot; decisions from &quot;invalid&quot; ones, how at the provisional stage could a Chapter VII decision ever be declared invalid, given Judge Weeramantry's <i>prima facie</i> presumption in favour of validity?
<p>
Judge <i>ad hoc</i> El-Kosheri took a different approach. He cited the <cite>South West Africa</cite><sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup> decisions as well as Kelsen<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> to suggest that not all authorities regard United Nations members as obliged to carry out all decisions of the Security Council. He thought it possible that by adopting paragraph 1 of resolution 748 (1992), the Security Council may have impeded the Court's jurisdiction freely to exercise its inherent judicial function. In so doing, the Security Council exceeded its authority in a violation of Article 92 of the Charter.<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup> This &quot;<i>ultra vires</i> character&quot; of resolution 748 (1992) was vitiated in light of the warnings of several Security Council delegates<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> regarding the risks of hasty adoption of its draft and a lack of respect for the Court's credibility and judicial function. Even on a <i>prima facie</i> basis, therefore, Judge <i>ad hoc</i> El-Kosheri regarded the resolution as having no legal effect on the Court's jurisdiction.
<p>
<h3>IV.   Rule of Law at the International Level</h3>

As Professor Reisman notes, the nominal constitutional matters in <cite>Lockerbie</cite> were straightforward enough: when the Security Council makes a valid decision under Chapter VII of the Charter concerning a state, that decision prevails over any other treaty-based right claimed by the state.<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup> Yet beneath this simple formula lay a fiendishly difficult problem: what (if anything) renders a decision under Chapter VII invalid, and who ultimately has authority to make this determination? These questions are particularly acute given the special character of Chapter VII decisions, which permit the Security Council to &quot;take such action by air, sea, or land forces as may be necessary to maintain or restore international peace and security.&quot; The importance of the issues in <cite>Lockerbie</cite> makes the brevity of the Court's Order all the more unfortunate, since they were certainly of a type that reached &quot;so far beyond the immediate case as ... to merit some extended examination.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup> Further, the case gave the Court an unequalled chance to pronounce upon these matters: the considerations at issue had never before arisen in so direct and immediate a way, or through as eminent and experienced international lawyers as those before the Court.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> Instead, the brief majority decision relegates to the separate and particularly to the dissenting opinions the pursuit of the most valuable aspects of the application. Doubtless the case's publicity, sensitivity, and provisional status understandably deterred a fuller judgment. Furthermore, some have lauded this judicial caution in the post-Cold War revival of the Security Council.<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup> Yet this caution need not have been displaced by a longer decision that treated the intricacies at stake with more candour and rigour.
<p>
I submit that such candour and explication could have revealed the focus of the case to be the supremacy of the rule of law at the international level.<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup> While only one judge employed this phrase explicitly, others used terminology having similar effect.<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup>
Regardless of the rubric under which these notions are considered, an inquiry into an international rule of law must first ask (as did Judge Weeramantry) whether a circumscribing boundary of norms limits the ambit within which United Nations organs must discharge their responsibilities.<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup> If such a boundary exists, the inquiry then must identify its content. It must also isolate the organ or organs competent to define those limits.
<p>
What I hope to demonstrate by pursuing these questions is that United Nations organs, and specifically the Security Council, operate within constraints to their competence. Some of the principles that inform these constraints lie in an international rule of law. A commitment to this rule of law necessitates a limited system of judicial review within the United Nations. This system, related to but distinct from domestic experience, would acknowledge the Security
Council's ability to assess its own competence at first instance. If an affected state objected to a binding recommendation resulting from that competence, the Court would have a broad power of <i>certiorari</i> to review the matter on grounds of institutional competence and compliance with general or customary international law.<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup> As a result, the system would grant the Court unlimited jurisdiction in the sense that no disputes would be beyond its competence. This broad jurisdiction would, however, be strongly
curtailed by a high level of deference. The effect is to confirm the Court as the ultimate safeguard against patently unreasonable violations of institutional competence and principles of general or customary international law by United Nations organs. The balance of this article will examine these considerations in detail.<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup>
<p>
1. DOES A BOUNDARY OF NORMS CIRCUMSCRIBE THE LEGITIMATE ACTIVITY OF UNITED NATIONS ORGANS?
<p>
The constitutive statute of an international body is the primary source of its jurisdiction. The United Nations Charter, notwithstanding the debate on whether it is a constitutional document, is at the very least a treaty. The <cite>Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties</cite><sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup> provides the general rules of treaty interpretation. By Article 31(1), we are to interpret a treaty in good faith, in accordance with
the ordinary meaning of the treaty's terms, and in light of the document's object and purpose. The United Nations arose from a basic aspiration for a secure peace based on justice, as expressed in the preamble to the Charter and in the basic principles and purposes set forth in Article 1. This starting point evinces that the framers intended to base the relations of states not solely on established rules of positive international law but also on the precepts of justice.<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup>
<p>
The Vienna Convention, by Article 32, also allows recourse to supplementary means of interpretation where an interpretation under Article 31 leaves the meaning ambiguous or obscure. These supplementary means include reference to the preparatory works (<i>travaux pr&eacute;paratoires</i>) of the treaty. The <i>travaux</i> from the
San Francisco Conference confirm that United Nations organs operate within constraints of positive international law and justice.<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> On 19 May 1945, during a meeting of Committee 2 of Commission III, dealing with the Charter's draft provisions relating to the Security Council, Belgium introduced a proposed amendment that proved prescient of the Libyan dispute. It observed that the power of the Security Council to recommend involved the possibility that a member state could be obliged to abandon a right granted to it by positive international law.
<blockquote>
The purpose of the amendment was, in case a party to a dispute considered that a recommendation of the Security Council infringed on its essential rights, to allow the state to request an advisory opinion on the question by the International Court of Justice. If the Court found such rights to be infringed or threatened, then the Security Council would be required either to reconsider the question or to refer the dispute to the General Assembly for a decision. It
was not in any sense the purpose of this amendment to limit the legitimate powers of the Security Council. It would, however, be desirable to strengthen the juridical basis of the decisions of the Security Council.<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Soviet and American delegates opposed the amendment, in part because the Security Council was already bound to act in accordance with the principles of justice and international law. The French and Byelorussian delegates also opposed the amendment. Although the British and South African delegates opposed the proposal
as well, they did so on the basis that its acceptance would cause delay at a time when prompt Security Council action was essential. The Belgian delegate withdrew the amendment when assured that the term &quot;recommend&quot; in what would later become Chapter VI of the Charter did not entail any compulsion or enforcement for states.<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup> Had the amendment been adopted, it would clearly
have granted the Court a power of review. Yet, as Geoffrey Watson notes, the demise of this amendment did not reflect a rejection of judicial review of Security Council conduct. Instead, the Belgian desire for such review appeared to be unnecessary since recommendations under what is now Chapter VI were not to be binding.<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup>
<p>
More problematic for review of the Security Council by the Court is the fate of a second Belgian proposal made on 29 May 1945: that the Committee on Legal Problems, a branch of the Commission on Judicial Organization, determine the proper interpretive organ for the several parts of the Charter. In the ensuing debate, the General
Assembly, the Court, and a committee of experts were all nominated as possible interpretive organs. Nevertheless, the Committee rejected the second Belgian proposal &quot;as an established procedure.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup> A later subcommittee report wrote that the Belgian proposal was unnecessary since each organ would interpret the parts of the Charter applicable to its function.<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> Furthermore, &quot;[u]nder unitary forms of national government the final determination of such a question may be vested in the highest court or in some other national authority. However, the nature of the Organization and its operation would not seem to be such as to invite the inclusion in the Charter of any provision of this nature.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> Note, though, that the report went on to conclude that if an organ's interpretation &quot;is not generally acceptable it will be without binding force.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> A similar discussion occurred in Committee 1 of Commission
III, which was considering the articles relating to Structures and Procedures. A proposal by the Norwegian delegate to enhance restraints on the Security Council was also rejected given the existing constraints within the Charter's introductory chapters of compliance with international law and justice.<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup> Finally, initial drafts presented at Dumbarton Oaks of Article 1 (the provision that now qualifies the manner in which international peace and security are to be maintained) did not include the phrase &quot;in conformity with the principles of justice and international law.&quot; This phrase was added to later drafts at the initiative of the
Chinese delegation in response to fears concerning the enormous powers that might be wielded by the Security Council.<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup>
<p>
These <i>travaux</i> certainly do not recommend a strong doctrine of judicial review within the United Nations. Nevertheless, they do illuminate the intended scope of the powers exercised by United Nations organs and especially the need for the exercise of those powers to conform to notions of justice and international law. These limits suggest that the degree to which a particular exercise of law-making authority tracks the corresponding norms of the Charter will determine the extent to which that use of authority is valid or invalid, legal or illegal.<sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup> It follows from the existence of this normative circumscribing boundary that United Nations organs can indeed act invalidly.<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup> The Charter does not confer an unlimited authority to do simply anything for which a political majority can be commanded at any given moment.<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup> That no body currently acts to review allegedly <i>ultra vires</i> conduct does not eliminate the possibility of either creating one or charging an existing one with this function.
<p>
This reference to a circumscribing boundary is familiar already from domestic experience. One of the earliest and most eloquent expositions of such a boundary remains that of the U.S. Supreme Court in its famous <cite>Marbury v. Madison</cite>.<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> There the Court observed that the U.S. Constitution had been written specifically in order to define and limit the powers of the legislative branch. Allowing those limits
to be ignored by those intended to be restrained would therefore negate the Constitution's objective.<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup> To accord the legislature an unrestrained ambit would grant it a practical and real omnipotence, even as one professed to restrict its powers within narrow limits. The exercise would simultaneously
prescribe limits while declaring that those limits could be excepted at pleasure, relegating the writing of constitutions to being &quot;absurd attempts ... to limit a power, in its own nature illimitable.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup>
<p>
The intent, therefore, is to mirror at the international plane this domestic insistence that governments are subject to certain ground rules. This point may be less controversial than I believe it to be; Professor Franck remarks that the majority and dissenting opinions in the Libyan case seem to agree that there are limits to the manner in which the Security Council can discharge its functions.<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup> If so, then the Court appears unwilling to enforce these limits, at least at the provisional stage. Whether or not this agreement exists, my
contention here is only that the <i>travaux</i> and Charter text do recommend the identification and enforcement of boundaries to the institutional competence of United Nations organs.
<p>
2. CONTENT OF CIRCUMSCRIBING BOUNDARY OF NORMS
<p>
Once the supremacy of law is recognized as preserving fundamental norms and rights, the meaning of that law needs to be determined immediately: concerns will remain if the laws to be given supremacy are antagonistic to the norms and rights that are meant to be served by this elevation. Hence, it is meaningless to discuss the supremacy of law without simultaneously describing the content of that law.<sup><a href="#one01">101</a></sup> The previous section established that justice and international law condition the exercise of power by United Nations organs. These notions suggest that the content of the pertinent boundary for United Nations organs includes (a) compliance with institutional competence under the Charter, and (b) compliance with relevant and applicable principles of international law outside the Charter.<sup><a href="#one02">102</a></sup> Both concepts assert that the Security Council cannot make law by breaking law.
<p>
Before considering these two aspects of the constraint on United Nations organs, it should first be noted that the Court grants a presumption of lawfulness to their conduct.<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup> This presumption is crucial to the satisfactory operation of the United Nations, whose organs work within a system not of blinkered parallel function but of fruitful interaction.<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup> Accordingly, as the Court held in <cite>Certain Expenses</cite>, &quot;each organ must, in the first place at least, determine its own
jurisdiction.&quot;<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup> Note, however, that this wording does not foreclose the
possibility of a final determination of jurisdiction by another organ.<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup> Furthermore, since the Court only presumes validity, I submit that this presumption should not be irrebuttable even at the provisional stage.<sup><a href="#one07">107</a></sup> Unfortunately, the Court's Order in <cite>Lockerbie</cite> leaves this point unclear. While many of the judges hinted that the Court had an ability to review Security Council conduct, few would displace the presumption of validity since an interim application was not supposed to embrace the merits. An example of this reasoning may be found in the declaration of Judge Oda. Invoking the presumption, he noted that a decision of the Security Council properly taken in the exercise of its competence could not summarily be reopened (implying that a decision improperly taken could be reopened). Nevertheless, he concluded that the Court had no choice at the provisional stage but to acknowledge the pre-eminence of resolution 748 (1992).<sup><a href="#one08">108</a></sup> Even Judge Bedjaoui, critical of the Court's Order in most of his dissent, believed that pre-eminence should be given to resolution 748 (1992) even though provisional measures were <i>prima facie</i> merited.<sup><a href="#one09">109</a></sup>
<p>
The difficulty with this logic is that it will deny provisional measures in any dispute where the Security Council has acted under Chapter VII of the Charter. It is pointless to speak of Security Council conduct &quot;in the exercise of its competence&quot; if no basis exists on which to consider that competence. For sake of clarity, I fully embrace the presumption of validity and the proposition that United Nations organs determine their own competence at first instance. However, because these are only presumptions, parties ought to be extended an opportunity to rebut them at the provisional stage. In order to permit this, though, the Court will need to consider the merits of the case at least as they pertain to the presumptions, including details relating to the conditions precedent for an organ's exercise of competence. The objection to this proposal will be that it violates the principle that the disposition of an interim application cannot prejudge the disposition of the application on its full merits. However, this proposition is not universally accepted as true.<sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup> Furthermore, only a subset of the full merits is relevant to competence. Thus, the non-anticipatory aspect of preliminary applications need not be compromised by a scrutiny of the merits that ground competence.
<p>
<i>Institutional Competence</i><br>
I turn to the first of the two constraints on United Nations organs: compliance with institutional competence. Being creations of the Charter enjoying delegated powers, such organs cannot derive authority but through the Charter.<sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup> Their competence, therefore, is limited to the ambit of the authority accorded them by the Charter. Once the principles of the Charter are compromised beyond reasonable bounds of flexibility, and community interests are subordinated to particularistic interests of nation states, the conduct of a United Nations body becomes both invalid and inimical to the purposes of the organization.<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup> This distinction between valid and invalid Security Council action is particularly important for resolutions under Chapter VII, which are often regarded as enjoying unrestrained discretion premised on the existence of a threat to international peace and security. I urge instead that the determination of a threat to international peace and security ought not be accorded a talismanic status so as to exempt the Security Council from its erstwhile constraints. The potency of a determination under Chapter VII illuminates the need for close attention to the threshold question on which that resolution rests: the existence of a threat to peace. If such a threat exists, then whatever discretion the Charter accords to the Security Council is well-founded; if, however, the existence of such a threat is determined arbitrarily, then the Security Council's discretion will be used outside the Charter, rendering any resultant resolution invalid.
<p>
The formal mechanism through which this constraint may be enforced is a preliminary objection to the jurisdiction of the Security Council: objection <i>conditio sine qua non</i>. Municipal and international law both recognize legal acts as either pure or conditional. Where the act is conditional, its intrinsic validity is said to depend on the fulfilment of the condition precedent, or the <i>conditio sine qua non</i>. Where this threshold condition has not  been met, conduct whose validity relies on the presence of that condition is rendered invalid. Because it is of a peremptory character, the objection <i>conditio sine qua non</i> is one to which claims of political expedience have little meaning.<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup> The powerful consequence of a successful objection, therefore, is to render the invalid act a nullity.<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup> The doctrine has clear application in several Charter provisions.<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup> 
<p>
The objection, I suggest, also seems appropriate for Article 39 as well, such that the Security Council's determination of a threat to the peace, breach of the peace, or act of aggression is a <i>conditio sine qua non</i> to its competence to act under Chapter VII. While the determination of a threat to international peace and security does lie within the Security Council's competence, its importance is such that validity ought not to attach to determinations made unreasonably or implausibly.<sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup> Surely the Security Council cannot arbitrarily proclaim anything it desires to be a &quot;threat to the peace.&quot; To hold otherwise would allow the Security Council to contravene the principles of justice and international law with impunity; it would also construct a new world order in which the Council is, in the words of Professor Dupuy, a &quot;world directorate.&quot;<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup> As Judge Gros remarked in <cite>South West Africa</cite>, almost any international matter can be construed as a threat to peace.<sup><a href="#one18">118</a></sup> Judge Fitzmaurice noted in the same case that limits on the powers of the Security Council &quot;are necessary because of the all too great ease with which any acutely controversial international situation can be represented as involving a latent threat to peace and security, even where it is really too remote genuinely to constitute one. Without these limitations, the functions of the Security Council could be used for purposes never intended.&quot;<sup><a href="#one19">119</a></sup>
<p>
This is not to advocate the substitution of one organ's opinion for that of the Security Council; <cite>South West Africa</cite> rejected the notion that the Court exercises full power of judicial review or  appeal.<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup> Nevertheless, municipal law concepts of separation of
powers do apply to international institutions, which feature a more organic integration, even if they are not directly applicable.<sup><a href="#one21">121</a></sup> Borrowing from municipal experience, I would propose a patent unreasonableness standard in the test of validity within the context of the interplay of law and politics.<sup><a href="#one22">122</a></sup> This would require the Court to ask itself whether the exercise of authority by the Security Council was so patently unreasonable as to constitute a loss of jurisdiction. This threshold would entail a high degree of deference to the actions of the Security Council, and would reflect the latter's primary (though not exclusive)<sup><a href="#one23">123</a></sup>
responsibility for the maintenance of international peace and security.<sup><a href="#one24">124</a></sup> It would also strike a balance that municipal law systems likely would not tolerate, granting broad <i>certiorari</i> but imposing a stringent test of invalidity. So long as a determination under Article 39 could not fairly be described as patently unreasonable, the Security Council would enjoy full authority, its discretion limited only by the ongoing need to comply with international law.
<p>
This resort to domestic law will be troubling for dualists, who regard international law and municipal law as parts of several legal orders existing independently from each other. Certainly it would be wrong to homogenize the two within a monistic whole. Domestic systems typically feature a strict separation of powers and a hierachical arrangement in which the judicial arm reviews the actions of the executive arm. This foundational nature of judicial review in municipal law is not paralleled at the international level, whose peculiar feature is its diffuse, horizontal distribution of often coextensive authority.<sup><a href="#one25">125</a></sup> The Court is thus not vested with the broad review or appellate jurisdiction often given to the highest courts in municipal frameworks.<sup><a href="#one26">126</a></sup> For this
reason, the dualists are right to oppose the casual transfer of domestic principles to the international plane.
<p>
This objection is not, however, sufficiently strong to discredit all reference to domestic law. While a conclusive formula remains elusive for the precise connection between international and municipal law, whatever the relationship---be it one of &quot;interaction,&quot; &quot;interdependence,&quot; &quot;complementariness,&quot; or &quot;dialectic links&quot;---it cannot convincingly be denied that the international r&eacute;gime owes a debt to its domestic counterpart.<sup><a href="#one27">127</a></sup> As Professor Brierly notes,
<blockquote>
[P]rivate law, being in general more developed than international law, has always constituted a sort of reserve store of principles upon which the latter has been in the habit of drawing. Roman law ... was so drawn upon by the early writers on international law, and the process continues, for the good reason that a principle which is found to be generally accepted by civilized legal systems may fairly be assumed to be so reasonable as to be necessary under any system.<sup><a href="#one28">128</a></sup>
</blockquote>
For example, the law of treaties is largely derived from general principles of contract common to various municipal legal systems.<sup><a href="#one29">129</a></sup> The same may be said for such principles as prescription, right of passage, estoppel, unjust enrichment, measure of damages, and <i>res judicata</i>, as well as international law on territorial sovereignty, boundary questions, water rights, aerial jurisdiction,
state responsibility, and occupation.<sup><a href="#one30">130</a></sup> This debt of international law to municipal law has already been recognized by the Court,<sup><a href="#one31">131</a></sup> which by Article 38(1) of its own Statute is directed to apply &quot;the general principles of law recognized by
civilized nations&quot; as one of the sources of international law. 
<p>
Until modern times, government had been considered an exclusively national function. In the mid-1800s, though, states began recognizing that without coordinating their action with that of other states they would be unable to serve fully the interests of their own people. If this recognition did not lead to the constitutionalizing of international society, it was at least a step toward that end.<sup><a href="#one32">132</a></sup> As a result, it is proper to consider the degree to which modern international bodies ought to perform for inter-state relations the functions that domestic institutions serve in national systems. Indeed, as Judge Weeramantry noted, the means by which the Charter fulfils in common the purposes and principles of the United Nations system resemble the constitutional framework of many domestic jurisdictions.<sup><a href="#one33">133</a></sup> Since issues similar to those raised
in <cite>Lockerbie</cite> have already been considered domestically, it is at least worthwhile to ask whether principles from the national context have an international role. In having recourse to domestic experience, the procedure is not to borrow a ready-made set of particular rules lock, stock, and barrel. Instead, the process is a threefold one of identification, abstraction, and generalization. First, identify the essential problems with which municipal and international law have both had to grapple. Next, consider the abstract principles with which municipal law has responded to these problems. Finally, strip these principles of their national particularities and synthesize them into their most general and truly universal aspects.<sup><a href="#one34">134</a></sup> This process yields an indication of policy or principle, one whose defining
characteristic is its legal (rather than international or municipal) nature. The conclusion is that there is a common core of principles that guide both municipal and international law.
<p>
In the following section, I will suggest several such principles and group them under the rubric &quot;rule of law.&quot; For the moment, though, my aim is to establish the first constraint on the conduct of United Nations organs, namely institutional competence assessed on a standard of patent unreasonableness. On this criterion of validity, resolution 748 (1992) is at least on an uncertain footing. Can it safely be said that the Security Council's determination of a threat to international peace and security was not patently unreasonable? It will be recalled that the threat was said to lie in the Libyan Government's failure to demonstrate its renunciation of terrorism and in particular its continued failure to respond fully and effectively to the requests in resolution 731 (1992). While our notions of threats to peace are broader today than in 1945, it is dubious whether they extend so far as to permit this type of conduct to support a Chapter VII decision. This is doubly so in view of the several constructive measures and proposals taken by Libya, each of which had been rebuffed by the British and American authorities. The original Lockerbie bombing was not characterized as a threat tointernational peace and security, and it is not clear that the mere
refusal of Libya to surrender the suspects---which was entirely legitimate at least until resolution 748 (1992)<sup><a href="#one35">135</a></sup> ---could constitute such a threat. Last, resolution 748 (1992) passed by only one vote more than the minimum of nine needed for approval---a smaller show of support than any of the resolutions dealing with Iraq during the Persian Gulf crisis. While none of these objections is fatal to a declaration of the existence of a threat to international peace and security, collectively they suggest that the Court's alacrity in upholding resolution 748 (1992) may have been premature without closer scrutiny of the alleged threat.
<p>
<i>General or Customary International Law</i><br>
What I urge to be a second aspect of the circumscribing boundary is more contentious: where the Security Council acts within its strict institutional competence but in a manner that contravenes general or customary international law. Judge Fitzmaurice noted in <cite>South West Africa</cite> that because the United Nations is itself a subject of international law, the Council is as much subject to the principles of international law as any individual member state.<sup><a href="#one36">136</a></sup> Additionally, although the competence of the Security Council derives primarily from Article 24, it is also restricted by that same Article's requirement that theSecurity Council act &quot;in accordance with the Purposes and Principles of the United Nations.&quot;<sup><a href="#one37">137</a></sup> These contexts evoke
notions of a rule of law, one whose content is not immediately obvious. As already suggested, however, we can look for inspiration to domestic frameworks of the rule of law, whose circumscribing boundaries the international order emulated in the first instance. Several universal principles characterize the core of most municipal visions of the rule of law. These principles include the belief that governmental actors must rely on authority that is conferred by law;<sup><a href="#one38">138</a></sup> that law must conform to standards of procedural and substantive justice; that a separation is critical between the judicial and legislative branches;<sup><a href="#one39">139</a></sup> and that the judiciary must be independent <i>vis-&agrave;-vis</i> the executive.
<p>
As discussed, the natural objection is that these principles are drawn from municipal or national law, which is not law in the same sense as international law. Yet our municipal legal orders are the prototype of all law,<sup><a href="#one40">140</a></sup> and nothing in these domestic principles need restrict them to the domestic context. The basic unit of law, whether national or international, is the legal rule or norm. The order of law being coercive, a sanction ought to take place when a norm is violated.<sup><a href="#one41">141</a></sup> The domestic rule of law helps to legitimate the imposition of this sanction; it strengthens the status of the order as a <i>legal</i> order. Similarly, at the world level we seek to affirm that the international community is also a legal community. The principles that strengthen the legality of the
municipal order have the same effect at the international level. The attraction of an international rule of law is thus its nurturing effect on the validity of international law, on our ability to say that an international actor ought to behave as international legal norms prescribe.
<p>
Support for this two-pronged constraint---compliance with institutional competence and with general or customary international law---may be found in <cite>South West Africa</cite>.<sup><a href="#one42">142</a></sup> Following World War I, South Africa was granted a Mandate for the former German colony of South West Africa (renamed Namibia in 1968). By resolution 2145 (XXI) (1966), the General Assembly decided that the Mandate was terminated and that South Africa had no other right to administer the Territory. When South Africa refused to withdraw its administration, the Security Council took various actions, including resolution 276 (1970), which declared the continued presence of South Africa in Namibia illegal. The Security Council intensified pressure on South Africa by requesting an
advisory opinion from the Court on the question, &quot;What are the legal consequences for States of the continued presence of South Africa in Namibia, notwithstanding Security Council resolution 276  (1970)?&quot; The governments of France and South Africa contended before the Court that both the General Assembly and Security Council had acted <i>ultra vires</i> in passing these resolutions. In its advisory opinion, the Court concluded &quot;that the decisions made by the Security Council ... were adopted in conformity with the purposes and principles of the Charter and in accordance with its Articles 24 and 25. The decisions are consequently binding on all States Members of the United Nations, which are thus under obligation to accept and carry them out.&quot;<sup><a href="#one43">143</a></sup> The
implication of this wording is that the decisions may not have been binding had the Court detected any violation of the Charter or a departure from the principles that inform it.
<p>
The separate and dissenting opinions in <cite>South West Africa</cite>, however, give a fuller discussion of the limits to the conduct of United Nations organs. Judge Petr&eacute;n noted that &quot;[s]o long as the validity of the resolutions upon which resolution 276 (1970) is based has not been established, it is clearly impossible for the Court to pronounce on the legal consequences of resolution 276 (1970), for there can be no such legal consequences if the basic resolutions are illegal ...&quot;<sup><a href="#one44">144</a></sup> This <i>de facto</i> presumption of invalidity was echoed by Judge Onyeama: &quot;[W]hen ... decisions bear upon a case properly before the Court, and a correct judgment or opinion could not be rendered without determining the validity of such decisions, the Court could not possibly avoid such a determination without abdicating its role of a judicial organ ... . I do not conceive it
as compatible with the judicial function that the Court will proceed to state the consequences of acts whose validity is assumed, without itself testing the lawfulness of the origin of those acts.&quot;<sup><a href="#one45">145</a></sup> A third separate opinion of note in <cite>South West Africa</cite> is that of
Judge de Castro, who regarded the (in)validity of resolutions of the General Assembly and Security Council as an interplay of two principles:
<ol>
<li>The principle of division of powers---the Charter set up three organs, each having sovereign powers in the sphere of its competence ...
<li>The principle of `legal-ness'---the Court, as a legal organ, cannot co-operate with a resolution which is clearly void, contrary to the rules of the Charter, or contrary to the principles of law.<sup><a href="#one46">146</a></sup>
</ol>
Judge de Castro's first principle is identical to that of institutional competence advocated earlier in this article. His second principle is less satisfying, leaving unclear, for example, how a resolution that complies with the Charter and the principles of law could nevertheless be clearly void. In any event, these three
separate opinions propose that validity be a threshold criterion and that such validity be gauged on principles of institutional competence and legality.
<p>
Two dissenting opinions in <cite>South West Africa</cite> attest to the Court's willingness to scrutinize closely the Security Council's claims of institutional competence. Judge Gros, among others, expressed dissatisfaction with the manner in which the Security Council exercised its discretionary power under the head of the maintenance of international peace and security. He regarded this exercise as &quot;another attempt to modify the principles of the Charter as regards the powers vested by States in the organs they instituted. To assert that a matter may have a distant repercussion on the maintenance of peace is not enough to turn the Security Council into a world government.&quot;<sup><a href="#one47">147</a></sup> Judge Gros therefore displayed no reticence at testing this assertion by the Security Council, lamenting that &quot;[i]t used not to be the Court's habit to take for granted the premises of a  legal situation the consequences of which it has been asked to state ... How indeed can a court deduce any obligation from a given situation without first having tested the lawfulness of the origins of that situation?&quot;<sup><a href="#one48">148</a></sup> Judge Fitzmaurice continued this theme in his
dissent: &quot;[Article 24] does not limit the <i>occasions</i> on which the Security Council can act in the preservation of peace and security, provided the threat said to be involved is not a mere figment or pretext.&quot;<sup><a href="#one49">149</a></sup>
<p>
<cite>South West Africa</cite>---in its majority, separate, and dissenting opinions---therefore stands as a model not only for the Court's acceptance of this two-pronged constraint on United Nations bodies but also of its awareness of its own interdependence and interrelation with the other primary United Nations  organs.<sup><a href="#one50">150</a></sup> Admittedly the case was only an advisory opinion with minimal binding effect, if any; it was also a decision at the merits stage rather than at the provisional stage.
Nevertheless, the various decisions unanimously scrutinize the validity of Security Council conduct, and they demonstrate a refusal to abdicate the judicial function by holding all contentious Security Council resolutions to standards of competence and legality.
<p>
The formal mechanism through which this second constraint may be pursued is the objection <i>ultra vires</i> which, like the objection <i>conditio sine qua non</i>, is of a peremptory character. The theory of excess of powers also originates in municipal administrative law and has been applied to international bodies as a general principle of law. Since then, no objection has been raised so frequently as that of <i>ultra vires</i>, even though no general Charter provision expressly authorizes this means of defence.
Although the objection has been weakened by the increasing tendency of United Nations organs not to cite the sources of their authority, it survives at least in respect of conduct---such as Security Council resolutions 731 (1992) and 748 (1992)---where the source of competence is explicit. Accordingly, an exercise of the Security Council's powers in contravention of general or customary international law is invalid on grounds of <i>ultra vires</i>, and if  made under Chapter VII ought to be of no binding authority. Although
in a positive sense it may continue to be regarded as binding for purposes of the Charter, this cannot resurrect its legality in the eyes of the general r&eacute;gime of international law.<sup><a href="#one51">151</a></sup>
<p>
On the second criterion of validity, both resolution 731 (1992) and resolution 748 (1992) almost certainly contravened the relevant and applicable principles of international law due to &quot;intrinsic defects.&quot;<sup><a href="#one52">152</a></sup> For example, resolution 731 (1992) incorporated (<i>inter alia</i>) the joint United States and United Kingdom statements of 27 November 1991. By requiring the payment of compensation by Libya immediately, these statements assumed the guilt of the two accused and therefore jeopardized the presumption of innocence. The resolution also demanded that the two accused be tried in either the United States or the United Kingdom, when it is doubtful whether a fair trial could be secured in either country. Third, since both the United States and the United Kingdom voted in favour of the resolution, it also was inconsistent with Article 27(3)'s requirement that any party to a dispute abstain from voting on any decision under Chapter VI regarding that dispute. China's abstention may also contravene the same Article's requirement that decisions by the Security Council be made &quot;by an affirmative vote of nine members including the concurring votes of the permanent members.&quot; Finally, the resolution seems to have ignored the Montreal Convention, which provided the international law in precisely the matters at issue; by so doing, the Security Council prevented a member state from invoking its
legitimate rights under a properly implemented international convention.<sup><a href="#one53">153</a></sup>
<p>
It may be observed that Security Council resolutions authorizing use of force regularly jeopardize principles of international law (such as, for example, due process). Yet such resolutions can be distinguished from those at issue here. Not every resolution that limits a right collateral to those truly in issue should be deemed <i>ultra vires</i>. As Judge Morelli noted in <cite>Certain Expenses</cite>, &quot;... to a large extent the non-conformity of [an] act with a legal rule [is] a mere irregularity having no effect on the
validity of the act. It is only in especially serious cases that an act of the Organization could be regarded as invalid, and hence an absolute nullity.&quot;<sup><a href="#one54">154</a></sup> Resolution 731 (1992), however, went to the core of the dispute, repudiating the very principles that Libya sought to invoke. For this reason, resolution 731 (1992) should likely have been held to be <i>ultra vires</i> and invalid on the
basis of its having violated the relevant and applicable principles of international law. If this is correct, then it follows that resolution 748 (1992), which repeats these same four violations by incorporating resolution 731 (1992), would similarly be <i>ultra vires</i> and invalid.
<p>
3. COMPETENCE OF UNITED NATIONS ORGANS TO ENFORCE BOUNDARY OF NORMS
<p>
If the boundary that I have described in fact exists, and if its effect is to hold all United Nations organs to standards of institutional authority and legal validity, then which of the organization's bodies is competent and best able to enforce this boundary? The entire question of the effect of illegal acts is closely related to the identification of suitable mechanisms that determine whether an act is in fact illegal.<sup><a href="#one55">155</a></sup> Indeed, the essence of international law has been described as a regulation of competencies, extending beyond mere assignments of jurisdiction to include confining international organs to the areas in which they are truly able to cope effectively.<sup><a href="#one56">156</a></sup> Presumably the organ best able to enforce limitations will be that with the highest ability to ensure compliance. Only two organs of the United Nations have the delivery of binding decisions identified explicitly as being among their powers under the Charter---the Security Council and the Court---and it is upon these organs that this discussion will focus. In brief, one facet of the rule of law that was postulated earlier was that governmental actors enjoy only that jurisdiction conferred by law. The autointerpretation of Security Council jurisdiction by the Security Council itself is of little persuasive value,<sup><a  href="#one57">157</a></sup> which leaves the Court as the organ best suited to ensure that Security Council resolutions comport with their normative limitations.
<p>
This is a highly controversial and oversimplified conclusion, and I expect that objections to it will follow one of two avenues: either that it disregards the text of the Charter, or that it corrodes the distinction between law and politics. Let me pursue these critiques with a view to assessing judicial propriety and the determination of what primacy (if any) is to be given to the Security Council <i>vis-&agrave;-vis</i> the Court.<sup><a href="#one58">158</a></sup> My goal is to strike a middle ground between two austere and I think equally undesirable extremes. One pole regards the Security Council as infallible not because it is wise but simply because it is final.<sup><a href="#one59">159</a></sup> This perspective, however, threatens to leave the relationship between the Security Council and Court indefinite at best and nonexistent at worst. The result is a Security Council, ostensibly bound by the Charter and international law, with an unrestrained ambit of discretion. The other extreme is to give the Court full reign to intervene into Security Council matters indiscriminately. What results is a violation of the Security Council's primary responsibility for maintenance of peace and security, and a paralysis of that organ's powers in times of true crisis and emergency. How best can these two extremes be reconciled?
<p>
(i) <i>The Charter of the United Nations</i><br>
One approach to determining the Court's competence to assess the validity of Security Council resolutions is a straight  textual analysis of the Charter. The concept that the Court has formed of its role within the United Nations system, and the attitudes of members toward the role of the Court, have a common basis in the Charter and the links it established between the Court and United Nations, and between the former's Statute and the latter's Charter.<sup><a href="#one60">160</a></sup> Unfortunately, the Charter does not expressly indicate the legal nature of most United Nations organs. Nevertheless, those who would deny the Court's competence to review Security Council conduct first note the grant of primary responsibility for the maintenance of international peace and security to the Security Council in Article 24(1). Although Article 92 appoints the Court to be the principal judicial organ of the United Nations, this provision does not accord
the Court a pre-eminent position in matters of dispute settlement or of Charter interpretation. As indicated earlier, proposals to this effect were made but rejected in favour of placing the Court on an equal footing with other organs in these matters.<sup><a href="#one61">161</a></sup> Therefore, as noted in <cite>Nicaragua</cite>, the Security Council and Court perform &quot;separate but complementary
functions.&quot;<sup><a href="#one62">162</a></sup>
<p>
Charter text also indicates that the organic relationship between the Court and the United Nations is much closer than that which existed between the Permanent Court of International Justice and the League of Nations.<sup><a href="#one63">163</a></sup> The Permanent Court, though intimately related to the League, was not one of its organs and operated as an exclusively judicial body. By contrast, the International Court of Justice is an organ of the United Nations, and the Statute of the Court forms an integral part of the Charter.<sup><a href="#one64">164</a></sup> Notably, nothing in the Charter's wording prohibits the Security Council from bypassing the Court altogether, even in the case of what is called a legal dispute. Article 37(2) contains no mandatory provisions; under it, the Security Council need only take into <i>consideration</i> that legal disputes <i>as a general rule</i> should be referred to the Court.<sup><a href="#one65">165</a></sup> In addition, by Article 25, member states agreed to accept and carry out decisions on matters of international peace and security when made by the Security Council in accordance with the Charter; hence, the Security Council uniquely enjoys a blend of executive, legislative, and at least quasi-judicial powers.
<p>
In short, the Charter's drafting and text are indeed fatal to claims that the Court enjoys a robust power to review the validity of Security Council resolutions---or at least to those claims that hope to be interpretive of the Charter. This objection is not, however, determinative of the issue. First, it leaves open the possibility
that the Court possesses some limited power of review. Although the Charter clearly makes the Court only one organ of several within the United Nations, the Court nevertheless &quot;occupies a special position
in relation to the other five principal organs, into whose hierarchical structure it is not integrated.&quot;<sup><a href="#one66">166</a></sup> While the Court decides cases in its own name, decisions by the Security Council are made on behalf of the organization as a whole.<sup><a href="#one67">167</a></sup> A second reason for not regarding Charter text as determinative is that multiple commentators regard the Charter as poorly drafted.<sup><a href="#one68">168</a></sup> Last, however the links that existed between the Security Council and the Court stood in 1945, they are capable of evolution. An analysis of the wording of the Charter will recall that the document as originally written and
adopted was viewed as only the framework of a potential system.<sup><a href="#one69">169</a></sup> 
<p>
(ii) <i>Law and Politics</i><br>
An alternate basis on which to assess the Court's ability to review Security Council resolutions rests on the supposed dichotomy between legal and political matters. Reference to this distinction has been drawn not only to support such review but also to deny it. For example, some have maintained that the Court's competence to review the validity of Security Council conduct stems from the nature of these organs. Judge Fitzmaurice has written that &quot;a political organ ... is not itself competent to make the necessary legal determinations on which the justification for [each] action must rest. This can only be done by a legal organ competent to make such determinations.&quot;<sup><a href="#one70">170</a></sup> Any decision otherwise, he warned, may have to be considered <i>ultra vires</i> and hence invalid. His contention was
that the influence of legal rules in the United Nations is contingent upon their degree of impartial authority; hence, it is argued, for maximal influence the organization should rely on the ascertainment of legal rules by a non-political body not subject to the control of any particular government.<sup><a href="#one71">171</a></sup> 
<p>
The Security Council is comprised of the representatives of 15 member states of the United Nations, with 5 permanent members---China, France, Russia, the United Kingdom, and the United States---and 10 additional members normally elected by the General Assembly for two-year periods. A General Assembly resolution requires that these 10 places be distributed as follows: one for East Europe, two for Latin America, two for West Europe, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand, and five for Asian and African states. In its primary
responsibility for the maintenance of international peace and security, the Security Council's main functions are the peaceful settlement of disputes, action with respect to threats to peace, and provisional measures for peacekeeping. The Court, by contrast, is composed of 15 judges elected by the General Assembly and Security Council irrespective of nationality (although no more than one national of any state may be a member of the Court).<sup><a href="#one72">172</a></sup> In practice, four judges have tended to come from West Europe, one from the United States, two from South America, two from East Europe, and six from Africa and Asia. By Article 2 of the Court's Statute, the judges must be candidates &quot;of high moral character, who possess the qualifications ... for appointment to the highest judicial offices, or are jurisconsults of recognized competence in international law.&quot; Apart from the Secretariat, the Court is the only principal organ not composed of representatives of governments. The judges' independence is further secured by the granting of diplomatic privileges and immunities to them during their term of office. Advocates of the political/judicial distinction cite this independence as revealing the non-political nature of the Court. The Security Council, by contrast, is said to be  a political rather than a judicial organ because its members are not independent. Hence, it is claimed, the impartiality of the Court recommends that organ's competence to review the validity of Security Council resolutions.
<p>
While I am sympathetic to the conclusion, I submit that this rationale does not withstand scrutiny. It must indeed be true that the authority of an organ's determinations increases with its impartiality, but this is an inadequate justification for granting the Court power to assess validity. The overt lobbying of the Security Council, though unsavoury, is nevertheless part of the  process. As Professor Schachter notes, members of the United Nations &quot;will, of course, exhibit partisanship and interest in varying degree. Governments are expected to take positions in the political organs in accordance with their conceptions of national   interest and it is apparent that these conceptions will embrace considerations based on ties of alliance, friendship or political bargaining.&quot;<sup><a href="#one73">173</a></sup> Although the Security Council is political in the common sense, it is also a political organization based upon the rule of law and operating under a legal institution. The mere fact that its decisions may result from the competition of national interests does not inevitably render it unfit to assess validity. Furthermore, the Security Council is an organ with mixed personalities, since (as noted) it has at times acted as a quasi-judicial body.<sup><a href="#one74">174</a></sup>
<p>
Reciprocally, the proposition that the Court is an entirely non-political body is dubious. More accurately, the Court is a hybrid of arbitral tribunal, legal adviser, and court of law; of trial and appellate court; of &quot;principal judicial organ&quot; of the United Nations and autonomous adjudicative body; of civil law and common law formalities and techniques; of diplomacy and law.<sup><a href="#one75">175</a></sup> It is true that Article 20 of the Court's Statute directs that each judge must solemnly declare that his or her powers will be exercised impartially and conscientiously. Nevertheless, the record indicates that individual judges, more often than not, are influenced by the views of their own governments. Indeed this is taken for granted when a judge is a national of a state party to the case; the provision for <i>ad hoc</i> judges is, at least in part, recognition of this partisanship. Many judges are former government officials, and one cannot help but conclude that &quot;[t]here is inevitably an irreducible political element in the Court.&quot;<sup><a href="#one76">176</a></sup> This is not to claim that decisions of the Security Council and the Court are indistinguishable; the latter body must at least justify its decisions through reference to authoritative legal norms. Nevertheless, both organs evince a blend of political and at least quasi-judicial function; their differences are in degree rather than kind. For this reason, legal and political
disputes cannot persuasively be distinguished by the nature of either the Security Council or the Court.
<p>
A different invocation of the supposed dichotomy between legal and political matters, one which aspires to deny the Court a power of review, relates to the nature not of the organs themselves but of the questions that they are able to entertain. On this rationale, the Security Council is deemed competent to decide political matters, whereas the Court is accorded primacy in legal matters. This distinction deserves exploration, not only because it derives in part from the Charter's text but also because of its rich pedigree.<sup><a href="#one77">177</a></sup> The notion of inherent limitations on the scope of the international judicial
process is comparatively recent. Edward Gordon has traced this notion to a distinction first drawn in the mid-1700s by Swiss jurist Emmerich de Vattel. While Vattel embraced arbitration as a reasonable means of dispute resolution, he saw it as appropriate for only those conflicts that did not directly affect the state.<sup><a href="#one78">178</a></sup> It therefore became necessary to distinguish essential rights
and less important ones in order to determine where arbitration would be useful. In practice, however, essential rights were construed as only those that threatened a state's very survival. Since these were few, Vattel's distinction became meaningless. Later international legal scholars sought to revive Vattel's insight by enhancing the class of essential rights, substituting broader notions of sovereign prerogative for those of national survival. Through this development we inherited the distinction now known as political disputes versus legal disputes.<sup><a href="#one79">179</a></sup> In his 1873 speech at the first meeting of the Institute of International Law, Professor Levin Goldschmidt defined legal disputes between nations as those &quot;which ought to be decided by the application of principles of law.&quot;<sup><a href="#one80">180</a></sup> Since 1899, this distinction has informed most general conventions for the peaceful settlement of disputes<sup><a href="#one81">181</a></sup> including its appearance in Article 13 of the Covenant of the League of Nations. The substance of this Article was in turn incorporated into Article 36(2) of the Statute of the Permanent Court of International Justice which, with slight modification a
quarter-century later, became an article of the Statute of the International Court of Justice.<sup><a href="#one82">182</a></sup>
<p>
Despite the distinction's longevity, neither the Charter nor the Statute explicitly define the term &quot;legal disputes,&quot; nor are any criteria offered in either instrument by which such &quot;legal disputes&quot; may be distinguished from others.<sup><a href="#one83">183</a></sup> Article 36(2) simply lists the categories of &quot;legal disputes&quot; in respect of which the obligation of compulsory adjudication exists.<sup><a href="#one84">184</a></sup> However, defenders of the distinction usually construe
&quot;law&quot; as consisting of the body of legal norms and relationships existing between and among states, which grew largely out of custom and treaty. &quot;Legal&quot; issues are therefore those governed by law in this sense, and &quot;political&quot; issues are those that are not. These notions in turn represent carryovers from certain domestic contexts, where &quot;legal&quot; issues are those suitable for adjudication, and &quot;political&quot; ones are not justiciable.
<p>
My difficulties with the distinction between legal and political issues are twofold. First, I am pessimistic as to the ability todistinguish convincingly legal and political matters.<sup><a href="#one85">185</a></sup> The parties at issue will always be independent states rendering public claims, implicating the policy choices of their respective sovereign governments. Hence, virtually every case the Court hears is of a &quot;political&quot; nature, whether or not it entails &quot;legal&quot; issues as well.<sup><a href="#one86">186</a></sup> As Professor Lauterpacht wrote in 1933
<blockquote>
[A]ll international disputes are, irrespective of their gravity, disputes of a legal character in the sense that, so long as the rule of law is recognized, they are capable of an answer by the application of legal rules ... . All conflicts in the sphere of international politics can be reduced to contests of a legal nature ... . [T]he only decisive test of the justiciability of the dispute is the willingness of the disputants to submit the conflict to the arbitrament of law.<sup><a href="#one87">187</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Furthermore, even if the distinction were clear, it would fail to identify the organ whose classification of the dispute is to be authoritative.
<p>
A second, and more fundamental, objection to the distinction between political and legal disputes pertains to its corrosive influence on the rule of law. The success of a constitutional approach to international law relies on its completeness and its ability to address all important issues that confront it; if certain matters lie beyond the reach of the constitution, they are by definition no longer constrained by that document. The system will therefore be incomplete with respect to those gaps.<sup><a href="#one88">188</a></sup> In domestic law, many issues deemed to be &quot;political&quot; still fall within the general constitutional
framework in that they must still be resolved peaceably and in accordance with law. However, at the international level there is no such framework and &quot;political&quot; issues become unregulated except by political forces. The traditional conclusion---that these &quot;political&quot; issues cannot, and must not, be subjected to any international rules---risks a r&eacute;gime of disorder.
<p>
Furthermore, the use of the qualifier &quot;political&quot; is easily expandable to include any situation to which the parties involved do not wish to see law or principle applied. Most serious issues are rarely regarded as anything other than political. Additionally, a majority of disputes feature at least one party seeking to justify its position by reference to what it claims to be its legal rights; that the dispute may involve high political issues does not make it any less legal. This classification is juridically unproblematic
until it serves to place those disputes beyond the sort of limitations that I am advocating.<sup><a href="#one89">189</a></sup> My submission therefore is that a commitment to the rule of law dictates
that no Security Council disputes, however framed, be regarded as inherently beyond either the need for validity<sup><a href="#one90">190</a></sup> or the purview of the Court to validate. This in turn
necessitates an identity between traditionally &quot;political&quot; issues and traditionally &quot;legal&quot; issues, and requires bringing both into an international constitutional framework.<sup><a href="#one91">191</a></sup>
<p>
Some would object that the distinction between political and legal matters does not claim to classify all disputes neatly and completely as legal or political. One defender sought to permit some overlap between the two by allowing a dispute's characterization to be determined by &quot;the objective aimed at or the position adopted by  each party in the dispute.&quot;<sup><a href="#one92">192</a></sup> This response is unsatisfactory on several grounds: it would allow parties to contract out of the requirements of
international law by mutually agreeing to frame the dispute as political; it is unhelpful where the parties adopt polar positions with respect to legal rights; and it fails to note that a dispute may be both political and legal in different respects.
<p>
If, as I suggest, a dispute should be regarded as both legal and political, then it follows that the same dispute may be submitted to both the Security Council and the Court, each of which impose a hybrid of legal and political procedure. While concurrent jurisdiction often raises the spectre of &quot;forum  shopping,&quot; this concern is absent if the final forum <i>is</i> the Court (that is, regardless of whether a party &quot;shops&quot; at first instance at the Court or the Security Council). The Court has repeatedly expressed its belief that the simultaneous treatment of one matter by multiple United Nations organs is unproblematic. In 1979, militant elements in Iran occupied and seized the United States Embassy in Tehran and elsewhere, detaining diplomatic staff and two private citizens as hostages. Besides appealing to the Security Council, the United States instituted proceedings before the Court in November, 1979. By the time that a decision on the merits was released on 24 May 1980, the Security Council had already passed resolutions and the Secretary-General had even struck a fact-finding commission. The Court nevertheless exercised its judicial function, and observed that
<blockquote>
it does not seem to have occurred to any member of the [United Nations Security] Council that there was or could be anything irregular in the simultaneous exercise of their respective functions by the Court and the Security Council. Nor is there in this any cause for surprise ... It is for the Court, the principal judicial organ of the United Nations, to resolve any legal questions that may be in issue between parties to a dispute; and the resolution of such legal questions by the Court may be an important, and sometimes decisive, factor in promoting the peaceful settlement of the dispute. This is indeed recognized by Article 36 of the Charter ...<sup><a href="#one93">193</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Hence, <cite>Tehran Hostages</cite> &quot;suggests a division of functional responsibilities between the Court and other United Nations organs, one that does not preclude, or indeed may even dictate, the simultaneous application of political and legal methods to the resolution of inter-state disputes.&quot;<sup><a href="#one94">194</a></sup>
<p>
A similar conclusion was reached in <cite>Nicaragua</cite>. On 9 April 1984, Nicaragua instituted proceedings before the Court against the United States, alleging that American involvement with military and paramilitary actions against Nicaragua had violated international obligations. Although the dispute had already come before the Security Council, the Court held on 26 November 1984 that it had jurisdiction to entertain the case and that Nicaragua's claim was admissible. The Court thus denied that the mere presence of an issue before one United Nations organ should preclude another organ from simultaneously considering that issue.<sup><a href="#one95">195</a></sup> This perspective has been echoed by academic commentators: &quot;[T]here is ... no express authority in the Charter or in the Statute for the proposition that, if a case submitted to the Court should constitute a threat to world peace, the Security Council may seise itself of the case and thereby put an end to the Court's jurisdiction.&quot;<sup><a href="#one96">196</a></sup>
<p>
It is therefore submitted that although this identity of question results in the possibility of conflict, such conflict should not deter the Court from pronouncing on a resolution's validity. Even if other organs do not comply with an order by the Court, rules of international law may still be characterized as obligatory even
when the possibility of applying them coercively, in the context of non-compliance, is limited or absent. This becomes a difficulty of legal efficacy, not legal validity.<sup><a href="#one97">197</a></sup> If, as I suggested in the previous section, both resolution 731 (1992) and resolution 748 (1992) were invalid, then
the case would have been an appropriate occasion for the indication of the provisional relief requested. No legitimate purpose would be gained by insisting that Libya, under Article 14(1) of the Montreal Convention, continue for six months a process that the United States and the United Kingdom had already dismissed as being out of the question. Even with a finding that both resolutions were <i>prima facie</i> valid, the Court could presumably have indicated some form of <i>proprio motu</i> provisional relief that would have complied with the resolutions, the Charter, and the Montreal Convention.
<p>
These disputes over the proper role of the Court show its need for a clearer sense of function. As the United Nations nears its first half-century, we still struggle to understand the nature of that union, and to frame the principles that will continue to guide its development. The confusion stems from its dual function as both an instrument of the United Nations and an organ of international law. How should these attributes be reconciled? <cite>Lockerbie</cite> shows the difficulty in preserving both of the Court's roles. These difficulties will only be exacerbated by Security Council ascendancy and the desire for an organ of oversight.<sup><a href="#one98">198</a></sup> As Professor Gross has concluded, what response is appropriate will depend on (a) the degree to which the United Nations becomes a truly universal international organization; (b) the evolution of the current organization from one of coordination to one of integration; and (c) as a consequence, the degree to which international law must adjust to and absorb United Nations law or <i>vice versa</i>.<sup><a href="#one99">199</a></sup>
<p>
<h3>V. Epilogue</h3>

On 31 March 1992, the Security Council voted to impose a ban on air travel and arms sales against Libya effective 15 April 1992. The sanctions did not affect the export of oil, Libya's main economic resource. As with resolution 748 (1992), ten members voted in favour of imposing sanctions and five abstained.<sup><a href="#twohundred">200</a></sup> Yet Libya refused to yield the two suspects, apparently because of Qaddafi's fear that, as part of a Western effort to topple his r&eacute;gime, their prosecution would lead to new indictments implicating him or others close to him.<sup><a href="#two01">201</a></sup> Mixed with this refusal, however, have been periodic hints of cooperation. Libyan Justice Minister Ibrahim Bakar reportedly indicated that Libya would not block the departure of the two accused if they decided to stand trial in Scotland or the United States.<sup><a href="#two02">202</a></sup> Libya also promised to give the United Kingdom specific information about Libya's dealings with the Provisional Irish Republican Army; this move apparently responded to a requirement in the United Nations sanctions that Libya demonstrate that it has severed ties with terrorist groups.<sup><a href="#two03">203</a></sup>
<p>
Since the sanctions come up for review every 120 days, the Security Council has continued them at four-month intervals in the face of Libya's continued failure to surrender the two accused.<sup><a href="#two04">204</a></sup> The only further response garnered by the renewed sanctions was Libya's
closure of its land borders for three days in January 1993.<sup><a href="#two05">205</a></sup> The new administration of U.S. President Bill Clinton, impatient with Libyan inaction, threatened to stiffen sanctions.<sup><a href="#two06">206</a></sup> U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher indicated that he would press allies to impose a global oil embargo, freeze Libyan assets abroad, and ban the sale of oil-related equipment to Libya. The proposal reportedly met stiff resistance from Britain and France, who believed that the Arab world would not accept new sanctions.<sup><a href="#two07">207</a></sup>
<p>
On 13 August 1993, upon the fourth renewal of the United Nations sanctions, the United States, Britain, and France issued a new warning which gave Libya until 1 October 1993 to surrender the two accused.<sup><a href="#two08">208</a></sup> The statement, read before the Security Council by U.S. representative Madeleine K. Albright, stated that if the suspects were not handed over by this new deadline &quot;we will table a resolution strengthening the sanctions in key oil-related, financial and technological areas.&quot;<sup><a href="#two09">209</a></sup> Although no details of these new measures were given, they still did not contemplate banning the sale of Libyan oil. Predictably, Libya rejected the new deadline two days later through a statement from its Foreign Ministry. The statement also reiterated Libya's readiness to discuss the issue with the Security Council and the three Western states in order to find a venue for an &quot;equitable and fair trial&quot; for the suspects.<sup><a href="#two10">210</a></sup> On 19 August 1993, Qaddafi himself again offered to open talks with the Clinton administration.<sup><a href="#two11">211</a></sup> Qaddafi was even reported to be suggesting that the two accused be tried in Canada, headquarters of the International Air Transport Association.<sup><a href="#two12">212</a></sup>
<p>
The October deadline did not achieve compliance. Scottish lawyers Alistair Duff and Lord Macaulay confirmed in September 1993, that they had been appointed to represent the two accused and would fly to Libya in early October to be briefed by their clients.<sup><a href="#two13">213</a></sup> Yet Libya still equivocated. A forty-page letter delivered to United Nations Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali on 14
September 1993 stated that the two accused might stand trial in Scotland if the procedures were fair and if the sanctions were lifted. The significance of this apparent concession was qualified by the Libyan assertion that the accused would need to &quot;be persuaded to stand trial under the Scottish legal system.&quot;<sup><a href="#two14">214</a></sup> The document could therefore have represented
reasonable questions leading up to a handover or reasons for non-compliance.<sup><a href="#two15">215</a></sup> Either way, the United States, Britain, and France acceeded to requests by Boutros-Ghali that they delay the imposition of new economic sanctions.<sup><a href="#two16">216</a></sup>
<p>
At the time of writing, therefore, it appears that the dispute is merely entering a new phase of stalemate. A team of international lawyers representing the two accused has now advised them not to surrender to Scottish authorities for trial, citing a &quot;grave concern&quot; that pretrial publicity could prevent them from receiving a fair hearing.<sup><a href="#two17">217</a></sup> If the two accused nevertheless elect to stand trial in Scotland, it will form theconclusion to a deeply flawed process, one in which the Security
Council disregarded municipal and treaty law by demanding the extradition of two Libyan nationals to a country where at least one justice of the Court feels a fair trial is unlikely.<sup><a href="#two18">218</a></sup>
<p>
<h3>VI. Concluding Remarks</h3>

The creators of the International Court of Justice held high hopes for the role that it could play in substituting the rule of law and justice for the rule of force:
<blockquote>
On the basis of the texts proposed for the Charter [of the United Nations] and the Statute [of the Court], the First Committee ventures to foresee a significant role for the new Court in the international relations of the future. The judicial process will have a central place in the plans of the United Nations for the settlement
of international disputes by peaceful means ... . A long road has been travelled in the effort to enthrone law as the guide for theconduct of states in their relations one with another. A new milepost is now erected along that road. In establishing the International Court of Justice, the United Nations hold before a war-stricken world the beacons of Justice and Law and offer the possibility of substituting orderly judicial processes for the vicissitudes of war and the reign of brutal force.<sup><a href="#two19">219</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The decision by that Court in <cite>Lockerbie</cite> seems far removed from these lofty ambitions. Instead, we are left with the vision of U.S. Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering that &quot;neither Libya nor indeed any other State can seek to hide support for international terrorism behind traditional principles of international law and State practice.&quot;<sup><a href="#two20">220</a></sup> If it is true, as one observer has remarked, that &quot;the principal problem the Court faces is the current perception that its
decisions turn ultimately on political, rather than legal, considerations,&quot; the <cite>Lockerbie</cite> judgments have done little to ameliorate the problem.<sup><a href="#two21">221</a></sup>
<p>
Had the Court indicated provisional measures, the United States and the United Kingdom would not have been left without recourse. Article 14 of the Montreal Convention directs that any dispute shall on the request of either party be submitted to arbitration. If this fails to reach agreement, either party may then refer the dispute to the Court for resolution. A judgment by the Court would then be eligible for enforcement by the Security Council and other United Nations organs. With hindsight it is clear that any indication of
provisional relief would have initiated a period of negotiation between the parties, likely with a view to finding a mutually agreeable jurisdiction for the trial which all three litigants conceded should take place. This is almost exactly what has happened anyway. While the propriety of indicating provisional measures turns on many factors, it can at least be observed that the Court's failure to indicate such measures did nothing to advance the resolution of this dispute. At the same time, though, <cite>Lockerbie</cite> threatens to minimize the rule of law in the post-Cold War international system, to restrict the Court to hearing only questions that are politically non-controversial,<sup><a href="#two22">222</a></sup> and
to convert instruments of international law into tools of convenience, rather than treaties of necessity.<sup><a href="#two23">223</a></sup> This latter danger is particularly troubling given that the United Nations Charter includes as one of its ends the maintenance of &quot;respect for the obligations arising from treaties and other sources of international law.&quot;<sup><a href="#two24">224</a></sup>
<p>
Some solace may be found in the judgments' insistence that the disposition of the provisional application will not affect the ultimate disposition on the merits. However, the degree to which the Court's refusal to indicate provisional measures anticipates its full decision on the merits is uncertain.<sup><a href="#two25">225</a></sup> Libya has accordingly kept the case alive for the moment, and the deadline for its memorial was 20 December 1993. The United States and the United Kingdom have until 20 June 1995 for their counter-memorials.<sup><a href="#two26">226</a></sup> The full decision will deny the majority the luxury of avoiding core issues by refusing to engage the merits, and it will doubtless be one of the most juridically important that the Court has delivered.
<p>
In the meantime, we have been given a spectacular illustration of the failure of international enforcement. Advocates of an international criminal court have found new support in Libya's refusal to comply with the Security Council's resolutions.<sup><a href="#two27">227</a></sup> At first blush, this failure of enforcement affects only the efficacy, rather than the validity, of international law. In Kelsen's words, efficacy of law asks whether the norms that are meant to shape conduct are actually applied and obeyed. Validity is instead concerned with whether those norms are legitimate, whether conduct should conform to those norms.<sup><a href="#two28">228</a></sup> Despite this conceptual distinction, though, an
interdependence exists between the two: &quot;[O]nly a legal order the norms of which are generally obeyed and applied is considered valid. It is not necessary that all the norms of this order be always and
without exception obeyed or applied; but it is necessary that it be on the whole efficacious.&quot;<sup><a href="#two29">229</a></sup> The failure to indicate provisional measures may therefore detract from the
validity of the international legal order in two respects: its erosion of the rule of law, and its demand of efficacy from a system seemingly unable or unwilling to provide it. 
<p>
Then-U.S. President George Bush, in a 1990 address to the United Nations, called for a &quot;new partnership of nations ... based on consultation, cooperation and collective action ... . united by principle and the rule of law ...&quot;<sup><a href="#two30">230</a></sup> I have argued that if the international system of the next century is to include a respect for the rule of law, it will fall to the Court to enforce that respect in the last resort. The mechanism discussed would be to allow United Nations organs to determine their own competence in the first instance but to have the Court curtail their flagrant operational anomalies by holding them to deferential tests of validity. This model of review would of course not require the Security Council, in a time of crisis, to delay its response until the Court provided the &quot;go-ahead.&quot; My proposal would, however, be willing to subject the course of action adopted by the Security Council to review by the Court after the fact.<sup><a href="#two31">231</a></sup> Even the limited review that I have advocated will entail a stronger activism by the Court than that it has traditionally evinced. This activism will, in turn, render even more important the composition of the Court. Current proposals to expand General Assembly voting rights and the veto also reflect a desire to enhance legitimacy and validity by increasing the number of stakeholders in a given decision.<sup><a href="#two32">232</a></sup> An effective international rule of law will also require an articulation of its principles---which currently lie in part explicitly and in large part interstitially within the Charter and the principles of international law. This is not to minimize the complementarity of the roles played by United Nations organs. The important question that remains, though, is what happens when the organs fail to complement each other, when (for example) the Security Council fails to be sensitive to both positive law and justice.
<p>
It is common to dichotomize the rule of law from political expedience based on the concept of national interest. Realists, minimizing the role of law in international relations, regard all international disputes as political disputes. Attempts to inject a normative legal order into this system are illusory and time-consuming diversions. Conversely, other commentators advocate the compulsory adjudication of every international dispute. Although all conflicts, they argue, are political in character, this does not exclude the possibility of treating the dispute as legal. Conflicts are therefore political with respect to the interests they involve and legal with respect to the normative order controlling those interests.<sup><a href="#two33">233</a></sup> Shared between these schools, then, are the recognitions that political and
legal disputes are interrelated to one degree or another, and that law and diplomacy are mutually complementary.<sup><a href="#two34">234</a></sup> This suggests that through a system of functional complementarity grounded in validity, expedience, and the rule of law are not inevitably antagonistic.<sup><a href="#two35">235</a></sup>
<p>
The realists will complain that this emphasis on the rule of law substitutes abstract idealism for the political and power bases that drive international relations. Yet discord and conflict will be the only result of any attempt by a group of member states to judge the conduct of another unless an independent, mutually agreeable set of standards can be consulted.<sup><a href="#two36">236</a></sup> As Professor Eagleton notes, &quot;[I]f the United Nations is to maintain any pretension of being a legal order, of seeking to carry out its purposes in terms of its fundamental law, it cannot do so by arriving at whatever decision the emotions of the moment demand and then asserting that the action taken was legal because it was taken.&quot;<sup><a href="#two37">237</a></sup> The rule of law therefore aspires to provide part of a set of standards on which to base legality. A desire for the rule of law in United Nations organs does not dictate a particular substantive outcome; it instead mandates an effort on behalf of the relevant organ(s) to achieve justice through dispassionate application of the rule of law and the principles that inform it. The goal is not to supplant <i>realpolitik</i> with abstractions, but to find a point of convergence where long-range interests can be defined based on power derived not only from expedience but also from principle and order. As United Nations Secretary General Dag Hammarskj&ouml;ld observed in 1955,
<blockquote>
... in the longer view, it is surely in the interest of all Member States to restrict as much as possible the sphere where sheer strength is an argument and to extend as widely as possible the area ruled by considerations of law and justice. In an interdependent world, a greater degree of authority and effectiveness in international law will be a safeguard, not a threat, to the freedom and independence of national States.<sup><a href="#two38">238</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Because states are autonomous and sovereign only in virtue of international law, every increment of strength in that law is bound to make more secure the independence of states.<sup><a href="#two39">239</a></sup> Similarly, by acting in accordance with principle the Security Council can strengthen, with cumulative effect, its own capabilities in future disputes.<sup><a href="#two40">240</a></sup>
<p>
<h3>ANGUS M. GUNN, Jr.</h3>
<p><br>
<hr>
<p><br>
<center><h2>Appendices</h2></center>

<h3><a name="A-1">Statement Issued by the United States of America</a><sup><a href="two41">241</a></sup><br>
27 November 1991</h3>

<dd>After the indictments were handed down on 14 November we conveyed them to the Libyan regime. We have also consulted closely with the Governments of France and the United Kingdom and in concert with those two Governments we have the following two declarations to present publicly today:
<p>
<center>JOINT DECLARATION OF THE UNITED STATES AND UNITED KINGDOM</center>
<p>
The British and American Governments today declare that the Government of Libya must:
<ul>
<li>surrender for trial all those charged with the crime; and accept responsibility for the actions of Libyan officials;
<li>disclose all it knows of this crime, including the names of all those responsible, and allow full access to all witnesses, documents and other material evidence, including all the remaining timers;
<li>pay appropriate compensation.
</ul>
We expect Libya to comply promptly and in full.
<p><br>

<h3><a name="A-2">United Nations Security Council Resolution 731 (1992)</a><sup><a href="#two42">242</a></sup><br>
Adopted by the Security Council at the 1033rd meeting, on 21 January 1992<br> 
Material paragraphs</h3>

<dd><i>The Security Council</i>,<br>
<dd><i>Deeply disturbed</i> by the world-wide persistence of acts of international terrorism in all its forms, including those in which States are directly or indirectly involved, which endanger or take innocent lives, have a deleterious effect on international relations and jeopardize the security of States,<br>
<dd><i>Deeply concerned</i> by all illegal activities directed against international civil aviation, and affirming the right of all States, in accordance with the Charter of the United Nations and relevant principles of international law, to protect their nationals from acts of international terrorism that constitute threats to international peace and security,
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd><i>Deeply concerned</i> over the results of investigations, which implicate officials of the Libyan Government and which are contained in Security Council documents that include the requests addressed to the Libyan authorities by France<sup><a href="#two43">243</a></sup> the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland<sup><a href="#two44">244</a></sup> and the United States of America<sup><a href="#two45">245</a></sup> in connection with the legal procedures related to the attacks carried out against Pan
American flight 103 and Union de transports a&eacute;riens flight 772;<br>
<dd><i>Determined</i> to eliminate international terrorism,
<ol>
<li><i>Condemns</i> the destruction of Pan American flight 103 and Union de tranports a&eacute;riens flight 772 and the resultant loss of hundreds of lives;
<li><i>Strongly deplores</i> the fact that the Libyan Government has not yet responded effectively to the above requests to cooperate fully in establishing responsibility for the terrorist acts referred to above against Pan American flight 103 and Union de transports a&eacute;riens flight 772;
<li><i>Urges</i> the Libyan Government immediately to provide a full and effective response to those requests so as to contribute to the elimination of international terrorism;
</ol>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<ol start=5>
<li><i>Urges</i> all States individually and collectively to encourage the Libyan Government to respond fully and effectively to those requests;
<li><i>Decides</i> to remain seized of the matter.
</ol>
<p><br>
<h3><a name="A-3">United Nations Security Council Resolution 748 (1992)</a><sup><a href="#two46">246</a></sup><br>
Adopted by the Security Council at the 1063rd meeting, on 31 March 1992<br> 
Material paragraphs</h3>

<dd><i>The Security Council</i>,<br>
<dd><i>Reaffirming</i> its resolution 731 (1992) of 21 January 1992,<br>
<dd><i>Noting</i> the reports of the Secretary General,<sup><a href="#two47">247</a></sup><br>
<dd><i>Deeply concerned</i> that the Libyan Government has still not provided a full and effective response to the requests in its resolution 731 (1992) of 21 January 1992,<br>
<dd><i>Convinced</i> that the suppression of acts of international terrorism, including those in which States are directly or indirectly involved, is essential for the maintenance of international peace and security,<br>
<dd><i>Reaffirming</i> that, in accordance with the principle in Article 2, paragraph 4, of the Charter of the United Nations, every State has the duty to refrain from organizing, instigating, assisting or participating in terrorist acts in another State or acquiescing in organized activities within its territory directed towards the commission of such acts, when such acts involve a threat or use of force,<br>
<dd><i>Determining</i>, in this context, that the failure by the Libyan Government to demonstrate by concrete actions its renunciation of terrorism and in particular its continued failure to respond fully and effectively to the requests in resolution 731 (1992) constitute a threat to international peace and security,<br>
<dd><i>Determined</i> to eliminate international terrorism,<br>
<dd><i>Recalling</i> the right of States, under Article 50 of the Charter, to consult the Security Council where they find themselves confronted with special economic problems arising from the carrying out of preventive or enforcement measures,<br>
<dd><i>Acting</i> under Chapter VII of the Charter,
<ol>
<li><i>Decides</i> that the Libyan Government must now comply without any further delay with paragraph 3 of resolution 731 (1992) regarding the requests contained in documents S/23306, S/23308 and S/23309;
<li><i>Decides also</i> that the Libyan Government must commit itself definitively to cease all forms of terrorist action and all assistance to terrorist groups and that it must promptly, by concrete actions, demonstrate its renunciation of terrorism;
<li><i>Decides</i> that, on 15 April 1992 all States shall adopt the measures set out below, which shall apply until the Security Council decides that the Libyan Government has complied with paragraphs 1 and 2 above;
</ol>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<ol start=7>
<li><i>Calls upon</i> all States, including States not members of the United Nations, and all international organizations, to act strictly in accordance with the provisions of the present resolution, notwithstanding the existence of any rights or obligations conferred or imposed by any international agreement or any contract entered into or any licence or permit granted prior to 15 April 1992;
</ol>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<ol start=14>
<li><i>Decides</i> to remain seized of the matter.
</ol>
<p><br>
<h3><a name="A-4">Convention for the Suppression of Unlawful Acts Against the Safety of Civil Aviation</a><sup><a href="#two48">248</a></sup><br>
Done at Montreal, 23 September 1971<br>
Material provisions</h3>

<dd><i>Article 5</i>.
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<ol>
<li>Each Contracting State shall take such measures as may be necessary to establish its jurisdiction over the offences in the following cases:
<ol type="a">
<li>when the offence is committed in the territory of that State;
<li>when the offence is committed against or on board an aircraft registered in that State;
<li>when the aircraft on board which the offence is committed lands in its territory with the alleged offender still on board;
<li>when the offence is committed against or on board an aircraft leased without crew to a lessee who has his principal place of business or, if the lessee has no such place of business, his permanent residence, in that State.
</ol>
<li>Each Contracting State shall likewise take such measures as may be necessary to establish its jurisdiction over the offences mentioned in Article 1, paragraph 1 (<i>a</i>), (<i>b</i>) and (<i>c</i>), and in Article 1, paragraph 2, in so far as that paragraph relates to those offences, in the case where the alleged offender is present in its territory and it does not extradite him pursuant to Article 8 to any of the States mentioned in paragraph 1 of this Article.
<li>This Convention does not exclude any criminal jurisdiction exercised in accordance with national law.
</ol>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd><i>Article 7</i>. The Contracting State in the territory of which the alleged offender is found shall, if it does not extradite him be obliged, without exception whatsoever and whether or not the offence was committed in its territory, to submit the case to its competent authorities for the purpose of prosecution. Those authorities shall take their decision in the same manner as in the case of any ordinary offence of a serious nature under the law of that State.
<p>
<dd><i>Article 8</i>.
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<ol start=2>
<li>If a Contracting State which makes extradition conditional on the existence of a treaty receives a request for
extradition from another Contracting State with which it has no extradition treaty, it may at its option consider this Convention as the legal basis for extradition in respect of the offences. Extradition shall be subject to the other conditions provided by the law of the requested State.
</ol>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd><i>Article 11</i>. 1.  Contracting States shall afford one another the greatest measure of assistance in connection with criminal proceedings brought in respect of the offences. The law of the State requested shall apply in all cases.
<ol start=2>
<li>The provisions of paragraph 1 of this Article shall not affect obligations under any other treaty, bilateral or
multilateral, which governs or will govern, in whole or in part, mutual assistance in criminal matters.
</ol>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd><i>Article 14</i>. 1.  Any dispute between two or more Contracting States concerning the interpretation or application of this Convention which cannot be settled through negotiation, shall, at the request of one of them, be submitted to arbitration. If within six months from the date of the request for arbitration the Parties are unable to agree on the organization of the arbitration, any one of those Parties may refer the dispute to the International Court of Justice by request in conformity with the Statute of the Court.
<p><br>

<h3><cite><a name="A-5">United Nations Charter</a></cite><sup><a href="#two49">249</a></sup> 26 June 1945<br>
San Francisco, California<br>
Material provisions</h3>

<dd>Article 1. The Purposes of the United Nations are:
<ol>
<li>To maintain international peace and security, and to that end: to take effective collective measures for the prevention and removal of threats to the peace, and for the suppression of acts of aggression or other breaches of the peace, and to bring about by peaceful means, and in conformity with the principles of justice and international law, adjustment or settlement of international disputes or situations which might lead to a breach of the peace;
</ol>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd>Article 7. (1) There are established as the principal organs of the United Nations: a General Assembly, a Security Council, an Economic and Social Council, a Trusteeship Council, an International Court of
Justice, and a Secretariat.<br>
<dd>(2) Such subsidiary organs as may be found necessary may be established in accordance with the present Charter.
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd>Article 24. (1) In order to ensure prompt and effective action by the United Nations, its Members confer on the Security Council primary responsibility for the maintenance of international peace and security, and agree that in carrying out its duties under this responsibility the Security Council acts on their behalf.<br>
<dd>(2) In discharging these duties the Security Council shall act in accordance with the Purposes and Principles of the United Nations. The specific powers granted to the Security Council for the discharge of these duties are laid down in Chapters VI, VII, VIII, and XII.<br>
<dd>Article 25. The Members of the United Nations agree to accept and carry out the decisions of the Security Council in accordance with the present Charter.
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd>Article 27. (3) Decisions of the Security Council on all other matters shall be made by an affirmative vote of nine members including the concurring votes of the permanent members; provided that, in decisions under Chapter VI, and under paragraph 3 of article 52, a party to a dispute shall abstain from voting.
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd>Article 36. (1) The Security Council may at any stage of a dispute of the nature referred to in Article 33 or of a situation of like nature, recommend appropriate procedures or methods of adjustment.<br>
<dd>(2)The Security Council should take into consideration any procedures for the settlement of the dispute which have already been
adopted by the parties.<br>
<dd>(3) In making recommendations under this Article the Security Council should also take into consideration that legal disputes should as a general rule be referred by the parties to the
International Court of Justice in accordance with the provisions of the Statute of the Court.
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd>Article 92. The International Court of Justice shall be the principal judicial organ of the United Nations. It shall function in accordance with the annexed Statute, which is based upon the Statute of the Permanent Court of International Justice and forms an integral part of the present Charter.
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd>Article 103. In the event of a conflict between the obligations of the Members of the United Nations under the present Charter and their obligations under any other international agreement, their obligations under the present Charter shall prevail.
<p><br>
<h3><cite><a name="A-6">Statute of International Court of Justice</a></cite><sup><a href="#two50">250</a></sup><br>
Material provisions</h3>

<dd>Article 16. (1) No member of the Court may exercise any political or administrative function, or engage in any other occupation of a professional nature.<br>
<dd>(2) Any doubt on this point shall be settled by the decision of
the Court.
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd>Article 36. (1) The jurisdiction of the Court comprises all cases which the parties refer to it and all matters specially provided for in the Charter of the United Nations or in treaties and conventions in force.<br>
<dd>(2) The states parties to the present Statute may at any time declare that they recognize as compulsory <i>ipso facto</i> and without special agreement, in relation to any other state accepting the same obligation, the jurisdiction of the Court in all legal disputes concerning:
<dd>(<i>a</i>) the interpretation of treaty;<br>
<dd>(<i>b</i>) any question of international law;<br>
<dd>(<i>c</i>) the existence of any fact which, if established, would constitute a breach of an international obligation;<br>
<dd>(<i>d</i>) the nature or extent of the reparation to be made for the breach of an international obligation.<br>
<dd>(3) The declarations referred to above may be made unconditionally or on condition or reciprocity on the part of several or certain States, or for a certain time.
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>
<p>
<dd>Article 41. (1) The Court shall have the power to indicate, if it considers that circumstances so require, any provisional measures which ought to be taken to preserve the respective rights of either party.<br>
<dd>(2) Pending the final decision, notice of the measures suggested shall forthwith be given to the parties and to the Security Council.
<p>
<center>. . . . .</center>

