<li><a name="fifteen">See D. Johnston,</a> &quot;Flight 103: A Solution Assembled From Fragments and Debris&quot; <cite>New York Times</cite> (15 November 1991) A8.
<p>
<li><a name="sixteen">The turning point</a> apparently came when a C.I.A. analyst linked a quarter-inch-square
wafer of circuit board found in luggage container AVE 4041 PA (and believed to be a fragment of the Pan Am 103 bomb's timer) to the circuitry of other timing devices known to be used in twenty other Libyan bombs. A Swiss firm had manufactured the twenty MST-13 timers for Libyan intelligence agents. Ten of the timers were confiscated in Senegal, one more through a bungled assault on a U.S. embassy in Togo, and a twelfth in the wreckage of another bombing: French Union de transports a&eacute;riens (UTA) Flight 772 on 19 September 1989. This circuit board, a digital model designed to trigger at a set time, also exculpated Jabril, whose bombs used barometric timers that triggered at particular altitudes. See Johnston, &quot;Plane Blast Still Open Case, U.S. Says,&quot; <i>supra</i> note 14, and M. Cox &amp; T. Foster, <cite>Their Darkest Day: the Tragedy of Pan Am 103 and Its Legacy of Hope</cite> (New York: Grove Weidenfeld, 1992) at 174--5.
<p>
<li><a name="seventeen">A piece</a> of an infant's Babygro blue cotton jumpsuit that carried the label &quot;Malta Trading Company&quot; showed blast damage, indicating that it had been inside the bomb
suitcase. The jumpsuit featured the same blast damage as a pair of patterned pants with the label &quot;Yorkie Trading Company 0005.&quot; Investigators travelled to Malta and, incredibly, used the labels to trace the clothing to the store in Sliema where it had been purchased. The shopkeeper could vividly recall the customer, who randomly bought a child's jumpsuit, a pair of herringbone pants, a cardigan sweater, and an old tweed jacket. Because it was raining that day, the man also purchased an umbrella. When investigators reexamined the five umbrellas recovered from the plane wreckage, they discovered only one with blast damage. Police photographs later allowed the shopkeeper to identify Libyan national Abdel Baset Ali Mohamed al-Megrahi as the man in his store on 7 December 1988. See A. Rosenthal, &quot;U.S. Accuses Libya as 2 Are Charged in Pan Am Bombing&quot; <cite>New York Times</cite> (15 November 1991) A1 at A8, and Cox &amp; Foster, <i>supra</i> note 16 at 138--9.
<p>
<li><a name="eighteen">Al Amin Khalife Fhimah,</a> an employee of Libyan Arab Airlines in Malta, was alleged to have stolen the luggage tags necessary to route the suitcase containing the bomb onto Pan Am 103. U.S. authorities had obtained a crucial diary alleged to belong to Al Amin Khalife Fhimah; it contained entries indicating his presence in Malta prior to the bombing as well as reminders to bring stolen Air Malta luggage tags marked &quot;Rush JFK.&quot; See Rosenthal, <i>supra</i> note 17 at A8, and Cox &amp; Foster, <i>supra</i> note 16 at 174.
<p>
<li><a name="nineteen"><cite>Aviation Security Act</cite></a> (U.K.), 1982, c. 36. See also the <cite>Announcement by the Lord Advocate of Scotland</cite>, 14 November 1991, reproduced in <cite>Letter dated 20 December 1991 from the Permanent Representative of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland to the United Nations addressed to the Secretary General</cite>, S/23307, 31 December 1991, Annex I.
<p>
<li><a name="twenty">A computerized baggage loading list revealed that a</a> 13th suitcase had been transferred from Air Malta Flight KM 180 to Pan Am 103A unaccompanied by a passenger. The list had been printed by an alert computer operator on duty the night that Pan Am 103 went down. Had she not made the printout, the information might well have been lost forever since the computer system purged such data after eight days. See Cox &amp; Foster, <i>supra</i> note 16 at 137.
<p>
<li><a href="twenty1">Johnston,</a> &quot;Plane Blast Still Open Case, U.S. Says,&quot; <i>supra</i> note 14. The Air Accident Investigations Board (AAIB), the British counterpart to the Federal Aviation Administration, had removed all of the plane's debris to a hangar in Longtown, Scotland. Reassembled metal shards indicated that the bomb had been placed on the left side of the plane and exploded just below the large &quot;P&quot; in the Pan Am logo. More careful analysis would point to cargo bay 14L, which contained almost no bags from Heathrow. See S. Emerson &amp; B. Duffy, <cite>The Fall of Pan Am 103: Inside the Lockerbie Investigation</cite> (New York: G.P. Putnam's Sons, 1990) at 152, 156--7.
