consistent pattern of Libyan-inspired terrorism dates from early in Qaddafi's leadership and cannot be ignored.&quot; Richard Boucher, a U.S. State Department spokesperson, stated that, &quot;[t]he bombers
were Libyan government intelligence operatives. This was a Libyan government operation from start to finish.&quot; Douglas Hurd, U.K. Foreign Secretary, speaking in the British House of Commons on 14
November 1991, stated that he regarded the case as one of &quot;mass murder, which is alleged to involve the organs of government of a State.&quot; See Rosenthal, <i>supra</i> note 17 and SC/5057, 30 December 1988, Annex II.
