<li><a name="ninety9"><i>Ibid.</i></a> at 177--78 (Marshall C.J.U.S.). See also Judge Bustamente's dissenting opinion in <cite>Certain Expenses</cite>: &quot;It cannot be maintained that the resolutions of any organ of the United Nations are not subject to review: that would amount to declaring the pointlessness of the Charter or its absolute subordination to the judgment---always fallible---of the organs.&quot; He then noted the special case of the United Nations, above which no higher tribunal existed to review its acts. Thus, only the United Nations itself had the power to rectify or confirm its own acts. See <cite>Certain Expenses</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 95 at 304 (Bustamente, J., diss. op.).
