<li><a name="one03">See</a> <cite>Certain Expenses</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 95 at 168. Note, however, the caution with which the presumption was identified: &quot;[W]hen the Organization takes action <i>which warrants the assertion that it was appropriate for the fulfilment of one of the stated purposes of the United Nations</i>, the presumption is that such action is not <i>ultra vires</i> the Organization&quot; (emphasis added).
<p>
<li><a name="one04"><cite>Libya v. U.S.</cite></a> (Prov. Meas.), <i>supra</i> note 6 at 138 (Lachs, J., sep. op.).
<p>
<li><a name="one05"><cite>Certain Expenses</cite>, <i>supra</i> note 95 at 168.</a>
<p>
<li><a name="one06">But see the opinion of Judge Morelli</a> in <cite>Certain Expenses</cite>: &quot;[T]he failure of [an] act to conform to the rules concerning competence has no influence on the validity of the act, which amounts to saying that each organ of the United Nations is the judge of its own competence.&quot; See <i>ibid.</i> at 223--4, para. 8 (Morelli, J., sep. op.). Judge Morelli appears to mean that each organ is the <i>final</i> judge of its own competence. This conclusion, I submit, is irreconcilable with his earlier assertion that United Nations organs can indeed act invalidly (see note 95, <i>supra</i>). Appointing each organ to be the only judge of its competence denies any limits to that competence, and thus denies the ability to act in an invalid manner.
