<head>
<title>UTLR Vol. 51 No. 2: Abstract 2</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol51#2">Volume 51 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>The Limits of Free Trade: Sovereignty, Environmental Protection, and NAFTA
<p> 
MICHAEL W. DUNLEAVY</h1>
<p><br>
<center><h3>ABSTRACT</h3></center>

A tension exists between the ongoing drive toward free trade in the world economy and the principle of state
sovereignty. As pressures to remove trade barriers increase, domestic law-making abilities are compromised. This article discusses the trade-sovereignty conflict, using domestic environmental concerns as a framework for discussion and using the North American Free Trade Agreement as a specific example of the problem. The nature of the interaction between trade and sovereignty is surveyed from theoretical and historical perspectives and some permutations of the clash between trade imperatives and sovereign choices, as embodied by environmental protection goals, are illustrated in both hypothetical and real-world scenarios. The potential for such a clash between
trade and environment in NAFTA is examined. Various approaches to the resolution of conflicts between the goals of free trade and those of environmental protection are surveyed, including dispute resolution and harmonization, and there is discussion of the applicability of these approaches in NAFTA.
<p>
Il existe une tension entre les efforts qui se poursuivent en faveur du libre-&eacute;change dans l'&eacute;conomie mondiale et le principe de la souverainet&eacute; d'&Eacute;tat. &Agrave; mesure qu'augmentent les efforts pour &eacute;liminer les barri&egrave;res commerciales, la capacit&eacute; l&eacute;gislative nationale se voit limiter.
Cet article fait le point sur le conflit entre le commerce et la souverainet&eacute; dans le cadre des pr&eacute;occupations environnementales nationales et donne en exemple l'Accord de libre-&eacute;change
nord-am&eacute;ricain. L'auteur &eacute;tudie l'interaction entre le commerce et la souverainet&eacute; dans une perspective th&eacute;orique et historique. De plus, pour illustrer l'opposition entre les imp&eacute;ratifs du  commerce et les choix souverains, tels que concr&eacute;tis&eacute;s dans les objectifs de la protection de l'environnement, l'auteur a recours &agrave; des sc&eacute;narios hypoth&eacute;tiques et r&eacute;els. Il examine par la suite les possibilit&eacute;s d'un tel conflit opposant le commerce et l'environnement dans le cadre de l'AL&Eacute;NA. L'auteur passe en revue diverses fa&ccedil;ons de concilier les buts respectifs du libre-&eacute;change et de la protection environnementale, y compris les processus de r&egrave;glement des diff&eacute;rends et d'harmonisation. Il discute aussi de la pertinence de ces approches dans le cadre de
l'AL&Eacute;NA.
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
Please send comments and suggestions to <a href = "mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</a>
