<html>
<head>
<title>UTLR Vol. 51 No. 2: Abstract 4</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol51#2">Volume 51 Number 2</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>Refugee Status for Female Circumcision Fugitives: Building a Canadian Precedent
<p> 
VALERIE OOSTERVELD</h1>
<p><br>
<center><h3>ABSTRACT / <a href="../utlr51-2/oosterv.htm">Fulltext</a></h3></center>

The French Commission for Appeals of Refugees has recently recognized that female circumcision may be considered as a form of persecution under the <cite>United Nations Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees</cite>. It is conceivable, and likely, that the Canadian Immigration and Refugee Board will follow this precedent in a similar case. The Chair of the Immigration and Refugee Board has recently released guidelines for assessing whether women fearing gender-related persecution qualify as refugees. These guidelines provide the most hope for claimants fleeing circumcision. The existing case law is useful insofar as it provides the Board with clues on how to approach a gender-related case. This article attempts to present the context of female circumcision and document the arguments that one would make on behalf of a claimant fleeing female circumcision to prove that she should be given refugee status.
<p>
En France, la Commission d'appel pour les r&eacute;fugi&eacute;s a r&eacute;cemment reconnu que la circoncision f&eacute;minine peut &ecirc;tre consid&eacute;r&eacute;e comme une forme de pers&eacute;cution au sens de la <cite>Convention des Nations Unies relative au statut des r&eacute;fugi&eacute;s</cite>. Il est vraisemblable, et m&ecirc;me probable, que la Commission canadienne de l'immigration et du statut de r&eacute;fugi&eacute; suivra cet exemple dans des circonstances semblables. La pr&eacute;sidente de la Commission de l'immigration et du statut de r&eacute;fugi&eacute; a r&eacute;cemment publi&eacute; des crit&egrave;res permettant de d&eacute;terminer si les femmes craignant d'&ecirc;tre pers&eacute;cut&eacute;es en
raison de leur sexe sont &eacute;ligibles au statut de r&eacute;fugi&eacute;. Ces crit&egrave;res constituent le meilleur espoir pour les revendicatrices qui fuient la circoncision. La jurisprudence existante est utile dans la mesure o&ugrave; elle indique &agrave; la Commission la fa&ccedil;on de proc&eacute;der dans un cas de pers&eacute;cution sexuelle. L'auteure pr&eacute;sente le contexte de la circoncision f&eacute;minine et tente
d'&eacute;laborer les arguments que l'on invoquerait en faveur d'une revendicatrice fuyant la circoncision afin de prouver qu'on devrait lui accorder le statut de r&eacute;fugi&eacute;.
<p><br>
<hr>
