<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>University of Toronto Faculty of Law Review, Vol. 52 No. 1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<CENTER>[<A HREF="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</A>] [<A HREF="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol51#2">Volume 51 Number 2</A>]</CENTER>
<P><BR>
<h1>Refugee Status for Female Circumcision Fugitives: Building a Canadian Precedent<br>
VALERIE OOSTERVELD</h1>

<i>The French Commission for Appeals of Refugees has recently recognized that female circumcision may be considered as a form of persecution under the</i> United Nations Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees<i>. It is conceivable, and likely, that the Canadian Immigration and Refugee Board will follow this precedent in a similar case. The Chair of the Immigration and Refugee Board has recently released guidelines for assessing whether women fearing gender-related persecution qualify as refugees. These guidelines
provide the most hope for claimants fleeing circumcision. The existing case law is useful insofar as it provides the Board with clues on how to approach a gender-related case. This article attempts to present the context of female circumcision and document the arguments that one would make on behalf of a claimant fleeing female circumcision to prove that she should be given refugee status.
<p>
En France, la Commission d'appel pour les r&eacute;fugi&eacute;s a r&eacute;cemment reconnu que la circoncision f&eacute;minine peut &ecirc;tre consid&eacute;r&eacute;e comme une forme de pers&eacute;cution au sens de la </i>Convention des Nations Unies relative au statut des
r&eacute;fugi&eacute;s<i>. Il est vraisemblable, et m&ecirc;me probable, que la Commission canadienne de l'immigration et du statut de r&eacute;fugi&eacute; suivra cet exemple dans des circonstances semblables. La pr&eacute;sidente de la Commission de l'immigration et du statut de r&eacute;fugi&eacute; a r&eacute;cemment publi&eacute; des crit&egrave;res permettant de d&eacute;terminer si les femmes craignant d'&ecirc;tre pers&eacute;cut&eacute;es en raison de leur sexe sont &eacute;ligibles au statut de r&eacute;fugi&eacute;. Ces crit&egrave;res constituent le meilleur espoir pour les revendicatrices qui fuient la circoncision. La jurisprudence existante est utile dans la mesure o&ugrave; elle indique &agrave; la Commission la fa&ccedil;on de proc&eacute;der dans un cas de pers&eacute;cution sexuelle. L'auteure
pr&eacute;sente le contexte de la circoncision f&eacute;minine et tente d'&eacute;laborer les arguments que l'on invoquerait en faveur d'une revendicatrice fuyant la circoncision afin de prouver qu'on devrait
lui accorder le statut de r&eacute;fugi&eacute;.</i>
<p><br>
Recently, the French Commission for Appeals of Refugees became the first judicial authority to recognize female circumcision<sup><a href="#one">1</a></sup> as a form of persecution under the terms of the 1951 <cite>United Nations Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees</cite>.<sup><a href="#two">2</a></sup> This landmark ruling has now set a precedent for the determination of claims by
fugitives from female circumcision in other countries that have a similar refugee determination process. It is likely that a similar case will present itself in the near future to the Canadian Immigration and Refugee Board (&quot;IRB&quot; or &quot;Board&quot;). This possibility necessitates the development of a thoughtful and informed approach to such a claim. The likelihood of a female circumcision case succeeding in Canada has been greatly improved with the federal government's recent announcement that guidelines have been issued to the IRB for deciding cases of gender-based persecution. The aim of this article is to outline and to analyze the arguments that may be used in such a case. 
<p>
The first section of this article describes the <cite>Aminata Diop</cite> case, and the context of female circumcision generally. The description of female circumcision is necessarily lengthy, and is meant to aid those with little knowledge of the practice and its history. The definition of &quot;refugee&quot; is then explored, especially the grounds enumerated in the definition on which a woman may claim gender-based persecution. The ramifications of the recent guidelines issued by the Immigration and Refugee Board regarding female refugees are then discussed. Finally, evidentiary problems that may arise in a Canadian case are set out. These considerations, taken together,  lead to the conclusion that it is plausible for a Canadian court or refugee tribunal to recognize the threat of, or practice of, female circumcision as a form of persecution and women facing this persecution as refugees within the existing legislation, and certainly within the recent guidelines on the definition of `refugee.'  
<p>
<h3><cite>Aminata Diop</cite> Case<sup><a href="#three">3</a></sup></h3>

The parents of 20-year-old Aminata Diop of Mali arranged a marriage for her to the son of her father's friend.
Before she could marry him, however, her family and fianc&eacute; insisted that she be circumcised.<sup><a href="#four">4</a></sup> When she refused to undergo this procedure, her father beat her. Diop did not want to be circumcised for many reasons, one of which was that she recognized the physical danger circumcision could put her in: her friend in Mali had died three days after her circumcision was done. Diop fled from Mali to France in October 1991 and made an unprecedented request of the French government for asylum as a refugee under the terms of the <cite>Geneva Convention</cite>. Her initial request was rejected, and she appealed that decision. 
<p>
On appeal, the French Commission for Appeals of Refugees recognized that the threat or practice of genital mutilation is a form of persecution and that Diop consequently fell within the definition of &quot;refugee&quot; set out in the <cite>Geneva Convention</cite>. However, she was denied refugee status because she had failed to appeal for help from authorities in Mali and therefore had not exhausted local remedies. The Commission acknowledged, but did not find it determinative, that the Malian authorities are guilty of tolerating female circumcision and probably would not have done anything for Diop. Diop, to prove that her fear of persecution was real, introduced as evidence a letter in which Diop's mother warned
her that she would be in danger if she returned to her village. Because the letter was dictated by Diop's illiterate mother rather than written by her, it was considered hearsay and was deemed inadmissible. A further appeal was filed in late November 1991, challenging the higher court's ambiguous position that genital mutilation constitutes persecution when &quot;the parties concerned had been personally exposed to the operation against their will.&quot; The actual operation is presumably the confrontation that a refugee claimant would hope to avoid, and if the refugee tribunals construe this comment narrowly, it is possible that the French authorities would only allow as refugees those women who were forced to undergo
circumcision. Those women fleeing the threat of circumcision, such as Aminata Diop, could be left out.
<p>
If a case similar to Diop's arises in Canada, it will be necessary to understand what female circumcision is and why it continues today. Vast numbers of women around the world are pressured to undergo this procedure every year, and there is a need for recognition of those who flee this pressure. The following
description of female circumcision sets out the context of the procedure and why it continues to be performed today, even after many groups and governments have expressed their opposition to the
practice. It is important to comprehend the various factors that affect a woman's decision to flee the practice of female circumcision in her community, because a court or tribunal must be made aware of how these factors can be viewed as persecution.
<p>
<h3>What Is Female Circumcision?</h3>

Female circumcision, also referred to as genital mutilation, is a traditional practice that involves the cutting away of all or part of the external female genitalia---the clitoris, the labia minora, and the labia majora.<sup><a href="#five">5</a></sup> There are varying practices with regard to the amount of genitalia cut away.<sup><a href="#six">6</a></sup> The least severe form is called ritualistic circumcision, where the clitoris is merely nicked. The second form is called &quot;sunna&quot; by Muslims, and involves the removal of the outer layer of skin over the clitoris.  Sunna has been equated with male circumcision since the clitoris itself is not usually damaged. A third, more severe form of circumcision is called excision or clitoridectomy. In some countries, this is also called &quot;sunna&quot; circumcision. This is the most common form of female circumcision, and involves the removal of the entire clitoris and usually the labia
minora. The most severe form is called Pharaonic circumcision, or infibulation. In this procedure, common in countries such as Sudan,<sup><a href="#seven">7</a></sup> virtually all of the external female genitalia are removed. With this type of circumcision, the entire clitoris and labia minora are cut or scraped away, as well as some of the labia majora, keeping enough skin on the labia majora to sew the lips together with acacia tree thorns. This process leaves only a small opening (roughly the size of a pinhole) for the passing of urine and menstrual fluid. In the most severe Pharaonic circumcisions,<sup><a href="#eight">8</a></sup> not even skin is left. With infibulation, the woman's or girl's legs are then tied
together so that she is immobilized while the wound heals.
<p>
The age at which female circumcision is done varies from country to country. In countries such as Kenya, Tanzania, and Mali, as in Aminata Diop's case, circumcision is performed on women on their wedding night or after they have had their first child.<sup><a href="#nine">9</a></sup> In Mauritania, Nigeria, and Ethiopia, the operation is performed on very young babies.<sup><a href="#ten">10</a></sup> Other countries circumcise girls at age 8 or 9.
<p>
Female circumcision occurs all over the world but is mostly seen in a band of countries stretching east from Mali, Senegal, and Sierre Leone in Africa to Oman in the Middle East. It is estimated that 98  percent of all Somalian women have been circumcised (about 4.1 million women).<sup><a href="#eleven">11</a></sup> In Ethiopia, the estimate is 90  percent of all women, which translates into roughly 23.3 million women. In West and Central Africa, the  percentages of women who have undergone female circumcision is lower, although where the population is high, the actual numbers are high: Nigeria is at 50 percent (29.7 million women) and Ghana at 30 percent (2.25 million women). Hosken estimates that the total number of women who have been circumcised in Africa is around 110.53 million. She does not include in this number those African countries where only a small  percentage of the population practises female circumcision (Cameroon, Congo, Zaire, and Tanzania, for example), so the actual total is 2 to 3 million higher.<sup><a href="#twelve">12</a></sup> In addition, female circumcision is &quot;exported&quot; to other countries, such as the Netherlands,<sup><a href="#thirteen">13</a></sup> France,<sup><a href="#fourteen">14</a></sup> and England,<sup><a href="#fifteen">15</a></sup> as well as Canada<sup><a href="#sixteen">16</a></sup> and the United States. Female circumcision is also practised in the Arab Peninsula and in the Persian Gulf, while a less damaging form is practised by devout Muslims in areas of Malaysia and Indonesia.<sup><a href="#seventeen">17</a></sup> Thus, a woman escaping female circumcision could be from almost anywhere, although she is most likely to come from a country, such as Sudan or Somalia, where the vast majority of women are circumcised, and from a society that does not offer any alternatives.
<p>
Why does female circumcision happen?  There are many religious, cultural, and health justifications given for the procedure by those that practise it. The most pervasively cited reason given for the practice is that it allows for the sexual control of females.<sup><a href="#eighteen">18</a></sup> Female circumcision is believed to discourage promiscuity by reducing a woman's desire for sexual intercourse: it is &quot;the most effective means to keep the girls' virginity intact.&quot;<sup><a href="#nineteen">19</a></sup> Lightfoot-Klein notes that circumcision serves not only to protect a woman from aggressive males, but also to protect her from her own sexuality.<sup><a href="#twenty">20</a></sup> The belief that uncircumcised women cannot help but exhibit an unbridled and voracious appetite for promiscuous sex is prevalent in all
societies that practise female circumcision.<sup><a href="#twenty1">21</a></sup> Because the only lifestyle deemed appropriate for an uncircumcised woman is prostitution, an uncircumcised woman is considered unmarriageable.<sup><a href="#twenty2">22</a></sup> In contrast, a circumcised woman (that is, a sexually controlled woman) is seen as a benefit to her family's honour and social position.
<p>
Another reason given for circumcision is that it is demanded by religion. Although Hosken notes that female circumcision is not advocated in any formal religious teachings,<sup><a href="#twenty3">23</a></sup> it is widely believed by those that practise circumcision that it is required by their religion. Female circumcision is largely found in African Islamic countries, and to a lesser extent among Animists, African Coptic Christians, and a small sect of Ethiopian Jews called Fallashas.<sup><a href="#twenty4">24</a></sup> It appears that the heavy emphasis on both the physical state of virginity within the Muslim religion and the importance of patrilineage leads to an institutionalization of female circumcision in some regions as the best method of controlling &quot;purity.&quot;  In this way, then, religion becomes inseparable from cultural values:
<blockquote>
From the standpoint of honor and of Islamic norms of modesty, female sexuality is threatening. Socialized to believe that infibulation offers a physiological and social sanctuary from the threat inherent in their sexuality, women remain its greatest advocates, gladly subjecting their beloved daughters and granddaughters to the ordeal in order to protect them and the patrilineage. The latter result is of utmost importance to traditional women, because the patrilineage is their immediate and primary source of identity and security ... in what they are taught to envision as a dangerous and hostile world outside the walls of the
family compound. Being more vulnerable than men (i.e., without institutionalized power or authority) they have an equal, if not greater interest in safeguarding the lineage's position in the larger society.<sup><a href="#twenty5">25</a></sup> 
</blockquote>
The justification of religion is intimately linked to the upholding of cultural values and to the maintenance of a certain power structure within society.
<p>
A further reason given for female circumcision is that the procedure will improve a woman's health and appearance. It is widely believed that the clitoris, if left in its natural state, will grow to the size of a penis.<sup><a href="#twenty6">26</a></sup> This possibility is considered extremely unfeminine
and ugly. It is also believed that a woman's genitalia, if left uncut, will produce offensive discharges: an uncut woman is considered polluted and unclean.<sup><a href="#twenty7">27</a></sup> Another reason given under the rubric of health is that circumcision increases the fertility of women and that it has other healing powers.<sup><a href="#twenty8">28</a></sup> Finally, in some cultures, the clitoris is considered poisonous<sup><a href="#twenty9">29</a></sup> or evil and therefore must be removed. For example, in Southern Nigeria, &quot;[t]he clitoris is considered to be a dangerous organ which can cause symbolic or spiritual injury to the baby.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty">30</a></sup> 
<p>
Female circumcision has been done for thousands of years,<sup><a href="#thirty1">31</a></sup> and is
therefore considered an important tradition. Slack describes several studies in which tradition was the reason given most often for why circumcision continues despite education campaigns that explain that the health and fertility beliefs are myths.<sup><a href="#thirty2">32</a></sup> Dareer notes that &quot;rites and traditional practices are taken for granted and people do not expect to be asked `why' they actually participate in them.&quot;<sup><a href="#thirty3">33</a></sup> Very often, traditions are so firmly woven into the social fabric of the culture in which circumcision is practised that people feel powerless to stop the practice.<sup><a href="#thirty4">34</a></sup> Female circumcision is seen by some as a custom much larger than the people who practise it.
<p>
Why does the practice of female circumcision continue? Some reasons have been hinted at above, such as the strength of tradition. A lack of education among the women who erroneously believe in the health benefits of circumcision also contributes to the perpetuation of the practice, since these women teach their children the myths their mothers taught them. Illiteracy plays a role, since men and women who cannot read must depend on what is said by others, such as their religious leaders, for information.<sup><a href="#thirty5">35</a></sup> They cannot read the Koran or other writings to determine whether female circumcision is demanded of them by their religion. Furthermore, there is often a psychological need to maintain tradition: the control women have over their daughters and daughters-in-law in terms of when the procedure is to be done is often the only control a woman can assert in a patriarchal society.<sup><a href="#thirty6">36</a></sup> The practice of female circumcision as a tradition is usually so deeply ingrained in a society that it serves as a power that helps to bind the community together at the same time as it provides a source of cultural identity that is crucial in small communities.<sup><a href="#thirty7">37</a></sup> Thus, any attempt to remove an identifier such as female circumcision without having something equally respected with which to replace it will face opposition from those affected. The concern is that communities faced with uncertainty will disintegrate with the removal of a central custom.
<p>
On a more individual level, the pressure to undergo circumcision can be overwhelming. Where the practice is widespread among the group one identifies with, one will hesitate to condemn the practice for fear of ostracism. Onadeko and Adekunle describe how, in Nigeria, even educated women opposed to female circumcision underwent the procedure because of family and social pressures.<sup><a href="#thirty8">38</a></sup> The practice is often surrounded with very positive rituals and attention
that women and girls do not regularly receive.<sup><a href="#thirty9">39</a></sup> To eliminate female circumcision could also eliminate these rituals, and the opportunity they provide for women to feel respected. Those midwives whose job it is to perform circumcisions and to attend to births oppose any change in tradition that threatens the source of their livelihood. In a society where women do not have many roles beyond daughter, wife, mother, midwife, and prostitute, the loss of &quot;business&quot; for a midwife due to the elimination of circumcision can be devastating.<sup><a href="#forty">40</a></sup> All of these sources of pressure add to the perpetuation of the practice, and also illuminate how many aspects of a society would have to change in order to eliminate circumcision.
<p>
Female circumcision is a very complicated practice, one that must be understood in the context of culture, religion, and tradition. In this article, the references to those fleeing female circumcision will be to women such as Aminata Diop. The reference is not to children, even though they also suffer circumcisions, because
children are affected by different laws, such as the <cite>United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child</cite>.<sup><a href="#forty1">41</a></sup> This article explores the possibility that women who flee their villages to escape from female circumcision<sup><a href="#forty2">42</a></sup> are <cite>Geneva Convention</cite> refugees within the context of Canadian immigration law.
<p>
<h3>The Refugee Determination Process</h3>

The definition of a refugee in international law can be found in the <cite>Geneva Convention</cite>. Canada has codified the <cite>Convention</cite>'s definition into s. 2(1) of the <cite>Immigration Act</cite>. Section 2(1) reads:
<blockquote>
&quot;Convention Refugee&quot; means any person who<br>
(a) by reason of a well-founded fear of persecution for reasons of race, religion, nationality, membership in a particular social group or political opinion,<br>
<dd>(i) is outside the country of the person's nationality and is unable or, by reason of that fear, is unwilling to avail himself of the protection of that country.<sup><a href="#forty3">43</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Women do not, as a class, fit within this definition. Grounds for fleeing gender-based persecution are not enumerated. Recommendations have been made by the international legal community to change this. The United Nations High Commission of Refugees commented in 1985 that states, 
<blockquote>
in the exercise of their sovereignty, are free to adopt the interpretation that women asylum-seekers who face harsh or inhuman treatment due to their having transgressed the social mores of the society in which they live may be considered as a &quot;particular social group&quot; within the meaning of Article 1 A(2) of the 1951 United Nations Refugee Convention.<sup><a href="#forty4">44</a></sup> 
</blockquote>
The need for a category that includes gender persecution arises from the fact that women have not, in the past, fit especially well within the existing categories. 
<p>
Worldwide, women are most active in the private, non-regulated, sphere of life. The private sphere is defined differently by different cultures but, in general, women are much less likely to be involved in traditional politics or in the publicly active religious, racial, nationalist, or social groups whose persecution or lack of
state protection is publicized.<sup><a href="#forty5">45</a></sup> As a result, in Canada the majority of refugee claimants are single men or men with families because their persecution is easier to identify.<sup><a href="#forty6">46</a></sup> The effect of this is to create a body of Canadian case law based on male claims such that female-specific definitions of &quot;social group&quot; or &quot;political opinion&quot; have not been created.<sup><a href="#forty7">47</a></sup> To date, there have not been any refugee cases in Canada that have dealt with the topic of female circumcision. For those who are fleeing female circumcision, or some other form of violence against women, these facts are not favourable. However, there are guarantees to which the Canadian government is bound which provide the basis for a positive finding of refugee status vis-&agrave;-vis these femaleclaimants.
<p>
The government of Canada has several objectives that it aims to fulfil with the <cite>Immigration Act</cite>. Two of these objectives are important for women. The first is &quot;to ensure that any person who seeks admission to Canada on either a permanent or temporary basis is subject to standards of admission that do not discriminate in a manner inconsistent with the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty8">48</a></sup> The second is &quot;[t]o fulfil Canada's international legal obligations with respect to refugees and to uphold its humanitarian tradition with respect to the displaced and the persecuted.&quot;<sup><a href="#forty9">49</a></sup> In deciding cases, then, the Canadian Convention Refugee Determination Board cannot contravene the <cite>Charter</cite> or any
international treaty law that Canada has ratified. In this context, the s. 15(1) guarantee of the <cite>Charter</cite> is especially important in the case of a woman fleeing female circumcision: her equality rights must be respected. The different position of women vis-&agrave;-vis men in the refugee determination process must be recognized. Women's experiences must be analyzed for what they are and should not be examined solely on the basis of comparison with male experiences. A woman's right to life, liberty, and security of the person under s. 7 must also be considered when her case is being decided,
which may include different concerns from those in the case of a male claimant.<sup><a href="#fifty">50</a></sup>
<p>
Canada's obligations to women in international law are important to keep in mind when framing an argument. Canada has signed and ratified the <cite>Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women</cite>, which states in art. 2 that parties shall condemn discrimination against women in all of its forms, and in art. 5(a) that 
<blockquote>
States Parties shall take all appropriate measures: (a) To modify the social and cultural patterns of conduct of men and women,  with a view to achieving the elimination of prejudices and customary and all other practices which are based on the idea of the inferiority or the superiority of either of the sexes or on
stereotyped roles for men and women.<sup><a href="#fifty1">51</a></sup>
</blockquote>
An obligation to protect women from female circumcision arises from this article, since much of the reasoning given for the practice is based on the idea of the inferiority of women, and on stereotyped roles for women and men. As a party to the <cite>Convention</cite>, Canada has therefore committed itself to ensuring that women's rights are considered during the refugee process. 
<p>
<h3>The New Guidelines for Refugee Determination</h3>

There are two criteria in the refugee definition that all claimants must satisfy. First, there must be a well-founded fear of persecution. Second, this fear must be based on membership in a particular group. In the case of female circumcision, a finding of refugee status would be dependent on the  haracterization/recognition of female circumcision as a form of gender-based persecution. The Minister of Employment and Immigration, Bernard Valcourt, announced on 29 January 1993 that female claimants may now qualify as refugees if they fear gender-based persecution. Previously, gender persecution had only been considered by the Immigration and Refugee Board if the persecution could also be characterized as persecution based on race, religion, nationality, political opinion, or membership in a particular social group. The new guidelines for refugee determination are intended to make it easier to determine whether women facing persecution based solely on gender are refugees.
<p>
The Minister made it clear in his statement, however, that the statutory definition of refugee will not be amended to include persecution based on gender as one of the articulated categories.<sup><a href="#fifty2">52</a></sup> Instead of changing the actual definition, the Immigration and Refugee Board has issued guidelines detailing how gender persecution is to be read into the existing statutory definition.<sup><a href="#fifty3">53</a></sup> The IRB has recognized that the category of &quot;membership in a particular social group&quot; is well-suited to reading in gender persecution because gender can be seen as an innate and immutable characteristic that is beyond a person's power to change.<sup><a href="#fifty4">54</a></sup> Decision makers are advised, however, to look first to other grounds, especially religion and political opinion, before looking to the more complex &quot;membership in a particular social group&quot; category.<sup><a href="#fifty5">55</a></sup> This approach is a more refined version of the present approach of the Board.
<p>
The changes that the new guidelines make in the determination process will be set out in the discussion of the grounds on which a woman can claim persecution. The most important result of the guidelines is that a woman can now claim that she fears gender-based persecution without concern that the IRB will declare that such persecution is outside of the statutory definition of refugee. It is much less clear, however, whether her persecution must also have some overt links to her religion, political beliefs, race, or nationality. If the Board takes the approach that these overt links are necessary, then a restrictive interpretation of the new guidelines, which appears to defeat the spirit of the proposed changes, will be the result. Such an approach should be guarded against by the Board, and can be if the guidelines are interpreted liberally. 
<p>
<h3>Arguments to Include Women in Social Groupings</h3>

It is most likely that if a woman fleeing female circumcision is to be considered part of any group, it would be a social group. Women are not likely to be publicly active in political, religious, racial, or nationalist organizations in those areas where female circumcision is prevalent. In the extremely patriarchal setting of communities that practise female circumcision, modest and quiet females are valued, and activism that
puts a woman in opposition to others may bring dishonour upon her family. Furthermore, in most Afro-Islamic communities, women have a very narrowly defined role: their focus is their family. In all likelihood, a woman fleeing circumcision will fit only within the social group category.
<p>
How is a social group defined? The United Nations High Commission of Refugees <cite>Handbook</cite> defines a particular social group as a group that comprises &quot;persons of similar background, habits, or social status.&quot;<sup><a href="#fifty6">56</a></sup> This has been defined by case law to include associations of a voluntary nature.<sup><a href="#fifty7">57</a></sup> Goodwin-Gill believes that there
are further factors that are important to the determination whether a person belongs to a particular social group:
<blockquote>
[It is important to identify] unifying factors such as ethnic, cultural, and linguistic origin; education; family background; economic activity; shared values, outlook and aspirations. Also relevant are the attitude to the putative social group of other groups in the same society and, in particular, the treatment accorded
to it by state authorities.<sup><a href="#fifty8">58</a></sup>
</blockquote>
There have been recent Canadian cases defining &quot;social group,&quot; although the resulting definitions are often not very useful in trying to categorize women who do not also have a racial, religious or political connection for their persecution. <cite>Attorney General of Canada v. Ward</cite> defines &quot;social group&quot; narrowly as a group of people associated with one another in some way that is perceived as a possible danger to the government.<sup><a href="#fifty9">59</a></sup> <cite>Astudillo</cite> mentions the immediate family as a social grouping.<sup><a href="#sixty">60</a></sup> In this vein, an argument can be made that a woman fleeing female circumcision is fleeing persecution arising from her membership in a close-knit extended family. The IRB explicitly recognizes that the pressures on that family and within that family to continue the tradition of circumcision may leave the woman with no choice but to flee. The new guidelines note that the strong
jurisprudential authority for allowing claims of familial affiliation may provide the most obvious grounds for a woman claiming persecution.<sup><a href="#sixty1">61</a></sup> In the case of a woman fleeing female circumcision, the Board would almost certainly recognize the pressure that kinship presents for a woman. 
<p>
In <cite>Minister of Employment and Immigration v. Marcel Meyers</cite>,<sup><a href="#sixty2">62</a></sup> Mahoney J.A. concludes that it is not an error in law to conclude that the Refugee Division might find &quot;Trinidadian women subject to wife abuse&quot; to be a particular social
group.<sup><a href="#sixty3">63</a></sup> This particular social grouping is characteristic of the approach of the Board to women's claims insofar as the Board appears to prefer to name a fairly narrow category in which the claimant falls. The Board approaches cases in which claims are specifically gender-related in a similar manner. First, the Board recognizes the obvious unifying factor of gender, as it has been set out in international practice. In the <cite>Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women</cite>, women's specific human rights have been deemed to differ from men's, especially because of the role that pregnancy and the nurturance of children play in women's lives, and because of the specific work women do in the non-monetized sectors of society.<sup><a href="#sixty4">64</a></sup> Women have also been considered as a distinctive group in other international human rights documents, such as the <cite>Convention on the Political Rights of Women</cite> (1953), the <cite>Convention on the Nationality of Married Women (1957), the Convention on Consent to Marriage, Minimum Age for Marriage, and the Registration of Marriages</cite> (1962), and the <cite> Declaration on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women</cite> (1967).<sup><a href="#sixty5">65</a></sup> There are other international arenas where women have been seen as belonging to a distinct social grouping. In 1984, the European Parliament adopted a resolution encouraging states to recognize as refugees women who faced persecution because they had transgressed the social mores of their communities.<sup><a href="#sixty6">66</a></sup> The delegates to the 1985 Soesterburg Conference on refugee women adopted a comparable resolution.<sup><a href="#sixty7">67</a></sup> As noted earlier, the Executive
Committee of the UNHCR has suggested that states adopt an interpretation of social group that would include as asylum seekers women who had offended the social mores of their society. A similar interpretation has been adopted in the <cite>Criteria for Determining &quot;Convention Refugee&quot; Status</cite>, the guidelines of the UNHCR Legal Project in Canada.<sup><a href="#sixty8">68</a></sup>
<p>
Second, the Board delineates the oppression faced by the claimant and others in her position. In <cite>Meyers</cite>, the oppression that the claimant suffered was spousal abuse. <cite>Meyers</cite> also sets out a third identifier: that of culture or race in this case. In making an argument based on the new criteria for determining refugee status, one should recognize the preference of the Board in the past that a woman's position be clarified by description as much as possible. For example, a Board would be more open to the classification of Animata Diop as an African, or a Malian, woman fearing female circumcision rather than as a woman fearing gender-based persecution. By creating a clear, particularized category for the claimant, it is easier for the Board to determine where a woman falls within the proposed framework of the new guidelines. The categorization allows the Board to evaluate in a focused manner how many women would fall within the category and how serious their claims are.<sup><a href="#sixty9">69</a></sup>
<p>
In terms of domestic Canadian case law, it is important to realize that Canadian courts have accepted that women can be recognized as a social group, even without the sort of particularization that the Board prefers. The Supreme Court of Canada has recognized in <cite>R. v. Lavallee</cite> that women's size, strength, socialization, and training in self-defence are usually different from men's in ways that work to women's
disadvantage.<sup><a href="#seventy">70</a></sup> Wilson J.'s decision in <cite>R. v. Morgentaler</cite> supports the argument that women share certain immutable characteristics that are not shared with men, such as the ability to become pregnant. This ability to become pregnant creates fundamentally different choices for women from those for men.<sup><a href="#seventy1">71</a></sup> Women are an easily identifiable group in Canada because of their ability to bear children, their overwhelming presence in low-income employment, their typical pay differential with men, the sexual harassment they encounter, and the treatment they receive as children and adolescents.<sup><a href="#seventy2">72</a></sup> Stairs and Pope state: &quot;This combination of biological and socially
attributed characteristics make women a social group within the meaning of the Convention definition.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy3">73</a></sup>
<p>
There are problems, however, that one may face when arguing that a female claimant falls within a social group defined solely by gender. First and foremost, the group &quot;women&quot; may be seen as too large and indistinct. The draft guidelines hint at this by stressing that the group to be considered under the refugee definition is not solely women, but rather women who have suffered from a serious form of harm that detracts from their human rights and fundamental freedoms.<sup><a href="#seventy4">74</a></sup> This
definition might exclude women who suffer from anything less than sexual violence or other sexual indignities. Despite this qualification on the ability of women to claim refugee status, some decision makers may still be concerned that a social group defined by gender allows too many women to qualify for refugee status under this heading.
<p>
The &quot;floodgates&quot; argument is understandable, but not valid. The argument ignores the fact that there are two phases to the refugee determination process: proving that a claimant is situated in a social group, <i>and</i> proving that she has been persecuted or fears persecution because of that situation. For example, under the new guidelines, a women cannot claim refugee status based solely on the fact that she is subject to a national policy to which she objects if she is not persecuted on the basis of the policy.<sup><a href="#seventy5">75</a></sup> Castel states that &quot;there is nothing in the Convention definition of refugee which would exclude a claimant from its application solely on the basis that the persecution feared was also directed to a large number of members of a group to which the claimant belonged.&quot;<sup><a href="#seventy6">76</a></sup> Castel also refers to guidelines 9 and 10 of the former Canadian
Refugee Status Advisory Committee, which state:
<blockquote>
A person is a refugee whether he is persecuted alone, or persecuted with others. A person need not be singled out for persecution in order to be a refugee. Each claim must be assessed individually. Once that large number of them could also legitimately fear the same persecution.<sup><a href="#seventy7">77</a></sup>
<p>
It is recognized that immigration considerations must not be brought to bear on the application of the refugee definition. The possibility that, if one person is given refugee status, many others might also be entitled to claim refugee status, is not relevant to whether a claimant is a refugee.<sup><a href="#seventy8">78</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Even if there are very large numbers of women persecuted because of gender, this fact is not enough to disqualify the women as claimants. What is relevant is that the woman's situation can be distinguished from the situation of the general population.<sup><a href="#seventy9">79</a></sup> Each case must be evaluated on an individual basis.
<p>
It is not clear that the new guidelines allow for as broad a definition of women as a social group as some may expect. However, even if the Board finds that the classification of &quot;women&quot; as a social group is too broad, a social group of &quot;women plus another defining characteristic&quot; would still help the women who need refugee status. In the case of women fleeing circumcision, their situation may or may not provide the necessary defining characteristic. They may also need to fit a geographic, cultural, racial, national, or religious category in common with other women in similar positions. There are two problems, however, with the narrow approach of &quot;gender plus another defining characteristic&quot; that may affect women claiming refugee status because of any gender-based persecution. The narrow approach is problematic because in defining the group as &quot;women,&quot; not all forms of gender persecution may be addressed.<sup><a href="#eighty">80</a></sup> The second problem with arguing that &quot;women fleeing circumcision&quot; is an appropriate subcategory is that the existing case law does not provide any sort of precedent for accepting two identifying factors as sufficient. The present case law contains definitions of &quot;social group&quot; that have three or more identifying factors. For example, in <cite>W(Y.L.) (Re)</cite>, it was held that &quot;Tamil women in the area of [Sri Lankan] IPKF operations without an adult male protector resident with them form a unity on account of their gender, geographic location and living conditions. They therefore form a group.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty1">81</a></sup> In this case, it appears that geographic location and living conditions are extra factors needed to qualify women as a social group. The tribunal also commented in this case that women were generally segregated socially from men in the claimant's village.<sup><a href="#eighty2">82</a></sup> This factor defined the gender difference. In <cite>Incircyan v. Minister of Employment and Immigration</cite>,<sup><a href="#eighty3">83</a></sup> the Board accepted that a
social group could consist of &quot;single women living in a Moslem country without the protection of a male relative.&quot;  Similarly, &quot;young Tamil women&quot; have been recognized as belonging to a social group.<sup><a href="#eighty4">84</a></sup> In all of these definitions there are more than two defining factors that narrow the grouping.
<p>
In the United States, the Immigration Appeal Board has rejected the floodgates argument and adopted the approach that the definition of social group &quot;must be given a broad and liberal interpretation in order to protect groups or individuals who do not necessarily have political, religious, or racial ties at the root of their persecution.&quot;<sup><a href="#eighty5">85</a></sup> In Canada, under the <cite>Interpretation
Act</cite>,<sup><a href="#eighty6">86</a></sup> every enactment, including the <cite>Immigration Act</cite>, must be given such &quot;fair, large and liberal construction and interpretation as best insures the attainment of its objects.&quot;  Therefore, it can be argued that the Canadian position on the interpretation of &quot;social group&quot; should be similar to the American approach. Edward Broadbent
describes the dynamics of the numbers of women that would actually come to Canada under the new guidelines, even if they are broadly interpreted:
<blockquote>
Voices will clamour that we cannot open the door ... because that would open the floodgates and they would never close. This argument is not only wrong in principle, but it ignores social and political reality. Women around the world are fighting to improve their situation, and the solutions to their problems lie
within their own societies, not in asylum in Canada. Women know this. Their principal struggles are and will remain at home, as will the overwhelming majority of women themselves.<sup><a href="#eighty7">87</a></sup>
</blockquote>
Thus, a fair, large, and liberal interpretation of &quot;gender&quot; as a social group will not attract vast numbers of women. Genevi&egrave;ve Camus-Jacques also believes that the floodgates fear would never be realized because social constraints on women in their country of origin are such that relatively few persecuted women ever manage to flee to other countries for protection.<sup><a href="#eighty8">88</a></sup>
<p>
The complexity involved in defining social groups is the reason for the recommendation in the draft guidelines that the Board look to religious or political factors before social group factors. In the case of women fleeing female circumcision, perhaps the extra defining factors the Board seems to require could be found under the political or religious categories.
<p>
<h3>Arguments to Include Women in Political Groupings</h3>

A woman fleeing female circumcision may face persecution because of her political opinion. This is made clear in the new guidelines.<sup><a href="#eighty9">89</a></sup> Canadian case law has determined that the definition of political is determined by the country of origin, not by Canada: &quot;[T]he crucial test is not whether the Board considers the applicant engaged in political activities, but whether the ruling government of the country from which he claims to be a refugee, considers his conduct to be political activity.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety">90</a></sup> This test could be difficult to meet unless an
interpretation of political opinion relating to women was adopted in Canada that is similar to that in American case law. In the case of <cite>Lazo-Majano v. Immigration and Naturalization Service</cite>,<sup><a href="#ninety1">91</a></sup> the Court held that the rape of a woman by an off-duty soldier could still fall under the category of political persecution:
<blockquote>
[I]f the situation is seen in its social context, Zuniga [the soldier] is asserting the political opinion that a man has a right to dominate and he has persecuted Olympia [the petitioner] through force to accept this opinion without rebellion. Zuniga told Olympia that in his treatment of her he was seeking revenge. But Olympia knew of no injury she had ever done Zuniga. His statement reflects a much more generalized animosity to the opposite sex, an assertion of a political aspiration and the desire to suppress opposition to it. Olympia was not permitted by Zuniga to hold an opinion to the contrary. When by flight, she asserted one, she became exposed to persecution for her assertion. Persecution threatened her because of her political opinion.<sup><a href="#ninety2">92</a></sup>
</blockquote>
As Stairs and Pope note, what appears to be non-political activity by women may, on more careful inspection, turn out to be a form of political protest or organization.<sup><a href="#ninety3">93</a></sup> It is important to ascertain whether a woman fleeing circumcision belongs to any anti-circumcision groups, or has expressed the opinion that she supports such groups. The fact that she had expressed opposition to the procedure and then was threatened with it could indicate that her opinion was viewed as political. Even if she had not expressed opposition to the practice publicly, the act of refusal could be characterized as political in a society where the vast majority of men and women support the procedure. This is analogous to the refusal of some Iranian women to wear a veil as an expression of opposition to the Islamic fundamentalist state.<sup><a href="#ninety4">94</a></sup>
 <p>
If women refuse to follow a community's social mores, they may be considered feminist, and therefore political. However, feminist activity has not in the past been widely perceived as political activity.<sup><a href="#ninety5">95</a></sup> The new guidelines note that where such a minute contravention as the wearing of make-up arouses political fear in certain regimes, it may be almost impossible for women to go
further and develop more recognizable indicia of political opinion.<sup><a href="#ninety6">96</a></sup> The fact that a tribunal or court may not find itself able to make an analogy between opposition to female circumcision and more traditional forms of political opposition because of the difficulty of comparing male and female political experience has been remedied by the draft guidelines. The political nature of the oppression of women in the context of religious laws and ritualization should be recognized by the Board,<sup><a href="#ninety7">97</a></sup> along with the strong ritual and religious connections attached to female circumcision.
<p>
<h3>Persecution</h3>

A woman who claims <cite>Geneva Convention</cite> refugee status must not only place herself within one of the enumerated groups in the definition of refugee, but must also prove that female circumcision is a form of persecution and that the fear of circumcision is well founded. How is persecution defined?  The term is not defined in the <cite>Geneva Convention</cite>, nor is it defined in the <cite>Immigration Act</cite>. The <cite>UNHCR Handbook</cite> notes that
<blockquote>
[f]rom Article 33 of the Convention, it may be inferred that a threat to life or freedom on account of race, religion, nationality, political opinion or membership in a particular social group is always persecution. Other serious violations of human rights---for the same reasons---would also constitute persecution.<sup><a href="#ninety8">98</a></sup>
</blockquote>
The Immigration and Refugee Board has stated that a &quot;serious threat to the claimant's `right to life, liberty and security of the person' amounts to persecution.&quot;<sup><a href="#ninety9">99</a></sup>
The Court in <cite>Rajudeen v. Minister of Employment and Immigration</cite> defined &quot;persecute&quot; by reference to dictionary definitions: &quot;To harass or afflict with repeated acts of cruelty or annoyance; to afflict persistently, to afflict or punish because of particular opinions or adherence to a particular creed or mode of worship.&quot;<sup><a href="#onehundred">100</a></sup> In <cite>Araya Heredio v. Minister of Employment and Immigration</cite>, the Immigration Appeal Board held that &quot;[a]ny repeated or sustained attack on not only a person's physical integrity, but also his moral integrity, constitutes persecution.&quot;<sup><a href="#one01">101</a></sup> The new guidelines note that these definitions were formed on the basis of male experiences, but that they could be applied to the case of circumcision.<sup><a href="#one02">102</a></sup>
<p>
Female circumcision must satisfy a fairly high standard to be considered as persecution. The <cite>Convention Against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment</cite> states in  art. 3(1) that &quot;[n]o State party shall expel, return (`<i>refouler</i>') or extradite a person to another State where there are substantial  grounds for believing that he would be in danger of being subjected to torture.&quot;<sup><a href="#one03">103</a></sup> This definition can be applied to refugee situations.<sup><a href="#one04">104</a></sup> At a minimum, the meaning of &quot;persecution&quot; includes the definition of torture in the <cite>Convention Against Torture</cite>:<sup><a href="#one05">105</a></sup> 
<blockquote>
any act by which severe pain and suffering, whether physical or mental, is intentionally inflicted on a person for such purposes as ... intimidating or coercing him or a third person, or for any reason based on discrimination of any kind ... with the consent or acquiescence of a public official.<sup><a href="#one06">106</a></sup>
</blockquote>
It can be argued quite persuasively that female circumcision is an act that is analogous to the definition of
torture: it causes both severe pain and mental and physical suffering, it is intentionally inflicted, and it is a manifestation of gender discrimination. As observed by the Court in the <cite>Aminata Diop</cite> case, public officials in the claimant's country may ignore the practice. This may be construed as the kind of &quot;consent or acquiescence&quot; referred to in the <cite>Convention Against Torture</cite>. If the
female victims are old enough, it is common for them to manifest severe anxiety and a generalized phobic reaction to being touched, of knives, of social gatherings, or of going to sleep before the circumcision is performed.<sup><a href="#one07">107</a></sup> Furthermore, the memory of friends and sisters who died or who suffered greatly because of the operation weigh heavily on the woman facing circumcision. Aminata Diop herself described her friend's death to the Court when trying to explain this anxiety.<sup><a href="#one08">108</a></sup> This satisfies the mental suffering requirement of the torture definition. 
<p>
This anxiety is well founded. Only rarely is the procedure done by a doctor in sanitary conditions. Usually, a midwife or a grandmother performs the circumcision, with the female being held down by many other women. The procedure is usually done without any anaesthetic, and is often done with an unsanitized sharp instrument such as a stone, kitchen knife, old razor blade, or broken glass.<sup><a href="#one09">109</a></sup> Animal dung and mud are often used to patch the wound in an attempt to stop the bleeding.<sup><a href="#one10">110</a></sup> The female is then immobilized for 15 to 40 days to let the wound heal enough. There are immediate and short-term complications. Slack describes these:
<blockquote>
The unsterilized instruments and unhygienic methods used in the various procedures, especially infibulation, can result in immediate medical problems: hemorrhage, septicemia, shock from pain and blood loss, acute infection (such as tetanus from unclean utensils and the materials used to patch the wounds), urine retention
due to occlusion, damage to and bleeding from adjacent organs and tissue (including rectum and urethra), and even death.<sup><a href="#one11">111</a></sup>
</blockquote>
In the Sudan, where antibiotics are not available, about one-third of all females die as a result of  circumcision.<sup><a href="#one12">112</a></sup> Long-term complications range from frequent urinary tract infections and blockages to severe menstrual problems to an increased likelihood of death during childbirth. Furthermore, the scarring that results can adversely affect how a woman walks<sup><a href="#one13">113</a></sup> and moves, and the method of circumcision can lead to an increased susceptibility to AIDS.<sup><a href="#one14">114</a></sup> Hosken and UNESCO both note that
these problems that stem from circumcision create deep psychological wounds that may be manifested in chronic irritability, anxiety, depressive episodes, psychosis, and fear of sexual intercourse.<sup><a href="#one15">115</a></sup> Torture and female circumcision have much in common. 
<p>
Other aids that courts might consider in defining persecution are the definitions of personal integrity found in Canadian case law. In <cite>R. v. McCraw</cite>, the Supreme Court of Canada held that &quot;[f]or women rape under any circumstance must constitute a profound interference with their physical integrity. As well, by force or threat of force, it denies women the right to exercise freedom of choice as to their partner for sexual relations and the timing of those relations. These are choices of great importance that may have
a substantial effect upon the life and health of every woman.&quot;<sup><a href="#one16">116</a></sup> Female circumcision has similar effects on its victims: a circumcised woman has experienced a profound interference with her physical integrity. A woman is often denied any choice in whether she is to be circumcised or not, and in what form.
<p>
A final consideration that may assist the Convention Refugee Determination Division in deciding whether the threat or practice of female circumcision is persecution is how female circumcision is viewed in Canada. The College of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario has recently banned doctors from performing female  circumcision.<sup><a href="#one17">117</a></sup> The College has also called on the federal government specifically to outlaw the procedure, as several other countries, including the United Kingdom, have done.<sup><a href="#one18">118</a></sup> The government has stated that the act of female circumcision in Canada is to be viewed as an offence under  the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>.<sup><a href="#one19">119</a></sup> In January 1992, Muslim leaders in Ottawa stated that the Koran does not advocate female circumcision.<sup><a href="#one20">120</a></sup> The Ontario Association of Children's Aid Societies considers the circumcision of girls to be child abuse.<sup><a href="#one21">121</a></sup> Clearly, in the Canadian context female circumcision is condemned as criminal and discriminatory.
<p>
<h3>State Connection</h3>

Explicit in the definition of a <cite>Geneva Convention</cite> refugee is the need for a state connection. The definition states that a claimant must be unable or unwilling to avail himself or herself of the protection of his or her country. In <cite>Rajudeen</cite>, it was held to be reasonable that the claimant would not go to the authorities since they were part of the majority group that was persecuting him.<sup><a href="#one22">122</a></sup> It was held that there is a state connection if the state refuses or is unable to protect the claimant from persecutory behaviour.<sup><a href="#one23">123</a></sup> In <cite>Surujpal v. Minister of Employment and Immigration</cite>, MacGuigan J.A. implied that both unwillingness and inability to act are forms of state complicity.<sup><a href="#one24">124</a></sup> In <cite>Ward</cite>, Urie J. held that a claimant who is unwilling to avail himself of the protection of his country of origin implicitly believes that the state and its authorities cannot protect him from those he fears will persecute him.<sup><a href="#one25">125</a></sup> This would usually be the case in those countries where the authorities turn a blind eye to the practice of female circumcision. However, the narrow definition of being &quot;unable&quot; to avail oneself of the protection of the state given in <cite>Ward</cite> as meaning &quot;physically unable&quot;<sup><a href="#one26">126</a></sup> does not assist those who fear circumcision, unless being physically unable is equivalent to being unable to seek protection from state authorities because there are no authorities in the vicinity, as in rural areas, or where the claimant has no means of transportation to the authorities. In <cite>Zalzali v. Minister of Employment and Immigration</cite>, &quot;unable&quot; was held to include situations in which there is no government to appeal to.<sup><a href="#one27">127</a></sup> This may apply in cases of women fleeing circumcision in Somalia.
<p>
The explanation of persecution in the UNHCR Handbook is similar to the Canadian case law:
<blockquote>
Where serious discriminatory or other offensive acts are committed by the local populace, they can be considered as persecution if they are knowingly tolerated by the authorities, or if the authorities refuse, or prove unable, to offer effective protection.<sup><a href="#one28">128</a></sup>
</blockquote>
It is hard to imagine a situation in which the threat of, or the performance of, female circumcision will ever be directly attributable to the state. The most likely scenario is one in which a woman is pressured by her family or community to undergo the procedure, and the state does not provide any adequate legal recourse
to protect against these pressures, or to punish the perpetrators after the fact. There are laws in many countries where female circumcision is practised that ban either the whole procedure or the most extreme procedure, infibulation. It is not enough, however, for states merely to pass laws. 
<p>
In 1974 Sudan passed a law forbidding Pharaonic circumcision. However, the Sudanese laws against infibulation have not been obeyed because &quot;the custom is still an integral, positive-functioning component of the familial complex, and so, indirectly of the entire socio-cultural system.&quot;<sup><a href="#one29">129</a></sup> Sudan's 10 million circumcised women are therefore left without effective enforcement or protection. Similarly, in 1959 the Egyptian Minister of Health recommended that the more extreme procedures performed by midwives be replaced by partial clitoridectomy performed by doctors.<sup><a href="#one30">130</a></sup> A further resolution in 1978 forbade midwives to perform the operations.<sup><a href="#one31">131</a></sup> These laws, however, have had no effect on the amount of circumcision still performed, except to make the performance of the procedure more secretive. The Central African Republic has had legislation banning female circumcision since 1960,<sup>,a href="#one32">132</a></sup> but as of 1992, 50 percent of all women in that country were circumcised.<sup><a href="#one33">133</a></sup> The situation is similar in Guinea: despite the existence of legislation against female circumcision for the last 20 years,<sup><a href="#one34">134</a></sup> 60 percent of all women in that country are circumcised.<sup><a href="#one35">135</a></sup> Tanzania has legislation against female circumcision at the local level, and the heads of state of Benin, Burkino Faso, Kenya, and Senegal have pronounced themselves to be against the practice of female circumcision.<sup><a href="#one36">136</a></sup> However, these positive developments have not actually reduced the numbers of women and girls undergoing circumcision, a fact that indicates the strength of tradition and social pressure and the ineffectiveness of legal sanctions. When female circumcision is supported by the majority of a community's population, it is unlikely that the authorities will be willing or able to enforce any prohibitive legislation. 
<p>
There are many reasons why a lone complainant will not or cannot seek the assistance of the authorities. A victim is sure to face ostracism in her community if she seeks the help of a doctor after a badly managed circumcision and reveals to him or her the name of the midwife, as is required by law in many countries.<sup><a href="#one37">137</a></sup> The law can only be effective if both parents are opposed to circumcision. The head of the family (usually the father of the victim) can threaten the grandmothers (who usually organize the circumcision) with police action should his daughter be circumcised. This has been effective in some cases.<sup><a href="#one38">138</a></sup> If, however, the head of the family supports the circumcision, it is highly unlikely that a young female will oppose her family and community and go to the authorities.
<p>
In many cultures in which circumcision takes place, women are not allowed to venture out of the private domain without a male chaperone, and a woman's evidence may be considered to be worth less than a man's. She would have to get someone to substantiate her claim, probably another woman (since women handle the circumcisions), and in a tight-knit community where a woman's honour is tied to her respect for community mores, this is unlikely. Dareer notes that an additional problem occurs in countries that are not culturally
accustomed to punishing women through the law.<sup><a href="#one39">139</a></sup> Since most of
those who perform and arrange circumcisions are women, countries without a history of charging or trying women are less likely than countries with such a history to have in place methods for the punishment of females that the general public will accept. Consequently, the authorities will be less likely to pursue a
complaint about circumcision. There is a very strong taboo against speaking about female circumcision in most communities that practise the procedure.<sup><a href="#one40">140</a></sup> This also deters women from going to the authorities. All of these factors make it unlikely that a woman could look to the law as a source of protection from circumcision and support an argument that a woman could not avail herself of the protection of her state.
<p>
<h3>Evidentiary Problems</h3>

In assessing a woman's claim of gender-based persecution, the evidence must show that what the claimant genuinely fears is persecution as distinguished from random violence or ordinary crime perpetrated against her as an individual.<sup><a href="#one41">141</a></sup> There may be several evidentiary problems
faced by someone trying to establish that circumcision is a form of persecution. These problems can also apply to other cases of violence against women. First, the claimant may consider it embarrassing or dishonourable to discuss the topic of female circumcision, especially in a public forum such as a Board
hearing.<sup><a href="#one42">142</a></sup> She may, therefore, not want to discuss the particular details of her experience. Second, there is a lack of knowledge within Canadian society generally about the topic of female circumcision, and this means that counsel will have to explain the claimant's situation
carefully. If a woman is fleeing circumcision and has not undergone the procedure, there is probably little physical evidence for her case. In Aminata Diop's case, she was beaten by her father for refusing to be circumcised, so she might have had medical proof of the beating. There may be problems encountered with any evidence that can support the word of the claimant: in Aminata Diop's case, her illiterate mother's dictated letter was considered inadmissible as hearsay evidence. All of these factors must be taken into account in making submissions. Stairs and Pope warn that more extensive submissions than usual will be required for such an unusual claim.<sup><a href="#one43">143</a></sup> 
<p>
There may be resistance to viewing the threat or practice of female circumcision as persecution. Some decision makers may feel that to call circumcision &quot;persecution&quot; is insensitive to the religious and cultural beliefs of the claimant's community. This cultural relativism argument is misleading<sup><a href="#one44">144</a></sup> because it values the practices of the community the claimant is fleeing differently from her right to the integrity of her body and total development. These are rights recognized by Canada in the <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>, the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>, and in Canada's international legal commitments to women. Cultural sensitivity is important, but it must not be used as an excuse for not exploring a gender-based refugee claim. Furthermore, it may be difficult to establish the general human rights record of the claimant's country of origin and the experiences of other similarly situated women, as required in the new guidelines.<sup><a href="#one45">145</a></sup> The new guidelines recognize these evidentiary problems, and direct the decision makers to evaluate the whole of the complainant's evidence with these difficulties in mind.<sup><a href="#one46">146</a></sup>
<p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>

The articulation of new guidelines for refugee determination in Canada is a positive step in determining &quot;the appropriate responses to the complex and inter-related issues of state-sanctioned abuse abroad, conjugal violence against women, and assistance to female refugees in times of world crises.&quot;<sup><a href="#one47">147</a></sup> Although the new policy that adds &quot;gender&quot; persecution to the definition of &quot;refugee&quot; appears to eliminate the need to determine whether women fall under a social or political grouping, it is very likely that the Immigration and Refugee Board will require that women must be linked not only to the gender category but also to another grouping. The political and social grouping tests will be important to demonstrate that a woman fleeing circumcision can fall under more than one part of the definition, thereby creating the web of connections that the Board has favoured in the past. It appears that &quot;state connection&quot; will play a very important role in determining whether a woman has suffered gender-based persecution. One must keep in mind that it is not enough that a woman fall into the category of being persecuted because of &quot;gender&quot;; she must also prove some sort of acquiescence or consent on the part of the state. The Board will interpret these new guidelines as they see fit; since these guidelines cannot be binding on the Board, the Board has the independence to determine exactly how the new guidelines will be used.<sup><a href="#one48">148</a></sup> The hope is that the Board will not expect a level of proof that is unrealistic so as to exclude those cases in which there are laws in place that prohibit female circumcision but societal pressures are such that the laws are not obeyed. 
<p>
It is likely that a case similar to Aminata Diop's, that of a woman fleeing circumcision, will arise in Canada in the near future. This article has attempted to outline the problems one would face in arguing such a case. With the issuing of the new guidelines, gender-related persecution is recognized as a ground for claiming refugee status. Thus, the task of convincing the tribunals and courts that female circumcision is a form of persecution is made easier. However, such a finding will never be automatic. First, the tribunal must decide that female circumcision is gender-related persecution. The fact that the practice is done to women satisfies the gender relation, but the persecution argument may have to be more fully developed if the type of circumcision faced by the claimant was of a less mutilating type or if all of the factors set out in the
<cite>Convention Against Torture</cite> definition are not evident. There will almost certainly be questions from a tribunal as to proof that the claimant had a well-founded fear of circumcision while in her country. The state connection is the hardest argument to make since, if there are laws prohibiting female circumcision in the claimant's state, she must prove that the protection they provide is effectively non-existent. Undoubtedly, there will be inquiries into other potential motivations for leaving the home country.
<p>
The new guidelines provide a better chance for success in cases similar to Aminata Diop's.<sup><a href="#one49">149</a></sup> However, the fact that the definition of refugee has not been amended to include gender as one of the enumerated grounds means that the strongest protection for women facing gender persecution has been denied by Canada. Since the new guidelines only recommend where gender-based concerns can be read in, there is still the danger that the Immigration and Refugee Board will ultimately define the grounds for claims by women narrowly. This may be done in response to the fear that too many women would qualify as refugees otherwise. A narrow reading of the new guidelines would defeat their purpose, and would make it uncertain who will qualify, thereby creating the confusion that the new guidelines were meant to avoid. Canada has the appropriate policies and case-law in place for a woman
fleeing female circumcision to claim refugee status. The test is now whether Canada will set an international precedent by following the letter and spirit of the new guidelines, and admitting women who fear female circumcision as refugees.
<p><br><hr><p>
<CENTER><H2>Endnotes</H2></CENTER>
