<li><a name="seven">H. Lightfoot-Klein,</a> <cite>Prisoners of Ritual: An Odyssey into Female Genital Circumcision in Africa</cite> (New York: Harrington Park Press, 1989) at 31. She notes that 85  percent of all
women in Sudan are circumcised. She cites A. el Dareer, <cite>Woman, Why Do You Weep?</cite> (London: Zed Press, 1982) at 1: out of a total sample of 3,210 women, 3,171 (98.8  percent) were circumcised, and only 39 (1.2  percent) were uncircumcised. Out of these, 2,636 (83.13 percent) were Pharaonically circumcised.
<p>
<li><a name="eight">Pharaonic circumcisions</a> may appear in places that do not have a tradition of female circumcision. Lightfoot-Klein describes this: in southern and western Sudan &quot;Arabization&quot; is spreading, and with it circumcision. Unfortunately, female circumcision is construed as a &quot;modern and hygienic&quot; and &quot;educated&quot; practice, and so excision is taken to extremes, referred to as &quot;scraping the girls clean.&quot;  A similar situation occurs in Uganda, where former exiled militants wish to preserve endangered African customs (not necessarily Ugandan in origin), and so practice the most extreme form of genital mutilation. Lightfoot-Klein, <i>supra</i>, note 7 at 48 and 50.
