<li><a name="ninety1"><cite>Lazo-Majano v. Immigration and Naturalization Service</cite></a>, 813 F.2d 1432 (9th Cir. 1987). In this case, petitioner Olympia Lazo-Majano is a native of El Salvador. A
sergeant in the armed forces, Rene Zuniga, hired the petitioner to do his laundry, and then raped her at gunpoint. He continued to extend his domination over her, raping her and using threats of bombings and grenades. He told her that if her husband, who had fled El Salvador, ever returned, he would kill them both. He told her that if she ever informed on him he would denounce her as a subversive and she would be tortured and killed. The petitioner believed that the armed forces would let Zuniga carry out these threats. The Board of Immigration Appeals affirmed the Immigration Judge's finding that her plight was strictly personal and was not political persecution. She appealed, and this ruling was overturned.
