<head>
<title>UTLR  Vol. 51 No. 1: Abstract 4</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>[<a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a>] [<a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/">Law Review</a>] [<a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/law-review/index.htm#vol51#1">Volume 51 Number 1</a>]</center><p><br>

<h1>Language, Law and Social Power: <cite>Seaboyer; Gayme v. R.</cite> and A Critical Theory of Ideology
<p> 
MICHAEL D. SMITH</h1>
<p><br>
<center><h3>ABSTRACT</h3></center>

Over the last 20 years, the issue of male sexual violence has been a crucial point of mobilization for the women's
movement, and law has been one of the important sites for this struggle. Although feminist agitation for the reform of sexual assault law has met with periodic success, legislative victories have often been nullified in subsequent litigation. This pattern suggests that judicial conservatism remains a significant impediment to progressive social change. To illustrate this point, the author considers the approach taken by the Supreme Court of Canada in <cite>Seaboyer; Gayme v. R.</cite>, the controversial &quot;rape shield&quot; decision. Drawing on critical social theory, the author uses the concept of ideology to demonstrate how the majority judgment, as a form of ideological discourse, serves to reinforce the subordinate status of women. By challenging the legitimacy of the
common-sensical assumptions and discursive strategies embedded in this legal text, the author seeks to undermine the presumptive authority and factitious neutrality that commonly mystify the judicial manufacture of truth.
<p>
Au cours des 20 derni&egrave;res ann&eacute;es, le probl&egrave;me de la violence sexuelle masculine a jou&eacute; un r&ocirc;le crucial dans la mobilisation du mouvement f&eacute;minin, et le droit s'est av&eacute;r&eacute; une dimension importante du d&eacute;bat. Bien que la campagne f&eacute;ministe en faveur d'une r&eacute;forme en mati&egrave;re d'aggression sexuelle ait port&eacute; fruit de fa&ccedil;on p&eacute;riodique, plusieurs victoires l&eacute;gislatives furent renvers&eacute;es au cours de litiges ult&eacute;rieurs. Cet &eacute;tat de choses sugg&egrave;re que le conservatisme judiciaire demeure un obstacle
important &agrave; une &eacute;volution sociale progressive. A titre d'illustration, l'auteur consid&egrave;re l'approche adopt&eacute;e par la Cour Supr&ecirc;me du Canada dans l'arr&ecirc;t <cite>Seaboyer; Gayme v. R.</cite>, mieux connue par la contreverse qu'il souleva au sujet de la loi prot&eacute;geant les victimes de viol. S'inspirant de th&eacute;orie sociale critique, l'auteur se fonde sur le concept id&eacute;ologique pour d&eacute;montrer comment le jugement majoritaire, en tant que forme de discours id&eacute;ologique, sert &agrave; renforcer le statut de subordination des femmes. En mettant en question la l&eacute;gitimit&eacute; des hypoth&egrave;ses et de la rh&eacute;torique qui soustendent le texte de loi, l'auteur tente d'affaiblir l'autorit&eacute; de pr&eacute;somption et la neutralit&eacute; factuelle qui mystifient commun&eacute;ment la
manufacture judiciaire de la v&eacute;rit&eacute;.
<p><br>
<hr>
