<TD width="25%" valign=top><IMG SRC="../../icons/house.gif" HSPACE=10 VSPACE=15 >

<A HREF="../../index.htm"><IMG SRC="../../icons/but3.gif" ALT="Library Home Page" HSPACE=13 VSPACE=15 BORDER=0 ></A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/"><IMG SRC="../../icons/but6.gif" ALT="Faculty of Law Home Page" HSPACE=13 VSPACE=15 BORDER=0 ></A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.utoronto.ca/"><IMG SRC="../../icons/but5.gif" ALT="University of Toronto Home Page" HSPACE=13 VSPACE=15 BORDER=0 ></A><BR>
</TD>

<TD width="75%" valign=top><A NAME="top"></A>

<H1>The Relevance of International Patenting and Plant Breeders' Protection
Systems to Kenya as a Developing Country: Myth or Reality? </H1>

<P>by James Otieno Odek</P>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>ABSTRACT</H3>

<P>This thesis evaluates the pertinence to Kenya of the principles and
standards of the TRIPs Agreement in the creation of local innovative and
adaptive research capabilities. It also examines the suitability of the
UPOV criteria for protection of new plant varieties to enhancing inventiveness
in Kenya. </P>

<P>The UPOV Convention and the TRIPs Agreement inaugurate comprehensive
principles and standards for international patenting and plant breeders'
protection that have altered the structure, function, and scope of technology
accessibility to developing countries. The TRIPs requirement that new plant
varieties must be protected either by patents or an effective <I>sui generis</I>
system makes it hard to divorce international patentability from the protection
of plant breeders. This difficulty invites a consideration of how plant
breeders' rights should be recognized and protected internationally. It
also solicits an analysis of the question of ownership of plant genetic
resources. </P>

<P>The proposition advanced in this study is that the principles and standards
sanctioned by the UPOV Convention and the TRIPs Agreement not only grant
preferential patent protection to enterprises of developed countries in
Kenya, but also condone the uncompensated extraction of plant genetic resources
from Kenya to developed countries. </P>

<P>Thesis thesis concludes by making an equitable case for the commodification
of plant genetic resources and proposes the conferral of ensuing proprietary
rights to groups and communities. A finding is also made that the principles
and standards inaugurated by the UPOV Convention and the TRIPs Agreement
represent a strong emphasis on private rights and a weak recognition of
the social obligations of patentees and holders of plant breeders' rights.
The principles also depict a limited role for public interest and institute
a non-viable public domain in international patentability. </P>

<P><BR>

<HR noshade width=90%></P>

<ADDRESS>Updated and maintained by the <A HREF="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora
Laskin Law Library</A>.<BR>
Please send comments and suggestions to <A HREF="mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</A>
</ADDRESS>

<P>Page created on 16-Aug-96 by Anne Johnston. </P>
</TD>
</TR>
