<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Aministrative Law<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Dyzenhaus</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, handouts, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>This exam is composed of two questions. You must do both questions. Question 1 will count for two thirds of the mark allocation and Question 2 for one third. Hence you should allocate roughly two hours to answering Question 1 and one hour to Question 2.<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you
receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator</b>.<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Question 1<br>
Recall that this question counts for two thirds of the total mark allocation so that you should allocate roughly two hours to answering it. I have no set idea of how long your answer should be. My sense is that you may be best served by spending some time, say, 30 minutes or more planning your answer so that you can spend the remaining time setting our your answer by way of as discrete a set of discussions as is possible. Please also note that to do option A within Question 2, you have to have answered Question 1.</B>
<p>
In 1997 the Conservative Government of Ontario enacts the <cite>Privatisation of Public Powers Regulation Act</cite> (the Privatisation Act). The purpose of the Act is stated in section 1 to be:
<p>
'To oversee the transfer of power from the public to the private sector in order to ensure that the transfer takes place in an orderly and consistent fashion'.
<p>
 The Privatisation Act sets up a Privatisation Board, which, in terms of section 2.1 of the Act, is described thus:
<p>
'The Board shall establish policy in regard to the process of privatization. That policy will be binding on all disputes that may arise in regard to privatisation, including disputes in regard to the Board's jurisdiction over a matter.'
<p>
Section 2.3 makes it clear that the main function of the Board is policy-making. The Board may itself decide that a policy needs to be established in regard to an issue, or it may be asked by any interested party to consider making a policy. But in either case, the way it proceeds is by notice and comment. That is, before a policy can be made, the Board is required to make public its intention to consider a particular issue, and to invite participation by all interested parties in hearings.
<p>
Because it is anticipated that there might be some public sector resistance to the Board's authority, the Board is given by section 2.4 contempt powers, which include the power to fine or sentence to a short term of imprisonment those responsible for refusing to comply with policy established by the Board.
<p>
The first Chair of the Board is a retired judge of the Ontario Court of Appeal. The other four members consist of a retired judge of the Divisional Court of Ontario, a former member of a Conservative Party commission on privatisation, a retired policeman with extensive experience in the Police Services Union, and a law professor specializing in employment law.
<p>
At the same time, the Conservative Government amends the <cite>Public Service Employment Act</cite> of Ontario (the Employment Act), which governs labour relations in the public sector. The amendment which concerns us here removes from section 6 of the Employment Act subsection 6.6.
<p>
This subsection had been enacted by the previous New Democratic Party Government to make it clear that public service unions could include in their bargaining units employees of the companies which had received contracts to perform services previously performed by public service employees. The New Democratic Government had added this subsection to section 6 without further amendment, since that Government regarded the subsection as simply clarifying an interpretative dispute about the powers of the panels of the Public Service Board deciding disputes under public sector collective agreements. The Conservative Government simply removed the subsection.
<p>
As a result, section 6.1 of the Employment Act continues to read as follows:
<p>
6.1 - 'In any dispute as to whether a group of employees constitute a unit appropriate for collective bargaining, the Public Service Board shall determine that question.'
<p>
And section 7 of the Act continues to read as follows:
<p>
7 - 'The Public Service Board shall have final and conclusive authority to determine the law in any matter arising out of a collective agreement, including authority to determine whether an employee is an employee for the purposes of this Act.'
<p>
The Chair of the Public Service Board, Leah Alensa, when asked for her comment on the enactment of the Privatisation Act, said the following.
<p>
'I was appointed to my position because I am known to be someone capable of giving strong leadership in difficult times. We are in those times, and we are going to see an attempt by private power to recreate the inequalities of the past. I will do my best to resist this process'.
<p>
Hospitals in Toronto, which have just been hit by another reduction in their base operating grant, then decide to contract out the bulk of their cleaning services for their hospitals. The Hospital Services Union of Ontario applies to the Public Service Board to include the workers of Speedy Cleaning Services, which has been awarded the contract, in the Hospital Services bargaining unit. The effect would be to include the workers within the scope of the collective agreement between the hospitals and the Union. This application is fully supported by the (otherwise non-unionized) employees of Speedy.
<p>
A tri-partite panel of the Public Service Board convenes to hear this application. Speedy opposes the application on two grounds. First, Speedy argues that the legislative amendment which deleted section 6.6 makes it clear that the panel has no jurisdiction over workers in the private sector. Second, Speedy points out that the issue of statutory interpretation of section 6 is now before the Privatisation Board. For, at the request of various employers' associations, the Privatisation Board is considering whether it should issue a policy statement clarifying the situation in respect of public service unions and employees of private sector companies who have been awarded contracts to do work formerly performed by public service employees.
<p>
Speedy thus argues that the panel should not make any decision prior to the Privatisation Board's determination. The Hospital Services Union argues that the matter is before the proper forum and that the Public Service Board has jurisdiction since the Conservative Government had not clarified the law, but merely returned it to its formerly ambiguous state.
<p>
In discussion after the hearing, the panel members consider whether a full board meeting should be convened to discuss the policy implications of its decision. Two members decide that such a meeting should be convened, but the third has been convinced by Speedy's arguments and sees no need for such a meeting. Against his wishes, a full board meeting is convened. In terms of the customary procedures, all three members attend the meeting, as does Alensa, Chair of the Board. (There is a register of attendance, but no minutes are taken, and no formal attempt is made to ascertain a consensus on the issue.) Speedy's counsel is tipped off about the full board meeting, but his request to be present at the meeting is denied.
<p>
After the meeting the panel reconvenes and the three members hand down a unanimous, closely reasoned decision which upholds the union's argument. That is, the panel declares Speedy's workers to fall within the scope of the collective agreement in the performance of their hospital cleaning services.
<p>
Part of the panel's decision reads as follows:
<p>
'To repeat the reasoning of the Supreme Court of Canada in a rather different context, the Legislature, in enacting the Employment Act made a 'policy choice' as to who is best placed to decide employment issues in the context of public sector employment relations (see <cite>Domtar Inc. v. Quebec</cite> [1993] SCR 756 (Que), Evans <U>et al.</U>, <cite>Administrative Law</cite>, 936, at 949.) To hold otherwise would be to hold that the Legislature has deliberately altered a long established and 'delicate institutional relationship' (Domtar at 946)'; and we would need very clear words to that effect, whether the relationship be between this tribunal and the courts, or between it and other tribunals. The statute under which we are appointed enjoins us in terms of section 1 to avoid imbalances of power in the public sector, and our decision does no more than reflect our statutory mandate'.
<p>
Shortly thereafter, the Privatisation Board convenes a hearing to discuss the situation in respect of public service unions and employees of private sector companies who have been awarded contracts to do work formerly performed by public service employees. The Board gives all interested parties a full opportunity to participate in the hearing.
<p>
At the hearing, various public service unions argue that the privatization policy made by the Privatisation Board should not be in conflict with the determinations of the Public Service Board. The Privatisation Board rejects this argument, saying that it would make a nonsense out of its policy-making function were its discretion to be fettered by the decisions of tripartite panels of another administrative agency.
<p>
Further, the Privatisation Board reasons that the inclusion of private sector workers within the scope of protection of public sector collective agreements will create instability in employment relations and that the legislative amendment to the Employment Act by the Conservative Government was clearly intended to avoid such instability. Hence, it establishes as a binding policy directive that private sector workers cannot be employees for the purposes of section 6 of the Employment Act. It also announces that non-compliance with this directive will be met by full use of its contempt powers.
<p>
The Hospital Services Union approaches you for advice. They are prepared to fight the decision of the Privatisation Board up to the Supreme Court of Canada if need be, but they are also concerned to preserve the decision of the Public Service Board.
<p><br>
<b>Question 2.<br>
Answer only one of the following; that is, answer either A or B or C. Recall that this question counts for one third of the total mark allocation so that you should allocate roughly one hour to it. Note: To do A, you must have answered Question 1 first.</b>
<p>
<b>A.</b> Reconsider your answer to Question 1 (the problem). Assume that you are drafting a report about administrative law reform. Give an account of how the central issues which you discussed arose and justify your recommendations as to reform. You may refer back extensively to your answer to question 1.
<p>
<b>B.</b> Discuss the principle of judicial deference to tribunal determinations of the law in the light of the Supreme Court of Canada's decisions in <cite>Dayco</cite> (Evans <U>et al.</U>, 857 and 951) and <cite>Bradco</cite> (Evans <U>et al.</U>, <cite>Administrative Law</cite>, 955).
<p>
<b>C.</b> Evaluate the thesis of the extract on page 7 of the exam from the <cite>Globe and Mail</cite> (January 29, 1996) in the light of your understanding of the place of judicial review in the Canadian legal order.
<p><br><hr width=50%>
GLOBE AND MAIL<BR>
JANUARY 29, 1996
<p>
In his Jan. 17 column (The Courts or the Public Square), Michael Valpy referred to a then-forthcoming public forum on Ontario's omnibus bill. The forum, held in Toronto on Jan. 24 and organized by an ad-hoc group of lawyers and legal academics (including the authors of this piece), was designed to inform political debate by focusing attention on the ways Bill 26 would undermine fundamental rights.
<p>
The bill would confer on the cabinet regulatory powers that could override enacted legislation. It would limit government liability to compensate those whose interests are adversely affected. It would erode basic principles that entitle those whose interests are affected to receive notice and be heard. It would expand government access.to private information while limiting public access to government information. The government thus proposes to implement its policies of cost efficiency through greater concentration of government power - a move that would, ironically, lead to more government, not less.
<p>
It is appropriate for lawyers and legal academics to focus attention on these issues, but Mr. Valpy seemed to question the bona fides of the forum because one of the organizers was constitutional litigator Mary Eberts (co-author of this piece). Referring to an argument by Ms. Eberts in Ontario Divisional Court against the. government's cuts to welfare benefits, Mr. Valpy asked, &quot;Are charter challenges in the courts an inappropriate alternative to political action?&quot; He questioned the very idea of, as he put it, &quot;the courtroom as an alternative to the political arena.&quot;
<p>
We wish to address his underlying assumption: that court proceedings and the political process are mutually exclusive and that right-thinking citizens must choose between them.
<p>
Bill 26 has galvanized many individuals and groups to political action. Nonetheless, it may be passed by Ontario's majority government without sufficient opportunity in the legislative process to address the implications of the bill's complex, wide-ranging provisions. While it is desirable that important issues of the day be hammered out in the political arena, the possibility of judicial review imposes discipline on governments where self-restraint is insufficient, and offers a way to restrain government power, safeguard liberties and preserve democratic values.
<p>
We need the legislative and judicial processes to interact with each other. That way, we ensure that majoritarian legislatures respect our democratic traditions and rights, while making sure that appointed judges hearing single cases do not substitute their judgments for those of the legislative process, with its capacity for comprehensive assessment of social needs and careful consensus-building.
<p>
There is no doubt that legislatures offer advantages as forums for deciding policies and priorities. Elections provide a mandate as Novell as accountability. Legislative hearings when they work effectively, let the government canvass a broad range of views in developing legislation. Effective debate in the assembly alerts the public to flaws in government policy and administration. Unless the government has a comfortable and disciplined majority, it is continuously accountable by reason of its need to maintain the confidence of the legislature.
<p>
Yet the courts play an important role in restraining the exercise of government power, on at least three grounds: when it exceeds the legislative jurisdiction assigned to it in our federal system; when it infringes rights guaranteed by the Charter of Rights; and when it breaches common-law principles that require government officials (a) to obey the law, (b) to observe principles of fairness and due process, and (c) to act within their authority. These restraints enhance the legitimacy of democratic government.
<p>
Strategic litigation may also help influence the political process. A minonty that cannot muster enough support to affect that process may be able to assert its interest in court as a legally protected right. Even if the case is unsuccessful, the public attention it draws may jumpstart the political process and lead to legislative change.
<p>
Democracy in Ontario today faces challenges from a party with a large majority, a continued high standing in the polls and sweeping ideas about what powers it needs to accomplish its mission. It is important that we consider, in public debate, the potential impacts of this agenda.
<p>
If public debate is ineffective, we may have resort to the courts - not to assess government policy, but to ensure that its implementation does not breach basic rights.
<p><hr width=50%><p>
<I>Marilyn Pilkington is dean of Osgoode Hall Law School, York University. Mary Eberts is a Toronto constitutional lawyer.</I>
<p><br>
