<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Advanced Contract Law<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Hadfield</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of two questions of equal weight. <B>Please read the following instructions carefully.</B>
<P>
<b>Question One</b> asks you to outline the issues; this part of the question is worth <b>50%</b> of the marks for Question One. You can identify issues as a question to be resolved and may use point-form and sub-issues. Define the issue as narrowly as possible (e.g. whether good faith term will be implied by court; whether Software Inc. will be at risk under &quot;springboard&quot; doctrine of losing flexibility to use ideas it develops on project with
Marketing Options for other projects/customers); at times you may want to note a relevant fact or case but do not get into detailed analysis and argument. You should not resolve the issue in the outline; however, if you identify an issue for the purpose of showing that it is a non-issue (i.e. clearly resolved one way or the other) note this clearly. (And if its really <b>not an issue,</b> leave it out.) Your goal in the outline is to demonstrate that you have recognized the issues. The second part of Question One asks you to analyse in detail one or two issues. Whether you
write on one or two issues will depend on the &quot;meatiness&quot; of the issues you choose and your treatment of them. I will be looking for your judgment about what is an important issue and the quality of your reasoning and legal argument. Only go on to a second issue if you think you can do so without compromising the quality of the analysis on the first issue. Above all, do not merely assert legal conclusions; I will be looking for solid argument.
<P>
<B>Question Two </B>asks you to identify the arguments you could make as the basis for a breach of contract action. This part of the question is worth <b>20%</b>. You need only identify the doctrinal basis for each argument (e.g. implied term to exercise due care in choosing between aereal and reserves pooling; breach of confidence in using information Corona revealed to acquire Williams' property. You are then asked to provide detailed analysis of what you consider to be the one or two most important issues or bases for the breach of contract action. Again, the emphasis here is on choosing an important issue or issues and developing carefully reasoned analysis. A creative,
persuasive treatment of a single issue will do well; so will solid treatments of two different issues. I suggest you move onto a second issue if you find your treatment of the first issue is in danger of getting into repetitive or unpersuasive arguments. I will also be taking into account the difficulty of the issue in light of the caselaw; a strong creative argument on a hard issue to win will also be rewarded.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</B>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<h3>Question 1 (50%)</h3>

Innovata Inc. is a well-known manufacturer of components used in the production of televisions, stereos and other electronic consumer products. For a number of years, Hi-Fi Inc. has been a customer of Innovata's, ordering components as needed from Innovata's wholesale catalogue using Innovata's standard form sales contract. Hi-Fi has frequently advertised the fact that it uses Innovata components and Innovata itself often advertises the quality, safety
and reliability of its components in magazines such as &quot;Popular Electronics&quot; which is read by consumers. (Faulty components reduce quality and reliability; can cause damage to the equipment in which they are installed, other equipment to which they are connected and software such as CDs; and may pose a fire hazard.
The more sophisticated the electronics, the lower the tolerance for deviations from design specifications.)
<P>
Recently, Hi-Fi has been experiencing financial difficulties in the face of strong global competition. They have approached Innovata and told them that they are interested in forming a supply alliance, modelled on the Japanese &quot;keiretsu&quot; but with some &quot;Western&quot; style changes. They referred Innovata to an article in the Wall Street Journal [<a href="#attached">attached</a>] which discusses the benefits of a supply alliance. Hi-Fi's goal is to increase its competitiveness by spurring innovation in components to improve the performance of Hi-Fi products, reducing the cost of coordinating Hi-Fi's activities and Innovata's activities, and reducing the total cost of Hi-Fi products. Hi-Fi has told Innovata that it wants to follow the lead of Chrysler, Motorola and Marks &amp; Spencer: focus negotiations on underlying costs while protecting Innovata's profit margin, adopt measures such as technical help, fair risk sharing and respect for proprietary information. Hi-Fi has told Innovata that they envisage a  cooperative give-and-take process by which Hi-Fi and Innovata exchange information to improve the final product while reducing costs: HiFi will keep Innovata up to date about its needs and prospects for developing new and/or modified products; Innovata will respond with ideas, information about its own plans and prospects for new components and provide test components. Hi-Fi anticipates that Innovata will work with HiFi to sort out and correct shortfalls, be they in performance (relative to the newest products coming on the market) or other criteria such as cost or safety. Hi-Fi has also mentioned that they are hoping that inventories of components would be held either by Innovata or by Hi-Fi depending at any given time on the relative costs of holding inventory for each and demand conditions (that is, Hi-Fi's abilities to sell what it has in stock.) At the same time Hi-Fi hopes to be able to reduce inventory costs by arranging for deliveries closer to critical production deadlines. Hi-Fi has said that if they can get a supply alliance up and running, they are planning some significant increases in capital investments in order to maximize the benefits of the arrangement.
<P>
Hi-Fi has said that they want to put nothing in writing and to rely on goodwill as the basis for the alliance.
<P>
Innovata is seeking advice on this proposed change in their relationship with Hi-Fi. Please outline the issues you think Innovata should be aware of in deciding how to proceed on Hi-Fi's proposal. Innovata is particularly interested in knowing whether there are contract provisions without which it might be too risky to proceed but are sympathetic with HiFi's interest in relying on trust rather than contract. Please also give me a detailed analysis of one or two issues that you consider to be important at this stage.
<P><br>
<h3>Question Two (50%)</h3>

BoldNet is a company that was formed by a group of computer afficionados in the 1980's when the Internet was almost exclusively used by academics and the military for transferring data and messages. BoldNet recognized early on the commercial potential of the net and began working on developing the software to configure access systems for commercial users that would facilitate electronic shopping. With so few consumers on line, these early phases were more in the line of a hobby than a business, but the reputation of this group for anticipating far-reaching changes in technology and applications spread rapidly among those in the know. Five years ago BoldNet decided it was time to go big and embarked on a franchising plan whereby they would sell to franchisees the right to use the BoldNet system to market consumer products. Franchisees operate as highly specialized electronic &quot;department stores&quot;. Individual franchisees are allocated a &quot;territory&quot; defined as a set of consumer criteria such as &quot;young professionals age 25-32, unmarried, who like new country music,  southwestern furnishings, J. Crew&quot; etc. The territories are in fact not defined by preexisting criteria, but rather developed on the basis  of interaction between consumers and the advertising and catalogues that consumers &quot;browse&quot; when they go to a franchisee's home page on the WorldWideWeb. (Consumers click on questions or products on the screen in order to learn more or purchase products; as they click, the system records their choices and can cross-reference these preferences with those who have made similar choices to develop a profile of a very narrow market niche.) BoldNet updates the territories monthly; the franchise contract sets out complicated guidelines that BoldNet follows in ensuring that a franchisee's territory grows or shrinks according to the demands of the consumers initially in the territory and not because of an outright transfer of consumers to another franchisee's territory that is not justified by underlying changes in taste and spending patterns. Franchisees
are responsible for maintaining the home page and updating it, all by following detailed instructions from BoldNet. They also perform the role of ensuring that orders for products are filled and deal with complaints or problems from customers or suppliers; all this information is also recorded on software from BoldNet and becomes part of the database on which BoldNet draws in selecting suppliers and products and defining territories. Franchisees must make significant investments in computer hardware and purchase BoldNet software on an ongoing basis; they also pay a $50,000 franchise fee upfront. Franchisees are invariably <b>not</b> computer experts and often have little expertise or experience in retailing, sales or the electronics industry.
<P>
Five years ago, when they began the franchise operation, BoldNet had already realized that future changes in technology and software would produce a rate of expansion in the electronic shopping market that would require frequent changes in the configuration of their system, necessitating frequent conversions in hardware, software
and procedures by franchisees. These were the same technological changes that BoldNet alone anticipated would open up the market for the highly targeted style of electronic shopping that was the cornerstone of its unique service in the market when it commenced operations. Nobody else had anticipated anything beyond electronic purchases from catalogues prepared by traditional retailers; nobody else had anticipated the nature of the rapidly and interactively developing consumer market on-line. Naturally enough, this was a highly-guarded secret at BoldNet.
<P>
John Simms is an ex-accountant who was looking for an investment in early 1991. He knew little about computers, and nothing about the Internet, but when a friend suggested he look into the franchise opportunity BoldNet was advertising, he quickly saw the potential for a lucrative venture. He eagerly read over the brochures BoldNet sent him explaining the franchise, wrote a cheque for $50,000, signed the standard form franchise agreement without legal advice and signed up for the month-long training session at BoldNet. Within two months he had invested another $400,000 in equipment and software and was up and running. Business was slow at first and he lost money the first year. BoldNet required some software changes in the configuration at the end of the first year, which cost him $35,000. By the second year he was earning reasonable profits even though twice during the second year he had to invest in further configuration changes for a total of $100,000. A similar pattern continued up until six months ago.
<P>
Six months ago Simms began to notice that configuration changes were coming from BoldNet somewhat more frequently than before but profits were not keeping up; indeed, gross sales were beginning to fall. For a little over a year he had been recording an increasing rate of consumer complaints and returns related to poor quality and had a number of puzzling episodes of transactions that were very difficult to trace and suppliers that were difficult to track
down for returns or product repairs. Last week Simms was stunned when he opened up the newspaper to see a full page announcement from BoldNet that, &quot;boldly going where no company had ever been before,&quot; the company was embarking on a new electronic shopping arrangement whereby all transactions would take place
centrally through BoldNet. The information at the website readers of the advertisement were directed to explained that BoldNet, again on the leading edge, had begun to recognize over a year ago that the net was becoming corrupted with copycat electronic retailers, fly-by-night manufacturers and Internet vandals who destroyed or altered advertising, product descriptions, consumer information or transaction data. BoldNet had developed a complete new system that leapt ahead of existing technology and would not be made available to franchisees for
security reasons.
<P>
Needless to say, Simms' franchise business is a big loser in all of this. He has asked you to file suit for him for breach of the franchise agreement. On discovery, you have learned that BoldNet deliberately introduced frequent configuration changes over the last year, which cost Simms a total of $200,000, but which were designed solely to ensure that potential competitors (including franchisees) did not figure out what BoldNet was planning and
so could not get a jump on BoldNet's major switch. BoldNet is now the leading electronic retailer but it depends on being the first in the market with system changes to secure customers by getting them attached to its system.
<P>
On reading the franchise agreement, you have learned that it says nothing about configuration changes and contains essentially no clauses that purport to limit BoldNet's discretion in any way beyond the provisions limiting the manner in which BoldNet adjusts territories. It does contain a clause which says &quot;The relationship between the parties is only that of independent arm's length contractors. No partnership, joint venture or relationship of principal and agent is intended,&quot; and a clause which prohibits Simms, if he ceases to be a franchisee for any reason, from engaging in electronic retailing or any computer-related business which competes with BoldNet.
<P>
Please identify what you consider to be the arguments you could make for breach of contract. Please also provide detailed analysis of what you consider to be the one or two most important issues you would argue on Simms behalf. (Be sure to deal with the weaknesses as well as the strengths of your argument.)
<P><br>
<hr>
<p>
<a name="attached">THE WALL STREET JOURNAL TUESDAY, DECEMBER 12, 1995</a>
<P>
<h1 align=center>Business World</h1>
<h2 align=center>By Jordan D. Lewis</h2>

Japanese keiretsu which link customer firms with their captive suppliers have long been regarded as a key to Japan's business success. But today a new kind of keiretsu is taking over - and this time it comes not from Japan but from the West. Considering that the average Western company spends more than 50 cents of every revenue dollar on suppliers (the figure is even higher in Japan) the value a firm gets from its suppliers is critical to its success.
<P>
In the past the Japanese tradition of customer-supplier cooperation for continuous improvement brought substantial advances In quality and reductions In cost. Meanwhile, Western firms traditional arm's length relationships with, and frequent hostility toward their suppliers frustrated any kind of teamwork.
<P>
But the traditional Japanese keiretsu also have big defects which are now being exposed by the new Western versions. In Japan captive suppliers march to the customer firm's sole drumbeat. Since the suppliers are guaranteed business and are insulated from direct interactions with the marketplace they are less inclined to innovate. That s not true for independent suppliers, whose survival depends on staying at the cutting edge of their fields. But in Japan's group-oriented culture the independents have a hard time forging close relationships with customer firms which inhibits the flow of innovations.
<P>
The West has found some stunning answers to these problems in a new style of customer-supplier relationship. Being pioneered by firms such as Chrysler, Motorola and British retailer Marks &amp; Spencer, these advances achieve high levels of supplier Innovation and substantial customer-suppler integration.  The result is superior performance. Since embracing supply alliances in 1990, Chrysler has become North America's lowest-cost, highest-profit per vehicle auto maker.
<P>
Motorola's Paging Products Group has won 60% global market share due partly to cooperation with suppliers that has brought significant advances in cost quality cycle time and technology. Supply costs have fallen 8% to 10% a year for many years. On the other hand Philips Consumer Electronics Co. - which buys the same kinds of items as Motorola but does not have alliances with its suppliers - has seen costs go down at only about half this rate.
<P>
Marks &amp; Spencer offers yet another case for the value of Western-grown keiretsu. Marks &amp; Spencer teams with its suppliers constantly pushing the frontiers of value in food clothing and home furnishings. Such close collaboration resulted in the easy-to-iron cotton shirt and machine-washable silk and lambswool knitwear among other developments. It also markedly reduced the cycle time between factory order and store receipt of piece-dyed knitwear from 12 to 16 weeks to a few days.
<P>
Central to the success of such advances is suppliers independence which helps encourage innovation. Customers support this by limiting their volume with each supplier to a small share of its business.
<P>
Another key is integration of customer and supplier activities which replaces arm's length bidding the traditional exchange of specification from the customer and price from the supplier. Integration lets both firms maximize their combined performance rather than each one's separate performance.
<P>
As an example consider cost. Only by identifying all cost sources for both customer and supplier - and understanding how they interact - can total cost be trimmed to the lowest levels. Take Chrysler. Teaming with a supplier, it developed a new part that, though costlier than the original part, reduced total vehicle cost by shortening assembly lime. The same logic applies to issues of quality and response time, where the goal is to improve together, rather than alone.
<P>
To earn suppliers' loyalty Chrysler, Motorola and Marks &amp; Spencer focus their negotiations on underlying costs while protecting suppliers' margins. Other measures such as technical help, fair risk sharing and respect for proprietary information are all aimed at winning and keeping suppliers' commitments.
<P>
In a practice that might seem more Asian than Western, most of these new customer-supplier relationships are based on trust, not contracts. Legal documents can't cover the many joint activities and high flexibility needed for substantial integration. Marks &amp; Spencer has no contracts with its suppliers; Chrysler and Motorola
use simple one-page agreements.
<P>
Motorola wants to be its suppliers' best customer and to that end uses supplier surveys and internal performance measures to keep moving in this direction. Marks &amp; Spencer monitors suppliers' financial health because the retailer needs them to remain strong, invest for the future and stay committed to its objectives.
<P>
Building these new relationships takes a real break with the past. To appreciate the consequences of the traditional ways,  consider recent events al General Motors.
<P>
In 1992 under a new purchasing chief GM demanded double-digit price cuts from suppliers and broke long-term
contracts to get them. In a quest for lower bids, GM also shared proprietary know-how among rival suppliers. Results were damaging: Suppliers withheld their newest developments from GM and shifted their brightest engineers to projects for other auto makers that treated their suppliers like partners. Further, a six-week shutdown
of Buick Roadmaster production at GM's Arlington, Texas plant was the result of the use of an ill-filling ashtray from a new supplier whose ashtray was cheaper but substandard. Perhaps the worst outcome was earlier this year when suppliers thwarted GM's plans to cut back its work force by refusing to take on tasks that GM performed in-house.
<P>
Since the start of Japan's economic decline earlier in this decade, some keiretsu suppliers there have broken their bonds of exclusivity and sought additional customers. But such initiatives are more an exception than a widespread practice. Further, Japanese customer firms have held their keiretsu suppliers to extremely thin margins. The newly free suppliers, which still get much of their business from their old masters, are a long way from being able to support significant R&amp;D.
<P>
There's little doubt that Japanese companies eventually will adopt supply methods that combine high degrees of innovation and integration. But the timing is hard to forecast. Obviously, they have adapted some Western practices in other areas, just as Western companies have adapted some of theirs. Nonetheless, the traditional keiretsu are no longer the model of best practice. For this, one has to look to the West.
<P>
<hr width=50%>
<I>Mr. Dennis is the author of &quot;The 'Connected Corporation: How Leading Companies Win Through Customer-Supplier Alliances,&quot; just out from The Free Press.</I>
<p><br>
