<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Advanced Family Law<br>
April 1996<br>
Philip M. Epstein and Susanne R. Goodman</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of two questions, which are of equal value. The suggested time allocation is indicated in the margin.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. if you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongs and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<B>Question One: </B>75 Minutes
<P>
Michelle and Robert began living together in June, 1989. For their family's sake, they went through a religious marriage on September 3rd, 1991, but without a marriage licence. Michelle thought it was a valid marriage because she knew nothing about a licence requirement. Robert knew there was a problem, but he wanted to make his parents happy without making a formal commitment to Michelle. When Michelle learned of the problem, she persuaded Robert to take her to City Hall on August 1st, 1994, and properly marry her.
<P>
The marriage broke down in February, 1996, when Robert left Michelle for his best friend, Roger. Michelle was absolutely devastated since she was pregnant at the time and never suspected that her husband was involved with someone else.
<P>
In October, 1986, Michelle inherited her late aunt's cottage on Stoney Lake. It was then worth $280,000, with a mortgage of $55,000. The parties used it regularly from the time they began living together until their separation. It has never changed in value, but the mortgage principal has declined at the rate of $1,000 per year since acquisition.
<P>
In 1988, Michelle was in a car accident and under the law then existing she had a pending claim for pain and suffering and lost income. The claim was settled on August 31st, 1991. Michelle received $35,000 for pain and suffering and $15,000 for lost income. She put the $50,000 settlement into the Toronto Dominion Bank and
immediately thereafter bought a one-year term deposit in the amount of $50,000. She continues on a yearly basis
to roll the term deposit over into a new term deposit. Each time, she simply reinvests the interest earned on the previous term deposit. In February, 1996, the term deposit then in place had a total value of $70,000.00, inclusive of interest.
<P>
Michelle had a student loan outstanding for many years. In September, 1991, the balance was $14,000 and by August 1, 1994, it was paid down to $7,000. In February, 1996, she still owed $1,000.00 on the loan. Michelle had a car that was worth $8,000 in September, 1991, and only $3,000 by July, 1994. She gave the car to her brother, Stanley. Shortly after, she and Robert married at City Hall.
<P>
In 1993, Robert won Lottario and used the winnings of $350,000 to purchase a home. He put it in Michelle's name to protect himself and Michelle if his business went sour. The house never changed in value until January, 1996, when the TTC put a bus route and parking lot nearby causing the house to drop in value by $60,000.
<P>
Robert is a mining speculator and his business fluctuates in value, depending on the stock market. In 1989, his business was worth $500,000. By September, 1991, it had fallen to $290,000 and by August, 1994, it was back to $350,000. In February, 1996, it was worth $450,000.
<p>
In 1992, Robert was sued for defamation in connection with some comments he made at a board meeting in December, 1991. His litigation lawyer has given Robert his opinion that Robert may well be liable and will likely have to pay about $50,000, inclusive of the claim, interest and costs.
<P>
Robert and Michelle each received a gift of $10,000 from Michelle's mother in October, 1991. Robert used his for an expensive vacation for both of them. Michelle used hers to buy a painting by Esmeraldi. The artist died in a fire six months ago and many of his paintings were destroyed. As a result, the painting is now worth $100,000. The painting has always been displayed in Robert's office and for that reason, Robert claims the painting is his. Michelle says the painting belongs to her. She acknowledges that it has been hanging in Robert's office. However, for the life of her, she can't remember why or how it came to be hanging in Robert's office.
<P>
Robert collects ancient coins. His father got him started on the hobby. In 1991, Robert's coins were worth $5,000.00. Robert's father died in 1992 and left Robert $58,000 worth of coins. Their value stayed the same until recently when one of the coins has become much sought after. The original coins left by Robert's father are now worth $90,000. Robert has also added to the collection on his own and in the last year, has acquired further coins worth $25,000. In total, the collection is now worth $175,000.
<P>
Michelle has come to see you. She has heard that there is some formula for dividing property in Ontario, but she doesn't understand it. She wants you to tell her what will happen in a court if they can't work out a solution on their own. Please do so, giving brief reasons for your opinion, including your calculation of the equalization payment owing.
<P><br>
<B>Question #2:</b> 45 Minutes
<P>
When Harry met Sally, they were both 24. Both were in teacher's college and both planned to teach high school upon graduation. After a whirlwind courtship, they were married in their last year of school in 1980. Unfortunately, the economy had already begun to change and Harry was unable to find full-time work as a teacher. Sally was more fortunate and was hired immediately, probably because she stood first in her class. Harry continued to work as a supply teacher, but he obtained less and less assignments and after a while, he had virtually no work being offered to him as a teacher. Sally and Harry wanted to have children, but they could not afford to have Sally give up her job, particularly because she was about to be appointed Vice-Principal. Accordingly, they decided that Sally would take two months maternity leave and, thereafter, Harry would stay home and look after the child. The hope was that the
economy would improve and Harry would get back to work full-time within three years. To their very great surprise, in 1987, Sally had twin boys and, unfortunately, one had serious respiratory problems which required constant care for the first four years (mostly by Harry). Further, Harry and Sally had a third son in 1990 and, accordingly, the plan for Harry to return to work could not be put in place. Firstly, the children needed one parent at
home, and secondly, the situation for teachers had become even worse. The parties thus decided that Harry would stay at home indefinitely.
<P>
Harry became increasingly unhappy with the arrangement. He deeply missed teaching and found the role of a full-time parent unfulfilling. While Harry was considering his options, he received devastating news. Sally has been having an affair with her accountant and has just announced to Harry that she wants to end the marriage. Sally proposes that they have joint custody of the children, that they agree that they will live within three miles of each other and that she will support Harry for one year while he either upgrades his qualifications, or finds a job teaching, or otherwise. Sally is now a high school principal, earning $82,000. The parties have a matrimonial home worth $250,000 which they jointly own. The car is registered in Robert's name. Sally's pension with the Board of Education has not as yet been valued, but is becoming substantial, given her years of experience.
<P>
Harry has come to see you for advice. He wants to know what to do about all this. He accepts that the marriage is over. He can accept Sally's suggestions for the children's custody arrangements, but he thinks Sally should support him indefinitely and that she should fully support the children. He asks you to explain the law in these two areas to him, with references to the case law and statutes you think applicable. Because he likes to think about these matters carefully, he would like your opinion in writing, but he can't afford a lot of your time so he asks that you spend
no more than 45 minutes drafting your opinion. Please do so. 
<p><br>
