<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Business Organizations 1<br>
April 1996<br>
Bruce Chapman and Ron Daniels</h2></center>
<h3>Instructions:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This is an <b>open book</b> examination. That means you may use any materials at all <b>except</b> materials borrowed from the library.
<P>
<li>There are <b>two</b> questions. <b>Question one</b> is worth <b>60%</b> of the final mark and <b>question two</b> is worth <b>40%</b>. Allocate your time accordingly.
<P>
<li><b> Please</b> write legibly, <b>double space</b> your written answer, and write on one side of the page only. <b>Begin each question in a new examination booklet</b>, indicating the question on the booklet cover.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the test, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the test.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the test has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol><hr><p>
<h3>QUESTION ONE (60 marks)</h3>

Health Foods Ltd. (&quot;HF&quot;) is a widely held company which is incorporated under the <cite>Ontario Business Corporations Act </cite>(OBCA) and which offers its class &quot;A&quot; voting shares for sale to residents of Ontario. Over the years, while selling its many natural food products to eager consumers, it has developed a reputation for its environmental sensitivity and for its involvement in aiding Third World development. In April 1993, however, it discovered, quite by accident, a very promising process for the development of a new chemical fertilizer which has since come to be called Gro-Fast. While Gro-Fast is very good for increasing crop yields in the Third World, its use there (or anywhere) is thought to be environmentally problematic. It was always clear that development of the new fertilizer would be very lucrative in the short run for HF, but the company directors and officers within HF became somewhat divided over whether it was good for HF in the long run to develop the new product and, possibly, to jeopardize HF's excellent environmental reputation.
<P>
All the furor began to attract the attention of Chem Life Inc. (&quot;CL&quot;), another widely held OBCA company. CL was interested in what Gro-Fast would do for its local suburban fertilizer business, and had no qualms at all about its possible environmental effects. Thus, the rumour began to develop that CL wanted to buy control of HF in order to acquire the rights to this lucrative new fertilizer.
<P>
In the face of these various developments, and the seeming inability of the directors and officers of HF to decide what to do, Green, who has been a 10% shareholder in HF since June 1993, requested the directors of HF to call a special shareholder meeting. She wanted the shareholders to consider her proposal that there be no development of Gro-Fast because to do so would &quot;seriously tarnish the fine reputation which HF has developed within the
international community of Third World environmentalists&quot; and &quot;set back, by at least a decade, the development of environmental consciousness where it is most needed, viz., in some of the globe's most precious and unspoiled eco-systems.&quot; Her proposal argued further that it would be wrong, and not in the best interest of
HF even to register and own the patent on Gro-Fast, let alone for the company to develop and market it, since to do so would discourage those ethically motivated investors, like herself, who had so long been specially attracted to  HF.
<P>
Initially, the directors of HF refused to circulate Green's proposal, but on hearing in January 1994 that CL had  accquired 15% of the class &quot;A&quot; voting shares in HF and had plans to acquire an even larger stake, these same directors decided to call a special  meeting of shareholders and to circulate Green's proposal with the management information circular. In addition, the HF directors proposed to shareholders that they ratify the adoption of a shareholder rights plan to help HF resist any possible takeover. The management information circular made no mention of the fact that CL had already acquired a 15% stake. This rights plan would allow HF  shareholders, should any one shareholder acquire 20% of its shares, to exchange any one of their class &quot;A&quot; voting shares for a new class &quot;B&quot; non-voting share plus a per share premium, while
still retaining the right to share in any takeover premium should a successful 50% takeover occur. This rights plan was not to be available to any 20% or over shareholder, and was to be (cheaply) redeemable by HF at the discretion of its board of directors.
<P>
At the shareholder meeting, both Green's proposal and the shareholder rights plan were approved by around 70% of the shares voted, half of which were voted by proxies held by the officers and directors. Two days after the shareholder meeting, when the market price of HF's class &quot;A&quot; shares was $20, CL launched its takeover
bid, seeking a 50% stake in the class &quot;A&quot; shares of HF at a price of $30 per share and promising to take up all remaining shares on demand in exchange for unsecured debt. However, almost no HF class &quot;A&quot; shareholders tendered into the bid.
<P>
Given the guidance they received at this shareholder meeting, the directors and officers of HF decided neither to register the patent on, nor to develop and market, the Gro-Fast fertilizer product. However, it has now come to light that a very similar product was subsequently patented and developed at Wealth Foods Inc. (&quot;WF&quot;), another OBCA company, which is a wholly owned subsidiary of All Foods Inc. (&quot;AF&quot;). AF, also
an OBCA company, has long held a 15% stake in HF and is wholly owned by Green, the 10% shareholder in HF. Moreover, Van Gorkum, one of the five directors on HF's board, is also on the ten member board of AF. Van Gorkum did disclose at the HF's director's meeting that to her knowledge WF was also developing a patentable product very like Gro-Fast, but she did not reveal that Green was the sole shareholder of AF. While Van Gorkum did vote on the Gro-Fast decision at the HF directors' meeting, her vote was not decisive for the result since the three other directors present (four of the five directors needed to be present to satisfy the board's quorum rule), being &quot;committed environmentalists&quot;, all voted that HF should not patent or develop Gro-Fast.
<P>
Nevertheless, Johnny Cash, who is one of the many small shareholders in HF and who, like them, invested in HF largely in ignorance of its reputation for being an environmentally friendly company, feels that there is something gone amiss. He is concerned that Gro-Fast looked to be a promising and profitable product for HF and that, somehow, an opportunity to participate either in those profits or in a lucrative takeover has been missed. He has come to you for advice as to what remedies might be available to him. Advise him.
<P><br>
<h3>QUESTION TWO (40 marks)</h3>

&quot;The study of corporations and corporate law is a good general introduction to an understanding of what can be problematic in,  and helpful for, the actual workings of a broad range of different institutions. Whether it be the collective action problems we observe in voting or market contracting, or the strategic difficulties which are involved in the litigation decision, or in the information requirements for an appropriate adjudicative response to the most complex forms of that litigation in cases, say, of fiduciary breach, the study of corporations and corporate law is replete  with systematic examples of both institutional pathology and of how institutions can be shaped to deal effectively with worst case scenarios.&quot;
<P>
Comment on the merits of the above claim, illustrating your points of agreement and/or disagreement with specific examples taken from the course. If you think that the study of corporations and corporate law provides an unbalanced or distorted account of how public institutions should properly frame problems and their solution, you should specify why you think that this is so and what special dimensions are missing from corporate analysis. On the other hand, if you think that the study of corporations and corporate law provides good general guidance for lessons on appropriate institutional design beyond the for-profit corporation, you should speculate a little on what some of those more general applications of the corporate analysis might look like.
<p><br>
<hr>
