<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Business Organizations II<br>
Take-Home Examination<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor MacIntosh</h2></center>
<h3>Instructions:</h3>
<ol>
<li>The exam must be returned within 24 hours of being picked up (unless you have made a special arrangement with Professor MacIntosh).
<P>
<li>You may not use any materials except class materials (i.e. casebooks, notes, etc.) or materials used in connection with the course (e.g. photocopies that you may have made during the course). In other words. this is a takehome exam, and <b>not</b> a research exam.
<P>
<li>In accordance with the Faculty Council resolution of Oct. 6, 1993, you may consult with other students in the course of working out your answer. However, please note that this resolution provides that &quot;the answer or answers returned by the students must be organized and written by that student alone&quot;.
<P>
<li>There are two questions. The marks are allocated as follows:
<blockquote>
Ql: 30%<br>
Q2: 70%
</blockquote>
<li>The word limit for the whole exam is 3500 words. You may allocate your 3500 words in any way you see fit as between the two questions.
<P>
<li>Please make a word estimate for the entire exam and put this estimate on the front page of your exam answer. Anything written in excess of the word limit <b>will not be read!</b> Be forewarned that this penalty will be enforced with absolute strictness, in fairness to those students who make a conscientious effort to observe the word limit. In the past, I have downgraded at least one &quot;A&quot; paper to a &quot;C&quot; for significantly exceeding the word limit, and have downgraded many more a half or a whole grade.
<P>
Please note that all word estimates are carefully checked. Given some complaints about uneven enforcement of the rule in the past, I have decided (commencing this year) to hire a graduate student to carefully check all work estimates. No prisoners will be taken.
<P>
<li>I would prefer that you type your examination answer. However, this is not required. If you write your answer, <b>please</b> make sure that it is legible, and written on <b>every other line.</b> If you choose, you may submit a handwritten copy of your answer and submit a typed copy within one week (or longer if you have made a special arrangement with me).
<P>
If you submit a handwritten copy and intend to replace this with a typewritten copy, <b>please clearly indicate this on the top of the handwritten copy</b>.
<P>
<li>I place a high premium on <b>organization and clarity</b>. Answers which have been well thought out in advance uniformly score higher.
<P>
<li>Feel free to incorporate by reference anything that you say in response to one question for the purposes of answering another question.
<P>
<li>Note that &quot;OSA&quot; means the Ontario <cite>Securities Act</cite>. &quot;OSC&quot; means the Ontario Securities Commission.
</ol>
<hr><p>
1. Attached (as <a href="#appendix-a">Appendix A</a>) is a copy of an advertisement that recently appeared in the <cite>Financial Post</cite>. You are on staff at the Ontario Securities Commission and have been asked to write
a memorandum indicating whether this ad complies with Ontario securities law, and if not, in what respects. Please write the memo.
<P><br>
2. Munitions Corp. is a corporation incorporated under the OBCA engaged in the business of manufacturing rifle ammunition. There are 20 shareholders, 8 of whom reside in Ontario. The other 12 reside in 6 different provinces. The Articles of Incorporation allow the directors to refuse to register a transfer of shares belonging to a shareholder indebted to the company. The Articles also forbid any offering of the corporation's securities for sale to the public.
<P>
The directors of Munitions decided that the company needed more money to carry on its activities. The President of Munitions, Ms. Fire, informed the board that she had secured commitments from the following sources:
<P>
i/ her significant other, Jean-Luc. Jean-Luc is an accountant who lives in Quebec City but spends his weekends with Fire at her fashionable home in Toronto. Jean-Luc has agreed to buy $100,000 worth of shares.
<P>
ii/ Smoots, a business partner of a former business partner of Fire, and also Fire's favourite golfing partner (fire plays golf as often as business will allow, usually once a week). Smoots is a person of substantial means. Because Fire likes to blab about business on the golf course, Smoots is generally familiar with the ammunition business. Smoots has also agreed to buy $100,000 worth of shares.
<P>
iii/ a venture capitalist (a firm whose business it is to take equity stakes in relatively small or start-up companies) called Novel Ventures Inc. Novel Ventures funded Smoots's business, and was recommended to Fire by Smoots. Novel Ventures has indicated that they would only be interested in investing under two conditions: first, that they be issued just enough shares so that, after all other contemplated share issuances are made, they will hold exactly 19.99% of the equity of the company (this would involve an investment of a few million dollars); second, that a unanimous shareholder agreement be signed under which they would get the right to replace the managers as they see fit.
<P>
iv/ through a friend, she had secured an introduction to Ronda Wait, an extremely successful business person and one of the wealthiest individuals in Canada. Fire told the board that she had met with Wait and that Wait had indicated a willingness to purchase a secured debenture in Munitions with a face value of $125,000.
<P>
v/ the Royal Bank is willing to lend Munitions $3,000,000, repayable in installments of principal and interest over 5 years.
<P>
vi/ after placing an advertisement in the Journal of Munitions Engineers of Canada, seeking equity investments from engineers, Fire received about 45 responses. After holding a promotional meeting attended by 25 of these engineers, 10 indicated a willingness to purchase shares in the amount of $100,000 (per engineer). For purposes of making the investment, the 10 engineers plan to form an investment corporation that will issue 1 share to ach of the engineers, and then purchase and hold all of the $1,000,000 worth of shares in Munitions.
<P>
<h3>Part 1</h3>

The board of directors would like to proceed to raise capital from all of the above sources. They will only do so, however, if they do not have to prepare a prospectus. They have hired you to figure out if (and how) this is possible. Please advise.
<P>
<h3>Part 2</h3>

What resale restrictions (if any) attach to the securities purchased in Part 1?
<P>
<h3>Part 3</h3>

A year has now passed since the transactions in Part 1. The board of directors of Munitions decided to amend the Articles of Incorporation, to eliminate the provision that allows the directors to refuse to register a transfer of shares belonging to a shareholder indebted to the company.
<P>
i/ Does this trigger any immediate regulatory requirements?
<P>
ii/ Will this action affect the resale restrictions (if any) attaching to the shares purchased in Part 1?
<P>
iii/ Suppose that the company had deleted the above restriction in its Articles prior to raising capital in Part 1. Indicate in a general way how this would affect your answer to Part 1.
<p>
<h3>Part 4</h3>

Since the above events, Munitions has issued shares under a prospectus (with the shares being offered in Ontario, Quebec, and Alberta) and has been listed on the Montreal Exchange (both of these occurrences took place 6 months ago). The directors of Munitions are concerned that Munitions might be open to a &quot;hostile&quot; takeover
(one consummated without their consent). They have therefore proposed adoption of a &quot;Shareholder Rights Plan&quot; under which &quot;rights&quot; to purchase further shares in Munitions will be issued as a dividend to the common shareholders of Munitions. Each right will enable the holder to purchase a common share in the company at half the market price of the share at the date of exercise. However, the rights will be inactive unless and until any shareholder acquires 20% or more of the common shares of the company. Once that threshold is reached, the rights will become active and can be exercised. Further, until the triggering event occurs, the rights will not be separately tradeable from the associated common shares. When the 20% threshold is crossed, the rights will &quot;separate&quot; from the common shares and will be separately traded.
<P>
You have been retained by Munitions to advise whether or not a prospectus will be required for the issuance of the rights. The Munitions board would also like to know whether, if the rights are exercised for common shares, it will be necessary to prepare a prospectus to issue the common shares. What resale restrictions (if any) will attach to the rights after a triggering event, and  to the common shares obtained by exercise of the rights? Supposing that the rights are issued under a prospectus, will this affect the resale restrictions attaching to the common shares received
in exchange? Just for the sake of argument, suppose that the rights were initially issued under s.71(1)(a) of the Act. Would this make a difference to the resale restrictions attaching to the common shares?
<P><br>
<hr width=80% noshade>
<center><h2><a name="appendix-a">Appendix A</a></h2>
<h3><font size=+3>Why On Earth</font><br> DO I WANT TO OWN AN<br> <font size=+3>Ostrich?</font></h3></center>

<font size=+3>S</font>ince 1986 our farming services have grown, as indeed the income of our private and corporate owners has. In fact the Ostrich Farming Corporation is now probably the world's largest and has over 2000 individual owners.
<P>
In 1995 the average financial return to owners whose ostriches' offspring were of age to sen was <font size=+3>57%*</font>.
<P>
The wondertul benefit of this 'alternate opportunity' is the control you exercise over your purchase, which you wholly own at all times. The Corporation simply provides all livery, veterinary, insurance and breeding services** within the price which range from <b>$3,100 CND to $36,750 CND</b>.
<P>
The Guaranteed Buy Back Option provides openers with a minimum cumulative return of <font size=+2>190.77%***</font> in the first five years of ownership.
<P>
Personal Herd Management<sup>TM</sup> planning over the bird's 25 year commercial breeding life will become your greatest
source of <I>natural interest!</I>
<P>
<b>Telephone today for the complete guide and free video, Mon - Fri 9:00 a.m. - 5:00p.m.</b>
<P>
<center><font size=+2><b>TOLL FREE</b> (Canada &amp; USA):
<br><b>1-888-0strich or</b><br>
1-888-467-8742<br>
FAX: 1-888-467-8740</font>
<p><br>
