<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Civil Appeals and Judicial Review<br>
April 1996<br>
John Campion and Paul Monahan</h2></center>
<h3>Introduction:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This is a take home examination. You may sign it out for a 24 hour period during the week of April 8, 1996. You must return it 24 hours later. It must be returned no later than 5:00 p.m. on April 12, 1996.
<P>
<li>You are to work on this examination without consulting others. You should require nothing else other than your course materials. No independent research is required.
<P>
<li>We estimate that you should spend 5 hours on the examination during the 24 hour period.
<P>
<li>Answers may be typed or hand-written.
<P>
<li>You are required to answer all questions.
<P>
 <li>Where required, assume any necessary facts.
</ol><hr><P>
<center><h3>PART I - FACTUM ASSIGNMENT</h3>

(Time allotment - 4 hours of 5 hour exam)</center>
<P>
<h3>BACKGROUND</h3>

On February 10, 1993 Walter Smith and his close friend Jack Jones had spent the day ice fishing and snowmobiling on Lake John in the County of Oz in the province of Ontario. Snow had been falling most of the afternoon. As it began to get dark in late afternoon Walter and Jack decided to head home. Walter was driving his own snowmobile and Jack was a passenger.
<P>
They headed west across Lake John and over a number of fields until they reached Highway 4 which runs  North/South. They headed north along the shoulder at the side of Highway 4. Driving a snowmobile on the side of a highway is legal in the County of Oz. Both the side of the road and the road itself were covered in snow.
<P>
As Walter and Jack travelled along on Highway 4 the snow continued and darkness fell. Walter and Jack hit the side of an NC train which was crossing Highway 4 in an easterly direction.
<P>
Both Jack and Walter survived but suffered numerous injuries. Walter broke both of his legs and cracked his skull. A blood test done on Walter at the hospital indicated that he had alcohol in his blood just below the legal limit. Jack suffered numerous broken bones and endured partial amnesia as well as depression.
<P>
The railway crossing in question had a flashing light mechanism to warn oncoming cars, vehicles, snowmobilers and pedestrians of the train crossing the roadway. It did not have a descending bar to prevent anyone from crossing the track. The train and the flashing light mechanism are owned and operated by the NC Railway Company.
<P>
Walter and Jack sued the NC Railway Company alleging negligence on the basis of the allegation that the flashing light mechanism was not working. Both Walter and Jack claimed damages for lost income and pain and suffering. The NC Railway defended alleging that the flashing light mechanism was working properly and that Jack and Walter had no one to blame but themselves since they had failed to see the flashing light. They also alleged that Jack was drunk.
<P>
<h3>Evidence at Trial</h3>
<P>
The significant evidence at trial was as follows:
<P>
1. Walter Smith
<P>
Walter Smith testified that as he drove north on the side of Highway 4, visibility was poor, but that he could see approximately 50 feet in front of him. He said he was driving his snowmobile at approximately 50 kilometers per hour (the speed limit was 60 kilometers per hour). He testified that he had had a couple of beers with lunch out on the lake. He stated that as he approached the railway crossing the railway flashing light mechanism was not flashing
and that he didn't know what he had hit when he hit the side of the train.
<P>
2. Jack Jones
<P>
Jack testified that he and Walter had enjoyed a great day snowmobiling and that lunch had included approximately 5 beers apiece. He indicated that he couldn't see a thing as they drove back on Highway 4 because the snow was so bad. Beyond that he had no memory of the accident and couldn't say whether the railway light mechanism had been flashing or not.
<P>
3. Frank McLaughlin
<P>
Frank testified that on February 10, 1993 he made his way home from work travelling in a northerly direction on Highway 4. He testified he was driving approximately 30 kilometers per hour as he approached the railway crossing which he knew well. He had driven that route on a daily basis for 5 years and he said that his practice was to look for the train itself rather than to look for the flashing lights. He testified that although visibility was poor, he saw the train crossing the road and that he stopped his car for that reason. He testified as well that although it was the sight of the train that made him stop, he was sure that the lights were flashing as well.
<P>
He had been sitting in his car facing north waiting for the train to pass when Walter and Jack had passed him on the side of the road to his right and hit the train. McLaughlin used his car phone to call for help and the police and ambulance soon arrived to take both Walter and Jack to c nearby hospital.
<P>
He also admitted that some ten years earlier he had been convicted of fraud in connection with stolen funds from his employer. He had gone to jail for five years but had been &quot;crime free&quot; ever since.
<P>
4. Police Constable Mary McKinnon
<P>
Officer McKinnon testified that she arrived on the scene some ten minutes after the collision. She testified that she was an expert in accident reconstruction and that on examining the scene she noticed that the snowmobile tracks heading in a northerly direction caused by Walter's snowmobile veered sharply to the right just south of the flashing light mechanism. It was her opinion that this was consistent with the driver of the snowmobile having seen the flashing light and having tried to veer to the right to avoid the train.
<P>
5. Katherine Johnson
<P>
She testified that she was an engineer who specialized in train derailments and accidents and who had been retained by the NC train company as an expert witness in this case. She testified that she had examined the flashing light mechanism from the scene of the accident. She testified that when she tested it, it operated correctly 99 times out of 100 but that one time out of 100 it failed to operate correctly.
<P>
6. Other Evidence At Trial
<P>
It was accepted by all parties that separate and apart from the issue of who was liable for the damages, the lost wages for Walter Smith were $200,000 and that his general damages for pain and suffering were $100,000. The lost wages for Jack Jones were $150,000 and his general damages were $125,000.
<P>
<h3>Reasons For Judgment of the Honourable Sandra James</h3>

(The case was tried by a judge without a jury)
<P>
An accident occurred on February 10, 1993 when Walter Smith who was driving his snowmobile, with his passenger Jack Jones accompanying him, collided with an eastbound NC train at an intersection with Highway 4. Mr. Smith and Jones allege negligence against the NC train company. The case comes down to whether or not the flashing light mechanism was working. There seems to be evidence on both sides of the issue. On the one hand Walter Smith testifies that the mechanism was not flashing. On the other hand Frank McLaughlin testified that he was certain that he saw the flashing light and that he himself had stopped his own car. I accept, without hesitation,
the evidence of Walter Smith that the light was not flashing. I saw his demeanor in the witness box and I found him to be an honest and straightforward witness. I see no reason why he would say the light was not flashing if it was. Presumably if the light had been flashing he would have stopped.
<P>
I reject the testimony of Frank McLaughlin for two reasons. First, the man is a convicted fraud artist and really can't be believed. Second, I don't see how he could see anything if it was snowing as hard as everyone says it was.
<P>
With respect to the evidence of Constable Mary McKinnon, she was not an eyewitness but rather was someone who came on the scene afterwards. I thought her testimony regarding the tracks in the snow was interesting but of doubtful assistance.
<P>
The testimony of Katherine Johnston seems to help Smith and Jones rather than hurt them. She testified that the mechanism was faulty and that although it worked properly 99% of the time, 1% of the time it did not work properly. It must have been the case in my view that the accident on February 10,1993 was one of the those
&quot;1%&quot; occasions.
<P>
There was an issue raised about contributory negligence. NC Railway argued that even if the mechanism was not working, Smith and Jones had been drinking an excessive amount that day and that it likely impaired their judgment and in particular the judgment of Walter Smith, the driver of the snowmobile. I tend to agree with this argument and I find that Walter Smith was 30% liable for the accident with NC Railway Company 70% liable. In the end, I award the full amount of the damages claimed by Walter Smith and Jack Jones. Mr. Smith shall receive $300,000 plus costs and Mr. Jones shall receive $275,000 plus costs.
<P>
<h3>Work Assignment</h3>
<P>
You are retained by the NC Railway Company to appeal this judgment on its behalf. It is necessary for you to draft a factum which will contain the following sections:
<blockquote>
 i) facts;
<P>
ii) issues;
<P>
iii) law;
<P>
iv) order requested.
</blockquote>
You do not need to do independent research outside of the course materials.
<P><br>
<center><h3>PART II - SHORT ANSWER ASSIGNMENT</h3>
<P>
(45 minutes to one hour)</center>
<P>
<h3>BACKGROUND</h3>
<P>
You are approached by Norm Numberhead who is a professional bookkeeper. He is charged by the Bookkeepers Society of Ontario under <cite>The Bookkeepers Society Act </cite>with professional misconduct. (You can assume that this society exists and that there is indeed such a statute. All you know about that society and all you know about that statute is provided for in this question). It is alleged that Norm Numberhead is guilty of professional misconduct by reason of alleged negligence in connection with bookkeeping which he did for various clients from 1985 to 1987. Negligent bookkeeping is grounds for a finding of professional misconduct under <cite>The Bookkeepers Society Act. </cite>The notice charging Norm Numberhead with the offenses is dated November 1, 1995 and calls for a hearing to take place on April 30, 1996. Norm can't even remember the clients he is alleged to have failed to serve during 1985 to 1987.
<P>
Norm will be judged by a panel of his peers. The Chair of the panel is a fellow bookkeeper with whom Norm used to work with and who once called Norm a &quot;thief&quot;. <cite>The Bookkeepers Society Act </cite>provides for a full hearing for charges of professional misconduct including rights to cross-examination, right to counsel
and the right to be advised of the full details of the charges against him. Norm Numberhead is assured by the Bookkeepers Society that he will have all of these rights in compliance with all of the provisions. There is also a full appeal provided for in <cite>The Bookkeepers Society Act </cite>which allows for an appeal to the Divisional Court after the hearing.
<P>
<h3>Work Assignment</h3>

Norm Numberhead comes to you and asks you a number of questions. You are obliged to give him an answer which is no longer than 2 to 3 pages (double spaced).
<blockquote>
Norm doesn't want to go to a hearing and wants to stop it ahead of time. If you tried to stop the hearing ahead of time what type of remedy would you ask for, on what grounds, and what type of proceeding would you commence? What type of considerations would be involved in determining whether or not you would be successful in the proceeding?
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<hr>
