<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Civil Procedure A and B<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Roach</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of three questions.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
<P>
<li><B>Unless otherwise stated assume that the relevant rules and statutes are those of the Province of Ontario.</b>
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
1. Fifteen months ago, Clifford received a flu shot vaccine at the Flavelle General. The vaccine was made by NoCold Inc., a maker of vaccines which is in financial trouble. It still sells vaccines, but it no longer answers the telephone or the door at its place of business.
<P>
Clifford has suffered chronic fatigue symptoms for the past ten months. Until recently he went to a holistic medical specialist without formal training who told him the symptoms were related to his lifestyle. Last month, he saw a medical doctor who told him he may be part of a small group of people who are allergic to the flu shot and as a result develop chronic fatigue symptoms. The doctor mentioned, however, that in most cases the symptoms appear within weeks of the final shot.
<P>
Under Ontario law, hospitals now can only administer flu shots approved by regulation and those manufactured by NoCold Inc. had been so approved. Both NoCold and Flavelle General will rely upon this approval. Clifford has heard rumours that when the government passed regulations approving the NoCold shot, it ignored some evidence that the shot would produce fatigue symptoms in some people. The government refuses to comment on these rumours and refuses to discuss the matter with Clifford or reporters.
<P>
The government's regulation approving the NoCold shot was issued under the <cite>Vaccine Approval Law</cite> which requires that the government consider the health risks to all Ontarians before approving vaccines. The <cite>Vaccine Approval Law</cite> also requires that no civil action with respect to the administration of a vaccine shall be brought one year after the cause of action accrues.
<P>
Clifford is not the only person who has experienced problems with the vaccine. Frank brought civil proceedings against NoCold three years ago, but was unsuccessful. Two years ago, Jane brought civil proceedings against NoCold and the judge found, after a lengthy and expensive trial, that NoCold was negligent because it ought to have known the risks that the vaccine could cause these symptoms in some people. At the time of the negligence, the <cite>Vaccine Approval Law</cite> had not been passed. It appears that no one else is willing to take action. Clifford knows this because he is member of a province wide group of 200 people who have similar symptoms
after receiving flu shots.
<P>
Clifford believes that the vaccine is a pressing public problem and wants to take the most expeditious, effective and least expensive proceedings to stop the administration of these flu shots. He is especially concerned about the cost of litigation.
<P>
Write a memorandum outlining the litigation options for Clifford's case including any procedural obstacles and/or shortcuts that he may face. Indicate which procedural options will best serve his objectives.
<P><br>
2. You are a junior lawyer in the legal department of Toys Inc., a large toy company headquartered in Toronto. Your boss has given you a statement of claim in which Sam, a 16 year old boy, is alleging that Toys Inc. negligently built the Tankmaster, your company's most successful product. Sam received a serious eye injury when he was 9 years old when a moving part came off the Tankmaster. He claims $1 million in damages. Sue is Sam's mother. She has also joined in the action to claim $200,000 under Ontario's <cite>Family Law Act</cite> for the loss of Sam's companionship.
<P>
Sam and Sue have recently served the statement of claim in Ontario, but they have just moved to Manitoba. They are not well off and their lawyer is in the first year of his practice, coincidentally after having articled for a Toronto firm that Toys Inc. has on retainer. Before they commenced the litigation, Sam and Sue held a news conference denouncing Toys Inc. as a corporate giant hungry for profits that wilfully places the safety of little children in jeopardy.
<P>
Toys Inc. has received several complaints about this moving part on the Tankmaster. A number of these complaints threatened to bring action against Toys Inc. while others threatened to report the company to various governmental departments in charge of product safety. Last year, you were put in charge of an internal investigation of the safety of the Tankmaster and you have a file with all the complaints, as well as memorandum addressed to you from the company's head toymaker and a consultant not employed by Toys Inc. who both say that the moving part is liable to detach. You also have an estimate from another outside consultant that the entire Tankmaster would have to be re-engineered at a substantial cost if the moving part was eliminated.
<P>
Write a memorandum outlining issues that will arise in the preparation of the statement of defence and affidavit of documents. You should also consider what, if any, pre-trial motions should be brought, whether defamation actions against Sam and Sue can be joined to the action, the strategy and effects of settlement offers and any ethical considerations which may arise in the defence.
<P><br>
Answer <b>one</b> of the following <b>two</b> questions
<P>
3a) Procedural fairness requires that plaintiffs and defendants and all classes of litigants be treated the same. It is not possible or desirable to tailor procedural rules on the basis of the effects that they might have on different litigants.
<P>
With reference to specific examples, assess the accuracy and the wisdom of the above statement.
<P>
3b) The adversarial system of civil litigation following prolonged discovery and culminating in a full oral trial is a luxury that litigants can no longer afford.
<P>
With reference to specific examples, assess the accuracy and wisdom of the above statement.
<p><br>
