<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Civil Procedure<br>
April 1996<br>
Allan C. Hutchinson</h2></center>
<h3>Instructions:</h3>
<ol>
<li>Students are to answer THREE questions: all questions carry equal marks.
<P>
<li>There is to be no <b>substantial</b> overlap between the answers.
<P>
<li>This is an open book examination.
<P>
<li>Be legible and organised.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<h3>QUESTION ONE</h3>

1. You are invited to take part in a symposium on &quot;The Rise and Rise of A.D.R.&quot;, organised jointly by the law school and the law society. You are specifically asked to contribute a short paper on the implications and changes that might be required to traditional understandings of legal ethics when lawyers become more actively involved in A.D.R. The invitation also recommends that you situate your remarks in a practical context and use concrete examples to illustrate your argument.
<P>
<center><h3>What would you write?</h3></center>
<p><br>
<h3>QUESTION TWO</h3>

2. You have been appointed to the Supreme Court of Utoro, the highest court in Canada. Several cases are slated for appeal. <b>Select <i>two</i> of the following cases and write the judgment that you would give:</b>
<blockquote>
(A) <cite>Phillips</cite> (Casebook p.220);
<P>
(B) <cite>Memphis Rogues</cite> (Casebook p.781);
<P>
(C ) <cite>Palmer</cite> (Casebook p.619); and
<P>
(D) <cite>Brett</cite> (Casebook p.608).
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<h3>QUESTION THREE</h3>

3. A Canadian Airlines plane has crashed in Northern Ontario near the town of Cochrane. A substantial part of the population is evacuated for a few days in order to facilitate rescue attempts and to guard against further explosions. Many lawsuits are commenced for different claims (negligence, nuisance, contract, etc), in different courts (Small Claims, General Division, etc.), for different amounts (from $1000 for lost profits to $5m for loss of life), and against different defendants (Canadian Airlines, the plane manufacturers, the Town, etc.).
<P>
Harry brings an action for $10,000 for damage to his house against Canadian Airlines, the plane manufacturers, and the Town. At trial, he is successful against Canadian Airlines who entered only a cursory defence to his claim; the action against the other defendants is dismissed. A few days later, a public inquiry by the Canadian Aviation Authority, mandated by the relevant legislation, determines that the accident was not the fault of the pilot or the airline.
<P>
Madeleine's action for $5m for the death of her husband against Canadian Airlines, the plane manufacturers, and the Town comes to trial. She pleads issue estoppel as to the liability of Canadian Airlines. Also, the plane manufacturers and the Town want to rely on issue estoppel against Madeleine.
<P>
The case comes before you as a judge.
<P>
<center><h3>What would you decide?</h3></center>
<P><br>
<h3>QUESTION FOUR</h3>

4. A few days after the crash of the Canadian Airlines plane (see question 3), you are approached by several groups of people -- townspeople, survivors, families of victims, etc. They want to know whether they should bring a class action. As well as the prospects of bringing such an action, they are particularly interested in the advantages and disadvantages that this would have over a more traditional set of multiple claims.
<P>
<center><h3>What would you advise them?</h3></center>
<P><br>
<H3>QUESTION FIVE</h3>

5. In the last year, Jaswan, a farmer, has become very ill. He attributes this to using a crop herbicide, manufactured by and distributed by Kill Products. He has used the herbicide for the last 10 years. In his recent statement of claim, after outlining the nature of his injuries, Jaswan simply claims that &quot;the plaintiff says that his illness was caused by the gross negligence of the defendant in the manufacture, sale and marketing of the pesticide.&quot; As a judge, you are confronted by the following motions:
<P>
(A) the defendants did not plead, but moved for particulars of the negligence. The plaintiff argues that he has no reliable information to particularize his assertion that is not already in the possession of the defendant.
<P>
(B) [assume that an order for particulars was not made and the action proceeded to discovery] the plaintiff asked the defendant, who refused, to produce various pieces of information. These included the existence of other claims relating to the herbicide; how such claims were resolved; a report prepared in 1992 by independent experts on the toxicity of the pesticide; and the sales volume of the herbicide.
<P>
(C) At the trial and after two days of its submissions, the defendant raised for the first time the argument that Jaswan was a known smoker and drug-user and that his illness is consistent with such usage.
<P>
<center><h3>How would you dispose of these matters?</h3></center>
<P><br>
<h3>QUESTION SIX</h3>

6. You are approached by a latter-day Mrs. Donoghue (of <cite>Donoghue v. Stevenson</cite> fame). You estimate that she has a claim for about $20,000 in damages and that she has about a 50/50 chance of succeeding against one of either the cafe-owner, the retailer or the manufacturer of the ginger beer. She has received a joint letter from them stating that they will settle for a combined total of $5000. She asks your advise about a number of matters:
<blockquote>
(A) whether such a settlement should be accepted;
<P>
(B) what are the economic implications of pursuing litigation to trial;
<P>
(C) whether she should make any counter-offer and how to do that;
<P>
(D) what financial arrangements can be made between you and her (who has no savings) about financing the litigation;
<P>
(E) whether she might be eligible for any state-support; and
<P>
(F) why it is so difficult to bring such actions.
</blockquote>
<center><h3>What would you advise?</h3></center>
<P><br>
<h3>QUESTION SEVEN</h3>

7. <b>Devise, state and answer your own question.</b>
<p><br>
