<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Conflict of Laws<br>
April 1996<br>
Take-Home Examination</h2></center>
<h3>Instructions:</h3>
<blockquote>
The Faculty of Law take-home exam policy states, in part: &quot;It is expected that there will be consultation
amongst students writing the same take home examination, although the answer or answers returned by the student must be organized and written by that student alone&quot;.
<P>
Students should pay particular attention to the need for a take home answer to be their own work. It must be &quot;organized and written by that student alone&quot;. Contravening this rule is an academic offence under the University's Code of Academic Conduct. You may refer to any materials you wish.
<P>
The examination answer is to be submitted within 48 hours of the time of pick-up. It may be returned to the Records office or faxed to the instructor at (416) 978-7899 or e-mailed to the instructor at rhowse@law.utoronto.ca. <B>In all cases, students should retain a hard copy of their examination answer. </B>The answer should not exceed 14 double-spaced, typed pages.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<P>
<B>Please answer all parts of the following question.</B>
<P>
Nordland is a federal country the laws of which, except as otherwise specified, are identical in all respects to those of Canada. Yesterday by less than a 1% majority, the people of Laurentia, a province in Nordland, voted to separate from Nordland and form a separate state. Immediately following the vote the leader of the Laurentian separatists, Gaston Foulard, announced that any move towards separation would be delayed by one year to give &quot;the rest of Nordland&quot; one last chance to negotiate an agreement that would address Laurentia's grievances and thereby avoid the necessity of separation.
<P>
You are an articling student in the legal department of the Prime Minister's Office. The Prime Minister requires a briefing on the legal implications of certain aspects of the referendum result and related actions or proposed actions of various governments. You have been asked by the Prime Minister's Principal Secretary to draft the portion of the briefing that deals with Conflict of Laws.
<ol>
<li>Because the vote was so close, the Prime Minister is considering the extent to which is should be accepted as the clear democratic will of the people of Laurentia. One matter that troubles the Prime Minister is that the right to vote in the referendum was determined not on the basis of residency but of &quot;domicile&quot;. Foulard had commented when asked by federal officials to explain this concept, &quot;you should know what it means, it comes from your British common law.&quot; The Prime Minister is interested to know whether: 1) use of this concept would allow individuals to vote who are not normally resident in the province of Laurentia; 2) if it would have, in
effect, prohibited from voting substantial numbers of residents of Laurentia, particularly newer residents, including recently arrived immigrants from other countries; 3)since there are concerns about bias in the administration of the vote, whether it would have allowed elections officers and poll clerks a large margin of discretion, in effect, to determine who could validly vote.
<P>
<li>Following the vote, public anger in certain other provinces of Nordland led the governments of those provinces to announce that the government of Laurentia and any entity owned or controlled by the government, including its enormous Pension Development Bank, would be barred from trading of securities on the markets of those provinces. Before stating publicly his response to these moves, the Prime Minister wishes to be briefed on the legality of such actions under conflicts and related constitutional principles.
<P>
<li>After a series of virulent attacks on the Laurentia separatist movement as &quot;racists&quot; and &quot;linguistic Nazis&quot; in newspapers and on radio talk shows in other provinces of Nordland that occurred during the referendum campaign, Foulard has announced his government will enact a law creating a civil right of action against anyone in Nordland who &quot;falsely dishonours&quot; the Laurentia people. The draft law explicitly states that this and other laws of Laurentia will apply, regardless of the place in Nordland where
the alleged dishonouring act occurred, and that the courts of Laurentia shall have jurisdiction over any defendant against which damages are claimed on the basis of the &quot;falsely dishonouring&quot; provision, whether or not resident in or engaged in business in Laurentia. Before reacting to these proposed moves, the Prime Minister wishes
to be briefed on the conflicts and related constitutional law issues to which they give rise. <B>Please note however that the question of whether these measures could withstand a constitutional challenge under the freedom of expression provisions of the Charter is the subject of a briefing note by someone else, and should not be dealt with in your answer except in relation to the application of common law principles.</B>
<P>
<li>The Prime Minister's Office has obtained a copy of a secret plan by Foulard and his movement to disrupt the markets in Nordland's currency in the following year, during which Laurentia is giving Nordland a &quot;last chance&quot; at a negotiated settlement. The Prime Minister is considering legislation that would prohibit the government of any province of Nordland or any entity of a province from engaging in the purchase and sale of Nordland currency beyond a certain amount, including on currency markets outside Nordland without the permission of the federal Government of Nordland. Any contracts for purchase or sale of Nordland currency entered into in violation of this provision would be declared null, void, and unenforceable in Nordland or elsewhere. The Prime Minister wishes to know whether these provisions would be recognized by courts or other bodies outside Nordland.
</ol>
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
Please send comments and suggestions to <a href="mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</a><p>
Created on JUL-29-96 by Anne Johnston.
</address>
