<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Constitutional Law<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Swinton</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This exam is composed of three questions. The grade and suggested time for each question is found at the beginning of the question. Note that the questions are not of equal weight. Remember that the exam is worth 40% of your final grade.
<P>
<li>You may think that you need to know more facts; if you do, say what it is you need to know, and, if appropriate, make some reasonable assumptions.
<P>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, the course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet, and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet during the exam, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be given for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion.
<P>
<li>At the conclusion, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing. Count the total number of booklets used, record this on the from of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. Then gather all your belongings and leave the exam room. All answer booklets are to be left on the table and will be collected by the invigilator.
<P>
<li>Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their booklets collected separately and may be subjected to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Question One</b> (40 marks/ 55 minutes)
<p>
Quebec's <cite>Charter of the French Language,</cite> intended to promote the use of the French language in the province, has a provision (s.65) requiring that all pre-packaged products offered for sale within the province be labelled both in French and English. Penalties for non-conformity with s. 65 include confiscation of the inadequately labelled Products and fines.
<p>
Prior to and during the recent eight day Jewish holiday of Passover, many foodstores in Montreal with a large Jewish clientele imported and offered for sale a variety of kosher Passover foods. (Orthodox Jews follow a strict set of dietary laws. &quot;Kosher&quot; refers to foods certified as having been prepared in conformity with Jewish dietary laws under the supervision of a rabbi or other designated person. Foods certified as &quot;kosher for Passover&quot; conform with the additional requirement of Jewish law that no food containing leavening agents be eaten during the eight-day Passover period. Kosher Passover foods include not only foods required for Passover observance such as matzah (an unleavened bread), but also a wide array of every-day food products such as orange juice, condiments, and canned and packaged foods.) Almost all of the kosher Passover foods offered for sale in Montreal stores were imported from New York and bore labels only in English or English and Hebrew. Kosher food manufacturers in the U.S. have explored the possibility of producing special runs of Passover items with French labels, but have concluded that this is impractical and prohibitively expensive, particularly with respect to perishable food products, given the relatively small market in Quebec. For example, one day's run of soup with bilingual labels would yield a six-year supply. While it would be possible for the importers of the Passover products to create special French labels to be attached to the products, they have also concluded that this is too costly and would make the price of the products prohibitive.
<p>
Responding to some complaints about the English-only labels, the Language Office which administers and enforces the language law ordered several stores to remove the Passover foods from their shelves. The stores were warned that if they did not comply, the products would be confiscated and charges laid under the language law.
There is also federal legislation governing the labelling of products. The <cite>Consumer Packaging and Labelling Act</cite> governs the labelling of all pre-packaged products sold in, imported into or advertised for sale in Canada. Section 4 of the Act prohibits such sale, importation or advertisement unless the product bears a label declaring the net quantity of the product in terms of either numerical count or a prescribed unit of measurement. Section 7 prohibits labels containing false or misleading representations about the product. Section 10 requires that labels show such information respecting the nature, contents and geographic origin of the product as may be prescribed by regulation. Section 20 of the Act creates an offense for violation of the Act and specifies penalties in the form of imprisonment or fines.
<p>
Section 18(1) permits the Governor in Council to make detailed regulations with regard to label form and content, including regulations prescribing &quot;the language or languages in which any information required to be declared or shown on labels shall be declared or shown.&quot; Pursuant to that section, regulations were passed, setting out in detail the contents and form of labels. Included was Regulation 6(2), titled &quot;Bilingualism Requirements&quot;, which requires that &quot;All information required by the Act and these Regulations to be shown on the label of a pre-packaged product shall be shown in both official languages.&quot; However, the federal regulations permit the Minister to grant exemptions from the labelling requirements in cases involving what are termed &quot;specialty products&quot;. The importers of kosher Passover foods have always applied for and been granted exemptions from the bilingualism regulations before bringing the products into the country.
<p>
A Jewish organization in Montreal wishes to bring legal proceedings to challenge the bilingual labelling requirements being imposed on Passover foods under the Quebec law. You are a junior lawyer in the law firm which the organization has approached for legal advice and you have been asked to write a memo on the federalism aspects of this problem. In your memo, you should set out the arguments which might be used to challenge the Quebec law on federalism grounds and assess both the strengths and weaknesses of those arguments. Do <b>not</b> deal with issues of standing or with the possible Charter issues raised.
<p><br>
<b>Question Two</b> (20 marks/ 30 minutes)
<p>
This question uses the same fact situation as in Question One. Your next task is to assess the likelihood of a successful <b>Charter </b>challenge to the language law's application under s. 2(a). Consider the strengths and weaknesses of the Charter arguments that the applicants might make for relief from the law. Once again, do not discuss standing.
<p><br>
<b>Question Three</b> (40 marks/ 50 minutes)
<p>
Ann and Beth are a lesbian couple who have lived together for five years now. They share a mortgage on their home and pool their finances. Ann has a six year old daughter, Chelsea, from an earlier relationship, which ended with the death of her partner.
<p>
Chelsea lives with them, and calls both Ann and Beth &quot;Mother&quot;. They have a warm and loving family arrangement, but the adults sometimes worry about what would happen to Chelsea, should Ann die or become incapacitated. They would like to have Beth adopt Chelsea, and thus become her legal parent.
<p>
Currently, the <cite>Adoption Act</cite> provides for so called &quot;family adoptions&quot;. In most adoptions, the ties between a child and his or her former parents are severed and a new parent-child relationship is created. With a family adoption, a child can be adopted by the spouse of his or her parent, with the approval of a Family Court judge, and the ties with the parent continue. &quot;Spouse&quot; is defined as the person to whom the parent of the child is married or is a person of the opposite sex with whom that person has been living in a relationship represented as that of husband and wife.
<p>
Ann and Beth have come to you for legal advice about the possibility of challenging the constitutionality of the adoption rules under the <cite>Charter of Rights.</cite> They cannot understand why they fail to qualify under the <cite>Adoption Act</cite>, whose purpose they understand to be the provision of a stable family situation for a child. Ann is also disturbed that her wishes for her child's security and development seem to be disregarded by the Act.
<p>
They have drawn to your attention extensive information about the ability of gay and lesbian couples to parent: many studies indicate that the most important element in the healthy development of a child is a stable, consistent, warm, and responsive relationship between a child and his/her caregiver; other studies conclude that there is no evidence that children raised by homosexual parents are likely to be significantly different from children raised by heterosexual parents in all areas of psychological development.
<p>
Discuss the strengths and weaknesses of the case that Ann and Beth might make under ss. 7 and 15 of the Charter, including the appropriate remedy that a Court might give.
<p><br>
<hr>
