<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Constitutional Law<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Risk</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This exam is composed of three questions, which are of equal value. To allocate your time equally among them, take 45 minutes for each one.
<P>
<li>Do not worry about federalism or the application of the Charter. You may think that you need to know more facts; if you do, say what it is you need to know, and, if appropriate, make some reasonable assumptions. For example, you may wish to make some assumptions about the purposes of legislation.
<P>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, the course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet, and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet during the exam, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be given for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion.
<P>
<li>At the conclusion, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing. Count the total number of booklets used, record this on the from of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. Then gather all your belongings and leave the exam room. All answer booklets are to be left on the table and will be collected by the invigilator.
<P>
<li>Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their booklets collected separately and may be subjected to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<h3>Question One</h3>

At present, Ontario Hydro, a publicly owned corporation, does virtually all of the production and distribution of electricity in Ontario. There has, though, been lots of talk about &quot;privatization lately. For the purposes of this question, assume that this talk became a reality a few months ago. That is, assume that the production and sale of electricity are now functions for private enterprise. In this new world, the production is done by a few large  corporations (who purchased the existing generating plants from Hydro). Some of the selling is done by these producers, as direct sales to large consumers, but most selling is done by businesses, large and small. that buy electricity from the producers and resell it to consumers. (The distribution network is still publicly owned, but this fact is not significant for this question.)
<P>
The government has made a set of regulations about advertising for sales of electricity, including these two rules:
<blockquote>
i) The total expenditures on advertising by any seller cannot exceed 10% of its total sales in the past year. (There are transitional provisions for new entrants that don't matter here.) This rule was a response to a strong, widespread fear, expressed during the debates about privatization, that competition among sellers would lead to waste, especially wasteful advertising.
<P>
ii) The advertising may not include persuasion to increase the use of energy generally. Instead it must be about the virtues of electricity contrasted to other forms of energy, or about the service and price of the particular seller. This rule was also a response to a widespread fear that in competing among themselves, the sellers would encourage wasteful uses of energy, endangering both our supply of energy and our environment.
</blockquote>
Several sellers brought an action claiming that their right to freedom of expression, given by section 2 of the Charter, has been unjustifiably curtailed. What arguments can be made, and what result do you think the Supreme Court will reach?
<P><br>
<h3>Question Two</h3>

Proclaiming the values of preserving family bonds and discouraging promiscuity, the government has enacted legislation about birth control. First, any health professional (for example, a doctor or nurse) must notify the parents of any person aged 16 or less who seeks advice or devices (for example, IUDs, pills, and condoms) for birth control. (There are provisions for situations in which parents are living apart or cannot be found that do not matter here.) Doctors who violate this requirement are subject to professional discipline. Second, birth control literature or  devices cannot be sold from any source to any person aged 16 or less without a prescription from a doctor, and sellers who violate this requirement are subject to substantial fines.
<P>
This legislation has been challenged as an unjustifiable violation of section 7 of the Charter by groups representing young people, and defended by the government and by groups representing parents. What arguments can reasonably be made, and what result do you think the Supreme Court will reach?
<P><br>
<h3>Question Three</h3>

Ann and Beth are a lesbian couple. Ann has a four-year old daughter, Chelsea, from a marriage that preceded this relation. Ann and Beth both want to have Beth adopt Chelsea, as a formal recognition of the loving bonds of parenthood that both feel exist.
<P>
In most adoptions, the ties between a child and his or her former parents are severed and a new parent child-relation is created. The Adoption Act does, though, proved for so-called family adoptions, in which a child is adopted by the spouse of his or her parent and the ties with the parent continue. Ann and Beth have this form of adoption in mind, but spouse is defined (and the details don't matter) in a way that requires the adopting person to be of the opposite sex to the parent.
<P>
Ann and Beth have come to you for advice. In your discussions with them, they have given you about the ability of gay and lesbian couple to parent: many studies suggest that the most important element in the healthy development of a child is a stable, consistent, warm, and responsive relation between a child and his or her caregiver, and that children raised by homosexual couples are not likely to be significantly different from children from children raised
by heterosexual couples.
<P>
They propose to make a claim that their equality rights given by section 15 of the Charter are unjustifiably violated by the Adoption Act. What arguments can reasonably be made, and what result do you think the Supreme Court will reach?
<p><br>
<hr>
