<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Constitutional Law B<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Patrick Macklem</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<blockquote>
You may use any kind of material you wish in the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
The examination contains two questions, which are of equal value. The examination is worth 40% of your final grade.
<P>
At the conclusion of the examination, you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE. IF YOU USE MORE THAN ONE BOOKLET, PLEASE INSERT ALL BOOKLETS INTO BOOKLET NO. 1.</b>
<P>
Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
<P>
<b>PLEASE DOUBLE-SPACE YOUR ANSWER.</b>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>QUESTION 1</h3>

You are an articling student at a law firm in British Columbia. Your firm is representing an Aboriginal couple, Mr. and Mrs. Ryan, who belong to the Gitksan nation. They live in Smithers, B.C., a large town in the interior of British Columbia. Their children attend Smithers High School, which is a publicly-run high school established pursuant to the provincial <cite>Education Act (British Columbia).</cite>
<P>
Section 11(b) of the <cite>Education Act </cite>provides that &quot;save for special language classes, instruction in public schools in the Province shall be in the English language.&quot; Section 14(c) requires all children between the ages of 6 and 14 to attend public school, with exceptions permitting home instruction in some circumstances as well as attendance at certain accredited private institutions.
<P>
The Ryans have come to your firm complaining of the fact that the school does not teach their children in the Tsimshian language. Tsimshian, which is the language of the Gitksan people, is spoken on the north-west coast around Prince Rupert and in the lower Nass and Skeena valleys where Smithers is located, and which historically
was Gitksan territory. Smithers has a population of approximately 2000 people, and its inhabitants are predominantly non-Aboriginal and English-speaking. There are about 150 Gitksan people living in the town; most Gitksan people live or near several reserves located approximately 70 kilometres from Smithers. There is a school on one of the reserves, established pursuant to the federal <cite>Indian Act, </cite>where students receive instruction in Gitksan, but the Ryans do not own a car and the school is too far to bus students to and from Smithers.
<P>
They state, and preliminary research bears this out, that teachers and administrators at the school received their training in, and predominantly come from, Vancouver or Victoria. No teacher or administrator either speaks Tsimshian or is Gitksan and, partly as a result, instructors have little knowledge of Gitksan traditions or culture. But for optional French language classes, courses at the school are taught in English. Nor do instructors make any
sustained effort to teach Gitksan history or beliefs. The Ryans fear that their children will lose their proficiency in Tsimshian, and that, as a result, they will become alienated from Gitksan history, traditions and culture.
<P>
Your principal has asked you to prepare a memorandum exploring possible Charter arguments that could be made in a constitutional challenge to the school's language policy. In particular, she has asked you to research ss. 2(b), 15, and 1 of the Charter, to outline and apply the relevant case law, identify useful arguments, identify and respond to those arguments that the school is likely to advance, and assess the likelihood of success of a challenge based on either ss. 2(b) or 15 of the Charter. She would also like guidance on what remedies she should seek in such a challenge. Please do not address any issues relating to s. 2(a) of the Charter as these are being addressed by another articling student.
<P><br>
<h3>QUESTION 2</h3>

Quebec's <cite>Charter of the French Language, </cite>intended to promote the use of the French language in the province, has a provision (s. 65) requiring that all prepackaged products offered for sale within the province be labelled both in French and English. Penalties for non-conformity with s. 65 include confiscation of the  inadequately labelled products and finess
<P>
Prior to and during the recent eight day Jewish holiday of Passover, many foodstores in Montreal with a large Jewish clientele imported and offered for sale a variety of kosher Passover foods. (Orthodox Jews follow a strict set of dietary laws. &quot;Kosher&quot; refers to foods certified as having been prepared in conformity with Jewish dietary laws under the supervision of a rabbi or other designated person. Foods certified as &quot;kosher for Passover&quot; conform with the additional requirement of Jewish law that no food containing leavening agents be eaten during the eight-day Passover period. Kosher Passover foods include not only foods required for Passover observance such as matzah (an unleavened bread), but also a wide array of every-day food products such as orange juice, condiments, and canned and packaged foods.) Almost all of the kosher Passover foods offered for sale in Montreal stores were imported from New York and bore labels only in English or English and Hebrew. Kosher food manufacturers in the U.S. have explored the possibility of producing special runs of Passover items with French labels, but have concluded that this is impractical and prohibitively expensive, particularly with respect to perishable
food products, given the relatively small market in Quebec. For example, one day's run of soup with bilingual labels would yield a six-year supply. While it would be possible for importers of the Passover products to create special French labels to be attached to the products, they have also concluded that this is too costly and would make the price of the products prohibitive.
<P>
Responding to some complaints about the English-only labels, the Language Office, which administers and enforces Quebec's language law, ordered several stores to remove the Passover foods from their shelves. The stores were warned that if they did not comply, the products would be confiscated and charges would be laid.
<P>
There is also federal legislation governing the labelling of products. The federal <cite>Consumer Packaging and Labelling Act </cite>governs the labelling of all prepackaged products sold in, imported into, or advertised for sale in Canada. Section 4 of the Act prohibits such sale, importation, or advertisement unless the product bears a label declaring the net quantity of the product in terms of either numerical count or a prescribed unit of measurement. Section 7 prohibits labels containing false or misleading representations about the product. Section 10 requires that labels show such information respecting the nature, contents and geographic origin of the product as may be prescribed by regulation. Section 20 of the Act creates an offence for violation of the Act and specifies penalties in
the form of imprisonment or fines.
<P>
Section 18(1) of the federal Act permits the Governor in Council to make detailed regulations with regard to label, form, and content, including regulations prescribing &quot;the language or languages in which any information required to be declared or shown on labels shall be declared or shown.&quot; Pursuant to that section, federal
regulations were passed, setting out in detail the contents and form of labels. Included was Regulation 6(2), titled &quot;Bilingualism Requirements&quot;, which requires that &quot;all information required by the Act and these Regulations to be shown on the label of a prepackaged product shall be shown in both official languages.&quot;
However, the federal regulations permit the Minister to grant exemptions from the labelling requirements in cases involving what are termed &quot;specialty products&quot;. The importers of kosher Passover foods have always applied for and been granted exemptions from the federal bilingualism regulations before bringing the products into the country.
<P>
A Jewish organization in Montreal wishes to bring legal proceedings to challenge the bilingual labelling requirements being imposed on Passover foods under the Quebec law. You are a junior lawyer in the law firm which the organization has approached for legal advice and you have been asked to write a memo on the following
aspects of this problem.
<blockquote>
(a) What arguments might be used to challenge the Quebec law on federalism grounds? What are the strengths and weaknesses of such of arguments? (Your answer to this issue will be worth 50% of Question 2.)
<P>
 (b) What arguments might be used to challenge the Quebec law on the basis that it interferes with freedom of religion as guaranteed by s. 2(a) of the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>? What are the strengths and weaknesses of such arguments and, given s. 1 of the <cite>Charter, </cite>the likelihood of their
success? (Your answer to this issue will be worth 50% of Question 2.)
</blockquote>
<p><br>
