<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Constitutional Law II<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor L. Weinrib</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of three questions. Recommended time allocations for each question are provided.
<P>
<li><b>Please <I>double space </I>your answer.</b>
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each </b>examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive
it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<b>1. (70 minutes)</b> Quebec enacted the <cite>Charter of the French Language </cite>to promote the use of French in the province. S.65 requires labeling in both French and English on all prepackaged products offered for sale. Failure to comply with s. 65 attracts penalties, including confiscation of the inadequately labeled products and fines.
<P>
Prior to and during the recent eight day Jewish holiday of Passover, stores in Montreal imported and offered for sale a variety of foods for the holiday. These foods complied with the relevant religious laws, which include the requirement of eating some foods (e.g., matzah, an unleavened bread), prohibition against eating other foods (e.g., bread, grains), and the permissibility of eating other foods only if certified as kosher for Passover by a recognized rabbinical authority (e.g., condiments, canned and packaged foods). Most of the Passover foods offered for sale in Montreal stores are imported from New York and bear the labels used in the U.S. market, i.e., English or English and Hebrew. Because of the wide variety of products and the fact that the market for them is both small and of limited duration, it would be prohibitively expensive for the American manufacturers or the Quebec importers and retailers to provide bilingual labels or add French labels.
<P>
Following up complaints about the English-only labels, the Language Office which administers and enforces the <cite>Charter of the French Language</cite> ordered several stores to remove the Passover foods from the
shelves or face confiscation and charges under the Act.
<P>
The federal <cite>Consumer Packaging and Labeling Act </cite>governs the labeling of all pre-packaged products sold in, imported into or advertised for sale in Canada as follows:
<ul>
<li>s. 4 requires a statement of the net quantity of the product by numerical count or a prescribed unit of measurement.
<li>s. 7 prohibits false or misleading representations about the product.
<li>s. 10 requires information respecting the nature, contents and geographic origin of the product as may be prescribed by regulation.
<li>s. 20 creates an offence for violation of the Act and specifies penalties in the form of imprisonment or fines.
<li>s. 18(1) permits the Governor in Council to make detailed regulations with regard to label form and content, including regulations prescribing &quot;the language or languages in which any information required to be declared or shown on labels shall be declared or shown.&quot;
<li>Regulation 6(2), titled &quot;Bilingualism Requirements&quot;, requires that &quot;All information required by the Act and these Regulations to be shown on the label of a pre-packaged product shall be shown in both official languages&quot;.
</ul>
In addition to these general rules, the Minister is also empowered by Regulation to grant exemptions from the labeling requirements for &quot;specialty products&quot;. This year, as in the past, the importers of kosher Passover foods applied for and received exemptions from the federal bilingualism regulations.
<P>
A Jewish organization in Montreal wants help in untangling the federal and provincial laws applicable to the importation of kosher food for Passover. In particular, the organization wants some legal assurance that the Jewish community will not have difficulty obtaining these foods in the future. You are a junior lawyer in the law firm that the organization has approached for legal advice. You are to write a memorandum of law on the federalism aspects of this problem. In your memo, set out the arguments which might be used on behalf of this client and assess the prospects of success. Do <b>not </b>deal with issues of standing or <cite>Charter</cite> issues.
<P><br>
<b>2. (70 minutes)</b> Since their introduction about 20 years ago, cochlear implants have gained acceptance as an option for individuals with profound hearing impairment for whom hearing aids are not effective. Unlike a  conventional hearing aid, which amplifies sounds, the implant bypasses damaged inner ear structures to send electrical signals directly to the auditory nerves. The vast majority of deaf adults with cochlear implants derive substantial benefit -- especially if the implantation follows soon after loss of hearing. Studies demonstrate decline
in loneliness, depression, and social isolation and an increase in self-esteem, independence, social integration, and vocational prospects.
<P>
The advisability of cochlear implants for children has proved more difficult to document. There is no data about the long term safety of the device and progress for children, while evident, is markedly slower than for adults, particularly for children who were born deaf. Some medical authorities are urging implantation earlier than the present recommended age (from 2 to 3 years) to take advantage of the period of greatest language learning capacity,
but earlier surgery would have to depend on less reliable testing of hearing levels and presents greater risk of complications. The surgery destroys the inner ear, precluding later use of technological developments that might require an intact inner ear. Success in learning to decode the electrical signals depends on sustained commitment by family members as well as extended and expensive, medical and educational support. There is considerable   anecdotal material indicating that some children, particularly those who have implants after hearing loss, do well with implants, e.g., integrating easily into regular classrooms, speaking on the phone, even taking music lessons.
<P>
Opposition to implants for children emanates from certain leaders within the deaf community. They view  implantation for children as misguided experimentation, based on the erroneous idea that deafness is a pathology or disability. For them, deafness is an individual identity as well as an exclusive, historic bond to a way of life defined by shared language and culture. All attempts to integrate the deaf into the hearing world by insisting on oral speech have failed in the past, they maintain, producing people who function poorly in both the hearing and the deaf world. Their literature includes the following statement:
<blockquote>
[Children with implants] will be forced to speak and not use sign language by their parents and audiologists. The deaf community is a very close one. Yet the deaf community will mock these people and they will feel left out of the community and certainly suffer as a result.
</blockquote>
These spokespersons devote themselves to creating a better future for the deaf against the background of Nazi persecution during World War II, eugenics policies that prohibited the marriage of deaf persons to each other, and the suppression of sign language in schools designated for the deaf in North America. They see hopeful signs in the enhanced respect for sign language and use of new electronic technologies, based on writing and images, that facilitate local and international communication. The biggest threat, in their view, is not the prejudice or ignorance of the past but the medical profession's desire, at great public expense and high psychological cost to the individuals affected, to snatch away the next generation.
<P>
Parents, who must give consent to implantation surgery for a deaf child, are caught between the opposing positions. They want to do the best for their child but find it difficult to make informed decisions given the conflicting understandings. These parents find attractive the possibility of providing some hearing capacity by means of an implant because a deaf child is prone to be solitary and hence vulnerable to dangers against which hearing children,
individually and in groups, are protected by warning sounds -- in the home, school and on the street. They also worry about their child's future because deaf children have in the past rarely mastered more than a basic facility in oral or written language and thus have had limited social, educational and vocational prospects. However, these parents are also moved by the anti-implant message from the community that presumably is most familiar with the burdens of deafness and the realistic possibilities of social life for deaf children beyond the family.
<P>
The groups who oppose implantation for children have approached the provincial government seeking legislation banning parental consent for cochlear implants for their children. They argue (1) that such legislation is necessary to sustain the future of their historically beleaguered, politically powerless and culturally creative, sign language based community, (2) that it is primarily wealthy and middle class parents who seek the implant for their children at public expense, thus leaving the deaf community with reduced resources and less effective community support, and (3) that in times of financial constraint the government should fund only those medical interventions that offer well-established health benefits.
<P>
You are a government lawyer who vets new policy proposals for their compatibility with the <cite>Charter</cite>. The premier's office has sent this proposal to you for consideration with the following annotation: &quot;Please
consider this innovative and money-saving proposal for consistency with the <cite>Charter</cite>.&quot;  Prepare a memorandum setting out and evaluating the <cite>Charter</cite> arguments raised by the proposal for legislation.
<P><br>
<b>3. (40 minutes)</b> We have read a number of <cite>Charter</cite> cases in the second term and often been critical of the ways in which judges in the Supreme Court of Canada have interpreted the <cite>Charter </cite>text. Imagine that you could go back to the time of the <cite>Charter's </cite>formulation. What one change would you make to the text and why? If you would make no change, account for this position.
<p><br>
