<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Contracts<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Trebilcock</h2></center>
<h3>Notes:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may consult any kind of material you wish during the exam, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of three questions. Answer all questions (which are of equal weight).
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional
booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the test, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the test.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>An examination answer booklets are to be on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits win be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the test has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol><hr>
<P>
<b>1.</b> Marlene D. (her stage name) is an aspiring actress. Originally from Toronto, she completed a degree in acting at Julliard and has spent the last five years in New York doing a lot of small theatre and developing her craft. Early on in her career she had the great fortune to meet and become friends with Darth Grabinsky, a hugely  successful producer of live theatre in Toronto. Grabinsky, who has a keen eye for promising actors and actresses, took an interest in Marlene's career and over the years has provided her with much advice; his advice has invariably proved valuable to her. It was he who advised her, for example, to stay at Julliard when in her first year she was offered a part in the touring company of &quot;Cats&quot;. It was he who advised her to do summer stock in Syracuse, New York, with a small and relatively unknown but inspired group of actors who have since gone on to greatness. And it was he who advised her that if she really wanted to be taken seriously in the increasingly sophisticated theatre world in Toronto, she should spend several years working in New York.
<P>
A little over a year and a half ago, Grabinsky called up Marlene to offer her a part in his upcoming production of &quot;Sunrise on Avenue Road.&quot; &quot;It's not the lead&quot;, he told her, &quot;but it's the biggest part that I can offer you at the moment and it will bring you to the attention of the theatre world in North America.&quot; Marlene accepted on the spot.
<P>
When she got off the plane, Marlene collapsed in tears of joy and relief. Although she had learned a great deal during her time in New York and while she loved city living, she found Manhattan unbearable; she pined for the Toronto she remembered from her undergraduate days at U of T. Moreover, she had always wished for nothing more than to return home to Canada. Here was her dream come true.
<P>
Marlene packed up her things, paid up three months rent to get out of her lease in New York and moved to Toronto. Her plan was to reimmerse herself in Toronto life, do work with local voice and drama coaches and get herself settled in her new life before rehearsals for &quot;Sunrise&quot; began. She rented an apartment in Cabbagetown and thoroughly enjoyed reacquainting herself with the city over the next several months. When the time came to begin rehearsals for &quot;Sunrise&quot; she told her friends she had never been so happy in her life; indeed, she had never realized how depressed and lonely she had been in New York.
<P>
One month into rehearsals Grabinsky came up to Marlene during a rehearsal break and told her that he was impressed with her performances. He said he had concluded that he had made a mistake casting her in &quot;Sunrise&quot; in a supporting role and that he felt she was better suited for the lead in a smaller production
of &quot;Sunrise&quot; he was mounting simultaneously in Chicago. He told her he had replaced her in the Toronto production with another actress and would arrange to have the Chicago rehearsals delayed a few weeks to give her a chance to move her things; he told her he anticipated a run of at least two years in Chicago. When Marlene told him she didn't want to go to the Chicago production, Grabinsky - who had a reputation for being somewhat volatile and arrogant - became angry, and berated her in front of the rest of the cast for fifteen minutes, telling her she was an ungrateful and foolish young woman.
<P>
Marlene was shattered by this turn of events. She couldn't bear the thought of moving to Chicago, giving up her life in Toronto and returning to the U.S. She also felt hurt and betrayed by Grabinsky, who had been like a father to her and on whom she had relied so heavily and on whom, it was clear, she could rely no more. She sank into a deep depression and lost all contact with Grabinsky. For the past year she has been unable to work in the theatre due to her depression and her lack of contacts in the business. She has depleted her savings, been forced to move into a rented room in a much less desirable neighbourhood and is scraping by on what she can earn waitressing.
<P>
She seeks your legal opinion as to her legal rights against Grabinsky.
<P><br>
<b>2. a)</b> Alicia Dellarock, a renowned concert pianist, has just returned to Toronto from a four-month concert tour in Europe. She will be giving a series of lectures at U of T's music department throughout the Summer, and is moving permanently to New York City thereafter. Before she left for Europe, she sold everything she owned, including her Queen's Quay penthouse condominium. (Her lecturing contract with U of T provides her with on-campus accommodation for the summer.) She had been unable to part with her beloved 1878 Steinway grand piano, however, and had therefore decided not to sell it, but rather to keep it in storage until her move to New York.
<P>
Concerned to find a reliable storage company, Alicia had turned for advice to Radoo Loopoo, an old friend of hers who had, just a year earlier, stored his own piano much to his satisfaction. Radoo had recommended that she contact Eazee Storage Inc., the storage brokerage firm he had used at the time. &quot;They're great!&quot;, Radoo had assured her, &quot;They'll find you the best and cheapest storage space in the city. You'll have no troubles with them. I'd stake my life on it.&quot; Alicia had thus arranged to meet with Brooke Broker at Eazee Storage Inc.'s offices.
<P>
During this meeting, Brooke had explained to Alicia that, as a brokerage firm, Eazee Storage Inc. does not own the spaces rented out, but rather contracts out with property owners who have available spaces. &quot;Customers contract with us to arrange storage for them. We find out what's available, go check it out, and select only the spaces that meet our very high standards. For all this, we charge you the storage price paid to the property owner plus
a mere 1% commission!&quot; She had added: &quot;As it turns out, I see on my list that we have a space that's just right for you. It is only three blocks away from where you live, so you wouldn't have to pay much for moving.&quot; Alicia had liked the idea of saving money on moving, but had nonetheless insisted that she needed a pressure-controlled space, as her piano was very old and could be damaged by pressure fluctuations. &quot;Most modern pianos can withstand pressure fluctuations,&quot; she had told Brooke, &quot;but mine is a collection piece with a very sensitive internal mechanism. It could be ruined if the pressure fluctuates.&quot; Brooke had responded: &quot;Not to worry. All the spaces we select are pressure-controlled. That's just part of our ground rules.&quot;
<P>
Somewhat reassured, Alicia had then been presented with a copy of Eazee Storage Inc.'s standard &quot;Storage Agreement.&quot; She had asked whether this Agreement mentioned something about spaces being pressure-controlled, and Brooke had said that it did not. Alicia had then asked whether a clause to that effect could be added. Brooke had answered: &quot;Well, I don't like to make changes to the Agreement myself, but if it bothers you that much, we can always ask my boss to do it. He has left for the day, but will be back tomorrow. Now, I assure you, you need not worry about that. We <b>never</b> rent spaces that are not pressure-controlled.&quot; As Alicia had not wanted to have to come back the next day, she had told Brooke to proceed with the Agreement in its standard form. Brooke had filled out the storage space's location, rental period, and price in the blank spaces provided to that effect. The space would be rented from Stuart Storer, 300 Lakeshore Blvd., from January 1, 1996 to August 31,
1996, for the total price of $100/month. Brooke had handed the completed Agreement to Alicia, who had signed it without reading it, and paid the total price of $800 upfront, as was required of her under the Agreement.
<P>
Yesterday, upon returning from Europe, Alicia went to 300 Lakeshore Blvd. to check on her piano. She was very distressed to find out that the space had not been pressure-controlled, and that her precious 1878 Steinway has lost its unique resonance as a result. While it probably can be resold to a beginner as a basic practice piano, it is unusable by her or by any other concert pianist. She asked Stuart Storer why the space had not been pressure-controlled, and Stuart responded: &quot;This is the first I've heard of pressure-control. None of my spaces is pressure-controlled. We're simply not equipped for it!&quot; Alicia then called Brooke, who apologized profusely,
but stopped short of offering Alicia any form of compensation. Nor would she release her from her contract for the months of May to August. &quot;I'm really sorry for this unfortunate mishap,&quot; Brooke said, &quot;but we never gave you any warranties to that effect.&quot; She then referred Alicia to a paragraph in smaller print at the very end of the Storage Agreement. This paragraph contains the following clause, which is commonly found in storage contracts:
<blockquote>
&quot;Eazee Storage Inc. gives no warranty as to temperature or any other matter pertaining to the maintenance of the storage space.
</blockquote>
Alicia has asked you to advise her. Specifically, she wants to know whether she can hope to recover any of the piano's lost value, her moving expenses, and/or her $800 from Eazee Storage Inc. or Radoo Loopoo. (She recently had a fight with him and would have no problems seeing him in court.)
<P>
You are to assume that Eazee Storage Inc. is fully bound by Brooke Broker's actions, and that it cannot be established that Brooke Broker or Eazee Storage Inc. acted with malice or fraud in this matter.
<P>
<b>b)</b> Assume the same facts as for Question 2(a), except that the space was fitted with pressure-control but it had just been activated due to the negligence of an employee of Stuart Storer, and that the Storage Agreement between Alicia and Eazee Storage Inc. contains the following clause:
<blockquote>
&quot;It is hereby expressly agreed that neither Eazee Storage Inc., nor its servants or agents, shall in any circumstances whatsoever be liable to the customer for any loss or damage arising from any act, neglect or default on its part while acting in the course of its performance of the present Agreement. &quot;
</blockquote>
Can Alicia recover damages from Stuart Storer's employees?
<P><br>
<b>3.</b> James Booker, a farmer near Flesherton, Ontario, entered into a written agreement on June 1st, 1995 to sell his 100-acre farm to Fred and Janet DeLuca for $200,000 as a retirement residence. The farm includes a  picturesque turn-of-the-century red-brick Victorian home (in original and rather dilapidated condition) where Agnes McPhail, Canada's first woman Parliamentarian, once lived. The closing date for the sale was August 31st, 1995.
<P>
Discuss the legal implications of each of the following scenarios:
<P>
<b>a)</b> Unknown to any of the parties the farm is the site of a buried toxic waste dump dating back several owners (and decades). This dump is uncovered in January 1996 when the DeLuca's were having excavations undertaken in the course of construction of a pond. It has contaminated the farm's water supply and will cost $1 million to clean up.
<P>
<b>b)</b> The facts are as in (a) but the excavations reveal a major mineral deposit.
<P>
<b>c)</b> Shortly before the transaction was to close on August 31st, 1995, the provincial government proclaimed the farm a &quot;National Treasure&quot; under relevant legislation, which precludes any significant modifications to the farm or its buildings, including the farmhouse, which the DeLuca's had intended substantially to remodel and update, and which allows the public to view the home externally at any time during daylight hours.
<p><br>
<hr>
