<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Contracts A<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Hadfield</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of one question. Please be sure to identify an issue only if you consider it important to the resolution of the case and to analyse and argue each issue you identify carefully. Please note that an &quot;important&quot; issue may nonetheless be relatively easy to resolve. Marks will be given for identifying the key issues as key, and deducted for discussing issues that are of  little or no importance.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
Marlene D. (her stage name) is an aspiring actress. Originally from Toronto, she completed a degree in acting at Julliard and has spent the last five years in New York doing a lot of small theatre and developing her craft. Early on in her career she had the great fortune to meet and become friends with Darth Grabinsky, a hugely successful producer of live theatre in Toronto. Grabinsky, who has a keen eye for promising actors and actresses, took an interest in Marlene's career and over the years has provided her with much advice; his advice has invariably proved valuable to her. It was he who advised her, for example, to stay at Julliard when in her first year she was offered a part in the touring company of &quot;Cats.&quot; It was he who advised her to do summer stock in Syracuse, New York, with a small and relatively unknown but inspired group of actors who have since gone on to greatness. And it was he who advised her that if she really wanted to be taken seriously in the increasingly sophisticated theatre world
in Toronto, she should spend several years working in New York.
<P>
A little over a year and a half ago, Grabinsky called up Marlene to offer her a part in his upcoming production of &quot;Sunrise on Avenue Road.&quot; &quot;It's not the lead,&quot; he told her, &quot;but it's a part that I think will bring you to the attention of the theatre here in Toronto. I think it's time to come back home and this is the play to do it. &quot; Marlene accepted on the spot.
<P>
When she got off the phone, Marlene collapsed in tears of joy and relief. Although she had learned a great deal during her time in New York and while she loved city living, she found Manhattan unbearable; she pined for the Toronto she remembered from her undergraduate days at U. of T. Moreover, she had always wished nothing more than to return home to Canada. Here was her dream come true.
<P>
Grabinsky sent Marlene a standard form contract which stated &quot;Actor agrees to comply with the following conditions&quot; and listed 26 conditions, including, showing up for all rehearsals on time, refraining from any activity which would jeopardize the actor's ability to perform, complying with all directions from the director and producer, and undertaking whatever professional training was deemed necessary to put on a first-rate production. The contract also stated: &quot;Producer retains the right to cancel, discontinue, or modify the production or the actor's engagement in any way he deems desirable and for any reason at any time.&quot;
<P>
Marlene packed up her things, paid up three months rent to get out of her lease in New York and moved to Toronto. Her plan was to reimmerse herself in Toronto life, begin work with local voice and drama coaches and get herself settled in her new life before rehearsals for &quot;Sunrise&quot; began. She rented an apartment in Cabbagetown and thoroughly enjoyed reacquainting herself with the city over the next several months. When the time came to begin rehearsals for &quot;Sunrise&quot; she told her friends she had never been so happy in her life; indeed, she had never realized how depressed and lonely she had been in New York.
<P>
One month into rehearsals Grabinsky came up to Marlene during a rehearsal break and told her that he was impressed with her performances. He said he had concluded that he had made a mistake casting her in &quot;Sunrise&quot; in a supporting role and that he felt she was better suited for the lead in a smaller production
of &quot;Sunrise&quot; he was mounting in partnership with a Chicago company in Chicago. He told her he had replaced her in the Toronto production with another actress and would arrange to have the Chicago rehearsals delayed a few weeks to give her a chance to move her things; he told her he anticipated a run of at least two years in Chicago. When Marlene told him she didn't want to go to the Chicago production, Grabinsky-who had a reputation for being somewhat volatile and arrogant--became angry, and berated her in front of the rest of the cast for fifteen minutes, telling her she was an ungrateful and foolish young woman.
<P>
Marlene was shattered by this turn of events. She couldn't bear the thought of moving to Chicago, giving up her life in Toronto and returning to the U.S. She also felt hurt and betrayed by Grabinsky, who had been like a father to her and on whom she had relied so heavily and on whom, it was clear, she could rely no more. She sank into a deep depression and lost all contact with Grabinsky. For the past year she has been unable to work in the theatre due to her depression and her lack of contacts in the business in Toronto. She has depleted her savings, been forced to move into a rented room in a much less desirable neighbourhood and is scraping by on what she can earn waitressing.
<P>
Is it worth it for Marlene to sue Grabinsky? (Assume that the Toronto contract is with Grabinsky in his capacity as &quot;Producer&quot; and that had Marlene gone to Chicago her contract would have been with a Chicago corporation and not with Grabinsky himself.)
<p><br>
<hr>
