<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Contracts B<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Valcke</h2></center>
<h3>Notes:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may consult any kind of material you wish during the exam, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of two questions.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive
it. No time wig be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the test, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the test.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the test has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<b>50% 1. a)</b> Alicia Dellarock, a renowned concert pianist, just returned to Toronto from a four-month concert tour in Europe. She will be giving a series of lectures at U of T's music department throughout the Summer, and is moving permanently to New York City thereafter. Before she left for Europe, she sold everything she owned, including her Queen's Quay penthouse condominium. (Her lecturing contract with U of T provides her with on-campus accommodation for the Summer.) She had been unable to part with her beloved 1878 Steinway grand piano, however, and had therefore decided not to sell it, but rather to keep it in storage until her move to New York.
<P>
Concerned to find a reliable storage company, Alicia had turned for advice to Radoo Loopoo, an old friend of hers who had, just a year earlier, stored his own piano much to his satisfaction. Radoo had recommended that she contact
Eazee Storage Inc., the storage brokerage firm he had used at the time. &quot;They're great!&quot;, Radoo had assured her, &quot;They'll find you the best storage space in the city, and for cheap. You'll have no troubles with them. I'd stake my life on it.&quot; Alicia had thus arranged to meet with Brooke Broker at Eazee Storage Inc.'s offices.
<P>
During this meeting, Brooke had explained to Alicia that, as a brokerage firm, Eazee Storage Inc. does not own the spaces rented out, but rather contracts out with property owners who have advertised available spaces. &quot;Customers contract with us to arrange storage for them. We find out what's available, go check it out, and select only the spaces that meet our very high standards. For all this, we charge you the storage price paid to the property owner plus a mere 1% commission!&quot; She had added: &quot;As it turns out, I see on my list that we have a space that's just right for you. It is only three blocks away from where you live, so you wouldn't have to pay
much for moving.&quot; Alicia had liked the idea of saving money on moving, but had nonetheless insisted that she needed a pressure-controlled space, as her piano was very old and could be damaged by pressure fluctuations. &quot;Most modern pianos can withstand pressure fluctuations,&quot; she had told Brooke, &quot;but mine is a collection piece with a very sensitive internal mechanism. It could be ruined if the pressure fluctuates.&quot;
Brooke had responded: &quot;Not to worry. All the spaces we select are pressure-controlled. That's just part of our ground rules.&quot;
<P>
Somewhat reassured, Alicia had then been presented with a copy of Eazee Storage Inc.'s standard &quot;Storage Agreement.&quot; She had asked whether this Agreement mentioned something about spaces being pressure-controlled, and Brooke had said that it did not.  Alicia had then asked whether a clause to that effect could be added. Brooke had answered: &quot;Well, I don't like to make changes to the Agreement myself, but if it bothers you that much, we can always ask my boss to do it. He has left for the day, but will be back tomorrow. Now, I assure you, you need not worry about that. We <b>never</b> rent  spaces that are not pressure-controlled.&quot; As Alicia had
not wanted to have to come back the next day, she had told Brooke to proceed with the Agreement in its standard  form. Brooke had filled out the storage space's location, rental period, and price in the blank spaces provided to that effect. The space would be rented from Stuart Storer, 300 Lakeshore Blvd., from January 1, 1996 to August 31, 1996, for the total price of $100/month. Brooke had handed the completed Agreement to Alicia, who had signed it without reading, and paid the total price of $800 upfront, as was required of her under the Agreement.
<P>
Yesterday, upon returning from Europe, Alicia went to 300 Lakeshore Blvd. to check on her piano. She was very distressed to find out that the space had not been pressure-controlled, and that her precious 1878 Steinway has lost its unique resonance as a result. While it probably can be resold to a beginner as a basic practice piano, it is unusable by her or by any other concert pianist. She asked Stuart Storer why the space had not been pressure-controlled, and Stuart responded: &quot;This is the first I've heard of pressure-control. None of my spaces is pressure-controlled. We're simply not equipped for it!&quot; Alicia then called Brooke, who apologized profusely,
but stopped short of offering Alicia any form of compensation. Nor would she release her from her contract for the months of May to August. &quot;I'm really sorry for this unfortunate mishap,&quot; Brooke said, &quot;but we never gave you any warranties to that effect.&quot; She then referred Alicia to a paragraph in smaller print at the very end of the Storage Agreement. This paragraph contains the following clause, which is commonly found in storage contracts:
<blockquote>
&quot;Eazee Storage Inc. gives no warranty as to temperature or any other matter pertaining to the maintenance of the storage space.
</blockquote>
Alicia has asked you to advise her. Specifically, she wants to know whether she can hope to recover any of the piano's lost value, her moving expenses, and/or her $800 from Eazee Storage Inc. or Radoo Loopoo. (She recently had a fight with him and would have no problems seeing him in court.)
<P>
You are to assume that Eazee Storage Inc. is fully bound by Brooke Broker's actions, and that it cannot be established that Brooke Broker or Eazee Storage Inc. acted with malice or fraud in this matter. Please ignore possible tort issues, as well as the issue of whether Eazee Storage Inc. can recover from Stuart Storer.
<P>
<b>b)</b> Assume the same facts as for Question l(a), except that the lack of pressure-control is instead due to the negligence of an employee of Stuart Storer, and that the Storage Agreement between Alicia and Eazee Storage Inc. contains the following clause:
<blockquote>
It is hereby expressly agreed that neither Eazee Storage Inc., nor its servants or agents, shall in any circumstances whatsoever be liable to the customer for any loss or damage arising from any act, neglect or default on its part while acting in the course of its performance of the present Agreement.
</blockquote>
Could Alicia recover damages from Stuart Storer's employees?
<P>
<b>50% 2.</b>
<blockquote>
If, whatever a man's real intention may be, he so conducts himself that a reasonable man would believe that he was assenting to the terms proposed by the other party, and that other party upon that belief enters into the contract with him, the man thus conducting himself would be equally bound as if he had intended to agree to the other party's terms.
</blockquote>
Please comment.
<p><br>
<hr>
