<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Criminal Law A and D<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Brudner</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>There are three questions of equal value.
<P>
<li>Discuss all issues reasonably raised by the facts even though your solution to one disposes of the case.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator</b>.
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<b>1.</b> Emma had an unhappy childhood. Her parents were divorced when she was five, and from then until she left home at eighteen, she lived with her mother, who was an alcoholic, and her mother's common-law spouse, who frequently struck and belittled her. While still living at home, she tried to commit suicide several times by cutting her wrists, and after each of these incidents, her &quot;stepfather&quot; would taunt her with such comments as &quot;Can't you even do that right?&quot;, &quot;You're hopeless at everything, aren't you,&quot; and the like.
<P>
Soon after leaving home, Emma moved in with Trevor. Trevor was jealous and possessive and frequently slapped and berated Emma for imagined infidelities. One day Trevor told Emma that he had grown tired of her, that he had a new girlfriend, and that he wanted her to leave. Emma meekly obliged, but a week later she returned, begging Trevor to take her back. He refused. Emma then began beating Trevor on the chest with her fists, telling him that she would commit suicide if he didn't take her back. At this Trevor (who knew of the previous incidents) laughed loudly and jeered: &quot;D'ya think ya can do the job right this time?&quot;
<P>
Emma left. Trevor's comment did not hit home instantly, but as she walked away, his words kept reverberating in her head and mingled with the memory of her stepfather's similar taunts. Other incidents in her past came back to her as well, and suddenly she saw her life for the first time as an endless cycle of affection-seeking, rejection, and humiliation. Very slowly anger welled up inside her until she could no longer contain it. She stopped, picked up a rock on the side of the road, and walked in a daze back to Trevor's flat. When he answered the doorbell, Emma struck him on the head with the rock with all the force she could muster. When Trevor collapsed, she struck him twice more on the face. Then she called the police and told them she had killed her &quot;father.&quot; &quot;I done it,&quot; she said, &quot;'cause he deserved to die.&quot;
<P>
Trevor, however, was not yet dead. He was taken unconscious to the hospital, where it was discovered that, besides the head injuries he had sustained, he had a pre-existing duodenal ulcer which, if not operated upon, might rupture and kill him. However, the doctors concluded that, because of Trevor's head injuries, it would be more dangerous to anaesthetize him for an operation on the ulcer than to wait until he regained consciousness. A few days later, Trevor, still unconscious, died of bleeding from the ulcer.
<P>
Emma was charged with murder. At her trial she raised the defence of provocation. A psychiatrist testifying on her behalf told the jury that Emma exhibited a &quot;depressive disorder&quot; characterized by deep feelings of ineptitude, helplessness, and low self-esteem but that she was not medically insane. He also testified that many women react to insult with a &quot;slow burn&quot; rather than by flying immediately off the handle, which, he said, is a response more typical of men. The trial judge, in instructing the jury on provocation, told them not to take into account Emma's depressive disorder in applying the standard of the ordinary person. He also told them that, to qualify for the defence, the accused must have struck &quot;at the instant of the provocation and before her passion had time to cool.&quot; Finally, he told them that if they were satisfied beyond a reasonable doubt that Emma intentionally caused Trevor's death and did not qualify for the defence of provocation, they should find her guilty of murder.
<P>
The jury came back with a verdict of guilty. The Crown then called a psychiatrist, who testified that Emma might not have understood what she was doing or that it was wrong and that her violent attack probably stemmed from deep-seated feelings of inadequacy. The judge then put the defence of mental disorder to the jury using nothing beyond the language of s. 16. The jury returned a verdict of not criminally responsible on account of mental disorder. Emma is now in a hospital for the insane. She will be there for the rest of her life or until doctors think it safe to release her.
<P>
Discuss the grounds of an appeal by Emma.
<P><br>
<b>2.</b> After acquiring the appropriate licence, J set up a laboratory to manufacture a line of pharmaceuticals. These drugs were on the list of controlled substances found in schedule G of the <cite>Food and Drugs Act</cite>. In the manufacturing process, J used chemicals which, when combined, produced a new substance akin to mescaline
but having many of the properties of phencyclidine. J asked a Nobel laureate chemistry professor at the University of Toronto what the substance was and was told it was mescaline. He also asked a lawyer who told him he could rely on the chemistry professor. So J produced what he thought was mescaline but without having obtained what he thought was the required licence for manufacturing it. He believed that mescaline was a restricted drug needing a
special licence to produce it, but in reality it is a controlled drug whose production was authorized by the licence J had already obtained.
<P>
J was charged with trafficking in phencyclidine. At his trial the judge ruled that the substance J was producing was mescaline and dismissed the charge. On appeal by the Crown, a judge of the Supreme Court of Ontario ruled that the substance was phencyclidine and substituted a conviction. Meanwhile H. after hearing of the trial judge's decision in J's case, also began producing the new substance (thinking it was mescaline), but without first obtaining
a licence to produce a controlled drug. He was charged with trafficking in phencyclidine and convicted by a judge who relied on the previous decision of the Supreme Court.
<P>
Mescaline is listed among the controlled drugs one is forbidden to manufacture without proper authority by s. 39 of the <cite>Food and Drugs Act</cite>. The penalty for a violation is a prison term not exceeding ten years. The penalty for an unauthorized manufacture of a restricted drug is the same. Phencyclidine is a narcotic whose manufacture and sale are regulated by the <cite>Narcotic Control Act</cite>. The penalty for trafficking in it is a maximum term of life imprisonment. &quot;Trafficking&quot; is defined in both Acts so as to include the manufacture of a listed substance without proper authority.
<P>
Discuss the penal liability of J and H.
<P><br>
<b>3.</b> Write a case comment on <cite>R. v. Hundel</cite> (casebook, p. 216). Explain the significance of the case as well as your agreement or disagreement with its reasoning and conclusions.
<p><br>
<hr>
