<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Criminal Law B<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Shaffer</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination - for example, your notes, the casebook, and the <cite>Criminal Code</cite> - <B>except</B> for books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of three questions. Everyone MUST answer Question ONE. You have a  <I>choice</I> of answering Question TWO or Question THREE. Make sure you do only two questions. Each question is worth 1/2 of your mark on the examination.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request additional booklets during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. <b>No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.</b>
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No  student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected be the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<h3>THIS QUESTION IS COMPULSORY:</h3>

<b>1.</b> One night Tom, Dick and Harry met for a game of poker. Tom and Dick were old friends, having met several years earlier while they were both serving sentences for aggravated assault. Harry was a recent acquaintance they'd met in a pub.
<P>
During the poker game, Tom, who was down on his luck, suggested that the three of them consider robbing a bank. Dick, who was short on cash, immediately agreed, but Harry wasn't so sure it was a good idea. Harry had already served a jail term for possession for the purpose of trafficking and didn't want to go back to jail. After some persuasion on the part of Tom and Dick, Harry said, &quot;Okay, I'll help you guys. But, ya gotta promise that no
one's gonna get hurt. I don't wanna go back to the slammer. No real weapons, Okay?&quot;
<P>
After talking it over for a bit, the trio agreed that they would not use real guns. They would, instead, use very realistic looking facsimiles which Dick knew how to procure.
<P>
On the day in question, the three met at Harry's house which was down the block from the bank. As planned, Dick had brought three fake guns with him. To the surprise of Dick and Harry, Tom revealed that he was carrying a real gun and that he was intending to carry it with him during the robbery. &quot;Come on guys, don't be stupid,&quot; Tom said. &quot;We need a real gun for our own protection. I won't use it unless I have to. Besides, I'll only fire warning shots. I'm not going to kill anyone.&quot;
<P>
&quot;No way!&quot; Harry said, &quot;you're not going in there with a gun. I'm not taking any chances. I'm not going through with this unless you leave the gun here.&quot;
<P>
&quot;I don't care what you do,&quot; Dick said. &quot;Just hurry up and decide, or else we'll blow our chance to do the job.&quot;
<P>
&quot;Okay, Harry,&quot; Tom said, &quot;you win. How 'bout if I take the gun but leave the bullets? See look, it's empty. I'll leave all the bullets here on Dick's coffee table .&quot;
<p>
&quot;Thanks, Tom,&quot; said Harry. &quot;Okay guys, let's go.&quot;
<P>
When they arrived at the bank, Harry gave the teller, Laura Secord, a note that read, &quot;This is a stick up. Give me all your money. We are armed and dangerous.&quot; Laura indicated that she would comply, but as she was collecting the cash, she pushed a hidden alarm button. The button triggered a silent alarm that was connected to the police station.
<P>
Unfortunately for Tom, Dick and Harry, two police cruisers were just leaving &quot;Donut Delite,&quot; a favourite police hang out that was located across the street from the bank. The officers responded immediately to the alarm and were inside the bank within seconds.
<p>
Officer Murphy spotted the suspects instantly. &quot;Drop your weapons and put your hands up,&quot; she shouted. Tom, Dick and Harry looked at each other in a panic. Then, Tom pulled a gun out of his jacket, grabbed Melvin Mirvish (a customer who just happened to be standing at the next teller) and yelled, &quot;NO! You guys drop YOUR weapons - or else this guy gets hurt.&quot; To show he meant business, Tom fired a warning shot into the air. Unbeknownst to either Dick or Harry, Tom had been carrying TWO real guns. He had only emptied the bullets from one of them.
<p>
Unperturbed, Officer Murphy drew her weapon and fired back. Unfortunately, the bullet struck Laura Secord in the chest. In the commotion that followed, Tom, Dick and Harry were subdued and arrested and Laura Secord was taken by ambulance to the hospital.
<p>
Laura's wound was serious but not life threatening. Unfortunately, while in hospital, Laura contracted an antibiotic resistant infection. After battling the infection for two months Laura died.
<p>
Tom, Dick, and Harry are all charged with first degree murder. Are they guilty?
<p><br>
<h3>CHOOSE ONE OF THE FOLLOWING TWO QUESTIONS:</h3>

<b>2.</b> In <cite>R. v. Creighton</cite>, the Supreme Court of Canada held that it was constitutionally permissible to impose criminal liability on the basis of objective fault. The court, however, split on how the objective standard should be constructed. Do you agree that it is right to hold people criminally liable on an objective standard or should our criminal justice system always require an element of subjective fault? Assuming that we continue to permit the <I>mens rea</I>for certain offenses to be based on an objective standard, how should the objective standard be constructed? In your view, do either of the judgments in <cite>Creighton</cite> set out the correct blue print for constructing the reasonable person?
<p>
<center><h3>OR</h3></center>

<b>3.</b> The problem of the criminal responsibility of the intoxicated offender has long plagued the legal system. With this in mind, comment on the Supreme Court's decision in <cite>R. v. Daviault</cite>. Does either the majority or the dissent chart the correct course for dealing with the drunken offender? What problems, if any, are there with the judgments? Is there a better way of handling the intoxicated offender? Finally, in light of the reasoning in <cite>Daviault</cite>, comment on the constitutional validity of s. 33.1 of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>, reproduced below.
<blockquote>
s. 33.1(1) It is not a defense to an offense referred to in subsection (3) that the accused, by reason of self-induced intoxication, lacked the general intent or the voluntariness required to commit the offense, where the accused has departed markedly from the standard of care as described in subsection (2). <a href="#note">*</a>
<p>
(2) For the purposes of this section, a person departs markedly from the standard of reasonable care generally recognized in Canadian society and is thereby criminally at fault where the person, while in a state of self-induced intoxication that renders that person unaware of, or incapable of consciously controlling, their behaviour, voluntarily or involuntarily interferes or threatens to interfere with the bodily integrity of another person.
<p>
(3) This section applies in respect of an offence under This Act or any other Act of Parliament that includes as an element an assault or any other interference or threat of interference by a person with the bodily integrity of another person.
</blockquote>
<a name="note">*</a> Please note that the use of the word &quot;general&quot; in this section differs from the Bill I handed out in class.
<p><br>
<hr>
