<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Criminal Law C<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Dickens</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<blockquote>
You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example notes, the casebook, and texts, except materials from the Law Library.
<P>
Answer <b>BOTH</b> of the following questions.
</blockquote>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<blockquote>
The questions are of equal weight.<br>
Question 1 carries 50% of the grade.<br>
Question 2 carries 50% of the grade.
<P>
At the conclusion of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and any coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE
WRITING TABLE.</b>
<P>
Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<P>
<h3>Question 1 (Counting for 50 percent of the total mark)</h3>

AB is a twenty-eight year-old member of a motor-cycle gang that traffics in drugs and has a recent history of related violence, including causing explosions of rival gang members' premises and equipment located in public places, causing serious injuries to members of the public. AB contracted HIV-infection from needle-sharing in injection drug use, and is in acute distress in the terminal phases of AIDS.
<P>
CD is a forty-eight year-old pharmacist employed in a pharmacy close to AB's gang headquarters. A month ago, five members of the gang entered the pharmacy, and demanded that CD supply and administer pain-killing drugs to AB, who lived in the gang's headquarters. CD knew that AB had already received prescriptions of pain-killing drugs at dosages close to a toxic level, and informed the gang-members that stronger pain-killing drugs could prove fatal to AB. The gang-members threatened CD that if he refused to help their colleague, the gang could not guarantee that CD's elderly parents or sixteen-year-old step-daughter would see 1997 in good health. Accompanied by the gang-members, CD took some drugs from the pharmacy and went to the gang's headquarters. He spoke in an upstairs bedroom to AB, who said that his pain was unbearable, and that he would prefer his life to end earlier in comfort rather than have to endure further suffering. CD said he did not need directly to administer the drugs he had brought to AB, since they were in capsules that AB could take unaided, and that he had brought enough for eight separate pain-relieving administrations. He informed AB that if he took too many, he might die, realizing that this was probably what AB intended. Before CD left the bedroom, AB seized and swallowed the equivalent of five doses.
<p>
AB died early the next day, and police traced the remaining pain-killing drugs to the pharmacy and to CD. CD has now been charged with the indictable offense under s.241(b) of the Criminal Code of aiding suicide.
<p>
Explain how you would defend CD.
<p>
<b>NOTE:</b> You have not been given precise wording of the indictment, and should not raise issues of vagueness.
<p><br>
<h3>Question 2 (Counting for 50 percent of the total mark)</h3>

EF was aged twenty-three two years ago when her grandfather died leaving her six acres of land on the outskirts of an expanding town in southern Ontario. The land had once been in agricultural use, but had not been farmed for several years. The grandfather's will expressed the wish that EF should develop the land to provide her with future income. EF was a student in a university commerce programme, and decided to use the land in the short term to finance graduate studies in business administration.
<p>
EF placed an advertisement in several newspapers that the land was available on a three year lease for a use that was permitted under local zoning regulations. GH and IJ offered to lease the land for recreational development, at a rent that seemed adequate to cover EF's fees and living expenses for a graduate programme of studies. The rent offered was, unknown to EF, six times the current rental value. A local lawyer drafted the lease, which included standard clauses against unlawful use of the land, insurance and indemnification of EF against legal liability arising from use, and EF's right of inspection, after due notice, to ensure compliance with local by-laws.
<p>
Ten months after granting the lease, EF visited the area and, one evening, when she went to the estate, she found a sizeable, noisy crowd gathered in a new, tavern-like structure built at a remote site on the leased land. She did not enter, she later explained to the local lawyer, for fear that the premises were being used for gaming or perhaps indecent entertainment. Two months ago, the police raided the building, and found that it was being used to stage cockfighting and betting. GH and IJ were not present, and are believed to have left Canada.
<p>
EF has now been charged with the summary offenses, contrary to s.447(1) of the Criminal Code, of keeping a cockpit on premises that she owns, and allowing a cockpit to be built or maintained there.
<p>
Explain how you would defend EF.
<p>
<b>NOTE:</b> You have not been given the language of the information, and should not address issues of vagueness.
<p><br>
<hr>
