<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Criminal Law<br>
Section 1<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Friedland</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>Students may use annotated copies of the Criminal Code, the Casebook, and their own notes.
<P>
<li>The test is composed of three questions. The value of each question is noted in the margin. The suggested time allocation is indicated in the margin.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name and the number of the booklet on <I>each </I>examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <I>first </I>booklet. If you require additional booklets during the examination, write the required information on each of the booklets at the time you
receive them. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</B>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<b>1. (45 marks approx. 80 minutes)</b> Jones and Smith were released from Kingston Penitentiary on the same day. They had both served long periods of time for violent crimes. As they were wandering around downtown Kingston they discussed the terrible treatment they had received by Guard Green while they were in the  penitentiary. Jones suggested that they &quot;get even&quot; by kidnapping and torturing Green. Smith said he wasn't interested in settling old scores, but reluctantly agreed to go along with the idea after Jones said that if he didn't he (Smith) might end up with a knife in his back.
<P>
They stole a car, waited for Green to leave the penitentiary, grabbed him and stuffed him in the trunk of the car. When they got to a deserted open field, Jones opened the trunk. Smith started lifting Green out of the trunk.
Green shouted: &quot;You'll never get away with this, you perverted jailbirds.&quot; Jones instinctively grabbed the tire iron and struck Green violently over the head with it. They left, thinking Green was dead. Green was found still alive the next day by a farmer and was taken to the Kingston Hospital. Green died in the recovery room following a brain operation when one of the monitors indicating a deteriorating, but correctible, condition failed to work properly.
<P>
Jones and Smith had taken Guard Green's gun and decided to rob a branch of the Bank of Nova Scotia. First they bought and consumed together a 26 ounce bottle of whisky and a case of beer (24 bottles). The branch was closed
when they arrived and the teller refused to open the door. They then went to a branch of Canada Trust which was still open. They both put on masks. Jones had the gun and said: &quot;This is a stick up.&quot; When a teller appeared to press an alarm, Jones shot and killed him. Jones and Smith fled.
<P>
The police later found Smith in the back of a laneway near the Trust Company. He was babbling incomprehensibly. They took him to the Kingston Mental Health Centre for a mental examination. Smith told the psychiatrist in charge the whole story. The psychiatrist passed this information on to the police, indicating that in his view Smith was, and is, a certifiably insane schizophrenic. The police then arrested Smith and later found and arrested Jones. While arresting Jones they find the gun that killed the teller between two mattresses. Jones says to the police, before any
warning can be given: &quot;It's obvious I shot the teller.&quot; Apparently the identification evidence against Jones and Smith at the Trust Company is weak. Both are charged with first degree murder for both deaths. Jones and Smith are denied bail and lodged in cells separated by a cell occupied by an undercover police officer. Jones is heard by the officer to say: &quot;If we stick together, they won't be able to pin anything on us.&quot;
<P>
You are an articling student with the Kingston Crown attorney assigned to the case. Smith's lawyer has offered to plead guilty to manslaughter for the murder at Canada Trust if all other charges are dropped. Jones' lawyer has offered to plead guilty to manslaughter for both killings if all other charges are dropped. Write a memo advising whether the Crown should accept the proposals.
<P><br>
<b>2. (30 marks approx. 55 minutes)</b> Assume that the Federal Government has just passed the &quot;Cattle
Preservation Act&quot; in response to fears about mad cow disease. One of its provisions states that &quot;No person shall import cattle or cattle products from the United Kingdom or any country added by regulation without a permit from the Minister of Agriculture.&quot; The offence is punishable by summary conviction and a person is liable to 6 months imprisonment and/or a fine of $10,000. Another section states that &quot;lack of knowledge that cattle products are involved is no defence to a charge under the Act.&quot;
<P>
Eatons Ltd. brought in a number of cattle products from the U.K. without a permit and the persons who placed the order and Eatons have been charged with a number of offences under the Act.
<P>
The manager of the cosmetics section for the Toronto area purchased face cream from Scotland which contained animal products. He says he had no idea that they contained animal products and didn't think to ask.
<P>
The manager of the food section for Quebec imported some frozen beef from Scotland. He had phoned Agriculture Canada and had been told by the official he happened to speak to that frozen products are not included in the ban. This was wrong. Frozen products are clearly included.
<P>
The manager of the Vancouver canned goods department had imported cans of beef stew from England. He had called one of the Eatons' company lawyers who advised him that canned goods were excluded from the ban. Again, this was wrong. Canned goods are included.
<P>
The manager of the Calgary store brought in beef products from Malta, which had been added to the list by regulation. The regulation had been published in the Canada Gazette, but because of a postal strike the Canada Gazette had not yet been mailed out.
<P>
The Cattle Preservation Act gives agricultural of finials wide powers of inspection. It states: &quot;An inspector can enter any place of business during regular hours and seize any products that the inspector suspects may have been obtained in violation of the Act.&quot; This is how all four alleged violations were uncovered.
<P>
Eatons Ltd. and the four managers have been charged with violating the Act. You are a young lawyer in the Eatons legal department. Prepare a brief memo on the liability of Eatons and the four managers under the Act.
<P><br>
<b>3. (25 marks approx. 45 minutes)</b> You are a student just completing first year law school and have been given a summer position with Allan Rock, the Minister of Justice. The Minister has been asked to address the Annual Meeting of the Canadian Bar Association in August on &quot;New Directions in Criminal Justice&quot; and has asked you to prepare brief notes on <b>each</b> of the following three topics:
<blockquote>
(A) Codification of the Criminal Law: Where is it going?;<br>
(B) First Degree Murder: Some New Ideas?; and<br>
(C) Simplifying the Classification of Offences.
</blockquote>
Please prepare a draft for discussion purposes with the Minister. You should include ideas that <b>you</b> think he should consider adopting.
<P><br>
A <b>bonus mark</b> will be given to you if you can identify two of the following characters:
<blockquote>
(A) Pierre Couchard;<br>
(B) Blanche Burns; and<br>
(C) Ruby Collins.
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<hr>
