<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Criminal Law<br>
Section II
April 1996<br>
Professor Mewett</h2></center>
<h3>Instructions:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes. the casebook, the Code and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of four questions, which are of equal value.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request additional booklets during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the conclusion of the examination you will be asked to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your books and coats and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD
BE LEFT ON THE WRIT NG TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty. 
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>1.</h3>
Section 740 of the Code states:
<blockquote>
An accused who is bound by a probation order and who wilfully fails or refuses to comply with that order is guilty of an offense.....
</blockquote>
Last year, Thomas Jefferson, was convicted of theft under $6,000 and was put on probation. One condition of the probation order was that he &quot;keep the peace and refrain from the commission of any criminal offence&quot;.
<P>
Two months ago, Jefferson was convicted of the sexual assault of a thirteen year old girl whom he had met at a party. At his trial, the Crown conceded that the girl had consented to the sexual activity in question and Jefferson's defence was that he thought she was over fourteen years of age. In convicting him, the trial judge stated:
<blockquote>
I am not saying that I believe the accused when he says that he thought the victim was over fourteen, but his evidence does lead me to have a reasonable doubt about it. Unfortunately for him, this makes no difference, since, whether he believed it or not, he fell far short of taking all reasonable steps to ascertain her true age as is required under S. 150.1(4) -- he merely accepted her word for it even though she was obviously very young and some
further enquiry would have been entirely reasonable. The fact that the accused was unaware of this requirement, is neither here nor there. I therefore convict the accused, but in the circumstances a fine of $500 will be sufficient.
</blockquote>
Jefferson has now been charged with wilfully breaching the probation
order. Is he guilty?
<P><br>
<h3>2.</h3>
Mrs. Rosemary Bomba, a petite woman of 45, was sitting in a booth at the Xippo Dunkin Donut one day last winter having some coffee when she heard two men (since identified as John and Rob) in the booth next to her talking. She was concealed from their view and heard one say to the other, &quot;It's agreed then. He has to be liquidated. How are we going to do it?&quot; and the other one reply, &quot;He keeps his car in the driveway. It'd be easy enough to go over tomorrow night and cut the brake cable and then when he goes round Satan's Corner, wham, over the cliff
he goes&quot;. &quot;Fine,&quot; replied the first one. &quot;What's the address?&quot; To her amazement, Mrs. Bomba heard the reply, &quot;1745 Republic Crescent&quot; which was her address and she realized that they had been talking about her husband.
<P>
Now it so happened that Mrs. Bomba had been thinking for some time about the million dollar insurance policy on her husband's life and had been wondering how to get her hands on it, so she decided to say nothing, waited until the men had left and then went home. She said nothing to her husband when he came back from work and, indeed, unknown to her husband watched from an upstairs window and saw John and Rob come up the driveway that night and tamper with her husband's car.
<P>
Next morning, to her distress, at 9 am., when she asked Mr. Bomba why he hadn't left for work by then, he replied that he had told Paul Freen, their next door neighbour that he could borrow his car for the day and that he wouldn't be going to work that day. &quot;In fact&quot;, said Mr. Bomba, &quot;He'll be over in half an hour&quot;. Mrs. Bomba, fearing more from exposure than worrying about Freen, decided to say nothing, and, sure enough, Freen got
into the car, drove away, and, wham, over the cliff at Satan's Corner he went.
<P>
Don't ask how, but all these facts are proved by the Crown. In a separate trial, John and Rob have been convicted of the first degree murder of Freen.
<P>
Mrs. Bomba is now charged with the first degree murder of Freen also. Is she guilty? Could she have been charged with anything else?
<P><br>
<h3>3.</h3>
It is now accepted by most, if not all, judges that criminal negligence offences are based upon an objective standard, but there is no agreement on what that objective standard consists of nor how to define it. Why is there this disagreement? What are the points of contention and what do you think the standard should be?
<P><br>
<h3>4.</h3>
Section 33.1 now reads:
<blockquote>
(1) It is not a defense to an offence referred to in subsection (3) that the accused, by reason of selfinduced intoxication, lacked the general intent or the voluntariness required to commit the offence, where the accused has departed markedly from the standard of care as described in subsection (2).
<P>
(2) For the purposes of this section, a person departs markedly from the standard of reasonable care generally recognized in Canadian society and is thereby criminally at fault where the person, while in a state of self-induced intoxication that renders the person unaware of, or incapable of consciously controlling, their behaviour, voluntarily or involuntarily interferes or threatens to interfere with the bodily integrity of another person.
<P>
(3) This section applies in respect of an offence under this Act or any other Act of Parliament that includes as an element an assault or any other interference or threat of interference by a person with the bodily integrity of another person.
</blockquote>
Last summer, Jason Picard, an eighteen year old youth, won $10,000 in Lotto 649 and invited several of his friends over to celebrate. Jason has led a sheltered life and his only previous experience with alcohol has been one glass of champagne at his parents' With wedding anniversary celebration. That night he drank more than he had ever had before. Most of the guests left at midnight, but Lisa Fulbright, a seventeen year old friend of his, stayed behind
to help clear up. Moments later, Jason tried to rape her. He says (and his defence is well supported by medical evidence) that he was blind drunk at the time and completely unconscious of anything he was doing and remembers nothing until he woke up in the police station next morning.
<P>
He is now charged with the sexual assault of Lisa. You are his defence counsel. What submissions would you make in his defence? 
<p><br>
