<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Debt Financing and Restructuring<br>
April 1996<br>
Mr. Murphy</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<blockquote>
This is a 24 hour take home exam. It must be picked up between 9:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. or 2:30 p.m. to 4:30 p.m. Monday to Thursday from April 11th to April 25th, 1996. You may refer only to the materials for the course (the casebooks and the documents distributed in class) and your class notes. The purpose of the take home format is <b>not</b> to encourage lengthy responses but to give you an opportunity to provide organized, thoughtful and succinct analyses of the issues raised in each question.
<P>
Your responses to both questions 1 and 2 should not in aggregate exceed 3,000 words.
<P>
Your answers to Questions 1 and 2 are each worth 1/2 of your grade.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<h3>QUESTION 1</h3>

With reference to the law and economics theory of agency, please identify and analyze different ways in which creditors and borrowers in their negotiations with one another in the marketplace, and courts (when litigation arises), have attempted to deal with the inherent conflicts between shareholders, directors/firm managers and creditors (secured and unsecured) of a corporation.
<P>
Explain how, in your view, each of those entities have, or have not, contributed to the rational control of those conflicts.
<P><br>
<h3>QUESTION 2</h3>

To what extent, if at all, in your view do the federal statutory regimes for corporate debt reorganization in Canada (the <cite>Companies Creditors Arrangement Act</cite> and the <cite>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</cite>) adequately protect the respective interests of secured creditors, unsecured creditors and shareholders of an insolvent
corporation (i.e. with assets, the realizable value of which are insufficient to repay in full the investments of each of those stakeholders). To the extent that you feel there are any general inadequacies in those regimes, please explain how you think those inadequacies could be solved.
<p><br>
<hr>
