<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Economic Integration: Lessons From The European Community<br>
April 1996<br>
S. Walker</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<P>
<li>The exam is divided into three parts: A, B and C. Students must answer <b>one</b> question from <b>each</b> part. Accordingly, it is suggested that you allocate one hour for each question.<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <B>each</B> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <B>first</B> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<h3>Part A - EC Legal Order</h3>
<b>Answer one of the following questions:</b>
<ol>
<li>&quot;The EC legal order has promoted the integration of the European Community by ensuring the consistent application of EC law across the Member States.&quot; Discuss the validity of this statement with reference to both the caselaw of the European Court of Justice and the EC Treaty.
<P>
<li>Explain why the doctrine of direct effect developed, as well as the conditions and limitations for applying this doctrine through reference to EC jurisprudence. How has the European Court of Justice been able to overcome some of these conditions and limitations?
</ol><P>
<h3>Part B - Free Movement of Goods</h3>
<b>Answer the following question:</b>
<ol>
<li>(a) Your client, &Eacute;lan, is a French manufacturer and distributor who is in the business of selling &Eacute;lan beauty and cosmetic products door to door. &Eacute;lan products are not available in shops; indeed, the personalized attention that door to door selling brings is seen as part of the &quot;cachet&quot; or special characteristic of the &Eacute;lan line of products. &Eacute;lan has been selling its products throughout the European Union. Recently, the Italian government has passed legislation that bans door to door selling, because it is concerned with undue pressure that may be brought to bear on consumers when the seller is in their homes. The Italian Cosmetics and Perfume Association, a trade association of major cosmetic dealers, lobbied in favour of this change as it will not affect its members who do not sell door to door. &Eacute;lan has complained to the European Commission that the new Italian law violates the principle of free movement of goods.
<P>
With reference to the case law of the European Court of Justice, advise &Eacute;lan on whether the European Commission would succeed in challenging the Italian law under Article 30.
<P>
(b) The Spanish Government has also introduced new legislation to regulate animal by-products in cosmetics, particularly handcreams and lotions. It claims that certain types of boviline, a by-product of cows, may be harmful to the health of its consumers, and therefore has established a licensing procedure whereby only particular types of boviline will be allowed. Based on your knowledge of EC caselaw, what conditions would the Spanish Government's boviline licensing procedure have to meet under Article 30?
</ol>
<h3>Part C - EC Competition Law</h3>
<b>Answer one of the following questions:</b>
<ol>
<li>The European Commission has hired you as outside legal counsel. Compex, a German manufacturer of computer software, has recently decided to increase its sales into the rest of the European Union. Its software has never penetrated the rest of the EU because governments of other Member States have in the past promoted their own computer software firms through various means of dubious legality under EC law (which you do not have to address). Such promotion has now ceased but Compex faces stiff competition from finds in other EU Member States as a result.
<blockquote>
(a) Compex has entered into distribution agreements with resellers in other Member States which require the resellers to buy all of their requirements only from Compex. An exclusive Compex distributor has been appointed
for each Member State. Compex has told the Commission that each distributor will be required to invest heavily in a highly trained sales force and in promotion. Each distribution agreement prohibits exports from the European Union and prohibits each distributor from actively seeking markets in other Member States but, subject to paragraph (b), permits distributors to respond to orders from customers from other Member States.
<P>
 (b) A new clause has been inserted into Compex's agreement with its German distributors which permits exports from Germany to other Member States only after the software has been on the German market for at least two years.
Since most software becomes obsolete within this period, this clause acts as an effective export ban. Compex has stated that this clause is necessary because Compex software prices in Germany are much lower (where the product
is well known) than what will be charged by distributors in other Member States who will have to recoup the costs of training and promotion.
</blockquote>
Advise the European Commission on the legality of the distribution agreements described in (a) and (b) under Article 85.
<P>
<li>Cacao, a Dutch manufacturer of chocolate developed a new diet chocolate (&quot;Chocolite&quot;) which has taken the Netherlands by storm. The recipe is protected under the Netherlands's intellectual property laws. In the trade, Cacao is said to have &quot;recipe rights&quot; to the diet chocolate; this right means that Cacao has the exclusive right to manufacture and sell this chocolate in the Netherlands. Chocolite now has approximately 60% of diet chocolate sales in the Netherlands and a much lower share (35%) in the European Union (&quot;EU&quot;) as a whole. Among consumers of all types of chocolate, Chocolite has a Dutch market share of approximately 25 % and an EU market share of less than 5 % .
<P>
In order to encourage sales of Chocolite across the EU, Cacao has engaged in the practice of providing discounts at the end of the year to customers who buy a range of chocolate products from it, including Chocolite. Distributors who do not buy all or a large proportion of their chocolate requirements from Cacao do not receive the discount or rebate at the end of the year. In addition, Cacao has just introduced a clause whereby it has the option to meet a lower price offered to its distributor or to release the customer to buy from another manufacturer.
<P>
Recently, Sweet Tooth, a UK chocolate manufacturer, has developed a diet chocolate that has virtually the same recipe as Chocolite. Sweet Tooth wishes to export the chocolate into the other Member States, but has been advised by Cacao's solicitors that Cacao will invoke its &quot;recipe rights&quot; to keep Sweet Tooth's diet chocolate out of the market.
<P>
You have been retained by Cacao to provide it with legal advice on the legality of its actions under Article 86 of the EC Treaty. What do you advise?
</ol>
<p><br>
<hr>
