<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Evidence<br>
Standard Sit-Down Examination<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Mewett</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>There are FOUR questions of equal value.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive
it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of the examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet and insert all the booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty. 
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<h3>1.</h3>

James DeWitt, aged 28, is charged with the first degree murder of Charles Link, aged 6. Link had been sexually assaulted and strangled. DeWitt's defence is simply that he did not do it and the Crown evidence against him is mostly circumstantial. DeWitt has a mental age of fourteen and for that reason, he was remanded for psychiatric examination by Dr. Pauling who, however, reported that he was fit to stand trial. DeWitt's lawyer also arranged for him to be examined by Dr. Linus who also reported that DeWitt was fit to stand trial. No issue as to this arises.
<P>
However, Dr. Pauling's report states, in part:
<blockquote>
DeWitt exhibits clear symptoms of a sadistic, homosexual paedophile. In my opinion, he is quite capable of committing the murder with which he is charged and is extremely dangerous. I have no doubt at all that he is responsible for Link's death.
</blockquote>
On the other hand, Dr. Linus' report states, in part:
<blockquote>
In my opinion, DeWitt is sexually immature, but, apart from that, exhibits no abnormal tendencies. I consider he is quite incapable of committing the murder with which he is charged but is, on the contrary, a gentle and timid individual who represents no danger to society.
</blockquote>
DeWitt does have two previous convictions, neither involving violence -- one for theft under $5,000 and one for break and enter with intent to commit theft.
<P>
DeWitt testified, and in response to a question from his counsel as to whether he killed Link, stated:
<blockquote>
I did not. I wouldn't do such a thing. I've never harmed anyone in my life.
</blockquote>
Would you permit the Crown, in the first instance, to call Dr. Pauling as a witness for the prosecution to testify in accordance with his report, or any part of it? Would you permit the defense, in the first instance, to call Dr. Linus to testify in accordance with his report or any part of it? If either is permitted, would you permit the other to call his witness in rebuttal? Given DeWitt's answer above, does this make any difference? Would you permit the Crown to introduce evidence of DeWitt's prior convictions and, if so, for what purpose?
<P><br>
<h3>2.</h3>

The accused, Henry Sweet, aged 29, is on trial for the first degree murder of Paul Sour, aged 27, who had been found shot to death in the stairwell of his apartment building last summer. The case against Sweet is based largely on circumstantial evidence, and it is the theory of the Crown that the killing involved a drug deal that had gone wrong. Sweet denied, and so testified, that he had anything to do with the killing, and to make the defence more believable, sought to pin the blame on Patrick Fee. In support of this, he called Fee's wife. She had been interviewed by the police shortly after the body had been found, and had stated to them:
<blockquote>
Patrick didn't come home until late last night. I was worried in case he'd done anything foolish. He told me just before he went out that he was going to get that bastard Sour for stiffing him on their last drug deal, but he told me when he came home that he'd just gone to a movie to cool down.
</blockquote>
She repeated this statement in a videorecording made at the police station, after promising that what she was about to say was the truth. The police thereupon questioned Fee who told them that he had been to see &quot;The Monster Leeches of Planet Phylo&quot; playing at the Cactus Cinema on the night in question, but upon investigation, the police found out that that movie was not playing the night Fee had said he'd seen it, but the week before. However,
after further investigation, the police were satisfied that Fee was not responsible for the killing, after he explained his lie by telling them that he thought they might be after him for a break and enter that had occurred the same night as the killing. In any case, there was more circumstantial evidence against Sweet than against Fee, so the police proceeded against Fee.
<P>
When she was called as a witness for the defense, Fee's wife was asked what Fee had said to her just before she went out. First of all, she refused to answer on the ground of marital privilege, but when ordered to answer by the trial judge, replied: 
<blockquote>
He said that he was going to a movie. He didn't say which one.
</blockquote>
(a) Should her claim of marital privilege have been upheld?
<P>
(b) Assuming the trial judge was right, what, if anything, can Sweet now do about her unhelpful reply?
<P>
(c) Can the defence in any way introduce in evidence the lie that Fee told the police and to what end?
<P><br>
<h3>3.</h3>

Last summer a fire occurred at the dry-cleaning establishment of Charles Hanley and the fire marshall's office, convinced that the fire had been deliberately set, called in the police. As a result of their investigations, the police came to the conclusion that Charles Hanley had committed arson in order to obtain the insurance on the building, but Hanley had a cast-iron alibi for the night in question and it was clear that he could not have set the fire himself. They sought and obtained a perfectly valid wire-tap authorization to tap Hanley's phone and in the course of so doing, heard one, Larry Finbein, call Hanley as follows: 
<P>
L.F. Well, I done it. What about my ten grand.<br>
C.H. Sure. I've got it here. You can have it next time I see you.<br>
L.F. O.K. Let's meet, usual place, Monday at six.<br>
C.H. O.K.
<P>
Having traced the call, the police had no difficulty picking up Finbein, and took him down to the station. He asked to contact a lawyer, but the police refused until he had answered their questions. After a lengthy interrogation, Finbein finally made, and signed, the following statement:
<P>
<I>I admit that I torched Hanley's dry-cleaning shop. Hanley had nothing to do with it. I did it because he wouldn't pay the protection money I was demanding -- ten thousand dollars in fact. I told him that next time, I'd kill him.</I>
<P>
He was then formally charged with arson and allowed to contact a lawyer. After consulting with his lawyer, Finbein then made a second statement to the police, which he also signed, as follows:
<P>
<I>The first statement I made was untrue. Hanley promised to pay me ten grand if I would torch his business and take full responsibility if the cops found out, but now that I've spoken to my lawyer, I realize that there is no reason why I should carry the can when it was all his idea.</I>
<P>
As a result of this second statement, the police arrested Hanley and charged him with arson. Hanley and Finbein are now jointly on trial. The Crown, realizing that Finbein's statements are inadmissible against him because of the Charter violation, makes no attempt to introduce them, relying instead on various other pieces of evidence the police have collected against the two. Finbein testifies in his own defense and the substance of his testimony is in accordance with his second statement, adding, however that he only went along with it because Hanley was blackmailing him over some other offences he had committed.
<P>
Hanley's counsel (whose defence is going to be along the lines of Finbein's first statement to the police) wishes to cross-examine Finbein on the first statement he made to the police for the truth of it. Crown counsel argues that it is only admissible to show a prior inconsistency. Finbein's counsel objects to its use under any circumstances.
<P>
As the trial judge, how would you rule?
<P><br>
<h3>4.</h3>

You are defence counsel in a sexual assault charge on a 22 year old woman. The Crown, being unaware of the fact, has not told you that she underwent rape trauma therapy after the event, but one of the victim's friends has told you that the victim told her that she had told the therapist during one of the sessions that she may have encouraged the accused into thinking that she was consenting. How do you go about getting hold of the records of the therapy sessions and could you use them at all, and for what purpose even if you did get hold of them?
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
Please send comments and suggestions to <a href="mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</a><p>
Created on JUL-22-96 by Anne Johnston.
</address>
