<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Evidence<br>
Take-Home Fact Examination<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Mewett</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>There are FOUR questions of equal value. All are based on the fact situation previously distributed to which reference should be made.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of the examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all the booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty. 
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>1.</h3>

The Crown wishes to introduce in evidence the torn panties found in Mary's car (page 10, lines 12 - 14), to which both defence counsel object. Would you admit this evidence?
<P><br>
<h3>2.</h3>

Would you permit Henry to testify for the defence (page 15, line 22 - page 16, line 4)? Why? To what extent?
<P><br>
<h3>3.</h3>

Assuming that Dubois is compelled to testify (page 18, line 8) and testifies that the only thing Beaver said when he came home was, &quot;Gee, I'm tired -- time for bed&quot;, (line 10), can the Crown in any way get in the statement he originally made (page 7, lines 19 - 21) to the effect that Beaver had said that he and George had been having some fun?
<P><br>
<h3>4.</h3>

Is any of Dr. Frank's evidence admissible (page 16, line 19 -- page 20, line 10)?
<p><br>
<hr>
