<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Family Law<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Shaffer</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination - for example, your notes and casebook - <B>except</B>for books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of THREE questions. Question ONE is mandatory. Question TWO offers choice of two topics: do only one. Question THREE also offers a choice of two topics: again, do only one. <B>THE QUESTIONS ARE WEIGHTED DIFFERENTLY</b>. Question One is worth <b>50%</b> of the exam. Questions Two and Three are each worth <b>25%</b>. You should allocate sour time accordingly.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request additional booklets during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. <B>No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.</b>
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination Answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<b>1.</b> A long time bachelor, Charles met Diana in 1980. Diana was a 19 year old kindergarten teacher; Charles was an &quot;older&quot; man of independent means. After a whirlwind courtship, the two decided to wed. They were married in a fairy-tale like ceremony in July, 1981.
<P>
Before the wedding, Charles and Diana each received gifts from family, friends and other well wishers. Diana received a red sports car from her family worth $25,000. From his family, Charles received two thoroughbred horses (he was very fond of thoroughbreds). The horses were each worth $100,000. Charles' family gave Diana various items of jewellery - including a sparkly tiara - that had been in the family for centuries. This was a very generous gift, the jewellery being valued at $100,000. For their part, Diana's family gave Charles a painting of one of their esteemed ancestors, worth $50,000.
<P>
In addition to these gifts, Charles and Diana each brought other property into the marriage. Diana had a rather extensive wardrobe, valued at $15,000. She also had some antique silver and crystal, worth $50,000.
<P>
Charles' pre-marriage wealth consisted largely of real estate and investments. He had two posh homes - one in the country and one in the city - both impeccably furnished. On the date of marriage, the country home was worth $200,000 and the city home, $300,000. The furniture in the city home was worth $100,000 and that in the country home, worth $50,000. His investments amounted to $500,000.
<P>
During the marriage, Charles and Diana each acquired more property. When Diana gave birth to their first son a year after the marriage, Charles gave her a ring worth $60,000. He also gave her a necklace, worth $40,000, when she gave birth to their second son a few years later. Diana also received a substantial inheritance from her great-uncle. This included a rather lavish country home in the Muskokas worth $500,000, furnishings worth $100,000, and artwork worth $100,000. Finally, throughout the marriage, Diana indulged her passion for personal adornments and acquired an even more extensive wardrobe.
<P>
For his part, Charles acquired more real estate and investments during the marriage. He also received an inheritance from his great-uncle Phillip who left him a country estate worth $500,000 in Collingwood. As Charles and Diana already had two country homes, Charles rented out the estate for $60,000 a year for five years (i.e. a total of $300,000). He deposited this money in a bank account in his name which he labelled the &quot;Collingwood Account&quot;.
<p>
Unfortunately, Charles and Diana were not destined for wedded bliss. As it turned out, Charles and Diana actually had very little in common. Charles, for example, had a passion for polo and for classical architecture. Diana enjoyed popular music, aerobics and expensive clothing. In addition, it turned out that for most of the marriage Charles had been yearning for his pre-marriage sweet heart, Crumelda. To Diana's utter dismay, it also turned out that Charles had been having an extra-marital affair with Crumelda for some time.
<p>
As Diana's unhappiness over Charles' infatuation with Crumelda grew, Charles and Diana began to live increasingly separate lives. By 1990 the two had stopped having meals together, occupied separate bedrooms and no longer had sexual relations with each other. They had also stopped socializing together except for special family occasions. What little communication there was between them was strained, even when it came to matters concerning their children. Finally, in 1994, Diana insisted that Charles move out.
<p>
Diana has now come to you for advice concerning the breakdown of her marriage. At the moment, she does not want your advice on spousal support or child support. Instead, she is primarily concerned about the kind of property settlement she can expect from Charles and about any other matter that might be relevant to her divorce. Diana has provided you with the following financial and personal information regarding her relationship with Charles. <B>She is not sure that all this information is relevant, nor that she has given you all the information you will require.</B>
<p>
<b>Personal Information:</b>
<ol>
<li>Charles' relationship with Crumelda had a profound affect on Diana. She became desperately unhappy to the point of becoming clinically depressed. She also developed an eating disorder which compromised her physical health. Charles knew that his attention to Crumelda harmed Diana both physically and emotionally. Diana believes that Charles delighted in her suffering and that he continued his relationship with Crumelda to spite her.
<p>
<li>Charles feels that Diana did not contribute much to the marriage and that she squandered too much of his money on clothes. He feels that he does not owe Diana anything because Diana was able to acquire far more property during the marriage than she would have been able to on her own.
<p>
<li>Diana agrees that she spent a lot of money on clothing, but claims that she contributed emotionally to the marriage. She notes that neither she nor Charles had to do a lot of work during the marriage since they employed hired help.
</ol>
<b>Financial Information
<p>
Diana's Property</b>
<ol>
<li>Diana still has most, but not all, of the property she owned on the date of marriage. She still has the jewellery she received as an engagement gift which was worth $150,000 in 1994 and is worth $160,000 now. She also has the antique silver and crystal, which were worth $60,000 in 1994 and are worth $65,000 now. She sold the red sports car during the marriage for $15,000 and used the proceeds to buy a black sports car. That car was worth $20,000 in 1994 and is worth $15,000 now. Finally, Diana no longer has any of the clothing she brought into the marriage. She doesn't remember what she did with it but she thinks she gave most of it to Goodwill.
<p>
<li>When she first learned of Charles' affair with Crumelda, Diana decided she could not stand to keep the jewellery Charles gave her. She sold the necklace and the ring for a total of $120,000. She invested the proceeds in bonds which were worth $170,000 in 1994 and are worth $200,000 now.
<p>
<li>Diana retained the lavish country home in the Muskokas. As it was a lovely spot to spend the summer, Charles and Diana spent most of their summers there with their children during the early years of their marriage. When the marriage began to founder, Charles began spending less time at the Muskoka home and more time at his home in Collingwood. By 1994 Charles had stopped coming to the Muskoka home entirely. Diana continues to take the children to the Muskoka home for most of the summer.
<p>
<li>The Muskoka home was worth $600,000 in 1994. Due to an unusual real estate boom in the area, the home has increased dramatically in value and is now worth $1,000,000.
<p>
<li>While Diana kept the Muskoka home, she was not fond of her great-uncle's taste in furniture. She sold the furniture shortly after she inherited it for $100,000. She used this money to buy entirely new furnishings. These have since depreciated in value as a result of the wear and tear inflicted by Diana's two young boys. The furniture was worth $70,000 in 1994 and is worth $50,000 now.
<p>
<li>Diana was also less than thrilled with her great-uncle's taste in art. She immediately sold the artwork she'd inherited for $100,000. She used this money to open up bank accounts for the two boys and deposited $50,000 in each account. By 1994 each account contained $75,000; there is now $80,000 in each account.
<p>
<li>Diana's wardrobe was valued at $30,000 in 1994. As she now has fewer clothes, her wardrobe is valued at $20,000.
</ol>
<b>Charles' Property</b>
<ol>
<li>Like Diana, Charles has also retained some of the property he owned before the marriage. He still has the painting of Diana's esteemed ancestor. It was worth $70,000 in 1994 and is worth $75,000 now. Charles also retained the city home and continued to live in it until Diana asked him to leave in 1994. The city home was worth $400,000 in 1994 and is worth the same now. The furniture in the home was worth $80,000 in 1994 and is worth $75,000 now. Finally, Charles also retained his pre-marriage investments which have proven very profitable. They were worth $1,000,000 in 1994 and are worth $1,200,000 now.
<p>
<li>Two years after the marriage, Charles sold the country home he had brought into the marriage for $225,000. He used the proceeds to buy a new country home which he and his family could use for ski holidays in the winter. Charles, Diana and the boys continued to spend time there until 1994 (although after 1990 Charles and Diana often went to the house at different times). The home was worth $250,000 in 1994 and is worth $260,000 now. The furniture in the new country home was worth $60,000 in 1994 and is worth $50,000 now.
<p>
<li>The thoroughbred horses Charles brought into the marriage have, unfortunately, long since been put out to pasture.
<p>
<li>The country house inherited from Great-Uncle Phillip was worth $800,000 in 1994 and is worth roughly the same now. After renting out the house for five years, Charles decided to evict his tenants and to spend time at the house himself. From 1990 on, Charles would frequently retreat to his Collingwood house when Diana and the children went to Diana's house in the Muskokas. Diana never visited the Collingwood house and the children visited only rarely.
<p>
<li>The &quot;Collingwood Account&quot; contained $340,000 in 1994. Now it contains $350,000.
</ol>
Prepare an opinion for Diana explaining how the property issues between herself and Charles would be resolved under the <cite>Family Law Act</cite>. As Diana is not a mathematical whiz, she wants you to explain clearly how the NFP calculation would be done. She does, however, want some sense of the numbers, so she would like you to attempt to do the calculation. Your opinion should also include discussion of other issues relevant to Diana's divorce, EXCEPT for spousal support and child support.
<p>
If you feel that Diana has not provided you with sufficient information about her marriage or her finances, you are free to make assumptions as long as you indicate where you are doing so.
<p><br>
<h3>2. CHOOSE <U>ONE</U> OF THE FOLLOWING QUESTIONS:</h3>

(a) In <cite>Moge v. Moge</cite>, the Supreme Court of Canada appears to have endorsed a modified compensatory model of spousal support. Drawing upon your materials and classroom discussion, comment on this model of spousal support. What are the strengths of the approach? What are its weaknesses or limitations? In answering this question, you will want to compare the compensatory approach with other philosophies of spousal support. You might also wish to consider whether there are other ways of thinking about the spousal support obligation.
<p>
<center><h3>OR</h3></center>

(b) Comment on the decision in <cite>Leek v. Lightfoot</cite>. Is the decision a good one? Is it consistent with the philosophy of spousal support articulated in <cite>Moge v. Moge</cite>?
<p><br>
<h3>3. CHOOSE <U>ONE</U> OF THE FOLLOWING QUESTIONS:</h3>

a) For some time, the Ontario Government has been considering whether it should amend the <cite>Family Law Act</cite>. The government has hired you as a consultant. They want your opinion concerning which aspects of the Act should be changed and which should be retained. They have given you free reign to consider everything in the Act - including, the rules regarding property division and the principles for granting spousal support. They also want your opinion on whether there are any areas which the Act does not address but which a new (and improved) family law statute would cover.
<p>
<center><h3>OR</h3></center>

b) Does matrimonial fault have a place in contemporary family law? If so, how should fault matter? To answer this question, you will want to provide a brief overview of the history of fault in family law, and to discuss the role of fault in family law today.
<p><br>
<hr>
