<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>International Taxation<br>
April 1996<br>
Mr. Richardson</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<blockquote>
You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the course materials book and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
The examination comprises four questions, one of which has three parts; the questions have the relative values indicated in the margin. It is suggested that time be allocated accordingly.
<P>
When answering questions provide references to the appropriate provisions of the Income Tax Act (Canada) and Regulations, tax treaties, or other relevant authority.
<P>
At the conclusion of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE
WRITING TABLE</b>.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>
<b>1. (25 marks)</b> Ms. A works as an engineer in the U.K. for a U.K. resident corporation that is in the software business. She has lived her entire life in the U.K. Her employer has arranged for her to work in Canada for a period of two to three years on a special project in Canada. She will begin working for her employer in Canada at the beginning of August, 1996, but will travel back and forth between the U.K. and Canada until the beginning of November, 1996. At that time she will move to Canada with her spouse and children. She plans to retain ownership of her house in the U.K. and rent it in her absence. She also owns a significant number of shares of her employer corporation, and a cottage in Canada that she inherited many years before from a distant relation.
<P>
Discuss the Canadian income tax considerations relating to Ms. A's proposed transfer to Canada and return to the U.K.
<P><br>
<b>2. (25 marks)</b> Describe the role of bi-lateral income tax conventions in Canada's income tax system, illustrating your description with relevant examples of provisions from the Canada-U.S. Income Tax Convention
or Canada-U.K. Income Tax Convention.
<P><br>
<b>3. (25 marks)</b> SHIPCO is a corporation incorporated under the laws of Bermuda with a head office there. It operates a domestic tugboat business in the U.S., where it has an office and employees, and it pays U.S. income tax on its business income connected with this U.S. business. SHIPCO intends to acquire the business of CANTUG,   another corporation incorporated and resident in Bermuda that operates a similar tugboat business in Canada, by buying the Canadian business assets of CANTUG. These assets include tugboats and a small office building in Vancouver from which the business is operated. The acquisition price for the business will be $10,000,000 which will be funded by $2,000,000 of SHIPCO's own money and a loan of $8,000,000 from a U.S. resident bank. The loan will bear interest at 10% per annum and is repayable in 4 years.
<P>
Advise SHIPCO as to the Canadian income tax considerations relating to its proposed purchase, including  considerations relating to whether it should establish a Canadian subsidiary.
<P><br>
<b>4.</b> As of the beginning of 1994, and from that time to the present, Canadian resident corporation C1 owned 100% of the common shares of Canadian resident corporation C2; C2 owned 80% of the common shares of B1, a corporation resident in Barbados; B1 owned 25% of the shares of B2, another corporation resident in Barbados; and B1 owned 100% of the common shares of US1, a corporation resident in the United States. C1 also owned 1% of the common shares of B1. All of the corporations have only one class of issued shares common shares; and all of their issued common shares not referred to above are owned by non-related persons not resident in Canada. All of the corporations have December 31 year ends.
<P>
None of the corporations had any kind of income or loss prior to 1995, except US1 which had a loss from its active business carried on in the U.S. of 60,000 Canadian dollars; in 1995, the three foreign companies had income in Canadian dollars as follows:
<p>
<center><table border cellpadding=15>
<tr>
<th valign=top>B1</th><td>100,000 interest income from U.S. government bonds<p>50,000 dividend from US 1 (100% of a 50,000 dividend paid by US1 on its common shares in December, 1995)<P>100,000 dividend from B2 (25% of a 400,000 dividend paid by B2 on its common shares in December, 1995)</td></tr>
<th valign=top>B2</th><td>200,000 interest income from US government bonds <P>400,000 income from its active business carried on in Barbados</td></tr>
<th valign=top>US1</th><td>140,000 income from its active business carried on in the U.S.</td></tr>
</table></center>
<P>
B1 and B2 utilize the services of only 1 employee each to manage their bond investments. No tax was paid by B1 or B2 in respect of this income, but US 1 paid tax measured in Canadian dollars of 30,000 for 1995.
<P>
<b>(a) (10 marks)</b> How much, if any, foreign accrual property income will be included in the income of each of C1 and C2 under Part I of the Income Tax Act for their 1995 taxation year? Indicate the analysis used by you in this determination.
<P>
<b>(b) (7.5 marks)</b> What is the &quot;exempt surplus&quot; and &quot;taxable surplus&quot; of each of B1, B2 and US1 vis-a-vis C1 and C2 as of the beginning of 1996? Indicate the analysis used by you in this determination.
<P>
<b>(c) (7.5 marks)</b> If B1 pays a total dividend of 500,000 Canadian dollars on its common shares on January 1, 1996, what are the Canadian income tax consequences for C1 and C2?
<p><br>
<hr>
