<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Labour Law<br>
April 1996<br>
David Beatty</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use your casebook, supplementary, and statutory materials as well as your own notes during the exam. Textbooks and other materials from the library are not permitted.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination
<P>
<li>During the test, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the test. 
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the test has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<b>1.</b> Fred Farmer IV is the great grandson of Fred Farmer I, the founder of <cite>Farmer's Choice</cite>, a well-known producer of fine jams and preserves in Eastern Ontario. What had begun as a simple Ma and Pa homestead operation had evolved, over the years, into a bustling enterprise of almost 100 employees, distributed across a farming operation (40 labourers), a processing plant (35 workers), a trucking service (10 drivers), and a small administrative and sales office (of 5-6 people).
<P>
On the whole life had been good for Fred and <cite>Farmer's Choice</cite>. Company sales grew over time and the only cloud in the picture was the increasing attention their success attracted among competitors and in the trade union community. Once their company became better known, several unions had put out feelers to the workers and in December 1993 the Teamsters had succeeded in organizing Fred's drivers. On February 15, 1994 Fred signed a standard, two-year collective agreement with the Teamsters which guaranteed, among other things, (1) that he retained exclusive authority to manage the business as he saw fit unless the Agreement specifically provided otherwise and (2) that all employees would work a forty-hour week.
<P>
In December 1995 Farmer and the Teamsters began negotiating a new collective agreement in a spirit of optimism and good will. However, relations soured as bargaining progressed and broke down completely when, at the middle of January, the company unilaterally instituted two important policy initiatives. First Fred announced that, owing to changes in harvesting practices, the regular schedule of work for everyone (labourers, plant and office workers as well as the drivers) would be pushed ahead four hours. As of the first of February all workers would start at noon and finish at 9:00 p.m. with an unpaid hour off for dinner. Secondly, Farmer told his workers that the company was installing hidden cameras in the plant and on the premises after it had discovered several marijuana plants growing in one of its hothouses.
<P>
Practically everyone who worked for the company was opposed to the changes. Labourers, plant workers, drivers and office staff alike all protested at having to work into the evening and at being subjected to surveillance by hidden cameras. Three of the drivers in particular, Anwar Ali, Betty Bible, and Charlie Christian - were especially incensed about the change in their hours because their religious beliefs prohibited them from doing any work after
sundown on Fridays. When Ali, Bible and Christian told Fred of their personal circumstances, the latter replied that it would be impossible to create special schedules for them and that he would have to fire them and replace them with people who could work a full forty-hour week. 
<P>
When conciliation collapsed, and with the anger of the workers at a fever pitch, the Teamsters called a strike for the first of March. The attitude of both sides was ugly. The Teamsters put pickets in front of the plant, at all the other roads that accessed Fred's farm, and even in front of the properties of other farmers who sold fruits and berries to Fred. As well, they initiated a consumer boycott by picketing all the local stores in the area that carried Farmer's choice products.
<P>
For his part, Fred hit back by recruiting replacement workers with promises that if they guaranteed they would work a full forty-hour week on the new schedule they would be given extra seniority rights that would ensure they would not be laid off at the end of the strike. Fred was able to attract seven drivers in this way, including two Doug Doublecross and Ernie Egoist - who were part of the group that had gone out on strike, but who had opposed the union and the idea of collective bargaining right from the beginning.
<P>
As spring arrived, the pressure on both sides to reach a settlement increased. Farmer's Choice would be ruined if the strike interfered with the planting season and the drivers were feeling the pinch of having had no paychecks for over a month. Indeed, several of them, including Gord Gettaway, Harry Haulage and Ivan Itinerant, had family members who worked either in the plant or in the fields, who had felt compelled to respect the drivers' picket line, and so they had lost two incomes instead of one.
<P>
Fred has come to you for advice. Before he makes a settlement with the union, he wants to know precisely what his legal situation is with respect to all of the events (and all of the workers) that have occurred up until now. In addition, he wants to know what he should make of a proposal the Teamsters have put forward in which, in  exchange for the union agreeing not to grieve the dismissals of Ali, Bible and Christian and allowing Doublecross
and Egoist to retain their jobs, Fred would be obliged to deduct the amount of money Doublecross and Egoist had earned by working during the strike and remit it to the union. According to the Teamsters, the forfeiture of earnings made by workers who cross its picket lines is part of their constitution and binds all of their members.
<P>
Finally Fred advises you that he has been thinking a lot, in the last little while, about the possibility of expanding the processing part of his operation and moving it closer to the Niagara Peninsula where he would have easier access to a much larger crop. The idea of moving also appeals to Fred because he believes it would make it less likely that the Teamsters would be able to continue their efforts to organize the workers in the plant that they had initiated during the course of the drivers' strike.
<P>
Advise Fred what his legal rights and obligations are not only with respect to the drivers and their union but with regard to his other workers as well.
<p><br>
<hr>
