<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Patent and Trade Secrets Course<br>
April 1996<br>
Donald M. Cameron</h2></center>
<h3>Instructions:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>The exam is composed of five questions, which are of equal value. Please begin the exam questions on a new page.
<P>
<b>For those writing the sit-down exam:</b>
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will gather you belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table
and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answers booklets collected separately and may be subject to penalty.
<P>
<b>For those who Write the take-home exam:</b>
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name and the number of booklets on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it.
<P>
<li>Please pick up the exam on Thursday April 25, 1996 at 9:30am from Ms. Pat Ward, Faculty of Law, Room 1 10 and return to Ms. Ward before 4pm Friday April 26, 1996.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<ol>
<li>Discuss the differences between the pith and substances test of infringement and the Purposive constructions of the <cite>Catnic</cite> and <cite>Eli Lilly</cite> cases.
<P>
<li>Your client is a carpenter. He has developed a set of tools that makes attaching drywall to the wall much easier than what everyone else uses. He's used them on a couple of jobs already and his co-workers are asking him if they can buy some. He's asked you if he can get patent protection on them. In point form, set out the questions you will ask him at the meeting you plan to have with him next week.
<P>
<li>Your client has told you that she has a Canadian patent application that was filed in Canada on May 15, 1994 and claimed the benefit of convention priority from a U.S. Patent application that was filed on June 23, 1993. In
reviewing her company records she came across some material which has caused her to ask you questions as to the patentability of her invention. Assume that each document fully describes her invention. Advise her as to the novelty situation only and deal with item individually and explain why or why not she will be able to obtain a valid patent.
<P>
 A. an advertising brochure that was issued by a licensee of your client on July 2, 1993;
<P>
 B. an advertising brochure that was issued by a licensee of your client in January, 1993;
<P>
 C. an advertising brochure that was issued by a licensee of your client in January, 1992;
<P>
 D. a pending Canadian patent application of someone else, filed on July 4, 1993;
<P>
 E. a pending German patent application filed by someone else on May 1, 1992.
<P>
<li>Your client Susan is the owner of U.S. Patent No. 5,123,456 (filed September 1, 1992, granted March 25, 1995) and Canadian Patent Application 2,123,457 which claimed convention priority on the American application but which has not yet issued. She recently found out about Bloggs widgets who she is sure is selling products here and in the U.S. that are exactly the same as what she has claimed.
<P>
She wants to write Bloggs a nasty letter telling them they are infringing her patent rights and they better stop right away or else everything awful will happen to them. She would like you to draft the letter so everything is Regale. Please write the letter.
<P>
<li>You client has just started a new company called Puget Electronics. They would like you do draft up a policy and procedures guide for ownership and protection of their employees inventions. They have asked you to write a &quot;Top Ten&quot; list of the legal controls or procedures they should put in place. Please write the list and explain briefly why each item is important. 
</ol><p><br>
<hr>
