<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Property<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Phillips</h2></center>
<h3>Instructions:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This is an open book examination. You may use the course materials and any notes or books of your own.
<P>
<li>There are four parts to the examination, of unequal value. You must answer Question One (20 marks), Question Two (25 marks), Question Three (30 marks) and <b>EITHER</b> Part A or Part B of Question Four (25 marks). The time you should allow is indicated in each question.
<P>
<li>If you believe that you need more facts to answer any question, say what you need to know. If you consider it appropriate you may make factual assumptions and continue with your answer on the basis of those assumptions.
<P>
<li>You may include in any of your answers, where appropriate, suggestions for changes in the law. Be careful, however, to distinguish between the existing law and any such suggestions for reform.
<P>
<li>At the conclusion of this examination you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER </U>BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON
THE WRITING TABLE</b>. Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>QUESTIONS ONE AND TWO (45 MARKS TOTAL!</h3>

In 1980 Albert bought a large 4-bedroom house in the Annex area of Toronto from Bob. A few months before the purchase Bob and a few of his neighbours noticed that a house a few blocks away had recently been bought by a charitable organisation and converted for use as a hospice for AIDS sufferers. (A hospice is a home for the destitute or sick). Bob and six of his neighbours, fearful of and ignorant about AIDS, agreed that if any of them sold their houses they would stipulate that the houses were not to be used as AIDS hospices. Having also noticed that another house in the neighbourhood was rather run-down in appearance, they also decided to try to make future purchasers conform to what they saw as the neighbourhood standard of appearance and maintenance. Thus the conveyance to Albert contained a short covenant, which read in its entirety as follows:
<P>
The grantee promises, covenants and agrees, to and with the grantor and his heirs and assigns, with the intention that the same shall run with the land and be binding upon all subsequent owners;
<P>
Firstly, that the land is not to be used for the purpose of a hospice for AIDS patients or for any similar purpose;
<P>
Secondly, that the dwelling house on the land is to be maintained in good appearance and the yard in neat order. No prefabricated or temporary structures shall be erected in the yard;
<P>
Thirdly, that any conveyance of the land hereafter shall be subject to the above restrictions.
<P>
The covenant was registered with the other documents conveying title to Albert. Albert lived in the house until 1985, and then sold it to Charlotte. Charlotte's lawyer told her that there was a restrictive covenant attached to the land, but as she did not intend to do anything but live in the house for the rest of her life she didn't care. Early last year Charlotte received a promotion that required her to move to Vancouver for five years. Not wishing to sell the house in a depressed Toronto real estate market, she decided to rent it out. She did not want to rent it for residential
purposes, preferring that it be occupied for some form of business. She made an agreement with Helping Hand  (SEW, an AIDS-related charity that wanted to expand its hospice facilities. She knew exactly why HH wanted to rent the house, and her lawyer assured her, <b>correctly</b> that Part IV of the <cite>Landlord and Tenant Act</cite> did not apply to such a use.
<P>
The lease with HH was for a five-year period, starting 1 July 1995. Almost immediately after HH moved in Darren, one of the neighbours who knew about the covenant, called his old friend Bob and told him what had happened. Bob then called Charlotte and complained about the use to which her house was being put. He was also annoyed that the house had not been painted for a while and that HH had put up a shed for storing bicycles in the yard. Charlotte refused to do anything, so Bob sued and at trial won a judgment that
<P>
(a) the covenant was a valid restrictive covenant that ran with the land and was enforceable against Charlotte as a successor-in-title to Albert, and
<P>
(b) that Bob was entitled to an injunction barring HH from using the house as a hospice, requiring HH or Charlotte to remove the shed, and also requiring Charlotte to have the house painted.
<P>
The judgment and accompanying injunction were issued on February 1st, 1996.
<P>
<b>QUESTION ONE. You are Charlotte's lawyer, and believe the trial judgment to be wrong. You know there was notice of the covenant through registration, but you don't believe it is enforceable against Charlotte. In response to the Ontario government's pledge to speed up justice, the Court of Appeal has introduced a scheme whereby appeals may be &quot;fast-tracked&quot; in appropriate circumstances. Counsel who want a quick hearing must submit a
memorandum on why they have a strong case and ought to be heard soon. For 20 MARKS, and in 35 minutes, please write that memorandum.</b>
<P><br>
When the injunction was served on HH, they consulted lawyers (Osgoode Hall graduates) who told them they could leave because Charlotte had broken her contract with them; she knew they wanted the house for a hospice and had rented them one that she knew or ought to have known could not be used for that purpose. HH told Charlotte about this advice, and in response Charlotte wrote to them as follows:
<P>
&quot;I am going to take the case about the covenant to the Court of Appeal. I understand that you are frustrated at not being able to use the house for a while, but I would prefer you not to leave the house unoccupied. I am willing to forgive the rent until we get the matter sorted out. If you feel you must leave, I am also willing to try to find another tenant for a short term, and you can come back when it's all sorted out&quot;.
<P>
HH were not persuaded to stay, and at the end of March 1996 left owing one month's rent, that for March. Charlotte was soon able to get another tenant. The rent was much lower than that which had been paid by HH, largely because the tenant agreed with Charlotte that it would leave immediately when asked. As Charlotte explained to the new tenant when they met to sign a lease: &quot;I'm just doing this to cover myself until I get the injunction lifted,
at which time HH can come back&quot;.
<P>
<b>QUESTION TWO. Charlotte is concerned about the precise nature of her rights and obligations vis-a-vis HH. For 25 MARKS, and taking 45 minutes, please explain to her exactly what her legal position is in relation to HH, and advise her what to do now.</b>
<P><br>
<h3>QUESTION 1TIREE - 30 MARKS</h3>
<P>
The recently-elected government of Flavelle, a province of Canada with laws identical to those of Ontario, has enacted a <cite>Flavelle Bill of Rights</cite> which includes the following provision:
<P>
&quot;Every resident of Flavelle has the right to the full and absolute enjoyment of rights of property of all kinds, and the right not to be deprived of property without just compensation &quot;
<P>
This was a measure dear to the heart of the Flavelle premier, Golf Pro, as was another piece of legislation, the <cite>Landlords' Protection Act</cite>. This act repealed all rent control legislation in Flavelle as well as Part IV of the existing <cite>Landlord and Tenant Act.</cite>
<P>
In a busy legislative session the legislature also passed another Act, the <cite>Heritage Golf Courses Preservation Act.</cite> This was a response to the fact that the land on which the Glenn Abbey golf course was laid out had been bought from the Glenn Abbey Golf Club by Disney Corporation. Soon after the purchase Disney announced that it intended to close the course and to build a Disney theme park on the land. Many members of the Flavelle cabinet were appalled at the possible destruction of one of Canada's finest golf courses, and at the loss of revenue
from the inevitable cancellation of the Canadian Open golf tournament, played at Glenn Abbey. The <cite>Heritage Golf Courses Preservation Act</cite> stipulated that certain golf courses in the province, including Glenn Abbey, were &quot;heritage golf courses&quot; and the land on which a &quot;heritage golf course&quot; stood could not be used for any other purpose. The <cite>Act</cite> contained no provision for the awarding of compensation.
<P>
Shortly after all this legislation was passed Disney sued the government, arguing that it should be compensated for the lost opportunity to develop the land. It based its claim on the common law and on the newly-enacted Flavelle <cite>Bill of Rights.</cite> At about the same time a tenants' rights organisation, the Flavelle Tenants Association, also sued the government, arguing that the <cite>Landlords' Protection Act</cite> was both a violation of the Flavelle <cite>Bill of Rights</cite> and unconstitutional under the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.</cite> Since both actions involved interpretation of the Flavelle <cite>Bill of Rights,</cite> they were
joined.
<P>
<b>QUESTION THREE: Please write the judgment of the court in <cite>Disney Corp and Flavelle Tenants Association v. Government of Flavelle</cite>. In the interests of speedy justice, you should not spend more than 55 minutes on your judgment.</b>
<P><br>
<h3>QUESTION FOUR - 25 MARKS - 45 MINUTES</h3>

<b>ANSWER EITHER QUESTION 4 (A) OR QUESTION 4 (B)</b>
<P>
<b>4 (A)</b> C.B. Macpherson variously argues that: &quot;The meaning of property is not constant. The actual institution, and the way people see it, ... changes over time .... [P]roperty is a political relation between persons .... The definition of property [is] ... an enforceable claim of a person to some use or benefit of something&quot;.
<P>
Discuss this quotation. In particular, please consider how you would use <b>either</b>
<P>
(i) the Canadian law of aboriginal rights in land, <b>or</b>
<P>
(ii) Ontario residential tenancies law
<P>
as an illustration of Macpherson's principal ideas.
<P>
<b>4 (B)</b> Give short answers to all three of the following questions
<P>
i) After <cite>Masidon Investments v. Ham</cite>, what do you think the purpose, or rationale, of adverse possession law is?
<P>
ii) What is the difference between these two rules:
<P>
(a) &quot;on the grant by the owner of a tenement of part of that tenement as it is then used and enjoyed, there will pass to the grantee all those continuous and apparent easements ... or, in other words, all those easements which are <b>necessary</b> to the reasonable enjoyment of the property granted, and which have been and are at the time of the grant used by the owners of the entirety for the benefit of the part granted&quot;.
<P>
(b) &quot;in certain circumstances the law will imply an easement of <b>necessity</b>&quot;.
<P>
iii) What are the principal factual issues which must be proved if a native society wishes to show that a traditional &quot;practice&quot; is an aboriginal right?
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
