<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Property A<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor A. Weinrib</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>This is a 2.25 hour examination. Answer all 3 questions; they are of equal  value.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet  on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the conclusion of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>ALL EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>Question 1</h3>

The Attorney General of Ontario has decided to initiate a review of property law in the province. As part of this process you have been asked to write a memorandum on the reform of the law relating to circumstances in which the defeasible fees are struck down. The Attorney General is particularly interested in your assessment of whether the law should remain as it is or whether it should be reformed. You should assume that the Attorney General knows
very little about property law. Therefore, he is particularly interested in your reasoning.
<P><br>
<h3>Question 2</h3>

Oscar owns a new luxury residential apartment building in Toronto. The building has a doorman who announces visitors to tenants and keeps out the uninvited. Unfortunately, the doorman persistently admitted canvassers who annoyed the tenants. One day he even admitted two large men posing as movers who made off with most of Jane's
furniture. Jane has demanded that Oscar pay her the replacement value of her furniture and fire the doorman. Oscar has refused both demands. He has pointed out to Jane a clause in her lease relieving the landlord of responsibility for damages suffered by tenants. He has also refused to fire the doorman who is his father
<P>
To make matters worse, the child of another tenant has broken the washing and drying machines. Oscar refuses to do anything about the washing and drying machines claiming that he is not at fault.
<P>
Jane went on an extended business trip and allowed a lawyer friend of hers to use the apartment. He was careless about where he threw his food and bugs appeared in the apartment. Jane moved back in. For the last several months, due to the facts already mentioned, Jane has refused to pay rent. Yesterday she moved out and mailed Oscar the keys. Oscar has written to her indicating that he will hold her responsible for both past and future rent and any other
damages that he may claim.
<P>
Discuss the legal issues raised by these facts.
<P><br>
<h3>Question 3</h3>

L and T enter into a written three-year lease of a suite in L's building in Toronto. T was a dentist, so he extracted a covenant from L that the suite could be used in the practice of dentistry. T covenanted to pay rent and not to assign or sublet any part of the premises without leave in writing by L.
<P>
During the first year of the lease L carried out an extensive scheme of remodelling the interior of the building. No work was done within the suite leased to T. but noise, dampness, dust, obstruction of hallways, and interruptions of
the supply of water and electricity substantially interfered with T's practice and injured his equipment to some extent. At first T protested to L and when L refused to have the work stopped, T ceased paying rent and moved out, taking his equipment with him. Three months later, when L had finished making the alterations to the building, T asked L for permission to assign the balance of the term to S. an architect. L refused to consent to the assignment.
L is an architect himself and he has his offices in the building. T gave S the key to the suite anyway and S moved in one weekend while L was out of town. The day after S moved into the suite (sometime in late January) it began to snow. Unfortunately S had left a window open and so much snow fell inside the suite that the hardwood floor was ruined. When L came back to Toronto a few days later, he immediately sued T for arrears of rent, damages for breach of the covenant not to assign without leave and for the cost of having a new hardwood floor installed in the suite.
<P>
Advise T as to his legal position.
<p><br>
<hr>
