<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Property II<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor A. Weinrib</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<P>
<li>This is a 3 hour examination. Answer all 3 questions; they are of equal  value.
<P>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet  on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<P>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
<li>At the conclusion of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>ALL EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b>
<P>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>Question 1</h3>

Jill, an accountant, owned an office building on Bloor Street. She leased a suite in the building to Ken for a term of 3 years. Since Jill practised accountancy in the same building, she and Ken agreed that Ken could not use the office he rented for the purpose of an accountancy practise. Ken also covenanted not to part with possession of the premises without Jill's permission. Shortly thereafter, Jill sold the building to Ann and moved her practise.
<P>
A few months later Ken rented space in his premises in the building to Barbara a well known tax accountant. Ken did not seek Ann's permission for his transaction, nor did Ann know about it. Ann was not a very efficient manager and failed to pay the electrical bills for the building on time. Ken and Barbara found it difficult to carry on their businesses because the electric power to the offices was often shut off.
<P>
Ann had trouble getting tenants to fill the other offices in the building. In desperation, she rented space for a body rub parlous This had a very detrimental effect on Ken's business. Ken complained bitterly about the body rub parlour but Ann refused to do anything about it. Ken then withheld the rent for the past two months. Ann has just found out about Barbara's presence in the building.
<P>
The rental market has just improved dramatically. Ann has now brought an action for possession against Ken. There is a clause in the lease allowing the landlord to terminate the lease if the tenant is in breach of any covenants.
<P>
What disposition would you make of the issues involved? Point out and argue briefly for any reforms in the law whose necessity you think is indicated by these facts.
<P><br>
<h3>Question 2</h3>

The Attorney General of Ontario has decided to initiate a review of property law in the province. As part of this process you have been asked to write a memorandum on the reform of the law relating to adverse possession. The Attorney General is particularly interested in your assessment of whether the law should remain as it is or whether it should be reformed. You should assume that the Attorney General knows very little about property law. Therefore, he is particularly interested in your reasoning, and in any cases you think are relevant to your assessment.
<P><br>
<h3>Question 3</h3>

Oscar owns a new luxury residential apartment building in Toronto. The building has a doorman who announces visitors to tenants and keeps out the uninvited. Unfortunately, the doorman persistently admitted canvassers who
annoyed the tenants. One day he even admitted two large men posing as movers who made off with most of Jane's furniture. Jane has demanded that Oscar pay her the replacement value of her furniture and fire the doorman. Oscar has refused both demands. He has pointed out to Jane a clause in her lease relieving the landlord of responsibility
for damages suffered by tenants. He has also refused to fire the doorman who is his father
<P>
To make matters worse, the child of another tenant has broken the washing and drying machines. Oscar refuses to do anything about the washing and drying machines claiming that he is not at fault.
<P>
Jane went on an extended business trip and allowed a lawyer friend of hers to use the apartment. He was careless about where he threw his food and bugs appeared in the apartment. Jane moved back in. For the last several months, due to the facts already mentioned, Jane has refused to pay rent. Yesterday she moved out and mailed Oscar the keys. Oscar has written to her indicating that he will hold her responsible for both past and future rent and any other
damages that he may claim.
<P>
What disposition would you make of the issues involved? Point out and argue briefly for any reform to the law whose necessity you think is indicated by these facts.
<p><br>
<hr>
