<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link = 00562d vlink = 440000>
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Public International Law<br>
In-Class Examination<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Knop</h2></center>
<h3>INSTRUCTIONS:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use the casebook, its document collection, the supplement and any notes of your own during this examination. You may not use any other material, such as textbooks.
<p><li>At the conclusion of this examination you will be asked to stop writing, gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>Your examination answer booklets should be left on the writing table.</b> Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
<p>
<li>The examination consists of two parts. You must answer both parts. <b>Part Two gives you a choice of two questions.</b>
<p>
<li>Part One is worth a total of 80 marks and is divided into 3 questions worth 30, 15, and 35 respectively. Part Two is worth 20 marks.
<p>
 <li><b>Part One involves a cumulative fact pattern: each question in Part One is based on all the facts that come before it.</b>
<li>You should be careful to apportion your time according to the value of each question. As a guideline only, the suggested time for Part One is 2 hours and 25 minutes, and the suggested amount of  time for Part Two is 35 minutes. The suggested time for each question in Part One is indicated in the body of the exam.
<p>
To avoid any problems at the end of the examination, please fill in the required information on the front of your answer booklet <b>before</b> the examination begins.
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>PART ONE (3 QUESTIONS)</h3>
 
 <b>Part One is worth a total of 80 marks. Suggested time for the entire part is 2 hours and 25 minutes. The facts for this Part are cumulative: each question is based on all the facts given up to that point. Where a name is followed by an abbreviation in parentheses, you may for convenience substitute the abbreviation for the full name.</b>
<p>
The states of Evokia (&quot;E&quot;) and Forgettia (&quot;F&quot;) face each other across a 200 mile channel connecting the Seas of Memor and Oblivion. Both states claim sovereignty over the small island of Amnesia (&quot;A&quot;), which lies 30 miles off the Forgettian coast.
<p>
Evokia is not a party to the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea (&quot;UNCLOS&quot;). Forgettia has signed the UNCLOS and is preparing to declare an Exclusive Economic Zone (&quot;EEZ&quot;) that would encompass
 Amnesia. This prospect has led to a patriotic frenzy in both states, and a sudden chill in the relations between Evokia and Forgettia.
<p>
 In 1720, a team of cartographers charged with mapping the possessions of the King of Evokia discovered the island of Amnesia and included it on an official map. Apart from a flag and a stone marker, they left no trace behind. So far as the cartographers could determine, Amnesia, a rocky and forbidding isle, had never been inhabited. There is no evidence that it has been inhabited since.
<p>
From about 1820 on, both Evokia and Forgettia routinely made a number of their legislative acts applicable to the island. In many of its bilateral commercial treaties, Forgettia, with the concurrence of the other state party, stipulated that the treaty shall not apply to Amnesia. In the late nineteenth century, Forgettian botanists visited Amnesia and made a record of the types of flora unique to the island. The record is now part of the archives of the Forgettian Museum of Natural History. In the same period, Forgettia built a lighthouse on Amnesia. The lighthouse has not functioned for over half a century. Forgettia has continuously maintained buoys and other nautical  markers  off the coast of the island.
<p>
 In a recent multilateral convention on the environment, Evokia made a reservation to the effect that certain articles of the convention, dealing with disposal of nuclear waste, would not apply to Amnesia. Forgettia, which is also a party to the convention, objected and precluded the entry into force of the convention as between itself and Evokia. Forty states, some of which are part of a regional trading bloc with Forgettia, also objected to the reservation, but did not preclude its entry into force. The remaining twenty states made no objection.
<p>
<b>A) Worth 30 marks. Suggested time 55 minutes.</b>
<p>
 Evokia and Forgettia agree to submit the dispute over Amnesia to the International Court of Justice. The Court is asked to decide which of the two states has sovereignty over Amnesia. Write the decision of the Court.
<p><br>
Assume that the International Court of Justice holds that Evokia has sovereignty over the island of Amnesia. (This decision should have no impact on your answer to Question A). 
<p>
About 40 miles from Amnesia is the equally small island of Nivhah (&quot;N&quot;). Unlike Amnesia, Nivhah has an indigenous population, who call themselves Nivhi. In the last century, Nivhah was colonized by the state of Glancia (&quot;G&quot;). Glancia mined phosphates on Nivhah during the colonial period and continued to do so even after it had listed the island as a non-self-governing territory under the UN Charter. By 1990, when a referendum was held on Nivhah and the population voted overwhelmingly for independence, the island had been ravaged by phosphate mining. Even though the Nivhi now have their own state, many of them leave the island and their traditional way of life to seek employment elsewhere. 
<p>
Over the last few years, a particular species of sea creature, the aubergine-de-mer (&quot;adm&quot;), has become a delicacy in Europe and North America. The waters off the coast of Nivhah are rich in aubergine-de-mer. The best grounds for harvesting aubergine-de-mer are between Amnesia and Nivhah, closer to Nivhah. In 1993, Nivhah declares an EEZ that extends to the halfway point between the islands, 20 miles out from the shoreline of Nivhah. Since the aubergine-de-mer grounds are 10 to 20 miles off the coast of Nivhah, this has the effect of encompassing all the aubergine-de-mer grounds. Conrad Black's new fishing concern, Byliner (&quot;BL&quot;), is very interested in acquiring the exclusive right to fish for aubergine-de-mer in this area and makes a very attractive offer to the Nivhah government for the right. The Nivhah government determines that such a deal would generate enough revenue to sustain many aspects of the traditional Nivhi way of life. Just as they are about to close the deal, in the spring of 1994, Evokia declares an EEZ around Amnesia. Instead of respecting the Nivhi EEZ, Evokia declares an EEZ that extends to the outer limit of the 12 mile territorial sea of Nivhah, thereby encompassing most of the aubergine-de-mer grounds. 
<p>
<b>B) Worth 15 marks. Suggested time 25 minutes.</b>
<p>
Evokia and Nivhah submit to arbitration the delimitation of a single maritime boundary involving both shelf and fisheries jurisdiction in the waters between Amnesia and Nivhah. Write the decision of the arbitral panel. 
<p><br>
There is a considerable delay before the arbitral panel hears the matter of the maritime boundary delimitation between Evokia and Nivhah. The Nivhah government suspects that the Evokian government is stalling. Byliner is anxious to close its deal with the Nivhah government and begin fishing for aubergine-de-mer. Without waiting for the matter to come to arbitration, the Nivhah government goes ahead with the deal and grants Byliner the exclusive right to fish aubergine-de-mer within the waters Nivhah claims. Gambling that the arbitral panel will decide on an equidistant boundary, Byliner begins to fish. The Evokian government reacts strongly to these actions. The Evokian Coast Guard stops a Byliner trawler fishing 15 miles off the coast of Nivhah and confiscates the lucrative catch onboard without compensation. 
 <p>
Evokia sells the confiscated catch to Joblaws (&quot;J&quot;), a Canadian supermarket chain that sells its own Prime Minister's Choice brand of pickled aubergine-de-mer called &quot;Memories of  Oblivion.&quot; When the catch arrives in Canada, Byliner sues Joblaws in the Ontario Court of Justice, claiming that it has title to the catch. Canada has never recognized Nivhah as a state in deference to the powerful People's Republic of Cauchemar (&quot;C&quot;). Cauchemar maintains that prior to colonization by Glancia, Nivhah was part of Cauchemar and that Nivhah should therefore have been restored to Cauchemar on decolonization.
<p>
<b>C) Worth 35 marks. Suggested time 1 hour and 5 minutes.</b>
 <p>
 Write the decision of the Ontario court.
<p><br>
<h3>PART TWO (ONE QUESTION)</h3>

<b>Worth 20 marks. Suggested time 35 minutes.
<p>
Choose one of the following two questions. Either
<p>
A)</b> The debate between the majority and the dissent in the Supreme Court of Canada decision in <cite>Finta</cite> translates into two distinct visions of what the domestic prosecution of war crimes is all about. What are these visions and which one is preferable? 
<p>
<b>or
<p>
B)</b> The debate between the majority and the dissent in the US Supreme Court decision in <cite>Sabbatino</cite> involves a disagreement over the role of the domestic courts in international law. What are these roles and which one is preferable? 
<p><br>
<hr>
