<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link = 00562d vlink = 440000>
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Public International Law<br>
24 Hour Take-Home Examination<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Knop</h2></center>
<h3>INSTRUCTIONS:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use the casebook, its document collection, the supplement and any notes of your own during this examination. You may not use any other material, such as textbooks.
<p>
<li>General consultation among students writing this take-home examination is permitted, but the answers submitted by each student must be composed and written by that student alone.
<p>
<li>The examination must be returned to the Records Office, Falconer Hall by 10:00 am on Tuesday, April 16, 1996.
<p>
<li>The examination consists of two parts. You must answer both parts.
<p>
<li>Part One is worth a total of 80 marks and is divided into 4 questions worth 25, 15, 10 and 30 respectively. Part Two is worth 20 marks.
<p>
<li><b>Part One involves a cumulative fact pattern: each question in Part One is based on all the facts that come before it.</b>
 </ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>PART ONE (4 QUESTIONS)</h3>

<b>Part One is worth a total of 80 marks. The facts for this Part are cumulative: each question is based on all the facts given up to that point. Where a name is followed by an abbreviation in parentheses, you may for convenience substitute the abbreviation for the full name.</b>
<p>
 The states of Evokia (&quot;E&quot;) and Forgettia (&quot;F&quot;) face each other across a 200 mile channel connecting the Seas of Memor and Oblivion. Both states claim sovereignty over two small islands, which they call Amnesia (&quot;A&quot;) and Baffould (&quot;B&quot;). The two islands lie within 30 miles of the Forgettian coast and are 40 miles apart.
<p>
Evokia is not a party to the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea (&quot;UNCLOS&quot;). Forgettia has signed the UNCLOS and is preparing to declare an Exclusive Economic Zone (&quot;EEZ&quot;) that, would encompass Amnesia and Baffould. This prospect has led to a patriotic frenzy in both states, and a sudden chill in the relations between Evokia and Forgettia.
<p>
In 1720, a team of cartographers charged with mapping the possessions of the King of Evokia discovered the islands of Amnesia and Baffould, and included them on an official map. Apart from a flag and a stone marker on each island, they left no trace behind. So far as the cartographers could determine, Amnesia, a rocky and forbidding isle, had never been inhabited. There is no evidence that it has been inhabited since. The cartographers noted the
 presence of indigenous settlements on Baffould, but did not make contact with the inhabitants.
<p>
From about 1820 on, both Evokia and Forgettia routinely made a number of their legislative acts applicable to the islands. In many of its bilateral commercial treaties, Forgettia, with the concurrence of the other state party, stipulated that the treaty shall not apply to Amnesia and Baffould. In the late nineteenth century, Forgettian botanists visited Amnesia and Baffould, and made a record of the types of flora unique to the islands. The record is now part of the archives of the Forgettian Museum of Natural History. In the same period, Forgettia built a lighthouse on Amnesia and another on a desolate point of Baffould. These lighthouses have not functioned for over half a century. Forgettia has continuously maintained buoys and other nautical markers off the coasts of both islands.
<p>
In a recent multilateral convention on the environment, Evokia made a reservation to the effect that certain articles of the convention, dealing with disposal of nuclear waste, would not apply to Amnesia and Baffould. Forgettia, which is also a party to the convention, objected and precluded the entry into force of the convention as between itself and Evokia. Forty states, some of  which are part of a regional trading bloc with Forgettia, also objected to the reservation, but did not preclude its entry into force. The remaining twenty states made no objection.
 <p>
 <b>A) Worth 25 marks.</b>
<p>
Evokia and Forgettia agree to submit the dispute over Amnesia to the International Court of Justice. The Court is asked to decide which of the two states has sovereignty over Amnesia. Write the decision of the Court.
<p><br>
In the mid-nineteenth century, the state of Glancia (&quot;G&quot;) briefly used Baffould as a penal colony, but abandoned the practice and has never made a territorial claim to Baffould. The prisoners, left to fend for themselves, became integrated into the indigenous society, and many current inhabitants of Baffould are of mixed race. The indigenous name for Baffould is Nivhah (&quot;N&quot;), and the indigenous population call themselves Nivhi. At the time, Nivhi political, social and economic organization was highly developed, and Nivhi have long traded with foreign traders and trading companies. There have never been, however, any dealings between the Nivhi and either Evokia or Forgettia. The Nivhi consider themselves a sovereign people and their island a sovereign state. A number of neighbouring states, foreign fishing fleets and recently a multinational corporation doing exploratory offshore drilling in the vicinity deal with the Nivhah government on this basis. However, Evokia and Forgettia have successfully pressured states not to recognize Nivhah as a state.
<p>
<b>B) Worth 15 marks.</b>
<p>
Evokia and Forgettia also ask the International Court of Justice to decide which of the two states has sovereignty over Baffould (Nivhah). The rules of the Court prevent the Nivhah government from intervening, but Glancia, which takes the Nivhah position, has been granted permission to intervene in the case.
<p>
What arguments can Glancia make to establish that the Nivhi have sovereignty over Baffould (Nivhah)?
<p><br>
Assume that the International Court of Justice holds that Evokia has sovereignty over the island of Amnesia and dismisses the case concerning sovereignty over Baffould (Nivhah) on jurisdictional grounds. (Neither decision should have any impact on your answers to Questions A and B). Evokia and Forgettia have since recognized the state of Nivhah (henceforth known as Nivhah). 
<p>
Like Amnesia, Nivhah has few natural resources. Many Nivhi leave the island and their traditional way of life to seek employment elsewhere. Over the last few years, a particular species of sea creature, the aubergine-de-mer (&quot;adm&quot;), has become a delicacy in Europe and North America. The waters off the coast of Nivhah are rich in aubergine-de-mer. The best grounds for harvesting aubergine-de-mer are between Amnesia and Nivhah, closer to Nivhah. In 1993, Nivhah declares an EEZ that extends to the halfway point between the islands, 20 miles out from the shoreline of Nivhah. Since the aubergine-de-mer grounds are 10 to 20 miles off the coast of Nivhah, this has the effect of encompassing all the aubergine-de-mer grounds. Conrad Black's new fishing concern, Byliner (&quot;BL&quot;), is very interested in acquiring the exclusive right to fish for aubergine-de-mer in this area and makes a very attractive offer to the Nivhah government for the right. The Nivhah government determines that such a deal would generate enough revenue to sustain many aspects of the traditional Nivhi way of life. Just as they are about to close the deal, in the spring of 1994, Evokia declares an EEZ around Amnesia. Instead of respecting the Nivhi EEZ, Evokia declares an EEZ that extends to the outer limit of the 12 mile territorial sea of Nivhah, thereby encompassing most of the aubergine-de-mer grounds. 
<p>
<b>C) Worth 10 marks.</b>
<p>
Evokia and Nivhah submit to arbitration the delimitation of a single maritime boundary involving both shelf and fisheries jurisdiction in the waters between Amnesia and Nivhah. Write the decision of the arbitral panel. 
<p><br>
There is a considerable delays before the arbitral panel hears the matter of the maritime boundary delimitation between Evokia and Nivhah. The Nivhah government suspects that the Evokian government is stalling. Byliner is anxious to close its deal with the Nivhah government and begin fishing for aubergine-de-mer. Without waiting for the matter to come to arbitration, the Nivhi government goes ahead with the deal and grants Byliner the exclusive right to fish aubergine-de-mer within the waters Nivhah claims. Gambling that the arbitral panel will decide on an equidistant boundary, Byliner begins to fish. The Evokian government reacts strongly to these actions. The Evokian Coast Guard stops a Byliner trawler fishing 15 miles off the coast of Nivhah and confiscates the lucrative catch inboard without compensation.
<p>
Evokia sells the confiscated catch to Joblaws (&quot;J&quot;), a Canadian supermarket chain that sells its own Prime Minister's Choice brand of pickled aubergine-de-mer called &quot;Memories of  Oblivion.&quot; When the catch arrives in Canada, Byliner sues Joblaws in the Ontario Court of Justice, claiming that it has title to the catch. Canada does not recognize Nivhah as a state.
<p>
<b>D) Worth 30 marks.</b>
<p>
Write the decision of the Ontario court. 
<p><br>
<h3>PART TWO (ONE QUESTION)</h3>
<blockquote>
International Society had to find its own theory. It chose to see itself as a collection of state-societies turned inside out, like a glove. It chose to be an unsocial society creating itself separately from the development of its subordinate societies, ignoring the idea and the ideal of democracy, depriving itself of the possibility of using social power, especially legal relations, to bring about the survival and prospering of the whole human race.
<blockquote>
Philip Allott, <cite>Eunomia: New Order for a New World</cite>
</blockquote></blockquote>
Discuss this quotation in the context of <b>either</b> subjects of international law or the law of the sea.
<p><br>
<hr>
