<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Taxation<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor A. Weinrib</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This is an open-book examination. You may not use any materials belonging to a library.
<p>
<li>This exam is composed of three questions. It is suggested that time be allocated accordingly.
<p>
<li>If you feel additional information is required to answer a question, you may make reasonable assumptions consistent with the information given. If you make such assumptions, state what they are in your answer.
<p>
<li>At the conclusion of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE. ALSO, IF YOU USE MORE THAN ONE BOOKLET PLEASE INSERT ALL BOOKLETS INTO BOOKLET NO. 1.</b>
<p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
 </ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>Question 1</h3>

 A few years ago, Charles Fairview, a well known Toronto real estate developer, bought some land on Bloor Street. He intended to tear down the stores on the land and erect an office building which he would retain as an investment property. He paid for the realty by transferring to the vendor an undeveloped lot in the suburbs worth $100,000, by assuming an existing mortgage of $300,000 and by giving the vendor $80,000 in cash which he had borrowed from his bank. Fairview's legal fees in relation to transactions amounted to $20,000. Fairview rented the stores to some merchants for a few months before he demolished the buildings.
<p>
 Fairview was busy with other projects and the site remained unused for several years. Fairview decided that he would not be able to build the project in the foreseeable future, so he sold the site to Ann Abel for $1,500,000. Fairview received $300,000 when the transaction closed, and took back a mortgage for the remainder of the price which ran for 10 years with yearly principal payments of $120,000. Interest on the outstanding balance was to be paid at the rate of 3% per year.
<p>
About five years later, when Abel had $700,000 left to pay on the mortgage, Fairview sold his interest in the mortgage to a broker for $400,000.
<p>
What are the income tax consequences of these events?
<p><br>
<h3>Question 2</h3>

The Federal Government is undertaking a review of the Income Tax Act. The Minister of Finance has heard complaints from various people and groups that the tax treatment of employees is unfair. The Minister is willing to reform the Income Tax Act if he is convinced that changes are necessary. He has asked you to prepare a memorandum relating to the taxation of employees and related issues. He is interested in understanding the present position and any reasoned suggestions which you may make.
<p>Write the memorandum. 
<p><br>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
Valerie operates a mail order book business. Five years ago she purchased the client list of a competitor for $80,000. The vendor agreed not to compete with Valerie in the business. A year later, Valerie decided to focus her business on those clients who lived in Southern Ontario, so she sold that part of the list which contained the names of clients outside Southern Ontario to Tony for $20,000. Valerie's business is going very well so she decided to sell her present office furniture and equipment and buy new equipment to refurnish her office. The new equipment cost $30,000.
<p>
In order to run her business more efficiently, Valerie contracts with LesIey for Lesley to actually distribute the books. In order to do this, Lesley has to spend $8,000 to reconfigure her distribution process. The expenditure is largely to buy the equipment which is dedicated solely to the distribution of Valerie's books. Valerie agrees to pay $5,000 of the $8,000 expenditure plus a set fee for each book distributed by Lesley. 
<p>
Unfortunately, the recession takes its toll on Valerie's business. Earlier this year she was forced to simply leave the business. All she was able to salvage was the furniture which she used in her office. She now uses the furniture in her home. The rest she left to her landlord as payment for the rent she owed him. At the time she got out of the business, she owed her law firm $7,500. The law firm was expanding and moving to new premises. In return for forgiving her debt, the law firm asked Valerie to be its decorating consultant in relation to the new offices. Valerie agreed. The law firm was also happy because it would have cost them over $10,000 to retain a consultant for these purposes. 
<p>
What are the income tax consequences of these events? 
<p><br>
<hr>
