<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Torts A<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Moran</h2></center>
<h3>Notes:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may consult any kind of material you wish during the exam, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<p>
<li>This exam contains 3 questions. <b>All questions must be answered.</b> The value out of one hundred is indicated for each question. Indicated times are suggestions only. The exam is worth 40% of your final grade in torts.
<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing,-count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
<p>
<li><b>Please make sure to double-space your answer and clearly indicate the number of the question.</b>
 </ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>Question 1 (50 marks, approximately one hour)</h3>

One Friday night, Sam Jackson and his friend Bill Mosun were watching television at Sam's house. Sam's parents were out for the evening and the boys had nothing to do. They were bored with the show they were watching and began to discuss what they could do to liven up their evening. Sam had just received his driver's license and was not allowed to take out the family car unless one of his parents was with him. However, his father had been in a hurry
 when he left the house, and he had thrown the keys on the counter just as he was going out the door. Bill noticed this and suggested that they take the car out for a quick spin. Sam was very reluctant. He had already taken the car once without his parents' permission and when his parents caught him, he was prohibited from going out with his friends for a month. However, Bill was enthusiastic about going for a ride and he assured Sam that his parents would never find out. Bill said they could just go to the drive-in and see who was there, grab some food and then
 be back in half an hour. Sam agreed that this sounded like fun so he decided they could take just a quick spin in his parents' car.
<p>
 Sam's family car was a beautiful red 1965 Mustang. Once Sam got behind the wheel, he found it impossible to resist the urge to just see what the car could do. As he drove away from his house, he pressed down on the accelerator. The car lunged forward. Some girls that lived down the street saw Sam and Bill and began to wave and yell at them. They stopped and two of the girls, Sarah and Emily, got into the car. Bill turned up the stereo and before the boys knew it they were cruising out towards the Flats where the hot rods raced. They were having
 a great time.
<p>
They decided that they would run just one race. Sarah got out of the car, but Emily wanted to stay in. Sam revved up the engine and tore down the strip. They were well ahead of the nearest car, when Sam suddenly noticed a dog about to run across the road. He slammed on his brakes. Their car skidded sideways and flipped into the ditch. Fortunately, no one was killed. However, both Bill and Emily were seriously injured. In addition, Mr. Partridge, who had been walking his dog along the highway, was injured when he was thrown into the ditch by the force of the car passing so close to where he was walking. Mr. Partridge did not hear the car because he was almost completely deaf.
<p>
The forensic evidence indicated that when the accident occurred, Sam was driving 20 kilometres above the speed limit and was accelerating rapidly. None of the occupants of the car were wearing seat-belts. There was no indication that any alcohol or any other illegal substances had been consumed.
<p>
Someone in a nearby house called an ambulance. However, because of budgetary cutbacks, there were fewer ambulances available than usual. Therefore the ambulance took over forty-five minutes to get to the scene of the accident--three times as long as the time period indicated in the provincial guidelines. The ambulance took Bill, Sam, Emily, and Mr. Partridge to the hospital.
<p>
When they arrived in the hospital, Dr. Watkins took charge of them. He properly diagnosed and treated the injures of Sam and Mr. Partridge. Unfortunately, while he did diagnose the severe break in Bill's right leg, he did not set the leg properly. Bill's leg never properly healed and he suffered a permanent impairment of his leg. However, it turned out that Bill had a rare bone condition, osteo-nonhealitis. This condition interfered with the normal healing process, with the result when a victim of the disease like Bill suffered a broken bone, there was only a 35% chance that the break would heal even with the best treatment.
<p>
Dr. Watkins also treated Emily who had sustained a head injury. Dr. Watkins diagnosed and treated her properly. Despite this, Emily did not make the recovery that might have been expected. In fact, she suffered some permanent impairment of her vision. However, it is impossible to determine whether this impairment occurred because of the nature of the original accident, because of the delay in treatment or because of some unknown natural causes. The medical experts indicated that they could not get an accurate record of the nature and sources of Emily's difficulty because of the delay in getting her to the hospital.
<p>
<b>As a result of this accident, Bill, Emily and Mr. Partridge are all considering suing in negligence. Your law firm has been retained by Bill, Emily and Mr. Partridge to make a preliminary assessment of the merits of their prospective actions. Please prepare a memorandum of law on this question. Your memo should be organized to first address Bill's ability to recover in negligence for his injuries, then Emily's ability to recover for her injuries and finally, Mr. Partridge's ability to recover for his injuries. If any of these plaintiffs could claim against more than one defendant, you should discuss the merits of their actions against each potential defendant. You should also make sure to discuss any defences that could be raised against any of these plaintiffs. Please explicitly indicate if you believe that you need to know more facts or if you are relying on any factual assumptions that are not contained in the above summary of the facts.</b>
<p><br>
<h3>Question Two (20 Marks, approximately 30 minutes)</h3>

The defendant is a firm of accountants called Tried &amp; True (&quot;Tried&quot;). Tried serves as the auditors and general accountants for Cosmo Cosmetics, plc. In 1987, Tried prepared the annual statutory audit for Cosmo, as it had done for many years. In 1986, the chief financial officer for Cosmo had discussions with Tried about raising capital for a planned expansion. Tried fully supported and indeed encouraged this idea. In fact, Tried released the annual audits of Cosmo's financial statements earlier than usual in order to facilitate Cosmo's efforts to secure investors. But while the financial statements were released early, they were in every respect just the ordinary annual financial statements required by statute.
<p>
Cosmo showed the 1987 financial statement prepared by Tried to several potential investors. Betty Boop had no familiarity with Cosmo but she was very impressed with the financial statements. She decided to invest $50,000 in Cosmo on the strength of the financial statements. However, Cosmo soon ran into financial difficulties. It turned out that Tried had mistakenly treated a $300,000 liability as an asset. The result was that while financial statements showed that the business was prospering, in fact it was operating at a loss. Unfortunately, Cosmo soon went out of business and Ms. Boop lost the entire $50,000 she had invested.
<p>
Ms. Boop brought an action in negligence against Tried. At trial it was found that Tried was negligent in preparing the financial statement and that they owed Ms. Boop a duty of care.  The Court of Appeal has affirmed. Tried has now appealed to the House of Lords. The only issue before the House of Lord is whether or not Tried owed Ms. Boop a duty of care. It has been agreed by the parties that if they do owe her a duty of care, they will be liable to compensate her for the loss she suffered when she invested in Cosmo.
<p>
However, it is now 1990, and the House of Lords has just handed down their decision in <cite>Caparo v. Dickman</cite> (in Volume IV of your torts materials at p. VIII-53 ff).
<p>
<b>Assume that you are a member of the House of Lords (if you wish, you may specify which Law Lord you are). Please write your judgment in Boop v. Tried on the issue of whether or not Tried owed Ms. Boop a duty of care. You may, of course, make reference to any material that you believe is relevant (including decisions from other jurisdictions) but you should pay particular attention to the very recent House of Lords decision in <cite>Caparo</cite>.</b>
<p>
<h3>Question Three (30 Marks, approximately 45 minutes)</h3>

In a recent article entitled &quot;The Uneasy Place of Principle in Tort Law&quot;, George C. Christie describes what he takes to be a central dilemma of the negligence inquiry:
<blockquote>
One could continue to maintain that tort law should be directed by clear statements of principle but that the principle of reasonable foreseeability is not the correct one. Or one could insist that the principle of reasonable foreseeability is the correct one but that the courts have made a hash of it. I do not think that either of these alternatives will work. To my mind the principle of 'reasonable foreseeability' is a good one; it just cannot do all the work demanded of it. Moreover, I am extremely doubtful that any better general principle of tort liability could be formulated.
</blockquote>
Discuss this passage. Is Christie's point persuasive? Discuss why it is or why it is not making reference to cases and other materials that we have covered in the course where they are relevant to your analysis.
<p><br>
