<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1996 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Torts I<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor E. Weinrib</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts.
<p>
<li>This is a three-hour examination. There are three questions of equal weight. All three questions must be answered. 
<p>
<li><b>PLEASE WRITE ON ALTERNATE LINES.</b>
<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course  name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet- If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<b>1.</b> Darth and Delendum are companies that have for decades been drilling for oil on lands that are north and south of each other. This oil drilling is the mainstay of the local economy.
<p>
Oil drilling produces vast quantities of brine. There is no market for this brine, and the prevailing practice among oil drilling companies is to place it in large steel tanks so that it will not pollute the neighbouring groundwater. Darth and Delendum used earthen pits instead of steel tanks. Their reason for using earthen pits, which are much cheaper than steel tanks, is that all the land that is adjacent to theirs sits on a huge zone of limestone. Scientists had advised
 them in accordance with the best scientific evidence that limestone is not porous, and so, because there was no chance that the brine would pollute their neighbours' groundwater, the more expensive steel tanks were unnecessary.
<p>
 Recently the Partridge family purchased what used to be grazing land to the west of Darth and Delendum. The Partridges built a house on the land and sunk a well to have drinking water. They soon noticed that their drinking water was quite salty. It turned out that contrary to the expectation of the scientists the salt from the brine pits had somehow worked its way through the limestone barrier and had contaminated the Partridge's groundwater. The evidence, however, also indicates that the groundwater was full of natural contaminants and would perhaps not have been drinkable in any case.
<p>
 The jurisdiction has a statute that reads: &quot;No person shall allow waste to pollute the waters of this province without first giving it the treatment necessary to safeguard the legitimate beneficial uses of such waters.&quot; The statute imposes a fine for violations.
<p>
Discuss the legal issues raised by a tort action by the Partridges against Darth and Delendum. Discuss also the contribution issues that arise between Darth and Delendum if both are held liable. (A copy of the statutory provisions governing contribution is appended to this examination). In answering this question, assess the soundness of the applicable law where appropriate, and if you think a court might come to an unjust conclusion suggest reasoned criticisms and reasoned alternatives.
<p><br>
<b>2.</b> Patricia and her partner had decided that they did not want (and could not afford) to have any more children and that they also wanted to avoid the inconvenience of using contraceptives. One day Patricia picked up a pamphlet that was available in the display section of her pharmacy. The pamphlet, entitled Voluntary Sterilization -- The Surest Way to Avoid Unwanted Pregnancy" was published and circulated by the Children-by-Choice Association. The pamphlet was organized in a question and answer format and stated at one point: 
<blockquote>
&quot;Q. Should contraceptives be used after tubal ligation?&quot;
<p>
A. No. There is no possibility of pregnancy and contraceptives are not necessary.&quot;
</blockquote>
Accordingly, on her next visit to her gynaecologist, Dr. Dense, she arranged to undergo a tubal ligation. Nevertheless, several months after Dr. Dense performed the operation Patricia became pregnant and gave birth to a healthy child.
<p>
In fact, the statement made in the pamphlet was incorrect. There is a known but small failure rate even in properly performed operations due to the spontaneous regeneration of the fallopian tubes. Moreover, in outlining the procedure to Patricia Dr. Dense had failed to mention the possibility that the operation might not terminate her ability to have a child.
<p>
Patricia now wishes to sue both Children-by-Choice and Dr. Dense. She claims that she would not have undergone the procedure had she been told that pregnancy remained remotely possible. However, it is impossible to tell whether the pregnancy resulted from the spontaneous regeneration of the fallopian tubes or whether it resulted from improper performance of the procedure by Dr. Dense.
<p>
Discuss the legal issues raised by Patricia's action against Children-by-Choice and Dr. Dense. In answering this question, assess the soundness of the applicable law where appropriate, and if you think a court might come to an unjust conclusion, suggest reasoned criticisms and reasoned alternatives.
<p><br>
<b>3.</b> The editor of the prestigious journal, The Legal Beagle of Canada, has asked you to write a comment on the following case. She knows that you have been intensively studying tort law at one of the best half dozen law schools in Ontario. She accordingly considers you a &quot;natural&quot; for commenting on this important judgment. You are given the liberty to comment on any aspect(s) of the judgment that seem to you to be interesting or significant.
<p>
Write the first draft of the comment. (Do not repeat the facts.)
<blockquote>
BOLD SPIRIT J.: The facts in this case are elemental. After a tragic quarrel between Mr. Lear and his daughter Cordelia (the plaintiff in the present case), Mr. F Lear executed a will cutting Cordelia out of his estate and leaving his entire fortune to his other two daughters, Goneril and Regan. Lear and Cordelia were subsequently reconciled, and Lear then instructed his solicitor, Mr. Kent (the defendant), to prepare a new will dividing his estate equally among his three daughters. Kent neglected to act on these instructions, and before the new will was prepared and executed, Lear died. After Lear's death, his estate went to Goneril and Regan in accordance with the existing will, and they refused -- as was their legal right -- to give Cordelia the share that their father intended her to have. Cordelia now sues Kent, claiming that the negligent delay has deprived her of the benefits to which she would have been entitled under the new will. It is acknowledged on all sides that if Kent owed Cordelia a duty, he negligently breached it. The question if is: did he owe her a duty?
<p>
 On hearing this case, my first inclination was to answer in the negative. Although here the plaintiff is fortunate in having been able to establish that the final intentions of the testator in the present case were firm, clear and attainable, such damage is generally too speculative and uncertain to be recoverable. The intention to benefit the plaintiff usually exists only in the mind of the testator, so that the solicitor's negligence harms only the plaintiff's hope and expectation, and not any existing financial or other interest.
<p>
Moreover, the duty that Kent was under appears to be a contractual one only, and owed to the person who retained and instructed him, Lear, rather than to the intended beneficiary. To allow the plaintiff to recover in tort might seem a circumvention of the rule against third party beneficiaries in contract.
<p>
Finally, if the law gave effect to Lear's wishes, it would effectively increase the size of his estate by the sum awarded to Cordelia at Kent's expense. No one can tell precisely how Lear would have wished to dispose of an estate thus augmented. What is plain is that the family as a whole would be better off because of Kent's negligence.
<p>
These considerations initially led me to wonder whether a decision in favour of the plaintiff would represent a departure from accepted principles of compensation. I have, however, concluded that they should not stand in the way of the simple justice of Cordelia's claim.
<p>
 Before addressing the legal questions at the heart of the present case, it is desirable to identify the reasons of justice that prompt me to conclude that a duty should be owed by the testator's solicitor to a disappointed beneficiary. The
 principal reasons are as follows.
<p>
 (1) In the forefront stands the extraordinary fact that, if such a duty is not recognised, the only persons who might have a valid claim (i.e., the testator and his estate) have suffered no loss, and the only person who has suffered a loss (i.e., the disappointed beneficiary) has no claim. It can therefore be said that, if the solicitor owes no duty to the intended beneficiaries, there is a lacuna in the law that needs to be filled. This I regard as being a point of cardinal importance in the present case.
<p>(2) The injustice of denying such a remedy is reinforced if one considers the importance of legacies in a society which recognises the right of citizens to leave their assets to whom they please, and in which, as a result, legacies can be of great importance to individual citizens, providing very often the only opportunity for a citizen to acquire a significant capital sum. It is where a testator instructs a small firm of solicitors that mistakes of this kind are most likely to occur, with the result that it tends to be people of modest means, who need the money so badly, who suffer.
<p>
(3) Solicitors cannot complain if such a liability may be imposed. If one of them has been negligent in such a way as to defeat his client's testamentary intentions, he must regard himself as very lucky indeed if the effect of the law is that he is not liable to pay damages in the ordinary way. It can involve no injustice to render him subject to such a liability.
<p>
I turn now to the law, which we must consider against the background of recent developments. Within a few decades our law has changed from a blanket denial of recovery for economic loss to a more liberal regime. I need only mention the well-known cases of CNR v Norsk and Winnipeg Condominium v. Bird.
<p>
In this case, the defendant is under a duty of care to the plaintiff arising from an extension of the principle of  assumption of responsibility explored in Hedley Byrne &amp; Co Ltd v Heller &amp; Partners Ltd. In my view, although the present case is not directly covered by the decided cases, the law in this area has not ossified. 
<p>
It is legitimate to extend the law to the limited extent proposed using the incremental approach by way of analogy advocated in Caparo Industries v. Dickman. 
<p>
A duty of care arises if there is a special relationship between the parties. The categories of cases in which such a special relationship can be held to exist are not closed. The special relationship is created by the defendant voluntarily assuming to act in the matter by involving himself in the plaintiff's affairs or by choosing to speak. If he does so assume to act or speak he is said to have assumed responsibility for carrying through the matter he has entered upon. 
<p>
The solicitor who accepts instructions to draw a will knows that the future economic welfare of the intended beneficiary is dependent upon his careful execution of the task. It is true that the intended beneficiary (being ignorant of the instructions) may not rely on the particular solicitor's actions. But the solicitor by accepting the instructions has entered upon, and therefore assumed responsibility for, the task of procuring the execution of a skillfully drawn will knowing that the beneficiary is wholly dependent upon his carefully carrying out his function. That assumption of responsibility for the task is a feature of all the categories of special relationship so far identified in the authorities.
<p>
Moreover, it is fair, just and reasonable to impose liability on the solicitor. Or The proper transmission of property from one generation to the next is dependent upon the due discharge by solicitors of their duties. Although in any particular case it may not be possible to demonstrate that the intended beneficiary relied upon the solicitor, society as a whole does rely on solicitors to carry out their will-making functions carefully.
<p>
Further, even apart from the decided cases the law should recognize the unique features of the present litigation and should fashion an effective remedy to repair the injustice to the disappointed beneficiary. In the case of a negligently drawn will, the will has no effect at all until the death. It will have been filed away, not to surface again until the testator either wishes to vary it or dies. In the majority of cases the negligence will lie hidden until it takes effect on the death of the testator, i.e., at the very point in time when normally the error will become incapable of remedy.
<p>
It seems to me that it is open to this court to fashion a remedy to fill a lacuna in the law and so prevent the injustice which would otherwise occur on the facts of cases such as the present. It is mere practical justice to make available a tort remedy to the intended beneficiary who (as the solicitor can reasonably foresee) may, as a result of the solicitor's negligence, be deprived of his intended legacy in circumstances in which neither the testator nor his estate will have a remedy against the solicitor. Such a remedy would merely provide an incentive through tort law for the solicitor to do what he is in any case contractually obligated to do. Moreover, the fact that all solicitors have malpractice insurance means that the costs of the solicitor's negligence, instead of being concentrated on the disappointed beneficiary, will be spread through the all users of legal services.
<p>
A famous judge once remarked that, at bottom, the existence of a duty is an issue of policy for the judge to decide. There is no more worthy policy than the pursuit of justice. To my mind it would be unacceptable if, because of some technical rules of law, the wishes and expectations of testators and beneficiaries generally could be defeated by the negligent actions of solicitors without there being any redress. If justice requires that a duty exist, courts should declare what justice requires. 
<p>
In the result, the problems that initially troubled me can be seen to fade innocuously away. Cases such as this call for an appropriate remedy, and the common law is not so sterile as to be incapable of supplying that remedy when it is needed.
<p>
For these reasons I hold that the defendant breached a duty owed to the plaintiff.
</blockquote>
<center><h3>Negligence Act</h3></center>
<ol>
<li>In this Act,<br>
(a) &quot;action&quot; includes a counterclaim;
<p>
(b) &quot;defendant&quot; includes a plaintiff against whom a counterclaim is brought;
<p>
(c) &quot;plaintiff&quot; includes a defendant who counterclaims. 
<p>
<li>Where damages have been caused or contributed to by the fault or neglect of two or more persons, the court shall determine the degree in which each of such persons is at fault or negligent, and, where two or more persons are found at fault or negligent, they are jointly and severally liable to the person suffering loss or damage for such fault or negligence, but as between themselves, in the absence of a contract express or implied, each is liable to make contribution and indemnify each other in the degree in which they are respectively found to be at fault or negligent.
<p>
<li>A tort feasor may recover contribution or indemnity from any other tort feasor who is, or would if sued have been, liable in respect of the damage to any person suffering damage as a result of a tort by settling with the person suffering such damage, and thereafter commencing or continuing action against such other tort feasor, in which event the tort feasor settling the damage shall satisfy the court that the amount of the settlement was reasonable, and in the event that the court finds the amount of the settlement was excessive it may fix the amount at which the claim should have been settled.
</ol>
<p><br>
