<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Torts II<br>
April 1996<br>
Bruce Chapman</h2></center>
<h3>Instructions :</h3>
<ol>
<li>This is an open book examination. That means you may use any materials at all except materials borrowed from the library.
<p>
<li>There are two questions. <b>Question one</b> is worth <b>65%</b> of the final mark and <b>question two</b> is worth <b>35%</b>. Allocate your time accordingly.
<p>
<li><b>Please</b> write legibly, <b>double space</b> your written answer, and write on one side of the page only. <b>Begin each question in a new examination booklet</b>, indicating the question on the booklet cover.
<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<p>
<li>During the test, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the test.
<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the test has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>QUESTION ONE (65 marks)</h3>

Of The Windrush River meanders south through Flavelle County and eventually flows into the saltwater of Heron Sound. It is a beautiful area and has long been a place for tourists to visit for a bit of holiday fun and seafood. Many years ago there was a regular passenger ferry, the Sea Star, which operated across the mouth of the river, connecting the holiday towns of West Heron and East Heron. However, the ferry service fell into disuse in the 1960s, and the Sea Star was simply moored alongside the West Heron pier, operating there as a souvenir shop.
<p>
Last summer Zak, a Toronto entrepreneur, decided to revive the old ferry service. Not having the cash for an outright purchase of the ferry, he decided to lease the Sea Star from Madge, its longtime owner. Madge also agreed to sell the piers in both West Heron and East Heron to Zak so long as her cousin Sue was given an exclusive long term lease to open oyster bars (or restaurants) for the local tourists on both the West Heron and East Heron piers. This was a way, thought Madge, of keeping some of the benefits of the re-opened ferry service in the family. Zak was also delighted to agree, thinking that this would help to integrate a ferry ride and an oyster dinner into a very attractive &quot;evening out&quot; for the tourists. He also offered to pay all of the maintenance and repair costs for the Sea Star for the summer.
<p>
Now the idea that Zak was going to revive the old Sea Star for his new ferry service was a source of some amusement for the local inhabitants of West and East Heron. No one figured that the ferry's old wooden hull, now somewhat rotted, would make it past midsummer. They tried to tell Zak this, of course, but Zak seemed to think that he would be fine. Zak was more concerned about possible underwater hazards in the river crossing between West and East Heron and asked Cal, a local official for the Heron Sound Sea Rescue and Safety Service, about this. Cal, who knew Heron Sound quite well but almost nothing about the Windrush River, replied, &quot;Oh, there should be no problem for you. Just keep to the port side of the channel. There are some rocks on the other side.&quot; Now Zak, who fancied himself to be a bit of a sailor, thought Cal meant the port (or left) side of the channel going from West to East Heron. After all, they were standing on the West Heron pier at the time of the conversation. But Cal, being even more the sailor than Zak, actually meant the port (or left) side going from East to West Heron since that is the way the current runs within the channel and it has long been the custom for seasoned sailors in Flavelle County (and elsewhere) to define the channel (and all directions through it) as running in the direction of the current.
<p>
The first day of Zak's new venture was June 21, l995, the first day of summer, and Zak decided to launch things with a big party for his friends from Toronto. Everybody had a little too much to drink at Sue's West Heron pier &quot;Sea Star Oyster Bar&quot; before getting onto the Sea Star for the inaugural trip over to East Heron. There was even more to drink on the ferry, and since Zak's Toronto friends had brought some uninvited friends of their own, the Sea Star was very much overloaded. While the Sea Star had a sufficient number of lifejackets for a ferry of
 its size according to s. 10 of Flavelle County's <cite>Water Safety Act</cite>, on this particular trip, due to the very unusual circumstances, there were twice the number of passengers as available lifejackets. 
<p>
The trip went well until the Sea Star was halfway across the river from West to East Heron. At that point, one of the drunken passengers (no one now knows who) on the port side shouted "Whale!" Although there had never been a whale sighting in the Windrush River, almost everyone rushed over to the port side of the Sea Star to have a look. This caused the ferry to lurch abruptly to port and to veer towards those very rocks that Cal had tried so unsuccessfully to warn Zak about. There was, almost immediately, a crunching sound as the Sea Star appeared to go aground on the rocks. The Sea Star quickly took on water and began to sink. The passengers grabbed lifejackets where they could and jumped into the water. 
<p>
We now have a complete account of this tragic affair. Of the 60 people on board, 30 managed to get hold of the 30 lifejackets that were available before going overboard, but half of these were drowned anyway. All of the other 30 passengers who did not get lifejackets have drowned. The Sea Star has sunk to the bottom of the river. However, it is now unclear whether the ferry first took on water because of her initial contact with the submerged rocks, or whether the ferry's lurch to port when the passengers rushed to that side to see the whale caused some cargo to shift in the Sea Star's hold and to go crashing through its thin wooden, and slightly rotted, hull. This also could have been enough for it to sink and to eventually come to rest and be damaged on the rocks. 
<p>
As it happens, the Sea Star was carrying some very special and unexpected cargo in its hold. Back in Toronto, Zak had long been storing about forty barrels of toxic waste on an old site near Falconer Hall. He had seen the inaugural voyage of the Sea Star as a first-rate opportunity to dump the waste offshore in Heron Sound. His plan had been to drop the ferry passengers off at East Heron for some further revelry and to steam out into the Sound to make the dump, returning for the passengers later. All this, of course, was strictly illegal according to Flavelle County's <cite>Toxic Waste Dumping Act</cite>. Only the sinking of the Sea Star had foiled the plan. 
<p>
But this was the cargo which had shifted in the hold of the ferry and now, at the bottom of the river, these barrels of toxic waste have begun to leak into the river. As a consequence, certain oyster beds owned by Sam near the mouth of the river, where it empties into the salt water of Heron Sound, have become contaminated. Sam normally sells all his oysters to Sue's two oyster bars but now cannot. Sue has secured, at greater expense, an alternative supply of oysters, but, unfortunately, a local newspaper, <cite>Shell Shock</cite>, has published a detailed story with the headline &quot;Heron Sound Oysters Contaminated with Toxic Waste&quot;. The headlined story, without all the details, has been picked up by the national press and now no tourist wants to buy any oysters in West or East Heron. Indeed, since the ferry accident, Sue hasn't had much trade of any kind, oysters or otherwise. After all, the ferry connection was to be very important for her business on the two piers and without a ferry, and without oysters, few tourists are keen to visit the Heron Sound area much at all.
<p>
Zak has approached you for legal advice. While he recognizes that he may have done to some things that were wrong, and may be sued by any or all of Sue, Sam, Madge, and the estate of Fred (one of the 30 passengers who died without a lifejacket), he is also of the view that others might be responsible. Indeed, he thinks that he should have a legal remedy himself for his lost profits on the summer ferry service. Advise him.
<p><br>
<h3>QUESTION TWO (35 marks)</h3>
<blockquote>
&quot;There is, of course, something which is initially quite attractive about tort liability. It seems right that a person wrongfully injured by another should be able to hold that other party personally accountable in a private law action for damages. Moreover, it seems appropriate that the correction of what is a personal wrong between them should not be much affected by social interests and public policy.
<p>
But the abstract promise of this view quickly unravels when it is executed in the cases. Soon we begin to observe that what is right, or (to use the legal jargon) &quot;reasonable&quot;, between the parties is pretty much conditioned by a set of social understandings which are, in the final analysis, nothing more nor less than matters of public policy and social calculation. For example, nuisance defendants simply are permitted to harm plaintiffs if &quot;the local standard&quot; says so. Economic loss either is or is not recoverable according to how society happens to understand &quot;the ambit of the risk&quot;. And the standard of &quot;reasonable prudence&quot; can be as subjective (and forgiving) or objective (and strict) as we want in the circumstances. To pretend otherwise, and to pretend in particular that there is really anything here other than the very same practical politics that informs social legislation, is mere self-delusion. What <b>is</b> problematic is that this legislation is effected by an unelected, unaccountable, and unrepresentative judiciary.&quot; 
</blockquote>
Comment on the overall merits of this claim using examples and materials taken from the course. 
<p><br>
