<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Trusts<br>
April 1996<br>
Professor Moran</h2></center>
<h3>Notes:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may consult any kind of material you wish during the exam, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<p>
<li>This exam contains 4 questions. <b>All questions must be answered.</b> The value of each question is shown in the margin.
<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
<p>
<li><b>Please make sure to double-space your answer and clearly indicate the number of the question.</b>
</ol>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>Question One (30 Marks)</h3>

Thomas Lee had three children. His wife had died when the children were very young. Thomas's sister Lucy moved in with Thomas after his wife died to help him take care of the children. Lucy had continued to live with Thomas and the children. In July of 1994, Thomas told his sister Lucy that he wanted to speak with her about some important matters. Lucy was so overcome with emotion during this conversation that she could barely speak. She could only sob and nod as Thomas spoke.
<p>
First of all, Thomas told Lucy that he was giving her the jewellery that had been in his wife's family for generations. He said that the jewellery was very valuable and therefore it should be kept secure and not worn or used by anyone until both of his daughters were 25. Then he said that he wanted her to divide the jewellery equally between the two girls so that they would have some momentos of their mother. However, Thomas never delivered the jewellery to Lucy and it remained in his safety deposit box.
<p>
In addition, Thomas also told Lucy that he was going to leave her the family house. He stated that he wanted her to be able to live in and enjoy the house. He said that when she died the house was to go to the three children.
<p>
Thirdly, Thomas told Lucy that he was giving her the shares in the Sunnyhill Cooperative. He said that he had made a note of what he wanted her to do with these shares. His note said:
<blockquote>
I give my shares in the Sunnyhill Cooperative absolutely to my sister Lucy. Lucy is free to do anything she chooses with the shares. However, when the youngest child turns 21, Lucy is to divide any of the remaining shares evenly between herself and the three children.
</blockquote>
The by-laws of Sunnyhill Cooperative required that in order to effect a valid transfer the shares had to be endorsed and delivered to the new owner and the Board of Directors of the Cooperative had to approve the transfer. Thomas endorsed the shares certificates to Lucy and delivered them to her. He also applied to the cooperative to have the
 shares transferred into Lucy's name. However, it took some time for the board to approve the transfer. In the interim, Thomas continued to receive the dividends from the shares. He used these dividends to purchase further cooperative shares which he put into Lucy's name. Unfortunately, Thomas died before the Board of Directors approved the transfer of the shares.
<p>
When Thomas died, Lucy went to see the family solicitor. She told him about her interview with Thomas and about what he had said about the jewellery, the shares, and the family home. Thomas had executed a valid will. It was dated September 12,1994. Lucy became the administratrix of Thomas's estate. The will made no mention of the
 jewellery or of the Sunnyhill shares. However, there was a clause of the will in which Thomas stated that he left the family home to his sister Lucy, &quot;fully trusting that she will carry out my instructions.&quot; Under other terms of the will, Thomas provided for his sister Lucy and for his three children. Thomas left the residue of his estate to his wife's sister Alba.
<p>
<b>Lucy has consulted you to determine whether she has legal title to the jewellery, the Sunnyhill shares, or the family home. She also wants to know whether she has any obligations with respect to any of this property. Please advise Lucy on these matters.</b>
<p><br>
<h3>Question Two (15 Marks)</h3>

In his majority decision in McPhail v. Doulton, Lord Wilberforce states (at p.4-20 of your materials):
<blockquote>
As a matter of reason, to hold that a principle of equal division applies to a trust such as the present is certainly paradoxical. Equal division is surely the last thing the settlor ever intended: equal division among all may, probably would, produce a result beneficial to none. Why suppose the court would lend itself to a whimsical execution? And as regards authority, I do not find that the nature of the trust, and of the court's powers over trusts, ever called for any such rigid rule. Equal division may be sensible and has been decreed, in cases of family trusts, for a limited class; here there is life in the maxim &quot;equality is equity,&quot; but the cases provide numerous examples where this has not been so, and a different type of execution has been ordered, appropriate to the circumstances&quot;
</blockquote>
<b>Comment on the significance of the above passage, addressing why Lord Wilberforce is discussing the maxim &quot;equality is equity&quot;, what he determines about  that maxim, and what the signficance of this aspect of his holding is for the test for certainty of objects.</b>
<p><br>
<h3>Question 3 (40 Marks)</h3>

Teresa, the testatrix, had been an active Roman Catholic all of her life. She was also a member of a movement for reform in the area of women's rights within the church. Her will contained a number of legacies. Under the terms of her will, the residue of her estate went in equal proportions to her nieces, Estelle and Eunice.
<p>
Her first legacy provided for the establishment of a Roman Catholic school for girls. Although the stipulated area already contained a number of Catholic schools, including schools for Catholic girls, Teresa strongly believed that there was still an unfulfilled need for a Catholic girls' school. The terms of her will set out very carefully the purpose of the school which was to provide Roman Catholic girls with a feminist education. To that end, she specified that the work of women be studied in all of the core courses, including literature, history, science and religion. She further specified that the health courses should include information about gay and lesbian issues and about birth control, AIDS, and abortion.
<p>
In addition, Teresa stated that at least 70% of the faculty of the school be female. She provided for the school to be run by a managing foundation which was composed of at least 70% women and she also ensured that a substantial proportion of the managing foundation be pro-choice on abortion and on sexual orientation. This foundation was to be run under the larger auspices of the diocese in which Teresa lived. 
<p>
The Bishop of the diocese brought an application to the court to have the money applied to the already existing Catholic schools on the ground that the population of the area would never support such a school. He noted that the population of the diocese was only 3,500, most of whom were devout Irish Catholics. 
<p>
The second legacy in Teresa's will provided for $75,000 of her estate to be left in trust to the &quot;Catholic Beneficial Society&quot; in her diocese for its work in relieving the suffering of the members of the diocese who lived in poverty, for the education of the children of the needy members of the diocese, and to provide for counselling and consciousness-raising activities for Catholic women who were having family or personal difficulties or who wanted to leave abusive situations. The terms stated that the legacy was to be divided equally among these three purposes. The President and Board of the Society were given absolute discretion concerning how to apply the funds to each of these purposes. There is no such body as the &quot;Catholic Beneficial Society&quot; in Teresa's diocese. However, there is a &quot;Catholic Benevolent Society&quot; and Teresa was a lifelong member of this society. It is an unincorporated body whose purposes were to provide any necessary assistance to members of the diocese and their families and to provide a meeting place and to provide social activities for Catholic members of the diocese.
<p>
The Bishop of the diocese has also applied to the court on behalf of the Catholic Benevolent Society. He is asking for guidance on the validity of this trust. 
<p>
<b>The judge who is to hear this application has asked you to prepare a bench memo. In addition to addressing the validity of the legacies under the relevant law, she also wants you to comment critically on any areas where there may be reasons to reconsider the legal position on a given issue.</b>
<p><br>
<h3>Question Four (15 Marks)</h3>

Susan was a journalist. She had a twenty year old daughter named Lisa who she had raised on her own. Lisa was at university now, but she returned home to live with Susan during the summers. They lived in rental housing for many years. However, in 1990, Susan decided that it was time for her to buy a house. She was fortunate enough to happen on a Victorian house that she loved. However it was more expensive than she had anticipated and it required a substantial amount of work. Susan's mother had always told her that she would help her with a house and so Susan asked her mother if she might consider making a contribution. Susan's mother readily agreed and contributed $10,000 towards the purchase price.
<p>
Susan and her mother did not ever discuss paying back the money, perhaps because it was clear that Susan had spent virtually all of her savings on the house and she was currently spending most of her income on mortgage payments and renovations.
<p>
In 1991, Susan met Pat. They hit it off immediately and Pat soon moved into Susan's house. In 1993, Susan was investigating a series of articles about a very wealthy businessman with reputed links to organized crime. She was concerned about the possibility of a libel action and she knew that the magazine maintained very limited libel coverage. Therefore, on the advice of the magazine's lawyer, she transferred the house to Lisa and Pat, as tenants in common in equal shares. However, Susan's fears were unfounded and no libel action was ever launched or even threatened.
<p>
Unfortunately, Susan was killed in a mysterious car accident some months after her series appeared. In her will, Susan left a number of legacies, providing for Lisa, her mother, and some other relations. Her will was made before she purchased the house and so it made no mention either of the house or of Pat. Susan left the residue of her estate to PEN International, a registered Canadian charity.
<p>
Susan's father, who is the executor of her estate, has asked Lisa and Pat to convey the property to him so that it can be included in the estate and administered under the terms of the will. Lisa and Pat have both refused to do so. They both claim a property interest in the house. Susan's mother has also made a claim that she is entitled to 10% of the value of the house because of the $10,000 she gave Susan (the purchase price of the house was $100,000)
<p>
<b>Susan's father has consulted you to determine whether Pat, Lisa or Susan's mother can claim any interest in respect of the house. Please advise him on this matter.</b>
<p><br>
