<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Business Organizations I<br>
Winter 1995<br>
Professor Macintosh</h2></center>
<h3>INSTRUCTIONS</h3>
<ol><i>
<li>This is a take-home examination. It can be picked up at any of the times posted on the bulletin board by Pat Ward.<p>
<li>There is only one restriction on the materials you may use. Because not everyone can have simultaneous access to library materials, I would prefer that you not use anything from the library collection. Previously taken photocopies do not violate the letter or spirit of this rule.<p>
<li>In accordance with the Faculty Council resolution of Oct. 6, 1993, you may consult with other students in the course of working out your answer. However, please note that this resolution also provides that &quot;the answer or answers returned by the students must be organized and written by that student alone&quot;. I ask that you follow the spirit, as well as the letter of this rule.<p>
<li>There are two parts. The first part consists of questions to be answered true/false, with an explanation, and there are 9 questions, each worth 2 marks (except for question 9, which is worth 4 marks). The second part is a single question worth 80 marks. Note carefully that there is a word limit of 3500 words for the whole exam. <b>Anything which you write in excess of 3500 words will not be read.</b> Be forewarned that this penalty will be enforced with absolute strictness, in fairness to those students who make a conscientious effort to observe the word limit. In the past, I have downgraded at least two &quot;A&quot; papers to a &quot;C&quot; for significantly exceeding the word limit, and have downgraded many more a half or a whole grade. l make word count estimates for every paper (this is not a bluff: I hire a graduate student to do word counts): you should make your own word count estimate and <b>put this on the font of your answer.</b><p>
<li>I would prefer that you type your examination answer. However, this is not required. If you write your answer, <b>please</b> make sure that it is legible, and written on <b>every other line</b>. If you choose, you may submit a handwritten copy of your answer and later submit a typed copy, within a week (or, if the law school closes before a week has elapsed from the date when you wrote the exam, then on the first day of classes when the law school reopens in January. However, if you intend to do so, please mark in a clearly visible place on your handwritten copy, &quot;TYPED COPY TO FOLLOW&quot;.
<p>
Typewritten copies of already submitted exam answers will be checked for accuracy against the handwritten original. If any part of your handwritten copy is illegible, then the typed part which corresponds with that part <b>will not be read</b>. If anything of substance appears in the typewritten copy which does not appear in the handwritten original, your exam will not be read, period.<p>
<li>I place a high premium on <b>organization and clarity</b>. Answers which have been well thought out and well organized typically receive a higher grade.<p>
<li>You may feel that in answering the question you sometimes have to cover the same material twice. Rather than repeating yourself, feel free to incorporate by reference part of your earlier discussion.<p>
<li>You need deal only with those issues raised in the course!<p>
<li>You may assume that all corporations in this exam are incorporated under the OBCA, unless otherwise indicated.<p>
<li>Feel free to use point form if that helps you economize on your total word count. Note, however, that this can interfere with the flow and comprehensibility of your answer.<p>
<li>Please do NOT use footnotes (or endnotes). All of your answer (including case names, etc.) should go into the text. This makes for easier reading.
</i></ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<h3>PART I (20 marks; 2 marks per question, except 4 marks for question 9)<p>
INDICATE WHICH OF THE FOLLOWING STATEMENTS ARE TRUE OR FALSE: BRIEFLY EXPLAIN YOUR CHOICE (AGAIN, POINT FORM IS SATISFACTORY).</h3>
<ol>
<li>In a memorandum of association jurisdiction, the memorandum of association may transfer the power to declare dividends to a committee of shareholders.
<p>
<li>The directors may declare dividends only in cash or property of the corporation.
<p>
<li>Preferred shares necessarily have <b>both</b> a preferential right (vis-a-vis the common shares) to the income stream and a preferential right to assets on winding up.
<p>
<li>The directors may create series of shares within a class, such that the various series of shares do not have identical rights.
<p>
<li>At common law, majority shareholder ratification of directorial wrongdoing constitutes a complete bar to a shareholder suit.
<p>
<li>A dissident shareholder wishing to solicit shareholders must send a dissident's shareholder circular to all shareholders of the corporation.
<p>
<li>Under a unanimous shareholders' agreement transferring some or all of the directors' powers to a committee of shareholders, the shareholders assume fiduciary duties to the company and to other shareholders.
<p>
<li>A corporation may have the following share structure:
<p>
Class A shares: 10 votes per share, but not entitled to receive any dividends or any of the property of the corporation upon dissolution.
<p>
Class B shares: Non-voting, entitled to receive a preferential dividend of $5 per share before any other class of shares is entitled to receive a dividend, and entitled to return of stated capital plus $10 upon winding up or dissolution.
<p>
Class C shares: Non-voting, with right to receive dividends as declared by the directors after payment of any preferential dividend, and residual claim to the property of the corporation upon winding up or dissolution.
<p>
<li>ABC Corp. proposes an amalgamation between itself and XYZ Corp. Both ABC and XYZ have two classes of shares: voting common shares and non-voting preferred shares. Under the terms of the amalgamation, the preferred shares of both ABC and XYZ would be replaced by new classes of preferred shares in Amalco, the corporation formed from the merger of ABC and XYZ. The preferred shares given to the preferred shareholders of ABC would be exactly the same as they had before, except that they will be subordinated in their entitlement to dividends and assets on winding up to the class of preferred shares given to the preferred shareholders of XYZ. The class of preferred shares in Amalco given to the preferred shareholders of XYZ will be identical in all respects to those they had before. The preferred shareholders of ABC may submit a shareholder proposal relating to the amalgamation, but the preferred shareholders of XYZ may not.
</ol><p><br>
<h3>PART II</h3>
Emperor's New Clothes Corp. (referred to below as &quot;ENC Corp.&quot;) makes clothing. It has one class of common shares, which trade on the Toronto Stock Exchange. Fran Farkle, the founder, Chief Executive Officer, and Chairwoman of the board of directors of ENC Corp., owns 20% of the 100,000 issued and outstanding common shares. The rest of the shares are widely held, including however 6 blocks of 5% held by institutional investors (i.e. banks, insurance companies, etc.; these are referred to below as the &quot;institutional blockholders&quot;). ENC Corp. manufactures clothes.
<p>
Farkle desired to invest money in a new business but was strapped for cash. She had also heard rumours that a hostile takeover bid for ENC was in the offing. At a board meeting described below, she therefore proposed that the corporation do a &quot;dual class recapitalization&quot;, pursuant to which the existing common equity would be divided into two classes, one voting, and the other non-voting. Under this proposal, each holder of 1 common share would receive 1 Class A common share, which would have 1 vote per share, and 10 Class B common shares, which would be non-voting. Aside from voting rights, the two classes of shares would be identical in all respects (e.g. re entitlement to dividends, assets on winding up, etc.). Both classes would be listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange. Farkle then planned to sell all of her Class B shares over the stock exchange, and use part of the proceeds to purchase (also over the stock exchange) a majority of the Class A shares. This would not only consolidate her control, but would leave part of the proceeds of the sale of her Class B shares to invest in her new business.
<p>
The board of directors of ENC consists of 9 directors, 4 of whom are &quot;insiders&quot; (i.e. officers of ENC), and 5 of whom are &quot;outsiders&quot; (i.e. not officers of ENC). Of these five outsiders, two are past business associates of Fran Farkle who have no current business ties to either Farkle or ENC Corp. One is the CEO of a large corporation, who also has no current business ties either to Farkle or ENC Corp. The fourth serves as lawyer to both Farkle and ENC Corp., while the fifth is a current business partner of Farkle (in an unrelated business venture).
<p>
The board initially met for two hours to consider Farkle's proposal for a dual class recapitalization. During this meeting Farkle indicated that she was short of cash and the recapitalization would solve this problem. She also indicated that she had heard rumours that there might be a takeover bid for ENC Corp. She expressed the view that this would be highly disruptive to the staff of ENC, and would jeopardize ENC's long-range business plan to expand ENC's clothing business into a new line of &quot;punker&quot; styles to be marketed to teens and young adults. This plan had been roundly criticized in the trade press and Farkle expressed the view that the market had completely failed to understand the genius behind this move. She felt that if a hostile acquisition occurred, her brilliant strategy to move into punker styles would likely be scrapped.
<p>
The lawyer/director suggested that it would be a good idea to constitute a committee of independent directors to investigate the wisdom of the dual class recapitalization. This was done. The committee was asked to make a report to the full board. The lawyer/director was deputized by the board to give the independent committee its marching orders. The lawyer instructed the committee to assume that the move into punker styles would be a good idea, that this plan could be jeopardized by a hostile acquisition, and to make a recommendation on whether the recapitalization would be an appropriate response. He also instructed the committee to investigate and report on whether the rumours of an impending takeover bid were seriously affecting employee morale.
<p>
After a short organizational meeting, each member of the committee talked to employees of the company and made such other further inquiries as each considered appropriate. These ranged from nothing at all, to conversations with clothing industry experts at various investment banking houses about town. Following these inquiries, the committee met for two hours and discussed the results of their investigations. They then unanimously reported to the full board that the employees of ENC were indeed unsettled by the takeover rumours, and that a dual class recapitalization would be a good way to protect ENC's long-range plan to move into punker styles. The full board then unanimously endorsed Farkle's plan to recapitalize the company. The formal resolution adopted by the board read in part:
<blockquote>
In consideration of Fran Farkle's financial position and desire to sell shares to raise cash, and in consideration of the need to protect the corporation's long-term strategy from the potential effects of a hostile acquisition, and in consideration of the unsettling effect that rumours of an impending takeover have had on the employees of ENC, the board hereby resolves to [effect the dual class recapitalization]...
</blockquote>
A special shareholders' meeting was called to approve the plan. A management circular was put together and sent to shareholders. The circular stressed the need to protect the corporation's long-term plans, and the adverse affect that takeover rumours were having on employee morale, but said nothing about Farkle's personal motives for favouring the recapitalization, nor that after the recapitalization she planned to buy up a majority of the voting shares (although that is often what happens following such a recapitalization).
<p>
Farkle was extremely active in attempting to get the major shareholders (i.e. the institutional shareholders) to vote in favour of the plan. She personally met with representatives of each large institutional shareholder. In doing so, she stressed that she was meeting with them as a shareholder, rather than as a representative of management, and that as the largest single shareholder in ENC, she felt strongly that the recapitalization was necessary to preserve the corporation's long run value.
<p>
The shareholders approved the plan. 70% of the shareholders voted in person or by proxy, including Farkle's 20% and the 30% held by the large institutional blockholders (each holding 5%). Farkle voted in favour, as did two of the institutional blockholders. Of the remaining 20% of the shareholders who voted, 85% voted in favour of the plan. Thus, in total 67% of the voting shareholders voted in favour of the plan.
<p>
Following implementation of the plan, Farkle did what she had intended to do: she sold all of her Class B shares into the market and bought up enough Class A shares to give her 50.1% of the Class A shares. She invested the rest of the money in her new business venture.
<p>
The new venture, called Zippity-Do-Dads Inc., involves the manufacture of zippers, buttons, and other types of fastening devices for clothes. Farkle owns 51% of the equity. The other 49% was sold to public shareholders (both institutional and retail) in a public offering. Zippity trades on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
<p>
Because Farkle was anxious to avoid any conflict between her duties as CEO of ENC and her involvement in the new enterprise, she declined to become either a director or officer of Zippity. However, she has been hired by Zippity in the capacity of consultant, with her remuneration paid entirely in generous options to buy the stock of Zippity (such that, if Zippity is successful, her remuneration as consultant could conceivably exceed that of the top executives of Zippity).
<p>
Farkle was optimistic that the business would be successful. ENC did not manufacture any fastening devices itself, but purchased them from external suppliers. Because ENC had been experiencing problems with these suppliers (e.g. too many broken fasteners, uninspired designs, etc.), Farkle hoped that ENC would take on Zippity-Do-Dads as its supplier.
<p>
This, indeed, was what happened. Farkle indicated to the board that it was her hope that ENC would purchase from Zippity. She also indicated that because she was an interested person, she could take no part in the decision. The board instructed the independent committee to investigate the virtues of Zippity versus other fastener suppliers. The committee members again made independent investigations, met together to discuss their findings, and then unanimously reported to the full board that Zippity had more interesting and reliable fasteners than its competitors, and sold them at prices competitive with other potential suppliers. The board as a whole decided to engage Zippity, and a contract was entered into pursuant to which Zippity agreed to supply ENC with fasteners of various kinds over a ten year period.
<p>
Indeed, Zippity's fasteners have become so successful that the demand for its product far outstrips the supply. Because the contract obliged Zippity to supply a large part of its current output to ENC, ENC secured an important advantage over its competitors by signing the long-term contract with Zippity.
<p>
Zippity is fast on its way to becoming one of the most profitable companies in Canada. Given Farkle's investment in Zippity, the value of her stock options, and the current market value of Zippity, her personal wealth is now treble what it was prior to the creation of Zippity, and increasing daily.
<p>
Please discuss any legal issues which you believe are reasonably raised by this fact situation (including who might sue whom, on what grounds, and for what relief).
<p><br>
<hr>
