<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Civil Procedure A and B<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Roach</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use your notes, casebook and <cite>Annual Practice</cite>.<p>
<li>This exam consists of one question.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.<p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<dd>The Attorney General of Flavelle is interested in constructing a system to deal with public complaints against judges. In the last year, there have been numerous complaints about the conduct of judges in Flavelle. Complaints have been made by lawyers, administrative staff and members of the public. They contain allegations ranging from discourteous service and excessive delay, to erratic behaviour, conflict of interest and sexual harassment. One well-publicized complaint concerned allegations of sexual harassment made by a judge's former administrative assistant ten years after her contact with the judge ended, but within a year of receiving counselling concerning the effects of the harassment.
<p>
<dd>Write a memorandum for the Attorney General outlining an appropriate structure for dealing with complaints against judges. You should make clear what role you contemplate within this system for negotiation, mediation, various forms of adjudication and public inquiries. You should also consider the implications of judicial independence and power imbalances when devising your system to deal with complaints. The Attorney General is also concerned about what role, if any, statutes of limitations should play in the system you have devised.
<p><br>
<hr>
