<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Civil Procedure<br>
Fall 1995<br>
Allan C. Hutchinson</h2></center>
<h3>Instructions:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This is an open book examination.<p>
<li>Please answer <b>one</b> question only.<p>
<li>Be legible and organised.<p>
<li>There will be a class at 9:00 to 10:30 a.m. on Wednesday, 3rd January, 1996 in a room somewhere underground at U. Of T. Keep a look-out!<p>
<li>Good luck . . .and have a good holiday.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<h3>QUESTION ONE</h3>
Aware of your precocious insight into the civil justice system, you have been contacted by the Ontario Law Reform Commission. As part of its review of Alternative Dispute Resolution procedures it would like you to make some suggestions about the best way for it to deal with the thorny problem of how to decide which types of disputes are most appropriately dealt with by which kind of procedures. It also asks if you could provide some practical illustrations to bolster your more general analysis. What would you write?
<p><br>
<h3>QUESTION TWO</h3>
(A) Marie represents Charlie in a tortious action against Bill and represents Sanjeev in a tortuous action brought against him by Susan. Both actions come up for trial on the sane day. In the Doming, Mane intends to argue for Charlie that the limitation period does not begin to run until the extent of damage is realised. In the afternoon, on almost identical facts, Marie intends to argue for Sanjeev that the limitation period begins to run immediately from the occurrence of the negligent act.
<p>
(B) B.I.G. Corporation is an important client of Marie's firm in which she is a four-year associate. She is asked by its President to represent him personally in a civil action against him by a former spouse for domestic assault. He says that she wants Marie to defend him as it will look a lot better if he has a woman for a lawyer. Although her membership has lapsed, Marie was once a member of W.A.V.E. (Woman Against Violence Everywhere) and still has strong views on the subject.
<p>
(C) Marie has acted successfully for Irnya in recent litigation who collects a damage award of $25,000. A month later, Marie is sent anonymously an authenticated letter of Irnya' s which indicates that Irnya lied at the trial about a crucial issue in the case.
<p>
<b>What would you advise Marie to do? What would <i>you</i> do? Why?</b>
<p><br>
<h3>QUESTION THREE</h3>
Jack is a thoroughly bad lot. In the past few years, much of his past is beginning to catch up wish him snag he it the named defendant in a series of civil actions:
<blockquote>
(A) Katrina, his 30 year old step-daughter, sues over incestuous incidents that go back over 20 years. She had gone through therapy and had begun to come to terms with her situation about years ago. However, Jack's return to Toronto from B.C. has stirred up her anxiety, she has become depressed and serves Jack a couple of weeks ago. Jack's lawyer seeks to have the action set aside as being out of time, and
<p>
(B) Jack was involved in a car accident in November, 1993 in which Allan and Barbara were
killed. There were protracted discussions with Jack's insurance company which informally conceded liability in a 'without prejudice' communication, but disputed the quantum of damages. Due to the insurance company's failure to conclude any negotiations, Barbara's estate issued an originating process against Jack in May, 1995. The lawyer for Barbara's estate decided not to serve the originating process until she had received fiber medical reports on the nervous condition of Barbara's husband. In the meantime, Allan's estate issued an originating process against Jack in October, 1995. This originating process has not yet been served. A week age the lawyer for Barbara's estate realized that the originating process had expired. She was successful in making an ex parte motion for an extension of
time for service. Jack's lawyer moves to set aside the order for extension. 
</blockquote>
<b>Both these motions are brought before you today as the presiding judge. How would you dispose of them?</b>
<p>
<dd>[Assume that the relevant limitation period in both cases is 2 years]
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
