<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Constitutional Law<br>
December 1995<br>
Professors Risk, Rogerson, and Swinton</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>The exam is composed of one question.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then	gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<dd>The spotted orange otter is an endangered species still found in a few places in Northern Ontario, Quebec and Manitoba. Wildlife experts fear that if swift action is not taken to protect the remaining animals, the species will die out, and Canada will be the poorer.
<p>
<dd>The federal Minister of the Environment has been under a great deal of pressure from SPOTTER (The Society to Protect the Spotted Otter) to act not only to save the spotted orange otter, but other endangered species as well. They argue that the federal Parliament should enact an <cite>Endangered Species Act</cite> in order to live up to its obligations under the <cite>International Agreement to Save Endangered Species</cite>. That treaty requires signatories, like Canada, to take steps to protect an agreed list of endangered species, which includes the spotted orange otter.
<p>
<dd>You are a lawyer for the federal Ministry. The Minister is inclined to meet SPOTTER's demands, but needs your help in determining the possible constitutional issues that may arise from the enactment of SPOTTER's proposed legislation, which is described below.
<p>
<dd>The legislation would create an offense, punishable with a large fine, for anyone to kill or harm an endangered species, as designated in the regulations (and which would include the spotted orange otter). The law would also give the power to the federal Minister of the Environment to issue regulations to protect the habitat of such species.
<p>
<dd>With respect to the spotted orange otter, the proposed regulations would include identifying certain zones to be refuges for the otters. Public access to these zones would be controlled by federal wildlife officers - but some access by the public would be allowed in order to promote awareness about these wonderful creatures. As well, the federal officers would be given the power, within these zones, to eliminate the natural predators of the otter, which are the wolf and coyote.
<p>
<dd>The provinces of Ontario and Quebec have registered opposition to any federal intervention in this area. Both claim that wildlife conservation is within provincial jurisdiction, since the provinces have extensive responsibility for natural resources and public property.
<p>
<dd>Ontario and Quebec (but not Manitoba) already have systems to protect the spotted orange otter. Their <cite>Wildlife Acts</cite> prevent hunting of any species without a licence, and no licence is available to hunt the spotted orange otter. Both have designated a number of refuges for these animals. These provinces fundamentally disagree with the federal proposal to allow public access to otter refuges, however, since they believe that the greatest danger to this species is destruction of their habitat by human beings. Most importantly, the provinces want to minimize damage to the northern lingonberry patches found in the refuges, since this berry is the sole food source of the spotted otter. Therefore, no member of the public is allowed access to provincial otter zones in order to protect the food.
<p>
<dd>The Minister asks you to advise her on the federalism issues that may arise if she proceeds with SPOTTER's proposal.
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
Please send comments and suggestions to <a href="mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</a><p>
Created on MAR-10-96 by Anne Johnston.
</address>
