<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Constitutional Law B<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Macklem</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>The examination contains one question.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
Mr. Jack Daniels is the owner and operator of Jack's Bar and Grill, a tavern located in the town of Brantford, Ontario. He has a cigarette vending machine in his tavern. He also sells cigarettes to youth, so long as they are over the age of 18. In so doing, he is acting in compliance with existing federal legislation.
<p>
The relevant provisions of the federal <cite>Tobacco Sales to Young Persons Act</cite>, S.C. 1993, c. 5, are as follows:
<blockquote>
<center><h4>PURPOSE</h4></center>
<b>3.</b> The purpose of this Act is to protect the health of young persons by restricting their access to tobacco in light of the risks associated with tobacco consumption.
<p>
<center><h4>OFFENCES</h4></center>
<b>4.(1)</b> Everyone who, in the course of business, sells any tobacco product to a person under the age of eighteen is guilty of an offence and liable to a fine not exceeding one thousand dollars...
<p>
<b>5.(1)</b> Subject to subsection (2), everyone who installs, or permits to be installed, a vending machine in any public place knowing that tobacco products will be sold therefrom is guilty of an offence and liable to a fine not exceeding two thousand dollars.
<p>
<b> (2)</b> Subsection (1) does not apply in respect of a place that is a bar, tavern or other similar beverage room.
</blockquote>
However, Mr. Daniels has not complied with the recently enacted Ontario <cite>Tobacco Control Act</cite>, S.O. 1994, c. 7. The relevant sections of the Ontario Act are as follows:
<p>
<blockquote>
<center><h4>PURPOSE</h4></center>
<b>2.</b> In light of the dangers to health posed by the consumption of tobacco products, the purpose of this Act is to prevent the provision of tobacco to young persons and to regulate its sale and use.
<p>
<center><h4>PROVISION OF TOBACCO TO PERSONS UNDER NINETEEN</h4></center>
<b>3.(1)</b> No person shall sell or give tobacco to a person who is less than nineteen years of age.
<p>
<center><h4>VENDING MACHINES</h4></center>
<b>7.(1)</b> No person shall permit a vending machine for selling or dispensing tobacco products to be in a place that the person owns or occupies...
<p>
<center><h4>OFFENCES</h4></center>
<b>14.(1)</b> A person who contravenes subsection 3(1) or 7(1) is guilty of an offence and on conviction is liable to a fine not exceeding two thousand dollars...
</blockquote>
Other sections of the Ontario Act prohibit the sale of tobacco in pharmacies, hospitals, other health-care facilities. schools. and universities.
<p>
In early December 1995, Mr. Daniels was charged with offences pursuant to ss. 3(1) and 7(1) of the Ontario <cite>Tobacco Control Act</cite>. You are an articling student for a lawyer representing Mr. Daniels. Prepare a memorandum discussing and evaluating any constitutional arguments that might assist Mr. Daniels in his defence.
<p>
For the purposes of this memorandum: (a) you are not to consider any arguments that could be made in reliance of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1982</cite>; and (b) you are to assume that Mr. Daniels has violated ss. 3(1) and 7(1) of the Ontario Act and that he has complied with the federal Act.
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
