<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Constitutional Law II<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor L. Weinrib</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>The exam is composed of one question.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.<p>
<li><b>PLEASE DOUBLE SPACE YOUR ANSWERS.</b>
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<dd>The spotted orange otter is an endangered species now found in only a few places in northern Ontario, Quebec and Manitoba. Ontario and Quebec have implemented programmes to protect the otter, but wildlife experts fear that the species will die out without federal government action. These experts maintain that it is important to preserve species diversity as a commitment to the environment, to sustainable development and to pride in our rich natural heritage.
<p>
<dd>The Society to Protect the Spotted Otter, &quot;SPOTTER&quot;, has been lobbying the federal Minister of the Environment to propose new federal legislation, in the form of an <cite>Endangered Species Act</cite>, to protect the spotted orange otter as part of a more general programme to protect endangered species. SPOTTER takes the position that Parliament is obligated to enact such legislation to fulfil its obligations under the <cite>International Agreement to Save Endangered Species</cite>, a treaty that requires its signatories to take steps to protect a listed number of endangered species, including the spotted orange otter.
<p>
<dd>The proposed legislation would empower the federal Minister of the Environment, by regulation, to designate certain species as endangered and to provide protection for such species, including the provision of protected habitats. Once the spotted orange otter and its habitat acquired this designation, federal wildlife officers would have the authority to restrict entry to the areas designated and, as necessary, remove or destroy the otter's natural predators -- the wolf and coyote. Enforcement would include the prohibition of killing, harming, having in possession or selling an animal identified as belonging to an endangered species and non-authorized entry into the habitat of an endangered species. Punishment set for first offences is a low fine; for repeat offences of a serious nature, punishment is set at higher fines and/or imprisonment.
<p>
<dd>Opposition to the proposal has come from several quarters. The provinces of Ontario and Quebec take the position that wildlife conservation is within provincial jurisdiction and that they are doing a good job. Public interests groups, under the banner &quot;Get a Life&quot;, insist that the programme is bad politics in a time of spending cutbacks to social programmes for human beings. They demand that the legislation include some features to recapture expenditures, such as making the habitats available, for a fee, to nature protection groups, students, tourists, etc. They note that it would be possible to sell souvenirs, calendars and books at the sites to these visitors. Other critics take the view that there is no point in protecting animals that no one can see or learn about first hand.
<p>
<dd>Ontario and Quebec, as noted earlier, have legislation in place to protect the spotted orange otter. Pursuant to this legislation, these provinces require a licence for hunting particular animals and no longer issue licences in respect to this animal. In addition, both provinces have designated a number of protected habitats for it. These provinces prohibit public access to such areas on the view that any human traffic will damage the northern ligon berry patches, which provide the otter with its sole source of food. Signs to this effect are posted but no officials are on site.
<p>
<dd>You are a lawyer for the Ministry of the Environment. The Minister is inclined to support enactment of the proposed legislation. The government favours a national &quot;feel good&quot; programme at this time but is concerned that constitutional difficulties may arise. Prepare a brief memorandum for the Minister setting out the federalism issues implicated, ranking their strength, and indicating how the Supreme Court of Canada would likely resolve them. Include suggestions as to how to bolster the arguments for federal jurisdiction.
<p><br>
<hr>
