<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Contracts<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Valcke</h2></center>
<h3>NOTES:</h3>
<ol><i>
<li>You may consult any kind of material you wish during the exam, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library<p>
<li>The test is composed of one question. In answering the question I urge you to <b>identify</b> the legal issues you think the problem raises and then <b>argue</b> both sides as well as you can making as much use of the <b>facts</b> as possible. There is no need to formally cite cases; a case name will do when you rely on a <b>holding</b> or are arguing what a case's <b>reasoning</b> suggest a court might do in resolving a particular issue you are analyzing.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time win be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the test, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the test.<p>
<li>At the end of this test, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>An examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Lime limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the test has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</i></ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
Esther and Stephen Dickinson are 73 and 70 years old. When they retired ten years ago, they sold their house in the city and moved into their country home on Georgian Bay. Their first years in the country were pure bliss, but the last few have been more difficult. Their old age brought along various health problems, and they have been finding it increasingly difficult to live on their own; household chores, property maintenance and errands have become a little much for them. Moreover, Esther and Stephen's son, Sylvio, has been worried about his parents living on their own in such a remote location. Sylvio hence suggested that Esther and Stephen move back to the city and live in a fully serviced home for senior citizens. Having always been fiercely independent, Esther and Stephen rejected this idea out of hand. Instead, they decided they would hire someone to help with the housekeeping, cooking, and driving, and to be generally available in case of emergency. This would require that this person live nearby, and it was therefore also decided that a fully equipped, winterized cottage would be built for this person's use just a few hundred yards from the house. Once the construction of the cottage was completed, Esther and Stephen went on a search for the perfect household helper.
<p>
<dd>Upon Sylvio's recommendation, they hired on a trial basis Sylvio's sister-in-law, Teresa, an experienced nurse who was unemployed at the time. Teresa and her son Tommy moved into the cottage, and after a mutually satisfactory three-week trial period, Esther, Stephen and Teresa decided to formalize their arrangement. They entered a written contract whereby Teresa agreed to be available weekdays for housekeeping, cooking, driving and emergencies, as requested by Esther and Stephen from time to time, in exchange for which she would receive $20.00 for every hour of actual services and she and Tommy would be allowed to live in the cottage rent-free. The contract also provided that Teresa would notify Esther and Stephen in advance when she would need to go out, and would not work for anyone else for the duration of the contract (2 years)
<p>.
<dd>Two days after the contract was concluded, Teresa realized that no minimal number of hours of services had been set in the contract, which would leave her with very few hours of services--and hence very little money--in those weeks where Esther and Stephen might not need much help. She mentioned her concern to Esther and Stephen who told her not to worry, for they would definitely need her services on a daily basis. Just to reassure Teresa, however, Esther and Stephen told her they could guarantee her a minimum of three hours a day.
<p>
<dd>All went well, until six months into the contract, when Esther and Stephen's son, Sylvio, got divorced, lost his job and, in an attempt to save housing money, decided to come to live with his parents. With Sylvio in the house, Teresa's services were no longer needed on a steady basis. She would be called upon for a few hours of work every now and then, but never more than six hours in any one week. In need of additional income, Teresa started working part-time at the local public library. Esther and Stephen found out about it and told her to move out of the cottage, as she had breached her contract with them. She tried to explain to them that the reason she had to find alternative employment was that they had failed to give her the minimum of fifteen hours of services they had promised her, but they refuse to discuss the matter.
<p>
<dd>Advise Teresa. Please ignore possible labour and family law issues.
<p><br>
<hr>
