<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Contracts<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Trebilcock</h2></center>
<h3>NOTES:</h3>
<ol><i>
<li>You may consult any kind of material you wish during the exam, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library<p>
<li>The test is composed of one question. In answering the question I urge you to <b>identify</b> the legal issues you think the problem raises and then <b>argue</b> both sides as well as you can making as much use of the <b>facts</b> as possible. Here is no need to formally cite cases; a case name will do when you rely on a <b>holding</b> or are arguing what a case's <b>reasoning</b> suggests a court might do in resolving a particular issue you are analyzing.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the test, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the test.<p>
<li>At the end of this test, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the test has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</i></ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
Olympus and Stork Ltd. (O &amp; S), commercial real estate developers, decided to construct a high-rise office tower in downtown Toronto during the late 1980's real estate boom and called for tenders from prime contractors against a detailed set of specifications developed by O &amp; S's architectural and engineering consultants. O &amp; S awarded the construction contract to Ron Ellis Construction Ltd. (REC), a Canadian subsidiary of a
major multinational construction company, for a fixed price of $50 million, full completion required within two years from the signing of the contract.
<p>
At an early stage of construction, REC encountered severe sub-soil conditions (uncovering an old toxic waste site dump that had caused extensive soil contamination problems) that made the foundation work much more costly and protracted than expected. REC demanded an additional amount of $10 million from O &amp; S in the absence of which REC intimated that it was likely to repudiate the contract by declaring bankruptcy. Senior management of O &amp; S reluctantly agreed to the additional payment.
<p>
The office complex was eventually completed but nine months late. During that period, a severe economic recession had set in in Canada and the real estate market had become severely depressed. Shanghai Bank, which had initially agreed to lease several floors of the building at attractive rents, repudiated the lease on account of the delay in completion and decided to withdraw from the Canadian market. Other prospective tenants with whom O &amp; S had been negotiating lease arrangements broke off negotiations in the face of uncertainty over the completion date and subsequently leased cheaper space elsewhere.
<p>
O &amp; S now sues REC for the difference between its current rental revenues and the revenues it claims it would have realized with timely completion of the building. REC counterclaims for the additional payment of $10 million, for which O &amp; S now denies liability.
<p>
If you were retained as counsel for REC, how would you argue their case?
<p><br>
<hr>
