<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Contracts<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Hadfield</h2></center>
<h3>NOTES:</h3>
<ol><i>
<li>You may consult any kind of material you wish during the exam, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library<p>
<li>The test is composed of one question. In answering the question I urge you to <b>identify</b> the legal issues you think the problem raises and then <b>argue</b> both sides as well as you can making as much use of the <b>facts</b> as possible. There is no need to formally cite cases; a case name will do when you rely on a <b>holding</b> or are arguing what a case's <b>reasoning</b> suggests a court might do in resolving a particular issue you are analyzing.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the test, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the test.<p>
<li>At the end of this test, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the test has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</i></ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<center><h4>MEMORANDUM</h4></center>
TO: Associates-at-Law<p>
FROM: GKH<p>
Richard Lopez recently called me seeking our advice about a housing deal he is working on. He has given me the following information.
<p>
Lopez is sixty-four years old and recently retired from his wholesale tobacco business. As part of the deal when he sold his business, he took a vacant lot on Woolsack Avenue; his dream is to build a small apartment complex on the lot.
<p>
From a financial standpoint, Lopez is not unreasonable in permitting himself to think in terms of apartment construction. He has accumulated a comfortable estate in his years of business, and by mortgaging the premises for about fifty percent of its cost--which he estimates will be $1,200,000. at the most--he figures that the investment is one that he can afford to make.
<p>
On August 14th, Lopez got a call from his old and wealthy friend Bill Sing and was invited to join him for lunch. The lunch was barely under way when Lopez launched into a description of his dream to build the apartment complex. Sing was both enthusiastic and encouraging.
<p>
&quot;Wonderful idea, Rick,&quot; said Sing. &quot;Best investment you could possibly make. And don't let high prices worry you. Take my word for it, in a few years these prices everyone is yelling about will look dirt cheap. The dollar is on the way down. Get your money in property now and you can't go wrong.&quot;
<p>
With the conversation turned to costs and financing, Lopez explained that of course he expected to put a mortgage of approximately $600,000 on the property. He asked Sing for his advice on the best places to apply for such a loan, the maximum rate of interest he should pay, and the terms he should seek.
<p>
&quot;Rick, I'll tell you,&quot; said Sing after a few moments of thought. &quot;You can get a loan without trouble, I'm sure; probably twenty years at 11% interest will do it. But when you have that kind of a loan hanging over your head, you're never free from worry. You can't expect sympathy from a big lending institution; business is business with them. Now I'll tell you what I'll do. Twenty years ago you did me a favor I'll never forget when you loaned me that $10,000 I needed to get my own business going and I told you then that someday I'd repay you and I meant it. Let me lend you that $600,000 you need. I'll take your mortgage, but I'll make it for twenty-five years with no required annual payments and you can pay it off as you get the money. And forget about interest. I mean it, Rick, and don't say no.&quot;
<p>
Lopez, registered the customary protests: that he couldn't take advantage of Sing's generosity; that this was a pure gift and much too large a one.
<p>
&quot;Look, Rick,&quot; replied Sing, &quot;Don't be a fool. Believe me, I can afford it. And it isn't a gift; I expect you to repay it and I know you will. And if it will make you feel better when you're taking the profits to the bank in a few years, you can always add some interest to the repayments.&quot; With this remark Sing chuckled loudly and slapped Lopez on the back. &quot;What's more, I'm getting security for the loan, and good security. Shake hands on it and get going on your building. The longer you delay, the more it's going to cost you.&quot;
<p>
&quot;Bill,&quot; said Lopez at last, &quot;I shouldn't take advantage of you this way, but I'm going to take you up. With this help from you I can't miss. You're a real friend, Bill, I will never forget it. Probably I won't be needing any of your cash for a while, but when I do, I'll count on you for up to $600,000 on a twenty-five year mortgage--of course I'll pay it off long before then-hopefully with interest.
<p>
&quot;You can count on me, Rick,&quot; said Sing. &quot;And don't talk about taking advantage of me. Let's shake on it.&quot; The two men shook hands and Lopez raised a toast: &quot;To the best friend a man could hope for. And in return, lunch is on me.&quot;
<p>
10 days later Lopez received a letter from Sing:
<blockquote>
Dear Rick,
<p>
<dd>I'm afraid I have bad news for you. After checking my affairs on my return here the day before yesterday, I discovered that I was a bit too hasty in my offer to lend you $600,000 on a 25-year mortgage on your proposed apartment building. The fact is that I just don't see how I can free enough of my funds at this time to make this advance to you.
<p>
<dd>Believe me, I feel very badly at having to let you down this way, but I have no alternative. And, after all, it won't seriously affect your project, since I know you'll have no trouble getting a loan through regular sources, and your building as you described it to me should easily earn more than enough to take care of the interest which I realize you'll have to pay.
<p>
<dd>I'm sure you'll understand that I have no choice in this matter. Please drop me a line in the near future and let me know how your building is coming along. I'll be most interested to hear.
<p>
<dd>As ever,
<p>
<dd>Bill
</blockquote>
Lopez has asked us whether or not he can enforce Sing's promise to loan him the money and on what terms. He has told me that he spent the week following his lunch with Sing working 10 hours a day researching zoning, architects, forecasts in the real estate market etc., and turned down an offer from his trust company for a $600,000 mortgage at 8% just days before he got Sing's letter. Is it worth his effort to pursue this claim? (For purposes of answering this question you should assume that a mortgage is a loan secured by a piece of real property. If the borrower fails to pay according to the terms of the loan, the lender has the right to force a sale of the property and collect from the proceeds the amount owing on the loan.)
<p><br>
<hr>
