<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Corporate Income Tax<br>
December 1995<br>
William J. Bies</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, texts, except books owned by the library.
<p>
The exam is composed of 3 questions.
<p>
Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<p>
During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<p>
At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<p>
Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
<p>
<b>Answer all Questions</b>
<p>
All the words and expressions defined in the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> (the &quot;Act&quot;) have the meanings therein assigned.
<p>
Always substantiate your answers, where appropriate, with reference to sections of the Act, jurisprudence and Interpretation Bulletins, etc.
<p>
<hr>
<p><br>
(25 marks) 1. Miss C, a resident of Ontario, incorporated Opco in Ontario in 1985. On incorporation, Miss C subscribed for 15 common shares of Opco and paid, in the aggregate, $150,000 in cash. On the issuance of the 15 common shares, the directors of Opco added $150,000 to the stated capital account for the shares. In 1986 Opco purchased for cancellation 5 of the 15 common shares held by Miss C for $60,000.
<p>
Opco declined in value and in 1989 Miss C sold her remaining 10 common shares of Opco to Mr. B. a resident of Ontario, for $50,000. Mr. B immediately subscribed for 10 additional common shares and paid $50,000, the amount added by the directors to the stated capital amounts for the shares.
<p>
In 1990 Mr. B sold the 20 shares of Opco to Acquireco, a resident of the United States, for $10,000. In 1991 Acquireco made a contribution of capital to Opco in the account of $200,000.
<p>
Discuss the tax implications of each of the above events.
<p><br>
(50 marks) 2. Assume the above facts and that Opco now has a value of $1,000,000. Opco's only asset is land in northern Ontario. The cost of the land to Opco is $200,000. Acquireco wants to dispose of its investment to a Canadian public company (Pubco) and use the net proceeds in the United States. Acquireco is considering 4 possible methods of realization:
<blockquote>
(a) Acquireco could sell the shares of Opco to Pubco for $1,000,000 in cash.
<p>
(b) Acquireco could transfer the shares of Opco to Pubco which is in the business of real estate development in exchange for shares of Pubco having a value equal to $1,000,000. Acquireco and Pubco would elect under section 85 of the Income Tax Act at an amount which would result in Acquireco not realizing a capital gain on the transfer. Acquireco could then sell the shares of Pubco for $1,000,000. Pubco's shares are listed on The Toronto Stock Exchange and trade regularly.
<p>
(c) Acquireco could make a contribution of surplus to Opco in the amount of $2,000,000 and then sell the shares of Opco for $3,000,000.
<p>
(d) Opco could sell the land for $1,000,000 and distribute the net proceeds after tax to Acquireco.
</blockquote>
Discuss the tax implications of each of the above methods.
<p><br>
(25 marks) 3. Gertrude owns a capital property which has a cost to her of  $10,000 and a current fair market value of $100,000. She decides to transfer the property to a company (Holdco) and to elect a transfer price under section 85 of the <cite>Income Tax Act</cite> of $10,000. Gertrude's daughter, Gladys, is the only shareholder of Holdco immediately before the transfer by Gertrude.
<p>
Gertrude could receive from Holldco any of the following four packages of consideration.
<p>
Discuss the tax implications of each:
<blockquote>
(a)	cash - $10,000<br>
common shares - $90,000
<p>
(b) promissory note - $15,000<br>
preferred shares - $80,000<br>
common shares - $5,000
<p>
(c) promissory note - $4,000<br>
preferred shares - $5,000<br>
common shares - $50,000
<p>
(d) cash - $120,000
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<hr>
