<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Criminal Law Section 1<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Friedland</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may bring into the examination a copy of the case book, an annotated Code or Codes, and your own notes.<p>
<li>The test is composed of one question.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you require additional booklets during the examination, write the required information on each of the booklets at the time you receive them. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<dd>The police learn from a legal wiretap that Jones and Smith are planning to rob the very rich Mr. &amp; Mrs. Victim in their fancy new condominium. The police contact the concierge of the condominium and ask him to alert them if a particular car shows up with persons in it matching the description of Jones and Smith. They also alert Mr. and Mrs. Victim, who move to a hotel with all their valuables. When the car shows up a few days later, the concierge calls the police and then goes out to stall Jones and Smith. They become suspicious and Jones shoots the concierge in the chest. Smith is heard to shout: &quot;You said you wouldn't shoot anyone - that the gun was only to scare people.&quot; Jones and Smith leave.
<p>
<dd>The police arrive at the scene and unfortunately one of the cars drives over the concierge, crushing his skull. The concierge is dead when he arrives at the hospital. The coroner later says that the concierge would probably have survived the bullet wound.
<p>
<dd>Jones and Smith immediately drive to a home in Forest Hill and knock on the front door. Mr. Rich is home and answers the door. Jones says that &quot;this is a stick-up; we want your money from the safe.&quot; Smith stays in the front hall as a look-out. After Mr. Rich opens the safe, an alarm goes off. Smith shouts: &quot;Shoot him and let's get out of here.&quot; Jones shoots and kills Mr. Rich and they flee.
<p>
<dd>Several hours later, Jones is stopped by a police officer for emitting too much smoke from his car exhaust contrary to the new Federal Exhaust Emission Act. [Assume that there is such an Act.] The car is registered in Jones' name and Jones was driving the car. The Act provides that &quot;Anyone who emits more than [a certain density] of smoke from his or her car exhaust, whether or not the person knows that such an amount is being emitted, is guilty of a summary conviction offence.&quot; Jones' exhaust emission is above the legal limit. Jones claims that he had just had his car certified the day before because he was about to sell it and certainly did not know that such a quantity of smoke was being emitted. He didn't even know there was such an Act. While they were arguing, another officer spotted Jones and Smith as the suspects in the murders that day and arrested them.
<p>
<dd>You are an articling student in the Crown Attorney's office. The Crown Attorney would like a short memo from you on the possible offences that Jones and Smith may be guilty of, from first degree murders down. The Crown also wants you to give your opinion on whether Jones and Smith can be guilty of &quot;illegally emitting smoke&quot; from the car, in case the other charges fail. Please prepare the memorandum.
<p><br>
<hr>
