<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Criminal Law<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Mewett</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>There is ONE question.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of the examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet and insert all the booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
Assume that all these facts can be proved by the Crown.
<p>
Daryl Kreep is a 35 year-old man who makes a practice of hanging out in the parking lots of shopping malls where he waits until he spots a young woman with an armful of shopping bags, at which point he will deliberately bump into her knocking her parcels to the ground. He thereupon moves a few feet away and gets sexual gratification out of watching her bend over to pick up the parcels. He then moves off to find another victim.
<p>
This is precisely what he did one day last month when he bumped into the victim in this case, Laurel Smith. He moved away a few feet to watch her, but as she was bending over to pick up the parcels Kreep had knocked from her arms, a car driven by Gertrude Steyn, aged 74, suddenly accelerated and struck Laurel causing severe injuries from which she has now, however, recovered. Investigation revealed that Mrs. Steyn, while driving her car out of the parking lot, had suffered a minor, but painful heart attack which caused her suddenly and by reflex action to put her foot heavily on the accelerator. She, too, has now fully recovered.
<p>
You work in the Crown Attorney's office and your principal would like to charge Kreep with the most serious offence you can find that will stick. She wants you to write a memorandum (or, in this case, an examination answer) advising her what to proceed on, and what the chances of success will be. The possibilities are:
<p>
Simple assault under s. 266 of the Code;<br>
Assault causing bodily harm under s. 267(1)(b) of the Code;<br>
Sexual Assault under s. 271 of the Code; and<br>
Sexual Assault causing bodily harm under s. 272(c) of the Code.
<p><br>
