<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Criminal Law A and D<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor A. Brudner</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may bring into the examination room any materials other than library books.<p>
<li>This exam consists of one question. Discuss all issues reasonably raised by the facts even though your solution to one disposes of the case.<p>
<li>If you think the court will reach an unsatisfactory result, feel free to offer reasoned criticisms and alternatives.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.<p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<dd>Raskolnikov (R) lived alone in an old farmhouse situated on a road about 15 kilometres from Alliston, Ontario. While generally in good health, he had suffered since childhood from asthma, and on occasion would experience episodes during which he would have much difficulty in breathing. On these occasions it was always enough to take his prescribed medication to restore his breathing to normal.
<p>
<dd>Late one night during a severe thunderstorm, R heard frantic knocking at his door. It was Zossimov (Z), a total stranger to R. &quot;My car's broken down on the highway,&quot; Z said, &quot;and all the garages around here are closed for the night. I wonder if I could stay until morning - I won't be any trouble, I promise.&quot;
<p>
<dd>R agreed with hardly a moment's hesitation. As Z's clothes were soaking wet, R loaned him some of his own. He then fixed Z a hot meal, put fresh sheets on the bed in the guest room, and wished Z a good night.
<p>
<dd>About two hours later, Z was awakened by a cry coming from R's room. R had begun to experience some trouble breathing and on discovering that he had run out of medication, had called to Z for help. Z went to investigate. R entreated him to drive his car to an all-night pharmacy in Alliston, but Z refused, saying it was a miserable night and that, in any event, it was probably just a chest cold that would clear up by itself. He then gave R some cough syrup that he found in the medicine chest and told him to go to sleep and not to disturb him any more.
For the next forty-eight hours, while R's condition steadily worsened, Z ate R's food, lounged in his living room watching television, and slept in R's guest room. Occasionally he would give R tea and cough syrup, but that was it. By the morning of the third day, R was in a coma. Finally a neighbour dropped by and asked Z how R was. Z replied that R had been ill with a bad cold but that the worst seemed to be over now. The neighbour went in to see R and, immediately realizing the gravity of the situation, quickly carried R into his car and rushed him to the hospital in Alliston. There R's respiratory problem was successfully treated by emergency surgery, but a week later R died from a bacterial infection he contracted through the surgeon's failure to observe proper sanitary procedures.
<p>
<dd>As a result of police and psychiatric investigations, the following facts about Z have come to light. He is eighteen years old and of below average (but normal) intelligence. He dropped out of school after grade ten and has been continuously unemployed ever since. An only child, he lives with his parents who have always catered to his every whim, allowing the most trivial of them to override more substantial interests of their own. As a result, Z has developed a tendency to overestimate the importance of his own needs and to undervalue those of others. He staunchly maintains that he did not realize how serious R's condition was.
<p>
<dd>Discuss Z's criminal liability.
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
