<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Criminal Law Small Group C<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Bernard Dickens</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library<p>
<li>The test is composed of <b>ONE</b> question.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklets and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<h4>QUESTION</h4>
<dd>AB, CD and EF are members of the Tronville University soccer team, which two months ago competed in Tronville for the Ontario Universities Soccer Federation Cup against the team from the University of Northern Ontario (UNO). The UNO team won, and became entitled to hold the cup for one year and payment of $200 to each player. After the game, AB, CD and EF decided to play a prank on GH, captain of the UNO team, by capturing the cup from the room GH had been given for the visit at Tronville University Graduate Students' Residence, and holding it until GH paid a ransom of $100 to a charity helping the homeless. GH had initiated a similar prank two years earlier, when Tronville University had won the cup. GH was known to be charitable and a good sport, more interested in success on the field than in receiving the payment, and keen to have the cup back for display at UNO's victory celebration to be held three days later.
<p>
<dd>AB, CD and EF went to the Graduate Students' Residence, located the accommodation GH had been given, a detached chalet-style bedroom and bathroom in the Residence grounds, and knocked on the door. A voice inside asked who was there, and EF replied &quot;Complimentary room service&quot;. When the door was opened, AB, CD and EF pushed their way into the room. They found that they were in the wrong chalet. The occupant, a distinguished visiting professor, was outraged at the violation of privacy, and complained to the Master of the Students' Residence. The Master bypassed the campus police and complained to the provincial police.
<p>
<dd>AB, CD and EF have now been charged with the offense, contrary to section 349(1) of the Criminal Code, of entering a dwelling house without lawful excuse with intent to commit an indictable offense.
<p>
<dd>Describe how you would defend AB, CD and EF against conviction, and explain what legal principles support the arguments you would make.
<blockquote>
<b>Note:</b> You have not been given the language of the indictment, and should not raise procedural matters such as the indictment being void for vagueness.
</blockquote>
<p><br>
