<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Criminal Procedure<br>
December 1995<br>
Michael Code</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, the texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>The exam is composed of four questions, which are of different value, as stated. The suggested time allocation is indicated in the margin. Students are expected to answer all questions.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
54 Minutes <b>Question 1:</b> Answer all 6 questions (5 marks for each part) for 30% of marks.
<p>
(a) Your client is charged with threatening death (or uttering death threats as it is sometimes called). What modes of
trial are available?
<p>
(b) The police arrest your client for assault. The complainant is his wife. There is some evidence that violence has
been escalating in the relationship and the wife fears for her life. What should the police do?
<p>
(c) Parliament proposes enacting a provision whereby the police may surreptitiously install very small radio transmitters (known as &quot;tracking devices&quot;) on any person's clothing, possessions or motor vehicle in order to follow them more easily during criminal investigations. A warrant lasting 60 days must be obtained from a judge on the basis of &quot;reasonable grounds to suspect&quot; that an offense has been committed and that
&quot;information relevant to the offense can be obtained&quot; from the tracking device. These devices cannot intercept conversations. They simply reveal a person's whereabouts and facilitate surveillance. What advice would you give Parliament about this provision?
<p>
(d) If the accused is charged with manslaughter can the judge at the preliminary inquiry commit the accused
for trial on murder? If the evidence is circumstantial, how should the judge apply the test for committal?
<p>
(e) What must the police say or do to effect a lawful arrest? What must the police say or do to effect a lawful entry to search premises?
<p>
(f) Your client, who is now 85 years old and lives in Thunder Bay with an extended family of equally elderly brothers and sisters, is charged in Kingston with sexually assaulting his son and his daughter in that city 35 years ago. His defense is a denial but his wife, who is now dead, is not available to testify in support of his defense. Furthermore, his elderly brothers and sisters, who can also support his defense, are too sick and frail to travel to Kingston. What remedies are available to the defence?
<p><br>
36 Minutes <b>Question 2:</b> Answer both questions (10 marks each) for 20% of marks
<p>
(a) The police in Kirkland Lake received an anonymous &quot;Crime Stoppers&quot; tip that two persons who had just tried to sell cocaine in a bar had left in a white 1988 Oldsmobile heading south to Sudbury. The driver was described as male with long curly hair and the passenger was described as female. The tip was dispatched and an O.P.P. cruiser on Highway 11 quickly spotted a southbound white Oldsmobile with 2 occupants. He pulled the car over with his flashing roof lights and noted that the driver and the passenger fitted the descriptions. Officer Fisherman advised the driver that he had just received a complaint about drugs and that he would like to clear it up by searching the car and then they could proceed on their way. The driver said &quot;sure&quot; and let Officer Fisherman search the car. The officer immediately found a loaded handgun under the driver's seat and charged the driver with possession of a restricted weapon. What issues should the defense raise at trial and how are they likely to be resolved?
<p>
(b) Your client is charged with manslaughter. The alleged offense was the result of a bar room brawl. There is some evidence of self-defence as a number of the patrons in the bar who are friends of the accused will testify that the deceased came after your client with a broken beer glass, slashing at him, and your client responded with a number of blows to the head with a pool cue which killed the deceased. Your client has a lengthy criminal record for crimes of violence and is feared in the small town where the offence occurred. He has always lived in the town but has rarely held a job. He has no record for failing to appear. Many of the patrons in the bar have not yet been interviewed by the police and the Crown wishes a publication ban at the bail hearing so that none of the evidence will be published in a way that would influence those witnesses who might be afraid of the accused and who have not yet given a statement. The Crown would like to call one of the investigating officers to testify at the bail hearing about the accused and about the offense, mainly on the basis of hearsay derived from the investigation. The accused does not want a publication ban at the bail hearing and wishes to call witnesses to testify in support of his defense that the death was caused in self-defence. What are the provisions of the Criminal Code that govern your client's bail hearing, what procedural rulings will likely be made at the bail hearing and what is the likely result?
<p><br>
45 Minutes <b>Question 3:</b> 25% of marks.
<p>
The 22 year old accused was charged in Newmarket with 3 separate counts of sexual assault, involving 3 young children, on October 3, 1993. He was released on bail on strict conditions that he reside with his parents (who acted as surety on his bail), maintain an 8:00 p.m. curfew, report to the police twice a week and not be in the presence of children under 16. The accused was a lifeguard at a local swimming pool and the bail conditions meant that he had to leave his job. It took 3 months for the accused to retain counsel and for the Crown to make disclosure. By January 3, 1994 the parties were ready to set a date for trial. The Crown elected to proceed by indictment and sought an early date so the 3 young boys could testify as soon as possible. The court advised counsel that its lists were heavily booked for the next year and offered January 12, 1995 as the earliest available date for a preliminary inquiry. The court invited counsel to speak to the trial coordinator so that if an earlier date became available, due to other trials being cancelled or adjourned, the case could be brought forward to the earlier date defence counsel advised the court that the January, 1995 date was satisfactory as the accused wished to return to university for the next 3 semesters in order to re-train for a new line of work.
<p>
On January 12, 1995 the preliminary inquiry commenced with two of the young boys testifying for the Crown but there was insufficient time to complete the evidence of the third boy. The next date available for continuation of the preliminary inquiry was June 12, 1995 and the accused was remanded to that date.
<p>
In May, 1995 the Crown provided some additional disclosure to the defense which had just come to light. The new evidence was some school records relating to the first boy, who had already testified, indicating that he had made a false accusation of sexual assault against a school teacher on a prior occasion. The accused's counsel immediately brought an adjournment application in order to further investigate the new disclosure material. He also sought an order requiring the first boy to re-attend for further questioning concerning the newly disclosed material. The adjournment was granted but the judge refused to order the first boy to re-attend at the preliminary inquiry as he held that the newly disclosed material related only to credibility. The next available date was December 12, 1995 and this was noted as the target date to be set when the information and the accused were back in court on June 12, 1995.
<p>
On June 12, 1995 the information was not in court and the case was not listed on the court docket as the court clerk had already filed it for the target date of December 12, 1995. The accused and his counsel sat quietly in the body of the court and when the case was not called or spoken to in any manner they left the court room.
<p>
On December 12, 1995 both the accused and the information are back in court on the docket for continuation of the preliminary inquiry. What should the Crown do? What should the defense do?
<p><br>
45 Minutes <b>Question 4:</b> 25% marks
<p>
There have been 3 serious armoured car robberies in Toronto in the month of September, all involving Brinks' trucks delivering money to bank teller machines. The perpetrator always seems to know the exact time and place of the truck's arrival and takes the guard delivering the money by surprise overpowering him from behind and then escaping in a waiting car. The guards in the 3 robberies all describe their assailant as a man with brown curly hair, tattoos on both arms, and driving a brown North American car with pink dice that dangle from the rear view mirror. The police investigation leads them to suspect that Johnny Rounder is the culprit as he has a lengthy criminal record for robbery, he fits the description given by the 3 guards, he drives a car that fits the description given by the 3 guards, he had just been paroled to Toronto in August when the robberies began in September and he has been known in the past to have contacts inside Brinks who could have informed him of the trucks' delivery schedules. The police conduct a photo line-up, with the 3 guards viewing an array of photos that includes Jimmy's latest mug shot. None of them identifies Jimmy as their assailant and, indeed, one of them remarks that Jimmy's nose is much longer and straighter than the robber's.
<p>
Nevertheless, the police are convinced that Jimmy is the culprit and they obtain a search warrant permitting them to search Jimmy's home for "any and all evidence" relating to the 3 robberies. The information in support of the search warrant is sworn by a junior officer, Constable Mark, who is not familiar with all the facts of the investigation. He sets out all the information known to the police, as recited above, except for the failed photo line-up, which he was not aware of. The police are unable to find the money from the robberies during the search of Jimmy's home but they seize his address book and his clothes. Further investigation of these two items leads to the discovery of the name of a Brinks' employee in Jimmy's address book and forensic testing of Jimmy's gloves produces traces of fibres consistent with Brinks' canvas money bags. The police arrest Jimmy at the local pool hall where he habitually hangs out. They search his car, which is parked two blocks away, and find some of the Brinks' money hidden in the spare tire in the trunk. Jimmy is charged in a single count in an information that alleges he:
<blockquote>
&quot;did steal the property of Brinks by using violence against three of its guards at Toronto on September 4, 16, and 22nd&quot;.
</blockquote>
Jimmy retains you once again as his lawyer and instructs you that he is innocent of the robberies and wishes to call an alibi defense in relation to two of the three dates when the robberies occurred and when he knows exactly where he was. He is unsure of his whereabouts on the third date.
<p>
What issues will you raise at trial in Jimmy's defense? If Jimmy calls alibi evidence in his defense can the Crown then produce Fred Trusty to testify that he is the Brinks' employee who gave Jimmy the information about the trucks' delivery schedules? The police have been using Fred as an informant, since discovering his name in Jimmy's address book, and had not told the Crown about him. The police had hoped to protect Fred's cover so they could continue to use his underworld contacts to solve other crimes. But once Jimmy testifies to an alibi the police feel they must use Fred's evidence now to insure Jimmy is convicted and they disclose it to the Crown
<p><br>
<hr>
