<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Economic Analysis of Law<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor S. Rea</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>The exam is composed of five questions, which are of equal value. The suggested time allocation is 30 minutes per question.<p>
<li>Before you begin ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request and additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<b>1)</b> The Morelawn Lawnmower Company sells a mower which is particularly effective at cutting grass. Because of its excellent performance, the mower sells for $500, which is $100 more than alternative mowers. The mower does not cost any more than other mowers to produce. Unfortunately, users have begun to experience problems with the mower. In 1 out of 100 mowers, the blade flies off the mower and severely injures a bystander. The typical injured bystander suffers losses of $14,000. Ordinary lawnmowers do not have this problem, but they do not cut grass as well. Morelawn could correct the problem by redesigning the mower, but the new mower would
cost $550, and no one will pay more than $500 for a lawnmower.
<blockquote>
a) Sam has suffered a $14,000 loss because of Jane's lawn mower. Under a contributory negligence liability system, whom should he sue, and what is the outcome?
<p>
b) If manufacturer's are strictly liable for losses caused by their products, what is the outcome?
<p>
c) How does your answer in b) change if the losses are suffered by Jane, not Sam.
<p>
d) How does your answer in b) change if the losses are suffered by Jane, and the losses are $9,000?
<p>
e) Describe the no fault approach to lawnmower safety, assuming that the losses are suffered by lawnmower owners. Compare the no fault approach with strict liability of manufacturers.
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<b>2.</b> Essex Wire built a plant next door to Alcoa Aluminum's plant in Indiana. Alcoa and Essex had a contract which specified that Alcoa would sell molten aluminum to Essex. Essex would make aluminum wire from the molten aluminum. The Essex plant was expected to generate $10 million per year in profits because of the lower cost of making wire from molten aluminum Alcoa expected to make $5 million in profits per year from the contract.
<blockquote>
a) Why would Essex want a contract before building the plant next to Alcoa's plant?
</blockquote>
During the energy crisis in the 1970's the price of electricity increased so much that Alcoa was losing $11 million per year on the contract. Alcoa refused to supply any more aluminum and Essex sued.
<blockquote>
b) What arguments would be made by each side in this legal case? Evaluate these arguments from an economic point of view.
<p>
c) If the court decides to enforce the contract, what damages are appropriate?
<p>
d) How would the outcome differ in c) if the court decided to use specific performance rather than damages.
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<b>3)</b> Mary, age 10, is an orphan as a result of the death of her parents in an automobile accident caused by David. Mary's parents were each earning $50,000 per year. She was adopted by her aunt and uncle who had no other children. They each earn $60,000 per year. How will an Ontario court calculate damages in this case? What level of damages would lead to economic efficiency?
<p><br>
<b>4)</b> Diane has rented a car for a twenty week period under an agreement in which she would own the car at the end of the rental period. The payments were specified to be $500 per week for 20 weeks. At the end of the twenty week period the car would have a value of $6000. The agreement contained a clause that said that the car could be repossessed if a payment were missed, and that the agreement would be terminated upon repossession.
Diane forgot to make the last weekly payment on the car and it was repossessed.
<blockquote>
a) Describe Diane's legal position.
<p>
b) Analyze the case and the relevant legal doctrines from an economic of point 
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<b>5.</b> In Lewvest Limited v Scotia Towers Limited the defendant (Scotia), a contractor, was constructing a building adjacent to the plaintiff's property. In the course of construction, the boom of a sky crane swung out over the property of the plaintiff. The plaintiff sought an injunction to prevent this practice.
<p>
The court noted that the extra cost of building without crossing the plaintiff's land is $400,000. Assume that the inconvenience to the plaintiff is valued at $50,000.
<blockquote>
a) The court in this case issued an injunction against Scotia Towers. Is this result efficient? Should the court have chosen another outcome?
<p>
b) How would the court's decision be affected if the court did not know the cost imposed on Lewvest?
<p>
c) If Scotia flew over the land of Lewvest in an airplane, would the court have ruled the same way? Compare the two situations from an economic point of view.
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<hr>
