<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Equality in Employment<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor K. Swinton</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>The exam is composed of one question worth 50% of your final grade.<p>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish (including notes, the casebook, and texts), but you cannot use books owned by the library.<p>
<li>If you feel the need for further facts in order to answer, indicate any factual assumptions that you have made.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.<p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<dd>NRG Company is the owner of Flavelle Hydro (a private operation). The company has a large workforce of both unionized and non-unionized staff. Most employees are represented by the Hydro Workers Union, although there is a separate unit of non-unionized clerical workers and a unit of professional employees represented by the Society of Engineers.
<p>
<dd>There have been a number of workplace incidents in recent months arising from employee use of alcohol and drugs. The most recent involved Tom O'Leary, a line installer. His duties included the installation of overhead electric power lines as well as installation of lines in underground vaults and attachment of lines to homes and other buildings. While working high above the ground in a &quot;cherry picker&quot; type of lift during an overhead line installation, he lost his balance and almost fell to the ground. The operator of the lift was able to get him down safely. Subsequent investigation revealed that Tom was under the influence of alcohol. When his supervisor threatened to recommend discharge, Tom confessed that he was addicted to alcohol, but that he would be willing to undergo treatment if only he could keep his job.
<p>
<dd>Note that Tom has worked for the company for three years. He is in a bargaining unit represented by the Hydro Employees Union.
<p>
<dd>At the moment, Tom is suspended without pay. The Vice-President of Human Resources has come to you for legal advice about a number of issues resulting from this and other incidents involving other employees:
<p>
a) The company's preference is to discharge Tom on the basis that he is a safety risk who endangered himself and other workers during the incident in question and who is likely to be a continuing risk because of his alcoholism. If discharge occurs, what is the likely liability of the company if he brings a complaint to the Ontario Human Rights Commission? Discuss his lines of argument, their likelihood of success and remedial issues. (Assume that the union will not arbitrate any grievance he might have under the collective agreement.)
<p>
b) The company is very concerned about performance problems associated with drug and alcohol use. Instead of discharging Tom, could the company require him to undergo random testing (urine tests or breathalysers) for a period of two years as a condition of keeping his job? If the tests show that he has consumed any alcohol or uses drugs such as cocaine, he will be discharged automatically.
<p>
c) The company might consider, as an alternative to random testing, that Tom be reinstated to a position that is not safety sensitive. Unfortunately, there are only two job classifications in the bargaining unit which fit this requirement - stores clerk and dispatcher. Under the collective agreement, all job openings must be posted and awarded to the most senior employee who applies. Since these two jobs are highly sought after, it is unlikely that Tom has enough seniority to bid for them, and the company wants to know if the seniority rules remain effective in this situation to prevent his reassignment.
<p>
d) Since the incident referred to above, a further matter has come to light. Kate Tyler, who worked on a crew with Tom over the last year, told the team leader that she hoped Tom would not be reinstated - or at least, not in the same work area. Apparently, he had made a series of remarks during their working relationship about her attractive physical appearance and his inability to understand how such a good looking woman could be a lesbian. She tried to laugh the comments off, but they bothered her a great deal. As she put it, &quot;I don't like to make trouble, but I want this to stop&quot;. Should the company be concerned about possible liability under the <cite>Human Rights Code</cite> because of harassment by Tom?
<p>
[In answering the series of questions above, one third of your time should be spent on part (d) and two thirds on the first three parts. Since the first three parts overlap significantly, I have not allocated specific marks to each in order to give you some flexibility in organizing your answer. I will mark them as a unit.]
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
Please send comments and suggestions to <a href="mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</a><p>
Created on MAR-11-96 by Anne Johnston.
</address>
