<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Evidence<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Stewart</h2></center>
<h3>NOTES:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This is a standard open-book examination. You may use any of the following materials during the test: the casebook, an annotated <cite>Criminal Code</cite>, and any notes or summaries. You may not use any textbooks or library materials during the examination.<p>
<li>The examination consists of four (4) questions relating to one fact situation. The questions are not of equal value. Please allocate your time accordingly.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request one or more additional booklet during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within 15 minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the conclusion of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>ALL EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL  BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
NOTE: While you are encouraged to read all four questions before beginning your answer, do not rely on the additional facts presented in later questions when answering earlier questions.
<p>
You may assume, for the purposes of this examination, that to prove a charge of possession of property obtained by theft, the Crown has to establish the following elements: (i) the property was obtained by theft; (ii) the accused was in possession of the property; and (iii) the accused knew the property had been obtained by theft.
<p>
<h4>Facts</h4>
The following facts were available to both the Crown and the defense before the start of the trials mentioned below.
<p>
Quark and Rom are brothers who jointly own and operate a secondhand clothing store in downtown Enterprise in the Canadian province of Flavelle. They live upstairs in a two-bedroom apartment. Quark and Rom share kitchen, washroom, and living room, and though each bedroom has its own lock, the brothers trust each other and rarely lock their doors.
<p>
On 1 August 1995, P.C. O'Brien of the Enterprise Police received a phone call from Garak, owner of a fashionable men's wear shop. Garak said that the previous evening, someone had taken one thousand silk paisley ties from a delivery bay outside his shop. There was little to indicate who had committed the theft, but someone had dropped a brown leather glove at the scene. Garak was extremely distressed about the theft and urged O'Brien to investigate it as quickly as possible.
<p>
Following this report, the Chief Inspector of the Enterprise Police sent P.C. Dax, an undercover officer, to look around second-hand clothing stores in downtown Enterprise. Dax went into Quark and Rom's store. Rom was working alone at the time. Dax asked him, &quot;Have you got any new ties in stock?&quot; Rom replied, &quot;No, no, nothing at all.&quot; It seemed to Dax that this answer betrayed some nervousness, and, seeking a small sealed box behind the counter, she asked Rom, &quot;What's in the box?&quot; Rom replied, &quot;Oh, nothing, nothing at all; it's just an empty box.&quot; Dax then identified herself as a police officer and said, &quot;Now will you tell me what is in the box?&quot; Rom handed the box to Dax, who opened it and discovered 50 silk paisley ties. On her way back to the station, Dax happened to run into Garak, who exclaimed, &quot;Oh wow! Good work! Those are my ties all right.&quot; Dax asked him how he could be so sure, and Garak replied, &quot;I purchased the ties from a foreign manufacturer, but I sewed my own logo directly into the material of each one. Can you see it?&quot;
Dax then obtained a valid search warrant, and returned to search Quark and Rom's shop and apartment. Another 950 ties were discovered in Rom's bedroom.
<p>
Rom was arrested, was charged with possession of property obtained by theft, and was properly cautioned and advised of his right to counsel. After consulting with duty counsel over the phone, Rom gave the following statement to Dax and her colleague P.C. Odo.
<dl>
<dt>Rom:
<dd>On 29 July at about 11:00 p.m., I had just come home from the Enterprise Odeon. True Lies was playing. Our old friend Morn came in with a big box and a small box. Quark spoke to him for some time, and I saw Quark give him some cash. Quark then asked me if I would keep the box in my bedroom, and I said I would.
<p>
<dt>Dax:
<dd>Did you ever see what was in the boxes?
<p>
<dt>Rom:
<dd>No. I didn't know anything until you opened the small box in front of me.
<p>
<dt>Dax:
<dd>Why did you seem so nervous when I came into the shop?
<p>
<dt>Rom:
<dd>You looked like a cop. Quark has been in trouble before, and I was afraid he might be again.
</dl>
Dax and Odo then contacted Morn. Before taking his statement, they said to him, &quot;You must tell us the truth, because if you don't you will be in big trouble.&quot; Morn admitted that he stolen the ties from outside Garak's shop and had brought them to Quark and Rom's shop. He said that in the meeting mentioned by Rom, he had told Quark about the theft. He agreed to testify against Quark in exchange for Dax and Odo's agreement not to prosecute him for the theft. Dax and Odo each made separate transcripts of Morn's statement. and these transcripts agree in every detail.
<p>
Dax and Odo then returned to the shop and arrested Quark for possession of stolen property. He was properly cautioned. When advised of his right to counsel, he said, &quot;I need to talk to Sisko right away.&quot; Dax allowed Quark to call Sisko but Sisko was unavailable. Quark was held overnight and in the morning attempted to contact Sisko again. He was informed that Sisko was away in Cardassia handling a murder trial that was expected to last another week. Dax said, &quot;Why don't you speak to duty counsel, or to another lawyer? We can give you a list of names.&quot; Quark said, &quot;No, Sisko is the best.&quot; Losing patience, Dax and Odo then questioned Quark about the ties. He gave the following statement:
<blockquote>
I don't know what you're talking about. I had no idea there were any ties on the premises. I never saw Morn on the 29th. That evening, I went to see Apollo 13 at the Enterprise Odeon. I not home at about 10:45 and went to bed. That's it.
</blockquote>
Dax and Odo then contacted Kira, the manager of the Enterprise Odeon. Kira confirmed that the theatre had only one screen and that <cite>Apollo 13</cite> was playing that evening.
<p>
Quark, though not Rom, has previously been involved in selling stolen property. In 1990, he was convicted of possession of property obtained by theft, and was given a suspended sentence. He has since been pardoned for this offense. In December 1994, Dax caught Quark in possession of raincoats owned by Bashir and stolen by Morn. Bashir is available to testify about this incident if necessary. Quark was again found guilty and was granted a conditional discharge. Sisko had acted for Quark in these cases and will be Quark's counsel on the current charge.
<p><br>
<b>Question 1.</b> (35 marks)
<p>
Quark has waived his preliminary inquiry and has elected trial by judge and jury. You are the judge. Rule on the following pretrial motions, outlining the positions of both parties and providing reasons and authority for your decisions.
<p>
(a) (15 marks)<br>
Quark has challenged the constitutional validity of s. 359(1) of the Criminal Code and asks that it be declared of no force and effect (this section appears on p. 609 of the materials; you may assume that the Crown has complied with the notice provision in s. 359(2)). The Crown seeks to uphold the section. Assume that you are deciding the question free from authority (that is, ignore any cases on point that may appear in your annotated Criminal Code). How do you rule?
<p>
(b) (20 marks)<br>
The Crown attorney has advised you that Garak has died. The Crown proposes to have Dax testify as to what Garak told her when she encountered him on her way back to the station. The defense objects to this line of questioning. How do you rule?
<p><br>
<b>Question 2.</b> (35 marks)
<p>
You are a member of Quark's defense team. Quark has decided to testify; he will admit knowing that Rom had ties in his bedroom, but will deny any knowledge of how they were obtained. Sisko has asked you to provide him with a memorandum considering any evidentiary issues that may be raised, other than those considered in Question 1, based on the facts presented so far. Write the memorandum, providing reasons and authority for your conclusions.
<p><br>
<b>Question 3.</b> (15 marks)
<p>
You are a law clerk for the judge at Quark's trial. Rom has testified that he himself stole the ties from Garak's shop, that he himself met with Morn to discuss how they should be disposed of, and that Quark was asleep during this conversation. Rom has testified further that he dropped the brown glove found at the scene during the theft; during his testimony, he has tried it on and it fits him perfectly. Morn's testimony is consistent with Rom's. Crown counsel has cross-examined both Rom and Morn on their earlier statements, but both witnesses have refused to adopt them. Crown counsel wants the judge to tell the jury that they can consider the earlier statements for their truth; defense counsel submits that the statements should go only to the witness's credibility. The judge has reserved her decision overnight and has asked you for a memorandum fully analyzing the parties' submissions and recommending a ruling. Write the memorandum.
<P><br>
<b>Question 4.</b> (15 marks)
<p>
You are an articling student in the Flavelle Crown Law Office. Rom is about to stand trial for possession of the stolen ties. Assume that he will testify in his own defense, and that his evidence will be consistent with the statement he originally gave to Dax and Odo. Your principal has asked you whether there is any way the Crown can use Rom's initial conversation with Dax, or Rom's testimony at Quark's trial and any evidence deriving from it, at Rom's trial. Prepare the memorandum, providing reasons and authority for your conclusions.
<p><br>
<hr>
