<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Family Law<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Rogerson</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>The exam is composed of three questions. Question one is mandatory. Question two offers you a choice of three topics: do only one. Question three offers you a choice of five topics: again, do only one. The questions are of equal value.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<b>1.</b> Sarah and David have been married for 27 years. They were married in June of 1968. At the time of the marriage David was working for a major automobile company. (He had started work when he was 18). He continued to work for the company throughout the marriage, and now, at the age of 52, holds an executive
position. At the time of the marriage Sarah, who is two years younger than David, had just completed a Masters Degree in history. During the first few years of the marriage she completed her doctorate, with financial support from David, combined with student loans and graduate teaching assistantships. After completing her graduate studies, she found a teaching position at a university. After many years of a successful academic career, she moved into university administration. Three years ago she was made President of the university, a position which she continues to hold. Sarah and David had no children. Sarah and David separated by mutual consent six
months ago, in June of 1995.
<p>
The parties have resided together in several homes. When David was 19 he inherited a house worth $18,000 from his grandmother, which was worth $25,000 at the date of marriage. The house is registered in his name alone. The parties moved into that house right after the wedding and lived there for eight years. When they moved into their second home, David rented out the first house. The rental income from the first house has always been deposited into a bank account in David's name. The account has accumulated rental income and interest and had a balance of $25,000 six months ago and $27,000 today. The first house was worth $100,000 six months ago. Unfortunately, last month David was notified that the house was built on property that has been found to be contaminated with toxic wastes. The tenants have moved out and the property is now worthless.
<p>
The parties' second home was purchased in joint tenancy and continues to be held that way today. At the date of separation, the parties were not living in the jointly owned home because as President of the university, Sarah was obliged to live in the President's residence on the campus. The jointly owned home was worth $350,000 when Sarah became President, $320,000 six months ago and $300,000 today. It had a mortgage of $150,000 when Sarah became President; $60,000 six months ago; and $58,000 today. When David moved out of the President's residence, he moved back into the jointly owned home and has now put it on the market for sale. He is making all mortgage and utility payments on the home. The President's residence in which Sarah lives was worth $500,000 both six months ago and today and has no mortgage.
<p>
When the parties moved into the President's residence, they put their furniture in storage. Six months ago the value of the furniture was $30,000. It is worth the same amount today. When David moved back into the jointly owned home, he took the furniture out of storage.
<p>
David has been purchasing shares in the auto company for which he works every year since he began employment. Today the shares are worth $75,000. Six months ago they were worth $70,000. At the time of the marriage, he owned shares worth $5,000.
<p>
When David and Sarah married each owned furniture worth $1,000, all of which has since been thrown out. David owed a car worth $3,000. Sarah had student loans of $6,000. She took out another $5,000 worth of student loans during her doctoral studies. The car was traded in after the marriage and the proceeds applied to the parties' first new car and the student loans were paid off years ago.
<p>
In addition to the bank account which contains the rental income from the first home, David has another account in his name. Six months ago it had a balance of $2,400 and today the balance is $1,800. The parties had a joint account that had $3,200 in it six months ago and is closed today. The parties split the money after separation and closed the account. Sarah also has her own bank account. Six months ago, the account had $1,000 in it. David says that within the last five months Sarah was awarded a prestigious prize, worth $25,000, for her contributions to academic life over the course of her career and the balance in the bank account is now $26,000.
<p>
In 1973, Sarah's grandfather died and left her a farm worth $75,000. Six months ago the farm was worth $250,000 and today it is worth $225,000. A farm manager looks after and lives on the property. David and Sarah visited the farm occasionally and had planned to move there after they retired. Sarah also inherited from her grandfather an antique desk, worth $6,000. The desk had always been kept in the room in their various homes designated as the study, and had been used by both of them. It was the one piece of furniture Sarah moved into the President's house. Six months ago its value was $15,000, and it has the same value today.
<p>
Two years ago David's mother died and left him $150,000. He used $75,000 of the money to pay down some of the mortgage on the jointly held home. In an effort to bolster their marriage, he used $25,000 for a two month world tour which he and Sarah took. He also bought Sarah $10,000 worth of jewelry, which he gave to her as a gift, and which she still has. Its value has not changed. He spent the balance of $40,000 to purchase an antique car. Six months ago the car was worth $50,000 and today it is worth $60,000.
<p>
Sarah's parents, who are still alive, own a cottage where David and Sarah spent a good portion of each summer during their marriage. It is understood within the family that Sarah, an only child, will inherit the cottage when her parents die. Over the years, David, who enjoys building and carpentry, has spent a fair amount of his time and labour improving and renovating the cottage, and he and Sarah have expended approximately $20,000 of their joint funds to pay for some of the improvements. The cottage, which was worth $25,000 when they were married, is now worth $200.000 (which was also its worth six months ago).
<p>
Both parties have credit card debts. Six months ago David owed $4,500, $2,500 of which was for corporate expenses for which he can be reimbursed. Today he owes $2,000 of personal expenses. Sarah owed $2,600 on her credit card six months ago and $1,800 today.
<p>
David and Sarah want to negotiate a separation agreement to deal with their property claims under the <cite>Family Law Act</cite>. (Spousal support is not an issue.) David has come to seek your advice. Please prepare an opinion for David explaining how the NFP calculation would be done on the facts as they have been presented above. Please provide a written commentary in addition to your numerical calculations so that David will be able to understand how each asset is being dealt with under the Act. If you feel you do not have sufficient information, feel free to make assumptions so long as you indicate you are doing so.
<p><br>
<b>2.</b> Please choose <b>ONE</b> of the following three questions:
<p>
(a) This question asks you to write a judgment in a case involving a claim for spousal support. Mr. and Mrs. Butler were married in 1984. There were no children of their marriage, although Mrs. Butler has a daughter born in 1975. Mrs. Butler had no continuing relationship with the child's father and he has played no role in their lives. Mrs. Butler is now aged 43. She completed high school with a Grade 12 diploma in June 1969. Prior to the birth of her daughter she was employed in a series of clerical positions and also worked part-time as a waitress. After the birth of her daughter, until her marriage in 1984, Mrs. Butler received Mother's Allowance benefits which she supplemented with income she earned from babysitting. During the marriage she did not work outside the home but continued to earn approximately $75-$100 per week from babysitting. Mrs. Butler suffered from longstanding health problems including recurring migraine headaches, shoulder pain, and back pain. Prior to their marriage, Mr. Butler was aware that Mrs. Butler had some health problems. Mr. Butler, an elementary school teacher, is 48 years of age. His current annual salary is $63,319.
<p>
The marriage was not a happy one. Problems arose early on, and late in 1986 the parties sought the assistance of the first of a series of marriage counsellors. By April of 1990 there was little communication between the parties; they participated in almost no activities together; and sexual relations had ceased. In May of 1991 they separated and Mrs. Butler commenced proceedings for divorce under the <cite>Divorce Act 1985</cite>. Since the separation Mr. Butler has paid interim spousal support of $400 per week. The parties have settled their property claims under Part I of the <cite>Family Law Act</cite> in a separation agreement. Mrs. Butler will receive $47,000 as her share of the net proceeds of the matrimonial home (which was purchased entirely with the husband's funds) and another $30,000 in respect of Mr. Butler's pension. In 1993 Mrs. Butler was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis. She is not employable and, as the disease progresses, she will likely become more incapacitated in the future.
<p>
The divorce proceedings are now being heard. Mrs. Butler's lawyer has asked for permanent spousal support pursuant to s. l5 of the <cite>Divorce Act</cite>, while Mr. Butler's lawyer has argued that no spousal support should be awarded. You are the judge hearing the case. Write your judgment on the spousal support issue. In your judgment you are expected to canvass the legal issues raised by this set of facts and the relevant case law. (Assume that there is no issue of child support. Mrs. Butler's daughter, who continues to reside with her, is now twenty years old and employed, earning a modest income.)
<p>
(b) Rejecting recent proposals now dominant in American law reform circles to restructure spousal support around the economic principle of compensation for lost opportunities, several American academics have instead lent their support to what they term an &quot;income-sharing&quot; regime of spousal support, under which divorcing spouses would continue to share their joint incomes equally for a set numbers of years after divorce. Some proposals are for one year of sharing for every two years of marriage; some for one year of sharing for every year of marriage. Discuss these proposals, drawing on the cases and materials you have studied in the course. Would such an &quot;income-sharing&quot; regime be preferable to the current regime governing spousal support in Canada? Should the federal government draft spousal support guidelines based on these proposals? (This question will require an assessment of the current state of the law in Canada, as well as of the implications of the proposed regime.)
<p>
(c) You have been asked by the editors of the <cite>Canadian Bar Review</cite> to write a case comment on the recent decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in the case of <cite>L.G. v. G.B.</cite> (casebook, page 785). In your case comment you should discuss, amongst other issues, the state of the law prior to the decision; the possible impact of the decision on the area of law it deals with; and whether the directions suggested by the decision constitute a desirable development in the law.
<p><br>
<b>3.</b> Choose <b>ONE</b> of the following five questions.
<p>
(a) In a recent article on family law Professor Carol Weisbrod has argued that &quot;...the expressive or symbolic aspects of law should be used in the field of family law to guide people to better behaviour.&quot; Discuss, drawing on the materials examined during the course. Do you agree that family law should serve this role? To what extent does current Canadian family law, as you have studied it in the course, reflect this understanding of the role of law? What are the symbolic messages currently sent out by family law? Should they be changed?
<p>
(b) Has the &quot;no-fault&quot; revolution in family law been a mistake, as some of the readings in the course have suggested? Should the law continue to make rulings on &quot;fault&quot; and condition family law relief accordingly? Are we deluding ourselves into thinking that &quot;fault&quot; has disappeared? Comment, drawing on cases and materials discussed in the course.
<p>
(c) Sociological studies reveal the diversity of family forms in Canada today. Has modern family law, to the extent that you have encountered it in the course, been appropriately responsive to that diversity? To what extent does family law still suffer from the &quot;monolithic bias&quot; described by sociologist Margrit Eichler as &quot;a tendency to treat the family as a monolithic structure with an emphasis on uniformity of experience and universality of structure and functions rather than on diversity of experiences, structures and functions&quot;?
<p>
(d) Carol Smart argued, when writing about family law in Britain in 1982, that although the law was no longer oppressive of women in a simple and direct fashion and no longer condoned the &quot;grossest abuses of patriarchal power&quot;, it still legitimated patriarchy in less direct and obvious ways. Could the same be said of family law in Canada today?
<p>
(e) Professor Barbara Bennett Woodhouse, writing of American law, has criticized modern family law's vision of marriage as an expression of values of independence and individualism rather than as a commitment to co-operation and interdependence. She urges a revitalization of family law based on rewarding nurturing, commitment and solidarity, and on sustaining friendly environments for children's growth:
<blockquote>
&quot;I would suggest that any proposed standard be based in care giving and be strongly child-centered: the goal against which to measure family laws should be whether they promote the family's contemporary purpose of insuring a stable base for the growth of children and the mutual support of adults. Laws should encourage and reward family-centric, cooperative, nurturing behaviour. Three things draw me to this choice: first, it seems morally right; second, it seems pragmatically sound; and third, it respects the notion of liberty as freedom coupled with responsibility enshrined by John Stuart Mill.&quot;
</blockquote>
Discuss. Do you agree with Woodhouse's proposed standard for revitalization of family law? Do you see any problems with it? To what extent does Canadian family law, as you have studied it in the course, fall short of that standard and, if it does, what implications would the adoption of such a standard have on the future development of family law in Canada?
<p><br>
<hr>
