<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>First Nations and the Law<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Macklem</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>There are two Parts to this Examination.<p>
<li>Those who have opted to hand in an Essay in accordance with the Essay Option are to answer only Part I. Part I is worth 50% of your final grade. Your Essay is worth the other 50% of your grade. Please include your Essay in your Examination booklet. You must stop writing at 11:00 a.m. Do not continue to write after this time. When you leave the room, please be considerate to those who are writing the complete Examination.<p>
<li>Those students who have opted not to hand in an Essay must answer Part I and Part II. Each Part is worth 50% of your final grade. You must stop writing at 12:30 p.m.<p>
<li>Because this examination contains relatively open-ended questions, you have some latitude in deciding what to discuss. You must make good faith efforts not to duplicate your responses in each Part. Similarly, those of you who opted to hand in an Essay must make good faith efforts to craft an answer to Part I which is distinct from your Essay.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.<p>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<center><h3>PART I</h3></center>
<b>NOTE: All students are required to answer Part I.</b>
<p>
Answer only <b>one</b> of the following two questions:
<p>
<b>1.</b> An Aboriginal Affairs Task Force established by the Reform Party of Canada issued a Report
on September 15, 1995. In its Report, the Task Force stated:
<blockquote>
&quot;We believe government, through a democratic process, should assist Aboriginal people to take responsibility for the programs affecting them, and encourage economic selfsufficiency. We believe in the equality of citizens of Canada and say that policies relating to Aboriginal persons should respect that principle.&quot;
</blockquote>
The Task Force recommended that the following policy statements form Reform Party policy:
<blockquote>
&quot;(a) Indian treaties will be fully honoured according to their original intent and in keeping with Court interpretation;
<p>
(b) Indian and Inuit affairs will continue to be administered by the federal government, and M&eacute;tis and non-status Indian affairs will remain the jurisdiction of provincial governments;
<p>
(c) Indian self-government will be a delegated form of government and not a recognition of inherent Aboriginal sovereignty;
<blockquote>
(i) all lands within the borders of Canada will remain part of Canada;
<p>
(ii) any form of self-government must uphold the principles of democracy and accountability (i.e., the freedom to organize politically, free and open election processes, opposition parties);
<p>
(iii) the laws of Canada (and the Provinces and Territories), including the Canadian Constitution and the Charter of Rights and Freedoms, will apply;
<p>
(iv) any laws enacted by Indian self-government must conform with the laws of Canada.
</blockquote>
(d) Land claim agreements and self-government agreements will be negotiated under the principle of equality for and among all persons;
<blockquote>
(i) settlement of land claims will be negotiated publicly. All settlements will outline specific terms, be final, and conclude within a specific time frame:
<p>
(ii) final settlements will be affordable to Canada and the Provinces;
</blockquote>
(e) Individuals residing on settlement lands will have the freedom to opt for private ownership of their entitlements.
<p>
(f) Property owners forced to defend their property rights as a result of Aboriginal land claims will be compensated for defence of the claim.
<p>
(g) Individuals may decide whether they wish to contribute financially to Indian political organizations such as the Assembly of First Nations. This will replace direct funding of these organizations.
<p>
(h) Individuals who live on reserves and who are eligible to receive benefits such as social assistance may receive those benefits either from the federal government or through Indian self-government.
<p>
(i) The Auditor General of Canada will have full authority to review the Indian management of federal funds.
<p>
(j) Complaints directed to Indian government about management of federal funds may be appealed to the Auditor General of Canada, who may recommend civil or criminal proceedings.
<p>
(k) The Chief Electoral Officer of Elections Canada will have the same authority to examine Indian election procedures as he/she would have in any other federal jurisdiction.
<p>
(l) Complaints directed to Indian government about election procedures may be appealed to the Chief Electoral Officer, who may recommend civil or criminal proceedings.
<p>
(m) As the economic climate within Indian-governed communities improves and money is transferred from senior governments to individuals, Indian governments will fund their operations by taxing the members of these communities.
<p>
(n) Since equality of all citizens is the ultimate goal, Indian persons and corporations will be subject to the same taxation provisions as other Canadians. As Indian economic conditions improve, the taxation exemption under s. 87 of the Indian Act [which exempts reserve lands and personal property of an Indian on a reserve from taxation], will be eliminated.
<p>
(o) The Indian Act of Canada will be repealed and replaced by legislation respecting the above principles.
<p>
(p)A new relationship with Aboriginal peoples shall begin with a convention of Indian representatives from across Canada (elected by Aboriginal people) who will meet with senior government leaders to discuss how to apply these principles.&quot;
</blockquote>
Please discuss these policy statements in light of what we have covered in the course. Do you agree with them? If so, why? If not, why not? You are not required to comment on every statement, but you should address at least three statements in your answer.
<p><br>
<b>2.</b> In <cite>Delgammukw v. British Columbia</cite>, Mr. Justice Lambert wrote a dissenting judgment in which he stated (at pp. 160-61 of vol. I of the casebook) that:
<blockquote>
&quot;I would declare that the present aboriginal rights of self-government and self-regulation of the Gitksan and Wet'suwet'en peoples, exercisable in relation to their aboriginal title, would include the specific rights claimed in this appeal by the plaintiffs in relation to aboriginal title, namely,
<blockquote>
(a) a right to harvest, manage and conserve the lands and their resources, having regard to:
<blockquote>
(i) the preservation and enhancement of the quality and productivity of the natural environment;
<p>
(ii) the immediate and long-term economic, social and cultural benefits that may accrue to the plaintiffs and their future generations; and
<p>
(iii) consultation and cooperation with ministries and agencies of the Crown and with the private sector who may be affected by the exercise of the plaintiffs' rights;
</blockquote>
(b) a right to maintain and develop their institutions for the regulation of their aboriginal title and for the harvesting, management and conservation of the lands and their resources:
</blockquote>
I would declare that the present Aboriginal rights of self-government and self-regulation of the Gitksan and Wet'suwet'en peoples, would include rights of self-government and self-regulation exercisable through their own institutions to preserve and enhance their social, political, cultural, linguistic and spiritual identity.&quot;
</blockquote>
Mr. Justice Lambert also held that the above-mentioned rights are recognized and affirmed by s. 35(1) of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1982</cite>. Do you agree with his definition of Aboriginal rights and his view that s. 35(1) recognizes and affirms Aboriginal rights of self-government? If so, why? If not, why not?
<p><br>
<center><h3>PART II</h3></center>
<b>Note: Only those students who have opted not to write an Essay are to answer Part II.</b>
<p>
Answer only <b>one</b> of the following two questions.
<p>
<b>1.</b> Will Kymlicka, in <cite>Liberalism, Community and Culture</cite> (1991) writes the following (at pp. 47-48 of vol. I of the casebook):
<blockquote>
&quot;... a liberal needs to know whether a request for special rights or resources is grounded in differential choices or unequal circumstances. Someone who cultivates a taste for expensive wine has no legitimate claim to a special public subsidy, since she is responsible for the costs of her choice. Someone who needs expensive medicine due to a natural disability has a legitimate claim to a special public subsidy, since she is not responsible for the costs of her disadvantageous circumstances....
<p>
We can legitimately ask that aboriginal people form their plans of life with a view to the costs imposed by others, as measured by the market.... If the land aboriginal people wish to be left undeveloped is valuable to others, then their desire is costly to others, and [one might argue that] it is only fair that they pay for this costly desire ....
<p>
However, we can defend aboriginal rights [to, among other things, secure and use the land they desire] as a response, not to shared choices, but to unequal circumstances. Unlike the dominant French or English cultures, the very existence of aboriginal cultural communities is vulnerable to the decisions of the non-aboriginal majority around them. They could be outbid or outvoted on resources crucial to the survival of their communities, a possibility that members of the majority cultures do not face. As a result, they have to spend their resources on securing the cultural membership which makes sense of their lives, something which non-aboriginal people get for free.... The rectification of this inequality is the basis for a liberal defence of aboriginal rights, and of minority rights in general.&quot;
</blockquote>
Please comment on Kymlicka's defence of Aboriginal rights in light of <cite>Norris v. Thomas</cite>, [1992] 2 C.N.L.R. 139, where the British Columbia Supreme Court held spirit dancing is not-a right recognized by s. 35(1) of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1982</cite>. Do you agree with Kymlicka? If so, why? If not, why not?
<p><br>
<b>2.</b> In <cite>Guerin v. The Queen</cite> (1984), 13 D.L.R. (4th) 321, the Supreme Court of Canada recognized a fiduciary relationship between the Crown and Aboriginal nations in Canada. Please comment on the Court's reasoning in <cite>Guerin</cite> in light of the various normative justifications for differential treatment on the basis of indigenous difference that we examined early on in the course.
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
