<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Insurance Law<br>
December 1995<br>
Mr. H.B. Radomski</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>The exam is composed of <b>one</b> question.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<dd>In late 1992, Glen Fox invited his brother, Neil, and two other brothers, at his expense, to travel with him from Seattle to Russia to tour Russia during July, 1993. Ultimately, an uncle, Ed Hewitt learned of the trip and was added to the tour, again at Glen's expense.
<p>
<dd>The tour was arranged through Whitman County Travel Inc. of Colfax, Washington, and was to depart from Seattle, Washington on July 1, 1993. The tour cost was U.S. $3,250.00 per person. Glen paid to Whitman all of the travel costs in U.S. funds on behalf of everyone, including the cost of travel from British Columbia for Ed Hewitt and the cost of travel for the others from Calgary.
<p>
<dd>The tour package provided for refunds subject to certain cancellation fees to be retained by the tour promoter up to June 1, 1993. The package provided that, after that date, &quot;no refunds can be expected&quot;.
<p>
<dd>On April 1, 1993, Neil, through Harding Hall and Graburn Insurance Inc. of Calgary, purchased two policies of travel insurance with John Ingle Insurance, a division of Commercial Union Life Assurance Company of Canada, one in his name and one in the name of Glen. The premiums for this insurance in the amount of $478.10 were paid by Glen. Coverage was confirmed by John Ingle on April 30, 1993. These policies provided, among other things, for the recovery of certain losses sustained by an insured by reason of trip cancellation.
<p>
The trip cancellation policies contained the following provisions, among others:
<blockquote><ol>
<li>Trip Cancellation, Interruption and Delay
<p>
When expenses are incurred as a result of an emergency or death of you, a member of your extended family or a companion or business associate with whom you are travelling during the policy period, the company will pay for:
<blockquote>
(i) The non-refundable portion of your deposit paid in advance and irrecoverable from any other source if you must cancel an insured trip, up to a maximum of $500.00, or up to the amount purchased at the time of application, per policy period. The maximum payable under the family plan is $15,000.00
</blockquote>
<li>Emergency was defined as follows:
<p>
&quot;Emergency&quot; means an unexpected or unforeseeable sickness or injury which requires immediate non-discretionary medical attention, treatment or care.
<p>
<li>Sickness was defined as follows:
<p>
&quot;Sickness&quot; means illness or disease which results in emergency treatment or care during the policy period.
<p>
<li>Claims
<p>
Please complete the Claim Form when making a claim under this policy and include (i) an original medical certificate from the attending physician indicating the diagnosis, (ii) cancelled transportation tickets, (iii) receipts for all pre-paid deposits, and (iv) correspondence and the amount of reimbursement from your travel agent.
<p>
Important
<ul>
<li>claims must be reported within 30 days of occurrence.
<li>written proof of claim is required within 90 days of occurrence.
<li>claims cannot be considered unless the claim form is duly completed and signed by the claimant and the attending physician with all required documentation.
<li>all documentation must be supplied free of expense to the company.
</ul>
</ol></blockquote>
<dd>On April 24,1993, Glen purchased three return airline tickets from Calgary to Seattle for himself and each of his brothers.
<p>
<dd>On May 12, 1993, Neil became very ill, suffering nausea, chills, fever and general malaise receiving medical treatment on two occasions up to May 19 when he was admitted to hospital where he remained until discharged on May 31. He was suffering from an acute infectious illness, presumably viral in nature, almost like acute malaria, although the nature of the infectious organism was never determined. Neil was advised by his doctor, on or about June 11, 1993, that he would not be able to travel and he accordingly advised Whitman County Travel Inc. and John Ingle to that effect on June 12 and 16, 1993 respectively. He continued under medical treatment for his condition until the end of September when he was advised that he could again travel.
<p>
<dd>When Neil applied for the travel insurance through Harding Hall and Graburn, he completed a questionnaire in which he was asked whether he was under doctor's care. He left the question blank but, in his discussion with Harding Hall and Graburn, was asked whether he was under any permanent disability and said no. At the time, Neil had not been feeling very well and had spoken to a cousin, a doctor, by telephone. The cousin told Neil that it was probably nothing more than fatigue and that the trip to Russia would be a welcome break.
<p>
<dd>Although not asked about prior trip cancellations either in the questionnaire or in his discussion with Harding Hall and Graburn, Neil had in fact experienced some bad luck in vacations in the past, having had to cancel two such vacations in the past five years due to illness.
<p>
<dd>On June 24, 1993, Whitman County Travel Inc. confirmed to Neil, in writing, receipt of the U.S. $3,250.00 on his behalf for the tour, for submission to his insurer. This, along with the doctor's statement, his airline tickets to and from Seattle and a claim form authorizing release of all medical records to the insurer were forwarded to John Ingle on July 6, 1993.
<p>
<dd>On September 10, 1993, Commercial Union paid Neil the sum of Cdn. $326.02 for reimbursement of the cost of the airline ticket to and from Seattle for Neil. John Ingle thereafter learned in telephone discussions with Whitman County Travel Inc. that there had been one cancellation of the tour for which a $200.00 cancellation fee had been paid to the tour organizer in Washington D.C., although there was no information in its records as to who had cancelled. John Ingle also learned that Glen had paid for Neil's tour package, among others.
<p>
<dd>Suspecting that Neil's uncle had gone in his stead and that a possible fraud was being practised on the insurer, John Ingle delayed payment of the balance of the claim until further information was provided. Proof of payment of the tour package for each of Neil, Glen and the brothers as well as the uncle was then provided to Commercial Union. It then issued a cheque payable to Neil in the amount of $4,049.50 (U.S. $3,250.00) but held delivery. On October 18, 1993, Neil filed a written proof of claim. On November 2, 1993 by letter in writing addressed to Neil, John Ingle declined the balance of the claim advising that an appeal could only be made by production of certified copies of payments made to the travel agent and the provision of a sworn Affidavit that Neil had paid for his own trip and had not received a refund.
<p>
<dd>In the interim, on October 13, 1993, Glen received a refund cheque marked &quot;Refund for Neil Fox&quot; from Whitman County Travel Inc. in the amount of U.S. $1,501.00 (Cdn. $1,870.25), the covering letter to Glen stating:
<blockquote>
&quot;Per our telephone conversation, attached find the refund cheque in the amount of U.S. $1,501.00 for your brother Neil.&quot;
</blockquote>
<dd>Neil only learned of this refund at or about the time of the receipt of the letter from John Ingle of November 2, 1993. As a result of that letter, Neil made demand against Commercial Union for the full recovery of the cost of the tour package. Commercial Union disputed Neil's claim on a number of grounds. Commercial Union also argued that, if Neil was entitled to recovery, the amount should be limited to $2,179.25, the sum of Cdn. $1,870.25 having been recovered by Glen or his agent on his behalf, as a refund from Whitman County Travel Inc.
<p>
<dd>Neil then sought legal advice as to commencing an action against Commercial Union for recovery under the cancellation policy.
<p>
<dd>As counsel for Neil, please advise Neil as to the following:
<ol>
<li>Who should be named as Defendants in addition to Commercial Union, if anyone?
<p>
<li>What claims should Neil assert and against whom?
<p>
<li>What possible defences are available to Commercial Union and any other Defendants?
<p>
<li>What is the likelihood of success in the action given the defences likely to be raised by Commercial Union and other Defendants?
</ol>
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
