<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>International Trade Regulation<br>
Take-Home Examination<br>
December 1995</h2></center>
<h3>INSTRUCTIONS:</h3>
The Faculty of Law take-home exam policy states, in part: &quot;It is expected that there will be consultation amongst students writing the same take home examination, although the answer or answers returned by the student must be organized and written by that student alone&quot;.
<p>
Students should pay particular attention to the need for a take home answer to be their own work. It must be &quot;organized and written by that student alone&quot;. Contravening this rule is an academic offence under the University's Code of Academic Conduct. You may refer to any materials you wish.
<p>
Your answer must be returned within 48 hours of pickup, either to the Records Office in person or by fax to (416) 978-7899 or (416) 323-9491. (However, if you are picking up the examination question by fax at the end of the day on Friday, you may return your answer at the beginning of business on Monday). If you are returning the answer by fax, please keep a copy of the activity report from your fax machine.
<p>
There is a limit of 14 double-spaced, typed pages. Both answers should be of approximately equal length (7 pages).
<p>
<hr>
<p><br>
Answer <b>any two</b> of the following three questions:
<ol>
<li>&quot;National Treatment is the core international trade principle that addresses the effects of domestic regulation on liberalized trade. Attempts to move beyond National Treatment towards harmonization of domestic regulation are likely to produce incoherence and further conflict in international trading relations.&quot; Discuss, drawing on at least two of the following three areas: services, intellectual property rights, product and process
standards.
<p>
<li>&quqot;Trade action against subsidies and dumping may be economically irrational but it helps preserve a political balance between the interests of trading partners in hard economic times. Alternative approaches, such as safeguards or emergency action, are unlikely to he effective in the real world.&quot; Discuss.
<p>
<li>&quot;Using trade sanctions as a last-ditch response to violations of labour rights and inadequate environmental standards of trading partners is a reasonable compromise of domestic sovereignty in an increasingly interdependent world.&quot; Discuss.
</ol>
<p><br>
<hr>
