<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Introduction to Legal Theory<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Nedelsky</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This is a three hour open book exam. Students may bring with them any notes, books, or materials that they wish. Each student must answer 2 questions. In choosing which theorists to <b>FOCUS</b> on, <b>YOU MUST CHOOSE DIFFERENT THEORISTS FOR EACH QUESTION.</b> Each question is weighted equally.
<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
1. What difference do conceptions of the self or agency make for law? Focus on 2 or 3 authors, referring to one or two others by way of support, contrast or example.
<p>
2. In different ways, Peller, MacKinnon, Finley and Williams all focus on law and language as contingent social creations. Explain how we can understand the nature of law and its potential and limitations as an agent of change (or of security or liberty) better by using their perspectives. What problems arise from adopting these perspectives and what are the potential solutions to them? (If you think the problems cannot be overcome, you may use this question to focus on the problems and use a contrasting author, such as Dworkin, to defend an alternative.) If you wish, you may use Taylor and/or Williams to focus on the importance of narrative or storytelling in the understanding and practice of law.
<p>
3. Discuss Dworkin's distinction between principle and policy and the role they play in his understanding of what a judge should do. Use two or three of the authors listed at the end of this question to critically engage with Dworkin's argument, and to reflect on what, if any, ways we should distinguish &quot;law&quot; from &quot;politics.&quot; Is there anything that should distinctively characterize "law"? Peller MacKinnon, Scales, Crenshaw and Williams.
<p>
4. What is Crenshaw's defence of the usefulness of rights? Does she tacitly accept a Dworkinian understanding of rights? What are the similarities and differences between their understandings (recognizing that Crenshaw is not spelling out a full theory of rights)? Use 2 of the following to further explore the strengths and weaknesses of invoking legal rights to achieve equality: MacKinnon, Peller, Taylor, Scales.
<p>
5. A great deal of feminist theory urges us to make &quot;difference&quot; central. Scales tells us to seek a legal system that &quot;works and at the same time makes differences a cause for celebration, not classification&quot; (p. 1376, 141 of casebook). How should we approach this issue? What would it mean to make difference central to law? What are the problems, what are the advantages? use three of the following: Benhabib, Spellman, Crenshaw, Gilligan, MacKinnon, Scales, Hoagland, Nedelsky.
<p>
6. There are many variants of the critique of universalistic conceptions of rights and of the replies that, however, useful the particularistic, context focused alternatives, we cannot do without some universal claims. Discuss three of the following: Scales, Benhabib, Tronto, Nedelsky and Taylor, or focus on two of them and contrast with Rawls.
<p>
7. Use Taylor, Galston, and Sandel (you may focus primarily on two of them) and Rawls to discuss the question of whether all theories of rights have a conception of the good underlying them. What difference does this issue make for our understanding of the nature of the law and its neutrality? Your essay may focus primarily on Taylor, Galston, Sandel and bring in Rawls only by way of counterpoint, or you may reverse the emphasis and focus on the defence of the priority of right. If you reverse the emphasis, you may also want to consider Dworkin.
<p>
8. Interpretation as an essential component of law is increasingly important in contemporary legal theory. Discuss the differences in the way 3 of the following theorists use argument about interpretation and the usefulness, strengths and weaknesses of each. Dworkin's &quot;Integrity in Law&quot;, Peller, Mackinnon, Crenshaw, and Williams.
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
