<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Labour Law<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Langille</h2></center>
<h3>NOTES:</h3>
<ol><i>
<li>You may use the casebook, the supplement, statutes, other course materials, and your own notes during the exam. Textbooks are not permitted.<p>
<li>Please try to write legibly and double space your answer.<p>
<li>Questions are NOT of equal value.<p>
<li>If you think you need further information to answer the question state what it is and why you need it.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</i></ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<center><h3>QUESTION</h3></center>
<dd>On Monday, December 11, 1995 a number of events occurred in London, Ontario by way of a protest against the policies of the new provincial government. These events were preceded by a media campaign financed by various unions, community groups and other organizations. The objective of the exercise was to bring the City of London &quot;to a halt&quot; and to hold a large protest rally. On that day the following events transpired and require your analysis.
<ol>
<li>[<i>20 marks</i>] At Truro Manufacturing Ltd., an auto parts manufacturer, the Union representing the production staff is the Canadian Auto Workers (CAW). The CAW and Truro are in mid-collective agreement. The CAW had approached Truro prior to December 11 to attempt &quot;to negotiate&quot; a special day off without pay in order to facilitate the protest. While some other employers in the area have agreed to do this, Truro remained firm and refused to participate in such an ad hoc arrangement. Management at Truro has been influenced by the views of a popular local radio station talk show host (Vic Vacuo) who has been lambasting the day of protest as a &quot;socialist conspiracy&quot; and &quot;an illegal strike to boot&quot;. On the day in question a very large proportion of Truro's employees do not appear at work and do participate in the protest rally. <b>What is the legal situation on the l1th? Fully and critically analyze the position of Truro, the CAW and the workers. What if Truro and the CAW had agreed to a day off without pay? Vic Vacuo says this would still be an illegal strike. Is he right?</b>
<p>
<li>[<i>20 marks</i>] Another radio announcer, Bob Doe, at another local radio station had taken a somewhat different view of the December 11th events and fully supported the protest in part by taking the day off work and participating in the rally. Mr. Doe was fired as a result. <b>Please advise him.</b>
<p>
<li>[<i>20 marks</i>] Meanwhile, at Fundy Electrical Co. the employees are represented by the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers (IBEW), and as is common in the construction industry their current collective agreement contains a &quot;closed shop&quot; provision which requires employees to retain union membership as a condition of continued employment. At a union meeting on November 30th, a very large majority of employees voted to support the day of protest on December 11th. This vote was taken after a fulsome debate in which Ernest Elves, a member of the union who is very much in favour of the Harris government policies, fully participated. On December 11th, Ernest Elves went to work (he was the only worker to do so) and he has subsequently been notified by letter from the Union that he has been expelled from Union membership and that the Employer, Fundy Electrical Co., has agreed that he will be terminated. <b>Fully advise Mr. Elves.</b>
<p>
<li>[<i>40 marks</i>] Still elsewhere in the City of London, the city employees are represented by the Canadian Union of Public Employees (CUPE). The collective agreement covering the workers is due to expire soon and the Union has been developing bargaining proposals for the upcoming negotiations. The City daycare workers, mostly women, are most anxious to participate fully and vocally in the day of protest because of their concerns about funding cuts for municipal daycare services. Other city workers in the unit are mainly &quot;outside&quot; workers and male. The &quot;outside&quot; workers are somewhat cool to the plight of their fellow daycare workers, partly because they in general have less seniority, but also because of a still outstanding pay equity claim by the daycare workers. On December 11th the daycare workers participate in the protest, but the other workers do not. The daycare workers are disciplined by the city by having written warning letters placed in their personal files. The daycare workers wish to file grievances, but the Union refuses to do so. The Union has also indicated that it has placed preservation of daycare as a low priority in its negotiating position. <b>Fully and critically analyze the situation in which the parties have found themselves.</b>
</ol>
<p><br>
<hr>
