<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Municipal and Planning Law<br>
Final Take Home Examination<br>
December 1995<br>
Stanley Makuch</h2></center>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<blockquote>
Please write on every other line. Be concise. Marks will be deducted for verbosity and irrelevance. Your answer to each question should be no longer than 8 pages.
<p>
This exam is a 48 hour take home exam which may be written during any 48 hour period of the exam session. Students should note on their exam that they spent only 48 hours. Students are to do their own work although they may discuss answers prior to writing them individually. Both questions are to be answered and are of equal value.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p><br>
<ol>
<li>Draft recommendations to improve local government in the Toronto area with an explanation for the recommendations.
<p><br>
<li>&quot;A&quot; has a gravel pit at the edge of an urban development in the &quot;City above Toronto&quot;, Vaughan. She wishes to use the gravel pit site for a ready mix plant. The pit was depleted and extraction had ceased for approximately six months and she thus wishes to construct a ready mix plant and import aggregate from other gravel pits to use in the plant.
<p>
The site also contains a small abandoned five unit apartment building which had	housed employees who worked on the site many years ago. &quot;A&quot; intended to tear down the apartment building and build the readymix plant on the foundations of it.
<p>
The land including the apartment building was zoned &quot;Industrial Extractive&quot; which permitted gravel pits and accessory uses including readymix plants. However, it was designated in the City's new official plan, which had just been completed after five years of study, as future urban. That official plan stated &quot;when lands designated industrial extractive are no longer required for extractive uses, they shall be used for urban residential purposes&quot;.
<P>
&quot;A&quot; was unaware that the lands were in an area of demolition control. She tore down the apartment building and constructed the readymix plant without fist obtaining either a demolition permit or a building permit. Once the plant was up and operating, residents in a neighbouring subdivision complained of the dust emissions from the plant. As a result of their complaints, the Town Building Inspector came and told &quot;A&quot; she needed a building permit and that she should stop operating until she had one. &quot;A&quot; refused to stop her operation.
<p>
&quot;A&quot; however, prepared plans for submission for a building permit. Before she was able to make an application for the permit, the Town passed an Interim Control By-law without notice to &quot;A&quot; and zoned the land as &quot;Rural&quot; which prohibited all uses except agriculture.
<p>
The City also approved the undertaking of a new study which recommended that the lands be zoned for &quot;social housing&quot; in accordance with the provincial Policy Statement on affordable housing which provided that &quot;housing should be provided in all municipalities for a wide range of incomes&quot;. Since Vaughan had no affordable housing for low income groups, the City zoned these lands for &quot;low income families, ie. families with incomes below $50,000 per year&quot;. At the public meeting prior to the passing of the zoning by-law, the neighbouring residents turned out in force and were opposed to both, the zoning by-law and the readymix plant use. Whenever &quot;A&quot; attempted to speak, they shouted her down so she was unable to make any coherent comments to the City Council.
<p>
The City passed the zoning by-law, which also included &quot;A&quot;'s property in an area of site plan control. The standards with respect to site plan control included provisions that all open pits must have 24 hour surveillance because of the danger of someone falling into them and in addition, there was a requirement that the owner of open pits pay $1,000 per cubic metre of pit area towards a fund for the rehabilitation of such pits. The City has told &quot;A&quot; that she must pay the $1,000 per cubic metre fee and that there must be a guard for the pit until the site is redeveloped, and that the zoning bylaw had to be passed because there was no affordable housing in Vaughan.
<p>
&quot;A&quot; comes to your office. All she wants to do is to use her readymix plant without any conditions. What can she do? Advise her.
</ol>
<p><br>
<hr>
