<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Property II and A<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor A. Weinrib</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol><i>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>The exam is composed of one question.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the conclusion of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>ALL EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</i></ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<dd>Bruce Guy is a Toronto lawyer who in his spare time invented and marketed herbal remedies which he hoped would replace regular drugs on the market. Some of the potions he invented were marketed commercially, but in very small quantities. However, after a number of experiments, he hit upon a combination of herbal remedies which, when combined together in pill form, could be used to induce sleep without any of the side effects associated with the drugs used for this purpose already on the market. Bruce entered into a very lucrative manufacturing and distribution contract for the pill with Blue Sky Remedies Company. Soon, the pill replaced most of the drugs used for this purpose previously on the market. The drug manufacturers were not happy. The Association of Drug Manufacturers lobbied the Federal Government to make a scientific study of Bruce's pill. The Association promised that its members would open new research facilities in Canada and hire more Canadian scientists if Bruce's pill was subjected to the same kinds of study as drugs ordinarily are in this country. This would mean that the pill would be off the market for at least five years. The Federal Government gave in to the pressure and ordered the Health Department to undertake the study. Using its powers in these circumstances, the Department forbade the sale of the pill while the study was ongoing. One of the tests undertaken by the Department showed that rats that were fed a steady diet of the pill in conjunction with beer for one month showed extreme disorientation. The Government then decided to ban the pill completely. Blue Sky Remedies brought an action against the Government for an injunction against the ban and damages.
<p>
<dd>Bruce is heartbroken over these events and dies. In his will he leaves whatever rights he has in relation to the pill to The University of Toronto.
<p>
<dd>In his will Bruce also left his house in Toronto to The University of Toronto &quot;on condition that it be used only for the education of law students who signed a declaration that they do not believe in God.&quot;
<p>
<dd>How would a court resolve the issues involved?
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
Please send comments and suggestions to <a href="mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</a><p>
Created on MAR-15-96 by Anne Johnston.
