<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Real Estate Law<br>
December 1995<br>
Bradley N. McLellan</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>The exam is composed of four questions. The suggested time allocation for each question is indicated at the end of each question. Ten minutes time has been allocated to reading the entire exam before starting to answer any of the questions.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
1. James has agreed to purchase Lana's home in Toronto. The purchase price is $200,000.00. The Agreement was signed on September 30, 1995. Closing is scheduled for December l 5, l 995.
<p>
<dd>James paid a deposit of $15,000.00 at the time that the Agreement was signed and the balance of the purchase price is payable on closing. The Agreement of Purchase and Sale contained a condition with regard to financing in the following form:
<blockquote>
&quot;This Agreement is conditional upon James being able to obtain financing for 80% of the purchase price at or below the prevailing interest rates.&quot;
</blockquote>
<dd>The Agreement of Purchase and Sale entered into between James and Lana was in the standard form used by the Toronto Real Estate Board and which was provided to you as a handout during this course. The Agreement was filled in by Colin, the real estate agent with whom Lana had listed the property. On the strength of the Agreement to sell to James, Lana has entered into another Agreement of Purchase and Sale whereby she will purchase another home property, with a closing date of December 15, 1995.
<p>
<dd>Lana has just finished meeting with you. During the course of her meeting with you, she has raised the following concerns:
<blockquote>
(a) Lana is aware that James agreed to purchase this property at a price which is somewhat above the market. For this reason, as well as because of the fact that she has agreed to buy other property, Lana is very anxious to have the sale to James completed. Lana is afraid, however that James would like to walk away from the sale.
<p>
(b) Nothing, as yet, has been said in any correspondence between James and Lana with regard to the condition on financing. Lana now regrets the very loose drafting of this clause in the Agreement of Purchase and Sale. Lana is willing, however, to take back a mortgage from James, if necessary, in the amount of 80% of the purchase price for
a one year term at an interest rate of 7%, which is the prevailing interest rate for one year mortgages, if this will help to make the transaction work
<p>
(c) Lana advises that one wall of the basement has a significant crack in it which has been getting wider recently. The wall is in the recreation room and is entirely covered with a decorative curtain which was installed before the crack appeared. Lana is not certain whether or not James noticed the crack. Lana did not, in any event, comment
upon it when James viewed the property.
<p>
(d) After the time for submitting requisitions pursuant to the Agreement of Purchase and Sale had passed, the City of Toronto registered a work order on December 11, 1995 against Lana's property because of deterioration in the front steps and railing of the house. Lana had received a deficiency notice from the City on October 2, 1995
regarding the steps and railing, but did not understand the importance of the notice and did nothing. Lana does not know whether she has an obligation to disclose the condition of the steps and railing to James and she is uncertain whether James' lawyer can raise the work order now that it has been filed by the City.
<p>
(e) Lana has recently learned that James and Colin are good friends. Colin is the one who introduced James to the property. That is why Colin is also shown on the Agreement of Purchase and Sale as the sales agent. Although Lana is happy with the above market price which James has agreed to pay, she has just learned that another prospective purchaser, Katy, spoke to Colin about this property a day or two prior to the submission by James of his Offer to Purchase and Lana has now learned that Katy would have paid $10,000.00 more for this home because it has unique attributes that are important to Katy. Since James' offer was the only offer presented to Lana, Lana was unaware that Katy had an interest in the property.
</blockquote>
<dd>Please advise Lana on her position with regard to James and Katy and the steps which Lana should take now, prior to closing, and after closing.
<p>
<b>QUESTION 1 IS WORTH 35 MARKS (48 minutes)</b>
<p><br>
2. Question two consists of two parts. The value of each part is shown below. Do not assume any facts not specifically stated. In particular, do not assume that consent has been obtained pursuant to Section 50 of the <cite>Planning Act</cite>, or that a transfer with the three <cite>Planning Act</cite> statements referred to in Subsection 50(22) has ever been registered, unless otherwise stated. Assume that &quot;North&quot; is at the top of the page.
<p>
(a) <b>12 1/2 MARKS (17 minutes)</b>
<p>
<center>
<table border cellpadding=10 width=50%>
<tr><th>X</th><th><center>W 1/2<br>Y</th><th>E 1/2<br>Y</th></tr>
</table></center>
<p>
<dd>Parcel X abuts Parcel Y. On January 1, 1991, Ann is the owner of X and Shirley is the owner of Y. In September of 1991, Ann conveys Parcel X to Shirley. As part of the purchase price, Shirley gives a mortgage back to Ann encumbering Parcel X. On closing, Shirley also grants a second mortgage in favour of the Bank, encumbering Parcel X. On December 1, 1991, a Plan of Subdivision was registered that included Parcel X and Parcel Y within its boundaries. Accordingly, as of December 1, 1991, Parcel X and Parcel Y were whole lots on a Plan of Subdivision. On January 1, 1994, the local municipality passed a By-Law lifting part lot control for the Plan of Subdivision that Parcel X and Parcel Y are part of. On September 1, 1994, Shirley sold the east half of Parcel Y to Malcolm. On October 1, 1994, the local municipality repealed the By-Law it had passed on January 1, 1994 and, therefore, the By-Law lifting part lot control for the registered plan that Parcel X and Parcel Y are part of ceased to have effect as of October 1, 1994. On December 1, 1995, Shirley sold the west half of Parcel Y to Lori. What is the effect of the subdivision control provisions of the <cite>Planning Act</cite> on these transactions?
<p>
(b) <b>12 1/2 MARKS (17 minutes)</b>
<p>
<center><table border cellpadding=10 width=50%>
<tr><th>D</th><th>E</th><th>F</th></tr>
</table></center>
<p>
D, E and F are not lots within a registered Plan of Subdivision. D abuts E. E abuts F. In 1976, Luke was the owner of D and E and Emma was the owner of F. In 1976, Luke obtained an unconditional consent from the local Committee of Adjustment to a mortgage by Luke to the Bank encumbering D. In 1985, Luke sold D to Brian. As part of the sale transaction, Brian gave a mortgage back to Luke encumbering D. In 1989, Luke sold E to Bonnie. In 1992, Emma sold F to Luke. Bonnie entered into an Agreement of Purchase and Sale on December 1, 1995 on the standard Toronto Real Estate Board form to sell E to Robert. What is the effect of the subdivision control provisions of the <cite>Planning Act</cite> on these transactions?
<p>
<b>TOTAL FOR QUESTION 2 IS 25 MARKS (Total estimated time for Question 2 - 34 minutes)</b>
<p><br>
3. You are a senior partner in a law firm known for its expertise in real estate matters. One of your valued clients has just telephoned and told you that she signed an agreement to purchase a new residential condominium unit on December 10, 1995. The condominium project which she has agreed to purchase a unit in is one of the most expensive projects ever in Toronto and the purchase price for her two bedroom unit is $1,200,000.00. Your client advises that the building will be ten storeys high and will have fantastic amenities. The developer has not yet started construction of the project, but units are selling very quickly.
<p>
<dd>Your client wants to meet with you tomorrow morning to go over the Agreement of Purchase and Sale and the Disclosure Statement which she received on the same day that she signed the Agreement of Purchase and Sale. She has never purchased a new residential condominium unit before, and she is having difficulty understanding when she has to pay monies to the condominium developer and what her rights are from the time that she signs the Agreement until the date that she acquires title.
<p>
<dd>Unfortunately (or fortunately depending on your viewpoint), you are leaving Toronto later this afternoon for a much deserved two week vacation in Mexico. Accordingly, you are going to be unable to meet with your client when she comes into the of fine tomorrow morning to deal with these issues.
<p>
<dd>Thankfully, the loyal and hardworking associate lawyer who works with you is available and will meet with your client tomorrow morning. However, the associate lawyer has never done a condominium transaction before and will be unable to provide the proper advice to your client tomorrow morning unless you can help him out by providing him with a memo that he can read over this afternoon and have with him when he meets with your client tomorrow morning.
<p>
<dd>The memorandum to the associate lawyer should set out the points that you wish him to discuss with your client when she attends at your of fine tomorrow morning. Obviously, you have not seen the Agreement of Purchase and Sale and you have not seen the Disclosure Statement. You will have to tell the associate lawyer in the memorandum what it is that he should watch out for in reading the material which the client brings in and, also, what protections, rights and remedies he should discuss with the client when they meet and after he reviews the documentation.
<p>
<dd>As you have other files to prepare memos on prior to your flight this afternoon, there is only a limited time that you have to set out the pertinent matters that the associate lawyer should know about prior to meeting with your client tomorrow morning. Accordingly, you only have time to deal with important points. Since your firm does not believe in formalities, you can design the memorandum to the associate lawyer in any way you wish.
<p>
<dd>Please prepare the memorandum to the associate lawyer.
<p>
<b>QUESTION 3 IS WORTH 20 MARKS (28 minutes)</b>
<p><br>
4. One of your clients, George, has just been served with a Statement of Claim in which Elaine has sued him on the covenant contained in a mortgage registered against Greenacre which George gave to Elaine in 1993. George had sold Greenacre to Kramer in 1994 and Kramer assumed Elaine's mortgage, with Elaine's approval, at that time. Unfortunately, Kramer encountered financial difficulties as a result of his failed investment in a small soup kitchen and Elaine sold Greenacre to Jerry two months ago under the power of sale contained in the mortgage. Due to the fact that the net sale proceeds that Elaine recovered were substantially less than the amount of the mortgage, she has sued both George and Kramer for the shortfall.
<p>
<dd>George is most upset at the turn of events and he is meeting with you this afternoon. George wants you to provide him with a written explanation of what his general rights and defences are under these circumstances and why it is that certain of his rights may be limited or certain defences unavailable to him. George also wants to know what additional information you will need in order to fully advise him of his rights and defences when you get together for your second meeting with him later in the week. George likes to know why things are the way they are and he is always appreciative of novel arguments that you might come up with.
<p>
<dd>Please prepare the written advice to George which he has asked for.
<p>
<b>QUESTION 4 IS WORTH 20 MARKS (28 minutes)</b>
<p><br>
<hr>
