<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Reproductive Health Law<br>
December 1995<br>
Professors R.J. Cook &amp; B.M. Dickens</h2></center>
<blockquote>
<b>You have 48 hours (including Friday 4:30 p.m. to Monday 9:00 a.m.) to present a response to the following question.</b>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p><br>
<h3>QUESTION</h3>
In <cite>Doiron v. Orr</cite> (1978), 86 D.L.R. (3d) 719, Garrett J. of the Ontario High Court observed <i>obiter</i> of a parent's claim for compensation for a failed sterilization that:
<blockquote>
it would be against public policy to award damages for the birth of a child (at p.723).
<p>
A. Has Canadian law on compensation for negligent sterilization resulting in childbirth changed since this view was expressed?
<p>
B. What information given to a sterilization patient before a procedure is undertaken can eliminate or reduce the practitioner's legal liability for subsequent pregnancy?
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<hr>
