<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Secured Transactions and Insolvency Law<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Ziegel</h2></center>
<h3>INSTRUCTIONS:</h3>
<ol>
<li>Answer <b>BOTH</b> questions in PART A and <b>ANY TWO</b> questions in PART B (four
questions altogether). The questions in PART A each carry 30 marks; the questions in PART B are worth 20 marks each, although Questions 3 and 4 are subdivided. You should allocate your time appropriately.<p>
<li>The names of all persons and all incidents described in the problem questions are fictitious. In all questions affecting chattel security law assume that the Ontario Personal Property Security Act, RSO 1990 as am., applies unless otherwise indicated.<p>
<li>Discuss all issues reasonably raised in each problem even though your resolution of a prior issue in the problem may technically make discussion of other issues immaterial. If added facts are necessary state those assumed.<p>
<li>A problem question may involve issues of chattel security law, insolvency law, or both. The nature of the problem and the advice you are asked to give will usually indicate whether you are expected to consider one or both branches of the law.<p>
<li>Please write <b>CLEARLY</b> and use <b>DOUBLE SPACING</b>. (Both these requests are most important and will be firmly enforced!)<p>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>At the conclusion of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE.</b><p>
Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<center><h3>PART A</h3>
(Answer <b>BOTH</b> questions.)</center><p>
(30 Marks) QUESTION 1<p>
<dd>In 1993, the Venerable Bank (VB) agreed to provide a line of credit to Telephony (TY), a manufacturer of telephone equipment, which was to be secured by a Section 427 Bank Act security on TY's inventory. VB filed a notice of intention to give the Section 427 security interest in the regional office of the Bank of Canada on February 1, 1993, and TY signed a Section 427 security agreement in VB's favour before the line of credit became operative. This was the only security agreement concluded between the parties. On February 15, 1993, VB registered a financing statement in the Ontario Personal Property Security registry in which an &quot;X&quot; appeared in the &quot;Inventory&quot; box in the collateral classification section of the financing statement.
<p>
<dd>In May 1993, TY signed a contract with High-Tech Components (HTC) for the supply of TY's requirements of components for use in its manufacturing operations. The contract provided that HTC was to retain a security interest in the components so long as any part of the purchase price for components, whenever delivered, remained outstanding. TY also gave HTC a security interest in a patent licence it held for the manufacture of some of TY's equipment. HTC registered a financing statement on May 15, 1993 in which an &quot;X&quot; appeared in the &quot;Equipment&quot; and &quot;Other&quot; collateral boxes. The financing statement spelled TY's name as &quot;Telephonie&quot;. HTC gave no notice of its security interests to VB.
<p>
<dd>TY needed a diagnostic machine in its manufacturing operations and, on the recommendation of its treasurer, agreed to lease such a machine from the New Leasing Corporation (NLC). The lease was for a 5 year period and the rental was $1,000 a month. The lease gave TY a right of renewal of the lease for a second 5 year period at $100 a month. The lease also obliged TY to keep the machine insured and in a state of good repair, to pay all applicable taxes involving the machine and to assume full responsibility for its safety. If TY had purchased the machine outright the cash price would have been $50,000. NLC never registered a financing statement in respect of the lease.
<p>
<dd>In June 1994, HTC's lawyer discovered the error in the collateral description in HTC's financing statement of May 15, 1993, and filed a financing change statement substituting an &quot;X&quot; in the &quot;Inventory&quot; box for the &quot;X&quot; in the &quot;Equipment&quot; box. (The notation in the &quot;Other&quot; box was left unchanged.) At that time $50,000 was owing to HTC in respect of previous deliveries of components. Between then and December 1994, HTC made further deliveries of components to TY in the amount of $75,000.
<p>
<dd>The market for TY's products deteriorated sharply and, in December 1994, VB successfully presented a petition for TY's bankruptcy. Jane was appointed trustee in bankruptcy. At the time of the receiving order, $100,000 was owing to VB in respect of the 1993 Section 427 security agreement and $45,000 was owing to HTC. $25,000 of this amount represented deliveries made by HTC before June 1994; the balance of the debt represented deliveries made after this date. The total value of the inventory in Jane's hands is $40,000.
<blockquote>
ADVISE JANE:
<p>
(a) whether HTC has a perfected security interest in the components and, if so, for which amount;
<p>
(b) as between VB and HTC, which of their respective security interests in TY's inventory has priority;
<p>
(c) whether HTC obtained a valid security interest in TY's patent licence;
<p>
(d) whether NLC lease with TY constituted a security agreement and is therefore subject to the OPPSA perfection requirements.
</blockquote>
(In answering question (c) ignore any provisions in the federal Patents Act.)
<p><br>
(30 marks) QUESTION 2
<p>
<dd>Farmakare Corp. (FMK) is a distributor and retailer of pharmaceutical and personal and home care products. It has 20 retail outlets in various parts of Ontario, the premises of which are held by FMK on 10 and 20 year leases from various landlords. Because of the renewed recession, fierce competition among drug stores, and the impact of the prohibition on the sale of tobacco products in drug stores, FMK is suffering from cashflow problems as well as incurring a net loss in its current retail operations. FMK's debt picture looks as follows:
<p>
<dd><i>Outstanding Balances</i>
<ol>
<li><i>Shopping Centre Bank (SCB)</i>:<br>
Medium term loan secured by FMK's fixtures and equipment and the personal guarantee of FMK's executive directors. $150,000
<p>
<li><i>Your Friendly Bank (YFB)</i>:<br>
revolving line of credit repayable on demand and secured by FMK's receivables $250.000
<p>
<li><i>Six major drug manufacturers and ten suppliers</i> of home and personal care products, each of whom holds a security interest in 	respect of its supplies $250,000
<p>
<li><i>Ten landlords</i>:<br>
Arrears of rent $100,000
<p>
<li><i>Other unsecured creditors</i> $300,000
</ol>
<dd>FMK is anxious to explore the feasibility of a successful reorganization. It feels it would be able to make a positive recovery if the following conditions con he met:
<blockquote>
(a) that it can repudiate ten of the twenty realty leases;
<p>
(b) that it is permitted to treat all the secured creditors (items 1, 2, and 3 above) as a single class for voting purposes;
<p>
(c) that the rental arrears to the landlords (item 4) can be combined in one class with the claims of other unsecured creditors:
<p>
(d) unpaid suppliers of goods, including those in items 5 above, will not be able to demand return of their goods in the event of FMK filing an application under the CCAA or the BIA.
</blockquote>
<dd>ADVISE FMK's directors whether these conditions can be met and whether they can best be met by proceeding under the CCAA or by proceeding under the Part III.1 provisions of the BIA.
<p><br>
<center><h3>PART B</h3>
(Answer any <b>TWO</b> questions.)</center><p>

QUESTION 3
<p>
(10 marks) (a)&quot;How ironic! In the late 19th century, the equity courts invented the floating charge, thereby replacing the earlier doctrine of the implied licence for a debtor to sell inventory in the ordinary course of the debtor's business even though it is subject to a security interest. And now that the PPS Acts have abolished the equitable floating charge, the courts are rediscovering the implied licence doctrine but giving it a much broader reach that it ever had at common law&quot;. EXPLAIN the development referred to by the author.
<p>
(10 marks) (b) W Co. is a trucking company whose head office is located in Winnipeg. All of W's trucks were purchased on a conditional sale basis from the M Co. The financing statements were registered in Winnipeg pursuant to the Manitoba PPSA. On March 15, 1995, W Co. traded-in one of the trucks in Toronto to Value Co. (&quot;VC&quot;) in part payment of the purchase price of a new Value truck. VC retained a security interest in the new truck for the balance of the purchase price. VC did not know of the outstanding security interest against the traded-in truck and resold the truck to T Co. in the ordinary course of VC's business.
<p>
<dd>ADVISE M Co.:
<blockquote>
(a) whether T Co. obtained a clear title to the truck; and
<p>
(b) whether M Co. can claim a security interest in the Value truck and, if the answer is yes, whether its security interest will have priority over VC's security interest in the truck.
</blockquote>
<p><br>
QUESTION 4
<p>
(10 marks) (a) &quot;It is difficult to find a common denominator linking the impeachable pre-bankruptcy transactions covered in sections 91101 of the BIA. It is even more difficult to justify the existence of a parallel set of provincial provisions.&quot; DO YOU AGREE?
<p>
(10 marks) (b) The Lakeshore Bank (LB) made a loan of $50,000 to the No-Calorie Restaurant (NCR) on February 15, 1992 to enable NCL to renovate and refurbish the restaurant. The loan was secured by a security interest in all of the assets of NCR, with the exception of NCR's receivables. The loan was repayable in monthly instalments of $1,500. The agreement contained an acceleration clause entitling LB to demand repayment of the balance of the loan if any instalment was in arrears for more than 15 days. NCT fell into arrears with its payments and on November 1, 1992, LB advised NCR that it would enforce its security interest on or after November 4 unless the balance of the loan was paid before then.
<p>
ADVISE NCR:
<blockquote>
(a) whether LB's notice is a valid one; and
<p>
(b) whether NCR will be liable for any deficiency if LB seizes and sells the collateral and the sale price is not sufficient to cover the balance of the loan.
</blockquote>
<p><br>
(20 marks) QUESTION 5
<p>
<dd>&quot;Read by itself, section 20 of the OPPSA leaves the impression that consensually secured creditors trump all other interests so long as the security interest is perfected. The impression is quite misleading. The correct position 	is much more complex, and this for two reasons. The first is because of the existence of non-PPSA legislation creating non-consensual superpriority security interests. The second and still more important reason is because of the diluting effects of the 1992 amendments to the BIA. If there is room for complaint it is that the 1992 BIA amendments do not go far enough.&quot; DISCUSS.
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
Please send comments and suggestions to <a href="mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</a><p>
Created on MAR-17-96 by Anne Johnston.
</address>
