http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca:80/exams/exmdec95/tax.htm 128.100.167.100 19970109124319 text/html 11490
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Thursday, 09-Jan-97 12:43:02 GMT
Server: WebSite/1.1
Allow-ranges: bytes
Accept-ranges: bytes
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Wednesday, 06-Nov-96 02:18:52 GMT
Content-length: 11269
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Taxation<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Sherbaniuk</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You many use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, count the total number of booklets and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>ALL EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE  TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.<p>
<li><b>Make any assumptions of fact you deem necessary in order to answer the questions properly. State your assumptions clearly.</b>
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
[100 marks]
<p>
Jean Dufour, of Lyon, France, gave up his career as a biochemist to earn a medical degree and practice as a family doctor. Discouraged by the high rates of tax and bureaucratic red tape in France, he and his wife, Marie, decided early in 1992 to relocate in Ontario, together with their son, Claude, aged 22, and Jean's aged father, Henri. The family thought it in their best interest to retain their home in Lyon in case the Canadian experience did not work out. Jean's widowed sister, Francine, agreed to move in and look after the house. Jean had purchased it in 1965 for the equivalent of $100,000 ($40,000 for the house and $60,000 for the land). The value at the end of 1971 was $135,000 ($55,000 for the house and $80,000 for the land).
<p>
Henri had some regrets about leaving France, having purchased a vineyard in 1990 for the equivalent of $100,000.
The family arrived in Ontario in July, 1992, when the value of the house in Lyon was $200,000 ($80,000 for the building and $120,000 for the land), and the vineyard, $115,000.
<p>
Notwithstanding Jean's professional qualifications, the Ontario government agreed to grant him a license to practice medicine only if he was willing to locate in a community that was without adequate medical services, an &quot;underserviced designated area&quot;. He accepted the conditions and took the family to Espanola. To help him defray his settlement expenses, the government of Ontario paid him $50,000. He used virtually all of the money to purchase the practice - essentially the &quot;goodwill&quot; - of the only other medical doctor in Espanola, Dr. Kavorkian, who had had a remarkable number of fatalities among his patients and decided to retire.
<p>
He also purchased Dr. Kavorkian's residence for $150,000 and converted it into a medical office on the ground floor and living quarters on the second floor. (The allocation of the purchase price was $60,000 for the building and $90,000 for the three acres of land.)
<p>
Jean's practice prospered in the growing community, which was found to be increasingly attractive to tourists. With a view to profiting from the growth, he and three friends, Tom and Dick, who were real estate developers, and Harry, the local dentist, incorporated a company, Cashco Inc., which purchased a 20 acre parcel of land which they intended to develop into a small shopping plaza and motel to cater-to the tourist trade. Jean's view was that he could achieve long-term financial security in this way. Each paid $60,000 for his 25k of the issued shares. As they were ready to proceed with development, they learned to their great dismay that the site was heavily contaminated with waste from a nearby nuclear generator and totally unfit for development. The exorbitant cost of removing the contaminated soil caused the company to sell the land to the government for $1, so as to be free of any responsibility for the property. Cashco Inc. surrendered its charter.
<p>
Distressed by his financial setback, Jean's mind was not on his practice and in treating Richard Roe for a serious ailment, he prescribed the wrong medicine and thereby caused Mr. Roe severe injury. Mr. Roe recovered $300,000 in damages from Jean for pain and suffering, nursing care and lost wages while he was off work. Regrettably, Jean had failed to take out malpractice insurance and bore the cost personally. Also, the disciplinary committee of the Ontario Medical Association investigated the matter with a view to determining whether or not to withdraw Jean's license to practice. Jean engaged counsel to appear on his behalf at the hearings and paid legal fees of $75,000.
<p>
Although he retained his license, Jean and his family decided in April, 1994, to leave Espanola for Toronto. He sold his practice and received $80,000 for the goodwill. The contract of sale provided for a down payment of $20,000 and annual payments of $10,000 for the next six years. He rented his home/office to his successor for $3,000 per month.
<p>
As an experienced biochemist, he had little difficulty finding employment with Biochem Inc. in Toronto. As part of his compensation package, Jean received a generous salary and a stock option to purchase 10,000 shares in Biopharm Ltd., Biochem's parent company, for $10 per share for a period of ten years. The stock was trading for $12 per share on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
<p>
The company offered him three options with respect to his travel on company business: (1) Biochem would provide him with a $60,000 Lexus automobile and pay all operating expenses, which were estimated to run to $8,000 per annum. Although Jean expected to travel by air extensively in visiting the various offices of the company, he anticipated that he would drive the car annually about 40,000 km on business and 3,000 km for personal purposes. (2) He could use his own car and be paid 35 cents per km when he used it for company business. (3) He could receive $10,000 per year as a lump sum payment for using his own car on company business. He chose the third option, but wondered about the tax consequences of all three.
<p>
The company also agreed to send a member of the nursing staff to pay visits three times per week to Jean's father who, although in frail health, chose to live alone but did require care and attention.
<p>
Jean also persuaded the company to hire his son Claude as a trainee in the treasury department.
<p>
Jean gave his stock option to Marie, who exercised it by purchasing 10,000 shares in August, 1994, when Biopharm shares were trading at $15. She received dividends quarterly in the amount of 20 cents per share. In an increasingly high tech oriented world, the shares of Biopharm escalated rapidly and Marie was able to dispose of them for $30 in July, 1996.
<p>
With a view to fostering good staff relations, the company agreed to lend to Jean and other senior officers $100,000 each, interest-free, in order to help them make provision for their retirement. Jean agreed to repay the loan from his salary in such amounts as met with his convenience. He used the funds to purchase a variety of investments, including shares in Acme Hardware Inc., an Ontario private company, shares in Imperial Oil Limited, and Ontario government bonds, having a face value of $100 each and bearing interest of 9k, for which he paid $97.
<p>
Marie's financial position was given a fillip by her purchase of a lottery ticket from one of the local charities. She was delighted to win the prize and although she requested that it be paid in a lump sum of $135,000, it was a &quot;cash for life lottery&quot; so that the funds were paid to an insurance company, which contracted to pay her $1,000 per month for life.
<p>
Each summer the family returned to Lyon to spend a month with Jean's sister in the family home, using his frequent flyer points to pay for the airline tickets, which had a market value of $3,000.
<p>
Jean's father, Henri, was informed that the French government had expropriated his vineyard for the construction of a highway and that his compensation was the equivalent of $300,000. Although frail, Henri was sufficiently mentally alert to reinvest the total proceeds in a mushroom farm near Lyon.
<p>
Jean's son Claude, a member of the &quot;instant gratification&quot; set, sought more financial means than he earned as a treasury officer and embezzled $80,000 from the company in September, 1994. The fraud was quickly discovered and Claude was charged with embezzlement. Because he had returned the funds to the company in May, 1995, prior to his trial (at which he pleaded guilty), he received a relatively short jail sentence.
<p>
The event soured relations between Jean and Biochem, which suggested he seek employment elsewhere. It forgave the outstanding loan of $100,000.
<p>
Jean formed his own biochemical company, Biodyne, Inc., paying $50,000 for all the issued shares. He exercised his talents as a biochemist to create a new product, Tylaprin, a pain reliever, which the company patented. It granted exclusive three-year licenses to manufacturers in Chicago (to cover North American distribution), Buenos Aires (Central and South America), London (Europe) and Tokyo (Asia), for lump sum payments totalling $1.5 million and a 10k royalty.
<p>
Henri returned to France to live in April 1997 in order to look after his mushroom farm.
<p>
When Claude was released from jail, in October 1997, the family decided to make a clean break with Canada and return to their home in Lyon, which had increased in value to $300,000 ($120,000 for the house and $180,000 for the land). Prior to departing, Jean sold the shares in his company, Biodyne, to Chemco Limited for 10k of Biodyne's profits for the next four years up to a total of $2 million.
<p>
He disposed of the house in Espanola for $400,000 ($150,000 for the house and $250,000 for the three acres), but retained the shares in Acme Hardware and Imperial Oil and the bonds.
<p>
Discuss the tax consequences of these events for Jean, Marie, Claude, Henri, Richard Roe, Cashco, Biochem and Biodyne.
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
