<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Torts II<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Chapman</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol><i>
<li>This is an open book examination. That means you may use your class notes, other study notes or outlines, and your casebook materials.<p>
<li>This exam is composed of <b>one question</b>. Please <b>double space</b> your written answer and write on <b>one side</b> of the page one.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you reserve it. No time will be Permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the test, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the test.<p>
<li>At the end of this test, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the f rst booklet. You wig then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be ~ on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the test has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</i></ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<dd>On a hot summer evening in July 1994, Larry Green decided to go out for a stroll. While walking down the main street of Floodsville, he noticed that a fire had started in the top floor of a recently constructed four storey apartment building, and that a small crowd had assembled outside, unsure what to do. Larry rushed to the scene and
asked the building superintendent, who was in the crowd, whether anyone was still inside. The superintendent answered that he had been told by two 11 year-old boys that there was a baby still trapped on the top floor, but that the fire department was on its way.
<p>
<dd>Larry said that he would try to get the baby out. Before rushing into the building, he yelled to the superintendent to turn off the electrical current to the building. This the superintendent tried to do by hitting what he thought was the main switch, a switch that would have shut off all electricity in the building. In fact, he hit an auxiliary switch which normally would cut off the current to the first floor of the building only. (Apparently, it has recently become common practice for Floodsville building contractors to have separate auxiliary switches for the first floor of new buildings; this is because spring flooding is not uncommon in the area and while electricity needs to be cut off on the first floor for safety reasons during these floods, a separate switch permits continued use of the upper floors of the building.)
<p>
<dd>Larry never did make it out of the building alive. Indeed, the medical evidence is that, being asthmatic, he was almost immediately overcome by smoke inhalation and passed out on the first floor. However, the coroner has determined that Larry actually died of electrocution. It seems that the electrical company, Sparks Ltd., which services the building, had on some earlier occasion negligently transposed two wires in the auxiliary switch in such a way that the electrical current could not be shut off at that switch. Thus, when water from the building's sprinkler system began to flood the building, it conducted electricity from the live wires on the first floor to the spot where Larry had passed out. The fire chief has indicated, however, that Larry's attempt to save the baby on the fourth floor was so &quot;idiotic&quot; that, in all probability, he would have died from smoke inhalation in any event by the time he reached the fourth floor. His advice is always that one should never enter a burning building in such circumstances.
<p>
<dd>Imagine that you are an articling student for the law firm retained by Larry's estate to seek damages for wrongful death in this case. Write a memorandum advising the senior partner who is handling the case for the firm as to the estate's prospects for recovering damages. Assume that at the time you write the memorandum, there is no damage on how the fire was originally started. Also note that it has turned out that there never was a baby inside the burning building; the two boys only told the superintendent this as a practical joke. If you think you need any additional facts to address a legal issue, specify what facts you need and why.
<p><br>
<hr>
