<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Torts A<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor Mayo Moran</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This is an open-book exam. You may make use of any books, notes, or papers.<p>
<li>PLEASE WRITE ON ALTERNATE LINES!<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the exam, write the required additional information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the exam.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<p><br>
<dd>The Headstart Factory has been manufacturing paint in the same location for over thirty years. The factory employs women who have just been released from prison and attempts to assist them in their efforts to re-integrate into the community. The factory disposes of its waste by burying it in pits near a stream that runs alongside their property. This is in conformity with all applicable laws, but left-over solvents nonetheless end up filtering into the stream. While Headstart is not a non-profit enterprise, it does operate on a very limited budget. According to Headstart. it could not continue to operate if it had to dispose of its wastes in any other way.
<p>
<dd>In recent years, the area around Headstart and the other factories has begun to change. A developer purchased the vacant surrounding land and then developed the residential community of Silver Stream within a few miles of Headstart. Although the community's drinking water is filtered and purified, its source is the stream which runs by Headstart. Residents of Silver Stream complain that their water smells and tastes extremely unpleasant, although there are no adverse health effects. They traced this back to the paint-related waste dumped by Headstart. Further, some of the residents of Silver Stream are very concerned about the criminal propensities of the women who work there. They fear that the women might damage their homes or families. In order to deal with these problems, the residents are thinking of starting an action in nuisance.
<p>
<dd>One of the residents of this community, Maeve, also has a related problem. Shortly after Maeve moved to Silver Stream, she became pregnant. Like many of the residents she and her partner often took an evening stroll on a path that ran beside the stream. One evening, as they were strolling, a group of adolescent boys on mountain bikes tore along the path. Maeve jumped off the path and fell into the stream. Maeve showed no signs of injury but when she gave birth, her child, Cora, was severely underweight. It turned out that Cora's condition was caused by pre-natal exposure to a particular type of solvent. Maeve's investigations revealed that the untreated creek water contained very elevated levels of this solvent and that the source of the solvent was the Headstart factory.
<p>
<dd>In order to remedy her condition, Cora required a blood transfusion. Because of widespread concern about the safety of the blood supply, Maeve's sister, Sheila, gave blood so that the baby could have the necessary transfusion. As a result of this transfusion, Sheila was too weak to work for several weeks.
<p>
<dd>Although Cora survived, she remained very small and frail for several years and consequently suffered several serious illnesses. Now, both Cora and Sheila are contemplating a negligence action against Headstart.
<p>
<dd>Discuss the liability of Headstart on these facts.
<p><br>
<hr>
<address>
