<html>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Trusts<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor R.E. Scane</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<blockquote>
Answer all questions. <b>Reasons for conclusions are essential.</b> The value of each question is shown in the margin.
<p>
There is no restriction upon the materials which candidates may use during this examination except the general Faculty rule against using materials belonging to the Law Library.
<p>
At the conclusion of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE. ALSO. IF YOU USE MORE THAN ONE BOOKLET, PLEASE INSERT ALL BOOKLETS INTO BOOKLET NO. 1.</b>
<p>
Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p><br>
[20 marks] <b>Q1.</b> Alan, after many years service in the management of a company, lost his job as a result of a corporate &quot;downsizing&quot;. Still in his mid-fifties, he could not afford to retire, and was unable to find any similar employment. He decided to go into business for himself, using his savings and severance settlement from his former employer for his start-up capital. His major other asset was his house, of which he was the sole owner. Alan had a second wife, Wilma, and three children by his deceased first wife, Barton, Celia and Doreen. Alan had consultations with a self-designated &quot;business consultant&quot;, who suggested that Alan try to safeguard his non-business assets from the risks of failure of the new business. On the consultant's suggestion, Alan proposed to transfer the house to Wilma and his son Barton as tenants in common, in equal shares. He told Wilma and all of the children that he was doing this &quot;to protect the family&quot;. The conveyance to Wilma and Barton was duly made. The lawyer who prepared and registered the conveyance was not told anything about its purpose.
<p>
<dd>The business in fact prospered from the start. When Alan died suddenly and unexpectedly a dozen years later, it was not only solvent, but had substantial cash reserves. At Alan's death, the title to the house still remained in the names of Wilma and Barton.
<p>
<dd>Alan's valid last will left his estate to Wilma for life, remainder to Barton, Celia and Doreen in equal shares.
Reliable Trust Company, the Estate Trustee [executor] of Alan's will, asked Wilma and Barton to reconvey their interests in the house to the Estate Trustee, in order that it might be administered and ultimately distributed according to Alan's will. Wilma and Barton have refused to do so.
<p>
<dd><b>Assess the legal position of Reliable Trust Company in an action against Wilma and Barton to recover the house for the benefit of Alan's estate.</b>
<p><br>
[30 marks] <b>Q2.</b> Thomas made a valid, &quot;home-made&quot; will which read as follows:
<p>
<dd>&quot;I leave $150,000 to my wife, Alma, to make use of as she pleases. When Alma dies, any of this -money which she hasn't spent is to go to my half-brother Victor, who will be aware of my expectations concerning its employment. All of the rest of my property is to go to my half-sister Barbara. Victor is to be the executor of my estate.&quot;
<p>
<dd>The will was dated and made on April 1, 1994. A few days later, Thomas handed to Victor a sealed envelope, saying, &quot;There is a note about my will in here, following up on what we talked about in January this year. Put it in your safety deposit box and don't open it until after my death.&quot;
<p>
<dd>In January, 1994, Thomas and Victor had had a conversation in which Thomas told Victor that he proposed to make a gift in his will to Victor &quot;of what was left of $150,000 after Alma was looked after.&quot; He reminded Victor that Alma was seriously ill and probably wouldn't live long enough to use up much of this sum. He told Victor that he wanted Victor to make use of this money to assist &quot;some of my [Thomas'] mother's family.&quot; Thomas was the child of his father's first marriage, while Victor and Barbara were the children of his father's second marriage. Thomas told Victor that he did not want to put the details respecting this provision in his will, which would become a public document, and that he could not even bring himself to discuss them with Victor. He would write Victor a letter giving necessary details. Victor agreed to carry out whatever were Thomas' wishes respecting any money he would receive under Thomas' will, as long as this was not unlawful.
<p>
<dd>Thomas died in September, 1995. Alma survived him, but died shortly thereafter, before any part of the $150,000 referred to in Thomas' will could be paid over to her Alma's will provided that, if Thomas predeceased her, as happened, her estate would be given to the University of Trawna.
<p>
<dd>After the death of Thomas, Victor opened the envelope that Thomas had given to him. It contained a typed letter, signed by Thomas, which read:
<blockquote>
&quot;Dear Victor,
<p>
<dd>The family members I asked you to assist are my three cousins, the children of a sister of my late mother. [The letter then gave names and addresses.] Each has a serious mental impairment. Other members of my mother's family have had similar impairments, so it seems that there may be some genetic problem. That is why Alma and I have never had children.
<p>
<dd>My cousins cannot function well enough to make any significant contribution to their own support, although there is some variance among them in their abilities. They depend upon income from their late parents' estates, but this is just barely enough to meet their basic needs. At my mother's last request, I have supplemented their support, and supplied a more generous lifestyle for them, when I was able to do so. I would like you to continue this for me, using the money you get from me as you think it is needed. I hope you will be generous, as they enjoy trips away from home, with suitable companions, of course, and other little luxuries. There will likely be considerable left over anyway, as they have short life expectancies, but even if there isn't, you have a good job and plenty of money of your own anyway. Thanks for your help, and best wishes to you.&quot;
</blockquote>
<dd>Victor located the cousins, and investigated their circumstances. Before he could take further action regarding any of them, the cousins, who were taking a bus trip together, were killed when the bus was in an accident.
<p>
Victor consults you. He considers that his responsibilities concerning the cousins have now ceased, and he is entitled to keep the $150,000 given by Thomas' will, and still not distributed from Thomas' estate, for himself. To his surprise and chagrin, his sister Barbara and the University of Trawna are each claiming that they are entitled to it. In addition, another cousin of Thomas, on his mother's side, one Xaviera, who is the sole next of kin of the cousins referred to in Thomas' letter, and who, by reason of their deaths intestate, is therefore ultimately entitled to receive the proceeds of the entire estate of each of them, claims that the $150,000 should be paid in equal shares to the estates of the three cousins. from which the money will make its way to her.
<p>
<dd><b>Who is entitled to receive the sum of $150,000 from the estate of Thomas?</b>
<p><br>
[25 marks] <b>Q3.</b> Goodfellow, who died recently, had lacked testamentary capacity for over a quarter-century, as a result of a head injury. While still capacitated, he had been a very successful business man, and an active and enthusiastic member of the Rhinoceros Club. This was an unincorporated association of men who banded together to promote both conviviality among themselves and service to the community. The Club held monthly dinner meetings, to hear invited speakers, and to enable the members to enjoy each other's company. However, in their more serious moments, the Club members devoted much time and money to furthering public-spirited projects, ranging from organizing and funding eye examinations of local school-children to supporting projects of international scope, usually health-related.
<p>
<dd>Goodfellow, at the time he suffered the accident, was a very wealthy man. He was a childless bachelor, and had spent his vacations travelling widely throughout the world, including areas seldom visited by travellers from the so-called &quot;Western world&quot;. He observed many persons, both locally and abroad, suffering and dying from a disease, bigpox, for want of vaccination. His own sister had died of this disease while still a child. While still capacitated, he persuaded the Rhinoceros Club to take up, as one of its major causes, the support of an increased attack against this disease.
<p>
<dd>At his death, Goodfellow's will, executed many years previously while he was still of sound mind, gave his entire fortune in the following terms.
<blockquote>
&quot;I give all the property I may own at my death, after payment of my debts and funeral expenses, to the Rhinoceros Club, of Ourtown, Ontario, the capital and income to be employed by the Club to reduce the incidence and effects of bigpox throughout the world. I wish the Club to do this by publicizing the effectiveness of vaccine, by persuading public and private agencies in various lands to develop means of widespread vaccination, by subsidizing the purchase of vaccine or supplying free of vaccine, and by training local persons to administer vaccines where there is a shortage of trained medical persons&quot;.
</blockquote>
<dd>Over the years of Goodfellow's incapacity, the value of his already large estate increased greatly, due to wise and fortunate investment decisions by those administering it. The Club is prepared to accept the responsibility of applying this fortune in the spirit of Goodfellow's desires, but two major problems face it.
<p>
<dd>First, over the years since Goodfellow made his will, world-wide efforts appear to have effectively wiped out the disease, bigpox, through improved vaccine and widespread usage of it. The Club has made enquiries of international health agencies, and has been advised that there is so little likelihood of finding any area where there is now any incidence of the disease that the Goodfellow inheritance cannot usefully be employed as stipulated.
Second, one Snively, who can prove that he is the nearest next-of-kin of Goodfellow now living, and that he is entitled to any portion of Goodfellow's estate not validly disposed of by Goodfellow's will, has demanded that all the capital of Goodfellow's estate he paid to him.
<p>
<dd>The executive of the Club does not want to give up this money to Snively. The Club, by unanimous vote of its members, wants to use the funds to combat some other worldwide dread disease. such as AIDS. The Club consults you.
<p>
<dd><b>Discuss the relative positions of the Club and of Snively.</b>
<p><br>
[25 marks] <b>Q4.</b>You are Smythe, a junior associate at a law firm in Ontario. You receive the following memo from a partner:
<p>
&quot;Smythe&quot;:
<p>
<dd>We act for the estate of Wimp. Wimp was a biochemist. He discovered a new drug, tentatively called &quot;Wimpazole&quot;, which, when added to animal food, makes animals grow fatter and better. Wimp's drug appears to be significantly more efficient than any competitor on the market, and was believed to be harmless to humans. Wimp's previous lawyer suggested that he not patent the drug, but keep it as a secret process, at least until he could work out the most advantageous financial deal for himself. Wimp followed this advice.
<p>
<dd>Wimp, on his own, could not raise the financing necessary to bring Wimpazole to market. He was introduced to executives of Rex Kong Gorilla Foods Inc. (hereafter referred to as &quot;Rex Kong&quot;), a major animal food manufacturer. After negotiations, Rex Kong agreed with Wimp that Rex Kong would manufacture and market Wimpazole, in consideration of an agreed royalty to Wimp. However, this was subject to the product, as tested in Rex Kong's and government laboratories, meeting the claims Wimp made for it, and also receiving government approval with respect to its safety for animals and humans. If it failed either of these requirements, the contract was to be at an end. Rex Kong would not further use or deal with the formula which Wimp had delivered to it for testing, but would return to Wimp all copies of that formula in its possession. After the contract was signed, Wimp handed over his formula to Rex Kong.
<p>
<dd>Rex Kong immediately began extensive laboratory tests, and controlled tests on animals. At a fairly early stage of these tests, there were preliminary indications that, in some rare circumstances, Wimpazole could have an adverse effect on animals, and possibly on humans who might subsequently eat meat derived from animals treated with the drug. Without referring the matter to Wimp, who had been rendered incapable by a stroke, Rex Kong's scientists went to work on the problem, and solved it by making a minor change to Wimp's formula. While continuing the testing of the original Wimpazole, Rex Kong instituted a parallel series of tests of the amended formula, which it called Kongitol. When the tests were completed, the government authorities refused to licence Wimpazole for distribution, but did licence Kongitol. Rex Kong then declared its contract with Wimp to be at an end, and, as Wimp had now died, returned to Wimp's Estate Trustee all copies in its possession of the original formula for Wimpazole. It is now marketing Kongitol, and making a lot of money on it.
<p>
<dd>Wimp's Estate Trustee [executor] has instructed us to sue Rex Kong. Several associates are working on possible claims in contract and in tort. I wonder if there is a possible cause of action in equity, particularly if this might lead to Wimp's estate attaining some ownership interest in Kongitol.
<p>
<dd><b>Write me a memo on the possibility of such an equitable claim in the above circumstances.</b>
<p><br>
