<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law December 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Wills &amp; Estate Planning<br>
December 1995<br>
Professor R.E. Scane</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<blockquote>
There is no restriction on the materials candidates may use in writing this examination, other than the general Faculty rule against use of materials belonging to the Law Library.
<p>
All questions must be answered. The marks assigned for each question, or part of a question, are set out in the margin. <b>Reasons for Conclusions are Essential.</b>
<p>
Answer all questions in Part A (Questions 1 and 2) in one answer book or set of answer books. Answer the question in Part B (Question 3) in a <b>separate</b> answer book or set of answer books.
<p>
At the conclusion of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE. PLACE	THE BOOK OR BOOKS IN WHICH YOUR ANSWERS TO PART &quot;A&quot; ARE CONTAINED IN A SEPARATE PILE FROM THE BOOK OR BOOKS IN WHICH YOUR ANSWER TO PART &quot;B&quot; IS CONTAINED.</b>
<p>
Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p><br>
<center><h3>PART A</h3></center>
1. [<i>Note: At the end of this question are a series of questions based on this fact situation. The total
value of all questions based on this fact situation is 50 marks.</i>]
<p>
In 1988, Ted made a valid, witnessed will, which contained the following provisions, among others:
<blockquote>
&quot;I give and devise my farm real property in Harris Township to my son Caspar, or his estate.
<p>
I give all the rest and residue of my estate real and personal, to which I may be entitled at my death to my daughter, Donna, or her estate.&quot;
</blockquote>
Ted died recently. This 1988 will was found among his papers, but, on the last page, following the signatures of Ted and of the witnesses, was a handwritten note, in Ted's handwriting, as follows:
<blockquote>
&quot;July 15, 1993. I want my niece, Ellen East, to have the one hectare parcel, containing the small cottage, which used to be used for our hired man, at the north-east corner of the farm&quot;. [Signed] Ted Testator&quot;
</blockquote>
As found after Ted's death, the sheet of paper containing the 1988 will had been cut completely across, immediately below the signatures of Ted and the original witness, and immediately above the handwritten note of July 15, 1993. That handwritten note had been attached to the cut original 1988 page with transparent tape on both sides of the page. The cut edges of the top and bottom pieces of the page matched exactly.
<p>
Reliable Trust Company, the Estate Trustee [executor] named in the 1988 will, tells you that it has ascertained the following facts:
<blockquote>
(i) According to the witnesses to the 1988 will, there was no writing of any kind following the signatures of Ted and the witnesses on that will at the time it was executed. There was a blank space a few inches deep after those signatures.
<p>
(ii) T had been a widower for a number of years. Ellen, a daughter of Ted's sister, had come to live at Ted's home, after the death of her parents in 1990. She was then in her mid-teens. In 1993, Ted told her, and several other people, that he wanted her to have a home of her own, as her parents had left her very little on their deaths. He proposed to give her the &quot;hired man's cottage&quot;, which stood on an enclosed one hectare parcel of the lands he was farming.
<p>
(iii) Ted was a person of very strict views about personal morality, and he tried to impose them on Ellen. Ellen had been rebelling against Ted's attitude, and matters come to a head when Ted, who had heard gossip in town that Ellen had been having an affair with a young man whose local reputation was rather poor, and was pregnant by him, confronted her with this story. In fact, this gossip was completely untrue. Ellen had dated this man a few times on a casual basis, had not had an affair with him, and was not pregnant. However, when Ted accused her of these alleged facts, she flared up, told him that her conduct was none of his business and, without bothering to deny the accusation, immediately moved out of the farmhouse to an apartment in town.
<p>
(iv) A few days after Ellen left Ted's home, Ted was discussing the incident with a friend. He was still very angry. He said to his friend, &quot;Ellen will never get any of my property. I shouldn't have let her have any of the property which should go to my children.&quot; Then he said, &quot;That reminds me,&quot; went to a drawer, took out an envelope on which was written, &quot;Last Will&quot;, removed a document from the envelope, and, with scissors, cut a piece off the last sheet. He put the remaining part of the document back into the envelope, and, put the envelope back into the drawer, tossing the cut-off piece in with it. The friend saw that the cut-off piece had handwriting on it, although he could not read it from where he sat.
<p>
(v) A short time before his death, Ted learned that the story about Cynthia's alleged affair and pregnancy was untrue. Ted wrote to Cynthia apologising for his conduct. In his letter he said, &quot;In my anger, I took the cottage from you, but don't worry, I have changed my mind about that, and given it back to you after I die.&quot;
<p>
(vi) At the time Ted made his will, he was farming 300 hectares in Harris Township. Of this tract, 200 hectares [&quot;Parcel A&quot;] had been the farm of his late father. Under his father's will, the farm had been left to his executors and trustees upon trust to sell the farm, invest the proceeds, and pay the income of those proceeds to Ted's mother for her life, and then to pay the capital to Ted and his sister (Ellen's mother) in equal shares. Ted had purchased his sister's interest in the remainder, and then made an agreement with his mother. By this agreement, Ted and his mother requested his father's trustees not to sell the farm during the lifetimes of Ted and his mother and the
survivor of them. Ted then operated the farm and paid his mother an agreed share of the farm income in lieu of her life income from the proceeds. At Ted's death, the title to this property was still in the hands of the executors of his father's estate.
<p>
The remaining 100 hectares, [&quot;Parcel B&quot;] which adjoined Parcel A, on the east thereof, had been purchased by Ted shortly after his father's death. He farmed this Parcel, along with Parcel A, as one operation, and his agreement with this mother calculated her share of income on the basis of the income from both parcels.
(vii) The &quot;hired man's cottage&quot; property [&quot;Parcel C&quot;] was part of Parcel B.
<p>
(viii) In 1993, Ted bought a ten hectare parcel of land [&quot;Parcel D&quot;], also in Harris Township. This was under cultivation as a fruit orchard. This orchard, which Ted always referred to as &quot;the fruit farm&quot;, was situated a few kilometres away from Parcels A and B. Ted had often told friends and members of his family that the fruit farm was being left to Donna, &quot;because Caspar was getting the farm&quot;, and he wanted Donna to have some land of her own.
<p>
(ix) Caspar, who is Ted's only surviving issue, and Ellen survived Ted. Ted's mother had died about a year before Ted's death. Donna had died shortly before Ted's death. She was separated, but not divorced, from her husband Frank, who survived Ted. Donna had no children or other issue. She left a valid will which after leaving a legacy to her brother Caspar, left all the rest of her property to her church.
</blockquote>
<b>Answer the following questions on the assumption that all of the facts stated above, if admissible, would be accepted as proved by a court.</b>
<p>
(a) [16 marks] <b>Who is entitled to receive Parcel C, the &quot;hired man's cottage&quot;? (If you should conclude that it should go to whoever is entitled to the residue of Ted's estate, just say this - don't try to work that out <i>in this part of the question</i>.</b>
<p>
(b) [12 marks] All parties interested in Ted's estate agree that Caspar is entitled to at least that portion of Parcel B remaining after Parcel C is cut from it. However, there is a dispute about Parcel A, the farm of Ted's father.
<p>
<b>Should Parcel A (or the proceeds of its sale, if the father's executors now sell it) he transferred to Caspar, as part of the gift of "my farm real property in Harris Township", in Ted's will, or should it go to whoever is entitled to the residue of Ted's estate". (Do not try to work out entitlement to the residue <i>in this part of the question</i>.)</b>
<p>
(c) [10 marks] <b>There is also a dispute about Parcel D (the orchard). Should Parcel D go to Caspar, or to whoever is entitled to receive the residue of Ted's estate? (Do not try to work out entitlement to the residue <i>in this part of the question.</i>)</b>
<p>
(d) [12 marks] <b>Who is entitled to receive the residue of Ted's estate?</b>
<p><br>
2. A enters into a contract with B to supply services to B. in consideration of an interest in some property of B. to be given to A by B's will. After the death of B. a dependant of B successfully obtains an order for support under that Part V of the Succession Law Reform Act of Ontario. If the stipulated consideration is fully paid to A, there will be insufficient other assets in B's estate to satisfy the support order.
<p>
[15 marks] <b>How does Ontario law resolve this competition? Should the Ontario solution be imported by provinces which have similar legislation, but do not deal specifically with the problem in their legislation, as Ontario has done?</b>
<p><br>
<center><h3>PART B</h3></center>
3. Client Bob Jones, age 50, has come to see lawyer Sally Smith for some estate planning advice. While Bob was waiting for Smith in her office reception area, Bob completed a checklist of assets. Smith regularly uses the checklist to speed up the interview process. (Smith claims that before she instituted the checklist, she was wasting too much time with clients as they babbled on about family matters.) From this checklist, Smith learns that Bob has a substantial investment in shares of three public companies. Two of these companies have been very profitable and the shares have increased in value since Bob acquired them. These shares also generate ordinary cash dividends and stock dividends on a regular basis. The investment in one company has decreased in value since acquisition. Bob also owns some term deposits, and owns all the common shares of his business, Bobco, which manufactures hightech products. This industry is growing and Bob's company is quite successful.
<p>
When Smith met with Bob, he mentioned that he no longer owns his home. It was sold when he and his wife Betty were experiencing marital difficulties a few years ago. (The principal residence exemption was claimed at that time.) Although they have since reconciled, Bob feels that the marriage is on somewhat shaky ground. He neglected to mention any of this in the checklist. Bob now lives in a rented home with his wife Betty and their three children Matt age 20, Jeff age 15, and Joe age 11. Matt is in University, and Bob anticipates that the other boys will attend University as well. Bob's mother, Nan, also lives in the home with Bob and his family, and in exchange for helping with the children, Bob provides financial support to his mother. Except for a small pension, this is Nan's only income.
<p>
Bob also tells Smith that he was the Executor of his neighbor Jane's estate. Bob says that acting as the Executor of Jane's estate was very easy. Jane's will had divided her estate between her 2 adult children and a 12 year old grandchild. (The grandchild is the child of a son of Jane who had predeceased her). The adult children told Bob that they did not want the grandchild to share and so Bob simply divided the estate between the 2 adult children. Bob also told Smith that, as Executor, he did not worry about Jane's creditors or taxes since as far as he knew Jane had no debts and she once admitted to him that she never paid income tax. Bob says he was quite flattered that Jane had selected him to act as Executor.  Bob would like to return the compliment by naming Jane the Executor of his estate. 
<p>
Bob has asked Smith for some inter vivos estate planning advice and to prepare a will. Smith is extremely busy and prepares a memo to her junior with the information Bob has given to her. Smith's secretary, upon reading the memo, tells Smith that while Bob was in the reception area, he took some pills and told Smith's secretary that he was quite ill. Smith is somewhat surprised by this information, given Bob's robust appearance, and the fact that there was no mention of his health in the meeting.
<blockquote>
<b>Assume that you are the junior lawyer. Prepare a memorandum for Smith</b>
<p>
[17 1/2 marks] <b>(i) discussing the inter vivos estate planning advice which should be given to Bob Jones;</b>
<p>
[17 1/2 marks] <b>(ii) discussing the critical issues to be addressed when considering Bob Jones' will.</b>
</blockquote>
<b>Note: In your memorandum, there is no need to discuss the principal residence rules.</b>
 <p><br>
