<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, SPRING 1995<br>
BUSINESS ORGANIZATIONS II<br>
EXAMINER: PROFESSOR MACINTOSH</h2>
</h3>INSTRUCTIONS</h3></center>
(1)	The exam must be returned within 24 hours of being picked up (unless you have made
a special arrangement with Professor MacIntosh).<p>
(2) There is only one restriction on the materials you may use. Because not everyone can have access to library materials at the same time, I would prefer that you not use anything from the library collection. Previously taken photocopies do not violate this rule.<p>
(3) In accordance with the Faculty Council resolution of Oct. 6, 1993, you may consult with other students in the course of working out your answer. However, please note that this resolution also provides that &quot;the answer or answers returned by the students must be organized and written by that student alone&quot;.<p>
(4)	There are four questions. The marks are allocated as follows:<p>
Q1: 25%<br>
Q2: 25%<br>
Q3: 20%<br>
Q4: 30%<p>
(5) The word limit for the whole exam is 4000 words. You may allocate your 4000 words in any way you see fit as between the various questions.<p>
(6) Please make a word estimate for the entire exam and put this estimate on the front page of your exam answer. Anything written in excess of the word limit <b>will not be read</b>! Be forewarned that this penalty will be enforced with absolute strictness, in fairness to those students who make a conscientious effort to observe the word limit. In the past, I have downgraded at least one &quot;A&quot; paper to a &quot;C&quot; for significantly exceeding the word limit, and have downgraded many more a half or a whole grade.
<p>
Please note that all word estimates are carefully checked. Given
some complaints about uneven enforcement of the rule in the past,
I have decided (commencing this year) to hire a graduate student
to carefully check all work estimates. No prisoners will be taken.
<P>
(7) I would prefer that you type your examination answer. However,
this is not required. If you write your answer, <b>please</b>
make sure that it is legible, and written on <b>every other line</b>.
If you choose, you may submit a handwritten copy of your answer
and submit a typed copy within one week (or longer, if you have
made a special arrangement with me).
<P>
If you submit a handwritten copy and intend to replace this with
a typewritten copy, <b>please clearly indicate this on the top of
the handwritten copy</b>.
<P>
(8) I place a high premium on <b>organization and clarity</b>
Answers which have been well thought out in advance uniformly
score higher.
<P>
(9) Feel free to incorporate by reference anything that you say
in response to one question for the purposes of answering another
question.
<P>
(10) Note that &quot;OSA&quot; means the Ontario <cite>Securities
Act.</cite> &quot;OSC&quot; means the Ontario Securities Commission.
<P>
1. At a Canadian Bar Association seminar in Toronto, 5 lawyers
were having lunch together. These lawyers were all graduates of
the Faculty of Law, University of Toronto, and had all been good
friends in law school. Having all graduated from law school in
the mid-1980s and moved to different parts of the country, they
had mostly bought houses in the late 1980s, at a time when the
housing market was at its peak. They were all grousing about the
fact that house prices in many parts of Canada had fallen precipitously
in the past 3 years.
<P>
One of them, Marjorie Mayhem, suddenly came up with an interesting
idea. She noted that house prices in various parts of the country
are far from perfectly correlated. For example, while in 1990
house prices in Vancouver jumped about 20%, prices in Victoria
went up by only 10%. Prices in Toronto fell by about 10%, while
in Halifax the price of the average house was unchanged. She dimly
recalled from her days in Business Organizations II that a superior
risk/return tradeoff can be achieved when investments whose prices
are imperfectly correlated are pooled in a portfolio of assets.
Normally, home owners are poorly diversified, since they own but
one home. But what if an investment vehicle was set up to give
all of them the benefits of diversification resulting from holding
interests in a pool of homes?
<P>
After putting their heads together, they came up with and put
into effect the following scheme to spread the risks of home ownership
amongst themselves. The scheme is contractual in nature (and binds
heirs, executors, and assigns). Each of the 5 participants signed
a contract giving them both rights and obligations vis-a-vis the
other 4 participants. In particular, the contract created a &quot;virtual&quot;
corporation called House-Hold Inc. A virtual corporation is an
imaginary corporation that does not in fact exist. Under the contract,
all 5 of the lawyers notionally &quot;sold&quot; their houses
to House-Hold, at current market values (set by an independent
appraiser). In return, they received notional (or imaginary) shares
of House-Hold, in proportion to the value of the house notionally
sold to House-Hold.
<P>
The following indicates the appraised values of each of their
homes in 1991, at the appraisal date, and the number of &quot;shares&quot;
in House-Hold each received.
<P>
<center><table>
<tr><th> Name</th><th> Value of House</th><th> % of Shares Received</th></tr>
<tr><td> David Dies-in-house</td><td> $2,000,000</td><td> 50%</td></tr>
<tr><td> David Bleaty</td><td> $ 400,000 </td><td>10%</td></tr>
<tr><td> Marjorie Mayhem</td><td> $ 600,000</td><td> 15%</td></tr>
<tr><td> Heironymous Borscht</td><td> $ 500,000</td><td> 12.5%</td></tr>
<tr><td> Wendy Wailer</td><td> $ 500,000</td><td> 12.5%</td></tr>
<tr><td></td><td>$4,000.000</td></tr>
</table></center><P>
Under the contract, if the owner of the house wanted to sell her/his
house, she/he would have to apply to a notional &quot;board of
directors&quot; for permission to do so. The board of directors
consisted of all 5 participants in the scheme. The board would
have to approve the sale price. In addition, if the participant
wanted to purchase another house and &quot;sell&quot; it to House-Hold,
the board was required to approve this purchase. These measures
were designed to ensure that all sales and purchases of houses
were prudent and at proper market prices.
<P>
If a house was sold, then the actual proceeds would of course
go to the owner. However, under the scheme, the proceeds would
notionally be paid to House-Hold. Then, the owner could force
the (imaginary) company to redeem all of her/his (imaginary) shares.
The value paid for the shares would be equal to the fraction of
the total number of shares held by the redeeming owner, times
the total (notional) value of the assets owned by House-Hold.
For example, if Jane held 20 of 100 notional shares of House-Hold,
and the total notional value of the assets of House-Hold (including
the proceeds from sale of her house) was $1,000,000, then her
shares would be (notionally) redeemed for 20/100 X $1,000,000,
or $200,000 (the &quot;redemption amount&quot;).
<P>
If the price at which the house actually sold was greater than
the redemption amount, the house seller would have to pay the
other house owners the difference between the sale price and the
redemption amount (in proportions corresponding to the shares
held by each owner). If it was less then the other owners would
have to pay the house seller the difference.
<P>
You may assume, if you think it important, that the above contractual
scheme did not in any way affect each owner's &quot;principal
residence&quot; exemption from capital gains tax (i.e. there were
no adverse tax consequences).
<P>
True to his name, one morning David Dies-in-house was found dead
in his house. Following instructions in the will, the executor
of his estate sold the house. The proceeds were $4 million. Since
none of the other house prices had changed at all, this means
that under the contract, the executor became obliged to pay $1,000,000
to the other participants. Note that while the executor failed
to seek the approval of the board of House-Hold to sell the house,
the board nonetheless met and approved the sale.
<P>
The executor has refused to pay. He has been heard to mumble something
about noncompliance with the Ontario <cite>Securities Act</cite>. The
other 4 participants have now come to see you, a crack Business
Organizations II student, for legal advice. Given your qualifications,
the Law Society has passed a special rule permitting you to dispense
the required advice. Please discuss any securities regulatory
issues you think this fact situation reasonably raises (with a
view to determining if the executor will have to pay up).
<P>
2. Daneco is a small firm incorporated under the OBCA. It is listed
on the Alberta Stock Exchange (&quot;ASE&quot;), and makes gidgets.
A gidget is a form of wanger which is instrumental in the manufacture
of plantagenets. Daneco is located in Edmonton, Alberta, and about
90% of its shareholders are in Alberta. About 5 % of its shareholders
are in Ontario. It has only one class of shares. which are not
&quot;legal for life&quot;.
<P>
Daneco decided to raise money by selling more shares, of the same
type which already trade publicly over the ASE, in a private placement.
In particular, it sold shares to a number of banks and insurance
companies under the Alberta equivalent of OSA s.72(1)(a). The
sales took place on March 1, 1995. You may assume for purposes
of this question that the Alberta <cite>Securities Act</cite> is identical
to the OSA.
<P>
The OSC has just discovered that a person resident in Ontario
bought a large block of shares in Daneco (15% of the equity),
through the facilities of the ASE. The transaction was negotiated
by a resident of Ontario through the Calgary office of a large
investment bank which has offices in every major Canadian city.
The seller was one of the banks that purchased shares from Daneco
in the aforementioned private placement on March 1.
<P>
(i) What concerns, if any, do you think the OSC might have about
this transaction?
<P>
(ii) What if the bank bought the shares from Daneco on March 1,
1994 (rather than 1995), sold them in a private placement to another
bank on Sept. 1, 1995, which in turn sold them over the ASE to
the Ontario resident? Would this make any difference?
<P>
(iii) If the OSC has some concerns about either variation of the
above transaction (i.e. the March 1 1995 version or the March
1. 1994 version) what can they do about it?
<P>
(iv) From a policy point of view, <b>should</b> the OSC be concerned
about either of these transactions? Would YOU recommend any changes
to the OSA?
<P>
3. Dane Gelder Inc. is a small firm incorporated under the CBCA.
It makes feltonbucklers. A feltonbuckler is a form of stem-bolt
which is instrumental in the manufacture of gidgets. Mulct, the
entrepreneur who originally incorporated Dane Gelder, is its largest
shareholder, holding 18% of the voting equity (there are 46 other
shareholders, other than employees and former employees who hold
shares). When he incorporated Dane Gelder, he hired Burne as the
firm's lawyer. Burne advised him he could buy his shares under
s.73(1)(a) and s.35(2)10 of the OSA, without the firm having to
issue a prospectus. The shares were then issued to Mulct.
<P>
Dane Gelder has 50 employees, all of whom are shareholders. 20
former employees are also shareholders. Mulct, the President of
Dane Gelder, was anxious to set up an employee share ownership
plan, and asked Burne if this was possible. Unfortunately for
Mulct (but particularly for Burne), Burne died before he could
return the call. The file was taken over by Bootstrap, an ambitious
junior in Burne's (former) firm. Bootstrap advised Mulct that
sales could be effected to employees, without the company having
to issue a prospectus, through s.72(1)(n) of the OSA.
<P>
Mulct, who wanted to ensure that all employees had a direct interest
in the business, sent a memo all employees indicating that, while
a purchase of shares was not required, preference in future promotion
decisions would be given to those who owned shares in the company.
About three-quarters of the employees joined the share ownership
plan, under which part of their monthly pay cheques go toward
the purchase of shares.
<P>
Mulct decided that he didn't like being the only director. He
asked four prominent business people (2 of whom he knew quite
well from prior business dealings, and two of whom he knew by
reputation only) to join the board. They all accepted. Mulct required
all of the new directors to purchase shares in the firm. On Bootstrap's
advice, the four new members of the board of directors purchased
shares under OSA s.72(1)(p). Between them, they now own 18% of
Dane (&gt;Gelder
<P>
The Articles of Incorporation of Dane Gelder state that the company
shall have no more than 50 shareholders, exclusive of present
and former employees. The articles also provide that the directors
may refuse to register a transfer of shares by any shareholder
indebted to the company, and that the company shall not offer
its shares to the public.
<P>
(i) What resale restrictions, if any, attach to the shares of
the various different shareholders?
<P>
(ii) After Dane Gelder sold shares to its directors, was it still
a private company?
<P>
(iii) Suppose that (on Bootstrap's advice, after the sale of shares
to the directors) Dane Gelder revises its Articles of Incorporation
to delete the provision restricting the number of shareholders
to 50 (exclusive of employees), as well as the limitation on offering
its shares to the public. Does Dane Gelder now have to comply
with the continuous disclosure obligation in OSA s.75?
<P>
(iv) Once the revisions to the Articles noted in (iii) occur,
what are the resale restrictions that attach to the shares of
the various shareholders?
<P>
(v) Who is the better lawyer? Burne (as he then was), or Bootstrap?
<P>
4. Target Inc. is an OBCA corporation that trades on the TSE,
and a majority of whose shareholders are resident in Ontario.
On the morning of Monday, Jan. 2, 1995, the market price for Target
was $10 per share.
<P>
Between 9:30 A.M. and 12:00 noon, T. Bone Chickens, a well known
corporate &quot;raider&quot;, acquired 10% of the voting equity
of Target. The shares were purchased from a variety of different
sellers through the facilities of the TSE, at prices ranging from
$10 to $10.50 per share. When news of the trading activity in
Target started to leak into the market, the price started to slowly
rise, on speculation that a takeover bid might soon occur. By
the afternoon, the market price was $11.
<P>
On the morning of Tuesday, Jan. 3, T. Bone acquired a further
5 % of Target, again over the TSE. He paid between $11 and $11.50
to effect the purchase, again from a variety of sellers. By the
morning of Wednesday, Jan. 4, further speculation about a possible
takeover bid drove the price of Target to $12. It stayed at $12
until Feb. 1.
<P>
On the morning of Feb. 1, T. Bone acquired a further 10% block
of Target, this time from an individual named Wally Schleper (who
retained 5 % of Target). The block was purchased at a price of
$13.80. News of the block trade leaked into the market; while
no one knew who purchased the block, the fact that a large block
of shares had traded hands further fueled takeover speculation,
and on the afternoon of Feb. 1, the market price rose to $13.50.
<P>
On April 2, T. Bone purchased a further 5 % of the shares of Target
at $13.50, through the facilities of the TSE.
<P>
Please identify and discuss any securities regulatory issues (including
policy issues) you think are raised by this fact situation.
<P>
<hr>
