<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>SPRING TERM EXAMINATION - 1995<br>
CIVIL APPEALS AND JUDICIAL REVIEW<br>
Examiner- John A. Campion</h2></center><p>
<h3>GENERAL COMMENTS/INSTRUCTIONS</h3>
<ul>
<li>This paper is made available for pick-up any time during the examination period.<p>
<li>Students must file their completed work at the Law School, at the Records Office, <b>within 48 hours</b> after signing out the examination paper.<p>
<li>Students should spend a <B>maximum of eight hours </B>completing their work, including transcription. From the examiner's perspective, the examination can be adequately completed in four hours or less.<p>
<li>Each student is on their honour to work alone and to spend only the maximum amount of time<p>
<li>Students need not do research independent of the course materials, although each student is free to do their work as they see fit<p>
<li>Answers may be typed or hand-written<p>
<li>This is an open-book, take-home examination<p>
<li>You are required to answer all questions<p>
<li>Where required, assume any necessary facts
</ul>
<hr>
<P>
<b>Question #1 (30 marks)</b>
<P>
You have been retained by David Cowan (&quot;Cowan&quot;) to advise
him with regard to a possible appeal of a decision of Oliver,
J., of the Ontario Court (GENERAL Division), released three (3)
days ago. Cowan is unhappy with the result and has retained you
after firing his previous counsel.
<P>
Cowan resides in British Columbia and was sued in Ontario by a
former friend, Jack O'Neil (&quot;O'Neil&quot;), with whom Cowan
was in partnership. The partnership carried on business solely
in British Columbia. The partnership ceased to carry on business
in May of 1992 when Cowan found out that O'Neil had been taking
money out of the partnership for his own personal use. The partnership
was in the business of manufacturing ski waxes which were distributed
solely in British Columbia.
<P>
Beginning in June of 1992, Cowan started a new business on his
own, manufacturing ski waxes, after finding out about his partner's
improper activities.
<P>
Cowan commenced a civil action in British Columbia in 1992 against
O'Neil for a declaration that the partnership was dissolved and
for damages suffered based on the monies which O'Neil had improperly
taken out of the partnership. O'Neil defended the B.C. action.
The British Columbia Supreme Court gave judgment to Cowan for
the sum of $150,000 against O'Neil and granted the declaration
that the partnership was dissolved. O'Neil did not appeal the
British Columbia decision and instead commenced the Ontario action.
(Action No. 236/95).
<P>
Cowan was served with the Statement of Claim in the Ontario action
in British Columbia. O'Neil has sued Cowan for improperly dissolving
the partnership; for breach of the partnership agreement; and
for breach of fiduciary duties for commencing a new business and
soliciting the partnership's customers. Cowan instructed his former
solicitors to bring a motion to set aside the service of the Statement
of Claim on him, and to strike out the Statement of Claim as disclosing no reasonable
cause of action. Oliver J. dismissed Cowan's motion giving the
following reasons:
<blockquote>
&quot;In my view Mr. O'Neil, as a resident of Ontario, has arguably
suffered damage in Ontario and can therefore bring this action
in Ontario. Further I am not satisfied that the Statement of Claim
does not disclose a cause of action &quot;
</blockquote>
Please advise Cowan as to what steps can be taken to overturn
the Oliver J. decision. In your advice, address whether the Oliver
J. decision is an interlocutory or final order and whether leave
to appeal is necessary. Refer to the appropriate rules in the
<cite>Rules of Civil Procedure. </cite>If you determine that leave to
appeal is necessary, draft the factum in support of the motion
for leave to appeal. If you conclude that leave is not necessary,
draft the factum for the appeal.
<P>
<b>Question #2 (30 marks)</b>
<P>
You have been retailed by Dr. Sam Collins, a medical doctor on
a matter concerning the revocation of his certificate of registration
allowing him to practise medicine in Ontario. A panel of the Discipline
Committee of the College of Physicians and Surgeons found Dr.
Collins to be incompetent under section 52 of the <cite>Health Professions
Procedural Code. </cite>The nature of the complaints made against
Dr. Collins were that he had prescribed the wrong drugs for patients;
that he had misdiagnosed several patients' problems and that he
had failed to properly treat several patients.
<P>
Dr. Collins was unrepresented by legal counsel at the hearing.
In the middle of the hearing he requested that the panel adjourn
the hearing to allow him to retain a lawyer, but this request
was denied. He has a number of other concerns regarding
the conduct of the hearing. Dr. Collins was not given the names
of the witnesses or a summary of their evidence prior to the hearing.
The panel was composed of three persons, one of whom participated
in a previous investigation concerning complaints about Dr. Collins.
Dr. Collins also has heard that another panel member had made independent
enquiries of other physicians regarding Dr. Collins' abilities.
Dr. Collins has also told you that one of the panel members was
not present for part of the hearing.
<P>
Please advise Dr. Collins as to what steps can be taken to overturn
the Discipline Panel's decision and the revocation of his licence
to practise medicine. The relevant sections of the Regulated Health
Professions (Code) are set out below. Please draft the appropriate
document to challenge the decision, ie. Notice of Appeal or Notice
of Application for Judicial Review, whichever you determine is
appropriate.
<P><center><table width = "60%">
<tr><td valign = top>Panel for<br>discipline<br>hearing</td>
<td> <b>38.-</b>(1) The chair of the Discipline Committee
shall select a panel from among the members  of the
Committee to hold a hearing of allegations of a
member's professional misconduct or incompetence
referred to the Committee by the Executive or
Complaints Committee.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Compositions</td>
<td> (2) A panel shall be composed of at  least three
and no more than five persons, at least two of whom
shall be persons appointed to the Council by the
Lieutenant Governor in Council.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Idem</td> 
<td>(3) At least one of the members of a  panel shall
be both a member of the College and a member of
the Council.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Exclusion<br>from panel</td>
<td>(4) No person shall be selected for a  panel who
has taken part in the investigation of what is to be
the subject-matter of the panel's hearing.</td></tr>
<tr>
 <td valign = top>Quorum</td>
<td>(5)Three members of a  panel, at least one of
whom must be a member who was appointed to the
Council by the Lieutenant Governor in Council, constitute a
quorum.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Parties</td>
<td><b> 41.</b> The College and the member the against whom
allegations have been made are parties to a hearing.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Disclosure of<br>evidence</td>
<td><b> 42.-</b>(1) Evidence against a member is not admissible
at a  hearing of allegations against the member
unless the member is given at least ten days before
the hearing.
<P>
  (a) in the case of written or documentary 
  evidence, an opportunity to examine the evidence;
<P>
  (b) in the case of evidence of an expert, a copy
  of the expert's written report or if there is no
  written report, a  written summary of the evidence; or
<P>
  (c) in the case of evidence of a witness, the
  identity of the witness.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Exception</td>
<td> (2) A panel may, in its discretion, allow the
introduction of evidence that is inadmissible under
subsection (1) and may make directions it considers
necessary to ensure that the member is not prejudiced.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>No communication<br>by panel<br>members</td>
<td> <b>43.</b> No member of a panel holding a hearing
shall  communicate outside the hearing in relation to
the subject-matter of the hearing with a party or  the
party's representative unless the other party has
been given notice of the subject-matter of the communication.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Admissibility<br>of evidence</td>
<td> <b>49.</b> Despite the <cite>Statutory Powers Procedure Act,</cite>
nothing is admissible at a hearing that would be
inadmissible in a court in a civil action and the findings
of a panel shall be based exclusively on evidence
admitted before it.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Members of<br>panel who<br>participate</td>
<td><b> 50.</b> Only the members of a panel who were
present throughout a hearing shall participate in the
panel's decision.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Incompetence</td>
<td><b> 52.-</b>(1) A panel shall find a member to be
incompetent if the member's professional  care of a
patient displayed a lack of knowledge, skill or judgment
or disregard for the welfare of the patient of a
nature or to an extent that demonstrates that the
member is unfit to continue to practise or that the
member's practice should be restricted.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Order</td>
<td> (2) If  a panel finds a member is incompetent, it
may make an order doing any one or more of the
following:
<ol>
  <li>Directing the Registrar to revoke the member's
certificate of registration.

<li>Directing the Registrar to suspend the member's
   certificate of registration.
<li>Directing the Registrar to impose specified
  terms, conditions and limitations on the
  member's certificate of registration for a
  specified or indefinite period of time.
</ol></td></tr>
 <tr><td></td><th>APPEALS TO COURT</th></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Appeals<br>from decisions<br>of the<br>Board</td>
<td><b> 70.-</b>(l) A party to proceedings before the Board
concerning a registration hearing or review or to
proceedings before a  panel of the Discipline or Fitness
to Practise Committee, other than a hearing of
an application under subsection 72 (1), may appeal
from the decision of the Board or  panel to the Divisional
Court</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Basis of<br>appeal</td>
<td> (2) An appeal under subsection (1) may be made
on questions of law or fact or both.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>Court's<br>powers</td>
<td> (3) In an appeal under subsection (1), the Court
has all the power of the panel that dealt  with the
matter and in an appeal from the  Board, the Court
also has all the powers of the Board.</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign = top>No stay of<br>certain<br>orders<br>pending<br>appeal</td>
<td><b> 71.</b> An order made by a panel of the Discipline
 certain Committee on the grounds of incompetence or by a
 orders panel of the Fitness to Practise Committee on the
 pending grounds of incapacity directing the Registrar to
revoke, suspend or impose terms, limitations or
conditions on a member's certificate takes effect immediately
despite any appeal.</td></tr>
</table></center>
<p>
<b>Question #3 (40 marks)</b>
<P>
You have been retained to appeal the decision of the Divisional
Court to the Court of Appeal in the case found in Chapter 5 of
Volume I of the materials, <cite>The Toronto-Dominion Bank v. Peat
Marwick Thorne Inc. et al. </cite>Leave to appeal was granted by
the Court of Appeal and the Notice of Appeal has been filed. You
are acting for the personal defendants, Gerdine, Weinstock, Anderson,
Sammon, Justice and Huntbatch. Please draft the appellants factum.
<p>
<hr>
