<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Annual Examinations, April 1995<br>
CIVIL PROCEDURE<br>
Examiners: Professors Mosher and Roach</h2></center>
<p><h3>NOTE:</H3><blockquote>
Students may use their copy of the casebook, the rules of civil procedure and any handwritten notes. Additional books are not allowed.<p>
The exam is composed of three questions of equal value.<p>
Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the correct booklets. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<P>
During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<P>
At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR</B>.<P>
Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote><P>
<h3>QUESTION ONE:</h3>
<P>
1. Jill was one of 25 people who invested $200,000 in a development
offered by Blue Shores Inc. Blue Shores represented to her that
her investment would be a tax deduction under Flavelle's <cite>Property
Tax Deduction Act</cite>. She also was advised by her lawyers, Green
&amp; Green, that the investment would be a tax deduction after
they reviewed the plan offered by Blue Shores Inc.
<P>
Jill was recently informed by Revenue Flavelle that following
an internal interpretation of the <cite>Property Tax Deduction Act</cite>,
her investment is not eligible for a tax deduction. Jill believes
that she has been deceived by Blue Shores and offered negligent
advice by Green &amp; Green. She phoned Blue Shores to complain
about the matter only to find out that they have closed their
offices. Green &amp; Green has told her that their legal advice
was not negligent and that if there is a problem it must be with
either the information they received from Blue Shores or with
Revenue Flavelle's interpretation of the act.
<P>
Jack, a fellow investor in Blue Shores, has already commenced
proceedings against Blue Shores claiming a contractual violation
because of similar representations made to him about the tax deductions.
Some of the other investors relied upon the investment as a tax
deduction while others were not told by Blue Shores about its
tax implications and did not consider them.
<P>
Citizens for Fair Taxation is an interest group who wants to argue
that the <cite>Property Tax Deduction Act</cite> is unconstitutional
because it violates s.15 of the Charter by favouring the wealthy.
<P>
<b>This question has two parts. Part A is worth three quarters of
the question so you should spend about 45 minutes while Part B
is worth one quarter or 15 minutes. You can assume that the laws in Flavelle are the same as in Ontario</b>.
<P>
A. Jill has come to your law office seeking advice on how to proceed
with her dispute. She is concerned about the costs of litigation
but also believes that Blue Shores and Green &amp; Green should
not be able to get away with their behaviour. Outline her options
including the one that you think is best designed to secure speedy
and comprehensive justice in the circumstances.
<P>
B. You are clerking for a judge who wants a memorandum on whether
Citizens for Fair Taxation should in a separate action be granted
standing to challenge the constitutionality of the <cite>Property
Tax Deduction Act</cite>. The judge is also interested in any relevant
theories of the role of judging and litigation that may help inform
the decision whether to grant standing.
<P>
<h3>QUESTION TWO: </h3>
<P>
The administrator of the estate of Jane Doe comes to you for advice,
today, April 19, 1995. Jane Doe died on March 15, 1993 after a
lengthy illness, at the age of 16 (she was born March 1, 1977).
During the latter phases of her illness she was treated by Dr.
Sound. He had described a proposed course of treatment to Jane
and her parents, which he represented to be the very best available
treatment for Jane's condition. Based upon this representation
Jane and her parents agreed that Jane should undergo the proposed
treatment. At the time of her death, her parents assumed that
Jane had received the best treatment, and that her death was not
preventable.
<P>
However, a coroner's inquest was ordered, as concerns about the
appropriateness of the treatments Dr. Sound was prescribing had
been raised by other patients and their families. Upon receiving
notice of the inquest on March 20, 1993, Jane's parents began
to wonder whether the treatment prescribed by Dr. Sound may have
contributed to Jane's death, but they had such faith in the competence
of Dr. Sound that they quickly cast this possibility aside. The
coroner's report was released May 1, 1993. The coroner concluded
that the treatment administered to Jane was completely inappropriate
and that much better treatment alternatives existed which would
have prolonged her life substantially. The coroner concluded that
the treatment fell well below the standard of care expected of
a medical doctor.
<P>
<b>This question has three parts. Part A is worth half of the
question so you should spend about 30 minutes. Parts B and
C are each worth one quarter, so you should spend about 15 minutes
on each</b>.
<P>
A. The administrator of Jane's estate tells you that he would
like to sue Dr. Sound on behalf of Jane's estate and asks your
advice as to whether this is possible. In the course of your research
you ascertain that all claims arising out of negligence or malpractice
in respect of professional services rendered by a medical doctor
must be brought within two years from the date the person bringing
the claim knew or ought to have known of the facts upon which
she or he alleges negligence or malpractice. (This provision is
not the actual provision, but is the one which you should use
for the purposes of answering this question.) You should also
consult the <cite>Limitations Act</cite> and the <cite>Trustee Act</cite>,
which are included in the materials.
<P>
B. Assume that the matter is proceeding and you have just received
the Affidavit of Documents of Dr. Sound. In the Affidavit he lists
only documents relating to Jane's care that pre-dated the coroner's
inquest as documents that he is prepared to produce. He lists
two other documents which were prepared for the coroner's inquest
and claims privilege for these documents. He further includes
a boilerplate, claiming privilege for all documents prepared in
contemplation of litigation. The affidavit has been certified
by his lawyer. You are dissatisfied with this affidavit, in part
because based upon information from your client you believe that
the doctor has in his possession other relevant, non-privileged
documents. How would you go about challenging the Affidavit to
obtain better disclosure and/or production and what arguments
would you make, (including what arguments would you make regarding
the appropriate cost award).
<P>
C. Two weeks prior to trial your office is served with an offer
to settle made by the defendant, Dr. Sound. He offers to settle
the claim for $20,000.00, with each party to bear their respective
legal costs. In the Statement of Claim, you had claimed $50,000.00
in damages, plus costs on a solicitor and client basis. Discuss
with your client the potential implications of having received
this offer to settle.
<P>
<h3>QUESTION THREE: </h3><b> Answer either
part A OR part B</b>.
<P>
A. The University of Toronto has recently adopted a Statement
on Prohibited Discrimination and Discriminatory Harassment. Currently
each Faculty and Department is being asked to design procedures
for the resolution, at the Faculty or Departmental level, of complaints
based upon discrimination or harassment on the basis of race,
ancestry, place of origin, ethnic origin, citizenship, color or
creed. Prepare a letter of advice for the Faculty of Law, setting
out pertinent issues which the Faculty ought to consider as it
develops its procedures.
<P>
<h3>OR</h3>
<p>
B. One of the most pressing issues currently facing the legal
profession in Canada is that of the scope of its responsibility
(or more accurately, the responsibility of its members) to make
legal services available. Many members of the public have complained
(and continue to complain) that they do not have access to legal
representation, let alone to <b>effective</b> legal representation.
For many, both within and outside the profession, both the monopoly
which the profession currently enjoys and its self-regulatory
status are deeply implicated in this debate. Discuss the scope
of responsibility which lawyers ought to have for the provision
of legal services, and in so doing, address whether the legal
profession ought to enjoy a monopoly and self-regulatory status.
<p>
<hr>
<address>
