<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Annual Examinations 1994-95. April 1995<br>
CIVIL PROCEDURE B<br>
Examiner: Professor Schiff</h2></center><p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<blockquote>
1. This examination has three parts, which will be weighted equally in grading.<p>
2. The fact-situation is set in the province of Flavelle. Flavelle is not Ontario; it is instead another one, but not any particular one, of the common law provinces of Canada. Assume nonetheless that Flavelle's civil procedure rules, code of lawyers' conduct, and relevant statutory provisions are materially identical to those of Ontario.<p>
3. You should have with you Ontario Civil Practice 1995 and the Supplement of Rules of Professional Conduct &amp; Statutory Provisions. They may contain underlining and highlighting but shall not otherwise contain any notes or other examination aids of any kind.<p>
4. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <I>each </I>examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
5. During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
6. At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</B><p>
7. Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote><p>
You are a lawyer practicing as an associate with a law firm in
Wrightsville, a city in Flavelle. From time to time, partners
send you memoranda asking for your help in client matters they
are handling. Set out below are three such memoranda about an
ongoing lawsuit, sent on the dates indicated.
<P>
Respond to each memorandum, complete with your reasoning and reference
to relevant authorities.
<P>
April 4, 1994. <cite>Re: Reprodex; suit by IBM</cite>. Frank Abel was
in to see me late yesterday. He is the president and major shareholder
of Reprodex Limited, a company I incorporated for him in the early
1980s. Reprodex is very big in the design and manufacture of components
for computers which it supplies to computer manufacturers all
over the world.
<P>
Abel was served with two copies of a Flavelle Court of Justice
statement of claim hours before my interview with him. He had
just returned the previous evening from a four-month business
swing through Europe. He has retained our firm to do what is necessary
to defend the action. Please write a memorandum for me, analyzing
everything that reasonably may support procedural defences at
this point. Also give me your assessment of the chances of success
on each defence you discuss.
<P>
Here is what Abel has told me.
<P>
In 1985, Reprodex entered into a contract with Intercontinental
Business Machines Ltd. (IBM), one of North America's biggest computer
manufacturers, to supply a disc drive built according to IBM's
stated specifications for a new, ultra-high-speed computer IBM
was developing. Abel and Leonard Broder, the head of IBM, had
been friends and business associates in the early days of the
industry in Canada, and because of that, Broder had tried to help
Reprodex ever since the company started up. When Reprodex delivered
the first shipment of the disc drives to IBM in mid-April 1986,
IBM immediately installed them and put the computers on the market.
Unfortunately, disaster struck eighteen months later: the computers
began to malfunction. Under a very generous consumer warranty,
IBM was obliged to service the machines free of charge for the
many purchasers who made claim. Worse, many purchasers returned
their computers under the warranty for full refund. IBM's engineers
immediately pinpointed the trouble in the Reprodex disc drive.
IBM thereupon demanded compensation from Reprodex for breach of
contract. During the lengthy negotiations between IBM and Reprodex,
Abel and Broder exchanged some pretty nasty language, and on one
of the occasions (I think Abel said it was some time in l991)
Broder retaliated by punching Abel in the face. Abel laid an assault
charge in Flavelle Provincial Court and Broder ended up paying
a $500 fine after conviction.
<P>
IBM issued the statement of claim in September, 1993. IBM sues
Reprodex for $1,500,000 for breach of contract to supply the disc
drive according to specifications and $500,000 allegedly owing
on a demand promisory note Reprodex executed as security for $500,000
IBM advanced to Reprodex ten years ago. Abel is joined as party
defendant on the promisory note claim as the alleged co-signer
and guarantor of the note.
<P>
<center><b>II</b></center>
<P>
June 6, 1994. <cite>Re: Reprodex: suit by IBM</cite>. Right now I am
drafting the defence in this action, and I attach to this memo
a copy of the version I have just finished writing up. [See the
end of this part.] What do you think of it?
<P>
I also have some other thoughts about how to proceed, and I would
like your opinion about what I have in mind. I am planning to
add a counterclaim by Abel against IBM and Broder for Abel's personal
injury caused by Broder's punch during that negotiation session.
If the fact of the punch is denied (or at least is not admitted)
in the defence to counterclaim, I think I will plead the criminal
conviction in the reply to defence to counterclaim in support
of a bar against Broder contesting the matter in these proceedings.
<P>
[The body of the attached document, without titles and such, reads
this way:]
<P><blockquote>
1. Defendants admit the following allegations in the statement
of claim -- that the corporate defendant was incorporated under
the laws of Flavelle and carries on business in Canada and internationally,
that defendant Abel is the president of the corporate defendant,
and that the corporate defendant entered into the contract to
supply the disc drive to the plaintiff.
<P>
2. Defendants deny all other allegations in the statement of claim
and put the plaintiff to the strict proof thereof.
<P>
3. Defendants particularly deny the allegations in paragraph 9
of the statement of claim that, as security for a $500,000 loan
from plaintiff to the corporate defendant, they and each of them
on May 3rd, 1984, signed a promisory note under which they and
each of them promised to pay on demand to plaintiff $500.000.
<P>
4. Defendants therefore ask that the court dismiss the claims
with costs.
</blockquote><P>
<center><b>III</b></center>
<P>
April 19, 1995. <cite>Re: Reprodex: suit by IBM</cite>. Please let me
have a memorandum giving your opinion of my chances of success
on the two motions I discuss below.
<P>
The oral examinations for discovery were held last week. I refused
to let Abel answer two of the questions he was asked:
<P><blockquote>
102. How many computers that IBM manufactured containing the Reprodex
disc drive have purchasers returned for refund of purchase price?
<P>
226. Tell me the names of the persons who were responsible for
developing the disc drive Reprodex was supplying to IBM under
the contract.
</blockquote><P>
Plaintiff's counsel has launched a motion to compel Abel's answer
to these questions.
<P>
Plaintiff's counsel also wants discovery of documents beyond what
we have given already. He wants us to produce and show to him
every document in the possession of Reprodex and this law firm
relating to the design, development and manufacture of the disc
drive from the time it was first conceived until the beginning
of this lawsuit. When I refused this request, he launched a motion
to compel production and allow inspection.
<P>
 <hr>
<address>
