<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Annual Examinations, April 1995<br>
COMPETITION LAW<br>
Examiner: Professor Dunlop</h2></center><p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any printed or written material you wish during the examination.<p>
<li>The exam is composed of 5 questions. <B>ANSWER ANY THREE. </B>Make reasonable assumptions as to any additional facts.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the correct booklets. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b>
</ol>
<P>
1. Commenting on the first two fully contested merger cases under
the <cite>Competition Act, Hillsdown Holdings (Canada)Inc. </cite>and
<cite>Southarn, Inc., </cite>an observer has stated:
<blockquote>
The starting point in merger cases is the identification of the
relevant product and geographic markets. In both cases the Tribunal
focused on the real-world behaviour of consumers and competitors
rather than theoretical or statistical economic evidence. Regrettably,
in <cite>Southam </cite>this degenerated into a 185 page review of highly
particularized evidence. If this bent for detail continues the
Tribunal risks missing the forest for the trees.
</blockquote>
Comment
<P>
2. It is inconsistent, some commentators claim, for a statute
aimed at maintaining and promoting competition to prohibit price
discrimination, predatory pricing and resale price maintenance.
<p>
Do you agree?
<P>
3. The Flavelle Law Association is an organization to which most
of the lawyers in the Judicial District of Flavelle (formerly
known as the County of Flavelle) belong. Like such organizations
throughout the Province, it provides a forum for discussion of
problems of common concern, acts as an occasional lobby and pressure
group, and has an active social program. With the help of the
Law Society it maintains a basic law library. The Judicial District
consists of the City of Flavelle (pop. 348,786) and its suburban
and rural environs.
<P>
In the past few years the Association has had a number of debates
on the future of legal practice in the District. Concern has been
expressed over the number of lawyers entering practice generally,
and the number entering practice in the Flavelle District in particular.
One school of thought is that the competition among members is
becoming &quot;cut throat&quot; and that the public is suffering
thereby. &quot;For example&quot; declaimed Art Park of Park &amp;
Ryde, a firm that devotes a large proportion of its time to estate
planning, &quot;Ann Abolic and Gerry Mander are advertising their
fee schedules, including a fee for a simple will, and an hourly
rate for the preparation of a plan. You and I know that they are
too young to have experience and judgment in estate planning,
and you just have to look at their fees to realize they must be
giving inadequate service or operating at a loss - perhaps both.&quot;
&quot;And the way some of them conduct litigation&quot; added
Titus Attik, of Attik &amp; Sellar, who specialize in civil litigation.
&quot;You'd think every preliminary and interlocutory motion provided
for in the rules was a compulsory element of every- legal dispute.
They must be running up huge bills of costs.&quot; The result
of several months deliberations by a committee was a Code of Professional
Behaviour to be approved by the Association and accepted by new members at time of joining the Association. Observance
was to be voluntary with the only sanction for breach of any of
the provisions being publication of the names of &quot;non-observers&quot;
with the particular form of non-observance in a monthly Newsletter.
One of the provisions reads: &quot;Advertising professional services
is inconsistent with the dignity of the profession and likely
to damage its reputation and the reputations of its members.&quot;
<P>
The executives have consulted you to determine the propriety of
such an undertaking. Advise.
<P>
4. The City of Emsworth has a population of 3.2 million and six
daily national newspapers. There are three &quot;quality&quot;
papers publishing news of international and national events and
commenting significantly on issues of importance. The Globe and
the World have circulations over 750,000 daily while the Planet
has 400,000. The three &quot;tabloids&quot; provide sketchy news
coverage but concentrate on features such as sports, gossip, and
opinionated exchanges on the &quot;letters&quot; page. The Comet
and the Meteor sell close to 2 million copies daily, while the
Asteroid manages just over 1,000,000. The Globe, the Planet and
the Meteor are all controlled by Market Blandings Inc., a conglomerate
with interests in many manufacturing, distributing, resource and
communication enterprises. The Planet was acquired recently when
it appeared to be in danger of becoming insolvent. As part of
a plan to &quot;rationalize&quot; its publications the management
of the press division positioned the Planet as a morning paper
and had the Globe begin to appear at noon. They began offering
joint subscriptions; for an additional 10 percent a subscriber
to either paper could receive both, or the Meteor. Advertising
rates offered similar bargains.
<P>
You have been consulted by Billy Club, a business columnist with
the World who doubts the economic rationale offered by Market
Blandings for its policy. He wonders whether the <cite>Competition
Act </cite>has any application to the circumstances. Can you assist?
<P>
 5. Write an essay on a topic of your choice.
<p>
<hr>
<address>
