<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-1995, APRIL 1995<br>
TAKE-HOME EXAMINATION<br>
CONFLICT OF LAWS SPRING 95</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>INSTRUCTIONS:</h3><blockquote>The Faculty of Law take home exam policy states, in part: &quot;It is expected that there will be consultation amongst students writing the same take home examination, although the answer or answers returned by the student must be organized and written by that student alone&quot;.
<p>
Students should pay particular attention to the need for a take home answer to be their own work. It must be &quot;organized and written by that student alone&quot;. Contravening this rule is an academic offence under the University's Code of Academic Conduct.
<p>
Your answer must be returned within 48 hours of pickup, either to the Records Office in person or by fax to (416) 978-7899 or (416) 323-9491. (However, if you are picking up the examination question by fax at the end of the day on Friday, you may return your answer at the beginning of business on Monday). If you are returning the answer by fax, please keep a copy of the activity report from your fax machine.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>
Est and Casino are provinces in a federal country whose laws are
identical to those of Canada. Shortly after his Reactionary Renewal
Party is swept to power in the province of Est. Premier Bill Bagg
declares war on environmentalists who, he says, are destroying
the competitiveness of the province's industrial base. Pending
a comprehensive review, Bagg's government passes legislation that
returns the province's air and water pollution standards to what
they were before, as Bagg puts it, the province started to be
run by &quot;commies and Green Freaks&quot;. Greatly increased
amounts of toxic pollutants are soon detected in the air and in
rivers and lakes in the adjoining province of Casino. Casino's
Premier, Cam Naptha, who has a longstanding self-made reputation
as a supporter of environmental causes, tells Bagg: &quot;I don't
care whether you poison your own people but keep that filth out
of my province.&quot; Bagg replies that Est has the sovereign
right to set its own pollution standards free from outside interference.
<P>
Indignant, Naptha pushes through the legislature of Casino the
Transboundary Pollution Responsibility Act (TPRA). The Act has
the following main features: it affirms the jurisdiction of the
Casino courts to hear any matter arising out of pollution flowing
into Casino from other provinces; it establishes absolute liability
as the standard to be applied with respect to tortious liability
of out of province polluters; it provides for damages, including
punitive damages, as a remedy, as well as injunctive relief where
the court sees fit; it gives standing to environmental interest
groups to sue on behalf of the public interest, provided that
any monetary award is distributed through a Compensation Fund
to which anyone who has been injured due to the pollution in question
shall have access. The Act also establishes the Transboundary
Pollution Litigation Subsidy, to provide environmental groups
as well as individuals with legal services to pursue litigation
under the Act. Finally, the Act also contains what Naptha calls
a &quot;save the world&quot; clause. This clause 1) confers on
the Casino courts the jurisdiction to hear any matter connected
with any polluting act anywhere that is in violation of international
environmental law and legal norms; 2) establishes that the applicable
law in any such action shall be the law of C&gt;einn
<P>
In response to the Casino legislation, the government of Est passes
the Extraprovincial Measures Act. The Act prohibits the Est courts
from recognizing or enforcing any judgment pursuant to the Casino
Transboundary Pollution Responsibility Act. The Act also makes
it an offence to remove from the province any document or any
other matter that may be used in evidence in litigation pursuant
to the TPRA. Finally, the Act declares that the courts of Est
have exclusive jurisdiction over any private action based on polluting
acts that are alleged to have taken place entirely within the
territory of Est. and abolishes public interest standing in any
&quot;environmental cause.&quot;
<P>
<b>75%</b> 1. Cindy Braka and Norbert Wellman are fishers who make their
living on rivers and lakes in Casino. Pollution flowing out of
a chemical plant across the Est border has come close to destroying
their livelihood, and they are considering taking legal action
against the owners of that Plant, a major corporation that does
business in, and owns assets in, most provinces. One-World is
an environmental interest group operating in Est. that wishes
to get the Plant shut down given the risk it is creating for nearby
communities in Est. Based on the above facts, advise Braka, Wellman,
and One-World on the conflict of laws and related constitutional
issues that may arise in any such action.
<P>
<b>25%</b> 2. Based on your answer to 1, reflect briefly on the adequacy
of conflict of law rules, included related constitutional rules,
for managing the private law implications of interprovincial conflicts
of the kind described in this fact situation. Does the federal
government have a role to play, or are the courts better able
to sort matters out using judge-made (and sometimes constitutionally-based)
rules?
<p>
<hr>
