<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95, April 1995<br>
CONSTITUTIONAL LAW B<br>
Examiner: Professor Patrick Macklem</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<blockquote>
You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
The examination contains two questions, which are of equal value.<br>
The examination is worth 40% of your final grade.<p>
At the conclusion of the examination, you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE. IF YOU USE MORE THAN ONE BOOKLET. PLEASE INSERT ALL BOOKLETS INTO BOOKLET NO. 1.</b><p>
Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.<p>
<b>PLEASE DOUBLE-SPACE YOUR ANSWER</b>.
</blockquote>
<P>
<h3>QUESTION 1</h3>
<P>
You are an Ottawa lawyer. Your clients, Todd Layland and Pierre
Beaulne, have cohabited in a homosexual relationship since August
1, 1991. They wish to marry one another.
<P>
On January 16, 1995, they attended at the office of the City Clerk,
City of Ottawa, and submitted a marriage licence application.
The marriage licence application is a form issued by the office
of the Registrar General for the Province of Ontario. On the form,
the applicants are asked to answer a number of questions about
their names, addresses, religious denomination, their marital
status, details of any divorce, and data relating to their parents.
There is nothing on the application referring to the sex of the
applicants, nor are there any words that prohibit same-sex marriages.
There are headings labeled &quot;Bride&quot; and &quot;Bridegroom&quot;.
Ms. Colette Latour, an employee of the City of Ottawa City Clerk's
Office, refused to accept your clients' marriage licence application.
In refusing their application, Ms. Latour stated that same-sex
marriages are not permitted by the <cite>Marriage Act</cite>, R.S.O
1990, c. M.3.
<P>
The <cite>Marriage Act</cite> makes no explicit reference to sexual
orientation in connection with marriages. The authority to marry
is set out in s. 4 as follows:
<blockquote>
4. No marriage may be solemnized except under the authority of
a licence issued in accordance with this Act.
</blockquote>
Section 5(1) sets out who can marry. It reads:
<blockquote>
5(1). Any person who is of the age of majority may obtain a licence,
provided no lawful cause exists to refuse to issue such a licence.
</blockquote>
It is common ground that there is no statutory provision that
defines marriage in a way that excludes the union of persons of
the same sex. Nonetheless, &quot;marriage&quot; at common law
consists only of the union of one man and one woman and cannot
include a homosexual union: see, for example, <cite>Hyde v. Hyde</cite>
(1866), L.R. 1 P. &amp; D. 130; <cite>Corbett v. Corbett (Ashley)</cite> (No. 2), [1970] 2 All E.R. 33 (P.D. &amp; A. Div.). The Oxford
English Dictionary also defines &quot;marriage&quot; as &quot;a
condition of man and woman legally united for purpose of living
together and usually procreating lawful offspring.&quot;
<P>
Prior to the enactment of the <cite>Charter</cite>, Canadian courts
relied on the above cases to hold that persons of the same sex
do not have the capacity to marry one another, and that, as a
result, &quot;lawful cause&quot; (within the meaning of s. 5(1)
of the <cite>Marriage Act</cite> and similar provisions in statutes
of other provinces) exists to refuse to issue a marriage licence
to same-sex couples. In <cite>North v. Matheson</cite> (1974), 53 D.L.R.
(3d) 280 (Man. Co. Ct.), Ormrod J. provided the following reasons
for this conclusion:
<blockquote>
[S]ex is clearly an essential element of the relationship called
marriage, because it is and always has been recognized as the union of a man and
woman. It is the institution on which the family is built, and
in which the capacity for natural heterosexual intercourse is
an essential element. It has, of course, many other characteristics,
of which companionship and mutual support is an important one,
but the characteristics which distinguish it from all other relationships
can only be met by two persons of opposite sex.
</blockquote>
You have applied for judicial review of the refusal by the City
Clerk's Of five to issue a marriage licence to your clients on
the basis that the refusal violates ss. 7 and 15, and cannot be
justified under s. 1, of the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and
Freedoms</cite>. The Attorney General of Ontario opposes the application.
What is your constitutional argument? What constitutional arguments
of the Attorney General should you be concerned about? How will
you answer these opposing arguments?
<P>
<h3>QUESTION 2</h3>
<P>
In a recent Ontario election, a conservative party swept into
office proclaiming &quot;a common sense revolution&quot;. Part
of its platform proposes to &quot;get tough on crime and drugs&quot;.
To this end, the government has announced increased funding for
police patrols, drug testing for new public sector employees,
and introduced new legislation entitled, <cite>An Act regulating
Illicit Drug Equipment and Literature (&quot;IDEAL Act&quot;)</cite>.
<P>
The <cite>IDEAL Act</cite> regulates the sale of drug-related instruments
and drug-related paraphernalia in so-called head shops, and regulates
the sale of publications and literature glamorizing, advocating
and promoting the use of drugs. Its stated purpose is to protect
vulnerable children and youth and to reduce the influence of organized
crime involved in the distribution of illicit drugs.
<P>
It is clear from speeches given in the legislature that the Government
was concerned about the fact that vulnerable children and youth
were the recipients of a double message. On the one hand, the
consumption of illegal drugs is banned and subject to severe penalty
by federal law; on the other hand, drug paraphernalia shops freely
sell instruments to aid in drug consumption and literature that
promotes the consumption of illicit drugs. This dilemma was expressed
by Ontario Provincial Police Assistant Commissioner Rod T. Stamler,
who was a witness in legislative committee hearings. He stated:
<blockquote>
While organized crime groups are reaping massive profits from
the illegal drug trade, we continue to permit the public sale
of instruments and literature for drug use, which no doubt reinforces
the motives and incentives of crime organizations in responding
to the obvious demand for drug supplies. Parents are appalled
at the open sale and availability of &quot;how-to&quot; publications,
such as <cite>How to Grow Marijuana and Magic Mushrooms, Cocaine
Handbook, Tootin' Tips </cite>and <cite>Grow Yer Own Stone</cite>. The
same is true for the availability of monthly issues of <cite>High Times</cite> magazine, published in the United States, which promotes
and glamorizes the drug trade.
</blockquote>
Section 1 of the <cite>IDEAL Act</cite> states:
<blockquote>
&quot;equipment for illicit drug use&quot; means anything designed
primarily or intended under the circumstances for consuming or
to facilitate the consumption of an illicit drug.
<P>
&quot;Literature for illicit drug use&quot; means any printed
matter or video describing or depicting, and designed primarily
or intended under the circumstances to promote, encourage or advocate
the production, preparation or consumption of illicit drugs.
</blockquote>
Section 4 establishes an Illicit Drug Equipment and Literature
Board (&quot;IDEAL Board&quot;), and s. 5 provides:
<blockquote>
5. (1) No place of business shall offer for sale without lawful
excuse any equipment for illicit drug use or any literature for
illicit drug use which has not been approved by the IDEAL Board.
<p>
(2) Any one contravening subs. (1) is guilty of an offence
and liable on summary conviction:
<P>
(a) for a first offence to a fine of not less than $2000.00;
<P>
(b) for second or subsequent offence to a fine of not less
that $10,000 and not more than $40,000.
</blockquote>
Section 6 of the <cite>IDEAL Act</cite> provides:
<blockquote>
6. In determining whether to approve illicit drug equipment
and literature for sale, the IDEAL Board shall not withhold approval
of literature that contains depictions of drug use that are essential
to a wider artistic, literary, medical or scientific purpose.
</blockquote>
You are a lawyer at the Office of the Attorney General of Ontario.
The Attorney General has asked you to prepare a memorandum addressing
the constitutionality of the <cite>IDEAL Act</cite>. In particular,
she has asked you to address the following issues:
<P>
(i) Does the <cite>IDEAL Act</cite> infringe s. 2(b) and, if so,
can it be justified under s. 1, of the <cite>Canadian Charter of
Rights and Freedoms</cite>? (Your answer to this issue will be worth
50% of Question 2.)
<P>
(ii) Does the Province of Ontario possess the legislative authority
under s. 92 of the <cite>Constitution Act, 1867</cite> to enact the
<cite>lDEAL Act</cite>? (Your answer to this issue will be worth 50%
of Question 2.)
<P>
<hr>
