<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95, April 1995<br>
CONSTITUTIONAL LAW C<br>
Examiner: Professor Carol Rogerson</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3><blockquote> 1. You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
2. The examination contains two questions, which are of equal value. The examination is worth 40% of your final grade.<p>
3. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
4. During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
5. At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.<p>
</B>6. Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<P>
<h3>QUESTION 1</h3>
<P>
You are an Ottawa lawyer. Your clients, Todd Layland and Pierre
Beaulne, have cohabited in a homosexual relationship since
August 1, 1991. They wish to marry one another.
<P>
On January 16, 1995, they attended at the office of the City Clerk,
City of Ottawa, and submitted a marriage licence application.
The marriage licence application is a form issued by the office
of the Registrar General for the Province of Ontario. On the form,
the applicants are asked to answer a number of questions about
their names, addresses, religious denomination, their marital
status, details of any divorce, and data relating to their parents.
There is nothing on the application referring to the sex of the
applicants, nor are there any words that prohibit same-sex marriages.
There are headings labeled &quot;Bride&quot; and &quot;Bridegroom&quot;.
Ms. Colette Latour, an employee of the City of Ottawa City Clerk's
Office, refused to accept your clients' marriage licence application.
In refusing their application, Ms. Latour stated that same-sex
marriages are not permitted by the <cite>Marriage Act</cite>, R.S.O
1990. c. M.3.
<P>
The <cite>Marriage Act</cite> makes no explicit reference to sexual
orientation in connection with marriages. The authority to marry
is set out in s. 4 as follows:
<blockquote>
4. No marriage may be solemnized except under the authority of
a licence issued in accordance with this Act.
</blockquote>
Section 5(1) sets out who can marry. It reads:
<blockquote>
5(1). Any person who is of the age of majority may obtain a license,
provided no lawful cause exists to refuse to issue such a licence.
</blockquote>
It is common ground that there is no statutory provision that
defines marriage in a way that excludes the union of persons of
the same sex. Nonetheless, &quot;marriage&quot; at common law
consists only of the union of one man and one woman and cannot
include a homosexual union: see, for example, <cite>Hyde v. Hyde</cite> (1866), L.R. 1 P. &amp; D. 130; <cite>Corbett v. Corbett (Ashley)</cite> (No. 2), [1970] 2 All E.R. 33 (P.D. &amp; A. Div.). The Oxford
English Dictionary also defines &quot;marriage&quot; as &quot;a
condition of man and woman legally united for purpose of living
together and usually procreating lawful offspring.&quot;
<P>
Prior to the enactment of the <cite>Charter</cite>, Canadian courts
relied on the above cases to hold that persons of the same sex
do not have the capacity to marry one another, and that, as a
result, &quot;lawful cause&quot; (within the meaning of s. 5(1)
of the <cite>Marriage Act</cite> and similar provisions in statutes
of other provinces) exists to refuse to issue a marriage licence
to same-sex couples. In <cite>North v. Matheson</cite> (1974), 53 D.L.R.
(3d) 280 (Man. Co. Ct.), Ormrod J. provided the following reasons
for this conclusion:
<blockquote>
[S]ex is clearly an essential element of the relationship called
marriage, because it is and always has been recognized as the
union of a man and woman. It is the institution on which the family
is built, and in which the capacity for natural heterosexual
intercourse is an essential element. It has, of course, many
other characteristics, of which companionship and mutual support
is an important one, but the characteristics which distinguish
it from all other relationships can only be met by two persons
of opposite sex. Marriage exists as a protected legal institution
primarily because of societal values associated with the propagation
of the human race. No same sex couple offers the possibility of
the birth of children by their union.
</blockquote>
You have commenced proceedings to challenge the refusal by the
City Clerk's Office to issue a marriage licence to your clients
on the basis that the refusal violates ss. 7 and 15, and cannot
be justified under s. 1, of the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights
and Freedoms</cite>. Your clients are prepared to take the case to
the Supreme Court of Canada, if necessary. The Attorney General
of Ontario opposes the application. What is your constitutional
argument? What constitutional arguments of the Attorney General
should you be concerned about? How will you answer these opposing
arguments? Are you likely to succeed?
<P>
The following information may prove helpful in structuring the
constitutional argument. Marriage is a status from which flow
many legal rights and obligations, including such things as sponsorship
in immigration law and medical decision-making powers if one spouse
becomes incapacitated. Denmark is the only country in the western
world to have essentially legalized same-sex marriage by creating
a new status of &quot;registered partnership&quot; open only to
same-sex couples and which carries almost all of the legal consequences
of marriage. Some countries are beginning, in a piecemeal fashion,
to recognize same-sex relationships as spousal relationships for
some purposes, just as the law recognizes unmarried heterosexual
couples as spouses for some purposes. In Ontario, a government
bill to accord same-sex couples the same rights and obligations
as heterosexual common-law couples was defeated in a free vote,
even after the government deleted provisions allowing same-sex
couples to adopt children, because of the perceived threat posed
to the traditional family.
<p>
<h3>QUESTION 2</h3>
<P>
In a recent Ontario election, a conservative party swept into
office proclaiming &quot;a common sense revolution&quot;. Part
of its platform proposes to &quot;get tough on crime and drugs&quot;.
To this end, the government has announced increased funding for
police patrols, drug testing for new public sector employees,
and introduced new legislation entitled, <cite>An Act regulating
Illicit Drug Equipment and Literature (&quot;IDEAL Act&quot;)</cite>.
<P>
The <cite>IDEAL Act</cite> regulates the sale of drug-related instruments
and drug-related paraphernalia in so-called &quot;head&quot; shops,
and regulates the sale of publications and literature glamorizing,
advocating and promoting the use of drugs. Its stated purpose
is to protect vulnerable children and youth and to reduce the
influence of organized crime involved in the distribution of illicit
drugs.
<P>
It is clear from speeches given in the legislature that the Government
was concerned about the fact that vulnerable children and youth
were the recipients of a double message. On the one hand, the
consumption of illegal drugs is banned and subject to severe penalty
by federal law (the <cite>Narcotics Control Act</cite>); on the other
hand, drug paraphernalia shops freely sell instruments to aid
in drug consumption and literature that promotes the consumption
of illicit drugs. This dilemma was expressed by Ontario Provincial
Police Assistant Commissioner Rod T. Stamler, who was a witness
in legislative committee hearings. He stated:
<blockquote>
While organized crime groups are reaping massive profits from
the illegal drug trade, we continue to permit the public sale
of instruments and literature for drug use, which no doubt reinforces
the motives and incentives of crime organizations in responding
to the obvious demand for drug supplies. Parents are appalled
at the open sale and availability of &quot;how-to&quot; publications,
such as <cite>How to Grow Marijuana and Magic Mushrooms, Cocaine
Handbook, Tootin' Tips </cite>and <cite>Grow Yer Own Stone</cite>. The
same is true for the availability of monthly issues of <cite>High
Times</cite> magazine, published in the United States, which promotes
and glamorizes the drug trade.
</blockquote>
Section 1 of the <cite>IDEAL Act</cite> states:
<blockquote>
&quot;Equipment for illicit drug use&quot; means anything designed
primarily or intended under the circumstances for consuming or
to facilitate the consumption of an illicit drug.
<P>
&quot;Literature for illicit drug use&quot; means any printed matter
or video describing or depicting, and designed primarily or intended
under the circumstances to promote, encourage or advocate the
production, preparation or consumption of illicit drugs.
</blockquote>
Section 4 establishes an Illicit Drug Equipment and Literature
Board (&quot;IDEAL Board&quot;), and s. 5 provides:
<blockquote>
5. (1) No place of business shall offer for sale without lawful
excuse any equipment for illicit drug use or any literature for
illicit drug use which has not been approved by the IDEAL Board.
<P>
(2) Any one contravening subs. (1) is guilty of an offence and
liable on summary conviction:
<P>
(a) for a first offence to a fine of not less than $2000.00;
<P>
(b) for second or subsequent offence to a fine of not less that
$10,000 and not more than $40,000.
</blockquote>
Section 6 of the <I>IDEAL Act </I>provides:
<blockquote>
6. In determining whether to approve illicit drug equipment and
literature for sale, the IDEAL Board shall not withhold approval
of literature that contains depictions of drug use that are essential
to a wider artistic, literary, medical or scientific purpose.
</blockquote>
You are a lawyer at the Office of the Attorney General of Ontario.
The Attorney General has asked you to prepare a memorandum addressing
the constitutionality of the <I>IDEAL Act. </I>In particular,
she has asked you to address the following issues:
<blockquote>
 (i) Does the Province of Ontario possess the legislative authority
under s. 92 of the <I>Constitution Act, 1867</i> to enact the <I>IDEAL Act? </I>(Your
answer to this issue will be worth 50% of Question 2.)
<P>
 (ii) Does the <I>IDEAL Act </I>infringe s. 2(b) and, if so, can
it be justified under s. 1, of the <I>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms? </I>(Your answer
to this issue will be worth 50% of Question 2.)
</blockquote>
The following information may be of use to you in preparing your
memorandum. Any publications which counsel the commission of a
drug-related offence and which pose an imminent threat of an offence
being committed can be prosecuted under the counselling offence
in the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>. Political advocacy groups such as
NORML (National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws)
have opposed the bill, as has the Writer's Guild.
<P>
