<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-94, April, 1995<br>
CONSTITUTIONAL LAW<br>
Examiner: Professor Risk</h2></center><p>
Time: 2:00 - 4:15, April 12
<p>
1. This exam is composed of three questions, which are of equal value. To allocate your time equally among them, take 45 minutes for each one.
<p>
2. (i) Section one needs to be considered in the first and third questions. You may, in answering one of these two questions, refer to something you said in the answer to the other. (ii) Do not worry about federalism or the application of the Charter. (iii) You may think that you need to know more facts; if you do, say what it is you need to know, and, if appropriate, make some reasonable assumptions. For example, you may wish to make some assumptions about the purposes of legislation in the course of considering section one
<p>
3. You may use any kind of material you wish, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<p>
4. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, the course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet, and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet during the exam, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be given for this at the end of the examination
<p>
5. During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the exam.
<p>
6. At the conclusion of the exam, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing. Count the total number of booklets used, record this on the from of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. Then gather all your belongings and leave the exam room. All exam answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.
<p>
7. Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their booklets collected separately and may be subjected to a penalty.
<p>
<b>Question One</b>
<p>
The government is considering prohibiting nudity in public entertainment, and it has retained you to give it some advice about freedom of expression.
<p>
During the past couple of years, an immense number of complaints have been made about nudity in public entertainment. Most of these complaints, by far, have been about nude dancing in taverns by females for male audiences, and some this dancing has involved intimate contact with members of the audience.
<p>
The essence of prohibition that the government is considering is that female entertainers must have an opaque covering over their breasts, and both male and female entertainers must have an opaque covering over their pubic areas. This requirement will apply to all places of entertainment, for example, theatres and taverns. The justifications are the need to preserve the family, and the need to prevent exploitation and debasement of women. Public opinion polls show that an overwhelming majority supports this prohibition.
<p>
The government has asked you whether this prohibition would violate the right to freedom of expression given by the Charter of Rights and Freedoms, and if it does, whether it could be justified under section one. In giving your opinion, assume that there is no other relevant legislation.
<p>
<b>Introduction to Questions Two and Three</b>
<p>
Questions two and three involve surrogate motherhood. These questions involve different issues than you considered in the Bridge, and you need not worry whether you can remember what you read there - or were supposed to have read.
<p>
Some explanation is needed, and this explanation can best begin with a description of the usual arrangement. Imagine that a married couple wishes to have a child; the male is fertile, but the female is not. They make a contract with another female - a relative, a friend, or a stranger, to be the surrogate mother. In return for payment, she will be inseminated with sperm from the male partner; she will carry the baby to term; and after its birth, the baby will become the child of the couple.
<p>
This usual arrangement can be varied. Some variations involve more complex technology, especially in vitro fertilization, a complex and uncertain process of taking a ovum from a female, fertilizing it with male sperm outside a womb, and returning it to the womb of the woman from whom the ovum came, or the womb of another woman. Other variations involve the prospective parents. Instead of a married couple, the parents might be an unmarried heterosexual couple, a homosexual couple, or a single person (and some of these variations of the prospective parents involve in vitro fertilization).
<p>
This process involves difficult moral questions; the experience may cause emotional difficulties for the participants; and formidable contract problems can arise if one of them changes her or his mind. Some women's groups are opposed to surrogate motherhood because it reinforces the stereotype of women as &quot;breeders,&quot; and because the surrogate mothers may be exploited.
<p>
The government is considering permitting surrogate motherhood, subject to very stringent restrictions about who could perform the procedures, the contract, the prospective parents, and the surrogate mothers. These restrictions would be supervised by an administrative agency, whose approval would be needed for every surrogate arrangement. Any contract for surrogate motherhood that was not approved would be void, and criminal-type sanctions would be imposed on persons who made arrangements intending to avoid the regulation (although on not the surrogate mother herself). The result of these restrictions would be that a large proportion of the arrangements now made would be prohibited.
<p>
<b>Question Two</b>
<p>
The government has asked you whether restrictions of this kind would violate section seven of the Charter of Rights and Freedoms; in particular, it has asked you to consider challenges by either of the prospective parents in the typical arrangement described in the introduction, by women who wish to be the surrogate mothers, and by the lawyers and doctors who have specialized in arranging these contracts and performing these procedures, and who will see their businesses either substantially curtailed or terminated. The government has not, though, asked you to consider whether a violation, if you think there is one, can be justified under section one, and it will not pay you any more if you do consider this possibility.
<p>
<b>Question Three</b>
<p>
The terms being considered stipulate that the prospective parents must be married. Heterosexual couples living in stable relationships but who are not married are excluded, and so are homosexual couples and single persons, no matter how well suited they may otherwise be to parenthood.
<p>
Your answers to the first two questions were so impressive that the government has asked you for advice one last time. It has asked you whether this requirement violates section 15(1) of the Charter of Rights and Freedoms, and, if it does, whether any violations can be justified under section one.
<p>
<hr>
