<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95, April 1995<br>
CONSTITUTIONAL LAW<br>
Examiner: Professors Sharpe and Swinton</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3><blockquote>
 1. You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.
<p>
2. The exam is composed of three questions. The suggested time allocation is indicated. Question 1 is worth 40 marks, Question 2 is worth 35 marks, and Question 3 is worth 25 marks
<p>
3. Question 1 should be in a separate booklet from the other questions and marked with <b>Professor Swinton's</b> name. Questions 2 and 3 should be in booklets marked with <b>Professor Sharpe's</b> name.
<p>
4. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the correct booklets. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<p>
5. During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<p>
6. At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR</b>.
<p>
7. Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<p>
<h3>QUESTION 1</h3>
<B>Value - 40%<br>
Time to Answer - 1 hour and 15 minutes</b>
<p>
The control of firearms is currently a very important issue on the public policy agenda because of fears about increased violent crime in Canada.
<p>
The federal government has introduced a bill to enact the <cite>Firearms Act</cite>, which will significantly tighten up the control of firearms by extending the existing registration system for handguns and prohibiting certain weapons. Specifically, it will:
<blockquote>
1. prohibit anyone from possessing a firearm (rifles as well as handguns) unless he/she has a Canadian Firearms License, which can only be obtained after the individual has passed an authorized firearms safety course and is 16 years of age;
<p>
2. require the registration of all firearms (rifles as well as handguns) by all firearms owners in Canada;
<p>
3. require registered handguns to remain at the place designated in the registration (e.g. the licensee's home) unless there is a license to transport the weapon for specified purposes (for example, to a gun club for target practice);
<p>
4. prohibit the importation or sale of certain types of weapons, such as handguns with a barrel length of less than 105 mm or assault rifles.
</blockquote>
Aboriginal persons are exempted from the licensing requirement in paragraph one, provided that they hunt or trap as a way of life in order to sustain n themselves or their  families.
<p>
The Act confers the power on the Cabinet to make detailed regulations to implement the Act. Possession of a gun without the necessary license and registration certificate or possession at an unauthorized place is an offense punishable by up to five years of imprisonment and forfeiture of the weapon.
<p>
The province of Ontario has also been concerned about an increase in violent crime. Believing that the federal legislation does not go far enough, the government recently introduced the <cite>Ammunition Sales Act</cite> bill. That Act will provide:
<blockquote>
1. No one can purchase ammunition in Ontario unless he or she has an Ontario Ammunition Permit. Such a permit is only available to those over 18 years of age who possess A va lid Canadian Firearms Licence;
<p>
2. Retailers of ammunition in the province must keep a record of every sale of ammunition that specifies the time of each transaction, the name, age and address of the purchaser and the Ontario Ammunition Permit number.
<p>
3. Retailers who contravene the Act can lose their retail license. Retailers, and others who contravene the Act, can be prosecuted and fined, on conviction, up to $25.000.
</blockquote>
Some members of the legislature want to make this Act tougher by controlling the import of ammunition from other provinces and the United States, and have suggested that a further section be added that will prohibit possession of ammunition in the province unless it has been purchased under an Ontario Ammunition Permit. Alternatively, they suggest an outright ban on the importation of ammunition.
<p>
The Canadian Rifle Association, a group opposed to further controls on gun and ammunition use, has been suggesting that the federal and provincial legislation are vulnerable on constitutional grounds under the <cite>Constitution Act, 1867</cite>. Representatives of Aboriginal peoples are also concerned about the implications of the Ontario bill.
<p>
Assume that you are a lawyer with the provincial Ministry of the Attorney General. You have been asked to give a reasoned legal opinion on the constitutional issues that might arise under the <cite>Constitution Act, 1867</cite> if both the federal and provincial laws were enacted (including the suggested amendment to the provincial law). Do not discuss the <cite>Charter of Rights</cite> or the <cite>Constitution Act, 1982</cite>, even if you think that issues under them might arise.
<p>
<h3>QUESTION 2</h3>
<B>Value - 35%<br>
Time to Answer - 60 minutes</b>
<p>
You are an Ottawa lawyer. Your clients, Todd Layland and Pierre Beaulne, have cohabited in a homosexual relationship since August 1, 1991. They wish to marry one another.
<p>
On January 16, 1995, they attended at the office of the City Clerk, City of Ottawa, and submitted a marriage license application. The marriage licence application is a form issued by the office of the Registrar General for the Province of Ontario. On the form, the applicants are asked to answer a number of questions about their names, addresses, religious denomination, their marital status, details of any divorce, and data relating to their parents. There is nothing on the application referring to the sex of the applicants, nor are there any words that prohibit same-sex marriages. There are headings labelled &quot;Bride&quot; and &quot;Bridegroom&quot;. Ms. Colette Latour, an employee of the City of Ottawa City Clerk's Office, refused to accept your clients' marriage license application. In refusing their application, Ms. Latour stated that same-sex marriages are not permitted by the <I>Marriage Act</i>, R.S.O 1990, c. M.3.
<p>
The <I>Marriage Act </I>makes no explicit reference to sexual orientation in connection with marriages. The authority to marry is set out in s. 4 as follows:
<blockquote>
4. No marriage may be solemnized except under the authority of a license issued in accordance with this Act.
</blockquote>
Section 5(1) sets out who can marry. It reads:
<blockquote>
5(1). Any person who is of the age of majority may obtain a license, provided no lawful cause exists to refuse to issue such a license.
</blockquote>
It is common ground that there is no statutory provision that defines marriage in a way that excludes the union of persons of the same sex. It is also common ground that the definition of &quot;marriage&quot; at common law consists only of the union of one man and one woman and cannot include a homosexual union. The Oxford English Dictionary also defines &quot;marriage&quot; as &quot;a condition of man and woman legally united for purpose of living together and usually procreating lawful offspring.&quot;
<p>
Prior to the enactment of the <I>Charter, </I>Canadian courts relied on the common law definition to hold that persons of the same sex do not have the capacity to marry one another, and that, as a result, &quot;lawful cause&quot; (within the meaning of s. 5(1) of the <I>Marriage Act </I>and similar provisions in statutes of other provinces) exists to refuse to issue a marriage licence to same-sex couples. In <I>North v. Matheson </I>(1974), 53 D.L.R. (3d) 280 (Man. Co. Ct.), Ormrod J. provided the following reasons for this conclusion:
<blockquote>
[S]ex is clearly an essential element of the relationship called marriage, because it is and always has been recognized as the union of a man and woman. It is the institution on which the family is built, and in which the capacity for natural heterosexual intercourse is an essential element. It has, of course, many other characteristics, of which companionship and mutual support is an important one, but the characteristics which distinguish it from all other relationships can only be met by two persons of opposite sex. Marriage exists as a protected legal institution primarily because of societal values associated with the propagation of the human race. No same sex couple offers the possibility of the birth of children by their union.
</blockquote>
You have commenced proceedings to challenge the refusal by the City Clerk's Office to issue a marriage licence to your clients on the basis that the refusal violates ss. 7 and 15, and cannot be justified under s. 1, of the <I>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms. </I>Your clients are prepared to take the case to the Supreme Court of Canada if necessary. The Attorney General of Ontario opposes your application. What is your constitutional argument? What constitutional arguments of the Attorney General should you be concerned about? How will you answer these opposing arguments? Are you likely to succeed?
<p>
The following information may prove helpful in structuring the constitutional argument. Marriage is a status from which flow many legal rights and obligations, including such things as sponsorship in immigration law and medical decision-making powers if one spouse becomes incapacitated. Denmark is the only country in the western world to have essentially legalized same-sex marriage by creating a new status of &quot;registered partnership&quot; open only to same-sex couples and which carries almost all of the legal consequences of marriage. Some countries are beginning, in a piecemeal fashion, to recognize same-sex relationships as spousal relationships for some purposes, just as the law recognizes unmarried heterosexual couples as spouses for some purposes. In Ontario, a government bill to accord same-sex couples the same rights and obligations as heterosexual common-law couples was defeated in a free vote, even after the government deleted provisions allowing same-sex couples to adopt children, because of the perceived threat posed to the traditional family.
<p>
<h3>QUESTION 3</h3>
<b>Value - 25%<br>
Time - 45 Minutes</b>
<p>
In a recent Ontario election, a conservative party swept into office proclaiming &quot;a common sense revolution&quot;. Part of its platform proposes to &quot;get tough on crime and drugs&quot;. To this end, the government has announced increased funding for police patrols, drug testing for new public sector employees, and introduced new legislation entitled, <I>An Act regulating Illicit Drug Equipment and Literature (&quot;IDEAL Act&quot;).</I>
<p>
The <I>IDEAL Act </I>regulates the sale of drug-related instruments and drug-related paraphernalia in so-called head shops, and regulates the sale of publications and literature glamorizing, advocating and promoting the use of drugs. Its stated purpose is to protect vulnerable children and youth and to reduce the influence of organized crime involved in the distribution of illicit drugs.
<p>
It is clear from speeches given in the legislature that the Government was concerned about the fact that vulnerable children and youth were the recipients of a double message. On the one hand, the consumption of illegal drugs is banned and subject to severe penalty by federal law; on the other hand, drug paraphernalia shops freely sell instruments to aid in drug consumption and literature that promotes the consumption of illicit drugs. This dilemma was expressed by Ontario Provincial Police Assistant Commissioner Rod T. Stamler, who was a witness in legislative committee hearings. He stated:
<blockquote>
While organized crime groups are reaping massive profits from the illegal drug trade, we continue to permit the public sale of instruments and literature for drug use, which no doubt reinforces the motives and incentives of crime organizations in responding to the obvious demand for drug supplies. Parents are appalled at the open sale and availability of &quot;how-to&quot; publications, such as <I>How to Grow Marijuana and Magic Mushrooms, Cocaine Handbook, Tooting Tips </I>and <I>Grow Yer Own Stone. </I>The same is true for the availability of monthly issues of <I>High Times </I>magazine, published in the United States, which promotes and glamorizes the drug trade.
</blockquote>
Section 1 of the <I>IDEAL Act </I>states:
<blockquote>
&quot;equipment for illicit drug use&quot; means anything designed primarily or intended under the circumstances for consuming or to facilitate the consumption of an illicit drug.
<p>
&quot;literature for illicit drug use&quot; means any printed matter or video describing or depicting, and designed primarily or intended under the circumstances to promote, encourage or advocate the production, preparation or consumption of illicit drugs.
</blockquote>
Section 4 establishes an Illicit Drug Equipment and Literature Board (&quot;IDEAL Board&quot;), and s. 5 provides:
<blockquote>
5. (1) No place of business shall offer for sale without lawful excuse any equipment for illicit drug use or any literature for illicit drug use which has not been approved by the IDEAL Board.
<p>
(2) Any one contravening subs. (1) is guilty of an
offense and liable on summary conviction:
<p>
(a) for a first offense to a fine of not less than $2000.00;
<p>
(b) for second or subsequent offense to a fine of not less that $10,000 and not more than $40,000.
</blockquote>
Section 6 of the <I>IDEAL Act </I>provides:
<blockquote>
6. In determining whether to approve illicit drug equipment and literature for sale, the IDEAL Board shall not withhold approval of literature that contains depictions of drug use that are essential to a wider artistic, literary, medical or scientific purpose.
</blockquote>
A number of public interest groups have indicated that they consider that the legislation may contravene the Charter of Rights and Freedoms and that they intend to mount a Charter challenge. You are a lawyer at the Office of the Attorney General of Ontario. The Attorney General has asked you to prepare a memorandum addressing the issues that are likely to arise in a Charter challenge.
<P>
<hr>
