<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95, April 1995<br>
CONSTITUTIONAL LAW<br>
Examiner: Professor L. Weinrib</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3><blockquote> 1. There are three questions on this examination, each worth one-third of the total grade. Questions 1 is a <I>Charter </I>question; question 2 is a split <I>Charter-</I>federalism question, with 50% of the grade allotted to the <I>Charter </I>and 50% to federalism. Question 3 is an essay question.
<p>
2. You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, <I>except </I>books owned by the Library.
<p>
3. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<p>
4. During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination
<p>
5. At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<p>
6. Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
<p>
7. <B>Please double-space your answers.</B>
</blockquote>
<P>
<h3>Question 1: one hour</h3>
<P>
The Church of Heaven is a relatively new and small religious sect.
It has a number of practices that seek to alleviate the stress
and alienation of modern urban life. Some of its prayer
and communal gatherings are held in its urban centres and others
are held in rural retreats. All activities emphasize a return
to nature, reading scripture, singing hymns, prayer and community.
There is a considerable amount of emphasis on spiritual maturity,
meaning accepting human life as a divine but finite gift. Communal
rituals mark events such as birth, marriage, divorce and death
as important spiritual turning points. There is a strong belief
in a happy and fulfilling afterlife.
<P>
The most distinctive feature of this new religion is to be found
in its death rituals. Because a &quot;good death&quot; is considered
one of the goals of life and part of the divine plan for entry
into the afterlife, there is an emphasis on accepting death as
an opportunity for spiritual growth for the individual and for
the community. When a member of the Church is nearing death, the
community gathers to give whatever support is needed, including
health care, meals, personal services, emotional support, spiritual
support and pain relief. Members of the faith who are closest
to the dying individual spend a lot of time discussing his or
her life's meaning and personal desire for a spiritually meaningful
death. The actual end of life is often a communal occasion, according
to the wishes of the individual. Although the details of these
deaths are held secret as part of the community's ritual knowledge
available only to its leaders, it is widely understood that --
while death comes naturally in some instances -- there is also
intervention to bring on death, especially to eliminate excessive
pain and suffering, including emotional pain and suffering, at
the end of life. A few recent autopsies have established that
death followed the administration of drugs and/or suffocation.
<P>
The Attorney General's Office is concerned and wants to turn its
attention to the Church's end of life ceremonies before things
get out of hand. Preliminary investigations have discovered rumours
of ritual suicides and assisted suicides in the past and plans
for many more. As news of the beauty and dignity of these end-of-life
services spreads, the Church is attracting a lot of attention
as well as an ever increasing number of adherents. Most of the
new members are people who have terminal diseases or extensive
disabilities.
<P>
The professional stance of the medical community is against assisting
suicide but individual doctors are clearly relieved of the emotional
burdens and physical demands of dying people. While the provincial
government doesn't want to be seen to approve or oppose the Church's
activities in a pre-election period, it sees clear advantages
in moving death out of hospitals and away from expenditures for
high technology life support systems, including artificial feeding
and hydration. The federal government is secure in its victory
in the Supreme Court of Canada in <I>Rodriguez </I>and takes the
position that the Supreme Court's upholding of the Criminal Code
prohibition against assisted suicide is secure in all circumstances
<P>
You are a lawyer with a number of dramatic success in <I>Charter
</I>litigation to your credit. A member of the Church approaches
you to settle the legal implications of the activities of the
Church, especially in respect to the end-of-life rituals. The
Church followed the <I>Rodriguez </I>case very carefully but is
confident that the Supreme Court would have reached a different
conclusion if the dying person had been a member of a recognized
religious community that could establish that its death rituals
conform to divine directives as revealed in holy scriptures and
are demonstrably consistent with a believing community's rituals
and teachings about the ultimate meaning of individual life as
well as life at large.
<P>
What <I>Charter </I>advice would you give the Heavenly Church?
<P>
<h3>QUESTION 2: ONE HOUR (Grading information provided at end of question)</h3>
<P>
In a recent Ontario election, a conservative party swept into
office proclaiming &quot;a common sense revolution&quot;. Part
of its platform proposes to &quot;get tough on crime and drugs&quot;.
To this end, the government has announced increased funding for
police patrols, drug testing for new public sector employees,
and introduced new legislation entitled, <I>An Act regulating
Illicit Drug Equipment and Literature (&quot;IDEAL Act&quot;).</I>
<P>
The <I>IDEAL Act </I>regulates the sale of drug-related instruments
and drug-related paraphernalia in so-called head shops, and regulates
the sale of publications and literature glamorizing, advocating
and promoting the use of drugs. Its stated purpose is to protect
vulnerable children and youth and to reduce the influence of organized
crime involved in the distribution of illicit drugs.
<P>
It is clear from speeches given in the legislature that the Government
was concerned about the fact that vulnerable children and youth
were the recipients of a double message. On the one hand, the
consumption of illegal drugs is banned and subject to severe penalty
by federal law; on the other hand, drug paraphernalia shops freely
sell instruments to aid in drug consumption and literature that
promotes the consumption of illicit drugs. This dilemma was expressed
by Ontario Provincial Police Assistant Commissioner Rod T. Stamler,
who was a witness in legislative committee hearings. He stated:
<blockquote>
While organized crime groups are reaping massive profits from
the illegal drug trade, we continue to permit the public sale
of instruments and literature for drug use, which no doubt reinforces
the motives and incentives of crime organizations in responding
to the obvious demand for drug supplies. Parents are appalled
at the open sale and availability of &quot;how-to&quot; publications,
such as <I>How to Grow Marijuana and Magic Mushrooms, Cocaine
Handbook, Tootin' Tips </I>and <I>Grow Yer Own Stone. </I>The
same is true for the availability of monthly issues of <I>High
Times </I>magazine, published in the United States, which promotes
and glamorizes the drug trade.
</blockquote>
Section 1 of the <I>IDEAL Act </I>states:
<blockquote>
&quot;equipment for illicit drug use&quot; means anything designed
primarily or intended under the circumstances for consuming or
to facilitate the consumption of an illicit drug.
<P>
&quot;Literature for illicit drug use&quot; means any printed
matter or video describing or depicting, and designed primarily
or intended under the circumstances to promote, encourage or advocate
the production, preparation or consumption of illicit drugs.
</blockquote>
Section 4 establishes an Illicit Drug Equipment and Literature
Board (&quot;IDEAL Board&quot;), and s. 5 provides:
<blockquote>
5. (1) No place of business shall offer for sale without lawful
excuse any equipment for illicit drug use or any literature for
illicit drug use which has not been approved by the IDEAL Board.
<P>
(2) Any one contravening subs. (1) is guilty of an offence and
liable on summary conviction:
<P>
(a) for a first offence to a fine of not less than $2000.00;
<P>
(b) for second or subsequent offence to a fine of not less that
$10,000 and not more than $40,000.
</blockquote>
Section 6 of the <I>IDEAL Act </I>provides:
<blockquote>
6. In determining whether to approve illicit drug equipment and
literature for sale, the IDEAL Board shall not withhold approval
of literature that contains depictions of drug use that are essential
to a wider artistic, literary, medical or scientific purpose.
</blockquote>
You are a lawyer at the Office of the Attorney General of Ontario.
The Attorney General has asked you to prepare a memorandum addressing
the constitutionality of the <I>IDEAL Act. </I>In particular,
she has asked you to address the following issues:
<blockquote>
 (i) Does the <I>IDEAL Act </I>infringe s. 2(b) and, if so, can
it be justified under s. 1, of the <I>Canadian Charter </I>of Rights and Freedoms? (Your answer
to this issue will be worth 50% of Question 2.)
<P>
 (ii) Does the Province of Ontario possess the legislative authority
under s. 92 of the <I>Constitution Act, 1867</i> to enact the <I>IDEAL Act? </I>(Your
answer to this issue will be worth 50% of Question 2.)
</blockquote>
<P>
<h3>QUESTION 3: ONE HOUR</h3>
<P>
We have read a large number of cases this year that demonstrate
a variety of approaches to constitutional interpretation in a
number of contexts and by a number of different judges. These
cases manifest a range of approaches to the reading of the constitutional
text, first the <I>British North America Act, 1867</i> and later
the <I>Charter. </I>Consider the importance of the constitutional
text to the analysis and conclusions in the cases we have read.
To the extent that the text is not the main focus of constitutional
analysis, what is? A list of cases that might be interesting follows.
Please feel free to discuss these or any other cases that you
think illuminate the Problem.
<P>
<table>
 <tr><th>Vol. I</th></tr>
<tr><td>&quot;Persons&quot; case</td><td> 20-28</td><td> (Supreme Court and Privy Council)</td></tr>
<tr><td> Board of Commerce Act</td><td> 83-88</td><td> (Privy Council)</td></tr>
<tr><td> General Motors</td><td> 333-342</td><td> (S . C . C.)</td></tr>
 <tr><th>Vol. II</th></tr>
<tr><td> Quong Wing</td><td> 83-88</td><td> (P.C.)</td></tr>
<tr><td> Saumur, Switzman</td><td> 93-103</td><td> (S.C.C.)</td></tr>
<tr><td> Big M Drug Mart</td><td> 148-58</td><td> (S.C.C.)</td></tr>
<tr><td> Oakes</td><td> 175-8</td><td> (S.C.C.)</td></tr>
<tr><td> Ref re. s. 94(2) Motor Veh Act</td><td> 520-9</td><td> (S.C.C.)</td></tr>
<tr><td> Morgentaler</td> <td>533-558</td><td> (S.C.C.)</td></tr>
<tr><td> Andrews</td><td> 611-627</td><td> (S.C.C.)</td></tr>
<tr><td> Conway</td><td> 652-3</td><td> (S.C.C.)</td></tr>
<tr><td> Sparrow </td><td>33-46</td><td> (S.C.C.)</td></tr>
</table>
<P>
