<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, APRIL 1994-95<br>
CONTRACTS<br>
Examiner: Professor Waddams</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>No materials are allowed in the examination room.<p>
<li>There are three questions, of equal value.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<hr>
<P><ol>
<li>Able is in the business of constructing swimming pools. Baker,
who wants a swimming pool built on her property, contacts Able, explaining
that she wants a pool without a diving board, but deep enough for safe diving from the
edge. Able says that 6 feet would be perfectly safe, as indeed the official guidelines
confirm, but Baker, who has a great fear of diving accidents insists on a depth of 8 feet.
Able says this would cost an extra $2,000, above the standard price of $40,000, and
Baker agrees to a price of $42,000. Baker then signs an agreement, on Able's standard
form, which refers to details in Able's brochure, which in turn specify a minimum depth
of 6 feet. When the pool is completed Baker discovers that the depth at the deep
end is only 7 feet. The evidence is that the pool is perfectly safe, and the market
value of Baker's property is not affected by the departure from contract specifications.
Building the pool to the specifications would have cost Able $3,000 more that the actual
cost, but now that the pool is complete, the only way to deepen it would be to demolish
it and rebuild it, at a cost of $50,000. Baker says that, despite the expert assurances
of safety, she would personally feel more comfortable with the greater depth, and had
specified the depth for precisely that reason. Advise Baker.
<P>
<li>Albert and Bertha are husband and wife, aged 65. Albert has
recently retired from a moderately successful small business. Their only substantial asset
is their home, jointly owned, worth about $1,000,000. Their daughter, Charlotte, and
her common-law husband, Doug, have been pressing Albert and Bertha to assist
them in a business venture of Doug's. Doug wants to borrow $1,000,000 from the bank,
and is urging Albert and Bertha to mortgage their home to guarantee repayment
of the loan. Albert's instincts are against this proposal: the figures are
too large; he doubts the soundness of the business venture; he thinks that arrangements
of the sort proposed are apt to lead to family quarrels. But Charlotte is very insistent,
saying that her happiness is at stake, and Bertha supports her. Eventually Albert
agrees, and Albert, Bertha and Doug go together to Doug's bank. The manager does not
know of the precise relationship among the parties, but supposes that Albert
and Bertha must be Doug's relatives. She says that, following some disagreeable judicial
decisions, new bank policy is that in such cases the guarantors must have independent
advice. Albert's opinion of the legal profession, except in respect of its ability
to charge fees, is low, and he expresses his opinion in forceful terms. The manager says that
she sympathizes, adding that she thinks the judicial decisions were designed to
enhance employment opportunities for the legal profession, but that, unfortunately,
bank policy must be followed. She gives Albert the relevant documents with a form
stating: &quot;We, Albert and Bertha, hereby certify that we have received independent advice
about the transaction referred to herein, and that we fully understand the
effect of a guarantee and a mortgage. Name of independent adviser: &quot; The manager
says, &quot;Bring this form back tomorrow, duly signed, and I will authorize the loan&quot;.
Albert and Bertha take the form home, sign it, and the mortgage and guarantee forms,
without seeking any independent advice, insert the name of a local lawyer in the
certificate, and take the documents back to the bank. The loan is made to Doug, whose
business fails six months later, leaving him insolvent. No part of the loan has been
repaid, and Charlotte and Doug have now separated. Advise Albert and Bertha.
<P>
<li>&quot;In contracts of all kinds, it is of the highest importance
that courts of law should compel the observance of honesty and good faith&quot;. Lord Kenyon
in <cite>Mellish v .Motteux</cite> (1792) Peake 156. Discuss.
</ol>
<p>
