<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95<br>
CONTRACT LAW<br>
Examiner: Professor Langille</h2></center>
<p>
<I><h3>NOTES:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use the casebook, other course materials, and your own notes during the exam. Textbooks are not permitted.<p>
<li>There are two questions. They are NOT of equal value. Please read them carefully before answering.<p>
<li>Please try to write legibly and double space your answer.<p>
<li>If you think you need further information to answer the question state what it is and why you need it.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be 1eft on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol></I>
<p>
<center><h3>QUESTION 1</h3>
<I> [value 1/3]</I></center>
<P>
The organizers of the Annual Melmerby Beach Marathon (&quot;the
run for the lobsters&quot;) had great ambitions and wished to
put the race in the same league as Boston, New York, etc. (The
organizers are actually a corporation - MBM Ltd.) To this end
MBM energized itself, obtained corporate sponsorship, and generated
a substantial pile of cash with which to promote its race. One
of its basic strategies was to attract a few &quot;big name&quot;
runners to run the race and thus raise the profile of the 1995
event, which was scheduled for April 25th. MBM entered into individual
contracts with three internationally known marathoners: Alan Mewett
(&quot;The Cornwall Cheetah&quot;), Ernie Weinrib (&quot;The Kantian
Go Cart&quot;) and an American named Speedo Smith. These contracts
provided each runner with $10,000 for running in and completing
the race. Their appearances, especially that of Smith, were crucial
to the profile raising enterprise.
<P>
As well, MBM entered into a contract with Team Nike Ltd. an offshoot
of the giant shoe manufacturer which, following in the tradition
of bicycle races, has created a team of 6 professional marathoners
who run in various races and thus raise the profile of both Nike
and the race in question. Under the contract between MBM and Team
Nike Ltd., Team Nike was paid $20,000 for the appearance of the
team.
<P>
In all of these &quot;special appearance&quot; contracts there
appears a clause which reads: &quot;All runners agree to be bound
by the rules of the International Marathon Association including
the rules regarding race safety&quot; (other &quot;ordinary&quot;
runners make a similar agreement as part of registering for the
race). One of the well known rules of the Federation provides
that all runners undertake not to abandon any running equipment
or other material on a race route. This is aimed at preventing
injury to other runners.
<P>
The build up to the big race was a triumph of public relations
and bold boosterism. &quot;Speedo Smith to Run for the Lobsters&quot;
ran the headline on April 22nd in the local newspaper <cite>The Black
Harbour Bugle</cite>. The number of local entrants eager to run with
Speedo Smith, signed up was at an all time high and MBM expected
a large profit from entrants' fees, ticket sales for the finish
line bleachers, and sales of race paraphernalia (including a T-shirt
with the image of Speedo Smith crossing the finish line with lobsters
raised in both hands) which were going at a brisk pace.
<P>
On April 23, Speedo Smith, after learning that <b>his</b> name
was attracting a lot of attention and that he was getting the
same payment as Mewett and Weinrib, contacted MBM and indicated
that he was not feeling terribly well and probably would not be
able to run in the race, but also indicated that he might feel
considerably better if the committee would raise its appearance
fee to $25,000. MBM debated this issue long into the night of
the 23rd, and agreed with Speedo Smith on the 24th to meet his
new demands
<P>
During the race one of the Team Nike runners is injured when Speedo
Smith throws a can of clam juice over his shoulder after drinking
half of it. By stepping on the container a Team Nike runner, our
old friend Zoe, seriously aggravates an old injury forcing her
out of the race and causing her to become quite depressed. She
also had to forego an appearance on the Sports TV Network demonstrating
her running technique for a fee of $5,000. In addition this cost
her a spot on Team Nike for six months.
<P>
Now that the race is over (&quot;The Cornwall Cheetah Confounds
Again&quot; blared the <cite>Black Harbour Bugle</cite>) Speedo Smith
sues MBM for $25,000. Zoe sues Speedo Smith in contract claiming
compensation for her losses.
<P>
<B>Fully analyze and critically evaluate the legal predicament
in which the parties find themselves.</B>
<P>
<center><h3>QUESTION 2</h3>
<I>[value 2/3]</I></center>
<P>
Times have been hard on the east coast. Even Brian Tobin could
not bring back the groundfish stocks and, as a result, many of
those families engaged for years, even generations, in the inshore
fishing industry (fishing from small boats within 20 miles of
the coast) have had to abandon their way of life. Asa Macdonald
was one victim of the collapse of the inshore industry. He had
been fishing out of Black Harbour since he was 16, but he has
just recently sold his boat (&quot;The Crying Shame&quot;) for
just enough to pay off the bank loan with which he had bought
it, and has gone on unemployment insurance. But every cloud has
some element of a silver lining (at least that is what Asa's mum
had always said). While most fish stocks are declining there are
a few species historically underexploited and now flourishing.
One of those is the specialized snow-crab fishing industry. The
federal government very strictly controls access to this fishery
through a licensing scheme under which the number of licenses
is very limited. As a result the licences have become much sought
after as a ticket to financial success. It is rumoured that holders
of &quot;crab licences&quot; have made hundreds of thousands of
dollars a year.
<P>
Zack Macmurray is an accountant in nearby Tatamagouche who has
been keeping his eye open for local investment opportunities for
himself and some of his clients. He is aware that two months ago
the federal government announced a new programme (the &quot;Plan
to Rehabilitate the Inshore Fishery&quot; or PRIF for short) under
which the government would slightly expand the number of crab
fishing licences available and allocate them to those recently
forced out of the inshore fishing industry in certain locations
in the Province of Nova Scotia - including Black Harbour. Sensing
an opportunity for investment, Zack starts looking for a person
just exiting the inshore fishing business. He had seen a notice
at the local co-op for the sale of &quot;The Crying Shame&quot;
and had made a note of Asa's number
<P>
Zack called Asa and they get together for a chat. Asa explains
that he does not have enough money to buy the special kind of
boat and equipment required for crab fishing and that in spite
of the fact that he might be a candidate for one of the new licences,
he will be unable to take advantage of the programme. Zack explains
that he is in a position to finance the acquisition of the new
equipment and help with the application for the licence under
the PRIF programme in return for &quot;fair return on my investment&quot;
as Zack put it. Asa asked Zack how much he thought could be made
in the crab fishing industry. Zack replied, &quot;Why if we don't
make $300,000 out of that licence a year I will give up drinking
beer.&quot;
<P>
This sounded all very interesting to Asa but, being a cautious
guy, he asked Zack what would happen if a licence were not awarded
to him; to which Zack replied, &quot;Don't worry - it's in the
bag - you are exactly the kind of guy they are looking for, and
besides, the local MP is a good friend of mine. Believe me, it's
a done deal.&quot;
<P>
So, on the evening of April 24th Asa and Zack agree that Asa would
acquire and Zack pay for a new crab boat (costing approximately
$300,000), that Zack would be paid back in installments at $30,000
per year minimum, and that Zack would get 50% of the profits from
the crab fishing enterprise. Zack promises to have the agreement
drawn up by his lawyer, and that they could sign it later because
time is of the essence. The deadline applications under the PRIF
programme is the next morning. Asa and Zack fill out the application
form that evening and Asa, because he lives closer, agrees to
take it down to the federal office in Melmerby Beach the next
morning before the 12 noon deadline.
<P>
On the way home that evening Asa drops into the boat manufacturing
operation of Bobby and Carol McDonough of Merrigomish Harbour
and agrees to buy the crab boat they are currently building at
a price of $300,000. Asa and Zack knew that the market for crab
boats will really heat up when the new licences are announced
and that it is a smart thing to jump at the chance to obtain a
boat now.
<P><blockquote>
 (a) Yes. It had to happen (&quot;every silver lining has a cloud&quot;
as Asa's dad used to say). Asa got up early to drive to the federal building in Melmerby Beach
but found that the local highway at the end of his driveway was closed for the running,
you will recall, of the Melmerby Beach Marathon. As a result he did not arrive at the
federal building until 12:30 in the afternoon - after the deadline. To his astonishment
there was a notice in the door saying that the office was closed that day anyway and that
the deadline for new crab licences under the PRIF programme had been moved up to 5:00 p.m.
the day before (the 24th), as had been announced last week by the Programme's Director
in Ottawa.
<P>
<B>Analyze fully and critically evaluate the legal predicament
in which the parties find themselves.</B>
<P>
 (b) Suppose that Asa makes it to the federal office in time,
it was not closed, and the application was timely; however, two weeks later Asa receives
a letter from the federal government telling him that he has not been awarded a licence.
(Apparently the number of applications was so great the programme had to resort to a
lottery to award the licences.) Upon hearing this Asa becomes very depressed.
<P>
<B>Analyze fully and critically evaluate the legal predicament
in which the parties find themselves.</B>
<P>
 (c) Suppose that the application goes in on time, and the application
is granted. Asa and Zack agreed to meet to celebrate the event at the local pub (recently
renamed &quot;The Admiral Tobin&quot;) over a few beers. They toast themselves and
sign a document Zack has drawn up containing their deal. Then for three years the crab
fishing industry goes reasonably well and Asa is catching crab at about $150,000 a year
before payments. Asa pays back $50,000 per year on the boat loan. Asa can see that
it will take longer than he had expected to pay off the loan for the boat from Zack. The
licence on the other hand is worth quite a lot and there is a thriving market in their
re-sale. Asa figures he could sell the licence, pay off his debt to Zack and retire earlier
than planned. When Asa approaches Zack with this idea, Zack tells him that that would
be a breach of their agreement - in particular Clause 15 which reads: &quot;[Asa] agrees
to pay 50% of the early profits to [Zack] and to repay the boat loan of $300,000 in installments
of at least $30,000 per year. In no event shall [Asa] be released from this
contract until he has paid back the loan and [Zack] has obtained $1,000,000 in profits. If
[Asa] breaches this contract [Zack] shall have the right to seize the boat, keep all
installments, and be entitled to all profits from the sale of the licence.&quot;
<P>
Upon reading these last two sentences, for the first time, Asa
has figured out he will have to keep working for a long time in
order to repay the $1,000,000 profit sharing obligation. Asa comes
to you for advice.
<P>
<B>Analyze fully and critically evaluate the legal predicament
in which the parties find themselves.</B>
</blockquote>
<p>
<hr>
