<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95 APRIL 1995<br>
CONTRACTS II<br>
Examiners: Professors Trebilcock and Valcke</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<ol>
<li>You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>ALL EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<P>
 40% 1. In <cite>Chicago Coliseum Club v. Dempsey</cite> (1932) 265
Ill. App. 542 (facts slightly adapted),  Chicago Coliseum Club brought an action against Jack Dempsey,
alleging breach of a written  contract executed on March 13, 1926, under which the plaintiff
was to promote a boxing match  between Dempsey and Harry Wills for the World Heavy Weight Boxing
Championship. Under  the terms of the agreement, plaintiff agreed to pay Dempsey
a sum equal to 50 percent of the  net profits over and above the sum of $2 million in the event
that gate receipts should exceed  that amount. The defendant further agreed not to engage in any
boxing match after the date of  the agreement and prior to the date on which the contest was
to be held. On March 6, 1926, the  plaintiff entered into an agreement with Harry Wills to engage
in a boxing match with Dempsey.  Under this agreement, the plaintiff was to pay Wills $50,000
immediately and to pay him 10  percent of gate receipts in excess of $2 million. On March 8,
1926, the plaintiff entered into  a contract with one Andrew Weisberg to promote the boxing match.
The agreement  contemplated that it would be necessary to incur expenditures
in the way of travelling expenses,  legal services, and other costs in the promotion of the boxing
match. Under this agreement  Weisberg was to furnish the funds for these purposes and was
to be reimbursed out of receipts  from the sale of tickets, together with a certain amount for
his services. Under the terms of the contracts between the plaintiff and Dempsey and the plaintiff
and Wills, the boxing contest was  to be held during the month of September 1926. On July 10, 1926
the plaintiff received a  telegram from Dempsey indicating that because of flagging ticket
sales for the match with Wills  he had committed himself instead to a boxing match with Gene
Tunney for the World  Championship and refusing to proceed with the planned match
with Wills. Instead he offered  to fight Wills after the match with Tunney (for which the promised
remuneration was much  greater). The plaintiff rejected his offer.
<P>
The plaintiff filed an action against Dempsey for breach of contract, seeking the  following relief.
<ol>
 <li> An injunction enjoining Dempsey from engaging in the contest
with Tunney.
<P>
 <li> Loss of profits which would have been derived by the plaintiff
in the event of the holding of the boxing match between Dempsey and Wills as contemplated
in the contract of  March 13, 1926.
<P>
<li> Expenses incurred by the plaintiff prior to the signing of
the agreement between the plaintiff and Dempsey.
<P>
<li> Expenses incurred after the signing of the agreement and
before the alleged breach of contract on July 10, 1926.
<P>
<li> Punitive damages for wilful breach.
</ol>
If an identical set of facts were to arise today in Ontario how
would a court decide these issues on the basis of Ontario law?
If further evidence would be required to resolve some of these
issues, indicate the nature of that evidence.
<P>

40% 2. a) Last year, the Halifax Harbour Commission (hereinafter
&quot;the Commission&quot;) advertised an invitation for tenders
&quot;to purchase a 1962 Loveboat cruise ship submerged on Aberlone
Reef approximately 10 miles offshore, north east of Halifax...&quot;
Your client, a ship operating company, submitted a $20,000 tender
for the purchase of the vessel, describing it as &quot;a cruise
ship lying on Aberlone Reef as advertised.&quot; $2,000 of this
sum were paid upfront by your client as deposit. The Commission
accepted your client's bid and deposit. Accordingly, your client
made preparations to salvage the vessel. They proceeded to fit
one of their towboats with diving and salvage equipment and engaged
a crew as well as an acknowledged expert in salvage work. These
preparations entailed substantial expenditures, amounting to some
$30,000. Your client now acknowledges to you that it would not
have been very difficult to take steps to find out whether there
was in fact a cruise ship in the locality advertised before these
preparations were made. In any case, your client's preparations
were wholly wasted because no cruise ship was ever found lying
at or near the place specified by the Commission. You are to assume
that there had been a 1962 Loveboat at that place, but that she
had been washed away before the Commission advertised for tenders,
and that the Commission had been negligent (although in no way
fraudulent) in advertising that she was still there. You may also
assume that, had the Commission used reasonable care before advertising,
it could have ascertained with virtual certainty whether the ship
was still there.
<P>
Your client's requests to the Commission for compensation have
been unsuccessful to date. The Commission argues the contract
is invalid or at least unenforceable because of mistake. Your
client wants to know whether the Commission is correct on this
point, and in the event that it is, whether they can nonetheless
expect to recover at least their $2,000 deposit and $30 000 of
expenditures.
<P>
b) Same as (a), except that your client is Toronto's Maritime
Museum, which was hoping to add a 1962 Loveboat to its collection,
and, although a cruise ship is indeed found on Aberlone Reef,
it is a 1964 Loveboat, which the Museum already owns. Also assume
that the Commission's advertisement included the following clause,
which your client read, understood and accepted at the time of
making the bid:
<blockquote>
&quot;THE PURCHASER AGREES TO TAKE THE CRUISE SHIP IN THE STATE
AND CONTITION IT IS FOUND.&quot;
</blockquote>
How do these new facts modify your answer in (a), if at all?
<p>
c) Same as (a). In addition, assume that the Vessel Salvaging
Act requires that towboats used in the salvaging of Loveboats
and bigger vessels be &quot;Size A towboats with Grade A towing
licenses,&quot; and that your client owns a Size A towboat, but
never bothered to obtain a Grade A license for it.
<P>
 20% 3. Facts identical to those in <cite>Barclays Bank v. O'Brien</cite>,
[1993] 3 W.L.R. 786, arise before  the Supreme Court of Canada today. You are to brief the Court
as to whether or not it is  desirable, from a policy perspective, that the reasoning and
conclusions of the House of Lords  in that case be followed.
<p>
