<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>FINAL EXAMINATION, APRIL 1995<br>
CRIMINAL LAW.<br>
EXAMINER: Professor Mewett</h2></center><p>
Time: 2 pm to 5pm Page 1 of 6<p>
<h3>Note:</h2><ol> <li> You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the case book and texts, except books owned the library.<p>
<li> There are THREE questions of equal value, so you have about an hour for each one. Make sure you have 6 pages.<p>
<li> Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request (an) additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li> During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li> At the end of the examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of books used, record this on the front of the first examination booklet and insert all the booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.
</b><p><li> Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<P>
 1. Jack Finch, the accused, is charged with manslaughter under
the following circumstances.
<P>
Finch lives in the town of Yukon, Ontario, a small rural community
not far from Sudbury. Finch, who fancies himself as an artist,
has erected in his front garden, a large object made mostly of
welded scrap metal which he calls &quot;Disco Delight&quot;. On
the fence round his property is a large sign reading &quot;NO
TRESPASSING. DO NOT TOUCH ART WORK&quot;. Jack is no welder and
in fact the whole structure is far from safe, though he personally
thought it quite safe. His neighbours, who consider the object
an eyesore, complained to the Town Council, which issued a demolition
order stating: <b>This structure has not received the required
permit and has not been inspected for safety.</b>
<P>
The Council acted under Town Ordinance 1992-813 which states:
<blockquote>
No person shall erect on his or her property any structure larger
than 3' in height and 2' in diameter without first obtaining a
permit therefor. Such permit shall be granted only where Council
considers the structure both safe and environmentally acceptable.
</blockquote>
The Municipal Act of Ontario enables the Town Council to pass
such bylaws and no question arises as to the validity of the Ordinance.
<P>
Finch neither applied for nor obtained such a permit and ignored
the demolition order.
<P>
One evening last summer when Finch was watching TV. he heard a
commotion in the garden. Going outside, he discovered Peter Pann,
a local thirteen year old teenager, lying under the structure
which had collapsed on him. He was bleeding profusely, while his
friend, Jeremy Pott, was trying to help him. It turned out that
the two had trespassed onto the property and had been climbing
over Disco Delight
<P>
&quot;Help&quot;, said Jeremy, &quot;Get an ambulance quick&quot;,
to which Finch replied, &quot;It's your own damn fault. I'm watching
TV. You'll have to wait until the show is over&quot; and he went
back inside. Jeremy did the best he could and rushed off to find
a telephone which took him about ten minutes. The town's only
ambulance was off on another call and did not arrive on the scene
for another twenty minutes. By this time Peter had lost a lot
of blood and when he got to the local hospital the doctors were
going to give him a blood transfusion when his parents, who had
arrived on the scene, refused to give permission. They belong to the Children of the Blessed Sect which
prohibits the receiving of blood transfusions. The doctors proceeded
to argue with them saying it was Peter's decision, not theirs,
but they were adamant. The doctors in fact called the police and
were about to give the transfusion in spite of the parents' objection
but it was too late. Peter had expired. The doctors are unanimously
of the view that if he had received the transfusion immediately
upon arrival his life would probably have been saved.
<P>
 2. The four accused are Nick Nerd, 22, Pete Pole, 23, Frank Fink,
22 and Gary Grebb, also 22. They have known each other as friends for a number
of years and hang out together. Last summer, they all agreed to rob
the patrons of a trendy cafe, The Bolero Bistro. They agreed that
they wouldn't take any firearms with them, but that Nick and Pete would have
with them realistic toy pistols, while Frank and Gary would take with them
their flick knives. Actually, the other three all knew that Pete liked playing
with guns and had a real semi-automatic which he'd shown them and they were
aware that he has twice been convicted already for armed robbery. Nick
repeated, &quot;no guns, uh?&quot; to which Pete replied, &quot;O.K., O.K.,
I heard you the first time&quot;.
<P>
Next night, as planned, the four arrived at the Bolero half an
hour before closing time, went in but then saw that the place
seemed too crowded. Getting cold feet, they merely sat down and
ordered coffee, at which point Gary said, &quot;I don't like it
guys. I'm pulling out of this. You go ahead if you want to but
leave me out of it&quot;.
<P>
The following night, the remaining three returned to the Bolero,
again half an hour before closing time. This time, there were
three trendy looking patrons there and two members of the staff.
Nick and Pete pulled out the pistols, while Frank brandished his
knife. They yelled for the five people in there to lie on the
floor and hand over all their valuables. One of the patrons, Charles
Chichester, resisted and started to insult the three calling them
&quot;no-good punks&quot;. At this point, Pete started hitting
him, Nick calling out to him, &quot;Give him hell, Pete. The bastard&quot;.
Frank, meanwhile, was ignoring the assault and was busy emptying
the till. Pete knocked the patron, stunned, to the floor and then
continued collecting valuables from the other persons in the cafe.
<P>
At this point, a second patron, Lucinda Labelle, made a dash for
the door in an attempt to escape, whereupon Pete pointed his pistol
at her and fired. It turned out that it was not a toy pistol at all, but his real semi-automatic.
Lucinda fell to the floor, injured in the hip and bleeding profusely
but she has since fully recovered. Frank shouted out, &quot;Christ,
you've killed her. Let's get the hell out of here&quot; and the
three started to leave, but as they left, Pete turned and fired
his semi-automatic at Charles who was just beginning to regain
consciousness. The bullet hit him in the head, killing him outright.
The other victims heard Frank say, &quot;F**k, man, why the hell
did you do that? That was no part of the plan&quot;.
<P>
What is the criminal liability of each of the four accused?
<P>

 3. You are a Judge of the Supreme Court of Canada and must, after
all arguments have been presented, decide on the validity of the new
&quot;No Defence of Extreme Drunkenness&quot; provisions of the new Bill
which, for the purposes of this examination we will assume has been duly enacted.
<P>
Write your judgment.
<P>
The full text of the new provisions is as follows:
<blockquote>
<cite>An Act to amend the Criminal Code (self-induced intoxication)</cite>
<P>
WHEREAS the Parliament of Canada is gravely concerned about the
incidence of violence in Canadian society;
<P>
WHEREAS the Parliament of Canada recognizes that violence has
a particularly disadvantaging impact on the equal participation
of women and children in society and on the rights of women and
children to security of the person and to the equal protection
and benefit of the law as guaranteed by sections 7, 15 and 28
of the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms</cite>;
<P>
WHEREAS the Parliament of Canada recognizes that there is a close
association between violence and intoxication and is concerned
that self-induced intoxication may be used socially and legally
to excuse violence against women and children;
<P>
WHEREAS the Parliament of Canada recognizes that the potential
effects of alcohol and certain drugs on human behaviour are well-known to Canadians and is aware of scientific
evidence that many intoxicants, including alcohol, may cause a
person to act involuntarily;
<P>
WHEREAS the Parliament of Canada shares with Canadians the moral
view that people who, while in a state of self-induced intoxication,
violate the physical integrity of others are blameworthy in relation
to their harmful conduct and should be held criminally accountable
for it;
<P>
WHEREAS the Parliament of Canada desires to promote and help to
ensure the full protection of the rights guaranteed under sections
7, 11, 15 and 28 of the <cite>Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms
</cite> for all Canadians, including those who may be victims of violence;
<P>
WHEREAS the Parliament of Canada considers it necessary to legislate
a basis of criminal fault in relation to self-induced intoxication
and general intent offences involving violence;
<P>
WHEREAS the Parliament of Canada recognizes the continuing existence
of a common law principle that intoxication to an extent that
is less than that which would cause a person to lack the ability
to form the basic intent or have the voluntariness required to
commit a criminal offence of general intent is never a defence
to at law;
<P>
AND WHEREAS the Parliament of Canada considers it necessary and
desirable to legislate a standard of care, in order to make it
clear that a person who, while in a state of incapacity by reason
of self-induced intoxication, commits an offence involving violence
against another, departs markedly from the standard of reasonable
care that Canadians owe to each other and is thereby criminally
at fault;
<P>
NOW, THEREFORE, Her Majesty, by and with the advice and consent
of the Senate and House of Commons of Canada, enacts as follows:
<P>
1. The <B>Criminal Code</B> is amended by adding the following
after section 33:
<P>
<center><I>Self-induced Intoxication</I></center>
<P>
33.1 (1) It is not a defence to an offence referred to in subsection
(3) that the accused, by reason of self-induced intoxication,
lacked the basic intent or the voluntariness required to commit
the offence, where the accused departed markedly from the standard
of care as described in subsection (2).
<P>
(2) For the purposes of this section, a person departs markedly
from the standard of reasonable care generally recognized in Canadian
society and is thereby criminally at fault where the person, while
in a state of self-induced intoxication that renders the person
unaware of, or incapable of consciously controlling, their behaviour,
voluntarily or involuntarily interferes or threatens to interfere
with the bodily integrity of another person.
<P>
(3) This section applies in respect of an offence under this Act
or any other Act of Parliament that includes as an element an
assault or other interference or threat of interference by a person
with the bodily integrity of another person.
<P>
2. <B>This Act shall come into forces on a day to be fixed by
order of the Governor in Council.</B>
</blockquote>
<p>
<hr>
