<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95<br>
CRIMINAL LAW A<br>
Examiner: Professor Brudner</h2></center><p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3><ol><li> You may bring into the examination room any materials <b>except </b>those belonging to the library.<p>
<li> There are three questions of equal value.<p>
<li> Discuss all legal issues reasonably raised by the facts even though your solution to one disposes of the case. If you think the court will reach an unsatisfactory result, feel free to offer reasoned criticisms and alternatives.<p>
<li> Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each </b>examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination<p>
<li> During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li> At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.
</B><p><li> Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<P>
1. Frank and Gwen lived together as common-law spouses. Frank
was sixty-seven years old, partially blind, and of subnormal intelligence.
Gwen was fifty and, according to a psychologist's report, &quot;ineffectual,
passive, and of low average intelligence&quot;. Frank had dropped
out of school after grade eight, Gwen after grade twelve.
<P>
Living with Frank and Gwen was Frank's sister Liz, who was sixty-five
at the date of her death. Liz had come to live with her brother
as a lodger after her sister, with whom she had been living for
several years, evicted her. Liz paid Frank and Gwen for room and
board from her monthly old age pension cheque. Gwen did the shopping
for the household.
<P>
Liz was suffering from anorexia nervosa, an eating disorder characterized
by an irrational fear of gaining weight. As a result, she would
deny herself proper meals, consuming only biscuits and some mineral
water once a day. Liz's behaviour was eccentric in other ways
as well. She would confine herself to her room for days on end,
coming out only at night when Frank and Gwen were asleep to take
her biscuits. In the weeks immediately preceding her death, this
behaviour became more extreme, as she refused to get out of bed
even to wash or to perform natural functions.
<P>
Liz was found dead by Gwen on the morning of July 14, 1994. Her
emaciated body was covered in sores from her immobilization and
weighed sixty pounds. Many of the sores went down to the bone.
A policeman described the conditions in which she was found as
follows:
<blockquote>
There was no ventilation in the bedroom. At one side of the bed
on a chair was an empty mineral water bottle and a cup. Under
the bed was an empty bucket. Otherwise there was no washing or
toilet facilities in the room. There was excrement on the bed
and floor. The bedclothes were soaked with urine. It was a scene
of dreadful degradation.
</blockquote>
During the last few weeks of her life, Liz refused whatever little
assistance Frank and Gwen offered. Gwen brought her food, but
Liz left it untouched. When Gwen asked Liz the name of her doctor,
Liz refused to tell her for fear of being &quot;put away&quot;.
Gwen made some half-hearted attempts to locate Liz's doctor on
her own, but soon gave up. She (Gwen) said she told Frank to try
to find another doctor, but Frank always said, &quot;Let's leave
it till tomorrow.&quot; When asked why she didn't call an ambulance
or the police, Gwen replied that &quot;Liz never complained and
so I didn't think it was serious. Anyway, Liz wasn't my sister,
and I didn't dare do anything without Frank, 'cause he's the boss.&quot;
When asked the same question, Frank answered:
<blockquote>
I didn't think she was dying. She had gone to bed for long stretches
before and then got up again and been all right. I'm almost blind
and so I couldn't tell whether she was looking good or not. I
went up three days before she died and asked her if she was all
right, and she said &quot;Yes.&quot;
</blockquote>
<P>
According to the coroner, the cause of death was lack of food
and toxemia spreading from the infected sores. He said that it
would have taken several weeks for Liz to deteriorate to the state
in which she was found. He also said that the infections could
have been prevented by keeping Liz clean and that the sores were
caused by lack of mobility.
<P>
Discuss the criminal liability of Frank and Gwen.
<P>
2. Recall the facts in <cite>R. v. Campbell and Mlynarchuk</cite>. Assume
that the Criminal Code offence of which Darlene Campbell was convicted
is punishable on indictment by a maximum fine of $5,000 and/or
a maximum term of two years in jail and on summary conviction
by a fine of up to $1,000. Assume also that the performance for
which she was charged took place in 1995. Ms. Campbell has come
to you because she wants to appeal her conviction (despite receiving
an absolute discharge, she is indignant at having a criminal record).
You see this case as a good one with which to mount a constitutional
challenge to s. 19 of the Criminal Code. Ms. Campbell has applied
for legal aid to the Legal Aid Sub-Committee for Group Applications
and Test Cases. The sub-committee has asked you to present a brief
commenting in detail on the chances for a successful challenge
to s. 19 under the <cite>Charter of Rights and Freedoms.</cite> Write
the brief. Be specific about the remedy you will be seeking.
<P>
3. H. L. A. Hart has written that &quot;[l]egal recognition of
the importance of excusing conditions is never unqualified; the
law, like every other human institution, has to compromise with
other values besides whatever values are incorporated in the recognition
of some conditions as excusing.&quot; 
<P>
Defend or criticize this statement with reference to any <b>two</b>
of the following excuses: mistake of fact, intoxication, and automatism.
<P>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
Please send comments and suggestions to <a href="mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</a><p>
Created on AUG-08-95 by Anne Johnston.
</address>
