<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>April/May Examinations, 1995<br>
CRIMINAL LAW<br>
Examiner: Professor Roach</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<blockquote>
Students may use their copy of the casebook and the Criminal Code and any handwritten notes. Photocopied sheets and additional books are not allowed.<p>
The exam is composed of two questions of equal value.<p>
Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on each examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the correct booklets. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be Permitted for this at the end of the examination During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b><p>
Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<P>
1. Sam is a curious ten year old boy who unfortunately likes
to play in the trash piles behind Medical Waste Inc. Sam is very allergic to insulin and one night
last month while playing in the trash at Medical Waste Inc., he accidentally stuck himself
with a needle with insulin. Unfortunately he died after the ambulance driver misdiagnosed
his reactions as epilepsy and did not provide a common antidote for the allergy.
<P>
Medical Waste Inc. is a licensed medical waste company, owned
and managed by Joan who generally works 16 hour days on the site.
Joan has contracted with a security guard company to provide night
watchmen and most nights for the last month John was the security
guard. Joan left all security guards instructions to empty needles
into an approved hard bin before putting them out back for disposal.
<P>
John, the security guard, is 64 years old and in poor physical
and mental health. He has a severe drinking problem and a history
of passing out after drinking. He also suffers from a paranoid
psychosis which makes him believe that he has the power to neutralize
any harm that others face. On most nights, he takes a rather lackadaisical
approach to the disposal of medical waste in part because he thinks
his special powers neutralize any harm that might come from the
waste.
<P>
On the night in question, John had been drinking since morning
and was severely intoxicated when he arrived at work, shortly
after Joan went home for the day. As he began to take the fatal
needle out in a soft paper bag, John began to feel very ill and
eventually passed out in the lot behind Medical Waste. As he passed
out, the bag fell out of his hand to the ground where Sam found
it shortly after. John did not wake for some time and when he
did, he forgot what he was doing and went back inside to sleep
it off.
<P>
Section 1 of the <cite>Flavelle Waste Disposal Act</cite> states: &quot;It
is an absolute liability offence for a licensed medical waste
disposal company to dispose of needles in any container other
than an approved hard bin. It is a strict liability offence for
any person in the employ of a licensed medical waste disposal
company to dispose of needles in any container other than an approved
hand bin.&quot;
<P>
You are articling for the Crown and the Crown Attorney wants a
memorandum discussing whether John and/or Medical Waste Inc. should
be charged with manslaughter and/or a violation of s. 1 of the
<cite>Flavelle Waste Disposal Act.</cite> In addition, she wants to
know what arguments can be anticipated in the defence of John
and the company to the various charges. The Crown Attorney has
heard a rumour that John is willing to plead to manslaughter and
also wants your views about what sentence would be appropriate
and for what reasons.
<P>
 2. Henry and Alison are a couple who are exiles from a small
country, Falconer. They had to leave the country because of their political activities and
Henry had been tortured before he escaped Falconer.
<P>
Henry wants to make a political statement about political conditions
in Falconer and has planned to seize an airliner from Falconer
Air so that he could make a statement to the media. Alison did
not think this was a good idea but went along because she had
seen Henry go into rages when people had opposed his political
ideas in the past. Henry had struck her two years ago when they
had first lived together but had not struck her since.
<P>
Henry also made secret arrangements (not even disclosed to Alison)
with the pilot of the airliner to co-operate in the seizure of
the plane. He had also secured a gun that could be smuggled through
airport security. Alison refused to carry the gun into the plane
but did agree to stand at the cockpit door when Henry tried to
seize the plane.
<P>
When Henry went into the cockpit to his great surprise he saw
not his pilot friend, but the general who had been in charge of
his previous torture. The general grinned at Henry and said &quot;we
have you back now&quot;. Henry was very shocked but somehow managed
to pull the trigger and shoot the general dead. Both Henry and
Alison are charged with first degree murder and attempted hijacking
under s.76 of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>.
<P>
You are articling for the Legal Aid Office and the Director wants
a memorandum discussing what the Crown must prove and what defences
are available to Henry and Alison respectively.
<p>
<hr>
