<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS 1994-95, APRIL 17, 1995<br>
CRIMINAL LAW<br>
Professor Shaffer</h2></center><p>
<h3>NOTE</h3><P><ol>
<li> You May use any kind of material you wish during the examination <b>EXCEPT</b> for books owned by the library.<p>
<li> The exam consists of two questions of equal value.<p>
<li> Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and number of the booklet on <b>EACH</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>FIRST</b> booklet. If you request additional booklets) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet the time you receive it. NO TIME WILL BE PERMITTED FOR THIS AT THE END OF THE EXAMINATION.<p>
<li> During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within 15 minutes of the conclusion of the examination<p>
<li> At the conclusion of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b><p>
<li> Time limits will be strictly enforced. students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their exam booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<p>
1. Arnie was charged with manslaughter, and was tried by Lorraine J. sitting without a jury. Lorraine J.'s decision was as follows:
<blockquote>
The accused Arnie and the victim, his dear friend Ernie, were both 20 years old and had grown up as members of a small religious group, based in Haliburton, who call themselves &quot;The Children of Ice.&quot; One of the central tenets of this group is that fire is an instrument of the Devil: they never use any cooking or heating device that has an open flame, nor do they ever have matches, or any other implement that could be use to create a flame, in their houses. Early in 1994, Arnie and Ernie decided to leave the Children of Ice. They moved to Toronto, where they were unable to find a job or a place to live. Ultimately, having run out of money, they moved into an abandoned house on Charles Street. Ernie was unaccountably attracted to the street life of Toronto, and had begun smoking crack cocaine; Arnie retained the aversion to flames instilled in him by his childhood religion and would have nothing to do with Ernie's habit.
<p>
On the night in question, Arnie was going to sleep while Ernie was smoking his nightly crack. Arnie awoke some time later and observed that Ernie's mattress was in flames, but that Ernie himself was nowhere in sight. Afraid to approach the flames, Arnie left the house to look for Ernie. Unfortunately, as it turned out, Ernie was in another room in the house. He would have had ample time to escape but, befuddled by the crack, he was unable to perceive the danger he was in, and was killed when the fire spread from the mattress and burned the house down.
<p>
I find that Arnie committed an arson offense as defined in s. 433 of the <cite>Criminal Code</cite>, in that he recklessly caused damage by fire to property, which fire caused bodily harm to Ernie. Since this unlawful act caused Ernie's death, Arnie is guilty as charged.
</blockquote>
Section 433 of the <I>Criminal Code </I>reads as follows:
<blockquote>
433. Every person who intentionally or recklessly causes damage by fire or explosion to property, whether or not that person owns the property, is guilty of an indictable offense and liable to imprisonment for life where
<blockquote>
(a) the person knows that or is reckless with respect to whether the property is inhabited or occupied; or<br> (b) the fire or explosion causes bodily harm to another person
</blockquote></blockquote>
Arnie's conviction was affirmed by the Ontario Court of Appeal, and he has been granted leave to appeal to the Supreme Court of Canada. You are a lawyer in the Crown's office responsible for drafting the Crown's factum. Write a memorandum to your file, outlining the submissions the appellant is likely to make and your best responses. Be sure to indicate your opinion as to whether the appeal will succeed.
<p>
2. The four accused are Nick Nerd, 22, Pete Pole, 23, Frank Fink, 22 and Gary Grebb, also 22. They have known each other as friends for a number of years and hang out together. Last summer, they all agreed to rob the patrons of a trendy cafe, The Bolero Bistro. They agreed that they wouldn't take any firearms with them, but that Nick and Pete would have with them realistic toy pistols, while Frank and Gary would take with them their flick knives. Actually, the other three all knew that Pete liked playing with guns and had a real semi-automatic which he'd shown them and they were aware that he has twice been convicted already for armed robbery. Nick repeated, &quot;no guns, uh?&quot; to which Pete replied, &quot;O.K., O.K., I heard you the first time&quot;.
<p>
One night, as planned, the four arrived at the Bolero half an hour before closing time, went in but then saw that the place seemed too crowded. Getting cold feet, they merely sat down and ordered coffee, at which point Gary said, &quot;I don't like it guys. I'm pulling out of this. You go ahead if you want to but leave me out of it&quot;.
The following night, the remaining three returned to the Bolero, again half an hour before closing time. This time, there were three trendy looking patrons there and two members of the staff. Nick and Pete pulled out the pistols, while Frank brandished his knife. They yelled for the five people in there to lie on the floor and hand over all their valuables. One of the patrons, Charles Chichester, resisted and started to insult the three calling them &quot;no-good punks&quot;. At this point, Pete started hitting him, Nick calling out to him, &quot;Give him hell, Pete. The bastard&quot;. Frank, meanwhile, was ignoring the assault and was busy emptying the till. Pete knocked the patron, stunned, to the floor and then continued collecting valuables from the other persons in the caf&eacute;.
<p>
At this point, a second patron, Lucinda Labelle, made a dash for the door in an attempt to escape, whereupon Pete pointed his pistol at her and fired. It turned out that it was not a toy pistol at all, but his real semi-automatic. Lucinda fell to the floor, injured in the hip and bleeding profusely but she has since fully recovered. Frank shouted out, &quot;Christ, you've killed her. Let's get the hell out of here&quot; and the three started to leave, but as they left, Pete turned and fired his semi-automatic at Charles who was just beginning to regain consciousness. The bullet hit him in the head, killing him outright. The other victims heard Frank say, &quot;F**k, man, why the hell did you do that? That was no part of the Plane.
<p>
What is the criminal liability of each of the four accused?
<p>
