<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95, April 1995</h2></center><p>DATE: MONDAY 17 APRIL <br>TIME: 2:00 - 4:15 p.m.<p>
<center><h2>CRIMINAL LAW D<br>
Examiner: Professor Stewart</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>This is an open-book test. You may use any of the following materials during the test: the <cite>Pocket Criminal Code, </cite>the casebook, and any notes or summaries. You may not use any textbooks or library materials during the test.<p>
<li>The examination is composed of TWO questions, which are of equal value.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request one or more additional booklet during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within 15 minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the conclusion of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>ALL EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<p>
<b>Question 1. (50 marks)</b><p>
The four accused are Nick Nerd, 22, Pete Pole, 23, Frank Fink, 22 and Gary Grebb, also 22. They have known each other as friends for a number of years and hang out together. Last summer, they all agreed to rob the patrons of a trendy cafe, The Bolero Bistro. They agreed that they wouldn't take any firearms with them, but that Nick and Pete would have with them realistic toy pistols, while Frank and Gary would take with them their flick knives. Actually, the other three all knew that Pete liked playing with guns and had a real semi-automatic which he'd shown them, and that Pete had twice been convicted for armed robbery. Nick repeated, &quot;no guns, uh&quot; to which Pete replied, &quot;O.K., O.K., I heard you the first time&quot;.<p>
The next night, as planned, the four arrived at the Bolero half an hour before closing time, went in but then saw that the place seemed too crowded. Getting cold feet, they merely sat down and ordered coffee, at which point Gary said, &quot;I don't like it guys. I'm pulling out of this. You go ahead if you want to but leave me out of it&quot;.
<p>
The following night, the remaining three returned to the Bolero, again half an hour before closing time. This time, three trendy looking patrons and two members of the staff were present. Nick and Pete pulled out the pistols, while Frank brandished his knife. They yelled for the five people to lie on the floor and hand over all their valuables. One of the patrons, Charles Chichester, resisted and started to insult the three calling them &quot;no-good punks&quot;. At this point, Pete started hitting him, Nick calling out to him, &quot;Give him hell, Pete. The bastard&quot;. Frank, meanwhile, was ignoring the assault and was busy emptying the till. Pete knocked the patron, stunned, to the floor and then continued collecting valuables from the other persons in the caf&eacute;.
<p>
At this point, a second patron, Lucinda Labelle, made a dash for the door in an attempt to escape, whereupon Pete pointed his pistol at her and fired. It turned out that it was not a toy pistol at all, but his real semi-automatic. Lucinda fell to the floor, injured in the hip and bleeding profusely (she has since fully recovered). Frank shouted out, &quot;Christ, you've killed her. Let's get the hell out of here&quot;. As the three started to leave, Pete turned and fired his semi-automatic at Charles who was just beginning to regain consciousness. The bullet hit him in the head, killing him outright. The other victims heard Frank say, &quot;F**k, man, why the hell did you do that? That was no part of the plan&quot;.
<p>
What is the criminal liability of each of the four accused?
<p>
<b>Question 2. (50 marks)</b><p>
Kirk has a long criminal record as a street-level dealer in cocaine. The last time he was released from jail on a drug charge, he swore to himself that he would &quot;go straight&quot; and would no longer deal in illegal drugs. But, because of his criminal past, he was unable to get a legitimate job. Bowing to the inevitable but determined to keep his promise to himself, Kirk asked his friend Spock, a lawyer practising civil litigation, whether there were any new drugs on the scene that had not yet been banned by the federal government. Spock told Kirk that there was a relatively new drug, with the street name &quot;dilithium&quot;, that had not yet been made illegal. To be doubly sure, Kirk phoned Chekov, an R.C. M.P. Officer, and asked him, &quot;Is dilithium illegal yet?&quot; Chekov said, &quot;Just a minute&quot;, and consulted the relevant Schedules to the <cite>Narcotic Control Act </cite>and the <cite>Food and Drug Act</cite>. Chekov told Kirk that he did not see dilithium listed anywhere. Kirk then obtained a supply of what he took to be dilithium from Rand, who used to be his main wholesale provider of cocaine.
<p>
Three days later, R.C.M.P. Constable McCoy was conducting an undercover operation on Enterprise Avenue, a well-known drug dealing area. He saw Spock hanging around, and asked him, &quot;Where can a guy get some coke around here?&quot; Spock directed McCoy to the outdoor patio of a nearby donut shop. Several suspicious looking persons, including Kirk, were sitting at the tables. McCoy approached Kirk, who appeared to be asleep, and said, &quot;How much for an 8-ball of coke?&quot; Kirk said, &quot;Got no coke; you want dilithium?&quot; McCoy said, &quot;Sure&quot;, and purchased 50 g of white powder. On analysis, the white powder turned out to be cocaine after all.
<p>
Kirk and Spock are charged with trafficking in cocaine. Kirk says that he was extremely drunk when the transaction occurred. He was an inexperienced drinker, and had consumed roughly half a bottle of Saurian brandy that day. He has some vague recollection of speaking with McCoy, but does not recall handing over the white powder or receiving any money for it. Spock says that he knew that Enterprise Avenue was a drug dealing area, but he did not know that Kirk was at the donut shop. He says he was meeting his girlfriend Uhura, and that he told McCoy about the donut shop just to get rid of him before Uhura arrived.
<p>
&quot;Dilithium&quot; is the street name for diethylproprion, which is a controlled drug under the <cite>Food and Drug Act. </cite>Section 39 of the Act makes it an offense to &quot;traffic&quot; (defined in s. 38) in a controlled drug. Cocaine is a narcotic under the <cite>Narcotic Control Act. </cite>Section 4 of the Act makes it an offense to &quot;traffic&quot; (defined in s. 2) in a narcotic.
<p>
What is the criminal liability of Kirk and Spock?
<p>
