<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-1995<br>
April 1995<br>
CRIMINAL LAW E<br>
Examiner: Professor Dickens</h2></center><p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<blockquote>
You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
Answer <b>BOTH</b> of the following questions.
</blockquote>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<blockquote>
The questions do <b>NOT</b> carry equal weight.<br>
Question 1 carries 55% of the grade.<br>
Question 2 carries 45% of the grade.<br.
Proportion the time you spend on each appropriately.<p>
At the conclusion of this examination, you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and any coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE</b>.<p>
Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their
examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<hr><p>
<B>Question 1 (Counting for 55 percent of the total mark)</b><p>
AB is a strong advocate of a woman's right to choose abortion, and is upset at statements from the Vatican that require that, in observance of their moral duty, legislators ensure that the law of their jurisdictions punishes abortion unless justified on narrowly defined grounds. AB joined several friends to attend divine service at a local Roman Catholic church where they believed the sermon would urge obedience to recent Vatican pronouncements. The church is an historic, wooden-fitted structure with a sizable upper gallery accessed only by a circular wooden staircase. Older members of the congregation meet here to obtain a clear view of the service while seated. AB and several friends sat in front pews, below the pulpit, concealing in their clothes small signs and leaflets they intended to exhibit and scatter at a point in the sermon that CD, a colleague of AB's, would indicate. AB believed that other protesters might be present in the church, but did not want to be part of anything more than dignified dissent and giving of information.
<p>
As the priest entered the pulpit, AB, CD and colleagues readied themselves to show dissent. In the pulpit, the priest took a sip of water and cleared his throat when a loud bang and a bright flash of light came from the back of the upper gallery. CD said loudly to AB &quot;The fools! They brought fire bombs and people could get hurt in here!&quot;
<p>
AB rushed forward to the rear stairway to the pulpit and mounted it shouting at the priest &quot;Stop the sermon! Stop the sermon! Someone could be hurt because of this!&quot; As AB entered the pulpit, the concealed signs and leaflets fell loose, and some floated down among the first pews. Then an authoritative voice from the gallery shouted &quot;It's O.K. It's just a blown fuse. We'll carry on with just a few of the lights out.&quot; AB, CD and their colleagues, in some confusion and disarray, left the church before the service resumed.
<p>
The priest, shaken by AB's approach and shouting, and distressed at the materials of protest AB had brought into the church, complained to the police.
<p>
AB has been charged with the offense, contrary to section s.176(1)(b) of the Criminal Code, of assaulting or offering violence to a minister of religion on his way to perform a function in connection with his calling.
<p>
Explain, with legal reasons, how you would defend AB against conviction.
<p>
<b>NOTE:</b><blockquote>You have not been given precise wording of the indictment, and should not raise such procedural matters as whether it is void for vagueness. Apply the facts to the words of s.176, and explain your defence strategy.</blockquote>
<p>
<b>Question 2 (Counting for 45 percent of the total mark)</b><p>
Section 8 of the Endangered Birds Act of Ontario [<b>Note:</b> This is a fictitious Act] provides that &quot;Whoever is found without lawful authority on lands designated as protected for the preservation of endangered birds commits a summary offense punishable on first conviction by a fine of up to $5,000 and/or six months' imprisonment, and on second or later conviction by a fine of up to $20,000 and/or twelve months' imprisonment, but not less than four times the greatest fine imposed on any earlier conviction but not to exceed $50,000.&quot;
<p>
RS, an unemployed forester, had pleaded guilty to the offence under s.8 several months ago, and was fined $1,000, which he gathered with difficulty with the support of friends. He admitted to entering a designated area to find rare eggs that he could sell, illegally, for up to $50 each.
<p>
Following conviction, RS carefully studied lands designated under the Act, and found that a narrow wedge of land in Northern Ontario, in the breeding grounds of some unusual birds, had not been designated.
<p>
RS traveled to the area on April 7th, 1995, marked out the boundaries of the undesignated lands, and proposed to search for eggs the next morning. On that morning, however, his bad back ached too much, so he fished all day by a stream and listened to music on his radio. Unknown to RS, on the afternoon of April 7th, the provincial Minister of Natural Resources had announced that the Ontario Gazette to be released the next day would declare that, from April 9th, 1995, some land omitted by oversight from coverage under the Act would become designated, including that discovered by RS. Late in the afternoon of April 9th, when RS returned to his campsite with eight eggs in a container, he was arrested by two wardens.
<p>
RS has now been charged with the offense contrary to s.8 of the Act.
<p>
Explain the legal grounds on which you would conduct his defense.
<p>
<b>NOTE:</b><blockquote>You have not been given precise wording of the information, and should not address such procedural matters as vaqueness.</blockquote>
<p>
<hr>
