<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994 -95<br<
April 1995<br>
CRIMINAL LAW-SMALL GROUP F<br>
Examiner Professor Friedland</h2></center><p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<blockquote>
Students may use annotated copies of the Criminal Code, the Casebook, and their notes. The value of each question, <b>totaling 100 marks </b>and the approximate time available for each question, is noted in the margin.<p>
At the conclusion of the examination, you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and coats and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE. ALSO. IF YOU USE MORE THAN ONE BOOKLET PLEASE INSERT ALL BOOKLETS INTO BOOKLET NO. 1.</b><p>
Time limits will be enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<hr><p>
<b>45 MARKS<br>
(approximately 1 hour is available for this question)</b><p>
1. Jones is a recently escaped convict from Kingston Penitentiary. He manages to get to Toronto and calls on his old partner-in-crime, Smith. Smith had recently been released from Kingston. Jones tells Smith that he wants to shoot the Crown Attorney who most recently
put him behind bars and that if Smith won't drive him to the Crown's
residence, he, Jones, may turn his anger towards Smith. Smith
says he doesn't want to do it. In any event, Smith says, he has
been having serious epileptic fits every few weeks and, moreover,
has been on a dunking binge for the past few days. Jones takes
out a .38 handgun and says, &quot;perhaps this will persuade you.&quot;
Smith then agreed to drive the car.
<P>
When they got to the Crown's residence, Smith acted as a lookout
while Jones entered the house and shot the Crown. Smith helped
him place the body in a trunk, which they carried to the car and
dumped into Lake Ontario. As it turned out, the trunk did not
sink and was recovered by a sailor who discovered that the Crown
was still alive. The sailor pulled the trunk into the boat and
headed for the main dock. Unfortunately, in the panic, a ferry
boat hit the sailboat and the badly wounded Crown, according to
the Coroner, drowned.
<P>
Several weeks later, Jones was spotted by the police in a bar.
He was immediately arrested for escaping from the Penitentiary
and was placed in a cell at the Don Jail awaiting his court appearance.
An undercover officer was placed in the cell next to him. The
police suspected that Jones had been responsible for the Crown's
murder. A witness living next to the Crown had picked out Jones
(from a collection of photographs) as the person he thinks he
saw ringing the Crown's doorbell. During a conversation with Jones,
the undercover officer asked Jones whether he knew what had happened
to the Crown, stories of which had been in the papers for the
past few weeks. Jones said he &quot;could say a lot about it,
but was keeping mum.&quot;
<P>
The police then charged Jones with the first-degree murder of
the Crown. The police warned Jones that he didn't have to say
anything and could get a lawyer if he wanted. Before they could
say anything about legal aid, Jones said he didn't need a lawyer,
as they only make things worse. He then admitted that he was involved.
He hadn't meant to shoot the Crown, he said, but only to scare
him. But the first thing the Crown said was: &quot;You dumb jailbird.
You'll be back in Kingston before you know it.&quot; Jones says
he then instinctively shot the Crown in the chest. Jones also
told the police about Smith's role in the episode.
<P>
The police went to Smith's residence and arrested him for first
degree murder. While there, they looked in a bedroom dresser drawer
and found a watch with the Crown's name engraved on the back.
Smith asked for a lawyer, but on the way to the police station
to meet the lawyer, Smith volunteered, without prompting or questioning, that he was forced to go along with what Jones wanted and, in
any event, he, Smith, couldn't think straight at the time because
of his drinking and his epileptic fits.
<P>
You are an articling student in the Crown Attorney's office in
Toronto. Both Jones and Smith say, through their lawyers, that
they are willing to plead guilty to manslaughter and take their
chances on the sentence. Advise the Crown whether she should accept
the pleas.
<P>
<hr><p>
<B>30 MARKS<br>
(approx. 40 minutes are available for this question).</b>
<P>
2. Assume that the government of Ontario has just passed an Act,
the <cite>Assisting Death Act</cite>. Dr. Green has been treating a
60-year old man, Mr. Frank, who has advanced lung cancer. The
Ontario Act says that &quot;it is legal for a doctor to provide
[certain deadly pills set out by regulation] at the written and
notorized request of any patient who, in the doctor's opinion,
is suffering from a fatal illness and has less than six months
to live.&quot; Another section makes it a summary conviction offence
to assist in causing death in any other manner. The possible penalty
is a fine of $10,000, without the possibility of imprisonment.
<P>
Dr. Green called the Department of Health and asked whether Drug
X was on the list. The Deputy Minister's secretary said that she
had recently seen a regulation adding the drug to the list. Dr.
Green administered the drug intravenously and Mr. Frank died.
Drug X is, in fact, not on the list. The secretary was mistaken.
As it turned out, Dr. Green administered Drug Y (Not Drug X),
which also is not on the permitted list. He had asked for Drug
X, but the pharmacy had given him Drug Y.
<P>
Dr. Green was then charged with &quot;assisting in causing death&quot;
by administering a drug, not on the designated list under the
<cite>Assisting Death Act.</cite> The Crown contends that this is an
absolute liability offence and, in any event, the doctor can't
&quot;administer&quot; the drug, but can only &quot;provide&quot;
it to the patient.
<P>
You are a junior lawyer in Eddie Greenspan's office and have been
asked to prepare a memo on whether Dr. Green will be convicted
under the <cite>Assisting Death Act</cite> and, if prosecuted, whether
he might later have a &quot;double jeopardy&quot; defence or any
other defence to a charge of &quot;aiding or abetting a person
to commit suicide&quot; under s.241(b) of the <cite>Criminal Code.</cite>
<P><hr><p>
<b>25 MARKS<br> (a little under 35 minutes are available for
this question)</B>
<P>
3. You are a young lawyer in the Department of Justice in Ottawa.
The Minister of Justice, Allan Rock, is considering bringing in
a new <cite>Criminal Code</cite> and has asked you to prepare a short
memo on what the government should do about <b>two</b> of the
following three issues:
<blockquote>
(A) omissions<br>
(B) provocation<br>
(C) capital murder
</blockquote>
Please prepare the memo.
<P><hr><p>
You get half a bonus mark if you can spot two out of the three
following quotes and a full mark if you can spot all three. Identifying
the subject area is satisfactory, if you can't remember the name
of the case.
<blockquote>
A. &quot;idea, while in Lima, Peru, that he had astro-travelled
back to Vancouver&quot;
<P>
B. &quot;no supply of food, except two 1-lb tins of turnips&quot;
<P>
 C. &quot;Did you shoot Morris Mayzel?&quot;
</blockquote>
<p><hr>
