<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>FINAL EXAMINATIONS, 1995<br>
DEBT FINANCING AND RESTRUCTURING<br>
Examiner: Mr. Murphy</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>Note:</h3>
<blockquote>
This is a 24 hour take home exam. It must be picked up between 9:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. or 2:30 p.m. to 4:30 p.m. Monday to Thursday from April 10th to April 27th, 1995. Since the University is closed on Friday, April 14th, 1995 the exam may not be picked up on Thursday, April 13th. Thursday, April 27th will be the last day to pick up this exam. You may refer only to the materials for the course (the casebooks and the documents distributed in class) and your class notes. The purpose of the take home format is <b>not</b> to encourage lengthy responses but to give you an opportunity to provide organized, thoughtful and succinct analyses of the issues raised in each question.<p>
Your responses to both questions 1 and 2 should not in aggregate exceed 2,500 words.<p>
Your answers to Questions 1 and 2 are each worth 1/2 of your grade.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>
<b>QUESTION 1</b>
<p>
With reference to the law and economics theory of agency, analyze how the following entities have dealt with (or have attempted to deal with) the inherent risks or conflicts between shareholders, directors and creditors (secured and unsecured) of a corporation which academics have identified in the literature in this area:
<blockquote>
(a) borrowers and lenders entering into relationships for borrowed money or credit in the market place; and<p>
	(b)	courts;
</blockquote>
Explain how, in your view, each of those entities described in (a) and (b) above have, or have not, contributed to the rational control of those so-called risks or conflicts.
<P>
<b>QUESTION 2</b>
<P>
To what extent, if at all, in your view do the federal statutory
regimes for corporate debt reorganization in Canada (the <cite>Companies
Creditors Arrangement Act</cite> and the <cite>Bankruptcy and Insolvency
Act</cite>) adequately protect the respective interests of:
<blockquote>
 (a) senior secured creditors<br>
 (b) bondholders (assume, for purposes of your response, that
the bondholders have a second and subordinate charge over the assets
of the corporate debtor)<br>
 (c) unsecured creditors<br>
 (d) shareholders
</blockquote>
of an insolvent corporation with assets, the realizable value
of which are insufficient to repay in full all of the stakeholders
identified in (a), (b), (c) and (d) above. To the extent that
you feel there are any inadequacies, please explain how you think
those inadequacies should be dealt with.
<P>
<hr>
