<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95, April 1995<br>
EVIDENCE: OPTION (a)<br>
Examiner: Professor Stewart</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>NOTES:</h3><blockquote>1. This is the examination based on the fact situation handed out in advance. This is an open-book examination. You may use any of the following materials during the test: the casebook, the fact situation, a <cite>Criminal Code</cite>, and any notes or summaries. You may not use any textbooks or library materials during the test.
<p>
2. The examination is composed of FOUR questions, which are NOT of equal value. Please allocate your time accordingly.
<p>
3. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and number of the booklet on <b>each </b>examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request one or more additional booklet during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.
<p>
4. During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within 15 minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<p>
5. At the conclusion of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>ALL EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b>
<p>
6. Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<p>
You are Janeway J., presiding over Worf's trial on the charge of first degree murder in the death of Sarjenka. Rule on the following questions.
<p>
<b>Question 1.</b> (30 marks)
<p>
Is Troi a competent and compellable witness for the prosecution?
<p>
<b>Question 2.</b> (30 marks)
<p>
Assume that Kheylar is not available to testify because she cannot be compelled to travel to Canada. May the Crown put into evidence the phone conversation between Worf and Kheylar (pp. 4-5)?
<p>
<b>Question 3.</b> (20 marks)
<p>
Assume that you have found no <cite>Charter </cite>violation in the conduct of the line-up (p. 8), and that, pursuant to s. 16 of the <cite>Canada Evidence Act</cite>, you have found Wesley incompetent to testify. Is Wesley's identification of Worf (pp. 4 and 8) admissible through Beverly, Odo, and Kira?
<p>
<b>Question 4.</b> (20 marks)
<p>
May Riker testify as to Worf's statements during counselling (p. 3)?
<P>
