</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95, April 1995</h2></center>
DATE: WEDNESDAY 19 APRIL<br>
TIME: 9:30 a.m. - 12:30 p.m.<br>
<center><h2>EVIDENCE: OPTION (b)<br>
Examiner: Professor Stewart</h2></center>
<h3>NOTES:</h3><blockquote>1. This is the standard open-book examination. You may use any of the following materials during the test: the casebook, a <cite>Criminal Code</cite>, and any notes or summaries. You may not use any textbooks or library materials during the test.<p>
2. The examination consists of TWO questions relating to one fact situation. The two questions are of equal value, but Question 2 is divided into four parts that are not of equal value. Please allocate your time accordingly.<p>
3. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and number of the booklet on <b>each </b>examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request one or more additional booklet during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
4. During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within 15 minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
5. At the conclusion of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>ALL EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS ARE TO BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE AND WILL BE COLLECTED BY THE INVIGILATOR.</b><p>
6. Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<b>Question 1.</b> (50 marks)
<blockquote>
NOTE: In answering this question, DO NOT consider the additional facts provided in Question 2.</blockquote>
You are the Crown attorney responsible for the prosecution of Bernard. Based on the following information, write a memorandum to your file analyzing the evidentiary issues that are likely to arise in the trial.
<p>
One Saturday evening in 1994, at about 11:45 p.m., Bernard boarded a northbound subway train at Queen station. At the next stop (Dundas station), three young men, Jeff, Larry, and Malcolm, boarded the train. What happened next is disputed, but before the train had reached College station, Bernard had shot Malcolm with a .44 calibre handgun. Larry and Bernard got off at College and fled in different directions. Meanwhile, Jeff had pushed the yellow emergency strip. An ambulance arrived and took Malcolm (and Jeff) to Toronto General hospital, where Malcolm died.
<p>
Tuvok is the officer in charge of the investigation into Malcolm's death. By 1:00 a.m., Bernard had been arrested and charged with second degree murder in Malcolm's death. Tuvok properly advised him of his right to counsel and gave him a chance to use a phone. Bernard spoke to duty counsel and declined to say anything to Tuvok. He was then placed in a cell with Paris, a charming, roguish street-level drug dealer who had just been arrested. Paris had had numerous dealings with the police in the past, both as an informer and as an accused. In particular, he had acted as an informant in a successful prosecution some years before. Tuvok had not told Paris anything about Bernard, and had not asked Paris to obtain a statement from Bernard, but he was hoping that Paris's charm would make Bernard open up a bit. Tuvok's plan succeeded. After some preliminary chit-chat, Paris said to Bernard, &quot;So, why don't you tell me how a nice guy like you ended up in a place like this?&quot; The following exchange then occurred:
<dl>
<dt>Bernard: <dd>I was sitting on the subway, minding my own business, when these three young punks approached me, with their hands in their pockets, and asked me for $5. I was really frightened; I thought they were going to kill me. I said, &quot;I don't have any money for you,&quot; whereupon one of them [later identified as Malcolm] took a handgun from under his coat and said, &quot;Maybe now you can find some&quot;. The other two looked surprised, and another one [Jeff] said, &quot;Where did you get that?&quot; We all tried to stop the one with the gun; we were not successful in restraining him, but the gun fell to the floor. I picked up the gun and, seeing [Malcolm] draw a knife, fired in his direction. The bullet must have struck him. At College station, I simply panicked at the thought of having shot someone, so I ran away.
<p>
<dt>Paris: <dd>What made you think they were going to kill you?
<p>
<dt>Bernard: <dd>Well, just last year I was robbed of $50 cash and all my credit cards by three young punks with knives, and in 1993 I was beaten up by two hoods when I was out jogging; they were mad because I wasn't carrying any money. And in 1990 I had my watch stolen at gunpoint just outside the Eaton Centre.
<p>
<dt>Paris: <dd>Did you report any of these offenses to the police?
<p>
<dt>Bernard: <dd>No, of course not. I don't have any insurance, so what's the point? Those guys never solve these property crimes anyway.
<p>
<dt>Paris: <dd>What happened to the gun?
<p>
<dt>Bernard: <dd>I threw it into the Don River.
</dl>
Paris reported this conversation to Tuvok, and a .44 calibre handgun was immediately recovered from the Don. Ballistics experts at the Centre for Forensic Sciences have since determined that the bullet in Malcolm's body came from that gun.
<p>
Early the next day, Tuvok went to Bernard's house and introduced himself to Bernard's wife Adele. Bernard and Adele have been happily married for years. When Tuvok told her that Bernard had been charged with second degree murder, she said, &quot;I'm sure he couldn't have done a thing like that; but if he did, I'm certainly not going to stay with him.&quot; Adele told him that Bernard owned a handgun, &quot;the same as the one Clint Eastwood carries in the 'Dirty Harry' movies&quot;. Tuvok then showed her the gun recovered from the Don River. Adele said that it might be Bernard's gun, but she was not sure.
<p>
That afternoon, Tuvok interviewed Jeff and Larry, and they gave him the following statements. These statements were recorded on audio tape, and at the beginning of each tape, Tuvok can be heard saying to the witnesses, &quot;You are going to tell me the truth, aren't you, because you know that it's a very serious matter to mislead the police in an investigation.&quot;
<p>
Larry says that the three of them were returning to their homes in Scarborough after going to see &quot;Forrest Gump&quot; at the Eaton Centre. He says that they were sitting on the subway, minding their own business, when Bernard approached them and began waving a handgun around, shouting obscenities. The three then got up and Malcolm reached for the yellow strip. Before Malcolm could press the strip, Bernard shot him. Larry says that he fled the scene at College station because he has in the past been hassled by the police for no reason, and he was afraid they would think he had something to do with the shooting.
<p>
Jeff's statement generally supports Larry's, but he recalls the movie as being &quot;Pulp Fiction&quot;. He says that when they boarded the subway at Dundas, he and Larry sat down, but that Malcolm stood near Bernard and &quot;sort of hovered over him.&quot; He was talking to Larry when he heard Bernard yelling at Malcolm; he then stood up and saw Bernard shoot Malcolm as Malcolm was reaching for the yellow strip. He remained with Malcolm because he was really worried about him.
<p>
Each of Larry and Jeff denies that he was armed. Neither of them saw Malcolm carrying any weapons, either. Tuvok showed Jeff and Larry the gun recovered from the Don, and each said that he had never seen Malcolm carrying it.
<p>
<b>Question 2.</b> (50 marks)
<p><blockquote>
	NOTE:	This question assumes that certain pieces of evidence
		presented in Question 1 are admissible. Please maintain
		that assumption, even if, in answering Question 1, you
		have reached a different conclusion. You will need to
		refer back to the facts presented in Question 1 to answer
		this question.
</blockquote>
You are the judge presiding over Bernard's trial. Defence counsel has advised you that Bernard is not going to testify. Rule on the following questions.
<p>
(i) (15 marks) During his examination in chief, Larry has testified that he saw the butt of a gun protruding from Malcolm's waistband when they left the movie, and that Malcolm, alone, approached Bernard and asked for $5. He has testified that he does not know whether Malcolm drew the gun, but he maintains that Bernard shot Malcolm. Crown counsel has cross-examined Larry on his earlier statement, but Larry has refused to adopt it. Crown counsel wants you to tell the jury that they can consider the earlier statement for its truth; defense counsel submits that the statement should go only to Jeff's credibility. How do you rule?
<p>
(ii) (20 marks) Defence counsel wants to call Dr Selar, a psychiatrist, who will give her opinion that Bernard suffers from &quot;paranoid urban anomie&quot;. According to Dr Selar, people who suffer from this condition tend to perceive any personal contact on the street or on public transit as a physical threat, especially late at night. The greater the number of people who approach, the greater the threat will appear to be. The sufferer will often invent, and then come to believe, a story of threatened assault or attempted robbery to justify his or her response to the perceived threat. Dr Selar has written extensively about this condition and has appeared as an expert in a number of other trials. She has based her opinion on a number of interviews with Bernard, on interviews with Bernard's father and with Adele, and on a standard psychological test. In the interviews, Bernard repeated the statement he gave to Paris. If Dr Selar testifies, the Crown proposes to call Dr Piper, who will testify that the psychiatric community does not recognize &quot;paranoid urban anomie&quot; as a valid diagnosis, that Dr Selar is the only psychiatrist who has ever written on it, and that even if &quot;paranoid urban anomie&quot; does exist, Bernard is not suffering from it. Dr Piper's opinion regarding Bernard is based on Bernard's statement to Paris and on interviews with Adele. Will you permit the jury to hear Dr Selar's and Dr Piper's evidence?
<p>
(iii) (10 marks) Defense counsel has discovered that Malcolm was twice charged with assaulting subway patrons. He was acquitted both times, but defense counsel has located the victims of Malcolm's alleged assaults. Each is prepared to testify that Malcolm robbed them at knife-point on the subway. Crown counsel submits that the alleged victims should not be allowed to testify. How do you rule?
<p>
(iv) (5 marks) Crown counsel has completed her charge to the jury, and has told them that Bernard's gun must have been a .44 calibre, because that is what Clint Eastwood carries in the &quot;Dirty Harry&quot; movies. Defence counsel has objected to this statement, because the Crown has not offered any evidence to prove anything about the &quot;Dirty Harry&quot; movies. What should you do?
<p>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
Please send comments and suggestions to <a href="mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</a><p>
Created on AUG-14-95 by Anne Johnston.
</address>
