<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95<br>
FAMILY LAW<br>
Examiner: Philip M. Epstein</h2></center>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<blockquote>
1. You may use any kind of material you wish during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts, except books owned by the library.<p>
2. The exam is composed of one fact situation and five questions which are of different values. The suggested time allocation and values are indicated at the end of the question.<p>
3. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
4. During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
5. At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b><p>
6. Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<P>
 1. Tom and Jessica met in Ohio in early 1980 when Tom was 27
and Jessica was 25. It was a second marriage for Tom and the first for Jessica.
Tom was divorced in California in 1978. Tom and Jessica fell instantly
in love and moved in together in November of 1980, into a home owned by Tom on Scott
Street in Cleveland. Tom had inherited this home from his grandfather in
1970. In December of 1980 and for at least two years thereafter, it was
worth $200,000.00 (Canadian) and it had a mortgage on it of $60,000.00,
the monies from which Tom had used to pay for his university education. On
September 8, 1982 Jessica announced she was pregnant and the couple made plans
to marry. On December 1, 1982, they married at St. Grace's Church in Cleveland.
Tom and Jessica continued to live in the Scott Street home until the
baby, Martin, was born in July of 1982. In August of 1985, Tom's employer asked
Tom to take an interest in and to head up the Canadian division of Widget Works
Inc. and, thus, Tom and Jessica moved to Toronto to take up permanent residence.
The initially had trouble selling the Scott Street home, but eventually
it sold in December, 1985, for $190,000.00. Tom used the net proceeds of
$140,000.00, (the mortgage had been paid down somewhat) to buy a home on Bilton
Street in Toronto for $210,000.00. Tom guaranteed a mortgage of $70,000.00
to make up the difference in the purchase price. Tom, on the advice of
his U.S. attorney, put the new home in Jessica's name to protect him if the new business
venture failed. On February 1, 1995, the property had a value of $240,000.00
and the mortgage has been paid down to $58,000.00. However, a development
has occurred with respect to the home that troubles Tom. The city
counsel has proposed a rezoning of Bilton Street and the unusual rezoning
proposal will, if it is approved, dramatically increase the value of all of the
properties on the street. Jessica's friend, Amy, a real estate agent, has told Tom
and Jessica that the change will improve the value of the home by $100,000.00.
The vote at city council is expected in about six months and, apparently, council
is narrowly in favour of the rezoning.
<P>
Tom and Jessica had a break-in at the home one year ago and the
damage claim has not yet been settled, but Jessica expects a cheque
shortly for the full amount, less her deductible of $2,000.00.
Some vandals did about $30,000.00 worth of damage while Tom and
Jessica were on a short holiday and Jessica has made a claim on
her home insurance policy. Tom paid for the repairs out of his
savings.
<P>
Tom has an RRSP of $60,000.00 as of February 1, 1995 and Jessica
has a spousal RRSP that Tom paid for of $30,000.00 as of the same
date.
<P>
Since moving to Toronto the Canadian widget business has prospered
and Tom increased his stake in the business to 75% in 1993. At
that time the business had a value of $500,000.00 and has probably
increased by February 1, 1995 to $600,000.00. Because of the success,
Tom is considering buying out the remaining 25% interest which
his partner is willing to sell for $150,000.00.
<P>
Tom had a car worth $8,000.00 and some furnishings worth $3,000.00
at the time of the marriage. He also had a student loan of $16,000.00
at the time of marriage, but he repaid it in March of 1983 when
he received a gift from his father of a $50,000.00 Canada Savings
Bond. Tom used $16,000.00 of that bond to pay down the loan, $5,000.00
for a holiday and $9,000.00 for two skidoos which have long since
been discarded. The balance was used by Tom to purchase an Ontario
Savings long term bond which, with accumulated interest. was worth
$44.000.00 on February 1, 1995.
<P>
In 1991, Tom's father died, leaving Tom the family cottage on
the shores of Lake Woebegone in Ohio. The cottage was worth then
and is worth now $80,000.00 Canadian. Jessica suffers from arachnaphobia
and, thus, has never been there.
<P>
Tom collects antiques and, over the years, has filled the home
with small, but valuable pieces. He believes the antiques in the
home have a value of at least $30,000.00.
<P>
Tom received $60,000.00 of life insurance proceeds from Mutual
Life on the death of his father in 1991. Tom spent $20,000.00
of the insurance monies to build a pool at the matrimonial home
and the balance for a 1994 Lincoln which he registered in Jessica's
name. The car is now worth $28,000.00.
<P>
At the time of marriage, Jessica also had a student loan of $6,000.00.
Jessica was a beneficiary of a trust created by her great grandfather
in 1940 and she was entitled to receive $25,000.00 when she reached
age 30. She also had a diamond pendant given to her by her grandmother
that was valued at $8,000.00.
<P>
Jessica sold the diamond pin in 1984 and used the proceeds to
pay off the student loan and the balance for some orthodonture
work. She received the trust proceeds of $25,000.00 in 1985 and
invested it in the stock market until her chosen stocks increased
in value to $35,000.00 by 1994. In early 1994, she sold the stock,
took the $35,000.00 and bought 2 paintings for the home, each
worth about $17,500.00. Unfortunately, one has turned out to be
a forgery and is worthless and the other is now worth about $20,000.00.
<P>
Jessica, unexpectedly, won $20,000.00 in Lottario last year and
used $12,000.00 for an expensive holiday to Paris and Rome for
her and Tom in a desperate attempt to save the marriage. The balance
is still in her bank account.
<P>
Tom and Jessica now have two children, Martin, aged 12 and Diane,
aged 8. Martin has serious asthma and severe learning disabilities,
but has managed to keep up in school as a result of both parties'
strenuous efforts with him. Diane is in a gifted children's programme
in school and is doing well there.
<P>
Jessica was studying at Art School when she married and hoped
to be an art therapist upon graduation. As a result of Martin's
health problems, she did not complete her last 6 courses and never
graduated. She would like to do so, but it would now require her
to go back to school for at least two years. Upon graduation,
she would have reasonable prospects for employment starting at
about $30,000.00 per year. She has occasionally helped Tom at
his office and has been very active entertaining his clients and
business executives.
<P>
Tom earns about $120,000.00 per year, plus some benefits. He is
a devoted father, but he has allowed the pressures of work to
interfere with the time he has had for both children and for Jessica.
This has become a significant source of tension in the home. In
her loneliness last year, Jessica turned elsewhere and had an
affair with a neighbour. She was guilt ridden about it and confessed
it instantly to Tom. Tom was devastated. Try as he might, he could
not put it behind him and the parties' relationship deteriorated
drastically. Tom decided that there must be an immediate separation
and that Jessica should move out and leave Tom and the nanny to
look after the children. The nanny is also angry at Jessica and
has apparently sided with Tom. She has been with the family for
6 years. When Jessica would not move out, Tom moved to a separate
bedroom on February 1, 1995 and has remained in the home, but
has clearly been living separate and apart from Jessica in the
home since that date. Martin has indicated he would prefer living
with Tom and Diane has not voiced a preference. Jessica says Tom
has been pressuring Martin and plying him with gifts.
<P>
Jessica is determined to have custody of the children and, in
view of Tom's rigid stance, does not believe that cooperation
with him is possible. She is sick of Tom's accusations and, unfortunately,
is in a fighting mood. She no longer sees any hope for reconciliation.
<P>
Jessica has come to see you and has asked the following questions.
Because her uncle is a lawyer in Ottawa, she wishes you to give
her a detailed, written response so that she can show your reasoning
to her uncle.
<P>
<b>The suggested time for dealing with the following questions is
as follows:</b>
<P>
Reading and analyzing the facts: 30 minutes
<P>
<center><table cellspacing = 10 cellpadding = 10>
<tr><td> 1.<br>2.<br>3.<br>4.<br>5.</td>
<td> 50 minutes<br> 25 minutes<br> 25 minutes<br> 30 minutes<br> 20 minutes</td>
<td>35 marks<br>17.5 marks<br>10 marks<br>20 marks<br>17.5 marks</td>
</tr></table></center>
<p>
<ol>
 <li> What is the likely result of <U>all</U> property claims <U>either</U>
party could assert and why?
<P>
<li> What is the likely result of the custody dispute and why?
<P>
<li> What steps could Jessica take in these particular circumstances
to try to resolve the custody dispute?
<P>
<li> Assuming that Jessica gets custody, is she entitled to child
and spousal support and if so, for how long and why?
<P>
<li> What single change would you introduce to any family law statute
that would either simplify or make it easier for Tom and Jessica to
resolve their dispute?
</ol>
For each question, explain your answer and in so doing, identify
the relevant statutory provisions and/or significant judicial
decisions which are relevant to the question. You may make up
or assume any additional facts necessary to answer the question
and where doing so, You should identify the additional facts or
assumptions.
<p>
