<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-1995, APRIL 1995<br>
TAKE-HOME EXAMINATION<br>
INTERNATIONAL. TRADE. REGULATION SPRINGS 95</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>INSTRUCTIONS:</h3><blockquote> The Faculty of Law take home exam policy states, in part: &quot;It is expected that there will be consultation amongst students writing the same take home examination, although the answer or answers returned by the student must be organized and written by that student alone&quot;.
<p>
Students should pay particular attention to the need for a take home answer to be their own work. It must be &quot;organized and written by that student alone&quot;. Contravening this rule is an academic offence under the University's Code of Academic Conduct.
<p>
The Examination must be picked up from the Records Office during normal business hours and returned no more than 48 hours later. Your answer must be limited to 14 double-spaced typed pages or the equivalent. You must answer both questions.
</blockquote>
<hr>
<P>
60% 1. The government of Nordia, a country that resembles Canada
in most respects, enacts the Worker Solidarity Act. The Act is
apparently attended to encourage companies to engage in progressive
labour practices, particularly worker ownership or worker participation
on boards of directors. A subsidy per worker of a thousand dollars
per year is offered to any company that undertakes such innovations
in labour relations. In order to be eligible to receive the subsidy
a company must be certified by a government agency (the Worker
Participation Board or WPB) to have made sufficient adjustments
to its labour relations practices. As well, the Worker Solidarity
Act provides that any Nordian company that undertakes to purchase
imported goods only from countries that have labour laws permitting
or encouraging worker participation is entitled to a rebate of
any customs duty paid on those imports. So far, although the subsidy
is available in theory to any industry or firm in the economy,
the Worker Participation Board has only certified companies in
the widget industry as eligible (this is an industry until recently
in decline which has engaged in major restructuring, with worker
share ownership a significant ingredient in the restructuring).
With respect to the duty rebate, 15 countries have been formally
listed by the WPB as qualifying because their labour laws permit
or encourage worker participation (for the most part, European
countries that have responded to a complex questionnaire provided
by the WPB). The Act also states that any company found to be
purchasing any imported goods manufactured in any country that
does not respect &quot;basic international worker's rights and
environmental norms&quot; will be disqualified henceforth from
receiving a subsidy. Finally, where a country is found to &quot;repeatedly
and systematically repress free collective bargaining&quot; the
WBP may recommend to the Minister of International Trade that
all imports from that country into Nordia be prohibited. So far
this recommendation has been made twice. In both instances, no
prohibition was in fact instituted, since the countries in question
voluntarily undertook to improve labour practices, as well as
agreeing to limit by quotas exports to Nordia of products competing
with Canadian firms in &quot;sensitive&quot; sectors.
<P>
Consider any trade law concerns about the Worker Solidarity Act
that Nordia's trade partners might wish to raise.
<P>
40% 2. &quot;Today, sustaining rule-based global trade increasingly
requires harmonization or adjustment of what have traditionally
been understood as domestic policies. We face the choice of either
going forward towards a world political and economic community,
with common policies in a wide range of regulatory areas, or reverting
to wide-scale unilateral protectionism and beggarthy-neighbour
regulatory competition.&quot;
<P>
Discuss this proposition, in reflecting on any two of the following
areas of international trade law discussed in class:
<P>
Subsidies and Countervailing duties<br>
Trade, transition costs and labour policies<br>
Trade-Related Intellectual Property Rights<br>
Trade in Services<br>
Trade and Environment
<p>
