<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>Annual Examinations. 1994-95. April 1995<br>
LABOUR ARBITRATION<br>
Examiner: Professor Schiff</h2></center><p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
1. This examination is composed of three parts. The approximate time you should spend on each part is indicated, and marks will be allocated correspondingly. The fact situation occurs in Ontario.<p>
2. Parts I and II involve stages in the hearing and determination of one grievance. Therefore, at least read part I before you write an answer in part II.<p>
3. You should have with you in the examination room a copy of the Appendix to the seminar materials. This may contain underlining or highlighting, but shall not otherwise contain any notes or other examination aids of any kind.
4. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <I>each </I>examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If you request additional booklets during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
5. During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
6. At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</B><p>
7. Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their answer booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
<P>
<center>I<br>(30 minutes)</center>
<P>
You are chairing a board created to arbitrate a grievance between
Pound Press Ltd. and Local 701 of the United Printers of America
The grievor is Ron Broder. The written grievance, filed with the
board at the opening of the hearing, reads: &quot;On December
2, the foreman ordered me to work through my lunch break and over
the Employment Standards Act limit. I left because I don't have
to do that. I want my job back and full pay and seniority.&quot;
The Pound Press third step reply, also filed with the board, reads:
&quot;The foreman asked Broder to stay on the job until relief
came. Broder refused, said he was quitting, and left the plant.
Since he voluntarily terminated his employment, he has no grievance.
<P>
After the formal grievance and the reply have been filed, counsel
to Pound Press says that the employer will defend the grievance,
not only on the ground of voluntary termination but also on the
ground that, if Broder did not quit, he was discharged for just
cause. Counsel to the union objects to the addition of the new
ground because, he argues, neither Pound Press nor its counsel
had earlier said that Broder had been discharged. Counsel to Pound
Press agrees that the alternative ground had not been mentioned
earlier.
<P>
Complete with reasons, set out the board's ruling responding to
the objection to Pound Press Ltd.'s proposal to defend on the
alternative ground.
<P>
<hr><p>
<center>II<br>(60 minutes)</center>
<P>
Without prejudice to what you set out in part I, assume that the
board has decided that Pound Press Ltd. may defend the grievance
on both grounds. Also assume that the facts set out below were
shown by the evidence introduced at the hearing. Deft the elaborated
award you conclude should be issued to determine the grievance.
<P>
Broder was hired in September 1990 and has been employed as a
packer on the day shift ever since. He has been a reasonably efficient
worker. Before the incident involved in this grievance, he had
been disciplined twice. He was given a written warning in April
1992 for coming in late twice in two weeks. And he was suspended
for one day without pay in January 1994 for careless packing resulting
in damage to a shipment. He did not grieve either time.
<P>
Early on the evening of December 1st, Leno Cevick, Broder's foreman,
telephoned him at his home telling him to report for work the
following morning at 7:30 a.m. instead of at the usual starting
time. A rush order for an important customer was being printed
that night and it had to be ready for shipping early the next
day. Situations like this had come up previously and, in Broder's
experience, packing of rush orders starting at 7:30 a.m. was usually
completed by noon.
<P>
On December 2nd, Broder and two other packers began the work at
7:30 a.m. Cevick told them that &quot;this is a rush order; you
must keep at it until it's ready to go out&quot;. The three packers
worked without a break but, since the order was bigger than Broder
had expected from experience, they were still not finished at
half-past twelve. At that moment Broder walked out of the shipping
room to retrieve his lunch pail from his locker. Seeing Broder
leave, Cevick ordered him to stay at the job until he (Cevick)
got someone else to fill in. Broder replied in an angry tone,
&quot;Nuts to that! It's past my lunch time. Why should I work
in this damned place if I can't eat?&quot; Cevick walked away
in the opposite direction without replying. Broder went to his
locker, put on his coat, took his lunch pail and went home. Within
ten minutes of the exchange with Broder, Cevick had arranged for
another packer to take over Broder's job on the rush order until
he had eaten lunch. Cevick looked for Broder in the plant, but
of course Broder was no longer there.
<P>
Cevick reported what had happened to the personnel office. In
mid-afternoon of December 2nd the personnel manager telephoned
Broder's home and told him that, since he had quit, he should
not come back to work. Several days later, Broder got in the mail
a cheque sent by the personnel office covering his pay for the
last days as well as accumulated vacation benefits. On Monday,
December 5th, Broder put in his formal grievance. Section 22 of
the Employment Standards Act says that &quot;[e]very employer
shall provide eating periods...at such intervals as will result
in no employee working longer than five consecutive hours without
an eating period...&quot;. Section 78 of the Act authorizes a
fine or imprisonment for violating any provision.
<P>
<hr><p>
<center>III<br>(60 minutes)</center>
<P>
Write an essay using one of the following as title and subject-matter.
Critically analyze the legal and arbitral doctrine and other relevant
considerations. If appropriate, also suggest desirable reform.
At the beginning of the essay please set out the title.
<ol>
<li> The Nature of the Arbitrator's Function.
<P>
<li> The Labour Arbitrator as Law-maker.
<P>
<li> Grievances Arising from Exercise of Management's Reserved Rights:
What Should Arbitrators Do?
<P>
<li> Labour Arbitration - An Institution for the Ongoing Elaboration
of the Collective Agreement.
</ol>
<p>
<hr>
<address>
Updated and maintained by the <a href="http://www.law-lib.utoronto.ca/">Bora Laskin Law Library</a>.<br>
Please send comments and suggestions to <a href="mailto:law.web@utoronto.ca">law.web@utoronto.ca</a><p>
Created on AUG-14-95 by Anne Johnston.
</address>
