<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<H2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95<BR>
LABOUR LAW<BR>
Examiner: Professor Langille</CENTER></H2>
<H3>NOTES:</H3>
<OL>
<LI><I>You may use the casebook, the supplement, statutes, other
course materials, and your own notes during the exam. Textbooks
are not permitted.</I>
<LI><I>There is only question. Please read it carefully and answer
it.</I>
<LI><I>Please try to write legibly and double space your answer.</I>
<LI><I>If you think you need further information to answer the
question state what it is and why you need it.</I>
<LI><I>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym,
course name, and the number of the booklet on <B>each</B> examination
booklet and the name of the instructor on the first booklet. If
you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write
the required information on the booklet at the time you receive
it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.</I>
<LI><I>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted
to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen
minutes of the conclusion of the examination.</I>
<LI><I>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask
you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used,
record this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all
booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings
and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets
are to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the
invigilator.</B></I>
<LI><I>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue
to write after the examination has ended will have their answer
booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.</I>
</OL>

<P>
Truro Auto Parts (TAP) is a manufacturer of car parts supplying
the major auto manufacturers in Ontario. It is a subsidiary of
a large U.S. auto parts firm. The Canadian Autoworkers (CAW) has
represented some 400 or so hourly paid production workers for
many years. The current collective agreement expires in 1996.
The plant works on a 3 shift, 24 hour, 7 days a week basis. Cito
Gasket is Human Resources Manager at the plant which is located
in Peterborough.
<P>
On advice of lawyers to its unorganized U.S. parent company, TAP
has recently announced that it will undertake measures to ensure
that it is complying with the Ontario Human Rights Code &quot;duty
to accommodate&quot; the various religious observance requirements
of the numerous religious groups represented in its workforce.
To this end it recently announced its intention to &quot; re-engineer&quot;
unilaterally the shift scheduling so as to accommodate these various
requirements. The collective agreement sets out the hours of the
various shifts and permits people to bid for the shift of their
choice based on seniority.
<P>
This move takes the CAW by surprise because the topic of religious
accommodation had been discussed during the last negotiations,
without ultimate success, but on the understanding that the matter
would be referred to a standing joint union/management committee
that has been in existence for years and whose purpose it is to
act as a place for discussion of issues of mutual concern during
the term of the collective agreement. (The collective agreement
provides for the setting up of the committee and also has a standard
management rights clause.)
<P>
As part of the plan TAP has circulated a questionnaire to employees
asking them to identify themselves as members of various religious
groups with special scheduling requirements.
<P>
The Union executive holds a meeting to respond to this management
initiative and to discuss strategy. They decide to tell the membership
not to fill out the questionnaire. They also decide to file a
grievance again &quot;management's insensitive and unilateral
actions&quot;.
<P>
The Union also takes their complaint about management's actions
to the next meeting of the Joint Union/Management Committee. At
that meeting Cito Gasket expressed some sympathy with the view
that perhaps management's actions were a bit sudden and undertook
to put the issue on the agenda for the next meeting of the Committee
as a priority item. Cito was fired the next day.
<P>
On the other hand, several union members have decided to fill
out the questionnaire and have, as a result, been fined under
the Union's constitution for contravening a provision that prohibits
&quot;actions designed to undermine union solidarity&quot;. This
action was approved at a lively union meeting by a majority vote.
These workers refuse to pay the Union fine and as a result are
expelled for such non-payment from the Union in accordance with
the union constitution. The collective agreement contains the
standard and required &quot;Rand Formula&quot; provision.
<P>
Meanwhile the Union has taken its grievance through the &quot;expedited&quot;
arbitration process set out in s. 46 of the Act and received a
quick decision from the arbitrator appointed by the Minister thereunder.
That arbitrator dismissed the grievance stating: &quot;This grievance
is a bad idea. What has this Union got against human rights? And
besides, haven't they read <CITE>Russelsteel</CITE>?&quot; Upon
receiving this decision, the day shift holds a spontaneous &quot;study
session&quot; to review the arbitrator's award and discuss its
impact. Production for that shift is lost.
<P>
ADVISE the Union, the Employer, and the employees identified about
their rights and obligations arising from these facts. In so doing,
describe fully and critically evaluate the legal predicaments
in which they find themselves.
<p>
<HR><p>
<ADDRESS>
