<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 199495, April 1995<br>
PATENT &amp; TRADE SECRETS LAW<br>
SITDOWN EXAMINATION<br>
Examiner: Donald M. Cameron</h2></center>
<P>
<h3>NOTE:</h3><blockquote>1. You may use any kind of material you wish during
the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts,
except books owned by the library.
<P>
2. The exam in composed of three questions, totalling 50
marks. The suggested time allocation is indicated in the margin.
<P>
3. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on
each examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the
fit booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during
the examination, write the required information on the booklet
at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the
end of the examination.
<P>
4. During the examination, only one student is permitted
to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen
minutes of the conclusion of the examination.
<P>
5. At the end of this examination, the invigilator will
ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record
this on the front of the first booklet, and insert all booklets
into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave
the examination room. <b>All examination answer booklets are
to be left on the writing table and will be collected by the invigilator.</b>
<P>
6. Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue
to write after the examination has ended will have their answer
booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</blockquote>
<p> 
1. Your client writes to you asking for your opinion and
advice:
<P>
Three years ago this month we applied for a Canadian Patent
for our SUPERBAG plastic bag. Last November we got our Canadian
patent. The claims and some of the drawings are attached.
<P>
The patent uses fancy patent language but what I meant to
patent was our grocery bag that comes with its sides all folded
inward (the patent calls it Inwardly gussetted&quot; which I think
is an OK description, just a little fancy). These things come
to the customer (like Loblaws) in a stack and they attach the
upper thingamajig (you called it the Separable support members
26) to a bracket and then you just tear off a bag each time you
need one. The outside pieces 28 and 30 become the ban's handles.
<P>
The claims also talk about our neat tearing system where the
handles are held to the &quot;separable support members 26 by
way of two ittybitty pieces of bag 36 and 38, on each side. The
patent calls them Spaced apart contact members&quot;.
<P>
I just found out Bags are Delightful (&quot;BAD&quot;) has
been making a bag like ours and selling it in Canada. There's
a drawing of their bag enclosed. It looks just like ours only
it just has regular perforations 30 between the side handles 18
and 26 and the separable support member 22  just like a tear line
on a ticket.
<P>
Oh, by the way they've been selling these since January 1994.
<P>
Based on this information, advise our client giving reasons
for your choices.
<P>
36 min <b>20 marks</b>
<P>
2. After advising your client in question 1, your client
writes you a letter:
<P>
Further to my last letter, I found out my dates were wrong.
They've been selling these since 1987.
<P>
How does this chance your earlier opinion?
<P>
Based on this information advise you client giving reasons
for your choices.
<P>
36 min <b>20 marks</b>
<P>
3. A classmate of yours has just completed a period of parttime
work at a commercial law firm. Your classmate tells you that she
has without obtaining permission from her employers, made copies
of memos and precedents (both of opinion letters and pleadings)
from the firm's precedent system and has asked you if you would
like a copy of them.
<P>
What liability does you classmate have for trade secret violations
or breaches of confidence? What liability do you have?
<P>
You answer should Five your conclusions and justified reasoning.
<P>
18 min <b>10 marks</b>
<P>
THE EMBODIMENTS OF THE INVENTION IN WHICH AN EXCLUSIVE PROPERTY
OR PRIVILEGE IS CLAIMED ARE DEFINED AS FOLLOWS:
<P>
1. A longitudinally tubular plastic bag structure comprising:
<blockquote>
(a) front and rear panels joined together along their top;
bottom and side edges
<P>
(b) inwardly gussetted side walls extending between said front
and rear panel top and bottom edges; and,
<P>
(c) an aperture extending through the upper, central region
of said panels to define a separable support member extending across the top edge of said aperture.
</blockquote>
2. A plastic bag structure as defined in claim 1, wherein
said aperture further extends through said gusseted side walls
to define a bag handle on each side of said aperture.
<P>
3. A plastic bag structure as defined in claim 2, further
comprising first and second perforations extending across said
support member at opposed ends thereof.
<P>
4. A plastic bag structure. as defined in claim 3, wherein
said first and second perforations each comprise at least two
spaced apart contact members joining said support member to said
handles.
<P>
5. A plastic bag structure as defined in claim 4, wherein
said first and second perforations are arranged to tear into said. support member.
<p>
