<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 199495, April 1995<br>
PATENT &amp; TRADE SECRETS LAW<br>
Examiner Donald M. Cameron<br>
TAKEHOME EXAMINATION</h2></center>
<P>
<B> NOTE:</B><blockquote>1. You may use any kind of material you wish
during the examination, for example, notes, the casebook, and texts,
except books owned by the library.
<P>
2. The exam in composed of three questions, totalling 50
marks.
<P>
3. Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on
<b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the
<b>first</b> booklet .
<P>
4. The maximum page length for the answers are question 1: 5 pages; question 2: 5 pages; question 3: 3
pages.
<P>
5. <B>Your answers should be returned to Mrs. Ward at the
Records Office at or before 9:30 on Thursday, April 20, 1995.</B>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<P>
<blockquote> 1. Your client writes to you asking for your opinion and
advice:
<P>
Three years ago this month we applied for a Canadian Patent
for our SUPERBAG plastic bag. Last November we got our Canadian
patent. The claims and some of the drawings are attached.
<P>
The patent uses fancy patent language but what I meant to
patent was our grocery bag that comes with its sides all folded
inward (the patent calls it &quot;inwardly gussetted&quot; which
I think is an OK description, just a little fancy). These things
come to the customer (like Loblaws) in a stack and they attach
the upper thingamajig (you called it the &quot;separable support
member&quot; 26) to a bracket and then you just tear off a bag
each time you need one. The outside pieces 28 and 30 become the
bag's handles.
<P>
The claims also talk about our neat tearing system where the
handles are held to the &quot;separable support member&quot; 26
by way of two ittybitty pieces of bag 36 and 38, on each side.
The patent calls them &quot;spaced apart contact members&quot;.
<P>
I just found out Bags are Delightful (&quot;BAD&quot;) has
been making a bag like ours and selling it in Canada. There's
a drawing of their bag enclosed. It looks just like ours only
it just has regular perforations 30 between the side handles 18
and 26 and the separable support member 22  just like a tear line
on a ticket.
<P>
Oh, by the way they've been selling these since January 1994.
</blockquote>
Based on this information, advise our client giving reasons
for your choices. <p>
<b>15 marks</B>
<P>
Discuss the remedies available to your client. <p>
<b>5 marks</B>
<P>
<blockquote>2. After advising your client in question 1, your client
writes you a letter:
<P>
&quot;Further to my last letter, I found out my dates were
wrong. They've been selling these since 1987.
<P>
How does this change your earlier opinion?
</blockquote>
Based on this information advise you client giving reasons
for your choices.
<P>
<b>15 marks</B>
<P>
Discuss the remedies available to your client.
<P>
<b>5 marks</B>
<P>
<blockquote>3. A classmate of yours has just completed a period of parttime
work at a commercial law firm. Your classmate tells you that she has
without obtaining permission from her employers, made copies of memos
and precedents (both of opinion letters and pleadings) from the
firm's precedent system and has asked you if you would like a copy of them.
<P>
What liability does you classmate have for trade secret violations
or breaches of confidence? What liability do you have?
</blockquote>
You answer should give your conclusions and justified reasoning.
<P>
<b>10 marks</B>
<P>
<B>THE EMBODIMENTS OF THE INVENTION IN WHICH AN EXCLUSIVE
PROPERTY OR PRIVILEGE IS CLAIMED ARE DEFINED AS FOLLOWS:</B>
<P>
1. A longitudinally Tubular plastic bag structure comprising:
<blockquote>
(a) front and gear panels joined together along their top;
bottom and side edges
<P>
(b) inwardly gussetted side walls extending between said
front and rear panel top and bottom edges; and,
<P>
(c) an aperture extending through the upper, central region
of said panels to define a separable support member extending
across the top edge of said aperture.
</blockquote>
2. A plastic bag structure as defined in claim 1, wherein said aperture further extends through said gusseted side walls to define a bag handle on each side of said aperture.
<P>
3. A plastic bag structure as defined in claim 2, further
comprising first and second perforations extending across said
support member at opposed ends thereof .
<P>
4. A plastic bag structure. as defined in claim 3, wherein
said first and second perforations each comprise at least two
spaced apart contact members joining said support member to said
handles.
<P>
5. A plastic bag structure as defined in claim 4, wherein
said first and second perforations are arranged to tear into said. support member.
