<HEAD>
<title>University of Toronto Faculty of Law April 1995 Examinations</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY link="#00562d" vlink="#440000">
<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>FIRST YEAR EXAMINATIONS, APRIL 1995<br>
EXAMINER: PROFESSOR PHILLIPS<br>
MONDAY, APRIL 10<br>
TIME: 2.00 - 5.00<p>
PROPERTY</h2></center><p>
<b>INSTRUCTIONS - PLEASE READ BEFORE THE EXAMINATION BEGINS</b>
1) This is an open book examination. You may use the course materials and any notes or books of your own.<p>
2) There are three parts to the examination, of unequal value. You must answer Question One (50 marks), Question Two (30 marks), and two of the questions that make up Question Three (20 marks). Question One is divided into two equal parts. The time you should allow is indicated at the beginning of each question.<p>
3) If you believe that you need more facts to answer any question, say what you need to know, make factual assumptions if necessary, and continue with your answer.<p>
4) You may include in any of your answers, where appropriate, reasonable suggestions for changes in the law. Be careful, however, to distinguish between the existing law and any such suggestions for reform.<p>
5) At the conclusion of this examination you will be asked to stop writing, gather your books and coats, and leave the examination room. <b>YOUR EXAMINATION ANSWER BOOKLETS SHOULD BE LEFT ON THE WRITING TABLE</b>. Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
<P>
<b>QUESTION ONE (50 MARKS) - 90 MINUTES</b><p>
In 1990 Alice Bronson was the sole owner of a retail personal computer business operating out of a store on Spadina Avenue. With her lease about to expire in a few months, and the landlord not wanting to renew it, she consulted a commercial real estate agency. They told her about a new mall opening in the expanding community of Suburbis, 15 miles north of Toronto. The mall was completed with space for 30 stores, although at that time only 15 tenants had moved in. She called the mall owner, who said: &quot;drive out and look at the place. When you get here park in the section of the parking lot closest to the main entrance to the mall. It's marked 'reserved for owner'. I park there and I also let my tenants park there. Use the space numbered 16&quot;. Alice did as she was instructed, liked the mall, and liked the fact also that it had no personal computer store.
<p>
Over a few meetings she was able to hammer out a good deal with the owner, who was keen to have her as a tenant because he saw a computer store as an attraction that would increase the number of people who visited the mall. In one of the meetings Alice asked about parking for customers, and was told that the lot was big enough that it was never full. She took care to drive out to the place at different times and confirmed this fact for herself.
The 10-year lease contained covenants standard in mall leases, including one that read: &quot;The tenant covenants to operate continuously a store for the sale of personal computer products.&quot;
<p>
On January 1, 1991, Alice took possession of the premises, and shortly afterwards opened for business. She had been given one of the best locations in the mall, store number 23, one that had an entrance right onto the parking lot and that therefore could advertise its presence very effectively. She did very well for over three years, although the mall itself was never entirely successful. At various times between 1991 and 1994 between 5 and 8 of the 30 store spaces were unrented. As a result the owner was barely able to make a profit given his large interest payments. In an effort to get more revenue he agreed to lease about half of the land used as the mall parking lot to a neighbouring office building, which did not have enough parking.
<p>
Thus when Alice turned up one morning in August 1994 she found half the parking lot cordoned off with temporary fencing, with just the portion of it nearest to the mall left for mall parking. She could still park in what used to be the reserved area, but the reserved signs and the numbers were gone and the area given over to general parking. As things turned out this made things quite difficult for her, because she or an employee used her car a lot during the day to collect products and make deliveries, and doing so took much longer once she no longer had a reserved parking space. Even worse, she quickly discovered that the remaining parking lot was often full. Not only was she forced sometimes to wait before being able to park, but trade dropped off substantially as potential customers refused to wait and went elsewhere. By the end of 1994 she was actually losing money, sales not covering rent, wages, and other expenses.
<p>
Discussions with the mall owner being unavailing, Alice decided to consult a lawyer. She chose your articling principal who passed the file to you, with this note:
<p>
&quot;If I remember my first year property course correctly, this is the kind of thing covered by easement law. Surely Ms. Bronson has a right to use the landlord's land for parking, which means she has the right both to the reserved space she used to have and to have enough parking for her customers. If I'm wrong about this, is there anything we can do for her using landlord and tenant law?&quot;
<p>
<b>QUESTION 1 - PART A (25 MARKS - 45 MINUTES):</b> Please write a memo In response.
<p>
Being keen you complete this memo quickly, but it then sits on your principal's desk because she is on vacation. In the meantime matters deteriorated for Alice, and she decided to cut her losses. She packed up all her goods on the evening of February 26th 1995 and departed; the next day she cancelled the March rent cheque and all subsequent rent cheques, and delivered a letter to the mall owner which stated, in part: &quot;You have broken our agreement by not providing enough parking. So I'm breaking it too by leaving. You can have your stupid mall.&quot; She was not the only one to feel this way. At the time she left there were a total of 10 stores empty in the mall.
A couple of weeks later she received a letter from the landlord's solicitors, which read:
<p>
&quot;Re: Suburbis Mall and Alice Bronson. This is to inform you that the owner of Suburbis Mall does not consider your lease to be surrendered. We will be looking to you for payment of the rent for the remaining period of the lease, until 31 December 2000. We intend also to hold you responsible for losses occasioned by your failure to operate a computer retail operation in store number 23&quot;. Alice again consults your firm. Your principal is still on vacation, so you interview her. In the meeting she says:
<p>
&quot;Surely this is ridiculous. Surely the law won't make me pay to the year 2000. Anyway, I happen to know that a friend of mine, who runs a clothing business, wants to move into my store. She thinks she can do all right even with the limited parking for customers as most of her clients are kids who have to go to the mall on public transit anyway. But the landlord won't give her that store, he says she must take one of the other empty ones. She doesn't really want one of those, although she'll take it if necessary; she really wants the one that faces the parking lot.&quot;
<p>
<b>QUESTION ONE - PART B (25 MARKS - 45 MINUTES):</b> Please advise Alice about her legal position.
<P>
<b>QUESTION TWO - 30 MARKS - 55 MINUTES</b>
<p>
Your client Mr. Thoreau owns a substantial piece of forested property in prime cottage country. He has not built on the lot, but has cut trails through the forest and cleared picnic/camp sites at several places. Every year, for a number of years, he and his family have spent time there in the summer. They camp, wander the trails, and observe nature. They also made a habit of pruning back the growth where the trails and sites had become overgrown and replacing any missing trail markers. Over the years Mr. Thoreau has been approached by property developers, who wanted to buy the land and sub-divide and develop it as cottage properties. [The developers know that there will be no problem with planning legislation]. Mr. Thoreau has always resisted such offers.
<p>
Mr. Thoreau has one son, now 30, and has always assumed that the land would eventually go to the son. But he is now worried by the fact that his son wants to &quot;get on&quot;, make some money, and thinks that the son might be tempted to sell the land to one of the developers. He is very concerned that this not happen. His worries about this have increased recently, because his own health is deteriorating and he does not find it easy to keep fixing up the trails and sites. His son has suggested that, since Thoreau is having these problems, and since the son will get it eventually anyway, he should sell the land to him now. Mr. Thoreau is not opposed to the idea in principle, indeed he thinks it would be good to have more cash on hand. But that nagging concern about his son's intentions remains with him.
<p>
Mr. Thoreau comes to your office with this story. He does want the land to go to his son, and he is indifferent about whether this happens before or after his (Thoreau's) death. But he also wants to ensure, in his words, that &quot;the property will be maintained in all its natural beauty&quot;. He asks you whether it is possible to do this at all, and if so whether he could achieve it better by selling the land to his son now or leaving it to his son in his will. Please advise him.
 <p>
<b>QUESTION THREE - 20 MARKS - 35 MINUTES</b>
<p>
Please answer any two (2) of the following questions.
<p>
A) What is the consequence of severing a joint tenancy? How can it be done?
<p>
B) In <cite>Treloar v. Nute</cite> Pennycuick J. said: &quot;The law ... is that if a squatter takes possession of land belonging to another and remains in possession for 12 years to the exclusion of the owner that represents adverse possession and accordingly at the end of the 12 years the owner's title is extinguished. That is the plain meaning of the statutory provisions...&quot;. Is this the law in Ontario? [Consider matters other than the different limitation period].
<p>
C) The current law in Ontario is that neither rent controls nor the granting of security of tenure to residential tenants represent a taking of property from the landlord. Briefly outline the arguments you would make if asked to say why either of these should be considered a taking.
<p>
D) In <cite>Re Gatti et al and Forsythe et al</cite> Goodearle D.C.J. stated that the question at issue was: &quot;Can the owner of residential premises dispossess tenants in preparation for a bona fide sale to third parties in the open market&quot;. What is the answer? What should be the answer?
<P>
