<center><h1><a href="http://www.utoronto.ca/">University of Toronto</a><br><a href="http://www.law.utoronto.ca/">Faculty of Law</a></h1>
<h2>ANNUAL EXAMINATIONS, 1994-95<br>
PROPERTY<br>
Examiner: Professor R.E. Scane</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>NOTE:</h3>
<ol>
<li>Answer all questions. The marks available for each question are shown in the margin. <B>Reasons for conclusions are essential.</b><p>
<li>Candidates are reminded that they have undertaken with the examiner not to make use of any materials for the purpose of answering Question 5. Otherwise, there is no restriction upon the materials which candidates may use during this examination, except the general Faculty rule against using materials borrowed from the Law Library.<p>
<li>Before you begin, ensure that you have written your pseudonym, course name, and the number of the booklet on <b>each</b> examination booklet and the name of the instructor on the <b>first</b> booklet. If you request an additional booklet(s) during the examination, write the required information on the booklet at the time you receive it. No time will be permitted for this at the end of the examination.<p>
<li>During the examination, only one student at a time is permitted to leave the examination room. No student may leave within fifteen minutes of the conclusion of the examination.<p>
<li>At the end of this examination, the invigilator will ask you to stop writing, count the total number of booklets used, record this on the front of the 	first booklet, and insert all booklets into the first booklet. You will then gather your belongings and leave the examination room. <B>All examination answer booklets are to be left on the writing table and will be collected 	by the invigilator.</b><p>
<li>Time limits will be strictly enforced. Students who continue to write after the examination has ended will have their examination booklets collected separately and may be subject to a penalty.
</ol>
<P>
 <b>Q1. [25 marks] </B>Alan owned a large farm in Ontario. On the northern half
of the property, hereinafter called &quot;Northacre&quot;, were
Alan's house and the farm buildings. Near the southern limit of
Northacre, the land sloped sharply downwards to the southern half
of the farm, hereinafter called &quot;Southacre&quot;. Southacre
sloped gradually towards the south, until it reached a creek at
its southern limit. To the east of Southacre was Eastacre, owned
by Brian. Eastacre was higher land than Southacre, and, near its
southern limit, sloped steeply towards Southacre. Across the creek
to the south of Southacre and Eastacre, the land rose again, to
a small hilltop. The local electricity utility had its transmission
line running over the hilltop. From there, Alan, at his own expense,
constructed a power cable feeding from that line to his farm.
Alan's cable passed about sixty feet over Southacre, to a tower
on Northacre, and then to the buildings on Northacre, to supply
them with power.
<P>
Surface water drained naturally from Northacre and Eastacre onto
Southacre. It did not flow in any defined channels. Alan had constructed
drains on Southacre, which carried water draining from Northacre,
and from the northern part of Eastacre, south to discharge into
the creek. He had never constructed any drains to carry off surface
water draining from the southern part of Eastacre onto Southacre,
with the result that a couple of hectares at the south-east corner
of Southacre were swampy.
<P>
A few years ago, Alan granted a five-year lease of Southacre to
Carol, who, to Alan's knowledge, wished to raise an exotic animal,
the heffalump. Heffalumps require extraordinary amounts of water.
Carol constructed a large farm pond by excavating near the northern
limit of Southacre. The pond was filled by diverting some of the
drains existing on Southacre, so that they discharged into the
new pond. This work was done with Alan's permission. By agreement
between Alan and Carol, incorporated as a term of the lease, a
power line was strung from the tower on Northacre to the house
trailer which Carol had moved onto Southacre, and in which she
proposed to live, Carol agreed to pay Alan a flat fee for her
electricity.
<P>
The heffalumps thrived, and, near the end of the lease, Carol
bought Southacre from Alan. As the existence of the private power
line over Southacre to Northacre had not been mentioned to either
of the parties' lawyers, the deed from Alan to Carol did not refer
to it. It simply conveyed the fee simple in Southacre. Carol continued
to make payments for power to Alan, and, after David bought Alan's
land, to David, as before.
<P>
After the conveyance of the fee simple in Southacre to Carol,
Alan sold Northacre to David. David decided that he too would
raise heffalumps. To obtain a necessary reserve of water, David
built a pond on Northacre. To fill it, he built an embankment
along the south limit of Northacre, retaining on that parcel much
of the water that had previously flowed onto Southacre. The water
level in Carol's pond soon started dropping, as the drainage from
Northacre, which was the main source of its. supply, was cut off.
Carol protested to David that, if he continued to impede the drainage,
she would have to spend large sums either in pumping water from the creek
at the south all the way to the north of her property, or in digging
additional wells. David told her that that was her problem.
<P>
Meanwhile, Carol wished to reclaim the swampy land at the south-east
corner of Southacre. To do so, she built an embankment near the
eastern limit of her property, to throw back onto Eastacre most
of the surface water which had previously drained down into the
swamp area. Brian protested that, during the spring melt and run-off,
this caused the basement of his house, which stood near the line
between the properties, to flood. Carol told him that that was
his problem.
<P>
Then Carol, furious with David, installed her own power generator,
disconnected herself from the power she had previously been receiving
from Northacre, and ordered David to remove the private cable
passing over Southacre, from the electricity utility's line, to
Northacre.
<P>
<B>Carol now consults you. She wants to sue David, to require
him to either restore the drainage of water from Northacre, or
pay the costs of obtaining an alternative supply, and to make
him remove the power cable. Brian is threatening to sue her for
the damage caused to his house by the flooding, and she wants
to defend that suit. Advise Carol</B>
<P>
 <b>Q2. [23 marks]</B> A report of the Law Commission of the United Kingdom, written
in 1984, contained the following passage:
<blockquote>
  &quot;A covenant amounts simply to a contractual obligation
undertaken in a deed by one person towards another; and the general principles of contract law apply to it. As a result it can of
course be enforced between the original covenantor and the original convenantee. On their deaths, the burden and the benefit, normally pass automatically to their respective personal representatives. And it is usually possible by assignment to transfer the benefit, though not the burden to some third party.....&quot;
<P>
  However, the last word is not said on all covenants by the law
of contract. Land law has something to add...&quot;
</blockquote>
<B>Discuss the manner in which &quot;land law&quot; adds to &quot;the
general principles of contract law&quot; with respect to covenants,
with particular reference to the policy reasons underlying such
addition or additions, and the controls which &quot;land law&quot;
puts into place to keep such additions within the scope of the
underlying policy reasons.</B>
<P>
 <b>Q3. [18 marks]</B> In a passage in the case of <cite>Williams v. Hensman,</cite>
the judge referred to three methods of severing a joint tenancy. This passage (reproduced
at p. F-38 of your materials) is sometimes referred to as containing the &quot;three
rules&quot; of that case.
<P>
<B>Discuss how and why this passage would guide your investigation
of the facts, if you were consulted by a client who had a material
interest in having a court find that a joint tenancy had been
severed prior to the death of one of the joint tenants.</B>
<P>
<b>Q4. [17 marks] Discuss how the common law concept of aboriginal, or native, title
to land compares to the common law concept of estates in land
held by tenure from the Crown.</b>
<P>
<b>Q5. [17 marks]</b> You are practicing law in a jurisdiction which has the same
common law with respect to property, and the same relevant statute
law, as the Province of Ontario, <b>except that</b> your
jurisdiction has no common law or statute law involving perpetuities.
<P>
What is the nature and effect of each of the following limitations
of real property, assuming that, in each case, the grantor or
testator owned a fee simple absolute, free of encumbrances? Do
<b>not</b> assume that any person to whom an interest is given
is dead at the creation of the interest.
<dl>
 <dt>(a) a grant: <dd>To T and her heirs, in trust for my son John for
John's lifetime, and then in trust for the first daughter of John to marry.
<P>
<dt>(b) a grant: <dd>To Z for the term of 20 years and then to the eldest
child of Z living at the expiration of Z's term, in fee simple.
<P>
<dt>(c) a devise: <dd>To my wife Wilma for life, and then to my son John
and his heirs, if John attains 18, provided that if John should at any time
after attaining 18 become a citizen of a country other than Canada, John's interest in the said lands will cease, and pass to my daughter Mary and her heirs.
<P>
<dt>(d) a grant: <dd>To the City of Toronto, to be held by the City during
such time as the lands are maintained by the City as a public park and botanical garden. Upon the lands being diverted to any other use, the lands shall pass to the University of Toronto.
<P>
<dt>(e) a grant: <dd>Unto and to the use of T and his heirs in trust for X and his heirs when X marries, or, if X dies unmarried, in trust for Y and his heirs.
</dl>
<p>
